<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
AS MOVIE EXHIBITORS PUSH TOWARD AN UNCERTAIN ENDING, AMC IS
CONFIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- AMC 2NDTAKE -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JENNIFER MANN, THE KANSAS CITY STAR   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the undertakings facing any such company would be
scrutinizing which leases to keep and which ones to reject on
properties it doesn't own.
</P>
<P>
   David Brain is president of Kansas City-based Entertainment
Properties Trust, a real estate investment trust that owns 26
megaplex properties that it leases back to exhibitors. AMC-operated
megaplexes make up 75 percent of its portfolio. Brown of AMC is the
nonemployee chairman of Entertainment Properties Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Brain said that after United Artists files Chapter 11, which he
and many others in the industry expect any day, he thinks the
company ultimately will close 1,000 screens, half of its total.
</P>
<P>
   An immediate wipeout of 1,000 movie screens would allow everyone
else in the industry to breathe just a wee bit easier.
</P>
<P>
   If another exhibitor follows United Artists into Chapter 11 _
and again take hundreds of movie screens out of the mix in one fell
swoop _ it would create even more breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon of Moody's said he thought it would be difficult for an
exhibitor to file for Chapter 11 because the movie distributors
then would probably want their money up front.
</P>
<P>
   But Brain disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``United Artists is essentially in bankruptcy, and they're still
getting film and still conducting day-to-day business,'' Brain
said. ``The studios are not scared to distribute product despite
(United Artists') situation, which is good news for all those who
may follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Brain agrees with Brown that industry analysts are painting the
entire troubled industry with one broad stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a two-part story that's being viewed through a single
lens,'' Brain said. ``You can't take total box office revenues and
divide that by the number of screens and come up with the whole
story; that other part of the story is that some are doing better
than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its current troubles, Brown said AMC is in that pack of
those doing better than others. Others, including Kuzio of KDP,
agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``AMC, in particular, is a company that we're recommending to
our clients,'' Kuzio said. ``We like what they're doing to better
position themselves relative to what others are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his faith comes in AMC's slowdown of capital spending
and commitment of more money to taking obsolete screens out of its
mix. Other exhibitors are on that track as well, but AMC is moving
more aggressively than many.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last year AMC recorded $16.7 million in expenses
for theater closures, compared with only $2.8 million the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of its current fiscal year in March 2001, AMC will
have closed almost 750 screens in the previous five years.
Meanwhile, the company will have opened 1,900 screens in new
megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, 62 percent of AMC's screens are at megaplexes, the
highest percentage in the industry and one that has increased each
quarter since it opened its first, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves 38 percent of its screens in smaller multiplexes.
But not all of those are obsolete, Brown said. He puts the
percentage at somewhere around 14 percent, which equals about 400
screens. Those, he said, will be taken out of the mix over the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than thinking of his mentor, Durwood, as the pioneer of
overbuilding, Brown prefers to think of him as the one who really
got the ball rolling in shifting the industry to what it will look
like in three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty darn clean portfolio of better-performing
theaters than, I'd say, a good 80 percent of the industry,'' Brown
said. ``Some would call that first-mover advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   During the more than 70 years that AMC has been in business, it
has teetered a few times itself, including in the late 1980s, when
international expansion almost brought the company to its knees.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he takes some comfort in the fact that the company
has been through the valley before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tended to change the industry a time or two, and we've
had challenges. And not to sound cocky, but I take comfort in
that,'' Brown said. ``There's a lot of drama on Wall Street right
now regarding this industry, but for us it's sort of background
noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a recent report from Banc of America Securities on
AMC in which analyst Christopher Harris dubbed AMC a ``probable
survivor'' in the exhibition industry, Brown bristled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should even have to say those two words:
probable survivor,'' Brown said. ``We're most definitely a
survivor. ... I really think our story will have a strong ending.''
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
