<SLUG> BC-KING-ONLINE-NOVEL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEWER FIRST-DAY DOWNLOADS THAN EXPECTED FOR KING'S ONLINE NOVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite top; picks up at 3rd graf. Describes DeFillippo's
job in 4th graf.)  
 By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Demand for horror writer Stephen King's new electronic book fell
short of expectations Monday, in a closely watched test of the
author's attempt to transform book sales over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for the book fell short of King's last novella in
March, which seemed to foretell a revolution in publishing when
more than 400,000 fans jammed computer servers trying to download
it in the first two days after it appeared.
</P>
<P>
   King's Web site operators had planned to handle similar demand
Monday, just in case. But as of late Monday afternoon, fans had
downloaded 41,000 copies of the first chapter of ``The Plant,'' an
epistolary novel about the predations of a vicious vine. King plans
to publish the novel in monthly installments.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difference may be that this time King elected to
publish the book without the support of a publisher, relying
entirely on the Internet and word-of-mouth to attract readers. ``We
didn't have the marketing and sales promotion that Simon &AMP; Schuster
put behind `Riding the Bullet,' and that obviously accounted for
some of the difference,'' said Marsha DeFillippo, an assistant to
King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riding the Bullet'' is the novella that King published in
electronic form.
</P>
<P>
   King's promotion of the project consisted entirely of two
advertisements, one in Publishers Weekly and another in USA Today,
as well as a morning television appearance and a few newspaper
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   King was ``very pleased'' with sales for far, DeFillippo said,
calling the first-day sales respectable. King's Web site designers
prepared for as many as half a million downloads, just in case. But
others in the industry said 40,000 was an impressive total for one
day's sales of an electronic book, for which there are few
benchmarks for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   King may have thrown off some readers by trying out an
honor-system payment plan. King asked readers to pay him a dollar
for each chapter they downloaded, and warned that he would not post
new installments unless he received payments for at least 75
percent of the downloads.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com agreed to handle the payments, and said that by late
Monday afternoon it had received about 25,000 credit card payments
for the first chapter, and that another 7,000 customers had
promised to send a check or cash. Amazon.com had distributed
``Riding the Bullet'' for free and all in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   King was particularly pleased to see that the number of payments
so far seemed to meet his 75 percent threshold, DeFillippo said.
</P>
<P>
   William Thornton, president of Radiant Ideas, who maintains
www.stephenking.com., said that some visitors to the Web site
objected to the installment plan.
</P>
<P>
   In e-mails and messages posted on the Web site, ``There was
fairly vehement reaction to the idea of paying multiple times for
it,'' Thornton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, Amazon.com's chief executive, said he hoped that the
honor-system model might inspire others to try distributing books
as if they were ``shareware,'' software circulated on the Internet
with payment expected later. ``If you can make it easy for people,
people are going to be willing to pay,'' Bezos said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lorraine Shanley, a principal in the book industry
consulting company Market Partners International, questioned just
how easy it was. She noted it took several clicks to finish the
Amazon.com payments. Then readers will need to come back and pay
for more installments. ``There wasn't instant gratification,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a hint perhaps of battles to come, some other booksellers
questioned King's decision to favor Amazon.com as the exclusive
bill collector. ``It is a shame,'' said Ed Morrow, owner of the
Northshire Bookstore in Manchester Center, Vt., and former
president of the American Booksellers Association. He noted that
King could have elected to send customers for payment to the
association's Booksense Web site or another store's, including his
own. ``We have a Web site, and we could have done it for him,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
