<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-TEX     07-25 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RODRIGUEZ-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Texas Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriquez, the
reigning American League Most Valuable Player, will miss the rest
of the season after breaking his right thumb in last night's game
against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, regarded by many as the best all-around catcher in
baseball, began the day batting .347 with 27 home runs and 83 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was hurt in the first inning when his thumb hit the
bat of Anaheim's Mo Vaughn on a swinging third strike as he threw
to second base on a steal attempt by Kevin Stocker.
</P>
<P>
   Home-plate umpire Gerry Davis called Stocker out on batter's
interference.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was taken to a hospital for X-rays, which revealed a
fracture of the metacarpal bone in his right thumb. The Rangers
said he would have surgery today in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as it happened, my thumb went numb. There was swelling
and I knew it was broken and I'd be out for the season,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   The team's director of medical services, Dr. John Conway, said
Rodriguez will need six to 10 weeks for the fracture to heal.
Rodriguez will be able to resume sports-related activities in two
to four months.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said there were no guarantees that Rodriguez would be
able to fully recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime there's an injury like this, there's a possibility for
a loss of performance,'' he said. ``But we think he'll make a full
recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Vaughn did nothing wrong, and added that the
Angels first baseman left a message in the Rangers clubhouse
expressing his sorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was on purpose,'' Rodriguez said. ``Mo is a
very clean player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, AL West champions the past two seasons, began the
night 101/2 games behind division-leading Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 28, played this month in his ninth consecutive
All-Star game. He received more votes than any other player in the
fans' All-Star balloting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was having a strong season so it's disappointing for it to
end two months before it was supposed to,'' Rodriguez said. ``But
there's always next season. I'll just go out and put up better
numbers next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has won eight consecutive Gold Glove awards, an
American League record. This year, he had thrown out 16 of 33 (48.5
percent) would-be base stealers. Last year, he caught 54.2 percent,
the fifth consecutive season that he led the AL in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez won the MVP award last year when he hit .332 with an
AL-record 35 home runs by a catcher. He had 113 RBIs and scored 116
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was replaced in last night's game by veteran Bill
Haselman, who is hitting .250 with five RBIs in 18 games this
season. Haselman is the only other catcher currently on the
Rangers' roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers purchased the contract of catcher B.J. Waszgis from
Triple-A Oklahoma. Rodriguez will be placed on the 15-day disabled
list today.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said Rodriguez's
season-ending injury, coupled with the loss of highly touted rookie
center fielder Ruben Mateo to a broken right leg on June 2, seemed
to sum up his team's season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day,'' Melvin said. ``We always take Pudge for
granted that he's always going to be out there. But you have to
realize it can happen to anybody. You wonder which player your team
can least afford to lose. He falls into that category.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin was unsure whether the loss of Rodriguez would mean his
team would be more willing to trade impending free agents such as
David Segui and John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is still running on our players who are going to be
free agents,'' Melvin said. ``But that doesn't change our thinking.
We're still going to try and win every game that we can. This does
give a chance to some of our young players.'' THIS REPORT CONTAINS
MATERIAL FROM THE ASSOCIATED PRESS AND THE BLOOMBERG NEWS SERVICE.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
