<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2078 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-LONESTAR-TEX     07-25 1750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONESTAR-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE _ Into everyone's life, a little rain must fall.
OK, sometimes it's a lot.
</P>
<P>
   And for a while during the thoroughbred season at Lone Star Park
at Grand Prairie, the track had to operate under the
when-it-rains-it-pours mode. There were 17 days of racing that were
conducted in rainy weather, compared to four last year.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike motorsports, baseball, golf and major tennis
tournaments, horse racing trudges on when the clouds burst. So it's
quite an accomplishment that average daily attendance at Lone Star
for the thoroughbred season was down only one percent compared to
last year.
</P>
<P>
   When the season ended last year, Lone Star was down four percent
in average daily attendance compared to the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe Lone Star is making progress.. It can be a challenge to
keep fans returning to a new and attractive facility when the
novelty is wearing off.
</P>
<P>
   The horse-racing product at Lone Star still remains on the list
of things to do for a sports fan/entertainment seeker in this
market. The facility is a financially solid franchise because its
long-term debt continues to be retired by the sales-tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   But the track, and the sport at large, is still only scratching
the surface. How far it can go will be determined by two things,
and neither has much to do with trying to open new racetracks in
minor markets including Lubbock and Laredo, initiatives Lone Star
has announced in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it has to do with the ability to lobby legislatures in
the effort to expand its business, and it depends on the
imagination of the people who market and advertise the track and
the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing's ability to argue it's case in front of lawmakers
always is dicey. There's no better example than last week when
horse racing was a part of the political coalition urging passage
of a bill that would ban gambling on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Horse-racing operators, like Lone Star president Corey Johnsen,
believe that part of their business is being undermined by people
who'd rather sit at home and bet through Internet sites based
offshore than go out to the track. Lone Star's off-track betting on
its races was down 14 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the doors fell off the bill once it hit the House of
Representatives. The bill came out of the Senate with an exemption
that would allow horse racing to handle wagers on Internet sites.
But that was removed in a House committee. Then, rather having the
bill pass by a simple majority, House rules were invoked that
required a two-third majority for passage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill got a simple majority, but failed to get a super
majority.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, however, it looks like the horse-racing industry will
push for a form of legalized, in-home account wagering when the
next session of the Legislature convenes in January in Austin. And
it could have an important lobbying ally with mainstream clout:
``TV Guide'' and Fox, which are major backers of the TVG network
that provides in-home telecasts of live horse racing via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   TVG also conducts account wagering, and residents in Kentucky,
Maryland and Oregon have legalized in-home account wagering. The
Legislature in Louisiana recently approved it for the opening of
the Fair Grounds racing season that starts in November in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star already is a partner with TVG. It has contracted with
the network to telecast races over TVG, even if people in Texas
can't legally bet on the races.
</P>
<P>
   But in a brave new world of people using their remotes to buy
exacta and trifecta bets the way they would purchase pay-per-view
boxing, horse racing is running somewhat of a risk. The sport is
bypassing an off-track betting system that, if overhauled from
previous failures experienced most notably in New York, could serve
as much as marketing outlets as convenient wagering locations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether horse-racing executives, and their television ally in
TVG, want to take that marketing route through off-track betting
locations _ dressed up as theme restaurants _ remains to be seen.
Whether any of it can get done or not depends on horse racing's
political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lone Star did well during the rain this year, the track
still may want to build a boat.  &QL; 
It's the horses, stupid
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star has tried for four years to make the racing world
notice its Lone Star Derby. The track even offered a $1 million
bonus for any horse that could win the Lone Star Derby on April 22
and any of the Triple Crown races.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a moment this year when even the local racing fans
ignored the race, and national fans almost missed it.
</P>
<P>
   The horses were being saddled before the race, yet the crowd
gathered around the paddock was looking away. Most everyone was
looking skyward where a number of parachutists hired by Lone Star
as a sideshow entertainment act were floating down to the track.
High winds played havoc with the parachutes, and three skydivers
were injured when they hit the ground with more force than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The Lone Star Derby had to be delayed while one of the
parachutists was treated on the track for a broken leg. The race
was televised nationally, and it barely made it before ESPN had to
switch to another scheduled event.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Lone Star officials could only say the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can rest assured,'' general manager Steve Sexton said.
``We won't be doing this again right before one of our big races.''
 &QL; 
Money in hand
</P>
<P>
   When Tahkodha Hills won the Lone Star Derby, he became eligible
for a $1 million bonus that Lone Star paid about $60,000 to
underwrite. Tahkodha Hills had to win one of the Triple Crown
events to cash the million. The owner of the colt would get
$750,000. The trainer would get $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Ralph Zaidie, trainer of Tahkodha Hills, already cashed that
day at Lone Star. He also trained Sir Bear, who won the Texas Mile
about 35 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   The winner's share of a race is 60 percent of the purse. Because
both the Lone Star Derby and Texas Mile are $300,000 events, the
winner's share is $180,000 for each race. A trainer gets paid 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   So Zaidie's take was $36,000. He would get no more. Tahkodha
Hills skipped the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness Stakes, then
finished ninth in the 11-horse field of the Belmont Stakes.  &QL; 
Who's in first?
</P>
<P>
   Corey Lanerie, who was leading rider at Lone Star in 1999,
became the all-time leading rider at the track when he rode his
212th winner May 3. But he moved to Arlington International
Racecourse near Chicago when that track opened May 14.
</P>
<P>
   Lanerie became the all-time leader by overtaking Marlon St.
Julien, who led the standings in 1998 before he moved to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   But St. Julien makes occasional appearances at Lone Star, and he
came back to the track May 29 to ride in a collection of stakes
races. And when he rode two winners that day, he moved back ahead
of Lanerie by one.
</P>
<P>
   Lanerie came back to ride June 17 and finished second in the
$250,000 Dallas Turf Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that Marlon got back in the lead,'' Lanerie said.
``The day he did it, I called my agent and said, `You know Marlon's
ahead again.' We'll be back.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien also came back again, to ride July 3 in the $150,000
Grand Prairie Turf Challenge. He won.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Ronald Ardoin, who has been riding at Lone Star all this
season in addition to previous seasons, won two races Friday night
to go to 215 and one ahead of St. Julien. So now he's the all-time
leading rider at Lone Star.  &QL; 
Season down the tubes
</P>
<P>
   It was looking like a breakthrough season for jockey Donnie
Meche. Meche, 25, won graded stakes races at Fair Grounds in New
Orleans for Hall of Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas.
</P>
<P>
   And he had a 14-race lead in the jockey standings this season at
Lone Star before a trip to the lake. He climbed onto a tube pulled
behind a power boat and suffered a small break in his right
shoulder when he was flung off the tube.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to swing the whip with his right arm, Meche still tried
to ride in the All-Star Jockey Championship on June 23. He won one
of the races against riders like Pat Day and Laffit Pincay Jr. and
had the lead in the competition heading into the final race.
</P>
<P>
   But Edgar Prado, the nation's leading rider by number of
victories the past three years, won the final race. That put him in
a tie with Meche, with the tiebreaker determined by the jockey who
received the most points in the last race. So the title went to
Prado.
</P>
<P>
   Because he missed the last 22 days of the racing season to rest
the shoulder, Meche also lost the Lone Star season riding title to
Glen Murphy.  &QL; 
So high, so low
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing has highs and lows. And trainer Wes Hawley
experienced both in a matter of a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Hawley won his first career stakes race with Caro's Royalty on
May 29 in the $100,000 Lone Star Park Turf Sprint. But he had to
scratch Midnight Klugh from the Grade III Lone Star Park Handicap
the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two days later, it was clear why Hawley had to do
that. Midnight Klugh was not able to recover from founder in his
foot. It's a painful condition that's often fatal. Hawley and
veterinarians were unable to save him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I win my first career stakes race, and then this happens,''
Hawley said. ``This is tough. I thought a lot about that horse. I
went back to the racing office and got the stakes saddlecloth with
his name on it, and I got choked up.''  &QL; 
A Lone Star heritage?
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Of Gold was named Horse of the Meet in 1999 at Lone
Star after she won three stakes races. To the surprise of many, the
local horse has developed into one of the nation's best. After the
Lone Star season, she won graded stakes race last year on the East
Coast and finished third in the Breeders' Cup Distaff. Are there
any horses from this year's season at Lone Star who could turn into
the next Heritage Of Gold?
</P>
<P>
   Luftikus: The horse's trainer, Vladimir Cerin, is one of
nation's hottest prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Nugget: He tries a major race Sunday in the Grade I Eddie
Read Handicap at Southern California's prestigious Del Mar meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Superpave: Trainer being cautious, but appearance in a Breeders'
Cup undercard race is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Wild Hits: Impressive 2-year-old must recover from slight
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's Viva: Little filly got good late in season, and she
could stand out next year at Fair Grounds or Oaklawn.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
