<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COMMENTAR     07-25 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-COMMENTARY-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ OK, repeat after me three times.
</P>
<P>
   It's always about money. It's always about money. It's always
about money.
</P>
<P>
   Now think about Cowboys offensive tackle Erik Williams' supposed
holdout//retirement for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't show up for camp at Midwestern State University,
which ranks as a smart move considering the sweltering heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys initially describe his absence as a ``business''
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' agent, Alan Herman, however, said his client has lost
his desire to play the game and is contemplating retirement. Herman
also scolds the Cowboys for hinting that Williams' intentions are
less than pure.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys then say Williams is mulling several future career
options, including retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's natural for Williams to contemplate retirement at
this stage in his career. He has three Super Bowl rings. He has
four Pro Bowl appearances in nine years. He has also suffered a
career-threatening knee injury and has been demonized for several
off-the-field incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 32, has packed a lot into his nine seasons with the
Cowboys. The retirement of Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin, a close
friend of Williams, doesn't help the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones understands all this, which is mainly
why he's not forcing the issue by fining Williams. He could be
fined up to $5,000 a day as long as he's away.
</P>
<P>
   But while it's not beyond reason that Williams, who's also
engaged to be married, is ready to start a new life, it still just
doesn't seem logical that he is ready to walk away from football.
</P>
<P>
   And even if he is as financially secure as his agent contends,
why would he walk away from roughly $5.4 million. That's $1.9
million in forfeited salary in 2000 and 2001 and another $1.6
million in signing-bonus money he would have to pay back to the
Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to want more money. It's another to give money
away, which is why the former makes more sense than the latter.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Williams' $1.9 million annual salary for the next
two years is low for a player presumably at the top of his game,
which three Pro Bowl selections in the past four years suggest.
</P>
<P>
   The league's top offensive linemen are making more than twice
Williams' salary. That's tough for an ego to digest. Players at
this stage in their career are moved by how they feel when they are
being appreciated. You measure that by money. Sources have said
that Williams would be in camp if the Cowboys showed him some more
appreciation//money.
</P>
<P>
   His problem, however, is leverage, or lack of leverage.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not what you think. The Cowboys aren't taking a
hard-line stance of not redoing Williams' contract because of his
supposed bad-boy past. Jones is not upset at Williams' absence
because of the support the Cowboys gave him during some tough
times.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is a realist, saying the Cowboys' support of Williams
wasn't philanthropic. It was because of what he did on the football
field and his importance during the three world-championship
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones also knows that Williams is no longer the player
he used to be, no matter the recent Pro Bowl pedigree. He was
considered to be no more than the team's third-best offensive
lineman last year, behind guard Larry Allen and future Pro Bowl
left tackle Flozell Adams.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cowboys are convinced that last season's second-round
pick, Solomon Page, who is filling in for Williams at right tackle,
is as good as Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The only hitch in the plan is that the Cowboys believe their
best five offensive linemen include Williams playing tackle and
Page playing guard.
</P>
<P>
   With Page at tackle, free-agent signee Jorge Diaz and veteran
backup Tony Hutson are the guard candidates, which is a dropoff
from the Page//Williams combo.
</P>
<P>
   But not so much that Jones is willing to be held hostage for
more money.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever this standoff ends, remember: It's always about money.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
