<HEADER>
A2081 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     07-25 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys are keeping a short list of
out-of-work NFL kickers at their fingertips, just in case neither
of the two rookie kickers in camp makes the 53-man roster.
</P>
<P>
   The list includes Michael Husted, Jeff Jaeger, Chris Boniol,
Scott Blanton and Richie Cunningham. Even 43-year-old Eddie Murray,
who finished with the Cowboys last season, is on the list.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the job belongs to either Tim Seder or Rian
Lindell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our young guys know the plan,'' Cowboys kickers coach Steve
Hoffman said. ``They know I want one of them to make it. But if by
the end of August it doesn't work out ... well, we can always bring
in a couple of veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman has talked recently to Murray and Boniol, both of whom
are former Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie knows \rthe plan\s. Boniol knows \rthe plan\s. I think
our young guys know it's a business,'' Hoffman said. ``I also think
they know I want one of them to make it. If that's coddling, then
I'm coddling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are in a similar situation at punter, where two
unproven players are competing for a job left vacant by the
departure of Toby Gowin.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys lost Gowin to free agency (New Orleans) and decided
not to re-sign Murray, who came out of retirement after 12 games
last season to replace Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman acknowledges that having a rookie kicker can make a
coach nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm nervous with any kicker,'' Hoffman said. ``It's just
that you're more nervous with a rookie because he hasn't been to
all the stadiums, so he has to learn on the run.''
</P>
<P>
   This year on the road, head coach Dave Campo will take his team
to the opposing stadium the day before each game. This will allow
whoever wins the kicking job to visualize lining up the
game-winning field goal, check into his hotel room and sleep on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RSeder and Lindell\S are pretty steady and don't show their
nerves,'' Hoffman said. ``Right now, I wouldn't be too nervous with
either one of them. Early in camp, I'm looking to see if they get
happy feet or take an extra little jab step or punch their
follow-through.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookies are about as similar in appearance as Penn and
Teller. At 6-foot-3, 241 pounds, Lindell could be an NFL tight end.
At 5-9, 180, Seder could only be a kicker.
</P>
<P>
   Lindell, 23, kicked in a Rose Bowl for Washington State. Seder,
25, went to Ashland University and has been a high school
physical-education teacher in his hometown of Ashland, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Tim is a little more accurate,'' Hoffman said.
``But Rian has made some major changes with his stance and
follow-through. He's still getting used to a lot of stuff. So you
kind of wait and see how far Rian can get. The next few weeks
should tell the tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindell hasn't allowed the competition to keep him from working
on his new technique, even with as many as four kickers in the
off-season programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a guy will go back to the way he was doing it, just
so he can hang with the competition,'' Hoffman said. ``Not Rian.
Jon Hilbert was way ahead of him this spring, but Rian passed
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech rookie Jaret Greaser and Louisville's Hilbert were
released before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   At punter, Utah State rookie Micah Knorr has had to undergo
technique changes while Fordham's Barry Cantrell, a first-year
player (Cowboys' 1998 training camp), has been left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry is polished ... \Rbut\S Micah is catching up fast,''
said Hoffman, adding that Knorr struggled early with his technique
changes. ``He just finally turned the corner the other day. He
understands now what I was trying to get him to ``feel.'' And once
they ``feel'' it, it's almost like you don't coach them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cantrell-Knorr punting duel, according to Hoffman, really
comes down to a kickoff battle. That's because the Cowboys want
their punter _ a la Gowin the past three seasons _ to kick off. The
punter also will be the holder on field-goal and PAT attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we want is someone to be just a steady punter ... don't
get us in trouble,'' Hoffman said, ``and to be a great kickoff
guy.''
nn
</P>
