<HEADLINE>
BY SIMON GONZALEZ AND JOHNNY PAUL
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Rodriguez injured
<TEXT>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez left last night's game in the first
inning after injuring his right thumb. Rodriguez was taken to the
hospital for X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   It was later determined that Rodriguez had a broken thumb and
would miss the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred with Kevin Stocker on first and Mo Vaughn at
the plate with a 3-2 count. Stocker ran on the pitch from starting
pitcher Kenny Rogers. Vaughn swung and missed, and lunged across
the plate. As Rodriguez threw to second, his thumb hit Vaughn's
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hasn't missed a game because of injury since 1998.
Segui sought
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox and New York Mets have expressed interest in
Rangers designated hitter/first baseman David Segui, according to
major-league officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox designated first baseman Mike Stanley for assignment
Sunday and remain interested in acquiring a player who can hit
left-handed such as Segui, a switch hitter who can become a free
agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also have discussed acquiring Philadelphia's Rico
Brogna, who hit more than 20 homers and drove in at least 100 runs
the previous two seasons. Brogna also can become a free agent after
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' interest in Segui stems from the injury to third
baseman Robin Ventura, who went on the 15-day disabled list July 14
with a strain in his right rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Reserves Matt Franco and Lenny Harris have played third base
during Ventura's absence, but first baseman Todd Zeile could move
to the opposite corner if the Mets acquire a first baseman. Zeile
played third base for Rangers during the 1998 and '99 seasons
before signing with the Mets as a free agent.
Resodded infield ``choppy''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers returned home for the first time since the All-Star
break to find new grass on the field. The turf in the infield and
in right field was re-sodded during the team's extended road trip
to replace dead and dying grass.
</P>
<P>
   After taking ground balls during batting practice, the Rangers
infielders said the new turf isn't as smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said, shaking his head.
``It's choppy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clouds of sand flew up when batted balls bounced in the infield,
and manager Johnny Oates was concerned the infielders might have
trouble seeing grounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different,'' third baseman Mike Lamb said. ``It's just
something else we have to deal with. That's why we get paid the big
bucks.''
Perisho to pitch
</P>
<P>
   Matt Perisho became the starting pitcher for tomorrow's game
when he wasn't needed in the bullpen in the early innings last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Since being knocked out in the first inning at Seattle on
Friday, Perisho has been available as a long reliever in place of
Doug Davis, who pitched 4 2/3 innings in relief that night.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates wanted to give Davis another day to
recover, so Perisho again was in the bullpen yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis said he's ready, but I'd like to give him another day,''
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   If Perisho had been needed, Davis would have made the start
tomorrow.  &LR; subheds:Milestone save  &LR; agatea:John Wetteland's save
Sunday was his 25th of the season, the ninth consecutive year he
has reached that plateau. That's the second longest such streak in
major-league history behind Lee Smith, who did it for 13
consecutive seasons from 1983-95.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland is tied for the third-most 25-save seasons behind
Smith and John Franco (11). Jeff Reardon and Dennis Eckersley also
saved at least 25 games in nine seasons.
Kapler improving
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Gabe Kapler extended his hitting streak to a
season-best eight games with a home run in the fourth inning.
Kapler was hitting .407 (11-27) in the previous seven games to
raise his average from .241 to .261.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable at the plate,'' he said.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Chad Hawkins, the Rangers' third-round pick in the
June amateur draft, went on the disabled list at Class-A Savannah
because of right elbow soreness. Hawkins attended Grapevine High
School and Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Darwin Cubillan, the reliever acquired from the Toronto Blue
Jays in the Esteban Loaiza trade, earned his first save for
Triple-A Oklahoma on Sunday. Cubillan worked 1 2/3 scoreless
innings to preserve the RedHawks' 4-2 victory.
nn
</P>
