<HEADER>
A2083 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-RAVENS-LEWIS-HNS &LR;      07-25 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAVENS-LEWIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ravens' Lewis seizes opportunity to turn life around
</P>
<P>
   By RICHARD JUSTICE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Md. _ Ray Lewis could have passed for the happiest
guy on earth Monday morning as he sprinted through the opening
practice of the Baltimore Ravens' training camp. He kidded with
teammates, gave rookies encouraging slaps, and all in all, seemed
to be approaching the whole thing with unbridled joy.
</P>
<P>
   He did not seem to mind the steady rain that fell or the
tropical humidity that made breathing difficult. Nor did he appear
bothered by the reporters who clustered around him to ask some of
the same old questions. The Pro Bowl middle linebacker smiled as he
peeled off his helmet to reveal a face covered in perspiration and
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful for every day I can wake up,'' Lewis said.
``There's joy any time I step on the football field regardless of
what I've been through. I've learned that joy is just waking up
every morning _ not just walking on the football field.''
</P>
<P>
   In another place or time, Lewis might not love training camp so
much. He might not like the early wake-up calls, the long practices
or the late-night meetings. He might not like the six-week grind or
the bumps and bruises he must endure before the Ravens open a
regular season of high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis may be grateful for a lot of little things these days.
He is returning to football seven weeks after having double murder
charges dropped against him. Before then, he had undergone a
4{-month ordeal that began when two men were stabbed to death
outside an Atlanta nightclub in the hours after Super Bowl XXXIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I can imagine how happy he is,'' teammate Shannon Sharpe
said. ``Spending the rest of your life in prison is no joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Until last January, Lewis was known only as one of the NFL's
best linebackers, a rising star who had been chosen for three
consecutive Pro Bowls and led the league in tackles in 1999. Now,
he may never be known for those accomplishments again.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he will be remembered as the guy charged with murder
because of a fight that took place outside a nightclub in which
Lewis partied until 4 a.m. A weak case quickly came undone after
the trial began, and the charges against Lewis were dropped. But
Lewis did plead guilty to a misdemeanor charge of obstructing
justice. In simple terms, he admitted to lying to police during the
murder investigation and is on probation for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis also testified against his two companions, but a jury
acquitted them on all counts. By the time the verdict was read,
Lewis had returned to Maryland to begin preparing for a new season.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his arrest, he seemed the latest in a series of
black eyes for the NFL. Carolina wide receiver Rae Carruth had been
charged with murder a few weeks earlier, so the two of them _
Carruth and Lewis _ became poster boys for what some saw as a
league of thugs. Green Bay tight end Mark Chmura was later charged
with sexual assault, and Indianapolis running back Fred Lane was
shot and killed after a dispute with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is alive and free, but his reputation is badly damaged. He
wasn't guilty of murder, but in the weeks before the trial, it was
revealed he had been charged with domestic abuse by at least one
former girlfriend. He also was captured in an X-rated video
enjoying a raunchy sex act.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while his public image probably is damaged beyond repair and
while he clearly is something less than the model citizen he
occasionally had been portrayed as, it is the murder charges that
could have sent him away for life. And despite the charges, there
wasn't presented a single piece of evidence that he had done
anything except be in the wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   So Monday morning, he was back at work. He declared himself ``in
the best shape'' of his career, thanks in part to Sharpe, who
signed with Baltimore after 10 seasons in Denver. Sharpe befriended
Lewis, and each day after the trial, the two would meet in an
Atlanta gym and lift weights.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the grueling nature of the workouts and the friendly
competition that developed allowed him to survive the stress of the
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon is a friend,'' Lewis said Monday. ``It was a blessing
we came together. Every day I was leaving the courtroom, I went to
work out. I think it kept my mind off it. It kept me settled. We
just went out and worked. I've always worked out, but he helped
give me a little more focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has spoken publicly about the incident only a couple of
times and politely declared the subject off limits Monday. However,
his teammates spoke effusively of their respect for him and the
sympathy they feel for what he has been through.
</P>
<P>
   ``In situations like Ray went through, some people will turn on
you,'' safety Kim Herring said. ``You find out who your friends
are. There wasn't one guy on this team who turned his back on Ray.
We gave him our full support. And we're happy to see him out here.
He's probably one of the happiest guys anyone knows. To go through
what he's gone through and to be able to come back and play, I
think he's probably looking at things in a different light.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe said he warned Lewis that he had better see things
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is young (25),'' Sharpe said. ``But I told Ray that at
some point in time, you can't use age as an excuse. People are
eventually going to think that the decisions he made were a
reflection on the person instead of the age. You have to start
being accountable. I told him he got his one strike; now learn from
it and move on. He's a good guy. He made a mistake. He realizes he
made a mistake. Now, he's going to learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lewis has admitted to is bad judgment and misleading police
investigators. In a news conference after the trial, he explained
why he lied.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're in situations that you've never been in your life, so
you just react,'' he said. ``And when you react, your reactions are
not all the time right. I think what I did was wrong. I'm paying
for it now with 12 months of probation.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the guilty plea, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue
declined to suspend Lewis, saying he already had been punished
enough. Tagliabue did ask Lewis to speak at the league's annual
symposium for rookies to discuss what he had learned from his
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was not on the schedule of speakers, and his appearance
stunned the 254 participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have heard a pin drop,'' said Earnest Byner, the
Ravens' director of player development.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis spoke for 30 minutes and then had two long
question-and-answer sessions. He cautioned the rookies against
associating with the wrong crowd and warned them to be cautious in
their private lives. He received a standing ovation when he was
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``A situation got me to a point to change,'' Lewis told the
rookies, according to a transcript released by the NFL. ``I had a
problem saying no to friends. You will come in contact with people
who always want to do something for you. We have to pick and choose
things we do. We're being watched 24 hours a day. Be firm and stand
on your own two feet. Understand that saying no to a lot of people
is very important. Be firm when you say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that when you step in the NFL, you're on a new
platform. Don't be with people who don't have the same focus as
you. You shouldn't be the only person trying to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his friends outside football insist Lewis has changed
for the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray realizes now that his mission in life is bigger than
football,'' Rev. Richard Harris, who attended the trial as the
linebacker's spiritual adviser, told the Baltimore Sun. ``Football
is just a means to an end, a means to give him a forum to really do
what God has commissioned him to do. This was a test to give Ray a
testimony. He bent, but it didn't break his spirit. It was a test
of faith. I think he passed the test. He's been to hell and back.''
</P>
<P>
   In his only extensive public comments on the matter, Lewis said:
``If there is anything I would change in my lifestyle, it's the
choices I make. I've always been a guy who made great choices,
always been a guy who kept his head on. Everybody stumbles every
once in a while. But I don't think it's about stumbling. It's about
recovery, seeing where you go from there. I would never wish on my
worst enemy to go through what I've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens have attempted to make his return as normal as
possible. Team owner Art Modell has asked his organization to
shield Lewis from ``unwanted exposure and let time take its
course.'' His teammates have embraced him with love and
good-natured kidding. They believe that if the Ravens are as good
as advertised this season, and if Lewis has another Pro Bowl
season, the repairing of his reputation will have begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy it's over and he's out there,'' cornerback Rod
Woodson said. ``We don't want to talk about that anymore. We want
to get on with the season.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
