TECH FIRMS SEE CLOUDS IN CORRIDOR &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The number of technology companies along the
Ventura Freeway Corridor has more than tripled in the past six
years but continued growth could be stifled without more capital
and better infrastructure, according to a study being released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The area from Woodland Hills to Camarillo is now home to 600
companies employing 115,000 people in tech industries, a
significant jump since the recession of the early 1990s, according
to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a hitch: Traffic and housing shortages threaten to
strangle the corridor by its own success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this warning sign on the horizon that we've unearthed
in this report that people might not want to live here,'' said
Rohit Shukla, president/chief executive officer of larta, the Los
Angeles Regional Technology Alliance. ``If companies are going to
have to grow in the corridor, they have to be able to attract the
best and the brightest.''
</P>
<P>
   The 101 Corridor stretches from Woodland Hills in the west San
Fernando Valley to Camarillo in central Ventura County. It
typically includes Chatsworth, Moorpark and Simi Valley,
communities that aren't along the Ventura Freeway but that have
close economic ties to the other corridor communities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, which is being released to coincide with
a conference drawing attention to the region, companies might be
turned off from the region by dwindling office space and rising
lease rates. Their employees _ or perspective employees _ could be
turned off by long commutes and, among younger technology
professionals, a lack of hipness compared with West Los Angeles or
the South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``How Green is Our Valley? Technology and
Transformation Along the Ventura Freeway Corridor,'' says local
universities need to contribute more to the tech work force and
that the area gets far less venture capital proportionally than
either Southern California or the United States as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, said report co-author Shukla, the corridor
needs to build a strong sense of identity like that of the Silicon
Valley. The area he prefers to call the ``101 Corridor'' has a
catchy enough name to take hold nationally but he added that's only
a small part of the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a decent name in its own right,'' he said. ``The
question is can the corporations really extend the brand?''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old organization believes the area has marquee name
employers to match Silicon Valley. The tech corridor is led by
companies like Litton Industries Inc., an employer of 4,000 that
remains predominantly a supplier of military communications
systems, and Amgen, the Thousand Oaks-based biotech drug
manufacturer that began with seven employees in 1980 and now
employs 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   All told, tech-based employers provide one out of every seven
jobs in 101 Freeway Corridor cities, according to the report.
Shukla estimates that when the organization was founded to divert
the defense industry's talent pool into new jobs, there were fewer
than 200 tech companies in the 101 Corridor. The report counts 600
now.
</P>
<P>
   Bonny Herman, president and chief executive officer of the
Valley Industry and Commerce Association, said there had been talk
of billing the area as a technology corridor 10 years ago but that
it never caught on because of the lack of companies in the area at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly the depth of tech companies now to justify
such a designation,'' said Herman, who will address the conference
tonight at the regional headquarters of GTE/Verizon in Thousand
Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Shukla said ``parochial tendencies'' among corridor cities could
dampen its chances of selling itself as a unified entity. The
report said, however, that the corridor is better suited to sell
itself as a place of small-town, family appeal in contrast with the
more urbanized Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the appealing thing about the Ventura
Corridor,'' said Jeff Jordan, GTE/Verizon vice president of sales
and another conference speaker. ``We have very moderately priced
housing in comparison. We have about everything you need here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
