<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO MORE MR. USELESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The last time the Anaheim Angels' Scott
Schoeneweis pitched in a major-league game, he was near tears in
the clubhouse in Baltimore afterward, knowing he was headed to the
disabled list with a strained rib-cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   That was June 16. Five weeks later, Schoeneweis was all smiles
in the clubhouse as he talked about his return to the rotation,
which will be Wednesday against the Texas Rangers. He could laugh
about the nickname he acquired while on the disabled list _ Mr.
Useless.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of Schoeneweis' injury didn't allow him to do much of
anything because it hurt whenever he moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do anything,'' said Schoeneweis, who is 5-5 with a
5.08 ERA in 14 starts. ``The world goes on without you. I didn't
feel part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schoeneweis said he was able to cope with it easier when he
reflected on his past _ he overcame testicular cancer when he was
in college, and he also had elbow surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered back to how I used to deal with stuff when it was
serious,'' he said. ``It's a double-edged sword. (The injury) is
not that bad, but I thought I had my fair share of things going on,
injuries and stuff. It's just one more thing that adds fuel to the
fire. It makes you a better person, a better competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis said he also gets inspiration from veteran pitcher
Tim Belcher, who is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch Belcher every single day,'' Schoeneweis said. ``He's
been hurt the last year or two and nobody in the clubhouse works
harder. It's a testament to his makeup. We might not talk about it,
but I want to be like that when I'm 38 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hands-off policy: Manager Mike Scioscia said he'd prefer not
to tinker with the batting order if possible. Although players like
clean-up hitter Tim Salmon and No. 5 hitter Garret Anderson have
struggled for extended periods this season, Scioscia is not quick
to shake things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the guys we have and you like the chemistry of the
lineup, you'd like to keep it as stable as you can,'' he said.
``You can get to a point where you'd like to be more productive,
but I don't think we're there. It's not like we're mired in a lack
of productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Shortstop Benji Gil returned to Orange County
on Monday to be with his wife Carly, who was scheduled to have
labor induced. It is the couple's first child. . . . Outfielder
Orlando Palmeiro has one career homer and it came here last year on
April 9 off John Burkett. Asked if The Ballpark at Arlington held
any special meaning for him, Palmeiro joked: ``It means nothing to
me, I don't know what you're talking about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
