 HAVE YOU HUGGED YOUR TOURIST?  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Behold the noble tourist.
</P>
<P>
   Today, if this is an average day in San Francisco, he and
145,999 of his brothers and sisters will be touristing throughout
the city.
</P>
<P>
   He will spend his share of the daily tourist outpouring of
kindness and generosity, $17.9 million. That's a lot of Alcatraz
Swim Team T-shirts and walkaway crab cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   If he and his family and the other tourists were to disappear,
every San Francisco resident would have to spend an additional
$8,300 in the city every year to make up for the shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   He arrives in the city by car only 18 percent of the time. When
it comes to Transit First, he shows us the way.
</P>
<P>
   He wears Bermuda shorts not because he is a doofus who can't
read a weather forecast, but because he is an optimist. Sun schmun,
he needs only the warmth of local hospitality and the golden glow
reflected off the city's treasures to ward off the goosebumps. That
and hot coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he knows that nobody ever dies of fogbite.
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of us gripe about waiting for a bus, he waits 90
minutes for a cable car ride, as the cable car crews take the
world's longest breaks.
</P>
<P>
   He gawks and snaps photos because he appreciates the sights that
many of the rest of us have learned to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   So if you come across the tourist today, give him a big hug, and
while you're doing it, don't lift his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST IT WAS resentment. A lot of the pro golf stars didn't
appreciate the kid from Stanford coming to the pro tour without
having won anything and stealing their spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tiger Woods started winning a lot, and resentment gave way
to embarrassment. If you're regaling the girls at the party by
dancing around with the lamp shade on your head, and Pierce Brosnan
walks into the room, your act loses some luster.
</P>
<P>
   Now the other pros have reached the state of shock. They have no
idea how to deal with the Tiger Woods thing. You show up with your
``A'' game, attack the flags like a Marine commando, putt with the
touch of a safecracker, and ... lose like a dog.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago the pros were assuring themselves, ``The kid can't
keep playing like this.'' They were right. He worked the kinks out
of his game.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a golf superstar, good luck on finding a corner stool
in a dark bar where the guy at the other end of the bar doesn't
want to ask you about Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Next tournament, they should give a lovely engraved tin cup to
the winner of the Non-Tiger flight.
</P>
<P>
   And yet: From here, it's a beautiful thing.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN DON JOHNSON met George Michalski 25 years ago, they both
cringed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had just signed to star on a TV series, ``The City,'' he
wrote a theme song for the pilot and needed a musician to help him
nail down the music. Someone told him about Michalski, demon piano
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked like Manson,'' Michalski says, ``and he walked in
wearing a tennis outfit with a sweater tied around his neck. We're
both thinking, `This is  &UR; not  &LR; going to work.'''
</P>
<P>
   They instantly became best pals, were roomies for years, and
Michalski is musical director of Johnson's TV series, ``Nash
Bridges.'' George is the only other cast member who has been with
the show since its start six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Michalski rejects the TV formula of plugging a popular song into
mood spots in the show. He haunts San Francisco clubs for obscure
talent and gives local music a national showcase on ``Nash.'' He
has used the work of more than 50 artists and bands, like White
Trash Debutantes, Gone Jackyls and Blag Dahla.
</P>
<P>
   Michalski also presides over a wild salon/jam gig every Monday
night at Le Colonial. And on the TV show, any time Nash Bridges
walks into a joint that has a piano player, it's George.
</P>
<P>
   ATM MACHINE: I know, that's redundant.
</P>
<P>
   As Brian Lehman points out, ``ATM machine'' is like ``PIN
number,'' ``pre-recorded message'' and ``past history.''
</P>
<P>
   I like redundancies. I could repeat 'em again and again. Maybe
it's a sports thing. In sports, it's ``slam dunk,'' even though all
dunks are slammed and all slams are dunked. It's ``road trip,''
even though there are no stay-at-home trips. Runs batted in are
called ``RBIs,'' even though that would be ``runs-batted-ins.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixed metaphors are welcome here, too. Somebody requested of
Lehman, ``Give me a thumbnail sketch of the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   And Seth Magalaner remembers announcer Dick Stockton on an A's
telecast in '94: ``Here's Dean Palmer. ... he's a dangerous power
hitter but he also strikes out a bit. I guess you could say that's
the double-edged sword he brings to the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   IT'S GREAT that they're taking care not to squish the garter
snakes at the BART-to-SFO construction project. Robin Thomson
wonders if maybe they'd like some more snakes.
</P>
<P>
   Robin lives in Marin County, in a well-civilized-and-paved
suburb, but says her yard is lousy with garter snakes. Robin combed
the Internet for suggestions, hoping to find a humane, St.
Patrick-like method of thinning the herd. Nothing. Got any ideas?
</P>
<P>
   BIG SALE at the Rite Aid on West Portal, reports Maggie Holmes.
The sign in the cold-beverage section last Friday read, ``Back-to
school sale: Red Dog Beer, $5.49 a 12-pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Not sure what school they're referring to, but after a 12-pack
of the 'Dog, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Here's mud in your eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
