<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2099 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHENEY-ANALYSIS-SFCHR     07-25 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS AND DEMOCRATS LIKE CHENEY _ FOR DIFFERENT REASONS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW and CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Not everyone felt comfortable saying so publicly,
but in Republican circles there was at least one universal reaction
to Richard Cheney becoming George W. Bush's running mate:
<P>
   Bush the younger would not repeat the mistake of Bush the elder.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney brings foreign policy expertise, a long resume and a
formidable reputation to the Republican ticket. In stark contrast
to Dan Quayle, George Herbert Walker Bush's running mate 12 years
ago, Cheney _ who at age 34 was President Ford's chief of staff _
is regarded as a heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by tapping his father's former Secretary of Defense, Bush
opens himself up to criticism that, after just 51/2 years of public
service, he is not yet his own man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, Cheney shores up foreign policy, but he opens up the
whole matter of Bush being nothing more than his father's son,''
said Democratic pollster Vic Fingerhut.
</P>
<P>
   Gleeful Democrats _ who early in the day fretted over reports
that retired General Colin Powell might be induced to join the
ticket _ said Cheney would be vulnerable on his conservative
congressional voting record which includes opposition to abortion,
environmental protections and the Equal Rights Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   And they seized upon the image of Bush selecting someone from
the ``old guard,'' as proof of the Governor's lack of political
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's stability and wealth of experience were touted as great
assets by Republicans who welcomed his addition to the ticket.
Cheney's background _ from President Gerald Ford's chief of staff
and 11 years as a member of Congress to President Bush's secretary
of defense _ make him a revered figure in the GOP establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no question from anybody that he's
qualified to be president,'' said Jack Pitney, a professor of
government at Claremont McKenna Colleage, and former aide to Cheney
from his days in the House in the early 1980s. ``You're not going
to have a `Quayle' problem, and that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney immediately adds heft to a ticket that had been
criticized for its lack of experience and foreign policy expertise.
He is not known for his rhetorical flourishes, yet he is well
regarded as a debater and a trusted partisan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney has proven himself a leader of national and
international stature,'' said Rep. Chris Cox, R-Calif., who was
once considered a potential Bush running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quality guy in every respect. ... He commands respect
instantly,'' said Ken Khachigian, the California Republican
political adviser who worked with Cheney in the Nixon
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Kvamme, one of Silicon Valley's most politically active
executives, who met with Bush last week at a high tech summit,
called the choice of Cheney ``terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a good, strong knowledgeable vice president who
understands foreign policy is an extremely important attribute for
us,'' Kvamme said of the tech community. ``I think Silicon Valley
will react very, very well.'' Pitney said his former boss was
``very businesslike,'' not one for small talk, and someone who
commanded great loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   In a period of several months, Cheney went from the man leading
Bush's search for a vice president to Bush's choice. ``My hunch is
that Bush kept stacking up all the competitors against Cheney
himself,'' Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's record in Congress will please conservatives but may
cause trouble for Bush's efforts to win moderate swing voters. Even
before Bush offered the post to Cheney, interest groups began
faxing reporters examples of Cheney's right-wing record which they
said cast doubt on Bush's claim to be a ``compassionate
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, state Democratic Party Chairman Art Torres said
Cheney's record will hand Democrats ``an opportunity to talk about
a woman's right to choose and the environment, which is so
important (here),'' he said. ``Do we want a guy who ran an oil
company when we're trying to protect our coastline?''
</P>
<P>
   And as far as Cheney's ability to reach crucial Latino voters,
he said, ``about the only Latinos these two guys see are at the
country club bussing their dishes in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro-choice advocates wasted no time in lambasting what they
called Cheney's ``fervently anti-choice'' record in his 11-year
stint in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that the big tent just closed. The flap has been
zipped shut,'' said Alice Germond, executive vice president of the
Washington D.C. based National Abortion Rights Action League.
</P>
<P>
   Germond said that in 26 out of 27 of House votes on abortion,
Cheney's anti-choice positions included supporting bans of federal
funding for poor women, U.S. servicewomen and army dependents
seeking abortion, even in cases of rape, incest or life of the
mother. And he supported legislation to prohibit women enrolled in
federal health plans from choosing insurance companies that
provided abortion coverage, even in those extreme cases, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear message of where Bush himself really stands,
where the GOP stands,'' she said. ``All the flirtations of being
moderate and compassionate were merely that. It was an attempt to
deceive the moderate pro-choice voter.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists also decried the Cheney nomination. The League
of Conservation Voters said Cheney has a 13 percent lifetime
environmental voting record. Robert Cox, president of the Sierra
Club, said he was disappointed Bush would choose a running mate
with ``a dirty record.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, the Sierra Club said in a release, voted to sustain
President Ronald Reagan's veto of the Clean Water Act, against
citizens' rights to sue polluters, and had a zero percent
environmental voting record in 1989 _ his last year in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adding Cheney to Bush's ticket would make a bad situation for
the environment worse,'' said Cox. ``A Bush-Cheney ticket would be
just what the oil industry wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats displayed no shyness in bringing up Cheney's health
problems, which include three mild heart attacks and quadruple
bypass surgery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cheney advance people might want to purchase some smelling
salts,'' said Bob Mulholland, a consultant to the California
Democratic Party. ``They're going to need jumper cables with him
everywhere they go.''
</P>
<P>
   (Marc Sandalow reported from Washington. Carla Marinucci
reported from San Francisco.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
