<SLUG> BC-ESTRADA-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOISY PROTEST GREETS PHILIPPINE PRESIDENT IN SAN FRANCISCO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENJAMIN PIMENTEL, MARK MARTIN and CHUCK SQUATRIGLIA 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Philippine President Joseph Estrada's first
official visit to America was met Monda night by a crowd of
boisterous protesters who gathered outside his San Francisco hotel
to demand an end to his nation's war against Muslim insurgents.
<P>
   Estrada received a warm welcome from a sympathetic audience
dining on filet mignon and portobello mushrooms at the Fairmont
Hotel, a counterpoint to the protesters outside who denounced the
corruption, war and political instability they claim he has brought
to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, 63, is visiting the United States this week to ask
President Clinton for more military aid and to urge Silicon Valley
firms _ including Intel, Oracle and Sun Microsystems _ to set up
shop in the Southeast Asian nation he has led since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear last night if Estrada saw or heard the 200
demonstrators when his entourage arrived at the Fairmont in four
buses shortly after 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters said the prosperity that Estrada's predecessor, Fidel
Ramos, brought to the Philippines has waned over the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came from there,'' said demonstrator Rudy Sacatlang,
65, who recently moved to San Lorenzo from the Philippines. ``Life
is so hard there. Investors are moving out because they are afraid.
There's no stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacatlang and other protesters chanted anti-Estrada slogans in
English and Tagalog as they marched up Powell Street to the
Fairmont.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine president ignored his critics, whom police kept
behind barricades across the street, as he entered the hotel to
deliver a speech. He was expected to defend his campaign against
the Muslim rebels and extol the benefits of investing in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   His speech was a warmup for Tuesday's main event: lunch with
Silicon Valley executives Estrada desperately wants to invest in
the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its high-tech industry, the Bay Area is important
to Estrada because it is home to more than a quarter-million
Filipinos. But many of them are disturbed by the way the one-time
movie star is running their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue Estrada has made a mess of the Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
   Although inflation has fallen and the nation's gross domestic
product has climbed under Estrada's watch, unemployment stands at
13.9 percent _ the highest level in nine years _ and one-third of
the nation's 80 million people live in extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Their plight was highlighted two weeks ago when more than 200
people were killed in Manila after a gargantuan heap of garbage
where they eked out a meager living collapsed in an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, who came to office amid vows to help the poor, also has
been dogged by allegations of corruption and cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   But it is his ongoing war against the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front, a rebel army fighting for an independent Muslim state on the
Philippine island of Mindanao, that most troubles his critics in
the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shown that he's completely inept at addressing the needs
of the people,'' said protester Rhonda Ramiro of the Committee for
Human Rights in the Philippines. ``Housing, jobs and health care
are what he should be addressing, not military spending.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving San Francisco Tuesday evening, Estrada will travel
to Washington, D.C., to ask President Clinton for more military aid
_ needed, in part, to sustain his administration's campaign against
the Moro rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have indicated Estrada will get the
money he is after because, as one administration official put it,
the Philippines ``are our good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Fairmont, Estrada's supporters defended the president
but called on him to make peace with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think President Estrada should work on making peace in
Mindanao,'' said Carmelo Rocco, a Filipino American physician in
San Francisco. ``We don't want a Jihad.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's administration has argued that the negative reports
about their work are unfair and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada's press secretary, Ricardo Puno, noted that the
country's economic woes are largely rooted in the Asian financial
crisis that began in 1997. The collapse of Southeast Asian
currencies began a flight of capital and a downturn from which the
region is still trying to recover, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Puno dismissed accusations of government corruption as
unfounded, and he defended the military operation against the Moro
rebels in the south as a campaign to protect Philippine
sovereignty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
