<SLUG> BC-LA-HEALTH-LADN </SLUG>
 
HOMICIDES, SUICIDES THE BIGGER KILLERS IN COUNTY &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY ANDERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles County residents have been more likely
to die a violent death than an accidental death, according to a
county report released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, titled The Health of Angelenos, also found that the
county's birth rate has fallen steadily from a high of 22.9 births
per 1,000 residents in 1990 to 17 births per 1,000 in 1997, largely
the result of changing birth patterns among immigrants, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The report, analyzing data from 1990 to 1998, was conducted to
help the county reduce health disparities between racial and ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most surprising findings was that intentional
injuries _ homicides and suicides _ accounted for 54 percent of all
injury deaths, as compared to 46 percent of injury deaths resulting
from accidents, including motor vehicle crashes, poisonings and
falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a concern,'' county Health Officer Dr. Jonathan E.
Fielding said.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police Sgt John Pasquariello said the city has
experienced a recent spike in violent crime, mainly a result of
gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're addressing those issues,'' he said. ``Crime is up
lately, but it's been down historically over the last 10 years.
People tend to forget that 10 years ago we had almost 1,000
homicides a year and now we're down to less than 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielding attributed the high rate of violent deaths to the
availability of guns and the growth of the young adult population.
``Certainly, you have to relate those kinds of numbers to concerns
in the educational system and job opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielding said the dropping birthrates are a result of a
reduction in teen-age pregnancies and recent immigrants adapting to
American culture and having fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The norm here is a smaller number of children, and we have
lower rates of illness and death among children than those other
places,'' he said. ``That generally leads over time to a lowering
of birthrates.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that 30 percent of Latinos, 27 percent of
Asians and Pacific Islanders, 18 percent of African-Americans and
12 percent of whites consider their health to be fair or poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a good predictor of how healthy people are and their
mortality risk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also found that half of the adults in the county are
obese.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a growing epidemic,'' Fielding said. ``The point is
that excess weight increases risks for many serious diseases and is
a major cause of mortality. We need to really sound the alarm
bell.''
</P>
<P>
   Fielding said the increase in obesity is related to the fact
that 20 percent of men and 23 percent of women in the state do not
exercise outside of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, the more important exercise gets in terms
of overall health maintenance,'' Fielding said. ``If you don't
start a pattern of exercise early in life, it's much less likely
you'll continue to exercise throughout your life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     07-25 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODRIGUEZ HURT IN ANGELS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ In a sense, Mo Vaughn passed the baton to Ivan
Rodriguez, one former MVP to another. Only Vaughn did it with such
force that Rodriguez will miss the rest of the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, the 1999 American League MVP and nine-time All-Star
catcher, suffered a broken bone in his right thumb and will have
surgery today. His right hand hit Vaughn's bat during the
follow-through of a throw to second base in the first inning of the
Anaheim Angels' bizarre 6-5, 12-inning win Monday night over the
Texas Rangers before 33,201 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   As Kevin Stocker tried to steal second, Vaughn swung and missed
at strike three. And, as he often does, Vaughn fell toward the
plate during the follow-through of his swing, leading to the
contact with Rodriguez's hand. The break _ at the base of the first
metacarpal bone _ was discovered by X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I hit it, my finger went numb,'' Rodriguez said.
``I didn't feel anything and it started to swell up. From that
moment I just knew it was broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens when a team's not going good,'' Rodriguez
added. ``Bad things happen. What can you do but get ready for
spring training next year.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened with Rodriguez might have been a freak play, but
it was nothing compared to the strange 10th inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were one strike away from losing in the ninth when
Scott Spiezio hit a two-run homer off Rangers closer John Wetteland
at 5. But in the 10th, the Rangers were in good position to win it,
putting runners on second and third with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Darin Erstad was brought in to form a five-man
infield, playing on the second baseman's side of second base.
</P>
<P>
   With the count 1-1 to Gabe Kapler, home-plate umpire Gerry Davis
called a balk on Angels pitcher Shigetoshi Hasegawa. Scarborough
Green raced in from third and the Rangers celebrated a victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the normally mild-mannered Hasegawa argued vehemently.
Angels manager Mike Scioscia stormed out of the dugout to argue,
too, and soon after the four umpires talked it over. After a few
minutes, the umpires waved both teams back on the field and
reversed the balk call.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler then popped out to the catcher, Erstad moved back to left
field, and after an intentional walk to Mike Lamb, Hasegawa got
Royce Clayton on a fly to center for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa (7-2) got the win with three scoreless innings. Tim
Salmon's two-out RBI single in the 12th scored Adam Kennedy with
what turned out to be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Monday's outcome, the Rangers' season has been a
disappointment. They've been in last place most of the season, and
now with Rodriguez out, there could be some big changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people have had their hands on the plug, and
they just haven't yanked it,'' Rangers GM Doug Melvin said. ``This
is a veteran club. We can't feel sorry for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he didn't blame Vaughn for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Rodriguez said. ``Mo is a very clean player. He
plays the game good. I don't think it was on purpose. He swung the
bat and it crossed the plate. It happens to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Vaughn, the American League's MVP in 1995, who was slowed
all of last season after injuring his left ankle on opening night.
He's never had a strikeout carry so much impact as Monday's. Vaughn
called the Rangers dugout during the game and ``wasn't feeling very
good'' when he heard the news.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have had their share of injuries this season,
including losing outfielder Ruben Mateo and pitcher Justin Thompson
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a year where the doctors have had more press
conferences than me,'' Melvin said. ``We all have injuries . . .
you almost take Pudge for granted, that he'll always be out there.
You have to realize it could happen to anyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
