A2106 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      07-25 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-SLUG-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DAVE WALKER'S WEB &AMP; MAGAZINE REVIEWS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Dave Walker's reviews of a Web site and current
magazines:
</P>
<P>
   WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   www.nationalreview.com
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL REVIEW ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of cutting-edge conservative thought on the
National Review Online site as well as the kind of tireless Clinton
watchdoggerel you'd expect plus movie reviews (''If you are easily
offended, (beginitalic)Scary Movie (enditalic)is not the film for
you'') and a clumsy link to electronic-commerce opportunities. Upon
discovering which, we felt immediately compelled to drop everything
and shop for - what else? - a not-too-loud necktie. The very first
selection offered us by the National Review Online Marketplace,
however, came from the Jerry Garcia Collection, and that freaked us
so far out that we had to quit and do freestyle spins around the
room for a couple of hours. But not before discovering another
nifty aspect of the site, Bill Buckley's Word of the Day, a daily
interactive vocabulary-building game, which we aced on the first
try by picking Answer C, ``Strictures,'' as the perfect fit for the
definition ``the demands, restrictions, requirements of.'' Proving
that we remain world-class guessers at multiple-choice questions.
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``RED HERRING''
</P>
<P>
   Hitch up your truss and lift with your legs, not your back. It's
another hefty slab of gab about venture capital and electronic
gizmos, accompanied by stylish graphics signifying who knows what.
The future of energy is the center-of-the-book theme, so follow the
mustard-colored tabs atop the key pages to get there, pausing first
to check out the Lexicon column on page 72. There writer Peter
Rojas hunts down and kills (we (beginitalic)wish(enditalic)) the
phrase ``thinking outside the box,'' among our era's least
meaningful and most-abused cliches. The phrase comes from the
brain-teasing Puzzle of the Nine Dots, created by Brit
mathematician Henry Ernest Dude!ney - ! added for emphasis {ndash}
way back in the 1900s. The puzzle asks players to connect a box
pattern of dots and is solvable only by drawing connecting lines
outside of the grid.
</P>
<P>
   ``OXFORD AMERICAN''
</P>
<P>
   This regional delight has been getting positive publicity in
recent months because its funding angel - author John Grisham -
chose its pages for the serialization of his latest novel,
(beginitalic)A Painted House(enditalic). Chapters 19 through 23
occupy the cream-colored paper stock at the issue's center, but the
material that surrounds the Grisham pages is why you (might,
depending) want a copy. The annual music issue includes
passion-packed writing about such Southern lights as Dolly Parton,
Doc Watson, Tom Petty and Big Mama Thornton. A few not-so-Southern
artists - Randy Newman, for one -also get similar treatment.
Tempe's own Ron Carlson writes fondly of Dean Martin.
</P>
<P>
   A free CD compilation of the featured artists is included.
Subscription info: www.oxfordamericanmag.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``WIRED''
</P>
<P>
   The usual collection of e-centric topics includes a piece about
e-paper (the future of printing, maybe), e-satire (Garry Trudeau's
dot-comic presidential campaign for his Uncle Duke character from
(beginitalic)Doonesbury(enditalic)) and the e-future in general (an
interview with Xerox PARC boss John Seely Brown). But the two most
interesting articles involve such pre-e technologies as blimps and
boats. The first details the CargoLifter project, a German baron's
attempt to revive the lighter-than-air airship industry, which has
suffered a bit of a downturn since the Hindenburg unpleasantness.
The second hits the beach at Alang, India, where supertankers are
dismantled for scrap. The stark photos of the grime-clogged chop
shop ``speak to the developed world about the real cost of
profligate production and premature obsolescence,'' writes Paul
Saffo, who took them.
</P>
<P>
   ``VANITY FAIR''
</P>
<P>
   ``When anything is blocking my head, I just {ndash}
(beginitalic)whoosh (enditalic){ndash} go sit on Mars and look back
here at Earth,'' says (beginitalic)The Patriot (enditalic)substar
and young cover hunk Heath Ledger, portrayed within as possessing
once-in-a-generation star quality. Says (beginitalic)Patriot
(enditalic)superstar Mel Gibson: ``He's much more grounded than I
was at that age, when it all started happening for me. I think
he'll handle it better than I did.'' Other features include a
profile of Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, an unpleasant visit to Sierra
Leone and a much-needed Bo Derek update replete with a couple of
hubba-hubba photos. Steve Garbarino drops in on Robert Downey Jr.,
who, thanks to a drug charge, is currently a guest of the state of
California. Asked her idea of perfect happiness, Proust
Questionnaire subject Phyllis Diller answers: ``Any day that
doesn't require dentistry or exercise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
