<HEADER>
A2107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-Astroslate-HNS &LR;      07-25 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Astros </SLUG>
 late-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros finally win third in a row
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ With victories so hard to come by this season, the
Astros won't soon forget Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Playing one of their most inspired games, the Astros extended
their winning streak to a season-high three with a 7-5
come-from-behind victory over the Cincinnati Reds at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was clearly the biggest win of the year for us,'' manager
Larry Dierker said after the Astros rallied from a three-run
deficit to pull out the victory in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 5-2, the Astros scored two runs in the sixth, one
in the ninth and two in the 10th. Glen Barker hit an RBI single
with two out in the top of the 10th to put the Astros ahead, and
Bill Spiers added a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge. There are so many positives to say about this
game,'' said Astros outfielder Lance Berkman, who tied the game at
5 in the ninth with a sacrifice fly. ``This was really the first
time we put it all together _ solid pitching, clutch hitting and
good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of heroes Monday:
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen, in relief of starter Chris Holt, combined
to hold the Reds scoreless over the final five innings. Octavio
Dotel picked up his first victory since May 1 with two perfect
innings of relief, which included four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Like Barker, Matt Mieske came off the bench and delivered a
clutch two-out single. Mieske's hit in the sixth drove in two runs
to pull the Astros within 5-4. Entering the game, Astros pinch
hitters were hitting an anemic .141.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, Berkman gunned down Ken Griffey Jr. when he tried to
stretch a single into a double. Second baseman Craig Biggio, who
went 3-for-6, made a diving grab of a grounder toward the hole to
rob Griffey. And Richard Hidalgo made a catch as he crashed into
the wall in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is in a great mood,'' said Berkman, who tied a
career high with three hits. ``It's really a mood we haven't seen
in the clubhouse in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the final two games of their weekend series with
National League Central-leading St. Louis, the Astros became the
last team in the majors this season to win three straight games,
the victory coming in their 99th game of the season. The last team
to go that deep into the season without winning three games in a
row was the 1985 Pittsburgh Pirates, who didn't win three straight
until their 145th game.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros appeared headed for another loss after the Reds
erased a pair of bases-empty home runs by Biggio and Hidalgo to go
ahead 5-2. Sean Casey delivered a two-run single in the fourth,
extending his hitting streak to 16 games, and Griffey provided a
three-run triple in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Houston slowly chipped away at the lead. Mieske, who pinch-hit
for Holt, hit a two-run single to left off Dennys Reyes, pulling
the Astros within 5-4. Berkman forced extra innings with a
sacrifice fly to center field off Danny Graves (9-2) with one out
in the ninth. It marked the first blown save for the Reds' bullpen
since June 21, snapping a streak of nine straight successful save
conversions.
</P>
<P>
   In he 10th, Mitch Meluskey hit a one-out double, and Barker
worked the count before sending a 2-2 pitch from Graves through the
hole at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't get many at-bats, you have to go out and
scramble and put the ball in play,'' Barker said.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers followed with a single to almost the exact same location,
driving in the Astros' final run. In the last two games, Spiers is
5-for-11 with seven RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel (2-5), who was moved from the starting rotation to the
bullpen on July 4, retired all six batters he faced, recording the
final out when Alex Ochoa popped out in foul territory behind home
plate. Dotel has yet to allow a run in seven relief appearances
covering eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go out there thinking a different way. I'm a closer now,''
said Dotel, who took over that duty for injured lefthander Billy
Wagner. ``My job is to try and keep the game close and give the
team a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in 10 days, Biggio came up a triple short of
the cycle. He homered in the first, doubled in the third and
singled in the fifth. He grounded to third and struck out in his
final two at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the first, Biggio hit his seventh home run into
the right-field corner. Hidalgo added a no-doubter to left-center
in the fourth inning _ No. 29 on the season _ and is one homer away
from becoming only the fifth player in club history to reach 30 in
a single season. The club record is 43, set by Jeff Bagwell in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who rank second in the National League with 149
homers, have hit eight over the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   After winning three straight division titles, the Astros now
find themselves trying to play the spoiler's role in the final two
months of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the character of the guys here to not quit and keep
playing hard,'' Biggio said. ``It's unfortunate our record is what
it is, but the least we can do is go out and give 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
