<HEADER>
A2108 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLICK WILL GET PLAYERS, NOT PLAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Pat Gillick emerged from his office around 5 p.m.,
another round of cat-and-mouse complete.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Mariners general manager calls this countdown to
Monday's trading deadline a poker game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like ... who's going to blink first?'' Gillick
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For clubs who have players that are attractive, you can't
blame them for trying to make the best deal possible. We have to
somewhat overpay, but we can't get completely scammed.''
</P>
<P>
   No, you can't. And you can't go too far down the road with one
deal, only to reach a dead end. And you can't waste time being
played for the fool.
</P>
<P>
   Mets GM Steve Phillips must be feeling that way. After thinking
New York had a shot at renting Barry Larkin, Phillips was left at
the altar.
</P>
<P>
   Reds GM Jim Bowden played the Mets to perfection, getting fans
in Cincinnati to cry over Larkin _ a formula that embarrassed Reds
owner Carl Lindner into signing the All-Star shortstop to the same
$27 million deal the Reds weren't willing to make until Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of mess won't take place in Seattle this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we heard about the Mets and Reds. Pat would be harder to
get into that kind of situation. He's pretty aware of the issues
involved,'' said Roger Jongewaard, Mariners VP of scouting and
player development.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus around baseball is that whatever deal or deals
Gillick makes in the next seven days, he won't be the one who gets
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to fry bigger fish than I have to offer him. He's
going for the big strike, and I don't have position players,''
Dodgers GM Kevin Malone said Monday from L.A., where Malone is
trying to upgrade his team.
</P>
<P>
   From their days together in Baltimore, Malone said he would be
shocked if Gillick didn't make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he won't leave any stone unturned. He's built that team
around that ballpark. He did it quickly, and they've proved they
can win. No, it's about how to make them better,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   What Gillick did in Baltimore and Toronto, citizens of
Marinerville are right to anticipate here as well. The Mariners may
need only a role player _ a left-handed batter who can hit .280 and
won't strike out. But it appears Gillick is heading toward a bigger
deal, possibly two.
</P>
<P>
   When you're Gillick, the man who traded for Joe Carter and
Roberto Alomar and won two World Series, the pressure is on to
continue your tradition of blockbuster deals.
</P>
<P>
   No one who knows Gillick, or works with him, will downplay what
he is capable of doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat is probably the most passionate (GM in baseball). He has a
very creative mind,'' Jongewaard said. ``He talks baseball 24 hours
a day. He comes in, in the morning, with a whole bunch of new
ideas. He doesn't even write anything down. He memorizes phone
numbers, deals and comments. He just puts them in his computer
upstairs _ in his brain.''
</P>
<P>
   While former Mariners GM Woody Woodward was structured and
rigid, Gillick is fluid and inquisitive, and fully capable of
delegating to all his deputies in an effort that has energized the
Mariners' staff.
</P>
<P>
   While Woodward had no escape hatches in many of the deals he
started discussing, Gillick will pull out the second he senses the
other team has set the price too high.
</P>
<P>
   Remember 1998, when the Yankees and Indians tied Woodward up in
knots in bogus trade discussions about Randy Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was led down the primrose path by the two American
League powerhouses. In the 11th hour, Woodward realized neither
team wanted to make the trade, and he was left to make the only
deal he had left, with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Woodward was more lucky than good. The Mariners did
not get their first two choices, but Freddy Garcia, Carlos Guillen
and John Halama were excellent consolation prizes.
</P>
<P>
   It could have just as easily been as bad as the time Woodward
sent Jason Varitek and Derek Lowe to Boston for Heathcliff Slocumb
while Mariners fans wailed in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Mariners face a trading deadline in the same
position they did in 1995 and '97. They are contending, in a
position to push to improve.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, instead of merely having a shot at their
division, the Mariners are good enough to consider making deals
that give them a shot at representing the AL in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Flush with pitching, the Mariners head to the deadline in a
position of strength for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this strength has not opened the door for a pre-deadline
deal. Prices are too high, Mariners officials say, and Gillick has
his eye not just on 2000, but 2001 and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   If Mariners manager Lou Piniella has clamored for a deal with
Kansas City for Johnny Damon, the left-handed bat the Mariners
need, it is Gillick who has refused to be bullied into paying the
asking price of Ryan Anderson, Joel Pineiro and/or Gil Meche.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what our priorities are,'' Gillick said.
</P>
<P>
   For all the buildup to the trading deadline, this is not his
favorite week in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to try and keep everything focused. Sometimes, other
people don't really (hold the line on reasonable trades) and are
willing to probably give a lot more than they should,'' Gillick
said. ``There are certain situations where you're going to give
more than you anticipated, but you can't get ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Cat-and-mouse. Poker. Whatever. Gillick is playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
