<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     07-25 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS EARN WIN AND A LITTLE PAYBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Manager Davey Johnson and left fielder Gary Sheffield
said it was just one of those pitches that happened to slip, a
Kevin Brown fastball that drilled Colorado's Todd Helton in the
back.
</P>
<P>
   It came an inning after Sheffield, already with a double,
triple, homer and three RBI, was plunked in the back Colorado's
Julian Tavarez.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was Brown watching Sheffield's back. Or perhaps it was
just coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever it was, it added a bit of theatrics in a pair of
sublime solo performances by Brown and Sheffield, who combined to
lift the Los Angeles Dodgers past the Rockies 4-1 Monday at Coors
Field to open a 10-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Brown (10-3) allowed three hits and one run in eight innings,
and taunted the altitude by getting 16 outs via ground balls in a
ballpark known for fly balls. Brown didn't allow a hit until Todd
Walker's one-out triple in the third, ending a string of 11 innings
in which he didn't allow a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fetters had a scare in the ninth when the Rockies had
back-to-back singles with one out, but he retired Helton and Brent
Mayne for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference pitching (at Coors Field), but you can't
let it affect you, you can't let it beat you before you walk out
there,'' Brown said. ``You have to make adjustments. You have to
expect your ball to move differently and you have to plan for that.
You can't throw the breaking balls that start off high and expect
them to still break. You have to start off lower. Just little
things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's triple in the first inning gave the Dodgers a 1-0
lead. He doubled in a run in the third to make it 2-0, and his
major league-leading 34th homer in the fifth gave the Dodgers a 3-0
lead. An RBI single by Shawn Green in the seventh accounted for the
Dodgers' fourth run.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's lone run came via Butch Huskey's homer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie's just awesome. He's not necessarily going hard all
the time, but putting a lot of movement on the ball,'' Johnson
said. ``That effort in this ballpark is just unbelievable.
(Sheffield) had the tough part of the cycle and then he gets
drilled in the back and then they don't even come close to pitching
to him. The Sheff and Brownie Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, in theory, had a chance to join Wes Parker (1970) as
the only Los Angeles Dodger to hit for the cycle, but he never got
a real chance.
</P>
<P>
   Having battered starter Rolando Arrojo around Coors Field,
Sheffield was hit in the middle of the back in the seventh inning
by Tavarez's first pitch. Sheffield said it knocked the air out of
him.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Brown retired Jeff Cirillo on a fly
ball to center field and hit Helton in the middle of the back with
his first pitch. Home-plate umpire Jeff Kellogg warned both
benches, but Colorado manager Buddy Bell argued, stating Brown
intentionally threw at Helton.
</P>
<P>
   As a chorus of boos rained upon Brown, he calmly got Mayne to
ground into a double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Sheffield) is seeing the ball well, he's staying center and
he's hitting pitches,'' said second baseman Mark Grudzielanek, who
scored the Dodgers' first two runs. ``You don't like to see (the
beanball) stuff. The last thing we need to do is have a brawl with
these guys, but on the other hand, I can understand Brownie's
reaction toward it. That's baseball. That's the way it's going to
be and you have to protect your guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's final chance at the cycle, in hindsight, really
wasn't that much of an opportunity. Sheffield, who leads the
Dodgers with a .342 average and 84 RBI, led off the ninth and was
walked on four not-even-close pitches by reliever Bobby Chouinard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
