u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      07-25 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER MASTERS ATHLETICS AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners opened the evening by getting another big
performance from a guy who has earned a reputation as a big-game
pitcher, Jamie Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   They the night three hours, 31 minutes later by getting a big
performance from a guy who is earning the same kind of reputation,
Kazuhiro Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   After Moyer held down Oakland as the Mariners carved out a 6-3
lead, Sasaki took over in the ninth inning and, despite allowing a
run, put away the Athletics in dramatic style, striking out Oakland
homer and RBI leader Jason Giambi on with a laser fastball, for a
6-4 Mariners victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, Sasaki had thrown exactly what catcher Joe Oliver
had called for. Forkball. Followed by forkball. Followed by
forkball. Each of the first eight pitches was a forkball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to throw the fastball,'' Sasaki said, aware that
Giambi is one of the game's best dead fastball hitters. ``I knew
sooner or later Joe would call it.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Oliver did that, with a runner at second and two out
and a 3-2 count on Giambi, the almost full Safeco Field crowd had
just about screamed itself hoarse. But there were enough nerve
endings left in the larynx to give forth one more roar as Sasaki
blasted a called third strike past Giambi for his 14th consecutive
save row (24th overall), tying Mike Timlin's 1998 club record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up a walk and a run,'' Sasaki said. ``I wanted to show
the fans my good pitches. I put a lot of feeling into it.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, did Moyer, now 11-3 after beating the A's for the sixth
consecutive time and the second time in a week.
</P>
<P>
   There are many pitchers with bigger pitches than Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners will insist, however, there aren't many pitchers
with a bigger heart.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the soft-throwing, hard-working Moyer came up with a
win in the important first game of a series with second-place
Oakland. The victory stretched the Mariners' lead in the American
League West to five games over the A's and also over Anaheim, which
beat Texas to move into a tie for the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland makes you work for whatever you get,'' Moyer said.
``They've got a good club, and they can really drive the ball. The
key to beating them is to keep away from the big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what Moyer did, giving up a two-run single to
Ryan Christenson in the fifth inning that made it 5-3 but otherwise
keeping the cantankerous Oakland bats in check.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly Moyer threw changeups. And mostly the A's either missed
them or didn't hit them with any authority.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the runs off Moyer were earned.
</P>
<P>
   Picked up by Seattle in the middle of the 1996 season, Moyer is
57-25 since the start of the 1997 season and 63-27 overall as a
Mariner. Small wonder then that manager Lou Piniella went out of
his way to set up his rotation so that the 37-year-old lefty would
face Oakland twice in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie pitched a nice game,'' Piniella said, ``especially
having to pitch against that club the second time around.''
</P>
<P>
   On a night when shortstop Alex Rodriguez, out since July 7, was
activated and eligible to pinch-hit, the Mariners didn't need him.
They scored five runs in the first four innings against Appier,
then added one run late to put the game in the win column.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had Alex ready,'' Piniella said. ``I'm glad we didn't have
to use him, though. I wanted to wait one more day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners got a big home run from Edgar Martinez, his 25th,
in the fourth inning, then added a bottom-of-the-eighth run on a
Mike Cameron single and stolen base, then an RBI hit by David Bell,
all of which helped Moyer keep his mastery over the A's intact..
</P>
<P>
   Moyer opened the game by pitching into the fourth inning without
allowing a hit. He gave up a couple of hits in the fourth, but it
was an error by third baseman David Bell that allowed an unearned
run to score.
</P>
<P>
   Two more runs came across in the fifth on a two-out hit by
Christenson, but by that time, the Mariners had built up a 5-1
lead, so the damage wasn't too severe.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer lasted until the seventh, when A's shortstop Miguel Tejada
beat out an infield grounder, leading Piniella to go to his
bullpen. Although Jose Paniagua surrendered a walk and was
replaced, Arthur Rhodes pitched 12/3 impressive innings of relief,
then turned the ball over to Sasaki in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
