<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEY-TALK0726-COX     07-25 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    People in 20s, 30s seem more financially astute
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stores are jammed with personal finance books, but
not many are tailored for young people.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that financial beginners don't have much money and
don't cause a lot of stir in the marketplace. Another reason may be
that young people haven't shown a great deal of interest in the
discipline, delayed gratification and long-term thinking that are
essential to building a financial stake.
</P>
<P>
   Those things may be changing. Studies suggest that people in
their 20s and 30s are saving and investing more these days.
</P>
<P>
   Author Beth Kobliner _ 35 years old and already an old hand in
the financial advice trade _ adds that the young are more alert to
the financial side of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a dramatic learning curve in the last few
years,'' Kobliner said in a recent interview. ``Four years ago,
when I wrote my first book, I had to explain what a mutual fund is.
Now pretty much everybody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobliner passed through Atlanta recently to talk up the newly
published second edition of her best seller, ``Get a Financial
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are highlights from an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do you think young people are better informed? Is there a
sense of increased responsibility?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, there are all these 24-hour financial shows on cable
TV. I was on jury duty in New York a few months ago. We were right
near Little Italy. In all these little cafes, they had CNBC on.
There are now literally thousands of investing Web sites. People
are researching, but in many cases they haven't seen the big
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do 401(k)s make people more responsible?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's one factor. Also, there is more of a sense that if you
don't do this, you're missing out on an opportunity. That's why
young people are trying to put at least a little money away. With
that, they have to make decisions _ stocks, bonds or a mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a lot of people in their 20s and 30s have credit cards.
The average credit card debt for young people is $2,500. Then you
can add $10,000 to $12,000 for student loans. So they are forced to
pay attention to their finances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has the boom in stocks made a difference?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the last 10 years, the market has quadrupled. Even if you
weren't investing, you would notice by osmosis that things have
changed. Students tell me, ``My roommate has a beeper, and his
broker is always calling him.''
</P>
<P>
   The money thing is much more a part of the zeitgeist of our
times. Even on TV shows, like ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
There's a lot of orientation towards money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Would you say this generation is nervous about their money?
Or are they more greedy? What's their emotional relationship with
money?
</P>
<P>
   A: The media has portrayed these young people as movers and
shakers _ young people getting into dot-com jobs and making more
money right out of college than their parents did. The reality is
different. Young people, on average, are earning less than people
of their age group in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 percent, the ones who get science degrees or graduate
from the top schools, they're doing dramatically better. I think
there's a sense among that top 10 percent that the sky is the
limit. They are maxed out in their 401(k)s. They're interested in
investing.
</P>
<P>
   But a large chunk of young people don't do as well as their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   That group is kind of hoping to be lifted with the tide, but a
lot of them feel they've missed the boat. There was a poll recently
that showed 82 percent of young people feel they have benefited
little or not at all from the stock market boom.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the greatest concerns you hear?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of young people have heavy debt and don't know how
they're going to get out of it. They're struggling to pay their
bills. There's a concern about how they're going to get out of
debt, and, after that, how they are ever going to save any money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can they cope?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you're carrying credit card debt and student loans, credit
cards generally are charging you higher rates. Paying off those
high-rate card debts first makes sense, particularly now that the
interest on student loans is deductible. With the deduction, you
change the effective rate from 8 percent to an effective rate of
about 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about rainy-day savings?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm a real believer in having an emergency fund, having
enough to pay your living expenses for at least three months. After
that, I think it makes the most sense to pay off those higher-rate
debts first.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's next?
</P>
<P>
   A: If they have 401(k)s with a matching feature, they have a
tremendous investment opportunity. Some companies say, ``For every
dollar you put in, (we'll) put in 50 cents or a dollar.'' That's an
immediate return on your money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Clearly some people aren't making much money, and putting
aside even $5 a day would be a problem. What do you say to them?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of young people say, ``I don't have any money to
save.'' But the reality is that when you're in your 20s, that's
when you have the fewest obligations. You don't have kids. You
don't have a home, generally. This is a very good time to scale
back a little here and there. It's so much easier than it will be
in your 30s and 40s. People think they'll get around to it when
they have more money. The reality is you'll never get around to it
until you make yourself.
</P>
<P>
   You get a raise every year, and often it's higher than the cost
of living. If it beats the cost of living, you have extra money
that you didn't have last year. You can just have the money taken
out of your checking account before you touch it. Even if it's just
$25 a month, you can put it into some sort of stock fund and you'll
never have to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you recommend for starter investments?
</P>
<P>
   A: You could begin with money market mutual funds to build your
emergency cushion, then move up to index funds. It seems to me it's
really hard to argue with index funds, particularly for people who
don't want to spend their lives looking at their investments. A lot
of people don't care that much. They just want to make sure they do
a little better than inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Somewhere in all this, don't you need an overall financial
plan?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, you can build your emergency fund, pay off high-rate
debt and get into a 401(k), if you can.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get beyond that, you can ask, ``What do I want from
life?''
</P>
<P>
   PAYING YOUR DEBTS
</P>
<P>
   How many months it will take to pay off credit card debt.
</P>
<P>
   How it works: Estimate what percentage of your debt you can pay
each month on your existing debt.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you owe $1,000 and can afford to pay $30 a
month, your payment will be 3 percent. Look down the left column to
find the percentage that works for you.
</P>
<P>
   Scan across the top row and find the annual interest rate
imposed by your credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Read across from the percent you can pay and down from the
interest rate on your card. At the intersection is the number of
months it will take to pay your bill.
</P>
<P>
   Annual interest rate
</P>
<P>
   8 % 10 % 12 % 14 % 16 % 18 %
</P>
<P>
   2 % 61 65 70 75 83 93
</P>
<P>
   3 % 38 39 41 42 44 47
</P>
<P>
   4 % 27 28 29 30 31 32
</P>
<P>
   5 % 21 22 22 23 23 24
</P>
<P>
   10 % 10 11 11 11 11 11
</P>
<P>
   15 % 7 7 7 7 7 7
</P>
<P>
   20 % 5 5 5 5 5 5
</P>
<P>
   25 % 4 2 4 4 4 4
</P>
<P>
   Payment as a percent of initial debt
