r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0726-CO     07-25 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All the lodge's a stage . . .
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PELEE ISLAND, Ont. _ Boy meets girl. Boy gets girls. Boy and
girl get married and open a bed and breakfast in the far north
boonies. Then one fine autumn morning, boy comes to breakfast
grumpy. Girl hasn't got a clue. He glowers. She
</P>
<P>
   chirps. That's where the play begins.
</P>
<P>
   Robin, Pat, and Sharon, my weekend island sisters, are sitting a
couple of rows ahead of me in the tiny, darkened theatre that, when
no one is treading the boards, doubles as the Masonic Lodge. The
stage is barely turning-around size _ just enough room for the
actors to get on, get off, and make their moves. They're using
every inch of it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the lights dimmed, I took a house count _ only 23 of the
60 or so chairs on the tiered platforms are filled. Maybe because
it's 4:30 on a Saturday afternoon. Or maybe it's because the
weather is stormy and the lake, being shallow, has a tendency to
toss boaters around like toys in a dishpan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Affections of May,'' the play bill proclaims, is a
``hilarious comedy'' in two acts.
</P>
<P>
   May is married to Brian _ he's the unhappy one with his chin
dragging in the oatmeal. May is, for the moment, the fatuously
cheerful one rattling inanely on about budgets and firewood. All is
right in her world _ except Brian.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon (we're sisters-in-law twice removed...divorced from
brothers) turns in the semi-darkness and gives me a knowing glance.
Brian is working his way up to a fast exit _ stage right because
he's had it with wood chopping and other
</P>
<P>
   things bucolic, and longs for the pace of the city they left
behind.
</P>
<P>
   May is shocked, once Brian finally gets through to her that he's
not kidding, but good wife that she is, she makes up her mind to
give up their dream and go with him. She's gonna' stand by her man.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not exactly what Brian has in mind. It takes almost
all of Scene 1 for May to catch on to what Brian is not saying.
There's another woman and he's not only leaving the budget, the
firewood, and the boonies, he's leaving May and her bib overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Exit Brian. Enter Quinn _ a hard-drinking, loose-living (in a
barn most recently) fellow looking for odd jobs and a place to
sleep. May needs help, not complications. But we all know that
without complications there'd be no plot.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn stays _ in the spare room.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon turns around giving me her eyebrow waggle that translates
to, ``AHA!''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hank Beavis _ a banker nerd with trousers up to his
armpits and the body language of a question mark. Hank says he's
had his eye on May for a long time and now, since that sorry Brian
has cut and run, maybe she'd like to go to the town Halloween party
with him.
</P>
<P>
   May insists Brian's coming back, but goes anyway because Hank's
mom has already made his costume _ a six-foot pink rabbit complete
with ears, thumpers, and a giant carrot. May is going as Little Bo
Peep.
</P>
<P>
   The plot thickens
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
