<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-LECRONE _ Dr. Hap LeCrone's weekly psychology column.
(LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald) ENTERTAINMENT-ARTSBEST-MOVIES _ What
are the real movie hits so far this year? Maybe ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' did top $200 million at the box office, but it also
cost an estimated $125 million to make. That makes its
dollar-for-dollar return not so golden. The really big financial
successes this summer are the smaller budget movies raking in
unexpected millions _ namely ``Scary Movie,'' the filmed-in-Georgia
``Road Trip'' and ``Big Momma's House.'' 9ongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RAILROAD _ Movie review: ``Thomas &AMP; the Magic Railroad.''
Teeny kids' movie with Peter Fonda and Alec Baldwin. Grade: C+.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).TRAVELGETAWAY-BEACHES _
Pensacola, Fla. _ When we saw that Perdido Key was included in the
ranking of top 20 American beaches compiled by the expert who bills
himself as ``Dr. Beach,'' we had to check it out. But when we found
it to be, in our humble estimation, less than award-winning, we
decided to see how it ranked among this Panhandle city's other fine
beaches. In this report, we're not claiming to be real Dr. Beaches,
we're just playing one. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
30.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   ARTISAN-BREADS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Artisan breads _ made by hand,
cherished for their taste, texture and crust _ have gone mainstream
in the Miami Valley. With the recent opening of Panera Bread, a St.
Louis-based chain, at Town &AMP; Country Shopping Center in Kettering,
the competition has heated up. To assess the quality of the
offerings, we assembled a panel of tasters and purchased four
popular kinds of artisan breads: sourdough, asiago cheese (a new
contender), multigrain and raisin bread. (Dayton Daily News). WITJH
PHOTOS, CHART.
</P>
