<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GOP-HOFFA26-COX     07-25 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-HOFFA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH FETE FOR HOFFA, GOP WORKING HARD FOR LABOR VOTERS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Republicans got his sweat and his skill, but
Steve Bromiley kept his suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a 100 percent union city, and Republicans don't like
unions,'' said Bromiley, a carpenter helping convert the First
Union Center sports arena into a political hall for the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the guys building the place are Republicans,'' said
Bromiley, 35, a member of the United Brotherhood of Carpenters and
Joiners. ``I don't know how they determined to come here.''
</P>
<P>
   But not only are the Republicans convening in a stronghold of
Democrats and organized labor, they are honoring Teamsters
President James Hoffa. Hoffa will attend the convention next week
and be the guest of honor at a reception hosted by the national
party chairman, Jim Nicholson, Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania and a
group of congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Convention said it's the first time in
20 years that a union president has been feted at a GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   By inviting Hoffa, ``we're reaching out to a leading
representative of working families,'' said Nicholson. He said
Republicans, especially Ronald Reagan, have had considerable
support from rank-and-file union members in recent decades and are
now making connections with their leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign that we're willing to talk,'' said Rich Bond, a
Republican political strategist.
</P>
<P>
   And Hoffa's willingness to attend indicates that despite the
``hostilities'' of AFL-CIO President John Sweeney, ``some union
leaders are willing to do business with the Republican Party,''
said Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters spokesman Bret Caldwell said Hoffa's attendance shows
``his willingness to reach across party lines to help working
families'' and his commitment to ``electing a pro-labor Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   But Caldwell cautioned that ``it should not be construed as a
message to any presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after the GOP convention ends, Hoffa will be a Michigan
delegate to the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Teamsters have not endorsed a presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoffa's silence speaks volumes about his enthusiasm for Al
Gore,'' said Bond.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the vice president has not achieved the unified backing
from organized labor that most Democratic candidates have usually
wrapped up well before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Teamsters, the United Auto Workers have so
far declined to join the AFL-CIO in endorsing Gore. Together, those
two unions represent about 2 million of the labor federation's 13
million members.
</P>
<P>
   Gore angered some labor leaders when he appointed former
Commerce Secretary William Daley, who led the administration effort
to open trade with China, as his campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa met with Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive
Republican presidential nominee, in April and later appeared on a
podium with Green Party candidate Ralph Nader. Caldwell said there
will be a ``scientific poll'' of the 1.5 million Teamsters members
before the union makes a presidential endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.teamsters.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
