<HEADER>
A2210 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS &LR;      07-25 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH LESSON IN GOING WIRELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The first sighting of this handy little device was not in
Boston or Silicon Valley. It was in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   We were nestled at a table at Ma Bourgogne, inches away from a
French couple, whose tiny dog lapped occasionally at her owner's
plate. (``Non, non, Penny!'' the lady quietly scolded.) It's the
kind of restaurant where waiters wear black vests and bowties, and
white aprons that hang to the floor. Grilled beef is bathed in wine
sauce, and the terrace overlooks Place des Vosges, home to French
kings and queens in the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until late in the evening, the '97 Chateauneuf du Pape
nearly finished, that we noticed: The waiter didn't jot patrons'
orders on a note pad. He punched buttons on a wireless gadget the
size of a Palm Pilot _ sending orders straight to the kitchen and
to a central computer. He swiped our credit card across the compact
machine right at the table to settle the bill.
</P>
<P>
   This, in the city of romance and Old World charm, yet not in
technology-obsessed Boston? Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, Americans are about as far behind in adopting this
kind of technology as we were with cell phones. Everyone in Europe
and Tokyo had a mobile phone glued to his or her ear a few years
ago; we've only recently followed suit. Wireless pros say it's been
easier to roll out services in Europe because digital
communications became the norm sooner, and countries there tend to
have one central system that everyone uses, while we have several.
</P>
<P>
   But there could be cultural reasons, too, for our slow embrace
of what seems a quintessentially American kind of efficiency tool.
As one restaurateur suggests, subtlety is hard to come by here.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Paris, they're secure. They aren't trying to create an
experience,'' suggests Jim Miller, chief executive of Fire &AMP; Ice, a
popular Cambridge, Mass. restaurant. Meanwhile, in the States, he
said, ``We're the antithesis of authenticity.'' He worries that
little computers could be ambience wreckers: ``It has a kind of
tacky feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet high-tech gizmos were apparently all the rage at this year's
National Restaurant Convention in Chicago. Industry people are now
talking about the concept of a wireless restaurant. In such a
world, the bus boys wear beepers and signal the host when a table
is clear. Wait staffers take orders on handheld units and runners
deliver food from the kitchen. A request for a new fork can be
handled without the server ever leaving the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   W.J. Kitchen (not a pseudonym, he swears) is chief executive of
Ameranth Technology in San Diego, a start-up with Microsoft venture
backing that makes software for handheld devices and electronics
for the hospitality industry. A former Motorola executive with a
deep Virginia drawl that makes you long for greens and black-eyed
peas, he suggests restaurant customers could even pay for valet
parking along with their meals, and find their cars at curbside the
moment they walk outside.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen says restaurants could turn tables over up to twice as
fast with the new devices, ``and the customer's not realizing he's
being hustled.'' The system could pay for itself in nine months to
a year, he says, unwilling to specify its exact cost.
</P>
<P>
   Mind you, in Paris, there is no rushing through meals. Dinner is
frequently a three-hour affair, and when you're ready to leave,
you've got to flag down your server. There, and perhaps in high-end
restaurants here, the electronics would seem to be more about good
service than fast food.
</P>
<P>
   But this is America. We like to know we can buzz through an
entree and make it to the late movie. The wireless ordering units
would seem ideally suited to large, busy restaurants and chains,
like Legal Sea Foods, Bertucci's, or Brew Moon.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Berkowitz, chief executive of Boston's Legal Sea Foods,
said he considered the units a few years ago, but the signals
didn't always work. It was like trying to talk on a cell phone
while you drive through a tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Like many restaurants, Legal has computers stationed around the
dining room where servers place orders electronically. He's not
convinced there's a huge benefit to doing it at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can walk 10 feet to a terminal, punch it in, and it might
be less obtrusive that way,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen says servers can learn to use the devices (made by his
partner, Symbol Technology, as well as by Hewlett-Packard, Casio,
and Compaq) in 20 minutes. His company is running focus groups with
California wait staffers to see if they like it. Most do, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Halloran, a restaurant consultant in Jamestown, R.I., and
former executive chef at Cornell University, thinks restaurants are
going to have to adapt to the new technology to boost profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at your tables as a little sales area for a waiter,''
Halloran says. ``Time is money these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he notes, ``Any gimmick works in America.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spectrum Equity Investors has closed its fourth venture fund at
$1.75 billion. The Boston firm _ one of many descendants of TA
Associates _ specializes in communications deals. Managing general
partner Bill Collatos says about one-third of the money will be
invested in Europe. Investments will range from early-stage deals
of $5 million up to $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
