<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS &LR;      07-25 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE ELECTRONICS: GETTING CIVIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phrase ``defense conversion'' refers to attempts by military
contractors to find civilian applications for their technologies.
The strategy has hardly helped the defense sector overall, as major
companies continue to struggle financially. But many defense
contractors in New England say they haven't given up hopes of
capitalizing on their know-how.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, N.H., for instance, the Sanders unit of Lockheed
Martin Corp. is developing a tiny drone aircraft it thinks could
have civil-sector appeal. Known as the ``micro air vehicle,'' or
MAV, the machine will be about six inches long and able to fly
about 20 minutes at speeds up to 30 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   That's comparable to some model airplanes made by hobbyists. But
Sanders engineers are also packing the tiny platform with cameras
and other optical instruments to feed data via radio to controllers
on the ground. Their goal is to keep the craft's takeoff weight
below three ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Some military applications for the MAV are obvious, such as
spotting enemy troops or directing artillery fire. On the civilian
side, Sanders envisions the product being sold to firefighters,
search-and-rescue teams, and agriculture or forestry companies,
says Sanders spokesman John Measell.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders and other Lockheed units are developing the MAV under a
$10 million contract from the Defense Advanced Research Projects
Agency. (On July 13, Lockheed announced plans to sell Sanders and
other units to Britain's BAE Systems for $1.67 billion in cash.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Wilmington, Mass., meanwhile, military contractor Textron
Systems is also looking to branch out from its defense roots. A
unit of Textron Inc. of Providence, the division changed its name
from Textron Defense Systems about four years ago in an effort to
demonstrate its move into new markets.
</P>
<P>
   Textron Systems is best known in military circles for making
antitank mines and portable microwave beacons that can be used to
land large transport planes on remote airstrips.
</P>
<P>
   Sensors related to this work might also be of interest to police
agencies that need to monitor remote territories, Textron thinks.
Lately, the company has been taking orders for surveillance gear it
calls its ``Terrain Commander'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to fit in a backpack, the equipment includes a video
camera on a stalk and four acoustic sensors to detect approaching
footsteps. A cheaper version does without the camera. Textron says
it is in talks with the Australian Army, which may buy units to
help monitor remote airfields in the northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Textron also has begun to market for commercial uses a
spectrometer that analyzes light in the near-infrared part of the
spectrum. First developed for applications like gunsights, the
technology has also proven useful for materials analysis. Now,
Textron is marketing it to the pharmaceutical and petrochemical
industries, and has already sold 40 of the devices for analyzing
protein and moisture levels in harvested grain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have done the same thing 10 years ago, but it would
have cost you $150,000 to $200,000 a unit,'' said Robert Buckley, a
Textron senior vice president. The new spectrometers sell for
around $15,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Burlington, Mass., a unit of France's Thomson-CSF is also
expanding beyond its military roots. The division, Cetia, has about
60 people locally and develops robust computer chips, circuit
boards, and software for defense contractors such as Lockheed
Martin, Raytheon, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Cetia has found some success selling its chips to cell
phone companies like Ericsson and Nokia. The company expects the
business will help it increase revenue to around $25 million in the
United States and Europe this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Thomson said it would combine Cetia with Matrix
Corp,. a Raleigh, N.C., company it recently acquired. Cetia
specializes in making parts that can tolerate shock and vibration,
while Matrix produces parts meant to function in extreme heat and
cold. Cetia's employment level won't change because of the merger,
Thomson said. But the new unit, while keeping the Cetia name, will
move its headquarters to Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ross Kerber is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at kerber(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
