<SLUG> BC-TECH-POLAROID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PICTURE FRAME CREATES POLAROID MOMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Polaroid may have solved the problem of delivering pictures in
real time to your technology-wary parents who don't yet _ and may
never _ own a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Soon you'll be able to buy them a $249 picture frame developed
by Polaroid subcontractor Ceiva Inc. of West Hollywood, Calif.,
before you leave on vacation. Then you can fly to Florida, snap
digital photos of the grandkids at Disney World and send them
directly into the picture frame on your parents' mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it'll work: Polaroid will sell a low-end digital
camera with a built-in modem and a small liquid crystal display to
see just-snapped images with VGA resolution (640 x 480 pixels)
suitable for computer screens. The camera, also $249, will include
four megabytes of internal memory capable of storing 30 pictures.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of sightseeing, a family can go back to their hotel,
connect the camera's modem to the telephone jack and push a button
that automatically dials into a new company Web site _
Polaroiddigital.com _ to upload and store all of the images. The
Web site's computers then download the collected images to either
the family computer or to the new digital picture frame.
</P>
<P>
   The picture frame also has a built-in modem that is plugged into
a telephone jack and can store 10 images, even in the home of
grandparents thousands of miles away who don't have a PC. (The
frame can also display news, weather, and sports headlines.)
</P>
<P>
   This entire transaction _ from shipping the images over the
Internet to receiving them _ will take a matter of minutes,
according to officials at Cambridge-based Polaroid. Both the camera
and the picture frame will have numeric codes matched to ensure a
secure transaction and avoid the images getting lost. And just as
Federal Express does not open sealed boxes, Polaroid says it will
not view the images before they are sent.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid, the 63-year-old pioneer of instant photography, has
been expanding into the digital camera business. Low-end digital
cameras and software now account for 10 percent of its $1.98
billion in annual revenues. Polaroid faces stiff competition in
that market, however, from Eastman Kodak and a host of smaller
companies catering to a fast-growing group of digital camera owners
using the Web for sending and receiving snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers familiar with Polaroid know that most of its instant
film costs about $10 for 10 single pictures. That's expensive
compared with 35mm color film, which sells for about $5 a roll, a
market dominated by Kodak and Fuji; a one-hour photo finishing
laboratory will develop and print 24 prints for under $10. Combined
with the film cost, the $15 total for more than twice as many
pictures, has limited Polaroid's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Digital photography and the Internet complicates this equation.
Fewer digital images are printed out compared with a single roll of
24- or 36-exposure film as users only want keepsake paper copies of
the best pictures. Sending images over the Internet or around the
country is quick and inexpensive. And Polaroid is expected to face
new competition next year from Kodak, Fuji, and others that are
developing low-cost printing devices to instantly capture digital
images on paper.
</P>
<P>
   This new photographic equation poses challenges for Polaroid,
which earns most of its profits from its instant film packs. One
answer is the digital frames _ sleek devices that use the same
screen technology found in laptop computers to display images from
a digital camera transmitted over the Internet through telephone
wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe connected digital frames will be a killer
application in driving mass consumer adoption of digital cameras,''
said Gibboney Huske, imaging analyst for Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid plans to begin marketing the digital frame early next
year after it rolls out its new digital camera in January. Due out
this fall is a new portable Polaroid printer (selling for, you
guessed it, $249) that uses Polaroid's $10 film packs to provide
paper prints of digital images on the frame.
</P>
<P>
   A similar concept is underway at Eastman Kodak Co., based in
Rochester, N.Y. Working with Weave Innovations Inc. of Santa Clara,
Calif., Kodak has developed Storybox, a $299 frame that can store
up to 36 images for a monthly fee of $4 to $9.
</P>
<P>
   Storybox, due out later this summer, also goes beyond
photographs by providing users with content from the Weather
Channel, MSNBC headlines and sports news, and, eventually, stock
quotes. Both Kodak and Polaroid's digital frames require using a
personal computer _ your own, if not your parents' _ for setup, to
register the transmission of images between the camera and the
digital frame.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Polaroid, which can print small images from its
digital frame immediately, Kodak requires going through its
Print(at)Kodak Web site and having prints returned overnight _ at
49 cents per digital picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real big initiative is to have a stronger presence on the
Internet with the ability to print images anywhere at any time
using wireless mobile technology,'' said Stephen Golden, Polaroid's
director of marketing for its Worldwide Consumer Electronics group.
Golden said the final pricing of Polaroiddigital.com services _ the
uploading, storing, and downloading of images _ has not been
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Polaroid faces a tough sell with its instant film packs
at $1 a print for pictures that are 2-by-3 inches, compared with
Kodak's 4-by-6-inch prints from digital images at 49 cents, albeit
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Polaroid chief executive Gary DiCamillo acknowledged
that a new instant imaging technology is on the way, possibly by
late next year, that will cut the cost down to around 25 cents an
image. No doubt Kodak and Fuji are not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Rosenberg is a member of the Globe staff. He can be
reached by e-mail at rrosen(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
