<HEADLINE>
SALAD DAYS OF SUMMER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, those salad days of summer. Readers sent along plenty of
salad recipe options to fill the Sherman Oaks request for delicious
and easy possibilities to serve at a summer shower. A sampling of
those received follows.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Becerra notes that the Broccoli Salad is great. Not only
is it easy to make, but even broccoli-haters have been converted
after tasting it. Although it's fattening, feel free to substitute
low-fat mayonnaise for half (no more!) of the regular mayonnaise
called for in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Munroe's Chicken Salad recipe was shared by a friend who is
a foods teacher at a local junior high. She's used the recipe for
years, and it has always been a hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Cucumber Salad can be made in advance and is delicious,
notes Frances Gleim. Sunshine Salad, with a rice base and lots of
veggies, is easy and attractive, writes Sue Pearcy. Use ham, turkey
or other cooked, cubed meat as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Walsh has made Chicken-Cranberry Molded Salad for
birthdays and wedding receptions. It is impressive, delicious and
convenient, as it can be made the day before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Elinor Koby has served Curry Chicken Salad at two showers and
received many compliments.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of choices. Some of them sound simple enough to
make and enjoy for a summer supper as well. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BROCCOLI SALAD &QL; 
(Shared by Robin Becerra, Newhall and Aleda Cowan, La Crescenta) &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
1 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
1/2 cup sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon cider vinegar &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
4 cups broccoli florets (bite-size portions) &QL; 
8 slices bacon, cooked and crumbled &QL; 
1/3 cup chopped red onion &QL; 
1/4 cup shelled sunflower seeds &QL; 
1/3 cup raisins (optional) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Dressing by mixing all dressing ingredients; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all Salad ingredients. Add dressing; toss to coat. Chill
at least 2 hours before serving. Makes about 8 (1/2-cup) servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHICKEN SALAD &QL; 
(Shared by Jan Munroe, Valencia) &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
1/4 cup salad oil &QL; 
1/4 cup red wine vinegar &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon pepper &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
Dash garlic powder &QL; 
2 teaspoons sugar &QL; 
1 1/4 teaspoons dry mustard &QL; 
1/3 cup finely minced parsley &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
6 boned chicken breast halves, cooked, torn into small pieces and
then chilled &QL; 
1/2 pound bacon, cooked and torn into small pieces &QL; 
2 large tomatoes, cut up &QL; 
1 medium head lettuce OR 1 head red leaf lettuce &QL; 
2 avocados, cut up &QL; 
Sliced mushrooms &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Make Dressing the night before serving by mixing all dressing
ingredients well. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, toss together all salad ingredients. Add dressing and
toss well. Makes 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DILLED CHICKEN SALAD &QL; 
(Shared by Marion Brussel, Canyon Country) &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
1 (16-ounce) package spiral pasta, cooked and drained &QL; 
2 cups cubed cooked chicken &QL; 
1 cup chopped celery &QL; 
1/3 cup chopped onion &QL; 
1 (10-ounce) package frozen peas, thawed &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
1 (1-ounce) envelope ranch salad dressing mix &QL; 
2 cups (16 ounces) dairy sour cream &QL; 
1 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
1 cup milk &QL; 
3 tablespoons minced fresh dill OR 1 tablespoon dill weed &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon garlic salt &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, in a large bowl, combine salad ingredients; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Combine salad Dressing ingredients; whisk until smooth. Pour
over salad; toss to coat. Cover and refrigerate at least 2 hours.
Makes 10 to 12 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CUCUMBER SALAD &QL; 
(Shared by Frances Gleim, Acton) &QL; 
1 (3-ounce) package lemon-flavored gelatin &QL; 
1 cup boiling water &QL; 
1 small cucumber, grated &QL; 
1 small onion, grated &QL; 
1 cup cottage cheese &QL; 
2 teaspoons vinegar &QL; 
2/3 cup mayonnaise &QL; 
2/3 cup chopped pecans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve gelatin in boiling water. Cool and while still liquidy
add remaining ingredients. Fill fancy oiled mold and chill. Serve
on a bed of fancy lettuce greens. Makes 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE RECIPES FOLLOW)
</P>
</TEXT>
