<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-4thTake </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PILED-HIGH STRAWBERRY PIE &QL; 
1 (9-inch) baked pie shell &QL; 
3 (1-pint) baskets fresh ripe strawberries (about 8 cups) &QL; 
1/4 cup sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons cornstarch OR arrowroot &QL; 
1 1/4 cups cold water &QL; 
1/3 cup red currant jelly OR strawberry jelly &QL; 
6 drops red food coloring &QL; 
Sweetened whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Prepare baked pie shell and set aside to cool. Rinse, hull and
dry berries. Invert a 9-inch pie pan. On inverted pan, arrange the
most attractive berries as desired for top of pie. If berries vary
in size, place largest in center and smaller ones around edge.
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, combine sugar and cornstarch. Gradually
stir in water. Stir constantly over medium heat until mixture
thickens and comes to a full boil. Stir and boil 1 minute. Add
jelly and food coloring. Stir until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Let glaze cool while filling pie shell, stirring occasionally.
Arrange less attractive berries in bottom of shell. Spoon about 1/2
cup glaze over berries. Use berries on inverted pie pan for top,
repeating same order. Spoon and brush remaining glaze over berries.
Refrigerate 2 hours or longer until ready to serve. Before serving,
pipe or spoon sweetened whipped cream around edge of pie filling.
Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Pies &AMP; Pastries,'' by Janet Pittman, HP Books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CHERRY AND APRICOT COBBLER &QL; 
FILLING: &QL; 
2 pounds fresh Bing cherries, pitted, OR 2 (1-pound) bags frozen
sweet cherries, thawed and drained &QL; 
2 pounds apricots, halved and pitted &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
3 tablespoons cornstarch &QL; 
1 teaspoon almond extract &QL; 
TOPPING: &QL; 
2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar &QL; 
1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon baking soda &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 cup (1 stick) chilled unsalted butter, cut into 1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
3/4 cup chilled buttermilk &QL; 
3/4 cup chilled whipped cream &QL; 
Whipped cream or vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   For Filling, toss all filling ingredients in large bowl to
blend. Transfer to 13x9x2-inch glass baking dish. Bake in preheated
400-degree oven about 35 minutes or until filling is hot and begins
to bubble at edges. Reduce oven temperature to 375 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare Topping: Whisk flour, 1/2 cup sugar, baking
powder, baking soda and salt in another large bowl to blend. Add
butter; rub in with fingertips until mixture resembles coarse meal.
Slowly add buttermilk and cream, tossing with fork until dough
comes together.
</P>
<P>
   Drop dough by rounded tablespoonfuls over hot filling to cover.
Sprinkle with remaining 1 tablespoon sugar. Continue to bake
cobbler until topping is golden and tester inserted into center of
topping comes out clean, about 40 minutes. Cool 15 minutes. Serve
cobbler warm with whipped cream or ice cream. Makes 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Bon Appetit magazine, July 2000. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
EASY CHEESY TART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pastry for a (9-inch) pie shell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 medium fresh nectarines (1 pound) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sieved apricot jam!off!
</P>
<P>
   Roll out pastry to a 12-inch round. Fit into 9-inch tart or
springform pan. Pierce crust generously with fork. Bake in
preheated 400-degree oven 10 to 12 minutes or until golden. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Beat cream cheese with sugar and vanilla; spread over bottom of
shell. Thinly slice nectarines to measure 3 cups. Arrange
nectarines in attractive pattern on top of cheese filling. Glaze
with apricot jam. Chill until serving time. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
