<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-3rdTake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RASPBERRY BROWNIE COBBLER
</HEADLINE>
 Here is a dessert for people who have trouble deciding between
fruit and chocolate  _  raspberries topped with chocolate-nut
batter rather than the usual oats or crumbs. It's best served warm,
so pop it in the oven a little before you sit down to dinner and
serve about an hour later, with vanilla ice cream, if desired. 
2 1/2 ounces bittersweet (not unsweetened chocolate) 
1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, cut into several pieces 
1/2 cup walnuts 
1 pint fresh raspberries 
1 cup sugar 
2 large eggs 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla 
7 tablespoons all-purpose flour 
1/4 teaspoon salt 
1 pint vanilla ice cream, softened a bit (optional)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put 2 inches of water in saucepan or bottom of double boiler and
bring to a bare simmer. Combine chocolate and butter in stainless
steel bowl and place on top of simmering water, making sure water
doesn't touch bowl. Heat, whisking occasionally, until chocolate
and butter are completely melted.
</P>
<P>
   While chocolate is melting, coarsely chop nuts. Spray 8-inch
square baking dish with cooking spray. Scatter berries across
bottom of dish.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together sugar, eggs and vanilla in bowl. Whisk in melted
chocolate. Stir in flour, nuts and salt. Pour batter over berries
and smooth with spatula.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven until a toothpick inserted
into center of cobbler comes out clean, about 45 minutes. Let stand
15 minutes and serve with ice cream if desired. Makes 6 to 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Instant Gratification: No Hassle Desserts in Just About
No Time,'' by Lauren Chattman, William Morrow. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
BLUEBERRY-WALNUT CRISP &QL; 
This is my basic crisp topping  &UR; _ &LR;  walnuts, brown sugar, flour,
butter  &UR; _ &LR;  sprinkled over blueberries. Any other fruit may be
substituted (apples, pears, peaches and plums are all good), but
few are quicker to prepare than blueberries, which just need to be
washed and picked over. &QL; 
2 pints fresh blueberries, picked over for stems &QL; 
1/3 cup plus 2 tablespoons packed light brown sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon cornstarch &QL; 
1/4 cup walnuts &QL; 
1/2 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
Pinch salt &QL; 
1/4 cup (1/2 stick) unsalted butter, chilled and cut into small
pieces &QL; 
1 pint vanilla ice cream, softened a bit
</P>
<P>
   Combine blueberries, 1/3 cup brown sugar and cornstarch in
8-inch square baking pan. Stir to combine, mashing some, but not
all, of berries with back of spoon to release some of juices. Stir
once or twice while preparing topping.
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely chop walnuts. Combine nuts, flour, remaining 2
tablespoons brown sugar, cinnamon and salt in small bowl and mix
several seconds to combine. Add butter and mix on low speed with
electric mixer just until clumps begin to form, 1 to 2 minutes. Do
not overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Scatter topping over fruit. Bake in preheated 425-degree oven,
about 30 minutes, until golden and bubbling. Serve warm with ice
cream on the side. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Instant Gratification: No Hassle Desserts in Just About
No Time,'' by Lauren Chattman, William Morrow. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
PLUM TART WITH MARZIPAN CRUMBLE &QL; 
The nutty marzipan mixture is a delicious contrast to the
sweet-tart plum filling. &QL; 
CRUST: &QL; 
1 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
3/4 cup sliced almonds &QL; 
1/4 cup sugar &QL; 
1/8 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 cup (1 stick) chilled unsalted butter, cut into 1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
2 tablespoons chilled whipping cream &QL; 
1 large egg yolk &QL; 
CRUMBLE: &QL; 
3/4 cup all-purpose flour &QL; 
1/2 cup packed almond paste (about 5 ounces) &QL; 
1/2 cup packed golden brown sugar &QL; 
6 tablespoons (3/4 stick) chilled unsalted butter, cut into
1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
1/4 cup sliced almonds &QL; 
FILLING: &QL; 
2 1/4 pounds plums (about 12), halved, pitted and thinly sliced &QL; 
1/2 cup granulated sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons plus 2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   For Crust, blend first 4 crust ingredients in food processor
until nuts are finely ground. Add butter, process until mixture
resembles coarse meal. Add cream and yolk. Blend, using on/off
turns, until dough comes together. Press over bottom and up sides
of 11-inch-diameter tart pan with removable bottom. Pierce all over
with fork. Chill at least 2 hours or up to 1 day.
</P>
<P>
   Bake crust in preheated 400-degree oven until golden, pressing
with back of fork every 5 minutes if crust bubbles, about 25
minutes. Transfer crust to rack; cool. Reduce oven temperature to
375 degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   For Crumble, blend flour, almond paste and brown sugar in
processor until almond paste is finely ground. Add butter and
blend, using on/off turns, until coarse crumbs form. Transfer
crumble to bowl; mix in almonds.
</P>
<P>
   For filling, combine all filling ingredients in medium bowl;
toss to blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle 3/4 cup crumble over cooled crust. Top with plum
filling. Sprinkle with remaining crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Bake tart about 40 minutes or until filling bubbles thickly and
top is golden. Cool 10 minutes. Push up pan bottom to release tart.
(Can be made 8 hours ahead. Let stand at room temperature.) Makes
10 to 12 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Bon Appetit magazine, July 2000. &UR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
