<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-PETS-COLUMN-NY     07-25 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-PETS-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOULDER CITY COUNCIL ASIDE, PETS ARE STILL PROPERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, July 25, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the JonBenet frenzy blemished its persona, the city of
Boulder, Colo., was known to outsiders as a breathtakingly
beautiful community nestled in the valley below the Rocky Mountains
and populated by many laid-back and eccentric characters of
considerable charm and whimsy.
</P>
<P>
   Let me put it another way. They've got a lot of freaks in
Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean that as a negative. As I always say, let your freak
flag fly! (All right, I never say that, but I heard Abbie Hoffman
say it on TV a long time ago. Or maybe it was Wavy Gravy.) But if
you walk down the Pearl Street Mall in Boulder, you'll see quite a
colorful array of aging hippies, long-haired bikers, skateboarding
runaways and tie-dyed Deadheads.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, from what I experienced on a couple of visits to
Boulder, a certain incense-burning, tie-dyed-fashion,
save-the-whooping-crane attitude permeates much of the town. So
when I received an e-mail last week from an animal rights group
about a ``bold and progressive move on behalf of animals,'' I
wasn't surprised to see a Boulder dateline on the news release.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I had my doubts about the validity of this
announcement, which arrived courtesy of a group known as In Defense
of Animals, or IDA.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from the release:
</P>
<P>
   ``BOULDER, Colo. _ In a bold and progressive move on behalf of
animals, the Boulder City Council voted 8-1 to accept a proposal to
change the city's municipal code to refer to people as the guardian
of their animal companions instead of as their `owners.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Erasing the category of `owner' does not change a person's
legal rights, responsibilities and liabilities to their companion
animals, and animals will still be deemed property. However, by
codifying the concept of animal guardianship, the City Council is
recognizing animals should be included in our social ethic for
reasons beyond their monetary worth as commodities.
</P>
<P>
   '''The Boulder City Council should be commended for their
foresight and conviction of recognizing companion animals, not as
mere objects to be bought, sold and discarded at their owner's
whim, but as individuals with needs and interests of their own,'
said Elliot Katz, president of In Defense of Animals. 'Boulder is
truly on the cutting edge in terms of evolving our social ethic to
include all beings, both human and non-human alike.'''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently no dogs, cats, chickens, snakes or tropical fish
could be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   My first reaction upon receiving this e-mail was one of delight.
After all, I'm compiling a new collection of Internet urban
legends, and this one was a beauty. A city council of grown adults
debating such an issue, and then voting by a near-unanimous margin
to change its municipal code to eliminate the term ``animal
owner,'' are you kidding me? What a clever hoax!
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem: It's for real. Last week, the Boulder City
Council actually did vote 8-1 to adopt changes in its animal
ordinances that will replace the phrase ``pet owner'' with ``pet
guardian.''
</P>
<P>
   As former Councilman Ben Greenlee, who said he would have voted
against the ordinance, told the Denver Post, ``It's the kind of
silly nonsense that we, somehow or another, adore here in
Boulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Well yes. Not that we have much room to talk in Chicago, what
with members of our City Council holding an inquisition of Jerry
Springer and debating everything from cheese sandwiches to whether
Hugh Hefner should have an honorary street name. But still, this
``pet guardian'' resolution is a priceless piece of precious
poppycock _ and it is of course pure bull droppings.
</P>
<P>
   I don't care if you project human emotions onto your pet and I
don't care if you prefer the cartoonishly simple love you have for
your pet over the much more complicated and textured relationships
a person has with another person _ if you have a pet, you own that
pet. That pet is your slave, kept in a cage or tethered to a leash
and completely at your mercy.
</P>
<P>
   How'd you get your pet in the first place? Either somebody gave
it to you or you bought it. From that point on you name your pet,
feed your pet, bathe your pet, give medicine to your pet,
discipline your pet.
</P>
<P>
   Pet your pet.
</P>
<P>
   Even the smartest animal is far too pea-brained to execute this
sort of reasoning or speak for itself, but let's take a kangaroo
leap in logic and imagine asking a domesticated creature _ say, a
French poodle _ if it would prefer to have complete and stupid
freedom, or if it would choose to continue with a life of having
its toenails painted, listening to its owner babble in babytalk and
wearing a collar and tags displaying its ridiculous name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Au revoir,'' the poodle would say. The poodle would bolt! But
it can't, because it is not sharing a life with a guardian or a
companion, it is a cuddly piece of property.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the ROEPER
COLUMN and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
