<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-2ndTak     07-25 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-2ndTake </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
COUNTRY PEACH PIE &QL; 
Nothing says summer and home better than a freshly baked pie, a pie
that, to quote a friend, ``screams peaches.'' &QL; 
Basic Pie Dough for a 2-crust pie (Recipe follows) &QL; 
8 large (3 1/2 to 4 pounds) ripe peaches &QL; 
1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice &QL; 
1/3 cup packed light brown sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup plus 1 tablespoon granulated sugar &QL; 
3 tablespoons cornstarch &QL; 
Pinch EACH ground cinnamon, ground mace OR fresh-grated nutmeg and
salt &QL; 
2 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into pieces &QL; 
1 tablespoon milk, for glaze &QL; 
Vanilla ice cream (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Divide Basic Pie Dough into 2 slightly unequal pieces. Roll out
larger piece on a lightly floured surface to a large circle no more
that 1/8-inch thick; fit it, without stretching, into a buttered,
deep 9 1/2- or 10-inch pie pan. Trim edge, leaving a 3/4-inch
overhang. Roll out remaining dough into a large circle and transfer
to a foil-lined baking sheet. Chill doughs.
</P>
<P>
   Dip peaches in boiling water 15 seconds; peel off skins. Squeeze
lemon juice into a large bowl. Working quickly, stone and thickly
slice peaches, letting slices fall into bowl. You should have about
8 cups. Toss gently and discard any excess juices.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together brown sugar, 1/4 cup granulated sugar, cornstarch,
cinnamon, mace and salt. Toss gently with peaches and pour mixture
into crust in pie pan, mounding peaches in center.
</P>
<P>
   Dot with butter. Moisten edge of crust with cold water. Loosely
drape remaining dough over filling. Trim off excess dough, leaving
a 3/4-inch overhang. Turn edges of top crust under edges of bottom
crust, forming a smooth border on rim of pie pan. Crimp or flute
border.
</P>
<P>
   Brush pastry lightly with milk, sprinkle with remaining 1
tablespoon granulated sugar. Cut several slashes in top crust to
release steam.
</P>
<P>
   Cover edges of dough with strips of foil if desired, to prevent
overbrowning. Place pie on rack in lower third of oven, with a
sheet of foil underneath to catch any drips.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 425-degree oven until golden brown, about 40
to 45 minutes, removing strips of foil, if using, after 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool pie on a wire rack. Serve warm or at room temperature, with
vanilla ice cream, if desired. Makes 1 deep 9 1/2- or 10-inch pie;
about 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Classic Home Desserts,'' by Richard Sax, Houghton
Mifflin. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BASIC PIE DOUGH &QL; 
The crusts for traditional fruit pies and other old-fashioned pies
are usually made with lard or vegetable shortening, or a
combination of butter (for flavor) and one of the other fats (for
flakiness). This recipe is a modern version. &QL; 
2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons sugar &QL; 
3/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
11 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into small pieces &QL; 
2 1/2 tablespoons cold solid vegetable shortening &QL; 
5 tablespoons cold water, plus more as needed
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, sugar, salt, butter and shortening in a food
processor or in a mixing bowl. Pulse machine on and off (OR cut
ingredients together with 2 knives) until mixture is crumbly.
</P>
<P>
   Add water and pulse (or toss with a fork) until mixture begins
to clump together. Gather into a ball, sprinkling with a few more
drops of water, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Flatten slightly into a disk, wrap in plastic wrap and chill at
least 30 minutes before rolling out.
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough dough for a double crust 9- or 10-inch pie. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FREE-FORM FRUIT PASTRY &QL; 
Packaged puff pastry streamlines the preparation of this
professional- looking pastry. Bake a crisp, flaky raft topped with
cheese or almond filling, then add your choice of fruit. &QL; 
1 sheet (half of a 17 1/4-ounce package) frozen puff pastry &QL; 
Cheese OR Almond Filling &QL; 
1/3 cup red currant jelly OR orange marmalade &QL; 
About 2 cups halved strawberries, sliced apricots OR sliced peaches
(OR 1 cup EACH of 2 different fruits)
</P>
<P>
   Thaw puff pastry at room temperature 20 minutes. Meanwhile,
prepare your choice of Filling.
</P>
<P>
   Place pastry on an ungreased 12x15-inch baking sheet and unfold.
Spread filling down length of pastry, to about 1 1/2 inches from
both long sides; then fold sides of pastry over to cover edges of
filling.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 425-degree oven about 12 to 15 minutes or
until browned. Place baking sheet on a rack; let pastry cool
completely. (At this point, you may cover loosely with foil and let
cooled pastry stand at room temperature up to 2 hours.)
</P>
<P>
   Up to 1 hour before serving, melt jelly or marmalade in a small
pan over low heat (use jelly with berries, marmalade with apricots
or peaches). Lightly brush filling with some of jelly. Arrange
fruit over filling, overlapping pieces slightly. Brush with
remaining jelly.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, cut pastry into slices with a sharp knife. Makes 8 to
10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CHEESE FILLING: In small bowl of an electric mixer, beat
together 1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese (softened), 1/3 cup
sugar, 2 tablespoons all-purpose flour, 1 teaspoon vanilla and 1/2
teaspoon grated lemon peel until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND FILLING: In small bowl of an electric mixer, beat 1/4 cup
butter OR margarine until creamy. Gradually add 1 (7-ounce) package
almond paste, 1 egg white and 1/2 teaspoon grated lemon peel; beat
until smooth and well blended.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Sunset Pies &AMP; Pastries,'' by the Editors of Sunset Books
and Sunset Magazine, Lane Publishing Co. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NO-BAKE BLUEBERRY PIE &QL; 
Pure blueberry flavor with no distractions. That's the best way to
describe this quick-to-fix pie filling. &QL; 
1 (9-inch) baked pie crust &QL; 
4 cups blueberries &QL; 
3/4 cup sugar &QL; 
2 1/2 tablespoons cornstarch &QL; 
2 tablespoons EACH cold water and lemon juice &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
Sweetened whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Fill baked pie crust with 3 cups blueberries.
</P>
<P>
   In a pan, crush remaining 1 cup berries and stir in sugar; cook
over medium heat, stirring, until sugar is dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Stir together cornstarch, water and lemon juice; add to berry
mixture along with cinnamon. Cook, stirring, until mixture boils
and thickens; spoon over berries in pastry shell. Refrigerate at
least 1 hour or up to 8 hours. Serve with whipped cream. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Sunset Pies &AMP; Pastries,'' by the Editors of Sunset Books
and Sunset Magazine, Lane Publishing Co. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
