A2276 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      07-25 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN-FINANCE CONTROL: JUST AIM FOR WALLET, SQUEEZE
</HEADLINE>
  By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   It's only July, but the best quote
of the 2000 political campaign may well belong to Mike Kelleher, a
Democrat running for Congress in Illinois. He's gleefully
circulating an old photo of a paper clip that his opponent,
Republican Timothy Johnson, sometimes used to hold his electronic
voting button in the ``yes'' position while he was away from his
seat in the state legislature.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Voting is the reason you are elected, and he delegated that
responsibility to a piece of office supply,'' says Kelleher, who's
created a Web site at www.timspaperclip.com. ``This goes to
character.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but voters in Illinois probably should count
themselves lucky if it's only a piece of office supply calling the
shots on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and Republicans recently celebrated the dubious
achievement of raising more than a quarter of a billion dollars for
this fall's congressional races. For that much money, every man,
woman and child in America could get a whole box of paper clips to
represent them. (I'd suggest we pool our resources, though, and get
something with a little more weight and personality like, say, a
lava lamp.)
</P>
<P>
   The torrent of cash _ and special-interest influence _ shows no
signs of letting up, of course. In fact, officials in both major
parties are boldly declaring they ought to be allowed to raise
more, not less money.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the leaders of some 527s _ the groups that have been
exploiting Section 527 of the tax code to hide the names of people
funneling money into campaigns _ said they may defy a new law
requiring them to state who they are and how much they're spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no intentions of submitting to this,'' William Wilson,
spokesman for a 527 called the Council for Responsible Government,
recently told The Center for Public Integrity. ``I won't let John
McCain or anyone else tell us who we can and can't support. I won't
roll over on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Majority Issues Committee, a 527 promoted by
House Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas, is among the law's critics.
</P>
<P>
   James Bopp, an attorney for the group, portrays it as a simple
matter of free speech. ``I'm never surprised when politicians get
together to shut up citizens who want to talk about their voting
records,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens in question are primarily of the wealthy, corporate
sort. Despite their success and already considerable influence, it
appears they're actually quite shy and uncomfortable speaking in
public. Rather endearing, isn't it? Perish the thought that they're
really trying to dodge questions about whether the politicians they
support are writing legislation on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman DeLay wants to help coax those donors out of their
shells even more. During a speech last week at the Cato Institute,
a think tank in Washington D.C., he called for the repeal of all
limits on donations. That's right _ all limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfettered political speech, along with the right to bear
arms, is the most certain means we possess of protecting the rest
of our freedoms,'' DeLay said. (Wouldn't that make a fine bumper
sticker on Capitol Hill? ``I support just one type of
campaign-finance control: Aim for the wallet and squeeze.'')
</P>
<P>
   In a paper-clip twist of logic, DeLay argues that limits protect
incumbents like him because challengers can't raise enough money to
win. So if we lift the limits _ and create the campaign equivalent
of the old nuclear-arms race policy of Mutually Assured Destruction
_ everybody would have a shot at bidding on the candidate of their
choice.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay recently told The Washington Post that the only folks who
want to impose caps on campaign donations are journalists,
``big-government liberals'' and ``politicians trying to make
friends with journalists and big-government liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   And voters, it would seem. A recent Gallup poll indicates that
62 percent of Americans favor public financing of campaigns, the
highest level since Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Four states now have ``clean election'' laws that give
candidates public funds to run for office, in exchange for
declining special-interest money. Similar measures appear close to
passage in seven other states, according to USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   These efforts may not be the best approach to reform. But I'm
willing to wager that the folks who get elected under such measures
will represent us better than paper clips and maybe even lava
lamps.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
