<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 Learning to Cook: Day-Old Bread's Not for the Birds   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Bread salad is a perfect example of old-fashioned
home cooking at its best.
<P>
   In the old days (any era in which the living was not easy), it
was a sin to let anything go to waste, so thrifty housewives
devised clever ways to recycle foodstuff that was past its prime.
Bread salad was a dish born of necessity, and is a dandy way to use
up stale bread.
</P>
<P>
   Today's recipe is an adaptation of the classic Tuscan bread
salad, which is popular to this day. And in these times of relative
affluence, the bread starts out fresh and is allowed to get stale.
</P>
<P>
   To make the best salad, I use a good, hearty loaf of artisan
bread. There are a number of small local bakeries that produce
these breads, and many supermarkets carry them, too. Whatever bread
you choose, be sure it has a sturdy texture _ avoid those wimpy,
soft loaves of sliced white bread.
</P>
<P>
   Since bread salad is simple and economical, you can go all out
on the ingredients: flavorful vine-ripened tomatoes, plump fresh
garlic, a crisp cucumber (wax-free), a sweet red onion, lush
peppery watercress and the best olive oil you can find.
</P>
<P>
   In line with the ``waste-not, want-not'' origin of the dish, if
you have any left over, cover it and put it in the refrigerator.
The next morning, you've got a satisfying, summery breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BREAD SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 large, ripe, juicy tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 large garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 red onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 loaf of day-old French or other country-style bread (to yield
3 to 4 cups cubes)
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch watercress
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Preparing the vegetables:  &LR; Rinse the tomatoes and cut out
the cores. Cut the tomatoes in half lengthwise. Put the halves
cut-side down on a chopping board. Cut each half lengthwise into
1/2-inch strips. Holding the strips together, cut them crosswise
into 1/2-inch pieces. Put the chopped tomatoes into a large bowl
and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the garlic and cut each clove into tiny lengthwise strips,
then hold the strips together and cut crosswise into tiny pieces.
Add to the tomatoes in the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the papery skin off the onion half. Trim off the stem top
and root bottom. Place the onion half cut-side down on a cutting
board and cut lengthwise into 1/4-inch strips. Holding the strips
together, cut them into 1/4-inch pieces. Add the onion to the salad
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the cucumber and cut it in half lengthwise down the center.
Using a teaspoon, scrape out the seeds and discard. Cut each
cucumber half into 4 lengthwise strips, then cut crosswise into
1/2-inch pieces. Add the cucumber pieces to the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Season the vegetables with salt. Use your hands to toss and mix
the vegetables. Taste, and add more salt if the salad tastes flat.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the vinegar into a small bowl. Add the olive oil and whisk
to mix well. (Or use a spoon and stir briskly.) Pour the dressing
over the salad. Use your hands to toss and mix the salad
thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the bread cubes:  &LR; Using a sharp knife, trim off the
crust on the bread. Cut the bread into 1/2-inch cubes by cutting
first lengthwise then crosswise. Add the bread cubes to the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the salad, using your hands to thoroughly mix ingredients
(I rub the bread into some of the salad). If it seems a little dry,
add more olive oil and another spoonful or two of vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Rise the watercress well, then drain and pat dry. Remove the
leaves from the stems and add to the salad. Toss to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 690 calories, &LR;   &LR; 17 g protein, 99 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 26 g fat (4 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 913 mg
sodium, 7 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2339 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-CUPS-SFCHRON &LR;      07-25 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CUPS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets Of Success: Betelnut's Specialty   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Cecilia Chiang, who owned the pioneering Mandarin
restaurant in Ghirardelli Square for 30 years, invented this recipe
for Minced Chicken in Lettuce Cups served at Betelnut, a restaurant
that specializes in food from all over Asia, including Vietnam,
Thailand and Singapore.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a take-off on the minced squab that was the signature dish
at the Mandarin. For Betelnut, which was designed to look like a
sexy back-alley speakeasy in Shanghai, Chiang wanted to use less
expensive ingredients, so she replaced the squab with chicken. The
dark meat in particular has a similar flavor and texture. It's a
wonderful blend featuring minced chicken, crunchy water chestnuts,
black mushrooms, Chinese sausage and toasted pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Chiang seasons the mixture with ginger, soy sauce and oyster
sauce and serves the warm stir-fry in crisp, cold iceberg lettuce
cups.
</P>
<P>
   I particularly like to add a little dollop of plum sauce to the
lettuce leaf before adding the hot chicken mixture. To eat, just
pick up the lettuce leaf and eat as you would a taco. The
combination of the hot, fragrant chicken and the crisp, cold
lettuce is a true culinary delight.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Betelnut, 2030 Union St. (near Buchanan), San Francisco (415) &LR; 
 &LR; 929-8855. Lunch and dinner daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The egg white. &LR;  Adding egg white to the chicken before frying
in a hot wok gives that moist, velvety coating so admired in
Chinese cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The lettuce cups. &LR;  Trim the leaves with scissors into round
cups and make sure they are well chilled to enhance the contrast
with the hot chicken.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MINCED CHICKEN IN LETTUCE CUPS
</P>
<P>
   If you really want to splurge, replace one-fifth of the chicken
with squab.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 head iceberg lettuce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dried black mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound boneless skinless chicken thighs, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 egg white
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely minced water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely minced Chinese sausage (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Asian sesame oil, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pine nuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   Plum sauce
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Remove the core from the lettuce and gently separate the leaves.
Use a knife or scissors to cut the leaves into cup shapes.
Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Place the mushrooms in a small bowl. Add enough hot water to
cover. Let soak until soft, about 1 hour. Drain, reserving the
mushroom-soaking liquid. Cut off and discard the mushroom stems.
Finely chop the caps.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the chicken, soy sauce, egg white and cornstarch in a
large bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the vegetable oil in a wok or skillet over high heat. Add
the chicken mixture and ginger and cook until the chicken loses its
translucency, about 3 minutes. Add the rehydrated mushrooms, water
chestnuts and sausage. Reduce heat to low. Stir in the oyster
sauce, scallions and white pepper. If the mixture seems too dry,
add enough of the reserved mushroom-soaking liquid to moisten.
Remove from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle with sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the mixture onto a platter. Sprinkle with pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the chilled lettuce cups and small bowls of plum
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To eat:  &LR; Each diner takes a lettuce cup, adds a dab of plum
sauce, spoons in some of the filling, then eats the delicacy like a
taco.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Chinese sausage (lop chong) is available at Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 175 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 10 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 8 g fat (1 g saturated), 53 mg cholesterol, 430 mg
sodium, 3 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
