 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Pierce's Disease Poses Threat to Growers  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Over the years the California wine industry has
battled many problems _ weather that can't be controlled and pests
that can't be understood, not to mention human pests in the form of
government and social pressures.
<P>
   Now along comes a two-prong attack on a small California wine
region that is forcing wineries to reassess their survival.
Temecula Valley in Southern California is ground zero for one of
the most dynamic battles between the forces of wine and the
inexorable pressures of nature and society.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1970s, Temecula has been under the thumb of
mounting commercial and residential pressure to expand and develop
the land currently used for vineyards. Then in 1998, Pierce's
Disease appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's Disease is a bacterial disease that attacks and kills
grape vines. There is no known cure. In the early 20th century, PD
destroyed 39,500 acres of grapevines, mainly in Southern
California. Another epidemic broke out in the 1930s and now the
scourge of the millennium has hit Temecula hard.
</P>
<P>
   The small Santa Cruz Mountain wine district also has been hit by
PD, and the disease has been seen in other North Coast vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway Winery, Temecula's largest, has had it with unyielding
development and the ravages of Pierce's Disease. According to Mike
Jellison, president of Allied Domecq Wines USA, Callaway's parent
company is shifting its main source of grapes to the Central Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting to produce 300,000 cases by 2001, Callaway would soon
outgrow the present supply of Temecula grapes, with or without PD.
To continue to meet demand for its wines, the winery, which
ultimately aims to reach 1 million cases, was forced to buy
cool-climate grapes from Santa Barbara, San Luis Obispo and
Monterey counties.
</P>
<P>
   Callaway's change in grape sourcing will surely change the style
and flavor profile of the wines, and fits in with part of a general
makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Labels on the new Callaway Coastal wines sport muted watercolors
of subtle sunbursts emblazoned with the Callaway Coastal name. The
line of $8 wines will include Chardonnay, Cabernet Sauvignon,
Merlot, Sauvignon and Chenin Blanc. Coastal Reserves, at $12, will
include Viognier, Chardonnay and Merlot. A $4 million advertising
campaign in the fall will announce the makeover.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Temecula Reaction &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at Davis has established a Pierce's
Disease Task Force to deal with the threat to the California wine
industry. The federal government has already added $22 million to
the $15 million from the state to fight the disease. Winemakers and
growers are optimistic that current experiments will help control
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In what could be a bit of coincidental irony, a new winery is
moving into Temecula just as Callaway is moving out. Ray and
Loretta Falkner's Falkner Winery will produce an ambitious line of
wines, including eight varietals and two proprietary blends, most
of which will come from Temecula fruit.
</P>
<P>
   The Falkners, who are moving to California from Texas, did not
come into Temecula blind to the problem. ``We did some very
thorough research before buying and are confident that we made the
right decision,'' Ray Falkner says.
</P>
<P>
   The Falkners claim that the winery owners in Temecula they spoke
with are more upbeat about the PD situation than what is generally
reported. Joe Hart, a Temecula veteran, is one of those optimists.
Hart, who has owned Hart Winery in the valley since 1980, has mixed
emotions on the PD problem and what it is doing to the image of
Temecula wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to come through this whole thing,'' he
says. ``The impact depends on how successful we are at controlling
PD.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart's Winery, at 5,000 cases per year, and the Falkners' new
winery, projecting 6,500 cases, are relatively small operations, as
are most in Temecula. In this case, size does matter. It's much
easier for small wineries to get healthy Temecula grapes than for a
large winery like Callaway.
</P>
<P>
   Hart, who has won many awards for his delightful Grenache
Ros &LR; e &LR; , focuses on Mediterranean-style wines like Grenache,
Viognier and Syrah, varieties that are thought to do better in the
area than Chardonnay. For now, he says there is no shortage of
Temecula grapes, but he worries about the future. ``Wineries
outside the valley don't want to buy Temecula grapes because of the
PD scare,'' he says. ``It's a tough situation for the growers.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Callaway move to source all of their grapes outside
Temecula, Hart believes, ``It is not a good thing for the rest of
us. From a business perspective, it looks to me like Callaway is
moving down-market by going from a Temecula appellation to the more
general Coastal appellation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
