<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 THE LAST OF THE INDEPENDENTS: Neighborhood markets are alive
and  well and holding their own against the big guys.   By Karola Saekel 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Warehouse clubs and online grocery shopping are
touted as the wave of the future, but they are causing barely a
ripple in the tranquil shopping pond of the Bay Area's last great
independent grocers.
<P>
   We are not talking mom and pop stores here, but a handful of
medium-sized, full-service, high-end markets that have not only
survived the sea change in consumer shopping habits, but are
thriving in the new climate.
</P>
<P>
   Their basic strategy is a combination of two seemingly opposite
approaches _ they employ the most advanced 21st century
merchandising methods while keeping the old-fashioned values of
service and individual attention.
</P>
<P>
   To their loyalists, the advertising slogan of that online
shopping service promising never having to set foot in a grocery
store again sounds more like a threat than a bright promise: They
like to go to their grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel the energy _ with the runners and the cyclists
stopping by on the weekends,'' says a longtime Woodside resident of
that town's own cherished market, Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a vital part of the community, she says. You know the
people there and they know you. Regular customers _ and most
Woodside residents are regulars _ have accounts, so ``you can just
pop in and pick up something, or kids can charge a sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the number of full-service, upscale grocery
stores has dwindled, to be sure. Some, like San Francisco's Ashbury
Market and the Marina Super on Chestnut Street, have thrown in the
towel. Others, like Andronico's and Draeger's, have grown from
one-location stores into prosperous regional mini-chains. But there
is still a solid core of single-outlet stores that serve a
particular community or neighborhood and are still the top dog on
their special turf.
</P>
<P>
   These successful survivors share a number of traits:
</P>
<P>
   _ They are in relatively affluent and stable neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   _ They are family-owned and family-run.
</P>
<P>
   _ They have updated their stores, so while they may retain a
certain old-fashioned air, they never look outdated.
</P>
<P>
   _ They employ the latest merchandising techniques.
</P>
<P>
   _ They stay in the culinary and nutritional forefront,
frequently featuring organic labels and products from local artisan
producers.
</P>
<P>
   _ They carry large selections of locally baked breads and
outstanding arrays of produce.
</P>
<P>
   _ They cater to customers, responding to requests and criticisms
in a way larger organizations cannot match.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to widely held beliefs, they are  &LR; not &LR;  geared to the
rich and famous. True, specialty items _ fresh white asparagus,
free-range chicken, fruit preserves cooked in small batches,
hormone- and antibiotic-free beef, handmade farm cheeses _ cost
more than their plebeian counterparts. But on a one-on-one,
equal-quality comparison basis, the independents don't charge
appreciably more than the chain markets (see chart). In other
words, if you come for the specialty items, you might as well save
time and gasoline and do at least most of your shopping here.
</P>
<P>
   We picked five such grocers as typical of this possibly
endangered but still thriving species. They all share the above
characteristics, yet each has its own individual style.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CAL-MART, SAN FRANCISCO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The banks of cut flowers and potted plants running the length of
the store send a clear signal that this is not your cookie-cutter
generic supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   Located in San Francisco's Laurel Village, the nearly
50-year-old store is still owned and run by the Giampoli family and
has stayed true to its green roots.
</P>
<P>
   The father of current owners Ronald and Joseph Giampoli's
father, the senior Joseph Giampoli, started in the produce business
in North Beach and the Marina, and produce of impeccable quality is
still a major focus. But the market also carries the staples, from
canned soup to kitty litter, interspersing them with imports and
small-producer products like Hegg &AMP; Hegg canned shad roe, fancy sea
salts, Lucca ravioli, The Well-Fed Baby organic frozen baby food,
Grannyola cereal and Ciao Bella ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   The small bakery, Sweet Things, is a concession, as is the large
meat, poultry and seafood counter. This is a market where butchers
still cut meat to order and are trained to advise customers.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch hour and in the late afternoon, the deli counter sees
most of the action. From sandwiches to interesting salads to
stuffed cabbage rolls and moussaka, this is the place to assemble a
lunch or a no-hassle dinner. And although this is a favorite
shopping spot of the Pacific Heights set, prices are down-to-earth.
That moussaka is $5.99 per pound.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Cal-Mart, 3585 California St. (near Spruce Street), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 751-3516. Open 8 a.m.-8 p.m. Monday-Saturday; &LR; 
 &LR; 8:30 a.m.-6:30 p.m. Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WOODLANDS MARKET, KENTFIELD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   What will it be for dinner? Spanakopita, grilled sea scallops or
Oriental beef stir-fry, chicken Marsala or grilled Cornish game
hens, or maybe something homey like chicken pot pie or corn
pudding?
</P>
<P>
   You can get it all at Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really a hybrid of a restaurant and a supermarket,''
says manager Gary Grosetti. And indeed, like in an eclectic
restaurant, this pretty, airy market's three professional chefs
cater to global tastes. They produce party platters ranging from
$39 for chicken satay skewers to $89.99 for either grilled beef
tenderloin or smoked salmon.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy entrees like ravioli in family- or party-sized
trays, or purchase a portion for just one. And if you are too
hungry to cart your purchase home, the store offers outside picnic
tables.
</P>
<P>
   Before you head for home, you might pop into the Woodlands-owned
separate flower shop to pick up a plant or a bouquet.
</P>
<P>
   For all these fancy features, Woodlands, created from a
remodeled and expanded small grocery in 1985 by owner Don Santa, is
still a regular market with all the staples. You can purchase
ordinary packaged bread as well as artisan loaves, and the produce
display holds iceberg lettuce alongside designer greens.
</P>
<P>
   Woodlands, like other fine independents, is strong on community
connections and customer service. There is a much-used bulletin
board and the store publishes a monthly newsletter. A professional
wine buyer is on hand to guide shoppers, and there are Friday and
Saturday tastings in the in-house wine bar. This Friday will
feature Bordeaux wines. Hours are 5-7 p.m. (4-6 p.m. on Saturdays);
and there is a nominal charge, but reservations are not required.
</P>
<P>
   Should a customer have concerns about health-related topics,
nutritionist Helen Roe holds forth in a small booth near the front
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Woodlands Market, 735 College Ave. (near Sir Francis Drake &LR; 
 &LR; Boulevard), Kentfield; (415) 457-8160. Open 8 a.m.-8 p.m. &LR; 
 &LR; daily.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BROWNS VALLEY MARKET, NAPA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Off the tourist-trodden main roads of the Napa Valley, this is
the favorite store for the Browns Valley as well as the Carneros
district. Owner Jerry Giovannoni grew up here. ``I used to ride
horses where now there's nothing but subdivisions,'' he says.
Twenty years ago, his father built the small shopping center in
which the market is located.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a neighborhood store,'' Giovannoni says. ``Ninety-five
percent of our business comes from folks who live right here.''
Once an area known for grazing land and extensive orchards, with
sky-rocketing land values the choice now seems to be either housing
developments or vineyards, and his market caters to the new,
sophisticated customer.
</P>
<P>
   The bread selection is extensive, including loaves from Acme,
Artisancq &LR; , Della Fattoria, House of Bread, Panorama and Sonoma
French Bakery.
</P>
<P>
   The wine section shows similar local orientation, featuring many
wineries whose owners or winemakers are among the market's
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Giovannoni added a large deli that offers dinner
entrees, almost all made on-site. There are tortas and tamales and
prepackaged containers of entrees like pork-fried rice or beef
Stroganoff. The service meat department also accommodates today's
short-on-time consumer with such options as succulent marinated
chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma-grown, the birds are labeled ``natural'' _ and that's an
important word here. This community, says the grocer, is savvy and
concerned with nutrition issues.
</P>
<P>
   And the community is what the store is all about, he says. He
points to the store's support of local schools, including
sponsorship of the Browns Valley Market Falcons, a junior girls
softball team.
</P>
<P>
   Giovannoni is optimistic about the future of stores such as his
and doesn't worry much about competition from chains and club
stores. ``Customers go there once a week,'' he says. ``They come
here every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Browns Valley Market, 3263 Browns Valley Rd. (near Austin &LR; 
 &LR; Way), Napa; (707) 253-1873. Open 8 a.m.-9 p.m. daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; VILLAGE MARKET, OAKLAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At 4,000 square feet, this is one of the smallest of the upscale
independents and is located in a largely residential area in
Oakland's Montclair district.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jim Trimble's mantra obviously isn't ``location, location,
location'' _ his market generates no walk-by and little, if any,
drive-by traffic. Rather, it's ``service, service, service.'' And
with that, the family, which includes his wife, Janie, and son,
Joseph, who both work in the store, managed to build a loyal core
of customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Trimbles make good use of the space they have. Indoors,
fruits and vegetables are stacked high in barrels and on terra
cotta coasters, creating a tempting still life in a very compact
area. The produce spills over into a large outdoor display, but
increasing the size of the display is not the sole motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Trimble says a great produce section should appeal to all
the senses, and the non-refrigerated outdoor area adds the
sensation of smell, which is lacking in traditional icy indoor
displays.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Jim Trimble became a founding member and first
president of a group of 17 non-chain markets called Raise the Bar,
which aims to improve customer service by educating and motivating
staff. The grocers employ a full-time consultant and make use of
the services of a psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble relentlessly follows up on customer requests. He has no
space for an in-house deli but does operate a rotisserie. He
assembles prepared foods and specialty items from outstanding small
producers _ artisan cheeses from Petaluma; Lisa Lerner chocolates
from Berkeley; scones and preserves from nearby Montclair Baking;
Gianna's pastries from Sand City near Monterey; cakes from Rubicon
of Richmond and more. He also buys fresh produce direct from a
dozen nearby farms.
</P>
<P>
   Packaged entrees and salads are displayed opposite the small
service fish/meat counter. Packaged meat and poultry include
top-of-the-line Harris beef and Diestel turkeys. A recently added
concession, a compact sushi bar, makes sushi to order.
</P>
<P>
   Village has a small section of British foods, including
Britain's beloved salad cream and canned mushy peas.
</P>
<P>
   How can Trimble spare the space for such oddities? He orders
only specific items that customers request, rather than a
producer's entire line.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran grocer (he worked for Albertsons before taking over
and revamping Village Market in 1974) says the heart and soul of
his operation is a little stand-up desk and bulletin board with
request forms. If customers include their phone numbers, they get a
reply via phone. If not, the answer is written at the bottom of the
request slip, which is then posted.
</P>
<P>
   One recent note read: ``Could you please keep H &LR; a &LR; agen-Dazs
low-fat vanilla ice cream in stock? We need it.'' The reply: ``We
have talked to the delivery man.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Village Market, 5885 Broadway Terrace (at Clarewood Drive), &LR; 
 &LR; Oakland; (510) 547-3200. Open 7 a.m.-9 p.m. Monday-Saturday; 8 &LR; 
 &LR; a.m.-8 p.m. Sunday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ROBERTS OF WOODSIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You can park your 10-speed bike or tie up your steed outside the
market and slip inside for a latte or a smoothie from the coffee
bar. You can also pick up a bottle of fine Rhone-style wine from
the Santa Cruz Mountains, thick-as-molasses aged balsamic vinegar,
a loaf of ciabatta, or a heat-and-eat tray of pot roast, mashed
potatoes and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Need a dozen eggs? Over there. Laundry detergent? Down the next
aisle on your left.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is an all-purpose grocery, specialty market and
community center in one _ the bulletin board displays official
notices and personal announcements from the lost-cat to the
sublet-wanted variety.
</P>
<P>
   In a charmingly old-fashioned vein, customers have numbered
personal charge accounts. No plastic cards here; you just write
your account number on the register slip.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we have always done it,'' says Christine
Roberts, the fourth generation of the Roberts family to work in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the 1880s at California Street and Divisadero in San
Francisco by William Roberts, grandson George, the current owner,
moved the operation to the Peninsula 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost among changes in the past four decades is the growth of
prepared food. ``You just cannot have enough of it,'' says
Christine Roberts, who is in charge of specialty foods.
</P>
<P>
   She points to such prepared dinners as the pot roast (about $7
per person), many house-made salads (curried turkey is a favorite)
and several dozen sandwiches that range from turkey or pastrami
($4.50 each) to such specialties as rosemary garlic chicken breast
with sundried tomato ai &LR; o &LR; li, lettuce, tomato and onion ($5.25) and
fresh mozzarella and tomato with basil, lettuce and Italian
dressing on a ciabatta roll ($6.25). There are 16 choices of bread.
</P>
<P>
   The lunch crush can be intense, so Roberts recently added
on-line sandwich service. Customers can e-mail and fax in orders
and pick them up at the smoothie bar. This no-wait service caught
on fast, Christine Roberts says. ``After all, we are right on the
edge of Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Roberts of Woodside, 3015 Woodside Rd. (at Ca &LR; n &LR; ada Road), &LR; 
 &LR; Woodside; (650) 851-1511. Open 7 a.m.-8 p.m. daily. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VINTAGE GROCERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Browns Valley Market &LR; , 3263 Browns Valley Rd. (near Austin
Way) Napa; (707) 253-1873
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cal-Mart &LR; , 3585 California St. (near Spruce Street), San
Francisco; (415) 751-3516
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Roberts of Woodside &LR; , 3015 Woodside Road (at Ca &LR; n &LR; ada Road),
Woodside; (650) 851-1511
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Village Market &LR; , 5885 Broadway Terrace (at Clarewood Drive),
Oakland; (510) 547-3200
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Woodlands Market &LR; , 735 College Ave. (near Sir Francis Drake
Boulevard), Kentfield; (415) 457-8160
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Small Grocers Remain Popular &QL;  &LR; 
These are some other Bay Area independent grocers that have a loyal
following:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Berkeley Bowl &LR; , 2020 Oregon St. (near Shattuck Avenue),
Berkeley; (510) (510) 843-6929
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bryan's Grocery &LR; , 3445 California St. (near Laurel Street),
San Francisco; (415) 752-0179
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cunha Country Store &LR; , 448 Main St. (near Kelly Street), Half
Moon Bay, (650) 726-4071
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mill Valley Market &LR; , 12 Corte Madera Ave. (at Throckmorton
Ave.); Mill Valley, (415) 388-3222
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Piedmont Grocery Co. &LR; , 4038 Piedmont Ave. (between Monte
Vista and Glen Streets), Oakland; (510) 653-8181
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Star Grocery &LR; , 3068 Claremont Ave. (near The Uplands),
Berkeley; (510) 652-2490.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Tower Market &LR; , 635 Portola Dr. (near OShaughnessy Boulevard)
San Francisco; (415) 664-1602 (currently undergoing a change in
ownership)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Young's Grocery and Meat Store &LR; , 285 Arlington Ave. (near
Amhurst Street), Kensington; (510) 526-9858
</P>
<P>
   If readers have other favorite stores that fit this profile _
full-service, high-end market, independently owned and operated _
we would like to hear about them. Drop us a line or e-mail us at
 &LR; food &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
