<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-MARTINEZ-MIGRATION-CO     07-25 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINEZ-MIGRATION-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS WITHOUT A NEST
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Wednesday, July 19, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MARTINEZ-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.2000 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGHLAND PARK, N.J. _ Every day, thousands of people abandon the
hell they think they are living in and travel in search of a
paradise where they imagine every kind of happiness is possible.
And what they often find, if they get there at all, is another
hell, even worse than the one they left.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to the 60 Chinese migrants who paid their
lifesavings to submit to a four-month odyssey that began in Fujian
Province, China, and ended June 18 in the sealed container of a
Dutch cargo truck aboard a ferry crossing the English Channel.
Anchored in front of the white cliffs of Dover, England, only two
men survived while the rest died of suffocation on the warmest day
of the English summer.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar, though with a more fortunate outcome,
happened to Iraqi Tara Mohammed. He walked barefoot from his home
in Kirkuk to the Turkish border, hiding by day in sewers and barns
and walking at night. After a week, with the soles of his feet raw,
he arrived in Istanbul, where he found a truck driver who accepted
the $4,000 dollars he had sown to his shirt in exchange for
dropping him ``anywhere in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidden in the closed trailer truck among gradually rotting
produce, he arrived very dehydrated in Dover. By coincidence, his
arrival was on the same day the English authorities found the
bodies of the dead Chinese migrants. Moved by his plight, the
immigration officers allowed him to stay in the London ``paradise''
for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Life in this world has never been fair, but perhaps it hasn't
been as unfair as it is now. Out of the 6 billion people on this
planet, the richest one-fifth receives 86 percent of all the income
produced, while the poorest one-fifth retains only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme differences have also created extreme fantasies. For
the poor, happiness will always be somewhere else: '' ... no matter
where, as long as it is far from this world,'' as Baudelaire wrote
in Le Spleen de Paris.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 19th century, whole families migrated from
Europe, which at that time was a continent without hope, and
traveled to Argentina, Brazil, the United States. The majority were
Italians, Germans, Irish, Spaniards, Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, migration flows in every direction, but especially
from the peripheral countries to industrial nations. And it is
usually only one member of a family at a time, because there's not
enough money to pay for other family members, too.
</P>
<P>
   But happiness, and even poverty, is relative. What is unbearable
for some may be coveted by others. In Mar del Plata, Argentina's
beautiful Atlantic coast city, the unemployment rate has reached 19
percent, and so one-tenth of the population has migrated in the
last two years. Thousands of young people currently wait for an
Italian or Spanish passport so they can travel to the homelands of
their grandfathers to search for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago Bolivian farmer Fidencio Choque traveled from
Tarija, Bolivia, to Escobar, Argentina, 40 kilometers north of
Buenos Aires. For him there's no better place in the world than the
fertile land near Mar del Plata. The free education he always
wanted for his sons and grandsons is still the best in the Americas
_ and he is right about that _ and bread, though sometimes not in
great quantity, is always on his table.
</P>
<P>
   Things were never easy for 31-year-old Choque. With a heart
tattooed on his chest, he settled in Escobar as a hired hand on one
of the area's many vegetable farms. After years of toil he was
finally able to rent 3 hectares of land for 300 pesos a month,
where he grows vegetables that he takes to market. He and 12
members of his family live in a little house with no windows,
bathroom or electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But these ``nothings'' were enough to inflame the envy of
others. Early on June 23, 10 armed and masked men broke into the
house, beat Fidencio for two hours and seared off his tattoo with a
white-hot iron. Aware the Choque family had no bank account _ it
seemed pointless for so little, Fidencio thought _ the thieves, who
some say were policemen, took whatever they found in the house,
including the family's lifesavings of $3,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In pain from internal injuries, hurt and terrified, Fidencio's
only desire now is to forget that nightmare and return to the
bountiful prairies of Mar del Plata, the place which so many young
men are so eager to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Borders are porous everywhere, and human beings cross illegally
any way they can. Their passage can take them through open air
sewers like those of El Bordo, in Tijuana, Mexico, or old ducts, or
aboard rickety boats like those that leave Tortuga Island, Haiti,
to cross the Caribbean Sea in storm season. Or they are hidden on
cargo boats and trains and in sealed containers such as the one in
which the Chinese met their death at Dover.
</P>
<P>
   It cost the Choque family very little money to travel to
Argentina. But the Chinese who want to journey to Europe are not so
lucky. The average cost of getting a Chinese to any place in the
European Union, fake passport included, is $25,000 dollars. Even
with that price, the migrants may have to wait two or three months
in seedy hotel rooms in Belgium or Moscow, surviving on only bread
and water.
</P>
<P>
   However, this price is merely half the amount charged for
smuggling humans into the United States. Which explains why
families send only one young man from the village, in the hopes
he'll save enough to allow the migration of another. The Chinese
estimate that if the young man works an average of 15-16 hours, six
days a week, he can earn in a month what it would take him a year
to earn in China.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone has to pay, no matter the distance. A man from Central
America has to come up with $2,000 dollars to cross from Tijuana to
Los Angeles, which is 20 percent more than what Mexicans have to
pay, and 90 percent of them have to suffer indignities and abuse
before crossing the border.
</P>
<P>
   This flow of human beings is now one of the most lucrative
trades in the world. More than $3 billion dollars change hands each
month just in illegal migration to the European Union. If the
situation doesn't improve, it will be an even greater and more
lucrative business than the drug trade.
</P>
<P>
   Rich countries are frequently intolerant of the foreigners who
arrive in search of a job. They don't stop to think that the
decision to risk everything in a perilous journey to an unknown
land, without knowing its customs or language, shows a bold courage
and will to survive worthy of admiration and respect. Exodus is
almost always born of desperation, but other motivations include
ambition, family unity and the ultimate dream of becoming
``someone'' in this life.
</P>
<P>
   Opening borders to anyone of good will was a utopian goal in the
19th century, but in this era of supreme inequality it can no
longer be. Nevertheless, a humane and sensible migration policy is
something that cannot be postponed any longer, because today's tide
could turn into tomorrow's flood.
</P>
<P>
   When Tara Mohammed reached Dover, he said simply that his only
aspiration was ``to live like the English.'' One doesn't have to
think hard to understand that to live ``like others'' is one of the
most legitimate rights of the human species _ and perhaps the least
attainable.
</P>
<P>
   (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the author of ``The Peron Novel'' and
``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American studies
department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an editor
and journalist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
