<HEADLINE>
MONADNOCK REGION VILLAGES AND COUNTRYSIDE BLOOM IN SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FITZWILLIAM, N.H. _ Nowhere else in New England can claim as
many Currier &AMP; Ives print-worthy villages as the Monadnock Region,
named for the mountain that rises dramatically from the gently
rolling countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly little has changed since the 19th century. Communities
like Fitzwilliam _ visualize white clapboard houses and steepled
meetinghouses grouped around a town green _ seem to doze much of
the year. Then high summer arrives (at last), and the landscape
suddenly gets lusher, the social scene livelier, and the
granite-ribbed countryside echoes with music.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-July, for instance, Rhododendron Maximum _ wild
rhododendron that grow up to 30 feet high _ are blooming, along
with other wildflowers, beside the paths and under the pine trees
of Rhododendron State Park in Fitzwilliam. Beautiful and profoundly
still, but for an occasional bird call, the park is a wonderful
spot for a picnic or a nature walk.
</P>
<P>
   Equally resonant of place is Monadnock Music, the acclaimed
local music festival. Each summer for 36 years the
Peterborough-based nonprofit organization Monadnock Music has
transformed the churches, meetinghouses, and town halls of regional
hamlets and small towns into concert halls. The venues are rural,
but the programs, which include infrequently performed classical
and interesting new pieces as well as standard works, are of
international-festival quality with first-rank instrumentalists and
singers from around the country and overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Monadnock Music 2000, which continues through mid-September,
offers nearly three dozen programs ranging from recitals and
chamber concerts to an adaptation of Gaetano Donizetti's opera
``Don Pasquale.'' Admission ($14 to $34) is charged for only 15
events, all at the Peterborough Town House.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the series, usually chamber music performances
or recitals by individual artists, are free and held in small
communities (some with fewer than 200 residents) across the
Monadnock Region. They include such unself-consciously beautiful
and relatively untouristed places as Nelson, Washington,
Harrisville, Hancock, Francestown, Fitzwilliam, and Jaffrey Center.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years quite a few concertgoers have come for Monadnock
Music and stayed to discover the area _ and even to settle.
``People are always telling us about how they came to a concert,
fell in love with a town, and decided to buy a house there,'' says
Jocelyn Bolle, executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the churches and meetinghouses used in the series date
to Colonial days. Designed by self-taught country builders, they
are gracefully proportioned and frequently have acoustics any
big-city concert hall would envy.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the Old Meeting House in Jaffrey Center, for
example, began the day the battle of Bunker Hill was fought. It has
been the focal point of the village ever since. In a concert Aug.
27, the old church's long paneled nave (site of many a
fire-and-brimstone sermon) will amplify the artful notes of a Haydn
symphony and a Mozart string quartet.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska-born writer Willa Cather spent many summers in the
Monadnock Region and wrote some of her best-known works in Jaffrey
Center. She is buried in the old graveyard behind the Meeting
House, beneath a headstone inscribed with a quotation from her
novel ``My Antonia,'' written in a nearby boardinghouse. ``That is
happiness,'' it reads,`` to be dissolved into something complete
and great.''
</P>
<P>
   Cather was one of the many writers, artists, and musicians who
first experienced the Monadnock Region while staying at the
MacDowell Colony in Peterborough, the oldest such creative retreat
in the country. Another MacDowell Colony writer-in-residence,
Thornton Wilder, used Peterborough as the model for the New England
small town in ``Our Town,'' one of the most frequently performed
plays in the English language.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing ``Our Town'' in the place that inspired it and where it
was written makes for a memorable theatrical experience. However,
to keep its repertoire fresh, the Peterborough Players, the area's
highly respected local summer theater company, presents the Wilder
play only once a decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, this is a new decade, and ``Our Town'' will be staged
Aug. 2-20. Veteran character actor James Whitmore will appear in
the key role of ``the stage manager'' or narrator. The company is
currently showing ``The Philanderer,'' a comedy by George Bernard
Shaw. All productions are in the renovated (and air-conditioned)
barn where ``Our Town'' had its local premiere in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everywhere you go in the region you get glimpses and
views of Mount Monadnock. Benignly omnipresent, Monadnock is
visible on clear days for more than 50 miles in any direction. It
is the centerpiece of Monadnock State Park, accessible from Route
125 (Dublin Road) west of Jaffrey Center.
</P>
<P>
   Monadnock is the second-most climbed mountain in the world
(Mount Fuji in Japan is first), which says something about the
sweeping view from the 3,165-foot-high summit. More than 130,000
people made the ascent last year, many climbing a mountain for the
very first time. Children are welcome, but pets are not allowed in
the state park.
</P>
<P>
   The six trails to the summit are well-marked but steep and rocky
in places. Caution, common sense, and appropriate footwear are
essential. Still, if you've always wanted to climb a mountain and
don't mind some company, Monadnock is the peak for you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
