<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-25 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKING PLANS FOR SARATOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saratoga, which opens Wednesday, offers first-class racing in a
beautiful setting, but don't act like a snob when you go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that struck me about last year's meeting was
the success of certain outfits that hadn't previously had
success,'' said Jim Mazur, coauthor of ``The Saratoga Handicapper
2000.'' ``The key to winning at Saratoga is to not downgrade some
of the shippers because they're coming from Calder or Rockingham.
Mohammed Moubarak (22-4-3-3, 18 percent winners, 45 percent in the
money, average win payoff $20.80) and Eddie Plesa Jr. (19-5-3-0, 26
percent winners, 42 percent in the money, average win payoff
$13.40) had their horses ready. From Rock, the two names that stick
out are Michael Aro and Charlie Assimakopoulos.''
</P>
<P>
   Mazur, 43, is the president of Progressive Handicapping, Inc.,
which publishes meet-specific handicapping books as well as ``The
Triple Crown Handicapper'' and ``Crushing The Cup.'' ``The Saratoga
Handicapper'' evolved from ``Saratoga Scorecard,'' written by
coauthor John Angelo, and the publications have a combined 13-year
history. With the 36-day Spa meeting, which runs through Labor Day,
on the horizon, helpful information is at a premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``In last year's book, we pointed out that Aro had won two
straight years with Champagneforlisa,'' Mazur said. ``Sure enough,
he came back and won with her for a third time (scored Aug. 2 at
5-2). He's 5 for 10, with an average win mutuel of $28, over the
last three seasons, and four of his winners came in the horse's
first start of the meet. He hits, and then he's gone.
Assimakopoulos is the opposite of Aro. Over the last three meets,
he's 0 for 13 the first time a horse starts, then 4 for 9 in the
second start.''
</P>
<P>
   For many fans, the highlight of the Saratoga meeting is the
2-year-old racing, and trainer D. Wayne Lukas always makes an
effort to shine in that category. He won nine juvenile races last
year and a total of 20 over the last three years. However, Mazur
points out that John Ward Jr. is also excellent with 2-year-olds,
winning with 4 of 8 first time starters over the past three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry Bailey's been the dominating jockey, but from a value
perspective, take a look at Jorge Chavez,'' said Masur. ``In the
last three years, Chavez has won 80 races, with an average payoff
of $12. Bailey has won 124 races, but his average payoff is $7.
Even better, try Edgar Prado. He's just starting at Saratoga, and
he's got 38 winners for a $16 average. I'd put Robbie Albarado in
that category, too, but it looks like he's going to ride in
California. I'm not saying to bet on second-tier riders, but you
don't have to bet on the riders who get all the attention, like
Bailey.''
</P>
<P>
   For reasons unknown, front-runners did better on the turf last
year than previously, winning at a 25 percent clip on the inner
turf and a 27 percent rate on the outer. In 1993, front-runners on
the outer turf won only 15 percent of their races. Stalkers still
win 50 percent of the events over the lawn. Mazur can't explain why
this is other than to speculate the competition has gotten slightly
weaker, but the front-running trend is one to watch.
</P>
<P>
   What you definitely can avoid is an inside horse in a sprint. At
6, 6 1/2, and 7 furlongs, only eight of 138 starters, or 6 percent,
captured a race from the rail. However, closers have a tough time
as well, with only nine winners among 63 starters, or 14 percent,
at three-quarters of a mile. At 7 furlongs, post Nos. 6-10 all won
more races than Nos. 1 and 2. For route races, the bias is
pronounced to the inside. Of 216 races run at 1 1/8 miles since
1993, 20 percent have been won by No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed plays well going long,'' Mazur said. ``Front-runners or
stalkers have won 75 percent of the routes over the last three
years. Last year, 43 percent of the nine furlong winners went
wire-to-wire, while only 13 percent rallied to win. But the best
advice is to watch closely for the first few days, because you
never know. One thing for sure, the hotter it is, the more
pronounced the speed bias will be. I think the track gets packed
down, and it can reach a point where, if you're not in the first
flight, you have no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping at Saratoga can also be enhanced by the Internet,
and for the first time, Mazur will offer The Daily Sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it takes time for our subscribers to look things up
and write them down,'' he said. ``Now we have The Daily Sheet,
about 10 pages of percentage highs and lows, key races, and horses
to watch, by John Angelo, who attends every day of the meeting,
that can be downloaded and printed out. We leave you no room to
forget. People are short on time these days, and now you don't have
to look things up yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We debuted this at Gulfstream last spring, are currently doing
it at Monmouth and Belmont, and will do it at Saratoga and Del Mar
this summer. It's been very popular. Streaks can develop at
Saratoga in two or three days, and even though we update the book
twice during the meet, the sheet will keep you informed
day-to-day.''
</P>
<P>
   More information on ``The Saratoga Handicapper 2000'' and The
Daily Sheet is available at 800-272-8039.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Keeping track, long distance
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hartmann, general manager of Plainridge Racecourse, is
moving to Florida, but he will stay involved with the harness track
in Plainville, Mass., as a consultant. Hartmann, 50, who also
worked at Foxboro Stadium, has been instrumental in establishing
Plainridge, now in its second year, through simulcasting,
marketing, and public relations . . . These are tough times for Bob
Baffert. Nautical Look, a 3-year-old trained by Baffert, tested
positive for morphine after winning the seventh race at Hollywood
May 3. Truesdail Laboratories reported the finding, which was
confirmed by a Texas lab. The California Horse Racing Board has
issued a complaint against Baffert, and the stewards at Del Mar,
which opens Wednesday, will schedule a hearing. George Hofmeister,
who purchased 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet for $1.1
million, has sued Baffert, claiming Real Quiet ``has been unable to
race due to severe injuries to both front legs.'' Baffert called
the suit ``frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to preapre this report.
</P>
