<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2375 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     07-25 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVICI SYSTEMS MOVES THE PIECES INTO POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's seven feet tall, weighs 1,200 pounds, and appears to make
investors salivate?
</P>
<P>
   It is the high-speed telecommunications gear manufactured by
Avici Systems Inc., a young company scheduled to go public this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters jacked up the size of the Avici IPO by 75 percent
Monday, adding another million shares for sale and increasing the
price range from the original $18 to $20 per share to $28 to $30.
Now the offering is expected to raise about $210 million and give
Avici an initial stock market value of about $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a sign they have solid institutional demand lined up,''
said Jeff Hirschkorn, a senior market analyst at IPO.com. Avici
``has a product that's in demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschkorn expects the stock to be hot when it begins trading,
scheduled for Friday. So does George Nichols, an IPO analyst at
Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This company has generated a lot of buzz,'' said Nichols.
``It's probably going to be a scorcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, considering Avici, of Billerica, Mass., is hitting the
market in what appears to be the biggest IPO week of the year so
far, as underwriters push out a huge number of shares in front of
the usual August lull.
</P>
<P>
   Avici certainly is selling the kind of hardware the
telecom-enamored stock market likes to see, giant terabit switch
routers that can help direct massive amounts of network traffic for
Internet service providers and other potential customers. Never
mind that customers may need to reinforce floors supporting the
machines that stand nearly as tall as Shaquille O'Neal and can
weigh about four times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware companies such as Avici sell components that can turn
the vast potential of fiber-optic networks into reality, connecting
and switching huge amounts of data so it gets to where it is
supposed to go at the speed of light.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are flocking to the stocks of those companies because
demand for their products is already impressive and expected to
grow enormously for years to come. Avici is likely to benefit from
that trend, at least in its early days as a public stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a position in the sun because they stuck it out,
persevered, and went after a big hairy market, which they're in
now,'' said Todd Dagres, general partner at Batterymarch Ventures,
a venture capital firm in Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the stock market likes high-end, high-performance
carrier equipment, particularly if it plugs into optical networks,
and that's where they're positioned,'' he said. ``The only question
I have is: do they really have the advanced technology?''
</P>
<P>
   Avici must wrestle with the same hurdles that small
communications gear companies face: tough competitors,
fast-changing technology, and a limited operating history with just
a few customers.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: Avici and its giant boxes face towering
competition from established companies such as Cisco Systems Inc.
and Juniper Networks. Even if it has an edge, will the company have
what it takes to stay ahead?
</P>
<P>
   The good news: Juniper Networks proved an upstart can muscle its
way into a rapidly evolving market. Juniper, the newcomer when it
went public last summer, has seen its shares soar astonishingly by
a factor of 21 since its IPO in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Several competitors on Avici's scale have been bought since by
giant companies, most notably the $900 million acquisition of
Nexabit Networks Inc. of Marlborough, Mass. by Lucent Technologies
Inc. last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Avici, which began marketing its products last fall, has
generated about $126 million in losses so far. Revenue in the
second quarter was estimated at $2.2 million, according to the
company's most recent public documents.
</P>
<P>
   Avici has been funded by three California venture-capital firms
and Nortel Networks Corp. Nortel had been seen as a possible
acquirer of the young company, but it severed its relationship with
Avici last summer at just about the same time Juniper went public
and Nexabit was sold to Lucent.
</P>
<P>
   Now Avici has tentative deals with Williams Communications and
Enron Broadband Services for the sale of $45 million worth of
equipment this year. The sales are subject to field trials now
being conducted by the customers. Avici's terabit switch router has
been lab-tested by AT&AMP;T Corp. and selected for field trials later
this year, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other telecom gear companies, there's no denying the
potential at Avici. But can all these companies be the big winners
their stock prices suggest, even with the huge anticipated demand
for their hardware?
</P>
<P>
   The sobering truth: it's hard to tell the best from the rest at
this stage and there's already a lot of money on the table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
