<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TEXTRON-MINES-ART-BOS     07-25 1761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXTRON-MINES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 HIGH-TECH LAND MINE TRIGGERS WAR OF WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Textron Systems stands to win hundreds of millions of dollars in
Army orders for a new high-tech land mine meant to enable the
United States to meet the criteria of an international treaty
restricting the use of mines.
</P>
<P>
   The ``man-in-the-loop'' technology being developed by a Textron
unit in Wilmington, Mass., in theory, would reduce the risks from
mines to civilians and friendly troops by using sensors to detect
enemy troops and alert soldiers who could detonate the mines
remotely.
</P>
<P>
   But the business, which would bolster Textron's defense
revenues, may be jeopardized by a dispute emerging over triggering
software that would give Army commanders the option of overriding
the ``man-in-the-loop'' on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration hopes to deploy the new mines in the
next few years as part of an effort to bring the nation into
compliance with the 1997 Ottawa Convention. Critics, however, say
the software being studied by the Pentagon would violate that
antipersonnel mine treaty by enabling the new mines to explode
nearly as indiscriminately as those in the Army's current arsenal.
One influential US senator, Patrick Leahy of Vermont, is
threatening to oppose funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's contracts carry the potential for as much as $500
million in orders for Textron Systems and a partner, Alliant
Integrated Defense Co. of Minneapolis. The orders are important to
parent Textron Inc. of Providence, R.I., as it seeks to diversify
its business base in the aftermath of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Textron's defense work peaked at around 25 percent of total
revenue in 1990. But that figure has declined in recent years under
chief executive Lewis Campbell, who has focused on the
manufacturing company's commercial lines ranging from automotive
parts to civilian helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Sales to the US government, primarily military goods, accounted
for $1.3 billion, just over 10 percent of Textron's revenue of
$11.6 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The military's high-tech mine program was a direct response to
criticism of the US refusal to sign the Ottawa treaty. The treaty
prohibits antipersonnel mines ``designed to be exploded by the
presence, proximity or contact of a person and that will
incapacitate, injure or kill one or more persons.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States held back from signing, citing a need for
mines in areas such as South Korea's northern border. But the
Clinton adminstration said in 1998 that the United States should be
ready to sign by 2006 if substitute measures are developed.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy centers on a setting that could be added to the
mine known as ``battlefield override.'' In this mode, the mines
would detonate whenever an approaching person tripped either a wire
or an electronic sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy, a longtime critic of land mine deployment, calls the
technology ``very troubling'' and says it would violate the Ottawa
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In a May 10 letter to Undersecretary of Defense Walter Slocombe,
Leahy wrote that ``it is clear to me that the (override) feature is
being included because some field commanders have never accepted
the administration's 1997 policy to accede to the Ottawa
Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon spokesman, Marine Lieutenant Colonel Dave Lapan, said
officials still are weighing whether to include the override. He
said the Pentagon hasn't yet begun a legal review of whether an
override would, in fact, violate the Ottawa treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still too premature to discuss specifics such as the
battlefield override feature,'' Lapan wrote in a recent e-mail.
``Our efforts are still in the exploratory stage, seeking to
address both humanitarian concerns and the needs of the
warfighter.''
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier letter to Leahy, Slocombe also wrote that by
studying the feature, the military might gain
``as-of-yet-unforeseen insights'' in mine development.
</P>
<P>
   The broad debate matters for the contractors because Leahy, a
member of the Senate's Defense Appropriations subcommittee, is
threatening to oppose funding to develop the weapon unless the Army
drops the software enabling the override setting.
</P>
<P>
   Other experimental designs might distinguish between tanks and
civilian vehicles automatically, or attach microelectronic homing
beacons to enemy troops or vehicles that could be used to target
shells fired from conventional guns or mortars.
</P>
<P>
   But Textron's design is the most advanced and is scheduled to
enter service by 2003. As a result, mine opponents have seized on
the override feature to press the administration on its stance on
the treaty as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Even consideration of the override ``certainly makes you
quesiton the commitment of the US government to joining the land
mine treaty,'' said policy analyst Rachel Stohl of the Center for
Defense Information, a liberal think tank in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   With an override, ``This weapon will be an indiscriminate
killer, unable to tell a soldier from a civilian,'' Stephen Goose
of the Human Rights Watch lobbying group, said in a statement.
``The Pentagon's alternative to land mines is no alternative at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Textron Systems senior vice president Frank Tempesta said the
company could develop the new mine either with or without the
override setting, which would be created with the addition of a few
lines of software code to the command modules soldiers would used
to control the mines.
</P>
<P>
   Textron and Alliant were issued contracts last month to begin
joint-development work on the new mines.
</P>
<P>
   Land mines have been used by the United States and NATO forces
for decades, particularly along borders where allied troops have
been outnumbered, such as the border between North and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the Cold War, though, mine use has come under
criticism for the damages mines cause in developing nations. The
State Department estimates there are between 60 to 70 million mines
buried worldwide, maiming and killing thousands of civilians each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy has been concerned about mines since the late 1980s, when
he started a fund to aid victims. In 1991, groups such as Human
Rights Watch and the Vietnam Veterans of America Foundation began
calling for the abolition of the weapon. Retired General Norman
Schwartzkopf and other figures eventually endorsed the movement
that became known as the International Campaign to Ban Landmines,
and one of its architects, Jody Williams of Putney, Vt., won a
Nobel Peace Prize for her work in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, 100 countries signed the Ottawa Convention
banning most antipersonnel mines, though not antitank devices or
certain other categories of mines. Signatories now include most
NATO members, such as Britain and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Russia and China are still holdouts. Two
years ago, President Clinton said the United States would sign by
2006 ``if we succeed in identifying and fielding suitable
alternatives'' to existing mines by then.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Textron Systems, which employs 1,200 people in and around
Wilmington making remote sensors and complex military gear such as
microwave transmitters to help land big transport planes on remote
airstrips. It also sells the Army an antitank mine known as the
Hornet Wide Area Munition.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Textron and Alliant were chosen from 52 companies
competing to build weapons for what the Army calls its
``Anti-Personnel Landmine Alternatives'' program.
</P>
<P>
   The Army hopes to replace some of its existing mines based on
World War II models, which blast steel fragments in a deadly circle
60 feet across. Officers at the Army's Picatinny Arsenal in New
Jersey said Textron's prototypes connected new electronics to the
Army's existing M16 mine, which includes up to four pounds of
explosive in a coffee can-sized container.
</P>
<P>
   The Army envisions a new weapon that would pack explosives into
tubes pointed in six directions, each of which could be fired
remotely, said Pentagon spokesman Lapan. The weapon also might
include nonlethal capabilities such as nets or tear gas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some military analysts say the override setting is needed to
make the mine effective, and that Clinton's 1998 pledge to try to
comply with Ottawa via technology was never realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man-in-the-loop would require that some poor fool stay at the
controls while the rest of the unit bugs out under an assault, and
that's not a great way to run things,'' said Dan Goure, of the
Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington. The
center's president, John Hamre, recently stepped down as deputy
defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Goure compared the ``battlefield override'' setting to one that
already exists on the Navy's Phalanx antimissile guns, which are
aimed by radar and can be set to fire at any moving target that
appears over the horizon in combat. ``There are rules of engagement
for that weapon, and land mines would be similar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army first described the override feature about six months
ago at a conference held by the National Academy of Sciences, but
only as a hypothetical possibility, said Lapan. The Army's actual
study of the override switch was publicized by Caleb Rossiter, a
policy consultant to the Vietnam Veterans of America Foundation,
which has close ties to the military and to Leahy's office.
</P>
<P>
   Rossiter says he supports an upgraded mine for the Army, and
that the override feature could be useful during a firefight. But
preparing the United States to sign and comply with the Ottawa
treaty is more important, he said. ``Our argument has been, of
course there's some military utility to these land mines,'' he
said. ``But the humanitarian cost far outweighs that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossiter said he is disappointed because the new mine
technologies previously have been advertised as in keeping with the
Ottawa treaty.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in a press release last month after it received
the Army contract, Textron's partner Alliant quoted its president,
Hubert D. Hopkins, as saying that the the man-in-the-loop design
``leaves no risk to friendly troops or noncombatants following a
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   An Alliant spokeswoman said the statement is still ``consistent
with what we believe the intent of the (new mine) program will
be.'' But with the final design unclear, she said, the company
might revise its statements in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
