<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN ANALOG AND DIGITAL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is the difference between the much used terminology of
``analog'' and ``digital'' as used in electronic equipment? K.B.,
North Attleborough, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Analog quantities are quantities that, at least in principle,
can take on any value within some range. For example, the
temperature outside might take on any value between 0 and 100 today
_ perhaps it will be 86.45321 degrees. They correspond to the
numbers you use to measure things and can, in principle, have an
infinite number of decimal places.
</P>
<P>
   Digital quantities can only take on a set of discrete values,
like the number of eggs you have in the refrigerator _ a 10th of an
egg would make no sense. They correspond to the numbers you use to
count things and always have a finite number of digits.
</P>
<P>
   Where it applies to electronic equipment, such as recording
devices, analog's advantage is that the entire sound is recorded in
a continuous wave and sent to the speakers, rather than the digital
method that essentially records pieces of sound and then links them
together.
</P>
<P>
   But this is also analog's drawback because, in the case of music
recording, background noise, distortion, interference, even the
sound of the recording equipment itself can be picked up and
recreated in the final product and there's nothing you can do about
it.
</P>
<P>
   It's also easy to make mistakes in sending, storing, and
processing analog information since it's often hard to tell whether
the last few decimal places were really what they were originally,
or if they corresponded to some unavoidable distortions that got
picked up along the way: In principle, you need an infinite number
of decimal places and while you might be able to send an infinite
amount of information in one analog number, the odds are that most
will get lost in all the little confusions that are bound to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Digital information is much more robust. Suppose you want to
send the number ``27,'' and what is received is ``27.0213.'' You
might guess then that the .0213 is due to some error, and that the
real message was ``27,'' and you would very likely be correct. If
you really wanted to send 27.0213, you might send 270213 and 4 to
remind you to put a decimal point four places in from the right.
</P>
<P>
   In music recording, then, all extraneous sound is stripped from
the signal and you're left with an exact electronic interpretation,
or picture, of only the music that was being created. This makes
digitally recorded music perhaps sound cleaner and brighter, but
purists would counter that it is only a computerized picture of the
sound, not the complete sound itself.
</P>
<P>
   Any analog information can always be approximated digitally,
and, although it means losing decimal places, you can always take
as many as you want and write the rest of them off as being no
bigger than the unavoidable noise. This is useful for turning old
scratchy Billie Holiday recordings into better-sounding digital
masters. You can try to keep some of the nonmusical essence that
makes the performance special while you discard annoying scratches
or other interference.
</P>
<P>
   It is for this reason that most music now is stored digitally.
Similarly, for computer calculations, it's convenient to represent
numbers, even if they might come close to representing a continuous
quantity, by a set of single digits _ usually in what is called
``binary,'' so that you only use ones and zeroes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
