<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-PILOTS-ART-2TAKES     07-25 1424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PILOTS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLYING SAFER SKIES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As peaks in the Olympic Range go, Green Mountain isn't
impressive. But, at 2,400 feet, it certainly is high enough _ and
wide enough _ to be a dangerous obstacle for airplanes. Watching it
grow larger by the second in the windscreen of Honeywell's
experimental Beechcraft King Air during a flight last month, the
mountain looked particularly ominous.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the flight was not to collide with Green Mountain
but to demonstrate technology's answer to what pilots call
``controlled flight into terrain.'' The innocuous-sounding phrase,
known in aviation circles by its abbreviation CFIT (cee-fit),
refers to mechanically sound airplanes flown by skilled pilots who
maintained perfect control over the airplanes as they flew into the
ground or mountainside.
</P>
<P>
   CFIT is the leading cause of death in airplane accidents, with
more than 2,000 fatalities worldwide since 1990. In 1995, an
American Airlines flight slammed into a mountain in Cali, Colombia,
killing 160 people, when a pilot unfamiliar with the area became
confused and didn't realize a mountain loomed ahead. Two years
later, a Korean Air Boeing 747 crashed into a hill 3 miles from a
Guam runway, killing 228.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that, until recently, pilots haven't had
instruments that can ``see'' obstacles in front of them _ even if
they are as big as a mountain. As a result, if the pilot doesn't
notice the obstacle, the instruments won't warn him, either.
</P>
<P>
   But, thanks to the same global positioning system technology
that can tell hikers and drivers where they are at all times, that
is changing. The Enhanced Ground Proximity Warning System, which
lists at about $68,000 per plane, is a computer that uses a
database of the world's topography, combined with GPS technology
and a complex formula for the plane's position and movements to
warn pilots of obstacles in the flight path.
</P>
<P>
   The display screen is adjustable to look ahead from 10 to 345
nautical miles, shows safe flight paths in green, marking places
where all obstacles are at least 500 feet below the plane. Yellow
lights mark terrain features that are less than 500 feet below the
plane or up to 1,000 feet above it. Even higher obstacles, which
would require dramatic maneuvers to avoid, are marked in red. A
voice amplifies the warning as the plane closes in on the yellow or
red zones.
</P>
<P>
   In the test plane, yellow and red were dominating the screen in
the path of the airplane as it approached Green Mountain, and pilot
Markus Johnson had ignored the initial alerts of ``Caution,
terrain!'' that came from the system when he was still a minute
away from hitting the mountain. At 30 seconds, the electronic voice
became more urgent, saying ``Terrain! Pull up! Pull up!''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, eager to alarm four journalists attending a recent
safety conference, not only continued flying toward the mountain,
the altimeter was actually winding down as the plane descended. It
was a matter of who would blink first and it wasn't close. When a
radio reporter broke and said, ``OK, you can pull up now,'' Johnson
banked and climbed away from the peak, the G forces pinning the
occupants in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-proximity warning systems have been around for more than
30 years, but they could only look straight down because they were
based on radar altimeter technology that throws radio waves off the
Earth's surface and calculates distance by the speed that they
return.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, pilots only learned of an approaching obstacle by
changes in the distance to the ground below. If the mountain was
steep-sided, such warnings would leave very little time to react.
In addition, the original ground warning systems had to be
suppressed when landing gear was down and the flaps were extended
because it meant the plane was landing.
</P>
<P>
   But the new enhanced version _ Honeywell is the prime
manufacturer _ runs on far less limiting technology. GPS, which
uses satellites orbiting the planet to determine precise locations
of anyone with a GPS transmitter, determines where the plane is.
Then, the highly detailed computer database of the world's terrain
gives the pilot a precise map of all terrain features around him _
including the exact position of runways.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, the computer employs a ``look-ahead
algorithm'' based on the plane's movement to determine which
obstacles pose the most immediate threat. That algorithm, or
formula, takes into account the aircraft's position, flight path
angle, turn rate or roll, and relative speed to give the pilot up
to several minutes of advance warning.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson demonstated the system after the close encounter with
the mountain. Flying out over Dabob Bay, Johnson brought the plane
down from 3,000 to 1,000 feet, as if he were beginning a final
approach to land. The only indication that something was amiss was
the radar screen painting what had been blue terrain (for water)
into yellow (for potentially hazardous land).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson put down the landing gear, and even turned on the
landing lights for effect. ``My flaps are set, the rate of descent
is fine,'' he said, running through a mental checklist. ``I'm
coming in to land and everything would be telling the older system
that we were making one hell of an approach.'' The only problem:
The plane was miles from any runway.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, when the altimeter read 700 feet, the electronic voice
blurted out: ``Terrain, terrain! Pull up! Pull up!''
</P>
<P>
   The database also contains more than 20,000 manmade obstacles,
like radio and television towers, in North America. And it will
alert the pilot when a turn or dive is extreme. When the airplane
took off from Boeing Field, traffic was flying overhead on final
approach to Seattle Tacoma International Airport, so Johnson was
forced to make a sharp right turn under the jets. Commercial
airplanes normally bank at no more than 30 degrees. The alerting
system on board the airplane was set to go off when the bank
reached 52 degrees, and when Johnson made the turn, the mechanical
voice let it be known to all on board he exceeded 52 degrees,
because it warned ``Bank rate!''
</P>
<P>
   Such a pointed warning system might have saved the passengers
and crew on Korean Air Flight 801, which crashed into a 650-foot
hillside in Guam in 1997, killing all but 26 on aboard.
Investigators found that the pilots flew an approach as if all
navigation aids used in instrument landings were working, but they
were not. As a result, the plane hit a small hill that was obscured
in a rain storm.
</P>
<P>
   Today, more than 5,000 commercial jetliners are equipped with
enhanced ground warning systems, about one-third of the worldwide
fleet. It is standard equipment on all new aircraft. Honeywell
officials say that there have been at least 15 incidents when the
system helped avert tragedy, including a 777 that was attempting to
land in Rio de Janiero, but was coming in too low when the system
alerted the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   A $30,000 version is available for small- and medium-sized
business jets and Honeywell is awaiting certification of a $10,000
general aviation model.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots say its widespread use cannot occur soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that (the new warning system) is the single biggest
safety advance since the installation of the jet engine,'' said
Capt. Robert L. Sumwalt III, chairman of the Air Line Pilots
Association human factors and ergonomics committee.
</P>
<P>
   The system is being used by several airlines in conjunction with
other equipment to not only improve the margins of safety, but also
lower costs by saving fuel and increase schedule reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines, which flies over some of the roughest terrain
in the world, uses enhanced ground proximity tied into its flight
management computer and a display system that allows the pilot to
keep his or her head up and view the system at the same time. The
$200,000 glass screen, which displays flight instruments, is
focused at infinity so the pilot can look out the windscreen
through the display, and still see readouts on speed, altitude and
other functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are looking in and out, up and down, while trying to
land at 150 nautical miles (per hour), it is a huge work-load
task,'' said Alaska Airlines pilot Mike Adams.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-PILOTS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     07-25 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PILOTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 SEATTLE: ... Mike Adams.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The display makes landings easier as well, because it has
vertical and horizontal guidance for runways.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system is particularly valuable for approaching Alaskan
airports, such as Juneau International, where planes must fly along
a channel between mountains, and then make a turn onto the runway
heading. The ground warning system and flight-management computers
help make sure the plane stays on its narrowly defined course by
monitoring specific checkpoints _ called waypoints _ that the plane
must pass at certain speeds and altitudes to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   At many airport in Alaska and elsewhere, the ground-based
navigation aids provide direction only to the runway centerline.
This lateral guidance does not give pilots vertical guidance, which
allows for a steady rate of descent. Because of that, pilots have
to use a so-called step-down approach, much like someone going down
stairs, rather than a steady descent like going down a slide.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation specialists such as Boeing Co.'s Bob Myers, the program
manager for safety technology development, say a constant descent
versus a nonprecision, or step-down approach, increases safety by a
factor or four to eight times.
</P>
<P>
   But Alaska Air's guidance system and the waypoints are so
precise that, even at the most challenging airports, pilots can
descend on a steady slope rather than using the step-down approach.
At Sitka Airport, for example, pilots now descend smoothly rather
than follow the nine steps down that they previously needed.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways is using a similar system on its Airbus aircraft to
eliminate all nonprecision approaches at every runway of every
airport where the airline's Airbus aircraft flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a major corporate commitment to eliminate nonprecision
approaches,'' said US Airways A330 chief pilot Tracy Barnett. ``We
wanted vertical and lateral guidance.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is a continuous debate on how much processed data to
give to flight crews _ because, as Boeing's Myers said, ``One man's
information is another man's clutter'' _ work is progressing on
developing a three-dimensional display of the world outside the
airplane. Such synthetic vision would give pilots a clear
electronic picture of what is outside the airplane, no matter what
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   NASA already has tested successfully a version of the system
using a database around Asheville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Global Position System signals, pilots can know exactly
where they are,'' said Michael Lewis, director of NASA's Aviation
Safety Program. ``Add super-accurate terrain databases and
graphical displays and we can now draw three-dimensional moving
scenes that will show pilots exactly what is outside. The type of
accidents that can happen in poor visibility just don't happen when
pilots can see the terrain hazards outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said both the computing power and the maps are available
now to create fairly reliable three-dimensional pictures. For
instance, the Radar Topography Mission of the Space Shuttle took
three dimensional measurements of 80 percent of the Earth's terrain
and is accurate to about 55 feet. But he said the data needs to be
updated and verified for accuracy before pilots can rely on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting synthetic vision certified for operation is the big
hurdle,'' Lewis said. ``It takes it from being an R&AMP;D trick to . .
. being always available.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, once the engineering is complete, every flight
will look like clear, daytime weather to the pilots, which will
translate into safer air travel for passengers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
