<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL VICTIMS OF TORTURE FIND A REFUGE IN BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes torture victims text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEGAN SCOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ To this day, men in uniforms make Carlos nervous and
fidgety. After all, it was a soldier _ a childhood friend, no less
_ who shot him in the back and left him for dead in his native
Guatemala in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Carlos (not his real name) had been an ordinary
peasant, struggling to survive amid a long civil war. But, when he
began organizing indigenous people in Guatemala _ teaching them
Spanish, the language of government _ he became a target.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Carlos hid from the soldiers, but they found him
when he returned to his town to visit his parents. The bullet
ruptured his spine, and, as he lay bleeding and paralyzed at his
own home, Carlos came within a heartbeat of becoming another of the
200,000 people who died in the 36-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But now Carlos has a job and a home in the Boston area, as well
as the safety of political asylum and doctors who help him cope
with the painful aftershocks of political persecution and violence.
Carlos was one of 90 patients from more than 25 countries who got
help at the Center for Refugee Health and Human Rights at Boston
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are places where people can get assistance for their
difficulties,'' said Michael Grodin, director of Human Rights
Advocacy and Education for the center, one of only a handful of
places in the United States to provide physical, mental, legal and
social services to refugees and survivors of torture. ``We're able
to really assess the needs of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pervasive use of torture as a political weapon from
Kosovo to Cambodia, there is a hidden prohibition against talking
about its victims, said Douglas A. Johnson, executive director of
the Center for Victims of Torture in Minneapolis, one of the oldest
such centers. While there are more than 400,000 survivors living in
the United States, the survivors' pain and suffering remain hidden
and unexplained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torture is such a frightening word,'' Johnson said. ``Not
enough people are taking the time to think about it. It's a topic
that's full of despair and fear.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Convention Against Torture and Other Cruel,
Inhumane and Degrading Treatment or Punishment defines survivors of
torture as those who have suffered from severe physical or mental
pain, intentionally inflicted by a public official or a person
acting in an official capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of torture is to destroy the individual that is being
targeted,'' Johnson said. ``Torture is not really about getting
information. They're trying to prove to the torture victim that
they're worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   According to 1999 Amnesty International figures, torture and ill
treatment were practiced in 125 countries, including Africa, Asia
and Southeast Asia, Latin America and the Middle East. More than
100 governments engage in the practice against leaders who are
active in the defense of human rights, political opposition
leaders, trade unionists, religious figures, human rights advocates
and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torture is a kind of lesson where repressive regimes are
teaching their communities to stay out of politics, to be apathetic
and disengage in public life,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Torturers destroy leaders, rendering them helpless and
dependent, and in turn send a message of fear throughout the
community. More than two-thirds of torture victims have at least
some college education, according to the Center for Victims of
Torture, and a similar proportion hold professional or political
jobs or they are students. The point of torture is to silence
voices, removing people's right to speak and their rights as human
beings.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors endure the trauma of physical, mental and sexual
torture. They are stabbed with needles; hung by their wrists,
ankles and genitals; burned, shocked and flogged with belts and
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Greater pyschological damage is inflicted with sham executions,
sexual torture, disappearance of loved ones, threats against family
members, and imprisonment with sensory deprivation.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional scars extend beyond the individual, affecting
their families, the community and society. But with the combined
efforts of psychiatrists, psychotherapists, physicians, physical
therapists and volunteers, survivors learn how to sleep through the
night without nightmares, engage with people and diminish the pain
and depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to use an interdisciplinary approach to these
patients,'' said Grodin, a professor of health law, sociomedical
science and psychiatry at Boston University. ``All these people
suffer from trauma. The hallmark is to try to get them to work. If
they work, they can support themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors come with their own stories, carrying the physical and
emotional scars from their country of origin. Most have
post-traumatic stress disorder. They also can be at risk for
anxiety disorders, substance abuse, somatic symptoms and psychosis.
Somatic symptoms are mental trauma manifested through physical
signs of symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't always make that connection between what they've
been exposed to and what they're experiencing,'' said Linda
Piwowarczyk, instructor of psychiatry for the International Mental
Health Program. ``Sometimes people don't make a connection between
their symptoms and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Victims of Torture struggles with funding,
receiving no money from the federal government. Instead, it relies
solely on donations from the community, devoting more than 85
percent of all operating revenue to programs that directly benefit
torture survivors. A speakers bureau assists their fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to dedicate time in going out and doing public
education and getting people involved in it,'' Johnson said. ``It's
about trying to get people to understand how important this is.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, torture survivors were making contributions in
their respective communities and they long to do it again. Although
most continue to receive lifelong care at the centers, they go on
to start their own businesses. Some who practiced medicine in their
countries become doctors in the United States. A tiny percentage
return home if it's not too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is full of hope,'' Johnson said. ``That's what excites
people here. That's what gets people out of bed in the morning.
This is a place that's full of hope. Our work is restoring the
dignity of the human spirit. That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos, at the Boston center, was rescued by a friend who took
him to a hospital after he had been shot. In 1990, he escaped
across Guatemala's border with Mexico and went on to Canada _ but
he couldn't stay away from his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the war ended and he returned to Guatemala with the
hope of finding his parents. But despite the peace agreement,
Carlos was nearly hit by a hand grenade and he was detained in a
psychiatric ward of a hospital for 10 days. Once again, this time
perhaps forever, he fled Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Carlos works on an assembly line. He lives in a shelter
and is working to obtain his driver's license. He also is learning
English. Ten years have passed since he last saw his parents. His
mother, who had moved to Mexico, died in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston center helped him get a new wheelchair, obtain
political asylum status and has provided him with ongoing,
continuous support. He is still undergoing treatment for
post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been very helpful to read about post-traumatic stress
disorder and depression, but still I get very jumpy and fidgety
when stressed,'' Carlos said.
</P>
<P>
   This happens particularly when he sees people in military
uniforms or when someone approaches him from behind. ``(The Center)
has been excellent. I have found support. I'm getting the
opportunity to be a person with some opportunities to be a person
again. That has helped a lot with my trauma and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston is also home to the International Survivors Center at the
International Institute of Boston. The center offers mental-health
services to survivors with an emphasis on rehabilitation and
returning the individual to self-sufficiency. The program will
serve about 85 survivors this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people move to the US searching for security,'' said
Kathleen Allden, medical director of the center. ``As Americans,
look at it as how we can welcome newcomers, assist them in
exploration of their new country. That will improve the
self-confidence of those individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
