<HEADLINE>
LONDON'S ART EXPLOSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   London has always been known for its art museums. But the year
2000 has seen a flurry of openings or major improvements. These
three institutions make up our Museums of the Month:
</P>
<P>
   --The Tate Museum of Modern Art has turned darkness into light,
transforming the old and dreary Bankside Power Station on the south
side of the Thames River into its bright and airy new branch, Tate
Modern. The new site features international modern art from 1900 to
the present. And as a bonus, the seventh-floor windows offer one of
the best views in all of London of St. Paul's Cathedral. The
original Millbank site, now called Tate Britain, exhibits older
British art. The Tate is free except for special exhibits;
donations are welcomed. For more information, visit www.
</P>
<P>
   tate.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   --Somerset House, one of Britain's great historic buildings,
opened to the public for the first time this spring. The 1,000-room
building, on the site of a 16th-century royal palace, houses two
major museums: the Gilbert Collection of decorative arts and the
Courtauld Institute Gallery with its noted collection of
Impressionist paintings. In the fall, the Hermitage Rooms, showing
highlights from the State Hermitage Museum in St. Petersburg, will
open. There is no charge to visit the Somerset House itself, but a
combination Gilbert-Courtauld ticket costs about $10.50 for adults;
separate admissions are about $6 each for adults. For more
information, visit www.somerset-house.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   --The National Portrait Gallery, which houses the world's
largest portrait gallery, is heading into the 21st century with
more light, space, and elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations provide for 50 percent more exhibition and public
space; a new central area from which one of London's largest
escalators rises to the second- floor galleries; a new Tudor
Gallery; and a new Balcony Gallery, adding space for portraits from
the 1960s to the '80s. The National Portrait Gallery even has
portraits of the Spice Girls, but don't let that stop you from
visiting. The gallery is free except for special exhibits;
donations are welcomed. For more information, check out
www.npg.org.uk.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on all of London, call 800-462-2748 or
visit www.londontown.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: In which country is the Kalahari Desert?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quotable: ``Sometimes a man hits upon a place to which he
mysteriously feels that he belongs. Here is the home he sought, and
he will settle amid scenes that he has never seen before, among men
he has never known, as though they were familiar to him from his
birth. Here at last he finds rest.'' _ from ``The Moon and
Sixpence'' by Somerset Maugham. (We thank Mary Fothergill of
Waquoit for suggesting and locating this quote.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: There is a restaurant/lounge in Bar Harbor, Maine,
called Carmen Verandah.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today's loopy law: It's illegal in Massachusetts to go to bed
without first having a full bath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An idea that spread: The Superior Hotel in Iron Mountain, Mont.,
was the first to have what virtually all US hotel rooms now have _
a Gideon Bible. The year was 1908.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you guess it? South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Our discussion of one-word state mottoes brought this comment
from Dan Kraft of Boston: ``I'm sure many of your readers guessed
that either New York or New Jersey would have four-letter words as
mottoes!'' (He's joking, folks. He notes that the two states that
actually have four-letter mottoes are Rhode Island (Hope) and
Washington (Al-ki, meaning ``by and by'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In response to our description of the $5,600-a-night luxury
suite at the Churchill Inter-Continental in London, Thom McCabe of
Westborough writes about his room at the Bali Inter-Continental:
``I was brought into . . . a suite which I later measured at 66
feet long and 44 feet wide including a 10 x 66 foot balcony
overlooking the ocean and Bali's spectacular sunsets.'' The cost of
this magnificent suite: $225 US per night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To the fan of Gillette Castle State Park in East Haddam, Conn.:
The historic castle will remain closed this year because of
continuing repair work. The park grounds and trails will remain
open to the public free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Schuster of Foxborough, Mass., a faithful contributor,
notes that not only does Orlando, Fla., have the world's largest
McDonald's, as we mentioned, but also the world's largest Hard Rock
Cafe, at Universal Orlando's CityWalk.
</P>
