<HEADLINE>
MUSIC'S ALL YOU NEED TO KNOW OF JILL SCOTT'S ID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who is Jill Scott?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question many asked after listening to her soaring,
unbridled vocals on the 1999 album ``The Roots Come Alive.'' It was
Black Thought of the Roots who first introduced listeners to Scott.
Before launching into this hip-hop group's hit, ``You Got Me,''
which featured Erykah Badu, Black Thought set the record straight
about the true creative mind behind that song's hooky chorus:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you were worried about where
</P>
<P>
   I've been or who I saw
</P>
<P>
   Or what club I went to with my homies
</P>
<P>
   Baby don't worry, you know that you got me
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On the song (originally on the CD, `Things Fall Apart'),
Erykah Badu is singing the chorus, this real smoothed-out melodic
(expletive), but guess what _ tonight I'm gonna introduce you to
the young lady from Philadelphia who wrote that piece,'' Black
Thought explains. ``She's down with the Roots crew, and she goes by
the name of Miss Jill Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   As ``Jilly from Philly,'' as Black Thought affectionately calls
Scott, began to sing, there was certainly more than a hint of
Baduizm. The inflections, the phrasing seemed pure Erykah, yet a
closer listen revealed a more soothing voice, but one that pierced
and stung like an arrow. With ?uestlove on drums and Scratch on the
turntables prodding along her jazzy improvisations, Scott tore the
roof off the joint, and made the song her own.
</P>
<P>
   On her debut CD, ``Who is Jill Scott? Words and Sounds Vol. 1,''
Scott includes a minutelong snippet of her performance from that
concert, and the rest of this album proves her moment on stage with
the Roots was no fluke. When she says, ``Y'all ready to settle down
and get with this,'' on the CD's first cut, ``Jilltro,'' it's an
invitation and a challenge. A singer-songwriter, Scott takes her
place alongside such neo-soul saviors as Macy Gray, Lucy Pearl, and
D'Angelo as the latest artist to shun the de rigueur, assembly-line
limitations of contemporary R&AMP;B.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is Jill Scott?'' is a 72-minute contemplation of love lost
and found. Love is a symphony, love is a sorrow song. Men love and
treat her right, or behave badly. Sometimes she begs them to stay,
others she needs to kick to the curb. She warns other women eyeing
her man to ``back down before you get smacked down,'' and finally
learns that loving yourself is perhaps the greatest feat of all.
</P>
<P>
   On every song, from the painful wanting of ``Do You Remember,''
to the funky collard greens and black-eyed peas chorus of ``It's
Love,'' to the sweeping strings of ``The Way,'' Scott creates a
full-scale montage of emotions. Like love, the CD is sexy, sad, and
beyond simplistic descriptions. Whether she's evoking a quiet-storm
mood, or an insinuating head-bopping groove, this is a funky,
fearless album by a true talent who, thankfully, is not the
creation of some knob-twiddling producer trying to cajole soul from
yet another pretty stone.
</P>
<P>
   It probably says a great deal about Scott that, on her album's
acknowledgements, she cites as ``two of my true inspirations, _
``Mr. Christopher Wallace'' _ that's Biggie Smalls, y'all _ and
``Miss Sarah Vaughn.'' There's certainly a hip-hop sensibility in
such cuts as the erotic spoken-word pieces, ``Exclusively,'' and
``Love Rain.'' But there's also all this jazz in songs like ``A
Long Walk'' and ``He Loves Me'' in the way she weaves words in and
out of the music, and making her voice another instrument. She has
a remarkable sense musically of what came before, and a clear
vision of where she wants to take her own mesmerizing rhythms and
inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any justice, Jill Scott's will be the voice pumping
out of speakers this summer and beyond. In an industry running on
artificiality these days, Scott is bringing something real. After
this CD, one of the best of the year, the question should no longer
be ``Who is Jill Scott?'' but what took her so long to get here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
