<HEADLINE>
THRILLS, CHILLS WHILE FLYING HIGH ON A PARASAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STAN GROSSFELD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE FEAR, N.C. _ Michael Jordan played high school basketball
in this neck of the woods and I want to be like Mike. I want some
hang time, but the problem is I can't jump. Not with a basketball
because I naturally embrace gravity, and not from an airplane
because with my luck the worker who folds my parachute has either a
massive hangover, just received a pink slip, has ties to Khadafy,
or all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Originally I came here merely seeking warm waters. I thought it
would be worth it to fly to Wilmington, N.C., halfway between New
York and Miami, to soak in the 80-degree surf at Wrightsville Beach
and enjoy what has been chosen as one of the top 10 beaches in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's hurricanes, the beach here is pretty
terrific, the waves and sandy bottom are perfect for body surfing,
and the natives are friendly. In fact the only sign that this is
prime hurricane territory is the street signs near the beach
warning about how many feet underwater you will be in the event of
a Category Five hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting under an umbrella out on a pier at the Oceanic
restaurant, feasting on crab soaked in curry and sipping ice cold
beer at reasonable prices is the epitome of the good life. Pelicans
cruise by in formation and fishing boats follow the swarming birds
offshore.
</P>
<P>
   I'm content until I see a multicolored parasail being towed just
offshore. Wouldn't it be fun to float over the ocean with a
pelican's-eye view of Cape Fear?
</P>
<P>
   So, after entertaining the locals by hopscotching across the
sun-baked blacktop in bare feet, I've driven to the Wrightsville
Parasailing Co. on Airlie Marina (phone 910-232-1235) and signed
without reading a small-type agreement that releases the company
from liability should I break free of my safety harness and wind up
as shark food in the Bermuda Triangle.
</P>
<P>
   Six of us have paid $45 apiece and boarded a special parasail
boat with a carpeted takeoff and landing platform in the aft. Our
captain, the jovial Jay Dalton, informs us that we will be gone for
two hours and will each fly for about 15 minutes. He says that he
has flown people from ages 3-82 in the last three years and has
never had an accident.
</P>
<P>
   But when we get out to sea his smile fades. He warns us that
something terrible could happen. That if we don't place the harness
just above our knees and allow centrifugal force to move it higher,
then we will get a ``parasail wedgie'' and have to endure our ride
sounding like Frankie Valli of the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Part of our group consists of two wide-eyed young women from
Easton, Pa., celebrating their high school graduation, and a couple
of their male friends from South Carolina. Because these hardbodies
weigh less than 300 pounds per couple, they can fly in groups of
two. Because I've had a big breakfast this morning, and every
morning for the last 40-odd years, my wife and I can't fly
together.
</P>
<P>
   One of the South Carolina guys eyes me as if I have more
frequent flier miles than Madeleine Albright. ``Ever do this
before?'' he asks. I tell him the truth: ``Once before, years ago
off the beach in Mexico. But tequilla was involved and I remember
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, a semiconductor process engineer who works in Raleigh
during the week, tells us that parasailing off the beach or from
stationary platforms is unsafe. He will launch us from his boat
``Live Like Libby'' with a winch and tow line that will keep the
parasail low enough so that it doesn't register as a hailstorm on
the Weather Channel radar.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton promises me that if I take my $2,000 camera with me on my
flight, he can keep it dry. Twelve seconds later a wave crashes
over the bow. Everybody gets wet.
</P>
<P>
   When we finally get off the coast of Cape Fear, Dalton pulls out
an anemometer and takes a wind reading: 11.7 m.p.h. Dalton says he
will not allow parasailing if the wind hits 15 m.p.h. ``Too
dangerous,'' he says. ``I cancel 40 percent of my trips because of
high winds or rough seas. We don't take chances.'' Accidents happen
because parasailing firms are greedy or don't have the proper
equipment or let out too much tow line and lose control, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his horror stories make you want to stay at home. A
young woman drowned while parasailing in the Bahamas recently, and
famous O.J. Simpson lawyer Johnnie Cochran is suing for $5 million
in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although we are required to wear a life vest, Dalton gives no
briefing on emergency water landings. We might drown but at least
nobody on this boat will drown with a wedgie.
</P>
<P>
   When I get home, I find some sobering facts. Over the past 10
years there have been 230 parasailing accidents, resulting in 11
deaths, according to the Parasail Safety Council.
</P>
<P>
   But 500 yards off the southeastern coast of North Carolina, on a
sun-drenched afternoon with a nice breeze, nobody's thinking of
becoming a statistic. The first couple goes up amid whoops of joy.
Rachael Bombardier holds the straps so hard her hands hurt. By
controlling the tow line and the speed of the boat, Dalton shoots
them up to 200 feet then lets them slowly descend for a brief dip
in the water. But when they are about two feet over the ocean, he
tells us to all point and scream, ``Shark!''. Startled, Bombardier
jolts her feet skyward. ``If you lift your feet up the shark's
gonna bite your butt,'' yells Dalton before he pops them back up in
the air like a helium balloon let loose.
</P>
<P>
   My flight is a blast. At 150 feet up and 250 feet out from the
boat, I'm floating over Cape Fear with no fear, until I use both
hands to take pictures and realize there's no net below me. I don't
want to wind up like the German U-352 submarine sunk off the coast
here during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The view alone is worth the money. I can see Wrightsville Beach,
clean and spacious with the surf rolling in hypnotically. I can see
Figure of Eight island, a gated community where a host of famous
people including Kim Bassinger, Alec Guinness, and Vice President
Al Gore vacation.
</P>
<P>
   I can see Wilmington, a hip eclectic city on the Cape Fear
River, which has rightfully turned up in the book ``The 100 Best
Small Art Towns in America.'' This month, some streets are blocked
off because Jody Foster is shooting a new film. Wilmington
generates more film revenue than any city other than LA and New
York. There are also just enough funky boutiques, restaurants,
antique shops, paddle boats, coffee houses, and clip-clopping
carriage rides to make this a charming and romantic destination.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Fear Museum in Wilmington has a Michael Jordan exhibit
that has artifacts from the days before he became His Airness. They
include the $119.76 pay stub dated July 20, 1980, from his
after-school job working at Whitey's El-Berta restaurant in
Wilmington, a certificate for perfect attendance from the New
Hanover County schools, and some of his old books including the
classic, ``White Fang'' by Jack London and the prophetic
``Basketball for Young Champions.'' Jordan has also financed a
Michael Jordan Discovery Center at the museum, a hands-on
children's exhibit on primary ecosystems in the North Carolina
coastal environment.
</P>
<P>
   And from the air, the environment looks pretty darn good. I hear
no engines. It's just the whoosh of the parasail above, a couple of
seagulls riding shotgun off in the distance, and a little white
boat bobbing slowly in the warm waters off Cape Fear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
