<P>
   RAND-SCHOOLS _ WASHINGTON _ Three popular education reforms seem
to have worked in some states between 1990 and 1996, according to a
massive RAND Corp. report to be released here Tuesday. Comparing
NAEP achievement scores by students from similar families from 44
states, the researchers found that fast-improving states like North
Carolina and Texas had smaller classes in the early grades, more
kids in public pre-kindergarten programs and a higher number of
teachers who said they had adequate resources than was true in
states like Georgia, where scores stagnated, or California, where
scores plunged in those years. Some other plausible explanations _
such as higher scores by students whose teachers had masters
degrees or higher salaries _ didn't pan out. But, years after the
fact, it now appears that the post-1996 decisions by policy-makers
to stress pre-k classes in Georgia and to lower class size in
grades 1 to 3 in California were smart moves. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 16.
</P>
<P>
   UGA-ADMISSIONS _ Followup story on a federal ruling that the
University of Georgia's raced-based admissions policy is
unconstitutional. (Rankin/McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE-CRASH _ PARIS _ An Air France Concorde jet, Flight
4590, crashed near a hotel outside of Paris Tuesday killing all 109
people _ passengers and crew _ on board. There are reportedly four
people dead on the ground, as well. It was a charter flight that
took off from Charles de Gaulle Airport with German tourists on
board en route to Ecuador via New York City. The crash comes just
days after British Airways grounded a Concorde jet for showing
cracks in its wings. But there is no evidence as to whether this
was at all involved in the crash. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Expected to move on the NYT Wire.
</P>
<P>
   UN-FUND _Ted Turner's UN Foundation announced it will provide
more than $42 million to support UN social and environmental
projects worldwide. The foundation, which has awarded more than
$300 million in grants since 1997, will invest more than $21
million to improve the social situation of adolescent girls in
countries ranging from Malawi to El Salvador and Mongolia to
Mauritania. In addition, the foundation will provide almost $13
million to clean arsenic-contaminated well water in Bangladesh and
protect coral reefs around the world. Other grants will be used for
providing health information on the Internet, studying the economic
agendas of factions in civil wars and evaluating an anti-personnel
landmine convention. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SUMMIT _ THURMONT, Md. _ Spot coverage of final status
peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians at Camp David.
There is no official deadline for the talks, which seek to
reconcile some 52 years of enmity and agreement on issues ranging
from a Palestinian state to sovereignty over Jerusalem. Developing.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
