<P>
   TOO-MUCH _ Call it the revolt of the Soccer Mom. With the
proliferation of kid activities, and the sprawl that means they are
further apart, many families find they spend more time on the road
or with Little League coaches than with each other. With all the
shuttling, the average American mother now makes 5.5 car trips per
day, up from 3.5 in 1983, and compared with 4.5 trips for the
national average. One town in Minnesota is rebelling. We check with
Atlanta families, and with experts, some of whom are critical of
the current obsession with extracurriculars. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
