<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANA AT ITS FINEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pure Americana. That's the best way to describe Shelburne Museum
in Shelburne, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are you've never been there. Only about 100,000 people
venture onto the 45 acres that make up this museum. But there's
never been a better time to visit than this summer, when a number
of new exhibitions have opened.
</P>
<P>
   First, a look at what's there. Shelburne has one of the
country's most extensive collections of Americana. Its folk art
collections include decoys and miniature carvings, weather vanes,
trade figures and signs, carousel figures, quilts, and hooked and
sewn rugs. Its decorative art collections include glass, ceramic,
pewter, metalwork, scrimshaw, and 18th- and 19th-century
paint-decorated furniture. Its fine-art galleries include important
works by American painters and by French Impressionists Corot,
Degas, Manet, and Monet (the museum's founder, Electra Havemeyer
Webb, was the daughter of H.O. and Louisine Havemeyer, who led
American interest in Impressionism).
</P>
<P>
   Shelburne's 37 historic exhibition buildings hold 150,000
objects. On the grounds you'll find historic houses, a lighthouse,
a two-lane covered bridge, a steam locomotive, a vintage carousel,
a general store, and the restored, 220-foot steamboat Ticonderoga,
a national historic landmark. That alone is worth the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibitions on view this summer include: ``The Fabulous '50s:
Welcome Home to Post-War Vermont,'' with a ``historic house'' that
shows life as it was in June 1950; ``The Saturday Evening Post and
America's Great Illustrators: Norman Rockwell and Others,'' with
original paintings and reproduced covers from the heyday of the
Saturday Evening Post; ``Landscape and Light: Paintings by Martin
Johnson Heade,'' a showcase of the museum's extensive collection of
Heade paintings; ``Gather 'Round: Tales of New England's Workaday
World,'' a multimedia experience of work in New England during the
last 100 years; ``Something Old, Something New: American Decorative
Art and Furnishings, 1700-1820,'' highlighting furnishings from the
museum's collections; ``Settlers' Home,'' telling the story of a
Vermont family in 1795; and ``From George Washington to P.T.
Barnum: Prints from the Shelburne Museum,'' showcasing the museum's
historical, circus, sporting, and maritime prints.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming at Shelburne is a Sotheby's Heirloom Appraisal Day on
Sept. 23-24 and the perennial favorite ``Celebrations of the
Season,'' a re-creation of an old-time New England Christmas, Dec.
1-2.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 802-985-3346 or visit
www.shelburnemuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beer, wine history
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This one's for me. ``Drink and Be Merry: Wine and Beer in
Ancient Times'' opens next Sunday at the Jewish Museum in New York
City. The exhibit, through Nov. 5, presents 5,000 years of drinking
culture in the eastern Mediterranean and Near East through an
exhibition of more than 180 objects. Organized by the Israel Museum
in Jerusalem, the exhibition explores two of the oldest known
beverages, valued throughout time for their abilities to lift
spirits, inspire religious fervor, deaden pain, and cure illness.
Wine and beer are among the oldest alcoholic beverages known,
originating in at least the sixth through fourth millennia BC in
the lands of the ancient Near East. While beer was the popular
drink at first, with wine being costly and rare, over time wine
became the most common drink. The Jewish sages even said, ``One in
whose home wine does not flow like water is not blessed.'' The
museum's shop is offering a book on the topic. For more
information, call 212-423-3200 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   thejewishmuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vermont feast
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top chefs and wine experts are heading to Vermont
Aug. 11-13 for an epicurean adventure at the KitchenAid Vermont
Wine &AMP; Food Festival. ``Here is an opportunity to learn more about
entertaining with wine and food, about how the two complement each
other,'' said Meri Spicer, festival director. ``Cooking with flair
does not have to be complicated.'' The festival features book
signings, workshops, tastings, and seminars, and participants
select from a full menu of cooking classes. The core festival pass
is $249, and a la carte entry into the grand tasting tent is
available on Saturday and Sunday. A highlight is the Celebration of
the Chefs dinner, which is $125 a person. For more information on
the festival at Stratton Mountain, call 800-STRATTON or visit
www.vermontwineandfood.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Rodin on view
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is The Year of the Arts in North Carolina, and the marquee
event is the continuing Festival Rodin through Aug. 13. Some 130
works by Auguste Rodin are on view at the North Carolina Museum of
Art in Raleigh, including such sculptures as ``The Thinker'' and
``The Kiss.'' In addition, ``The Hand of God'' is making both its
US debut and its first public appearance since 1905. For more
information on North Carolina, call 800-849-8499 or visit
www.raleighcvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jellyfish on view
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They have no eyes, no brain, no heart, and they can wield a
painful sting. And, if you head to the ocean, chances are you've
come across them _ jellyfish. The Aquarium of the Pacific in Long
Beach, Calif., has just opened a gallery dedicated to the more than
one dozen sea jellies, as they are properly known. These mysterious
creatures have survived for more than 650 years and can range in
size from smaller than a pencil eraser to larger than a basketball
court, and consist of 95 percent water. The exhibit explores all
the wonders of these creatures, which are found on both coasts, and
tells which jellyfish to look out for. Included is a Sting-O-Meter
where you can safely find out what different sea jelly stings might
feel like. For information, call 562-590-3100.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Art in Puerto Rico
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico, with a 500-year history of artistic life, has just
opened the Museo de Arte de Puerto Rico in San Juan. The opening
exhibition, ``Treasures of Puerto Rican Painting,'' showcases the
rich talent of Puerto Rican artists and will be on view through
January. More than 250 pieces of art are being shown, including
works by the island's most recognized artists, Campche and Rafael
Tufino. There is also a five-acre sculpture garden. For information
on Puerto Rico, call 800-866-7827 or visit www.prtourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Scenic highways
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thirty roads in 20 states have been designated All-American
Roads or National Scenic Byways for 2000. US Transportation
Secretary Mortimer Downey said the roads provide visitors with a
unique driving experience and are considered destinations unto
themselves. Being designated All-American Roads helps preserve
these roads that have become American icons, Downey said. In New
England, the Acadia Byway in Maine was named an All-American Road,
and named National Scenic Byways were Connecticut State Route 169
and the Merritt Parkway; Old Canada Road, Rangely Lakes, and
Schoodic scenic byways in Maine; and the Kancamagus Highway in New
Hampshire. For information, visit www.byways.org or call
800-4-BYWAYS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Potholes in the roads
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you're on the road this summer, always read the fine print
and be a little skeptical when visiting historic sites, says James
W. Loewen, adjunct professor of sociology at The Catholic
University of America in Washington and author of ``Lies Across
America: What Our Historic Sites Get Wrong.'' Be wary, he says of
words such as ``traditional'' or ``according to.'' For example, he
notes that Lincoln's Birthplace Cabin in Hodgenville, Ky., was
actually built 30 years after Lincoln's death. ``The National Park
Service does not go out of its way to tell you the cabin is not
where Lincoln was born. In fact, signs tell tourists not to use
flash photography and risk damaging the logs,'' said Loewen. The
cold and starving image of George Washington in Valley Forge is
also false, he says. In fact it was a mild winter, and ``the food
was monotonous but adequate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Plastic anniversary
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Did you realize that the term ``charge it'' is just 50 years
old? In 1950, a world without cash was inconceivable, but that's
when ``plastic'' was born. In 1949 Frank McNamara dined at a New
York restaurant only to find he had left behind his wallet. That
incident, which he managed to finesse, led to his developing the
Diners Club Card. When he returned to the restaurant in February
1950, he paid the bill with a small cardboard card _ a Diners Club
Card _ and signed for the purchase. In the credit card industry,
that event is known as the First Supper. The credit card concept
soon caught fire, including a movie, ``The Man from the Diners
Club,'' and by 1952 became the first international charge card.
This year, Diners Club earned its third successive Freddie Award
for Best Affinity Charge Card Program. Its Club Rewards offers
points that never expire and other services. For information, call
800-234-6377 or visit www.dinersclubus.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
