   LYRICS-EDIT (Undated) _ An array of song-lyric review and
editing procedures have become a routine part of the record
business. Artists with explicit material are routinely asked to
re-sing lyrics, edit out particular words and even excise entire
songs from albums. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   CHOREOGRAPHERS-LEGACY (Undated) _ A growing sophistication about
preserving the legacy of dance has largely institutionalized the
handing-down of choreography, which was first passed down from
dancer to dancer, then by written notation and film and video. The
idea of owning a dance as property is relatively new. Changes in
copyright law are in part responsible for this, as well as
increasing general interest in copyright and ownership in a
new-media age that has effectively widened the possibilities of
illegal appropriation of artistic property. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-ISLAND-WINE (Peconic, N.Y.) _ The Long Island wine business
is booming; it's almost giddy from its own success. Handsome new
wineries are opening, old ones are changing hands for astonishing
prices, new vineyards are springing up, and suddenly, there isn't
enough wine to go around. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
