<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2405 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-HDTV-PUZZLE-BOS &LR;      07-25 1500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV-PUZZLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HDTV COSTS MAKE ITS FUTURE LOOK FUZZY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kevin Miller remembers the first time he saw
high-definition television. It was at the Consumer Electronics Show
in Las Vegas. Zenith was demonstrating an HDTV broadcast of a Ray
Charles concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was stunning,'' Miller said. ``You could see the beads of
sweat on his forehead as clearly as anything you've seen in real
life. When the camera zoomed in on the microphone, you could see
all the metal mesh. You saw the fingerprint smudges on the piano.
These kinds of details just jumped off the screen and freaked you
out. I couldn't wait to see more.''
</P>
<P>
   That was in January 1996. HDTV was heralded as the television of
the future. Four years later, the future hasn't come much closer.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is now audio-video editor of etown.com, a
consumer-electronics Webzine. He spends much of his time watching,
reviewing, tweaking, and installing the most high-tech televisions
on the market. But he's still waiting for HDTV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the technology,'' he says. ``The technology is here,
HDTV sets are here. It's the chicken-egg problem _ that's what's
holding things up.''
</P>
<P>
   Chickens and eggs are the common metaphor that people in the
industry use to describe the predicament.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens are the network chiefs, who don't want to spend
millions of dollars on HDTV cameras, tape machines, and
transmission hardware when only a teeny segment of viewers own HDTV
sets and decoders.
</P>
<P>
   The eggs are the consumers, who don't want to spend thousands of
dollars on HDTV sets and decoders when the networks are
broadcasting only a handful of HDTV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle are the TV manufacturers, who can lower
prices on these sets only so far as long as consumer demand remains
so meager.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, they have cut prices by 20 to 50 percent.
However, that still leaves these sets at $2,000 minimum, with most
of them well more than double that, still too expensive for a
mass-market commodity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done our part, so when is there going to be something
worth watching?'' asks Dave Arland, spokesman for Thomson Consumer
Electronics, which owns RCA. ``People aren't going to make the
switch if there's not enough to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, ABC broadcast ``Monday Night Football'' in
high-definition. There were 32 local ABC stations with the hardware
to carry the beam. But, one network executive complained, ``We have
no idea how many people were watching. And there's no evidence that
the broadcast increased sales of HDTV sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic paid for the HD equipment and the HD transmission, at
a reported cost of $2.2 million for the season. But the deal will
not be renewed next season.
</P>
<P>
   Some public and cable networks are dipping into HDTV on their
own dime. PBS is experimenting, with WGBH in Boston leading the way
in producing programs in high-definition. The Discovery Channel
will start doing so next year. DirecTV satellites currently carry
one Showtime and two HBO channels that beam movies in HDTV format.
</P>
<P>
   The major networks are hesitating, unless the manufacturers pick
up the tab. Samsung has funded HD broadcasts of movies for CBS,
Thomson covered HD transmissions of the NCAA basketball tournament,
Sony supplies HD equipment for golf tournaments and for NBC's
``Tonight Show,'' the only program broadcast nightly in
high-definition.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi paid for HD broadcasts of CBS's entire prime-time
lineup this past season, but, like Panasonic and ``Monday Night
Football,'' the company is not renewing the deal, though it will
pay for some sports and specials. CBS is looking around for other
sponsors. Glen Dickson of Broadcasting &AMP; Cable Magazine says the
network will suspend the experiment if none are found.
</P>
<P>
   Many manufacturers are growing impatient. ``The gravy train is
over,'' Arland said. ``We're not Proctor &AMP; Gamble. It's time the TV
broadcasters, who have been given their free airwaves, make use of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony is, new digital TV sets _ the only kind that can pick
up HDTV signals _ are selling better than expected. According to
the Consumer Electronics Association over 200,000 of these TVs have
been sold since coming on the market in August 1998. Sales so far
this year are 4 1/2 times larger than this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this market is but a speck on the larger horizon. There
are 250 million old-fashioned analog TV sets in US households _
meaning digital TVs constitute less than one-tenth of 1 percent of
what's out there.
</P>
<P>
   And this speck has little to do with HDTV. Gary Merson, author
of the Web newsletter hdtvinsider.com, said, ``HDTV programs are
not what's driving the digital TV market. It's DVD home-theater,''
which ``looks great on digital televisions.''
</P>
<P>
   To pick up HDTV broadcasts, even digital TVs must be hooked up
to special HD decoder boxes, the cheapest of which cost $650.
According to industry figures, just 33,000 of these boxes have been
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Callahan, marketing director for Princeton Graphics, which
makes computer and HDTV monitors, glumly asked, ``If you were Mike
Eisner, would you want to spend a lot of money to please 30,000
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Again: the chicken-and-egg problem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, HDTV does have appeal, for three reasons. First, it is
broadcast in widescreen, like a movie at a theater. By comparison,
normal TV images seem square and cramped.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it is broadcast digitally _ a series of coded zeros and
ones _ which means the signal comes in perfectly, with no
ghost-images.
</P>
<P>
   Third and most impressive, it is ``high-definition.'' A normal
TV image is made up of 480 lines. HDTV is made up of either 1,080
lines or 720 lines that are scanned twice as quickly. This accounts
for the vast improvement in detail, the you-are-there presence, and
for how smoothly people and objects move across the screen. Regular
TV and even DVDs seem murky and choppy by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you show people HDTV, they want it,'' said Kevin Miller.
``That's a fact. I've seen that response many times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission is pushing the networks to
pick up speed. FCC regulations require all broadcasters to shift
entirely to digital by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   First, while high-definition is digital, digital does not
necessarily mean high-definition.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Congress has added a proviso that this change-over will
take place only if 85 percent of US households have digital TVs.
Few believe this will be the case. For instance, commonplace as
cable TV seems today, it has penetrated just 67 percent of homes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Consumer Electronics Association predicts that if
broadcasters go full-speed ahead, digital TVs will reach just 50
percent of homes by 2006. If delays continue, the estimate drops to
between 15 percent and 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, the networks know they can move at whatever
pace their cautious budgets allow.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Smith, head of the Boston-based Professional Audio/Video
Retailers Association, recently attended a summit of consumer
electronics CEOs. ``Everybody was saying that all the lobbying to
get broadcasters to move on HDTV just keeps hitting a brick wall,''
Smith recalls. ``It's very expensive for the broadcasters. It's
just not happening. It may not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Pete Putman, a video consultant and HDTV advocate,
said, ``We're still in a stage where things have just barely
begun.''
</P>
<P>
   The first nationwide HDTV broadcast took place in October 1998.
Since then, things have moved ahead far more swiftly than color TV
at its early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Color TV made its national debut in 1954, with a closed-circuit
telecast of the Rose Bowl Parade. Five years later, there were just
three shows televised regularly in color, all on NBC: ``Perry
Como,'' ``Bonanza,'' and ``Walt Disney's Wonderful World of
Color.'' Not till 1965 did all three networks start dipping their
toes into color.
</P>
<P>
   According to TV historian Ed Reitan, 1965 marked the first year
that more than 1 million color TV sets were manufactured, and the
typical set cost $1,000, a staggering sum at a time when the
average annual income was $7,200.
</P>
<P>
   It is striking that, in today's dollars, this price tag
translates to $5,600, the same as many of today's HDTV sets.
</P>
<P>
   There are two big differences between now and then, though.
``Back then, TV was about the only form of home entertainment,''
Putman says. ``Now people get it from lots of things. HDTV is going
to have to get a lot cheaper before a lot of people buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, back then, NBC, the network pushing color TV the
hardest, was owned by RCA, the company producing the most color TV
sets. There was a collusion for color between the biggest network
and the biggest manufacturer. Now, with HDTV, there is only
fighting, which everyone agrees might be the biggest stumbling
block on the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1409EDT &QL; 
