<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2407 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-TWIST-BOS &LR;      07-25 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TWIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O. HENRY FACTS STRAIGHT UP, WITH A `TWIST' OF FICTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A TWIST AT THE END 
A Novel of O. Henry 
By Steven Saylor 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 462 pp., $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Saylor has written seven books in the popular Roma Sub
Rosa mystery series, which the Texas-born novelist never intended
to go forth and multiply as they have. In a Boston interview a few
years ago, Saylor recounted how the publisher of ``Roman Blood''
had called to ask for a sequel. ``But I'm a literary novelist,''
Saylor exclaimed, hanging up _ before calling back to take the
publisher up on the offer.
</P>
<P>
   It is a virtue of Saylor's mysteries set in ancient Rome that
his writing does have literary distinction; he has not only
researched the time of Cicero but has imagined himself there. Now
he has taken a temporary sabbatical from dark doings in marble
alleys to write a determinedly literary novel about the writer O.
Henry _ more specifically, about an unsolved series of murders in
Austin, Texas, in the late 1880s, when the young William Sydney
Porter lived there, years before he adopted a pen name and became
just about the most famous storyteller in America. (Even today it
is difficult to escape ``The Gift of the Magi'' at Christmas, and
any unexpected twist at the close of a story is called an ``O.
Henry ending,'' usually disparagingly.)
</P>
<P>
   Will is only in his mid-20s during most of the novel, an
amiable, directionless young man with a handsome ginger mustache
and a pleasant bass voice he uses to serenade pretty young ladies
and sing in ``The Mikado.'' In a series of meaningless jobs and in
a habit of noticing people and things, he is accumulating
experiences that will serve him well later on, though he doesn't
know it yet; he has vague ambitions to become a writer without
realizing that he is one.
</P>
<P>
   Saylor's strategy is to bring what is known about O. Henry in
this period into alignment with what is known about personalities
and events in Austin at the same time. Will meets the
independent-minded German-born sculptor Elisabet Ney, for example;
Ney has a very individual way of speaking English in German syntax,
as her letters indicate she actually did. Will attends sessions of
the legislature during which a bill requiring the state government
to hire female clerks is being debated, and learns of the brutal
police beating of an innocent black man, an incident documented by
history.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, Saylor brings Will into the middle of a
grisly series of murders. The cases were never solved, but Saylor
provides a solution that is congruent with all the facts. The first
victims were African-American servants, and Will dubs the
perpetrators the ``servant girl annihilators.'' The last two
killings are of white women; press and the city go crazy. Some
suspects are found and framed by a particularly dense and racist
police force; there are a couple of trials, and the second of them
is full of steamy revelations when two of the town's madams are
forced to take the stand. The madams did exist, and they stand
alongside Saylor's fictional characters, inventions, and
semi-inventions _ a couple of con men, for example, who recall the
Duke and the Dauphin in ``Huckleberry Finn.'' There is also a
framing story set forward in 1906 _ when O. Henry is famous, in New
York, and haunted by his past _ not to mention some elaborate
strands of symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   The solution to the crimes, like an O. Henry ending, is more
ingenious than satisfying, and the novel itself stubbornly refuses
to come to life the way Saylor's Roman novels invariably do. The
characters tend to fall into stereotypes long familiar from Western
movies, and as the author downloads years of note-taking, one
occasionally feels he knows too much and imagines too little.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a quality in the book, and in the writing, that
does carry a reader through: It's Saylor's obsessive infatuation
with the place and time. ``A Twist at the End'' is not really a
novel of O. Henry; it is a novel of Austin by a writer who arrived
there as a student at the University of Texas and who still spends
part of every year there. Saylor loves the geography of the city,
its streets, houses, and buildings, and the diverse people who live
in them. He delights in evoking period detail of the interiors,
furnishings, carpets, and pictures, as well as placing the reader
in the timeless natural landscape of hills and the winding Colorado
River. The book isn't exactly a celebration of Austin, because the
city's gaudy past of fancy women, corrupt and conniving
politicians, hypocrisy, sexism, and racism is not much to celebrate
_ though there was also honor and decency and vision. Trying to
understand it all is a perfectly good way of trying to understand
ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1410EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
