<HEADLINE>
NEW CHAMPION OF ITALY'S CAUSE IS AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Paul Cayard sailed Italy to a Louis Vuitton Cup victory in
1992 _ symbolic of the top challenger for the America's Cup _ there
was a tinge of disappointment among Italians that it took an
American rock star to lead them to glory.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Louis Vuitton Cup again last February in Auckland
was sweeter, though San Diegan Doug Peterson helped pen the design
lines for Prada and Brazilian tactician Torben Grael called many of
the race moves. Still, syndicate chief Patrizio Bertelli was so
energized he left New Zealand tossing high-fashion Prada sunglasses
to everyone in sight and was already planning his 2003 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be another Italian stallion ready to make a move _
42-year-old Napolitan sailor Vincenzo Onorato, who has been racing
in Newport this month and was just crowned IMS World Champion in
the Cruiser/Racer division. Onorato took the honors at the wheel of
his new Farr 43 called Mascalzone Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The American boat Vim won the Racing division as a pair of
America's Cuppers _ Terry Hutchinson on Vim and Ken Read at the
helm of Idler, the runner-up _ went to war all week in the five-day
Rolex IMS Offshore World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Owner of the shipping firm Moby Lines in the Mediterranean,
Onorato raised some eyebrows around Newport when he said in an
interview that entering the America's Cup is more than merely a
dream, but that he intends ``to organize an all-Italian America's
Cup team'' that might draw on the pool of free-agent talent from
throughout the world, but that non-Italians ``won't have a role
onboard during the races.''
</P>
<P>
   Onorato brings some weighty race credentials, and thus
credibility, to a possible run for ye auld mug, and Italians have
been passionate about America's Cup racing since the Azzurra team
splashed in at Newport in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Onorato began racing as a 21-year-old in 1978, and his list of
accomplishments include second place in the Farr 40 division at GMC
Yukon Yachting Key West Race Week, and he was a member of the
European Admiral's Cup team that placed second this year.
</P>
<P>
   But he is also a realist, who says he does not want to ``make a
lot of noise'' about his possible Cup entry until ``I have all my
facts together. I don't have to invent stories about myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows, for example, that if he did muster up a Cup challenge,
he would not win the first time around. Anyone who thinks such a
thing is possible, in his term, is ``ingenuous.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he does have additional backing from a Japanese
insurance company, Yasuda Kasai, though he acknowledges that if
finances are not a worry, there are many technical roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   First, the lack of good used IACC boats. Without a good boat, he
says, it's hard to start a training program. Also, ``there are not
many sailors in Italy capable of covering the role of skipper in an
America's Cup syndicate.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Onorato has signed on a designer, Giovanni Ceccarelli,
who has designed his share of modern winners, and though he seems
beset by many problems to solve if he hopes to meet his
self-imposed decision deadline in October, Onorato says: ``The
chance I will do it is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Newport last week, Vim, whose owner Craig Speck
had fitted his Nelson/Marek 43-footer with a new keel, and whose
crew was laden with star talent, placed 1-1-1-5 for a 14.75 score,
just three ahead of Idler, which placed 2-5-3-3 for the week.
</P>
<P>
   In third place was another Italian boat, Atlantico Yah-Man, a
Frers 39 owned by Vittorio Rava from Milan, which scored 17.87 with
finishes of 4-6-6-1. At the helm was Tomasso Chieffi, skipper the
1986 America's Cup entry, Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Winning skipper Terry Hutchinson, an Annapolis sailor who was
mainsheet trimmer for Cayard's AmericaOne campaign in Auckland,
praised Speck the excellent showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took Bruce's and my recommendations about the boat, about
the crew choice, and now it has paid off.'' With some light-air
days and one day with winds exceeding 30 knots, Vim showed speed
over a range of conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Newport's Ken Read, who helmed Team Dennis Conner's Aukland
entry Stars &AMP; Stripes, called tactics aboard Idler and praised the
victor. ``The fact is they sailed better than us, and I've had my
share of regattas where we've won when racing was cancelled on the
the final day. You live by the sword, die by the sword,'' Read
said, referring to the light flukey winds that forced cancellation
of the last day of racing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's Cup winner Russell Coutts spoke to about 200 people at
the Pleon Yacht Club fund-raiser Tuesday night. Earlier in the day,
about 150 youngsters from Pleon, the junior sailing club, had a
90-minute session with Coutts, most of them curious about his rise
to become one of the most accomplished sailors in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts, who skippered New Zealand to consecutive America's Cups
victories in 1995 and 2000, stunned his team when he and tactician
Brad Butterworth defected to sail for Switzerland in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Coutts handled the matter up front, telling the audience that
money ($4 million to $5 million, according to most speculation) was
one of the major factors in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the Swiss are at a tremendous disadvantage,
and that just as America's loss of the Cup in 1983 was good for
international sailing, so would it be good for the Cup if New
Zealand loses it. Coutts was smiling when he said it, though it is
clear he means it.
</P>
<P>
   Said John Collins, PHRF rater and long time race official in
Marblehead, Mass.: ``Everyone in the audience felt that here is a
professional athlete who tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tony Chamberlain covers the out of doors for the Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
