u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-25 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS IN RARER AIR THAN EVEN JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In most cases, the idea is simple: smile, take the praise, and
be on your way without asking any questions. You are Tiger Woods,
surrounded by thousands who are prepared to fit you with a precious
(itals)I Am The Next Michael Jordan(unitals) crown. This is a
compliment _ usually.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, a great athlete/pop culture success story, retired from
the Chicago Bulls on Jan. 13, 1999. By Jan. 14 the sports world was
Camelot, with daily tests to see which athlete would be picked to
pull a Jordan-autographed sword out of a stone.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm, Vince Carter, and Kobe Bryant have been among the
frequent nominees. And now that the 24-year-old Woods has become
the youngest golfer to win the sport's grand slam, the public has
decided that it's his turn, although there is no comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Woods? The next Jordan? When you consider the athletic and
social legacy created by both men, you'll see that placing their
names in the same sentence is indeed a compliment. For Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Woods is Jordan's age (37), the documents listing
golf's records will read like a repetitive roll call: Tiger Woods .
. . Tiger Woods . . . Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to win the US Open at Pebble Beach, Calif., but
to win it by 15 strokes is staggering. It's one thing to win the
British Open at St. Andrews in Scotland, but to face a course with
112 bunkers and not be affected by them is amazing. One year, 1997,
you dominate the Masters in Augusta, Ga. Shortly after that you
overhaul your swing, briefly struggle, listen to people talk about
you as if you are some one-hit-and-out child actor, and then pull
2000 out of your pocket as if it were a trump.
</P>
<P>
   There are no weaknesses in Woods's game. His shots off the tee
are accurate projectiles that often travel 350 yards. He's got a
great short game, able to use a pitching wedge from 160 yards
(while some others use 8-irons). His presence has dampened the
silly question, ``Is golf a game or is it a sport?'' Watch him.
It's a sport. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Woods? The next Jordan? The analogy doesn't fit, especially when
the discussion goes beyond sports. They are both pitchmen for Nike,
the company that tries to put its famous swoosh on your psyche.
They are both handsome, dominant, and rich. But let's examine them
closer.
</P>
<P>
   It has become a cliche to say that Jordan is the best basketball
player to ever live. An addendum to that is that the NBA never saw
the likes of him before. As much as I love Jordan, I can tell you
neither statement is true. Wilt Chamberlain was a more resourceful
scorer; Oscar Robertson and Jerry West could be considered near
equals as guards; Dr. J and Connie Hawkins were in-flight stylists.
The point is that there were elements of Jordan's game that were
seen before he came to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   What no one saw, though, was a man who created such an off-court
phenomenon. They never saw a man who sold ads such as he did,
inspired kids to shave their heads clean as he did, and introduced
a new style of clothing _ socks low, wristband high, shorts baggy _
as he did.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods, no one can argue this point: We've never seen anyone
who looks like him remix golf the way that he is remixing it. Sam
Snead and Jack Nicklaus certainly knew how to win. The late Ben
Hogan, whose father killed himself when Hogan was 9, certainly had
a rougher life (and a similar level of concentration). Arnold
Palmer had his devotees _ although few of them were like the
streakers who showed up at St. Andrews Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But has anyone seen a golfer drive like this?
</P>
<P>
   ``Before Tiger, if you saw someone hit the ball 300 yards you
thought it was impressive,'' John Rieker said Monday. ``But he can
hit it 350. People have never seen anyone hit the ball 350 yards _
with accuracy _ like he does.''
</P>
<P>
   Rieker is the head pro at Franklin Park Golf Course in Boston's
Dorchester neighborhood. The course is located near the
intersection of Blue Hill Avenue and Columbia Road. Step off the
course and walk around the block, and you can see a lot of people
who look like Tiger Woods. More than ever, because of Woods, you
can see more people on the course who look like him, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Woods was winning the British Open Sunday, about 50 people
gathered in the Franklin Park clubhouse and watched the broadcast.
That wouldn't have happened five or 10 years ago, Rieker said. The
camps offered at the course, for children between the ages of 7 and
14, have had attendance double since they began eight years ago.
Attendance reached its peak last year at 600. If you had miked the
area Monday, you would have heard one name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the topic of discussion here,'' Rieker said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods? The next Jordan? Here's another reason it doesn't fit:
When Woods goes to work, he can practically shake the hand of Jim
Crow. In 1997, he acknowledged that he had been receiving death
threats since he was 16. He once described himself as a mix of
Caucasian, African-American, Indian, and Asian. But, obviously,
when some people see him, they focus on all aspects that are
nonwhite. Woods further challenges the imaginations of some fans
(and raises the ire of others) with his current romantic choice,
still seen as taboo in some areas. His girlfriend is white.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he does seems to stretch and redefine the rules,
whether they be written athletic ones or unspoken social ones. No
one who looks like Woods has ever been this successful in golf, so
no one has ever had to ponder these things while also pondering
course layouts.
</P>
<P>
   If Woods must be compared to another athlete, it should probably
be Bill Russell, not Michael Jordan. In 1957, Russell entered an
NBA that hadn't seen many men of his complexion nor men who had his
vertical skills. He changed an aspect of his sport; Woods is doing
a full-scale remodeling of his.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing aspect of the Woods tale is imagining how
the sport will look when he is gone from it. He has brought an aura
of accessibility and athleticism to a country club sport. This
sport and its crowds will change a decade from now. It will become
younger. And it will become darker. A lot of it will have to do
with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cool to be a golfer now,'' Rieker said. ``Kids love
(Woods). When I'm out, people always ask, `How good is he, really?
And what will he do next?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The question is not what (itals)he(unitals) will do next. He'll
be fine. He'll continue to dazzle galleries and titillate home
audiences. A more interesting area is trying to foresee what will
come after him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
