<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-WriteT     07-25 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PIES-LADN-WriteThru-4Takes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH FRUIT PERFECT PIE FILLING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Adds photo information 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   2 photos moving by Michael Owen Baker/Daily News &QL; 
1 Plentiful summer fruits perfectly complement your favorite
crust. &QL; 
2 Whip up a beautiful fruit pie such as peach this summer with the
lovely array of fresh fruits available at markets in your area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like the glorious taste of a freshly baked
fruit pie. With produce bins overflowing with a rainbow of the
season's fresh fruits  &UR; _ &LR;  from peaches and nectarines to plums and
pears and an array of berries  &UR; _ &LR;  the time is ripe for turning out
some luscious and glorious beauties at home. The possibilities and
combinations are numerous and rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   If making a pie crust eludes you (or you don't have time), don't
give up. Simply skip creating the crust altogether and pick up a
box of refrigerated, rolled-out and folded prepared crusts in the
supermarket deli section  &UR; _ &LR;  they're ready to use on a moment's
notice. It's even feasible to use store-bought phyllo and puff
pastry dough for lining pie pans. And if you want something even
simpler to use the bounty of summer fruits, you might find
cobblers, crisps and crumbles even less intimidating. A range of
recipe choices is included here.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Classic Home Desserts,'' the late Richard Sax writes,
``Many find baking a pie more threatening than preparing any other
dessert. And it's making and rolling out the crust that gets the
Anxiety Devil going.''
</P>
<P>
   It's really not that difficult if you follow a few simple
procedures. The general rule for making good pie crust doughs:
``Handle them as little as possible and keep them cool as you
work,'' writes Sax, to avoid having the fat break down and become
greasy, which results in a leaden crust.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C.-based baking expert Lisa Yockelson, author of
``Country Pies'' (and numerous other baking books), writes, ``When
making pie dough, remember all liquids and fats (even shortening)
should be used cold so your pie crust will bake up tender and
flaky. When working with pie dough, your hands should be cool; if
they are warm, rinse them in cold water before handling the dough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone should learn to make a pie crust by hand to
get the feel of how a dough is actually formed,'' encourages
Yockelson. A food processor allows you to make the dough without
actually touching it except at the end. Be careful to avoid
overmixing or overworking the dough. ``If you're concerned about
overmixing, make the dough by hand.''
</P>
<P>
   While some experts suggest combining butter and solid vegetable
shortening for the most tender, flaky doughs, others prefer using
only butter for best flavor results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I favor butter for flavor,'' says Yockelson, who never uses a
packaged pie crust. ``To me, making a pie crust is like an act of
breathing. I make a pie crust as someone would pour milk into a
glass. It is that natural to me.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's feasible to roll out the dough as soon as the pastry
ingredients are combined, chilling the dough
 &UR; _ &LR;  which gives the gluten a chance to rest and relax a bit
 &UR; _ &LR;  makes it more tender and prevents it from contracting during
baking.
</P>
<P>
   The trick to rolling out the dough is to push outward from the
center  &UR; _ &LR;  not back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   You can refrigerate the prepared pie dough three days or freeze
it up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   To save time, Yockelson keeps 10-inch rounds of rolled-out
pastry dough (which she freezes on a baking sheet between two
sheets of waxed paper until firm and then wraps well and stores in
a plastic pie carrier) stashed in the freezer. Transfer from the
freezer to the fridge to slowly thaw overnight.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to thickeners  &UR; _ &LR;  which give the juice of the
fruits body and sheen  &UR; _ &LR;  some baking experts avoid flour because
it turns the fruit juices gummy and cloudy. Food writer John Thorne
of the Simple Cooking newsletter is adamant that fruit fillings
should never be thickened with flour.
</P>
<P>
   Yockelson says she selects the thickener for her fruit pies
based on the type of fruit being used. She sometimes uses flour
with good results. ''I've never seen it as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   However, many bakers recommend using cornstarch, quick-cooking
tapioca, arrowroot or potato starch.
</P>
<P>
   Sax thickens his fruit creations with cornstarch, using about
three tablespoons per five to six cups of fruit.
</P>
<P>
   But the amount of thickener necessary depends on the fruit and
how juicy it is. It's best to use a tested recipe as a guideline so
you don't end up with juices flowing out of control. Also keep in
mind that the riper the fruit, the lower its pectin level, so you
may want to add more thickener if your fruit is very ripe.
</P>
<P>
   You can judge the juiciness of the fruit by how much juice is at
the bottom of the bowl a few minutes after you mix in the thickener
combined with sugar, points out Yockelson. If you have very juicy
fruit  &UR; _ &LR;  like peaches  &UR; _ &LR;  you'll see a lot of juice at the bottom
and may need to adjust the amount of thickener.
</P>
<P>
   Yockelson  &UR; _ &LR;  whose first consideration is one of taste and gel
 &UR; _ &LR;  uses flour (which she refers to as an old-time, readily
available thickener) with some acidic fruits like sour cherries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sour cherry pie (you end up with) is not that cloudy. It
doesn't have the vivid (color) tone of a pie made with cornstarch,
but I like the mouth feel of the flour thickener
 &UR; _ &LR;  and it condenses the juices of the pie and cuts well.''
</P>
<P>
   But other times  &UR; _ &LR;  in apple and deep-dish peach pies, for
instance  &UR; _ &LR;  she opts for cornstarch, which binds well and has a
lighter feeling to it. She avoids quick-cooking tapioca as she
doesn't like the little pellets you end up with in the pie  &UR; _ &LR;  and
even if the tapioca is pulverized in the food processor before
using, she has found the results less than satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   A lattice-top fresh peach pie article in the July/August issue
of Cook's Illustrated touts using potato starch as a thickener.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potato starch scored big: its clarity outshone flour but
was less cosmetically glossy than cornstarch; its thickening
qualities rivaled tapioca in their strength and neutrality; and
still better there was no need for pulverizing.'' The article also
noted that if potato starch isn't available, an equal amount of
pulverized Minute tapioca can be substituted.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever thickener you decide to use, remember that flour and
cornstarch can't be used interchangeably in terms of amounts. One
tablespoon of cornstarch is the equivalent of two tablespoons
all-purpose flour.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to whip up something that takes less time and energy
than a fruit pie, try cobblers, crisps or crumbles. In a cobbler,
the fruit is covered with biscuit dough  &UR; _ &LR;  either rolled out or
dropped  &UR; _ &LR;  and then baked until golden. In crisps, you avoid dough
altogether, topping instead with a mixture of butter, sugar, flour
and sometimes nuts and then baking. Cookie crumbs, graham cracker
crumbs and buttered bread crumbs can also be used. In a crumble,
the fruit is topped with a mixture of butter, brown sugar, flour
and oats and then baked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cobblers have been my standard casual company dessert for
years,'' writes author Pam Anderson in her ``The Perfect Recipe''
cookbook. ``Enriched with whipped cream or ice cream, they taste as
good as a fruit pie and can be assembled much more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice is yours. Showcase this season's ripe, juicy fresh
fruits in some of these delectable ways. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1415EDT &QL; 
