<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2416 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-STRUG-ART-BOS &LR;      07-25 1755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-STRUG-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 WHEN HER ANKLE TURNED, KERRI STRUG'S LIFE TURNED WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even now, she'll ask herself whether it was chance or fate four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times I wonder, `Why did Atlanta happen?' ' Kerri
Strug says. `` `Why was it me? What am I supposed to do with this
role that came my way?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It just happened that Strug was the last US gymnast up on the
last event of the Olympic team competition. It just happened that
the gold medal was on the line. It just happened that Strug tore up
her left ankle on her first vault. It just happened that the ankle
was good enough that she could try again, bad enough that she
couldn't walk afterward. Everything just happened.
</P>
<P>
   In the few seconds it took Strug to sprint-limp down a runway
inside the Georgia Dome on that night in July, her life changed
utterly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flying high,'' Strug recalls. ``It was surreal, really
incredible. Initially I thought, `OK, it'll be this way for two
weeks.' Then it was, `OK, a year.' If anyone had said four years
ago that things would still be transpiring the way they are, I
would have thought they were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Magnificent Seven who won the team gold in 1996, only
Strug and Amanda Borden won't be at this week's national
championships in St. Louis, trying for another shot at Olympus. But
even though Strug has retired from competition, even though she's
about to graduate from college, even though a new generation of
Vanessas and Alyssas has taken the floor, it goes on. The
interviews. The speeches. The clinics. The celebrity benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Troy Aikman and I was so ecstatic,'' Strug says. ``Then
he said on his AOL site that he got to meet Kerri Strug and I was,
`Oh my gosh, he knows who I am and he remembers me!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Strug, like Mike Eruzione and Brandi Chastain, is on an eternal
video loop, immortalized for one glorious sporting moment. Eruzione
will always be dancing in the corner of the rink at Lake Placid
with the Soviet goalie on his knees. Chastain will always be
screaming in her sports bra on the floor of the Rose Bowl. Strug
will always be in coach Bela Karolyi's arms on the medal stand, her
ankle wrapped and bulging like a Christmas package.
</P>
<P>
   She accepts that now, even if she doesn't quite understand it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure it's going to be the defining moment of my life,''
Strug says. ``But I don't want it to be The Moment. Maybe this was
my one chance to make a worldly impact and the rest of the things
that I do won't. But that doesn't mean that having a family or
graduating with a master's from Stanford isn't going to be just as
satisfying as the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way to top The Moment, which is one reason Strug has
no desire for a reprise in Sydney this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `Why aren't you going for Sydney?' '' she says.
``They don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Strug is 22 now and she hasn't trained seriously for three
years. To get back to world-class shape, she would have to starve
herself and live in the gym for eight hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get older, you're defying the odds,'' Strug says.
``You can't stay on top forever in a sport like gymnastics. The
young ones have more energy, they're lighter, they're swifter. And
they don't know there's another world out there because they
haven't experienced it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was always going to be her finish line, and Strug
wouldn't even have been there if she hadn't barely missed making
the all-around final in 1992. She already had a team bronze from
Barcelona. What she wanted in Atlanta was an individual medal. When
she realized that her ruined ankle dashed her chances, Strug was
devastated. She never dreamed that the ankle would make her rich
and famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a gymnast, you're never thinking about those
things,'' says Strug. ``At least, I wasn't. Sure, in the back of
your mind you always think it'd be nice if you get some
recognition. But if that's why you're doing it, you're doing it
backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Strug didn't know that she was vaulting for the gold medal. She
had no idea what the score was. And she couldn't have known that
her second vault wouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians still had two competitors left on floor exercise
and they usually save the best for last,'' says Strug. ``There was
a lot of controversy in the media afterwards. `Why did she do it?
She didn't have to.' But we didn't know that at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Strug would have done the second vault anyway because she had
botched the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have fallen on the first one,'' she says. ``That's
how I viewed it. The last thing you want to do is end your Olympic
career on a fall. That's awful. If I didn't do it, I always would
have said, `What if . . .?' I think anyone would have. Even if I'd
gone for it and not made it, it would have been better than walking
away.''
</P>
<P>
   And Strug still would have done the vault on a bad ankle because
gymnasts _ especially Karolyi's gymnasts _ are trained to perform
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely felt a little worse than usual but I thought,
`Oh, it's just another one of those things _ go!' '' says Strug,
who had torn both the medial and lateral ligaments. ``I'm lucky
that I didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   So she landed the vault and the Americans won the gold for the
first time and suddenly Strug was the gritty heroine who'd risked
crippling herself for her team and her country. It wasn't Shannon
Miller or Dominique Moceanu, who'd gotten marquee billing before
the Games. It was the doctor's daughter from Tucson with the chirpy
voice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strug made more than a million dollars during the next year. She
wrote two books (``Heart of Gold'' and ``Landing On My Feet''). She
went to the president's 50th birthday party. She met Mikhail
Gorbachev. She bantered with Rosie O'Donnell. She spoofed herself
on ``Saturday Night Live.'' Amazing, she marveled. All because of
one vault.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable, Strug says, that there would be ruffled
feathers among her teammates, especially when Strug didn't join
them on the sanctioned post-Olympic tour and did a rival weekend
tour. Hadn't they won the gold medal together?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of hurtful, to be honest, because these were girls
I thought were like my sisters,'' says Strug. ``Yes, we were very
competitive and we didn't always love each other. But you do care,
you do relate. By no means have I ever thought I was different from
the team. It just so happened that the cards were dealt that way
for me that time. But of course you're going to think: `We all won
the gold medal. Why does she get to do this, why does she get to do
that?' It's just human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   If Strug weren't due to enroll at UCLA, she says, she would have
joined the other six on tour (which she did, a year later).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not to say that I didn't want to be with them,'' she
says. ``But I wasn't going to alter another whole year of my life
just to go touring. Because I'd already altered so many things.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympus, then college, was always the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew that Atlanta was going to be it for me,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   She had already taken a year out of school. It was time, her
parents said, to do what most normal 18-year-olds do.
</P>
<P>
   Strug, who had been living in a gym since she was 5, had no idea
what normal was.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're coming from a different world,'' she says. ``You
realize, oh my goodness, there are boys. Pizza does taste good.
It's fun to go to the movies. Going on a date, going to a college
football game _ to everyone else, that's nothing. But when you're
19 and you haven't done it yet, it's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions were easy in the gymnastics world because there were
so few to be made. At UCLA, Strug found herself with a bewildering
array of choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even deciding what to eat, that was a big deal,'' she says.
``While you're going through it, you don't like Bela telling you
everything to do, you don't like having that dictator. But once
it's taken away, it can be very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strug eventually found UCLA and Los Angeles overwhelming, so
after her sophomore year she transferred to Stanford, a.k.a. The
Farm, where celebrity students (like Chelsea Clinton) are taken in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `She won a gold medal. Well, I started my own
dot.com, I'm a millionaire. So what?' '' Strug says.
</P>
<P>
   At Stanford, the expectations on her are mostly self-inflicted.
Once a gold medalist, always a gold medalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll think, well, I have to be top of the class,'' says Strug,
an A student who is two classes short of her undergraduate degree
and will be staying at Palo Alto to get a master's in
organizational structures. ``No, I don't. But it was part of being
a perfectionist, being afraid of failure. I'd be afraid to take a
biology class because it was going to mess up my GPA. But I like
biology, so why not take the class? If you have one class where you
don't have an A, you're going to be OK. But it takes doing poorly
to realize that life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   One poor vault on one night changed her life forever. Had it
been perfect, Strug might just have been the face between Moceanu
and Miller in the team photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a wonderful four years and I've loved every
opportunity,'' she says. ``That's not to say that every morning I
wake up happy to challenge the day, but more so than not. The pros
definitely outweigh the cons.''
</P>
<P>
   There are times, Strug says, when she misses the adrenaline rush
she used to get as a gymnast _ ``that feeling of being nervous but
knowing that you're going to do awesome.'' She misses the
satisfying simplicity of doing one thing extraordinarily well. And
she misses the playground camaraderie of the gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite as much fun going to the library for six
hours,'' she says, ``as it was flying around in the air for six
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Her flying days have been over for a while now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw online that I was coming back,'' she says. ``I said,
really? That's news to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She moved on when it was time to move on and she has left the
floor to those who eat not of pizza. ``I think, well, in Sydney
there'll be some new little star and in 2004 there'll be another
one,'' Kerri Strug says. ``But I guess nobody can take away from me
or the girls what we did in Atlanta.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
