<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT PRACTICE CASUALTY OF PATRIOT INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Max Lane walked out of the cafeteria at
Bryant College sporting a wrap all the way up his right leg; he did
not participate in the afternoon practice. Ditto for Ryan Tujague,
a free agent rookie out of Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Both players were added to a staggering list of New England
offensive linemen who have gone down with injuries at training
camp. The situation is so bad that coach Bill Belichick Monday
called New York Giants coach Jim Fassel to cancel their joint
practice at the University of Massachusetts that was to have taken
place Thursday from 12-2 p.m. The reason, according to Patriots
spokesman Stacey James, was ``a lack of depth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who train in Albany, N.Y., were going to meet the
Patriots at McGuirk Stadium in Amherst, which is about midway
between the teams' camps.
</P>
<P>
   The scary thing is that the Patriots may not be in appreciably
better shape by the time they take the field for their first
exhibition contest _ Monday's Hall of Fame Game against the San
Francisco 49ers in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The linemen who are missing practice because of injuries or
surgery aftereffects are second-round pick Adrian Klemm, right
guard Todd Rucci, left tackle/guard Lane, guard/center Lance Scott,
left tackle Bruce Armstrong, right tackle Grant Williams, and
Tujague. Those who remain standing include center Damien Woody
(though he got up gingerly after going down in the morning
practice), guard Derrick Fletcher, rookie free agent guard Adam
Davis, rookie tackle Greg Robinson-Randall, guard/center Jason
Andersen (who was playing left tackle before the morning practice
was over), and free agents Brent Warren and Terrance Beadles.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has been slow to recover from knee surgery but seemed
to be picking up his intensity in personal drills and may be forced
to suit up long before he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also have taken a hit on their defensive line with
Henry Thomas going down with arthroscopic knee surgery, while
Brandon Mitchell is nursing a calf injury. Linebacker Ted Johnson
and Chad Cascadden have been nursing injuries all week.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Patriots are a mess.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellation of Thursday's scrimmage at least removes the
risk of injury to Drew Bledsoe, who would have been protected by a
makeshift offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   It is tough to judge offensive linemen until they play in games,
so who knows whether Robinson-Randall, a fourth-round pick out of
Michigan State, and Davis, out of Oklahoma State, can provide
adequate protection for Bledsoe's right side? Who knows whether
second-year man Fletcher, a 6-6, 350-pound mass of humanity, can
prevent Bledsoe from seeing major time on the turf Monday?
</P>
<P>
   Is this the way the Patriots really want to find out?
</P>
<P>
   Belichick and offensive coordinator Charlie Weis understand the
situation, so they say the right things: They'll hope for the best,
and hope to give young quarterbacks Michael Bishop and Tom Brady
most of the snaps. Bledsoe probably has to show up and play a
series or two because the game is on national television, but you
can bet the house that he will be handing off a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Drew about it before the start of training camp,''
said Belichick. ``With the extra preseason game, what I'd like to
do is get the two younger QBs the opportunity and then evaluate
them after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll talk to Drew about that. We haven't decided if this guy
will play 10 plays or that guy will play 15. My plan is to play
Brady and Bishop more than Drew and John (Friesz) the first two
games.''
</P>
<P>
   What if one of the 49ers' experienced linemen eats up a young
Patriot and imperils Bledsoe?
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you play a preseason game, you have to manage the
game, whether it be the first quarter or fourth quarter,'' said
Belichick. ``You have to understand who you're putting on the field
and what they're capable of doing. When you're playing 70-80
people, you can't play them all the same. There's a certain level
for each player. Then you look at what the other team has out
there. We don't want to put ourselves in a situation where you're
overmatched.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has said from the start of camp that he doesn't have
an opinion about having to play so early in the preseason. Nor has
he said there's any disadvantage or advantage to playing five
exhibition games as opposed to four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play what's in front of us,'' said Belichick. ``I have
no control over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more frustrating is that the roster is at its limit, so to
add players, he would have to drop some.
</P>
<P>
   There also is concern about players being overworked in
two-a-day sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to manage that,'' said Belichick. ``We don't want to
run down the guys we have. Sometimes there's an imbalance if you
only have, for instance, a few defensive backs and a lot of
receivers. I think we're OK. We can do what we need to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains to be seen. Everytime an offensive lineman gets
nicked, there's a hush from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Playing an early game doesn't help, though it could give young
players a chance to get some valuable experience.
</P>
<P>
   With a new coach and a new system, the Patriots have not had a
lot of time to practice all of the new things. Suffice to say there
will be some rust and awkward moments Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Right now there can be no real competition on the offensive
line. It's just football's version of ``Survivor,'' and the big
question is, will Drew Bledsoe survive in the end?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
