<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BLOUNT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK BLOUNT WISE TO HIS WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The ``Wisdom Tour'' started the moment Mark Blount
declared himself eligible for the NBA draft, leaving the University
of Pittsburgh in 1997 after his sophomore season.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-10-inch center gave his brief NBA stint and sojourns
to the CBA, IBL, and USBL the title ``Wisdom Tour'' after realizing
how little he knew about the world of professional basketball.
Since the tour kicked off, Blount has made stops in Seattle,
Atlantic City, Los Angeles, Sioux Falls, S.D., and Baltimore. With
serious interest being shown by the Celtics, he has booked an
extended stay in Boston, beginning with training camp and, he
hopes, continuing through the season.
</P>
<P>
   If Blount can make it through the first two weeks of camp _ and
there's no reason to expect he won't _ he will make the team.
According to Celtics director of player personnel Leo Papile,
Blount has a ``99 percent'' chance of making the squad. Papile
considers Blount a bonus draft pick and compares the starting
center for the Celtics' entry in the Shaw's Pro Summer League very
favorably with the big men selected in 2000. Papile also foresees
Blount getting minutes, not just pushing his teammates in practice.
</P>
<P>
   But the experience gained through the minor leagues and the
major disappointment of not sticking with an NBA team (despite
short stays with the Sonics and Clippers) out of college kept
Blount from celebrating. His biggest lesson has been that a
professional basketball career ``is a long journey the whole way
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount does not regret leaving Pittsburgh, though some
basketball pundits believe early struggles attached a stigma to
him. By some accounts, Blount became a cautionary tale for
early-entry candidates and NBA teams steered away from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he made a major mistake coming out of school,'' said
Kevin Mackey, who coached Blount in the USBL. ``He was just
learning how to play the game. There's a different clock on a
(6-10) guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Papile likened Blount to a basketball leper. As an unwritten
rule, teams sometimes don't want to touch a player who makes a
mistake by leaving school before he's mentally and physically
ready.
</P>
<P>
   Banished to the minor leagues without playing a regulation NBA
game and with the word ``potential'' at the top of his resume,
Blount remade himself and matured.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the period of time (after the draft), I had to work on
myself,'' said Blount, 24. ``I slowed myself down and said, `Hey,
now you're a man. You're supposed to be working. You're supposed to
take care of yourself.' After the draft, it was like a whole new
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that I could play in (the NBA) and have a statement in
this game. I had done this and that. But I knew it was time to get
where I wanted to be and do what I wanted to do. I think I've done
a great job over the past two or three years getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   A bigger, stronger, wiser Blount is on display at UMass-Boston's
Clark Athletic Center. Through commitment to a weight-lifting
program, Blount has gained 15 pounds since college, allowing him to
bang his 220 pounds around. Among his summer league peers, his
shot-blocking skills stand out. Although 2.3 blocks per contest is
not an overwhelming number, it's the manner in which Blount
collects blocks that impresses.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter against Philadelphia Thursday, Blount
anticipated a pass and tipped it away. He could not complete the
steal, but hustled back toward the basket and managed to block the
shot. Monday, in the league finale, Blount scored 17 points,
recorded three blocked shots and had eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Blount averaged 10.3 points in eight games.
Apparently, the Celtics have found a big man who not only has solid
skills at both ends of the court, but also genuinely enjoys playing
in the team's system with an emphasis on defense.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of summer league play, Blount plans to rest for a
few days at home in St. Augustine, Fla., and then continue to
refine his game for training camp. Although excited about his
prospects with Boston, Blount does not want to get overly excited.
He has not talked with his family about the future and the positive
feedback he has received from the Celtics, preferring to focus on
the hard work ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The levelheaded outlook comes from the ``Wisdom Tour.'' It was
on the road in the CBA, IBL, and USBL that Blount learned he had to
put his ``wild and partying high school and college days'' behind.
(He attended three high schools, disuading such college suitors as
UMass with his inability to stay in one place.) Along with his
basketball skills, Blount now practices patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's finalized, I'll call my family,'' said Blount.
``Right now, I've got work to do. I don't think there's going to be
any celebrating. If you want to be the best you can be, what are
you celebrating about until it's all over? You don't celebrate
until you hang up the shoes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
