<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2428 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-PANOZ-HNS &LR;      07-25 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-PANOZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TRADING IT ALL FOR A HAND-BUILT PANOZ 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Attn: Ga., Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Fred and Sherry Smith really weren't looking to
buy another new car.
</P>
<P>
   They had a 2001 Toyota MR2 Spyder, just eight days old, not even
broken in yet. And of course, there was the red '99 Plymouth
Prowler, one of those $40,000-plus retro-looking street rods that
they bought a year or so ago.
</P>
<P>
   But while they were out driving around one recent Saturday
afternoon, the Smiths, who live in Boerne, Texas, happened upon the
Hovey Motorcars lot in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Smith saw the brand-new, silver Panoz 10th anniversary
special edition Roadster, and as Fred Smith tells it, ``It was love
at first sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The devil didn't make me do this; it was Sherry,'' he says of
his on-the-spur-of-the-moment decision to buy the $80,000,
supercharged, hand-built, all-American sports car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yeah, I liked it, too,'' he admits. ``But it was her
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right! Fred also admits that he hasn't let Sherry drive it
yet, adding: ``She has a heavy foot.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two did take the car home that Saturday afternoon, and
no cash changed hands. They traded:
</P>
<P>
   The Prowler.
</P>
<P>
   The MR2.
</P>
<P>
   A trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Three Korean War-vintage military trucks.
</P>
<P>
   And an old tractor.
</P>
<P>
   Their reaction to the Panoz is typical of people who see it: If
they are truly car people, they want it, says Rick Hovey, one of
the dealership's owners (along with his dad, Rich, and brother,
Todd).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Panoz Roadster is a unique automobile, and it turns heads
wherever it goes,'' he said. ``We've been the exclusive San Antonio
dealer for over a year now, and the cars have been a great draw for
us -- even if the people they brought in didn't end up buying one
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The question Rick Hovey gets the most is: ``What is a Panoz?''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of answering, Hovey hands them his business card, which
opens up to reveal two full-color photos of Panoz cars: the
Roadster, a hot-rod-looking car that has been in production in some
form for the past 10 years, and the new Esperante, a more
traditional sports car, which goes on sale later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The cars are hand-built in Hoschton, Ga., by Panoz Automotive
Development, founded in 1990 by Danny Panoz _ son of Don Panoz, who
developed the Nicoderm nicotine ``patch'' and earned a fortune with
it. The family also owns a motorsports company, which competes in
several racing series, and the Road Atlanta race track, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz Auto Development was born of Danny Panoz's desire to build
an American sports car. He bought the manufacturing rights for an
Irish company's chassis designed by engineer Frank Costin, well
known for his work with Lotus, Lister and Maserati.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1989, using Costin's chassis as a philosophical
starting point, Danny and two former engineers of the Irish company
began work in their new shops 50 miles northeast of Atlanta _ a
converted 2,000-square-foot state salt storage shed, according to
the company's published history. Panoz Auto has since grown to fill
five buildings covering 100,000 square feet of floor space.
</P>
<P>
   The first handcrafted Panoz Roadster was introduced just seven
months later, on June 27, 1990, the company says. It was equipped
with a 5.0-liter pushrod Ford V-8 engine, had an all-new
stainless-steel tube space frame, and was the first production car
in the United States to use a superplastic formed aluminum body.
Superplastic forming was developed to make durable parts for the
aerospace and aviation industries, the Panoz history says.
</P>
<P>
   After some improvements to the Roadster, Panoz in 1996 became
the first U.S. manufacturer to design and build a production
``aluminum intensive vehicle,'' as Panoz calls the Roadster.
</P>
<P>
   The original steel space frame was replaced with a twin-tiered
extruded aluminum chassis, and the pushrod cast-iron V-8 engine was
dropped in favor of an all-aluminum, 305-horsepower, 32-valve V-8
built by Ford's Special Vehicle Team and also used in the Ford
Mustang SVT Cobra. This was the new A.I.V. Roadster, whose special
edition would end up in Fred and Sherry Smith's garage.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1996, Danny Panoz and his father launched Panoz Motor
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both knew that racing was the way to develop new
technologies and create a heritage for the company, so it was
important that the same front/mid-engine, rear-wheel drive layout
built for the street was reflected on the track,'' the company
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing guru Adrian Reynard was tapped to help build and enter
two front/mid-engine, rear-wheel drive Esperante GTR-1 cars in the
1997 24 Hours of Le Mans,'' the company says. ``With no racing
experience, Panoz went head to head with the top guns of Porsche,
Mercedes and Ferrari. After 18 hours of racing, Panoz was running
ninth overall when an oil failure knocked it out of contention.
Though neither of the two Panoz cars finished, it was one of the
most impressive showings by an independent manufacturer in the
history of Le Mans.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that start at Le Mans in 1997 and in the American Le Mans
Series, founded by Don Panoz, the Panoz team has finished Le Mans
twice in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   At Hovey Motorcars, there is a bright yellow Panoz Roaster on
display _ not one of the silver anniversary editions (only 10 of
those were built, and none are left), but one of the standard
models with the 4.6-liter Ford SVT engine (not supercharged).
Sticker price is $64,185, but no more of this particular style will
be built; it is being redesigned for 2001 to reflect new smog rules
that are forcing the car's exterior styling to change to
accommodate a new fuel-tank placement, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The Roadster looks a lot like the Prowler, but the Panoz design
has been around a lot longer. The similarities between the two cars
end with the exterior appearance, however, Hovey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is the performance,'' he said. ``The Panoz
Roadster out-handles the Dodge Viper, out-accelerates the Porsche
911, and leaves the Prowler _ which has only a V-6 engine _ sitting
in its dust.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith agrees with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prowler was a boulevard cruiser,'' he said. ``It just
didn't have the get-up-and-go and the handling of the Panoz. And
the Panoz's craftsmanship is much better than the Prowler's, even
though the Prowler's is very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason he traded the Prowler was that he ``hated always
getting beat at the traffic lights'' in the relatively slow
Prowler, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The regular Roadster has a 305-horsepower engine and goes from
zero to 60 mph in 4.5 seconds, compared with 253 horsepower and
acceleration from zero to 60 mph of about 7 seconds for the
Prowler. Top speed for the Panoz is about 132 mph; it is limited
because of aerodynamic problems, but if the car would stay on the
ground, it probably could do more than 170 mph, Hovey said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's supercharged Roadster has even more impressive
performance: It has 322 horsepower, and gets to 60 mph in under 4
seconds. It completes the quarter-mile in under 12 seconds. The
aerodynamic problem keeps the top speed down, even though the
speedometer goes to 160 mph, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said that if you took those front fenders off, it could
go much faster,'' Smith said. The fenders act like wings on the
2,595-pound car and create lift, taking the front wheels off the
ground if the car is driven too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The more practical Panoz Esperante, which is designed for daily
drives if the owner so chooses, will list for nearly $80,000. The
car was unveiled at the New York Auto Show in April, and the
company says it already has more than 215 deposits for the first
year's production run _ representing about two-thirds of the
plant's capacity for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Panoz also builds track-ready race cars, one of which is on
display at Hovey Motorcars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're probably going to race it, but for now, it's just for
display,'' Rick Hovey said. ``It isn't street legal; it doesn't
have a title, and their aren't even any headlights on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the Panoz products, visit
www.hoveymotorcars.com or the Panoz site, www.panozauto.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
