<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-FORD-SUPERCREW-H     07-25 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-FORD-SUPERCREW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEITHER PICKUP NOR SUV, FORD SUPERCREW OFFERS BITS OF BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The all-new 2001 Ford F-150 SuperCrew seems to be misnamed.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps the 2001 Ford Explorer Sport Trac is the one that is
misnamed.
</P>
<P>
   These two vehicles are identical in concept, yet one is held out
to be a version of the nation's most popular sport-utility vehicle
_ the Ford Explorer _ while the other is positioned as a version of
the nation's most popular vehicle, period _ the Ford F-150 pickup.
</P>
<P>
   The Explorer Sport Trac essentially is an Explorer SUV with the
cargo compartment's top chopped off to create a combination
Explorer/pickup, while the SuperCrew is, essentially, a Ford
Expedition with the cargo area's top chopped off to create a pickup
bed.
</P>
<P>
   But as most of us know, the Expedition is really a full-size
F-150 pickup with the cargo area covered up, turned into a
family-hauling sport-utility.
</P>
<P>
   And the Explorer? It's a Ford Ranger compact pickup turned into
a sport-utility.
</P>
<P>
   Confused?
</P>
<P>
   In this day and age of cost-cutting and more efficient
manufacturing, automakers are sharing their various vehicle
platforms among a variety of different products more than ever, and
it's hard sometimes to tell just by looking what vehicle is derived
from what other vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The SuperCrew is to the Expedition what the Sport Trac is to the
Explorer. From the front bumper to the back of the rear seat, the
SuperCrew is an Expedition. Sure, there are some minor cosmetic
differences, but they're really just superficial. Then from the
back of the rear seat to the tailgate, this becomes an F-150
pickup, although with a shortened bed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, calling it the F-150 SuperCrew instead of the Expedition
Sport Trac (or something along that line) might be a misstep. This
vehicle is going to appeal more to the sport-utility crowd than the
pickup crowd, because it is first and foremost a passenger vehicle.
The pickup bed seems almost an afterthought, especially since it is
smaller than the average F-150 bed _ just 5.5 feet long (a sheet of
plywood is eight feet long, and will fit into many full-size pickup
beds).
</P>
<P>
   People who need a real pickup won't want the SuperCrew because
of its limited cargo-hauling capabilities. But people who like the
idea of the Explorer Sport Trac, yet want more passenger and cargo
room, might flock to the SuperCrew if they see it as a larger
version of the Sport Trac, rather than as a crew-cab pickup for
commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. Who cares what they call it. The SuperCrew is a great
idea, just like the Sport Trac, and I had fun driving it for a
week.
</P>
<P>
   My only complaint was the same one I had with the Sport Trac: If
the vehicle is full of people, then any cargo you carry has to go
outside in the bed, exposed to the elements.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you planning to take family trips with the
SuperCrew, the luggage would have to be stowed in the bed, and that
could subject your stuff to wind, rain and sun.
</P>
<P>
   So even though the SuperCrew isn't the most practical family
vehicle, it does have its attributes, and it will fill the needs of
many people who choose to buy it. It will be great for hauling
dirty toys (such as muddy four-wheelers and such) while the
passengers remain inside in clean comfort.
</P>
<P>
   And, like the Explorer Sport Trac, the SuperCrew isn't as
expensive as the sport-utility vehicle it is derived from.
</P>
<P>
   The base price for a two-wheel-drive, entry-level SuperCrew (the
XLT model) is $26,090 (plus $665 transportation), compared with
$29,655 for the two-wheel-drive Expedition XLT.
</P>
<P>
   That's nearly a $3,600 discount for having the back third of the
vehicle chopped off. What a deal! That means that you can buy an
almost-Expedition for $3,600 less than a real Expedition, if you
can live with an uncovered cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   Just like the Expedition, the SuperCrew is available with either
the 4.6-liter Ford Triton V-8 engine (which is standard) or the
5.4-liter Triton V-8, an $800 option.
</P>
<P>
   The 4.6-liter engine is rated at 220 horsepower and 290
foot-pounds of torque; the 5.4-liter offers 260 horsepower and 350
foot-pounds of torque. When properly equipped, the SuperCrew can
tow a trailer of up to 8,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It comes with a four-speed electronically controlled automatic
transmission with overdrive. A limited-slip rear axle is available
for $285.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the SuperCrew is as comfy as an Expedition, and can
carry five full-size adults easily. A sixth person can squeeze
between the driver and front outboard passenger if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The SuperCrew is the same overall length as the 139-inch
wheelbase F-150 SuperCab model, which is an advantage when
maneuvering in tight spaces such as parking lots or garages, Ford
says. What the SuperCrew lacks in bed length is added to the
passenger compartment to increase leg room for the people in the
rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   An optional bed extender ($195) lengthens the cargo area to
seven feet. This metal cage folds out onto the open tailgate to
hold cargo into place, using the flat tailgate surface as the
additional cargo area.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its Expedition heritage, the SuperCrew has
electrically adjustable pedals _ the only pickup with this feature.
A switch will raise the brake and accelerator pedals for people
with short legs, or lower them closer to the floor for long-legged
folks.
</P>
<P>
   This system also is available on the Expedition, the large Ford
Excursion SUV and on the Ford Taurus/Mercury Sable sedans. It is
designed to allow short people to sit far enough back in the seat
to keep them from being injured by the air bag, should it deploy.
</P>
<P>
   In most vehicles, really short people have to scoot the seat as
far forward as possible so they can reach the pedals. In doing so,
they position themselves too close to the steering wheel, in which
the air bag is mounted. Some people have died from being too close
to the air bag when it deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The SuperCrew drives and rides just like an Expedition; the ride
seems to be more carlike than in the typical pickup, but part of
that could be due to the passenger-carlike interior accouterments.
</P>
<P>
   Two trim levels are offered, and each can be purchased with two-
or four-wheel drive. The XLT is the base model, while the Lariat is
the premium.
</P>
<P>
   The two-wheel-drive Lariat is $27,670 (plus transportation and
options); the four-wheel-drive XLT lists for $29,310; and the
four-wheel-drive Lariat is $31,125.
</P>
<P>
   Braking is excellent, thanks to the power-assisted four-wheel
disc system with antilock.
</P>
<P>
   Power steering, air conditioning, power windows/mirrors/door
locks, cruise control, remote keyless entry and power outside
mirrors are standard.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are 12 miles per gallon city/17 highway
for the 5.4-liter engine, and 15 mpg city/20 highway for the
4.6-liter.
</P>
<P>
   The tank holds 25 gallons of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
