<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NBC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NBC SEARCHES FOR ITS OWN `TREND' SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ You want to praise NBC's top entertainment
executives, or at least feel sorry for them, but you can't.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't have ``Survivor'' or ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't even have a piece of piffle like ``Making the Band.''
</P>
<P>
   Too highbrow? Too much class?
</P>
<P>
   Nope: Too late.
</P>
<P>
   When the reality wave struck, NBC just stood there on the beach
with its surfboard tucked under its arm, feet sunk in the sand. The
network talks about developing such a show soon _ but there's a
feeling that by the time they take the plunge, the water will be
calm or even chilly.
</P>
<P>
   You want to give props to NBC West President Scott Sassa and NBC
Entertainment President Garth Ancier for sticking with quality
dramas and comedies. The network did give us ``The West Wing'' last
year, and still has ``ER,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``Friends,''
``Frasier'' and ``Will &AMP; Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   You know behind closed doors they are getting pounded by the
higher-ups. They joke about it breezily to critics, but these are
the guys who are going to get marooned unless they strike reality
gold. Yes, you want to be in their corner. But you can't.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a lot easier to defend them if they were presenting
a new fall slate of shows that were full of the richness and
originality and, yes, the truth that only good dramas and comedies
can offer. Maybe one of their seven new series will rise to that
lofty level _ but I don't see it happening, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, NBC acknowledges that it has been tardy on another
important trend: Launching shows in the summer against weak rerun
competition. ABC did it two years in a row with ``Whose Line Is It
Anyway?'' and ``Millionaire,'' while CBS is scoring huge with
``Survivor'' and is hoping to cash in on ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, instead of leading the next trend, NBC is going to jump
into reality as well, probably next summer. ``This is not just a
fad, it's a trend,'' Sassa said. ``It's going to be around for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the shows the network is looking at is the Dutch program
``Chains of Love,'' in which four guys are handcuffed to a woman,
then voted out one by one. ``It's a relationship show,'' Ancier
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fill in the punch line of your choice here.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said the lesson learned from everyone copycatting
``Millionaire'' (poorly) last year is to not rush into a genre just
because a show is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a better idea: Don't rush in at all.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving us the next Regis, give us a different
alternative. Great shows would be a start.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? That could even be the next wave.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the scene would have been unfathomable: a news
conference with the cast and writers of ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' where the
focus of discussion was not the homosexuality of two of the key
characters.
</P>
<P>
   The pressing issue for the third-year NBC comedy is that it's
moving to the coveted 9 p.m. Thursday time slot, the former home to
classics such as ``Cheers,'' ``Seinfeld'' and ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accomplished what we try to do, which is to try to make
the show mainstream, and (that's why) we're on Thursday night,''
said executive producer/director James Burrows, who also created
``Cheers.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Titans,'' the new NBC cheesefest soap from Aaron Spelling, is
so over-the-top it might be the most unintentionally funny show
this season.
</P>
<P>
   All this and Casper Van Dien (of ``Starship Troopers''), who
makes Al Gore look as loose as Gregory Hines.
</P>
<P>
   The show is so bad it may just be brilliant, but we're rooting
for you, Casper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
