<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODEL-E-AUTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEXT ON THE INTERNET: FULL-SERVICE AUTO DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Silicon Valley is getting ready to challenge
Detroit for a piece of the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   A company called Model E plans to offer a high-tech alternative
to the traditional automakers by manufacturing built-to-order,
limited edition cars that can be ordered on line.
</P>
<P>
   The company, backed by Softbank Venture Capital of Mountain
View, Calif., will also offer the option of ``subscribing'' to a
car or several models over a period of time as an alternative to
buying or renting.
</P>
<P>
   The concept would allow the company to bypass the dealers and
establish a direct relationship with the customer. Model E's plan
is to handle every aspect _ the vehicle design, personalized
features, financing, registration, as well as maintenance and
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   According to a news release from the Fremont, Calif., company,
customers will be able to subscribe to various car models over a
specific period, such as three cars over a two-year span.
</P>
<P>
   The investors in Model E plan to make an official announcement
about the company and its business lines next month.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Leathern, digital commerce analyst for Jupiter
Communications, said he is aware of the company and finds the
concept ``intriguing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That isn't something that exists today,'' he said. ``It may
well be exciting for the consumer. But ultimately it will be judged
on whether it meets a need. We've seen a lot of cool ideas that
just haven't worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is planning to develop customized vehicles that can
be ordered over the Internet. Those cars, limited edition models,
are scheduled to be available next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Model E will have an ``eConcierge'' team to handle
registration and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from the venture capital arm of Softbank, the
Japanese Internet investor, did not return calls for comment.
Efforts to reach Model E's chief executive officer, Bill Li, and
co-founder George Kim were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Model E's management team comes from such companies as Lexus,
Toyota, Ford Motor Co., General Motors Corp., Ritz Carlton, Walt
Disney Co., Apple Computer and America Online.
</P>
</TEXT>
