<HEADER>
A2435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-INTERNET-HEALTH-HNS &LR;      07-25 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GUIDE TO ON-LINE HEALTH RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD A. MARINI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the earliest days of the Internet, health and medical
sites have been some of the most popular on the World Wide Web. But
today there is much more to do on line besides simply looking up
the latest news on a specific disease or ailment.
</P>
<P>
   New sites now do stuff that previously required a trip to the
gym, the drugstore or even the doctor's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of interesting and useful sites out there,''
said Charles B. Inlander, president of the People's Medical
Society, a medical consumer advocacy organization based in
Allentown, Pa. ``But like everything else when it's new, it's buyer
beware.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. For example, the once-high flying DrKoop.com, which
traded on the reputation of former U.S. Surgeon General C. Everett
Koop, came under blistering attack last year for not making a clear
distinction between its medical content and advertising. The site
now more clearly labels information provided by or sponsored by
outside companies.
</P>
<P>
   The following are some of the best sites recommended by Internet
experts. While they are listed under certain categories, most also
offer other health- and medicine-related services. These can
include medical news, e-mail newsletters and general health and
fitness information.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site type: On-line Drugstore
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: Drugstore.com, www.drugstore.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Sells a full-line of prescription and
over-the-counter drugs, health and beauty aids and medical devices.
If it's in your neighborhood drugstore, you'll likely find here.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Accepts most major insurance plans and claims to
monitor prices so it can sell for less than national drug
stores--especially with free standard shipping. Offers e-mail
reminders to replenish regularly ordered products. Pharmacists are
available 24/7 to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Delivery can take two to 14 days, way too long in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site type: On-line drugstore
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: Walgreens, www.walgreens.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: The on-line version of the familiar chain sells
only prescription medicine. Need shampoo? You'll have to go
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Prescriptions can be delivered by mail or picked up
at any Walgreens store. The site maintains a complete prescription
history to make re-ordering easy and avoid potentially dangerous
drug interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Limiting the selection to prescription drugs also
limits the site's usefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Consult a Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: AmericasDoctor, www.americasdoctor.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Offers free, one-on-one chats with board-certified
or board-eligible physicians. Doctors will answer general questions
and suggest sources of information, but won't diagnose, recommend
specific treatments or prescribe medication.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: The user-friendly site provides fast, if anonymous,
answers to basic questions.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Doctors are extremely limited in what they'll say or
do. (The site repeatedly warns that they're not entering a
traditional doctor-patient relationship with you.) For more
personalized help, see your regular doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Consult a Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: CyberDocs, www.cyberdocs.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Provides confidential consultations with
U.S.-trained, board-certified physicians either immediately or by
appointment. Doctors will address simple medical problems and, if
circumstances warrant, initiate treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Physicians will prescribe medication only from a
carefully selected list of approved drugs. Drugs that require close
supervision or can be easily abused are not available. Patients are
advised to seek an appropriate follow-up in a hospital or office
setting, although there's no enforcement procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Depending on the medical specialty and where you're
located, you may have a choice of only one or two physicians. And
CyberDocs are not available in all states. Consultation fees range
from $50 to $75.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Find a Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: AMA Physician Select, www.ama-assn.org/aps/amahg.htm
</P>
<P>
   Description: Run by the American Medical Association, this site
includes background and contact information on virtually every
licensed physician practicing in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Comprehensive listings can be searched by name or
medical specialty and all information has been verified for
accuracy. Most listings include the physician's office hours, phone
numbers and educational background. Some even have maps with
driving directions.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Raw listings provide only basic information.
Physicians haven't been screened for competency.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Find a Doctor
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: Best Doctors, www.bestdoctors.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Lists doctors rated as the best in their respective
fields according to anonymous, ongoing surveys of about 30,000
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: You can search for doctors by specialty and
location. For complex medical cases, registered nurse advocates are
available for a $975 fee to help get the best medical care
available. A Spanish language version of the site is also
available.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: The ``best'' doctor may be several hundred miles from
where you live. The site charges a $25 fee per referral.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Find an On-line Support Group
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: Self-Help Sourcebook Online,
http://www.mentalhelp.net/selfhelp/
</P>
<P>
   Description: Lists and links to more than 800 national and
international self-help support groups.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: The extensive database is searchable by either
ailment or keyword, such as ``infertility'' or ``depression.''
Listings include a description of the group and contact
information. There are also instructions for forming your own
self-help group.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: The site contains such a wealth of information it's
almost overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: On-line Medical Records Storage
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: PersonalMD.com, www.personalmd.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Free, password-protected service stores and manages
all your medical records, including records of visits to the doctor
or hospital stays, lab results, X-ray reports, EKGs, medications,
allergies, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Keeps medical records in one easy-to-access location
available from anywhere in the world, either by computer or fax.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: You are responsible for entering and maintaining your
medical records, which can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: On-line Medical Records Storage
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: 98point6, www.98point6.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Combines health information from both you and your
physicians in one central location.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Allowing you to add to your doctor's records
promises a more complete medical file.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Your doctor must be able _ and willing _ to keep
on-line medical records current and up-to-date. The site also
promises several services _ such as a private messaging system
between you and your doctor and an on-line appointment maker _ that
are not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Buy Health Insurance
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: HealthAxis.com, www.healthaxis.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Offers instant quotes on health insurance, dental
and prescription medicine coverage to individuals and some managed
care members.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Insurance coverage is available from a number of
well-known carriers, including Aetna U.S. Healthcare, Blue Cross of
California and U.S. Life.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Because insurance companies are licensed and their
rates are regulated by state insurance commissions, premiums are no
lower than those available directly from the insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Buy Health Insurance
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: eHealthInsurance.com, www.ehealthinsurance.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Sells individual, small group and Medicare
supplement health plans through establish insurance companies
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Lets you quickly and easily make a side-by-side
comparison of the benefits and prices of different plans.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Not all plans are available in all states.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Health and Fitness Consultation
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: EDiets.com, www.ediets.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Tailors a personalized diet plan based on your
personal goals, lifestyle, and even food preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Comprehensive program includes customized menus
(updated weekly), recipes and printer-ready shopping lists to take
to the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Charges a $10 registration fee plus $10 per month.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Site Type: Health and Fitness Consultation
</P>
<P>
   Name/URL: Gymerica.com, www.gymerica.com
</P>
<P>
   Description: Get a personalized workout plan program or follow
those of sports stars such as Craig Biggio (baseball), Rodney
Rogers (basketball) or Drew Bledsoe (football).
</P>
<P>
   Good Stuff: Animated workout demonstrations illustrate proper
form.
</P>
<P>
   Bad Stuff: Personalized diet program is promised but not yet up
and running.
</P>
</TEXT>
