<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, July 26:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LONG-ISLAND-WINE (Peconic, N.Y.) _ Wine Talk Column: The Long
Island wine business is booming; it's almost giddy from its own
success. Handsome new wineries are opening, old ones are changing
hands for astonishing prices, new vineyards are springing up, and
suddenly, there isn't enough wine to go around. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   PARMIGIANO (Undated) _ Most people who buy Parmigiano-Reggiano
never give a thought to the variations in the way it tastes. I
always assumed the flavor differences had to do with the aging
process or the quality of the cheese itself. Or so I thought until
last week, when I tasted Parmigiano-Reggiano produced in fall,
winter, spring and summer. I was amazed at how distinctive each one
was. By Marian Burros. (With photo)
</P>
<P>
   PLATE-PAINTING (New York) _ Critic's Notebook: Some things you
don't miss until they're gone. The painted plate is one of them. It
was not too many years ago that no plate left a New York kitchen
until, like a subway car parked overnight in a railyard, it had
been decorated in drips, dots, dabs and hash marks. Now white is
making a comeback. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   CANADIAN-CHICKENS (Undated) _ Imported free-range chickens
processed by a new method are winning converts among New York chefs
and could be in supermarkets this fall. By Rozanne Gold.
</P>
<P>
   CHATEAU-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The pretentious tone of the
title aside, ``From My Chateau Kitchen,'' by Anne Willan, is
accessible and reliable. Willan, the founder of La Varenne, a
cooking school, uses her home in Burgundy as La Varenne's summer
headquarters (the U.S. branch of the school is at the Greenbrier
resort in West Virginia). By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: Michel Richard on fried
chicken with a potato crust.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Pizzas for summer. By
Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: On New Zealand sauvignon
blancs. By Erik Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Dining Section stories by early evening in
the ``d'' news file, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
