<HEADER>
A2458 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-OIL-NAT     07-25 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-OIL-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        REGIONAL OIL RESERVE CRITICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 21 - With another winter of punishing home
heating costs possible in the Northeast, federal energy officials
and members of Congress are scrambling to assemble an emergency oil
reserve to help prevent shortages that hit the region hard last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Department of Energy pushes to have two million
barrels of home heating oil stored by October 1, and as Northeast
lawmakers push legislation needed to authorize the president to tap
the oil, the initiative is coming under fire from a skeptical oil
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Energy analysts and oil industry officials said in interviews
that, at best, the reserve is a politically-motivated measure whose
ability to ease the effect of low supply and price spikes is
unproven. At worst, they said, government intervention could
disrupt the heating oil market at a cost to oil marketers, and
ultimately make matters worse for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Although five months remain before buyers begin to stockpile
heating oil, the outlook for the coming winter in New England,
where the majority of heating oil is used, is already bleak. The
region's inventories are one-fourth the size they were at this time
last year, and oil prices are running about 65 percent higher than
they were a year ago, according to the American Petroleum
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after the Strategic Petroleum Reserve -- a stockpile of
crude oil held on the Gulf Coast for national crises -- the
regional reserve is for emergency use only. The president would be
allowed to draw oil in times of short supply, when extreme cold
snaps cause demand -- and prices -- to spike. The Department of
Energy is soliciting bids for the storage facilities -- due August
1 -- and is considering splitting the reserve into as many as four
areas -- Boston, New Haven, New York harbor and a site in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet oil company officials from the region said the government
effort to affect the price of heating oil - a publicly traded
commodity -- threatens to disrupt the market and cause oil buyers
to be more cautious. The chief concern, they said, is that during
extreme weather conditions, oil companies would refrain from buying
oil if they believed the government was about to tap the reserves.
This could exacerbate supply shortages like those that rocked New
England last winter, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's looking for a disaster,'' said Alfred Slifka,
chairman of Global Petroleum in Waltham. ``I'm going to lose a
fortune. I haven't heard one economist that says this makes
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar argument has been made against the Strategic Petroleum
Reserve, which has only been tapped once, by President Bush during
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said the stockpile would come under intense
political pressure from Northeast residents, creating great
uncertainties for the independent heating oil buyers in New
England, who purchase their supplies in weekly increments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a political trigger was pulled, it could devalue the
inventory of the wholesale market overnight,'' said Jack Sullivan,
executive vice president and CEO of New England Fuel Institute in
Watertown. ``That's frightening. A regional reserve is a tremendous
disincentive to re-supply.''
</P>
<P>
   Last January's crisis came when oil stockpiles - in severe
shortage following the decision to limit crude oil production by
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries - couldn't keep
up with demand during cold snaps. When the temperature plummeted in
January, prices jumped 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, who took a battering of
criticism over high gas prices in the Midwest this summer, now is
focusing attention on the Northeast, and last week announced a set
of 14 policy recommendations aimed at diversifying the region's
energy sources. In a meeting last week with regional oil industry
officials, Richardson gave assurances that the reserve wouldn't be
used to jigger market prices. ``DOE doesn't involve itself in the
market,'' said spokesman Drew Malcolm. ``The secretary assured them
it would not become a market issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The reserve is a top priority for Northeast legislators, who
said the exorbitant heating bills of last year are simply
unacceptable. ``I'm not comfortable leaving it up to market forces
to determine the price when the prices could go through the roof
and people can't afford to heat their homes,'' said Representative
James McGovern, a Worcester Democrat, who helped pitch the reserve
to Clinton last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that had we had a sizable reserve of home heating
oil we could have dealt with the price spikes'' last winter, said
Representative John Olver, Democrat of Amherst.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the impact of the reserve on heating costs is uncertain.
Conservation may be the real solution, said Bob Slaughter, public
policy director at the National Petrochemical and Refiners
Association. Moreover, two million barrels would last no more than
two days in the entire Northeast region.
</P>
<P>
   The energy department is tackling several thorny questions about
where and how to set up the facility. Still undetermined is who
would pick up and distribute the oil, and how long would it take to
deliver it to residents' homes if it was released. Environmental
and procurement regulations are also possible stumbling blocks to
getting it in place quickly, industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation that authorizes the actual use of the reserve is
the most pressing concern, however. Senator Olympia Snowe, a Maine
Democrat, secured $4 million in funding to operate it through
September, 2001, attached to a spending bill passed in the Senate
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the president is unable to tap it without legislation that
decides upon what should trigger its release, and the oil industry
and state governments are preparing to battle with Congress over
the details of the unwritten legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve funding may also face opposition from oil-state
lawmakers. ``There is enough of a push'' for a reserve, said
Representative Richard Neal, a Springfield Democrat. ``The question
is how much resistance is there going to be?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
