<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2479 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t BC-CHEAP-EUROHOPS-500&AMP;SI     07-25 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAP-EUROHOPS-500&AMP;SIDEBAR-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LES PUDDLE-JUMPERS' ARE LIKE WINGED EURAIL PASSES  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: 500-word SIDEBAR at end of 500-word story)   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' financial story _ WITH HELPFUL
SIDEBAR _ is from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it
must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been moved to the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``t'' travel news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RUDY MAXA  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Once, flying around Europe was an expensive and difficult
proposition involving just a handful of big-name airlines. Today,
there's a new army of smaller, ``niche'' carriers in Europe, whose
names are largely unknown not only to most Americans but also to
many American travel agents. Airlines with names like Eurowings,
easyJet, and Spanair.
</P>
<P>
   Airline deregulation, to which Americans grew accustomed more
than 20 years ago, is relatively new to the Continent. In the past,
governments in Bonn, London, and Paris regulated not only air
routes but also airfares.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's a free-for-all in the skies, and the revolution
benefits passengers by providing a wealth of options and cities to
fly into, often at substantially lower fares.
</P>
<P>
   Buzzing around Europe by air has become almost as easy as buying
a Eurail pass.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these smaller airlines were started by major carriers
that watched the success of Southwest Airlines in the U.S. and
decided that if anyone was going to cash in with low-cost service,
it might as well be them.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago, British Airways spawned a stepsister named
Go; last year, KLM Royal Dutch Airlines started a subsidiary called
Buzz.
</P>
<P>
   What are the drawbacks? To begin with, many of the European
niche airlines fly in and out of secondary airports.
</P>
<P>
   While most Americans are used to landing at or departing from
London's Heathrow or Gatwick airports, Go flies out of Stansted, 30
miles northeast of London. EasyJet, begun by a 33-year-old Greek
entrepreneur known only as Stelios, calls London's obscure Luton
(32 miles north of the city's center) its home base.
</P>
<P>
   These airports aren't any more difficult to reach than Heathrow
and Gatwick, but you face a hefty commute if you're connecting via
one of the two major airports.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the airlines have baggage agreements with major carriers
(just as Southwest doesn't in the U.S.), so you can't check your
luggage through when you're connecting. You'll have to fetch your
bags from a baggage area and recheck them on your next flight.
</P>
<P>
   Not all airlines have toll-free telephone numbers accessible
from the United States. And not all Web sites offer English
versions, so polish up on your Croatian.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan on hopping around Europe, you may want to consider a
Europe Flight Pass, a coupon book that allows you to fly one-way or
round-trip on any of 16 participating airlines (serving 127 cities
in nearly 30 countries) for $99 per segment.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, you must buy at least three segments, and you can use
the coupons for up to 120 days after your first flight. And while
you must purchase your coupons before going overseas, you may make
specific reservations anytime, in the U.S. or elsewhere. Details:
888-387-2479.
</P>
<P>
   ``Les Puddle-Jumpers'' shows the niche airlines that can have
you hopping around Europe this summer; to see the extensive list of
cities linked by airlines that accept Europe Flight Pass coupons,
go to Europebyair.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Rudy Maxa is a frequent contributing writer at
WORTH.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDEBAR: `LES PUDDLE-JUMPERS' FOR BARGAIN HUNTERS &LR;  &QC;
</P>
