<P>
   LYRICS-EDIT (Undated) _ An array of song-lyric review and
editing procedures have become a routine part of the record
business. Artists with explicit material are routinely asked to
re-sing lyrics, edit out particular words and even excise entire
songs from albums. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   CHOREOGRAPHERS-LEGACY (Undated) _ A growing sophistication about
preserving the legacy of dance has largely institutionalized the
handing-down of choreography, which was first passed down from
dancer to dancer, then by written notation and film and video. The
idea of owning a dance as property is relatively new. Changes in
copyright law are in part responsible for this, as well as
increasing general interest in copyright and ownership in a
new-media age that has effectively widened the possibilities of
illegal appropriation of artistic property. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-ARTS-CENTER (Snowmass Village, Colo.) _ Rustic cattle barns
and sheep sheds that until 1966 were the heart of an active ranch
here now draw acclaimed and aspiring artists from around the world.
The Anderson Ranch Arts Center is a bucolic center for potters,
photographers, painters, printmakers, woodworkers, sculptors, art
historians and critics. By Elizabeth Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Thomas and the Magic
Railroad,'' which moves the PBS children's show ``Shining Time
Station'' to the big screen, Alec Baldwin plays Mr. Conductor. He
brings to the role not only the most sinister voice ever heard on a
good guy in a G-rated movie, but he performs with a vigor not
normally seen in such a picture. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   WATERFORD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``New Waterford Girl,''
directed by Allan Moyle, is animated by a feisty spirit. It's about
a young girl's struggle for independence against the forces _ her
parents, her town, the way things are _ that rein her in. Reviewed
by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   SIGN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Aimee Bender's intriguing ``An
Invisible Sign of my Own'' pursues a course through the charmingly
deformed personality of its narrator, evoking as it goes the dark
themes of the parable. Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTRESS-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ If played straight, ``The
Huntress,'' a series that USA is unveiling Wednesday night, would
surely be tiresome. But presented as an off-kilter spoof, and
draped around a winningly drawn central character, the premise has
promise. Reviewed by Ron Wertheimer.
</P>
