<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TEAMSTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND JURY SAID TO PROBE TEAMSTER FILM CONTRACTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With Movies-Union; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY AND STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A federal grand jury is investigating allegations that
local Teamsters Union officials extorted Hollywood producers who
filmed a series of box-office hits throughout New England,
according to sources familiar with the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are looking into whether moviemakers were
forced to hire a local company with alleged ties to organized crime
to provide rental vehicles _ such as wardrobe trailers _ on all
movie sets, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   They are also looking into whether union officials extorted
favors from movie producers and forced them to hire a small group
of hand-selected drivers .
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the grand jury subpoenaed records from Teamsters
Union Local 25, in Charlestown, detailing the union's contracts
with filmmakers of such hits as ``The Perfect Storm,'' ``The Cider
House Rules,'' ``Message in a Bottle'' and ``Good Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, agents from the US Department of Labor's
division of labor and racketeering raided the Weymouth home of
James P. Flynn, the union's transportation coordinator, and seized
records relating to the movie industry, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Local 25 President George Cashman, a longtime fund-raiser for
Governor Paul Cellucci who was recently reappointed to the
Massachusetts Port Authority board of directors for another seven
years, has also come under scrutiny as part of the probe, according
to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Flynn nor his attorney, Richard Egbert, could be reached
for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman Monday acknowledged the federal investigation, saying
that the union's contracts on several past movies had been
subpoenaed. He downplayed the intensity of the investigation,
however, saying federal authorities are ``always looking at the
movie industry. This time it involves us.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said he did not know the particulars of the probe, but
when asked about allegations involving Flynn, said, ``I've heard
some scuttlebutt about that, but nothing specific.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was a subject of the investigation, he said,
``Absolutely not. If I am, no one has told me.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is focusing on allegations that the Teamsters
forced producers filming around New England to hire the Location
Connection, a Boston company that provides wardrobe trailers and
other vehicles and is allegedly controlled by Flynn, according to
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the company's workers have links to organized crime in
Charlestown, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking into whether Flynn forced movie
producers to hire the same small group of drivers for each movie _
a group he had allegedly hand-picked, according to a source.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of disgruntled Local 25 guys who are
legitimately working and see a handful of guys in the union making
incredible amounts of money on these movie productions when they
film in Boston,'' said a source. ``It's always the same guys who
work on them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Flynn was acquitted of the 1982 gangland slaying of
Brian Halloran, a Winter Hill gang member who was gunned down on
Boston's waterfront after cooperating with the FBI against gangster
James ``Whitey'' Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Flynn, 66, has been back in the limelight as an
actor. He had cameo appearances in ``Cider House Rules'' and ``Good
Will Hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation is being led by the division of labor
and racketeering and the New England Organized Crime Strike Force,
attached to US Attorney Donald K. Stern's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our policy that we can't confirm or deny whether there is
an active investigation,'' said Dennis Kurdek, assistant special
agent in charge of the Department of Labor's Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Martin, a spokeswoman for Stern, declined to comment on
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters Local 25, which supplies the drivers for all films
shot in Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Vermont and Maine, negotiates
contracts with movie producers over wages _ a figure that can
dramatically impact production costs.
</P>
<P>
   Movie producers have long complained about the cost _ and
aggravation _ they encounter in contracting with Local 25 for
drivers on their movie productions. Under the current contract,
Teamster drivers are paid $2,000 a week for working eight hours a
day in addition to lucrative overtime and fringe benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, as one of a handful of crew chiefs, benefits from a
provision that requires he be paid for every hour that the movie
set is open, even if he is not on the set or no filming is being
done.
</P>
<P>
   One executive, who asked not to be identified, recalled that
Flynn had received weekly paychecks of about $9,000 for several of
the weeks that he had worked on the production of ``Cider House
Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole movie industry is being held hostage in Boston,
that's why they avoid it,'' said a source familiar with the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman butted heads with Warner Bros. executives during the
``Perfect Storm'' negotiations last year, prompting a producer to
fire off an angry letter to Cellucci, complaining that they were
being priced out of Massachusetts by the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, the executive producer complained that
the Teamsters wanted Warner Bros. to pay 72 percent more to some
union drivers than they'd been paid a year earlier when working on
``Message in a Bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Cashman said the increase in wages was justified
and was the first in many years.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci interceded with a call to Cashman and eventually the
Teamsters and Warner Bros. reached an accord, resulting in scenes
from ``The Perfect Storm'' being filmed in Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cellucci led a delegation that included Cashman on a
trade mission to Los Angeles in an effort to convince moviemakers
to film in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   John Birtwell, spokesman for Cellucci, said that the governor's
office was not aware of any federal investigation into the
Teamsters' union. However, he said that a few movie studio
executives had complained to Cellucci about their problems in
dealing with Local 25 but had not produced any evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time Teamsters Local 25 has been investigated
for alleged corruption involving the movie industry. In 1982, two
Local 25 members were convicted for defrauding producers of
Boston-made movies by placing no-shows and fictitious names on
their payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Victimized were producers of the following films made in Boston:
``The Brinks Job,'' produced in 1978 by Dino DeLaurentis;
``Oliver's Story,'' produced by Paramount Pictures in 1978; and
``International Velvet,'' produced by MGM in 1977.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
