<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKERS CHOOSE LESS COSTLY LOCATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With Movies-Teamsters; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A movie about playing baseball in the Cape Cod League has been
shot in recent months _ in North Carolina. While the producers of
``Summer Catch'' will be filming scenes on the Cape for a few days
this week, the bulk of the $20 million movie was filmed in
Wilmington, N.C., because of the filmmakers' concerns that they
would face problems with Teamsters' Local 25.
</P>
<P>
   According to several independent and studio filmmakers, dealing
with Local 25, which controls Teamster contracts for movies made in
Massachusetts, Vermont, New Hampshire and Maine, invariably
presents sizable financial costs as well as aggravation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not worth it,'' said one Warner Bros. executive who
asked not to be identified. ``Their contract is just too expensive
and it's impossible to get them to compromise on anything. It's a
whole lot easier just to go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official, who tracks the industry nationwide, estimated
that Massachusetts is losing out on as much as 50 percent of the
movie business it could attract because of studios' concerns about
dealing with the Teamsters. Last year, approximately $50 million
was spent in Massachusetts by the filmmaking industry, about half
of what was spent in 1997 when a major production, ``A Civil
Action,'' was filmed here.
</P>
<P>
   George Cashman, president of Local 25, agreed in an interview
Monday that his union does have either the first or second most
lucrative filmmkaking contracts in the nation, in terms of wages
paid to union members.
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledged that industry executives often complain
about the costs of making films in Massachusetts, Cashman denied
that Local 25 refuses to compromise in negotiating contracts with
the producers of individual films, though he offered no specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are always complaining about the cost of doing business
here, but there's been many times that we've made concessions with
them that they never tell you about,'' Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Bros.' executive said the Teamsters have been
unwilling to compromise on several key contract provisions,
including one that stipulates the number of drivers assigned to
work on sets as well as another that pays crew chiefs whenever the
set is operating, regardless of whether they are needed or if
shooting is being done.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the minute that the coffee gets put on in the morning at
a set, the Teamster drivers are getting paid,'' the executive said.
</P>
<P>
   Movie executives also complained that the members of the
Teamster work crews are often unfamiliar with the sophisticated
equipment that must be moved around a set, but that Local 25
officials have steadfastly refused to allow any Teamster members
from other locals who specialize in such equipment from being
assigned to the set, unless accompanied by a Local 25 member.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros., which is producing ``Summer Catch,'' is not the
only studio to decide in recent months to shoot a movie that has a
decidedly local storyline out of state. Producers of ``Prozac
Nation'' and ``The Harvard Man,'' both of which concern Harvard
University students, decided to do the bulk of their shooting in
Canada, minimizing filming in and around Boston to a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, who has been president of Local 25 for nine years, said
it is expensive for any enterprise to do business in Massachusetts
and that Local 25 should not be faulted for insisting that
moviemakers pay higher-than-average costs for filming here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very profitable industry,'' Cashman said. ``We are
only asking that our members get their due share.'' If the
situation were as dire as some producers contend, Cashman said,
studios would not continue to do business in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, two comedies _ MGM's ``What's The Worst That Could
Happen'' and the Farrelly Brothers' ``Osmosis Jones'' _ are being
filmed in Boston and Plymouth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Dawson, executive director of the Massachusetts Film
Bureau, acknowledged that some moviemakers wanted to shoot their
films in Massachusetts because the story was centered here but
decided to shoot elsewhere because of problems with the Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Location decisions are driven by budget and yes, the Teamster
budget is one of the highest cost elements of a production,''
Dawson said. ``Filmmakers have told me it weighs heavily on whether
a production will decide to shoot here.''
</P>
<P>
   John Birtwell, spokesman for Governor Paul Cellucci, said that
one or two studio executives had complained directly to Cellucci
about the Teamsters when the governor went to Hollywood in 1997 and
again in 1999. Cashman accompanied Cellucci on both trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found more often than not is that it was anecdotal
rather than anything pervasive,'' said Birtwell. ``There seems to
be a lot of talk without much hard evidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
