<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, gossip from the wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The World Wrestling Federation's ``Fully Loaded'' pay-per-view
looked like it left the WWF's talent shelf unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   Brutal matches, Triple H vs. Chris Jericho, Rikishi vs. Val
Venis and The Rock vs. Chris Benoit, looked to take a toll on the
WWF roster. But The Rock and Benoit were back out in the ring on
Monday. And with the return of the Big Show and the increased use
of Kurt Angle, it looks like the WWF has again weathered a
physically demanding pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   One loss they may not be able to avoid is Triple H. He has been
working as the top heel for more than three year. If nothing else,
it would benefit him to take a month off and the WWF has been
working its angle so he could leave for a month and they could
carry on with Benoit and Angle taking over top heel status.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of that duel, teaming the Big Show with them could be a
stroke of genius. Since jumping from the WCW over a year ago, the
Big Show has not found theperfect gimmick. Because of his size, he
must be a heel and teamed with the newest top heels, he should
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   WCW executives must cringe when looking at the WWF roster.
Former WCW wrestlers Benoit, Jericho, Big Show, Saturn and Eddy
Guerrero are all in contention for titles or big pushes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reports on the internet have Hulk Hogan and Eric Bischoff
booking WCW ``Thunder'' shows and Vince Russo booking ``Nitro''
shows. Not true, as Russo is still handling most of the booking
duties with right-hand man Terry Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   _ According to reports from fans at Monday's ``Nitro,'' when the
show went off of the air Goldberg left the ring just holding his
arm as though he was injured. Not good news for WCW. Especially,
with Scott Steiner and Kevin Nash are missing ``Nitro,'' WCW needs
all its weapons to continue its battle with WWF. Steiner is not
injured, he is still on his honeymoon (he was married Friday),
which pushed back last week to work WCW television.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of getting married, The Undertaker got married on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Diamond Dallas Page made some noise last week about WCW not
using him because of his age. The 44-year-old is listed on upcoming
house show booking sheets, but not for television. Many in WCW
believe that Page came up with the idea for the ``Positively''
Kanyon gimmick as a way to keep him in the minds of viewers.
Kanyon, a longtime friend of page, enjoys the gimmick and should
face Page in a pay-per-view when Page returns.
</P>
<P>
   _ A wrestler without a home, Randy Savage, was on a Providence,
R.I., radio station last week. He said he is between contracts and
is trying to decide between the WWF and WCW. The 45-year-old said
that he is not too old for wrestling because he hasn't made it to
the top yet. He also said that he will be making a shocking
announcement in the near future. Yeah, probably that he's going to
drop his asking price so he can get some work.
</P>
<P>
   _ WWF talent man Jim Ross touted Ron Waterman as an intriguing
prospect in his most recent ``Ross Report.'' At 6-foot-2 and 260
pounds, Waterman has an amateur wrestling and mixed martial arts
background that could help him rise through the ranks quickly.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the WWF injury front, Billy Gunn's return date has been
moved up to September. The orginal diagnosis for the torn rotator
cuff from October at best.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to see Tazz get a chance at the Intercontential title
soon. Also, Trish Stratus days with T&AMP;A are number. She will be the
exclusive valet of Val Venis soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
