<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIFE WITH ROVER, NOT LAND ROVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here I have been happily living without kids,
and now I find out I'm supposed to be angry and militant about it.
To add to this country's surplus of movements, America now has a
child-free movement.
</P>
<P>
   And I just thought I was part of a pro-dog movement, one that
liberated me from worries about child care and schooling. I can
stay up as late as I want, and wake up at a civilized hour, and
never have to sock piles of money away for tuition or buying my
16-year-old a car.
</P>
<P>
   My oldest dog is 16, in people years, but he isn't getting a
Jetta or taking the College Boards.
</P>
<P>
   So what am I supposed to be mad about? The fact that parents of
real children get a few tax credits here and there?
</P>
<P>
   My dogs don't get the $500 tax deduction given each dependent,
but they never outgrow their clothes, they never need more than a
bowl of dried rice and animal parts each day, and when I go to work
they can be locked unsupervised in the house without child
protection agencies locking me away.
</P>
<P>
   Am I supposed to be upset about the so-called
``family-friendly'' workplace, which provides day care and generous
leave arrangements for parents?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, I haven't seen such a workplace, although my home
newspaper is pretty good with pregnancy leave and part-time work
schedules for parents, and occasionally lets them bring in kids on
days when the child care arrangements fall through. This is very
healthy for children, because they quickly get bored and decide not
to go into the newspaper business.
</P>
<P>
   As a former teacher, I'm prejudiced in favor of children, and
have no wish to live in an environment free of them, except when
they're screaming. My wife is more adamantly anti-child, so much so
that she had a tubal ligation at 23. We regularly argue about
whether people without children have an obligation to support the
propagation of the species.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say she's not as big on our species as I am.
</P>
<P>
   It's some parents I don't like. If I had any use for movements,
I'd start the overindulgent-parent-free movement.
</P>
<P>
   Go anywhere and you'll see these parents acting out, and the
richer the place you go, the more you'll see terrible parental
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   When we're in stores, on airplanes or in fast food restaurants,
we expect to see young children, and we further expect some of them
will start screaming, bawling or running around. We expect the
parents will feel harried, and we'll feel sorry for them.
</P>
<P>
   What's unacceptable is if parents ignore their kids' behavior,
and act as if strangers should feel privileged to be overrun and
deafened by such charming little geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   Don't ever try telling one of those precious children to desist.
Then the parent will get in your face to protect the child's First
Amendment rights to scream in your ear.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is harder to take when the overindulgent parent tries
to discipline the child. What he or she does is kneel down, look
the precious one calmly in the eye and try to reason with the
unreasonable forces of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we talked about this before, didn't we, Max?'' says the
parent, as if the child would remember any discussion at an early
and pitiless Piagetian stage. ``We agreed you wouldn't kick
strangers in the knees, didn't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Almost always, the parent makes indirect requests in the form of
tag questions, which children don't understand nearly as well as a
good sharp ``No.'' But no, the overindulgent parent believes the
child is on the fast track to Harvard, and already has mastered
logic and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   The overindulgent parent is very concerned with that fast track
to Harvard, and indulgence verges on abuse as parents make their
children run on that track like rats.
</P>
<P>
   First the kids get their Playskool toy computers, then real ones
so they're well on their way to repetitive stress injury and
geekdom. Then they start taking practice SAT tests in elementary
school, often a school where recess has been abolished because
parents decided it's a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   In high school the parents hire consultants to advise the kids
on how to make themselves more attractive to colleges by
diversifying their portfolios. ``Sorry, all that soccer practice
your parents drove you to was a waste of time. Take up lacrosse.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the consultants ghost-write the college applications, and
if all goes well, the kids can head off to the college of their
parents' choice in the cars their parents bought them.
</P>
<P>
   All people want their children to have a better life, but I'm
not sure these kids are getting it. A job, to them, isn't mowing
lawns. It's something you get after getting an MBA. Sports aren't
for fun. They're for being No. 1, and we talked about how you have
to practice lacrosse five hours a day, didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   But kids can survive all kinds of childhoods, and I'm sure they
can survive overindulgent parents, and become productive citizens
helping to support me and my dogs in our old age.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
