<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-$ADV29     07-25 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-RUSSIA-$ADV29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: IN MOSCOW, COLD WATER -- NOT COLD WAR -- THREATENS
 &HT;    With photo mug of Coker available.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., July 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The menace returns, like clockwork, as soon as the
weather warms in Moscow, gripping Russia's capital in panicky
bursts of conversation about who has found the small, handwritten
note that marks you as the next victim of the cold water creep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wait in dread. It's like a mad serial killer stalking town.
You never know when you and your family are next,'' says Marina
Kazakova, the 73-year-old mother of one of my Russian friends.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer the hot water in this city of 10 million is turned
off, district by district, block by block, for almost one month at
a time, so that workers can examine the steel pipes responsible for
transporting people's bath water, dishwater and drinking water and
replace them if they are leaky or rusty.
</P>
<P>
   It's an annual tradition that I remember from my first visit to
the Soviet Union in 1986. Then, I thought it was an exotic learning
experience, and after my 21-day trip, I went back to my parent's
home in Oklahoma City for a long, hot soak in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   The fun evaporated on my next trip, when I studied at a
university in the Russian Far East in 1991. At that time, my
Russian roommate and I would come home from classes, stand outside
our dormitory and count which floors the light was on. When there
was light on our floor, there would be hot water. When there
wasn't, Rita and I would walk over to a friend's home for the
evening, cursing the sadistic bureaucrat who had flipped the switch
again.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, names my friends hurl at the head of Moscow's
utility system, the department in charge of heat, electricity gas
and sewage, when they wake up that fateful morning to only cold
water are strong enough to make your hair stand on end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clock that devil for me,'' my friend Natasha Petrovna told me
when I told her who was going to meet last week. ``Tell him he's a
murderer. Last summer both my husband and my grandbaby got sick
taking cold showers!''
</P>
<P>
   When I walked into his office, Mikhail Lapir, the 86-year-old
head of the city's public works, hardly resembled the horned
misanthrope we imagined him to be. The sprightly engineer looks
more like a trim Santa Claus, except for the drawn look of remorse
on his face that tells a listener that he actually does feel your
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine walking up the stairs to your apartment and your
neighbors giving you looks that pierce your heart. For those 23
days, how can I relax?'' he says, sighing deeply in his cavernous
office in downtown Moscow that is adorned with nothing except an
equally enormous map of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want explanations when they long for a hot
bath,'' he says. ``They complain, and complain. It's a cry from the
soul, and after hot, sweaty weekends, it becomes a cry from other
parts of the body, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's heat and hot water system came on line in 1924, as part
of Stalin's push to modernize life in Russia. After the dictator
died, few upgrades to the system were made.
</P>
<P>
   Today, like then, most of the city's hot water comes from the
town's electric power stations. The steam used to run the
electricity-producing turbines is redirected to heat water, which
is then piped through a 9,000-mile-long centralized pipe system to
people's kitchen and bathroom faucets. The hot water travels at
near-boiling temperatures, which requires a whole section to be
turned off and cooled before any work can be done.
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't defend the system, Lapir, who started work at
the city utility company more than 50 years ago, knows it inside
and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a model of collectivization when it was built,'' says
the director, whose clear, blue eyes matched the color of his tie,
which was given to him by his colleagues on his last birthday. ``It
was, and still is, highly efficient and very cheap. But it's also a
real monster, when there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat and water system was built very quickly, with little
thought given to the length of time needed for maintenance, he
said. Moscow only has one diagnostic tool, an expensive
computerized piece of machinery, that allows workers to locate
leaky sections of pipe without turning the system off.
</P>
<P>
   Because the same system heats radiators and buildings in the
winter, the only time to turn off the system is the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people would really have my head if this system broke down
in the depths of winter. People actually would die then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of living a quiet life in retirement, like other men his
age, Lapir says he won't stop working until he gets a new heating
system installed around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a dream,'' he says. ``I dream that some day we won't
have to switch it off for so long. That would make me feel my life
was worth something.''
</P>
<P>
   I've been in Russia long enough to know that change doesn't
happen very fast, but at least I'll escape the cold water this
year. Lapir let it slip that my neighborhood's hot water would be
turned off the first week of August, and I've re-arranged my
vacation accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker is Moscow correspondent for Cox Newspapers. Her
E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
