<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-$A     07-25 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REBEL CONFLICTS TURNING COLOMBIA'S POOR INTO COLOMBIA'S
DISPLACED
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-INTRO-$ADV30; COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. July 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ Libia Barahona remembers the day clearly _ a
Tuesday in July of 1998 _ when the sound of the trucks echoed
through her small town of Mapiripan(CQ), a remote village 200 miles
southeast of Colombia's capital of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks carried about 100 armed members of a paramilitary
group, who had come looking for leftist sympathizers _ families
whose sons or fathers might be supporters of the Marxist rebels
trying to overthrow the Colombian government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They rounded up everybody at 5:30 a.m.,'' said Barahona, 60, a
widowed mother of five who ran a small restaurant and store. ``They
stuck a machine gun in my chest and asked where the guerrillas and
the guns were. I told them I didn't know anything about this.''
</P>
<P>
   With no police and no army soldiers around, the paramilitaries
had their way in remote Mapiripan for weeks. Suspected informants
and sympathizers were rounded up, questioned and beaten, their
hands tied behind their backs.
</P>
<P>
   Barahona, her children and the rest of the townspeople were told
to stay in their homes with the windows closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were torturing and killing people,'' she recalled. ``We
couldn't even count the number of the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In war-torn Colombia, Barahona's story is all too common.
Colombia's military has ceded huge swaths of the countryside to the
guerrillas or right-wing paramilitary gangs. Both groups sweep
through rural towns looking for recruits and enemies, conducting a
reign of terror funded by tribute they collect from Colombia's drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle are poor campesinos like Barahona, most of
whom hide any political opinions they might have in a desperate bid
for survival. Whipsawed between the warring parties, many wind up
fleeing the countryside, heading for the larger cities.
</P>
<P>
   Official government figures list more than 1 million Colombians
as displaced from their homes in the past five years, but human
rights advocates say the number of ``desplazados'' _ the displaced
_ is closer to 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has spread over the last two years to areas not
traditionally affected,'' said Albeiro Salazar, a researcher at the
Center for Investigation and Education, a human rights group based
in Bogota. ``The guerrillas and the paramilitaries want the civil
population to take sides, and they enforce their will through
massacres and torture. Now we have whole regions of the countryside
that are depopulated.''
</P>
<P>
   While the poor have fled within Colombia's borders, the
better-off have fled the country altogether. As Colombia's woes
have grown, they have formed long lines outside foreign embassies,
applying for visas to move to Spain, Canada, the United States,
Costa Rica and other nations. There are fears that Colombia is
losing its professional class of doctors, lawyers, engineers and
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   But for the poor like Barahona, the only escape is a bus ticket
to Bogota, Medellin or the like. Hoping to find work in the
relative peace of the cities, many stumble from the crisis of the
countryside into lives of poverty and homelessness.
</P>
<P>
   Few can find work; Colombia is now enduring its worst economic
crisis of the last 70 years, with official unemployment topping 20
percent and unofficial estimates ranging up to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to living in the city,'' Barahona said recently
as she stood aimlessly outside a building she has occupied with
more than 100 other displaced people. ``I feel trapped here. Where
I lived before, I knew everybody. Here, the rich people walk past
and insult us. We want to work and get on with our lives, but there
are no jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Barahona now spends her days looking for work, applying for
government assistance and hoping something will happen. Her nights
are spent reliving the terror of the past few years, longing for a
home she fears she will never see again.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second of August, 1998, the guerrillas arrived and
there was a terrible shoot-out,'' she said. ``The paramilitaries
were dug in beside our house and the shooting went on for hours. It
started at 2 a.m. and went on until the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Huddling in her house with her children, Barahona eventually
escaped during a lull in the shooting, running for the nearby
woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back two days later and everything from the store and
restaurant was stolen,'' she said. ``I saw more than 40 dead,
guerrillas and paramilitary.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocked townspeople buried their dead and tried to go on, but
the war wouldn't leave them alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Nov. 3, the guerrillas came again and they killed three
young boys they said were accomplices of the paramilitaries,'' she
said. ``They told us then to leave or die. We left with just the
clothes we were wearing.''
</P>
<P>
   After living several months in a nearby town, Barahona returned
to Mapiripan yet again when she heard that things had quieted down.
This time she stayed until the guerrillas returned in October 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted my three oldest children,'' she said. ``They
wanted them to join the fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   This time she fled all the way to Bogota, only to find thousands
of other refugees like herself, homeless and desperate for work.
</P>
<P>
   Barahona knows little of plans by Colombia's President, Andres
Pastrana, to fight the drug lords _ and the guerrillas that prey on
them _ with nearly $2 billion in foreign aid _ more than $1 billion
from the United States. She doesn't know that critics fear the
plans will just lead to a huge new wave of displacement of poor
peasants like herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fear is that this plan will make the war intensify and
will create more forced displacement,'' said Salazar, the human
rights investigator. ``It's a military plan that does very little
in the way of social investment that is needed to fight the
underlying causes of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Barahona hopes only to find work, a home, some way out of the
living nightmare her life has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no place to go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' E-mail address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1535EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-$ADV3     07-25 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAP-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KIDNAPPINGS BECOMING NEW FACT OF LIFE IN COLOMBIA
 &HT;    (900&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With chart data attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With COLOMBIA-INTRO-$ADV30; COLOMBIA-DISPLACED-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sun. July 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ The families arrive each Friday afternoon,
standing quietly in the dim hallway of Radio Nacional de Colombia,
faces etched with sadness and tension.
</P>
<P>
   Most clutch handwritten notes they will soon read into the
microphone, while others cluster in a corner or near the stairway,
whispering among themselves and scribbling words of hope tinged
with pain.
</P>
<P>
   Torn by civil war, drug trafficking and a terrible crime wave,
Colombia has the highest kidnapping rate in the world, with nearly
3,000 reported victims last year.
</P>
<P>
   The crime has become so common in this nation of 39 million that
several radio stations now broadcast messages each week from
families hoping to reach their missing loved-ones. Many may never
know if the messages are heard, but they come anyway because they
don't know what else to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps because you feel you are doing something,'' said
Deisy Gonzalez Castillo, 30, a Bogota lawyer whose uncle was
kidnapped in April. ``We never thought this would happen to us. It
leaves you so upset. You can't eat or sleep and you get
bad-tempered. You just want to go outside and run away.''
</P>
<P>
   While the drug war and the civil war have paralyzed parts of
Colombia, the wave of kidnapping _ an average of eight people per
day _ has touched nearly everyone here: rich and poor, rural
peasants and the urban middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become a business,'' said Olga Lucia Gomez, a
psychologist who works with ``Pais Libre'' _ ``Free Country'' _ a
group that aids families of the victims and has organized a
national campaign against kidnapping. ``But the impact is brutal.
It's like ripples in a pond when you throw in a stone. The victim
is damaged, his family is damaged, their friends are damaged and
all of society is damaged. It breaks down trust and creates
chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the crimes are committed by Colombia's leftist
guerrilla and right-wing paramilitary groups, which use the ransoms
to fund their armies. Common criminals also nab people, often
selling their victims to the guerrillas or paramilitaries.
</P>
<P>
   Ransoms range from a few hundred dollars to hundreds of
thousands. Families are forced to sell their homes and businesses
and borrow every peso they can find, while businesses are extorted
for the return of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Most shocking to many is that of the 2,945 kidnap victims in
1999, 7 percent were children.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's government has recently made the kidnapping of
children a major issue in its talks with the leading guerrilla
group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. The
group's leaders have denied taking children, but defend kidnapping
as a legitimate means to fund their 36-year-old insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Deisy Castillo family is typical of the victims. Her uncle,
Silvio Castillo, wasn't a guerilla or a paramilitary. He wasn't
political at all, and he certainly wasn't rich.
</P>
<P>
   A truck driver, he was on a routine trip from Bogota to Medellin
to deliver auto parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A jeep cut him off and men got out with guns,'' said Deisy
Castillo. ``Another driver who was ahead of him saw it happen. We
have heard nothing from Silvio or the kidnappers since he was
taken. They never found his truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Families often wait for months before a ransom note arrives _ a
tactic that increases the pressure, leaving them desperate and
willing to pay whatever it takes to recover their loved one.
</P>
<P>
   Many report their loss to the National Police, but often little
can be done but wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't express the pain you're feeling, and how can you
expect anyone to understand?'' said Sylvia Lopez, 36, whose brother
Jorge disappeared in May 1999 while driving a delivery route in
Bogota. ``These kidnappers are people without hearts or
consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are happy moments when families are reunited. Just
recently, the radio station was buoyed by visits from four released
victims, who came to encourage the families with loved ones still
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept me with a rope around my neck and my hands tied, all
day and all night,'' said Nidia Velazco, who was held for six
months. ``It was the FARC. They didn't treat me badly, but they
watched us and kept us tied up even when we went to the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colombian government estimates that in 1999 68 percent of
kidnapping victims were released after ransoms were paid, 26
percent were rescued and 6 percent were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Velazco was kept in a house in the mountains outside Bogota with
several other victims. Meeting with the wives of two kidnapped men
after her release, she gave them encouraging details, describing
their health, eating habits and long hair from months without
visiting a barber.
</P>
<P>
   The wives of the missing men listened intently to every detail,
often laughing and making jokes. But the warm scene was etched with
uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, the psychologist, worries that the crime has become so
common that Colombians now simply accept it as a normal part of
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks it's just the rich who are the -----------
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAPPINGS: A New Fact of Life in Colombia
</P>
<P>
   Number of Kidnappings in Colombia:
</P>
<P>
   1990: 1,282.
</P>
<P>
   1991: 1,717.
</P>
<P>
   1992: 1,320.
</P>
<P>
   1993: 1,014.
</P>
<P>
   1994: 1,293.
</P>
<P>
   1995: 1,158.
</P>
<P>
   1996: 1,042.
</P>
<P>
   1997: 1,687.
</P>
<P>
   1998: 2,887.
</P>
<P>
   1999: 2,945.
</P>
<P>
   Source: La Semana newsmagazine and ``Pais Libre.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
