<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2571 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE REAL CULPRITS BEHIND UNITED'S FLIGHT DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The angry quotes are predictable from business
and vacation travelers stranded or delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Someone with a notebook or microphone asks what the travelers
think of the particular labor action _ by pilots, flight attendants
or maintenance workers _ that CAUSED their delayed or canceled
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't print (or put on TV) what I think,'' is the general
hostile theme. ``I don't care what their complaints are. Right now,
I think they should all be fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Just once, I'd love to hear the question asked from a different
point of view. For example:
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think of the invisible corporate management team
that has CAUSED your delay _ those high-paid folks who have dragged
their feet for months, engaging in half-baked negotiations and
knowing full-well that X,000 pilots (or flight attendants or
mechanics) are coming to the end of their labor contract?''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, it would be refreshing to hear BOTH sides of a
labor dispute get dissed for wrecking the travel plans of thousands
of ``consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it takes two entities to cause a labor dispute, two
to lead to a strike or work slow-down.
</P>
<P>
   But in so many labor-management fights, the only side that gets
blamed is the one whose members are out in public, not the one
whose proponents sit in board rooms and behind closed mahogany
doors.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the public villains have been the pilots and
mechanics of United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   All U.S. airlines have had a rough summer because of unusually
bad weather and high jet fuel costs, but United has been in the
news the most often.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the most recent month for which the Department of
Transportation has figures, United's on-time performance was a
dismal 57 percent. In nearly every news report in print or the
electronic media, most of the blame has been heaped on United's
pilots and maintenance crews.
</P>
<P>
   Since April 12, pilots have refused to work overtime, sending
the airline's complex scheduling into low-grade crisis. Since July
12, mechanics have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   United's pilots have been working without a contract since April
12; the mechanics' contract expired July 12. Most news reports
contain but a throwaway line about this, as though an expired
contract were insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   An expired contract means employees continue working under the
same conditions _ for the same money and benefits _ they've worked
under for the past several years. It means a kind of financial
freeze, but one that's good news for company management while it
penalizes union employees.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, UAL Corp. will settle on new contracts with its
pilots and maintenance workers, no doubt giving raises to members
of both unions. In the ensuing months, however, management will be
using that large chunk of salary increase cash to make money.
United's pilots and mechanics meanwhile will be in economic statis,
paying their bills from salaries they negotiated years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, United is in the throes of a typical
labor-management tug of war. Corporate execs are playing it smart
by delaying a final contract and the unions are using a classic
labor tool to try to force management to settle _ i.e., refusing to
work overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Although United is an employee-owned airline, it is a public
company, and 45 percent of its stock is owned by non-employees.
United's second-quarter earnings were technically down from last
year _ $336 million from $637 million _ but the 1999 figure
includes a one-time only gain of $428 million from United's sale of
its holdings in another company.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: UAL Corp.'s second-quarter earnings were up from
$244 million last year to $374 million this year. Second-quarter
revenue increased from $4.54 billion to $5.11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In May, UAL announced a multibillion-dollar plan to take over
the nation's sixth-largest airline, U.S. Airways. Conveniently, its
president, Rakesh Gangwal, is a former United executive who worked
closely for years with United's president, Rono Dutto. Both men
went to the same university in India. Gangwal got his master's
degree in business administration from Wharton, Dutto took his at
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Next time your United flight gets delayed or cancelled, why not
add Rono and Rakesh to the list of folks who've CAUSED your
inconvenience? It's only fair.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
