<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-PIZZA-     07-25 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-PIZZA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMALIST PIZZA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 2nd take contains recipes.) 
 By   MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like pasta, pizza is one of the easiest meals to make fast and
vary endlessly. If you skip the usual cooked tomato sauce on top,
pizza seems even simpler. Just start with raw ingredients,
especially the fresh herbs and vegetables of summer, augmented by a
little richness, like cheese or sausage.
</P>
<P>
   There may be more possible combinations of pizza toppings than
moves in chess or atoms in the universe, but I've found that using
the fewest components works best. Too many ingredients merely muddy
the flavors. Just zucchini, sausage and garlic, for example, will
deliver intense but clear tastes.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest pizzas begin with basic combinations: olive oil and
salt with rosemary and minced garlic, chopped onions or chopped
shallots; freshly grated Parmesan with sage; shallots with olive
oil and thyme; chopped basil with garlic and oil.
</P>
<P>
   Sliced tomatoes, mozzarella and basil also fall into the basic
category, but even that mix can be varied with great results. Green
tomatoes are good companions for Parmesan and basil.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh toppings should never be too wet or the dough will become
soggy. Fresh tomatoes should be seeded and drained; other moist
vegetables like zucchini should be thinly sliced and salted and
left to drain so they exude some liquid. Toppings that are too dry
are liable to fall off, though that's not an issue with these. It's
unlikely that you'll be eating pizza you make yourself while
walking down the street, and you can handle dry pizzas pretty
efficiently with a plate, knife and fork. Some people think all
pizzas have to have cheese to bind the other ingredients, but this
is ridiculously limiting.
</P>
<P>
   Corn kernels, freshly cut off the cob, make a crunchy topping
with shredded arugula and diced bacon; the bacon helps the other
ingredients adhere to the crust. Black olives add a twist to a
typical tomato topping.
</P>
<P>
   As for the dough, there are three ways to produce it (by
machine, by hand, by shopping) and three ways to cook it (on a
baking sheet or a pizza stone in the oven, or on the grill). In
every case, a very high temperature is essential for the best
crust. Professional pizza ovens cook at 700 degrees or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Using the food processor is quick and efficient, but you can
also make the dough by hand; it's not difficult. I use instant
yeast because it works much better than the regular kind. Or you
can buy dough, either in the supermarket (usually in the freezer;
use white bread dough if specially prepared pizza dough isn't
available) or from a local pizza shop (just ask; you'll usually be
accommodated).
</P>
<P>
   The dough can be mixed from an hour to two or three days before
you want to cook the pizzas. You can also keep dough for weeks in
the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Like nearly identical bread dough, pizza dough is best when it
is moist and a little sticky, so use flour judiciously. The dough
should be allowed to rest, especially before and during the final
shaping, although you can cut corners.
</P>
<P>
   If you are patient, and stretch the dough a little bit at a
time, you can produce a thin crust without tearing it. Small pizzas
are easier to handle than large ones, especially if you're
grilling. If necessary, grill or bake the pies sequentially, eating
one while the second is still cooking. Or serve them at room
temperature, as is commonly done in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   An oven lined with a baking stone (or several uncoated quarry
tiles) is ideal for baking pizza, but it requires a flat sheet of
wood or metal with a long handle, called a peel, to move the pizza
about. A baking sheet, with or without a lip, is easier to use,
because you can press the dough right onto it and get the thinnest
crust. Olive oil, on the pan and on your hands, will prevent
sticking.
</P>
<P>
   Grilling pizza is easier than you might think; the dough never
sticks to the grill, and it develops lovely grill marks, a crisp
crust and good flavor.
</P>
<P>
   To do it, start a medium-hot charcoal or wood fire, or preheat a
gas grill to the maximum. Roll or lightly press a ball of risen
pizza dough into a flat round, lightly flouring the work surface
and the dough only as necessary. Let the dough sit a few minutes,
and then roll or pat it out as thin as you like, turning
occasionally and sprinkling the top with flour as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Slide the crust directly onto the grill. Cook until brown grill
marks appear, about three to five minutes. Flip the dough over with
a spatula or tongs, lay on whatever topping you choose, cover the
grill and cook until the bottom is crisp and brown and the topping
is hot.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a pizza stone built into your oven, shape and top
the dough right on the peel, and then slide it into the oven. The
timing is about the same as for pizza cooked on a baking sheet, or
perhaps just a bit shorter.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   FOUR-CHEESE PIZZA WITH BASIL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pizza dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded or cubed mozzarella
</P>
<P>
   { cup shredded or cubed fontina or taleggio
</P>
<P>
   { cup freshly grated pecorino Romano
</P>
<P>
   { cup freshly grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   { cup coarsely chopped or torn basil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Top dough with all cheeses. Bake about 10 minutes, or until
nearly done. Sprinkle with basil and finish baking.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA WITH TOMATOES, ONIONS AND OLIVES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Pizza dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 medium red onion or 4 shallots, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   20 black olives like calamata, pitted and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil as needed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Core tomatoes, then cut in half horizontally. Gently squeeze
out liquid and shake out most seeds, then slice tomatoes as thin as
possible. Salt lightly and let sit at least 10 minutes, then drain
off any excess liquid.
</P>
<P>
   3. Top pizza rounds on baking sheet with tomatoes, onions,
olives and a little olive oil. Bake for about 15 minutes, or until
nicely browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller pizzas. GREEN TOMATO
PIZZA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 large or 4 small green tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Pizza dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup freshly grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   { cup coarsely chopped or torn basil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thinly slice tomatoes, salt lightly and let sit at least 20
minutes, then drain off any accumulated liquid.
</P>
<P>
   3. Top pizza rounds with tomato slices and Parmesan. Bake about
10 minutes, or until nearly done. Sprinkle with basil and cook
until done.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   ZUCCHINI-SAUSAGE PIZZA  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 small or 2 large zucchini
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Pizza dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 sweet Italian sausages, meat removed from the casing and
crumbled
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thinly slice zucchini, salt lightly and let sit at least 20
minutes, then drain off any accumulated liquid.
</P>
<P>
   3. Top pizza rounds with zucchini, sausage and garlic and bake
about 15 minutes, or until nicely browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA WITH ARUGULA, CORN AND BACON  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Pizza dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   6 cups loosely packed arugula, measured after washing, drying
and shredding
</P>
<P>
   Kernels from 4 ears of corn
</P>
<P>
   { cup minced bacon.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   2. Top prepared pizza rounds with arugula, corn and bacon. Bake
about 15 minutes, or until nicely browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller pizzas.
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA DOUGH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour or more
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose or bread flour, plus more as needed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons instant yeast, such as SAF-Instant Yeast.
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons coarse sea or kosher salt, plus extra for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   1 to 1\ cups water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. If using a food processor, combine flour, yeast and salt in
work bowl. Turn machine on and add 1 cup water and the oil through
the feed tube. Process 30 seconds, adding up to \ cup more water, a
little at a time, until mixture forms a ball and is slightly sticky
to the touch. (In unlikely event mixture is too sticky, add flour,
a tablespoon at a time.) To make dough by hand, combine half the
flour with the yeast and salt in a bowl and stir to blend. Add 1
cup water and the olive oil; stir with a wooden spoon until smooth.
Add remaining flour bit at a time; when mixture becomes too stiff
to stir with a spoon, begin kneading, adding as little remaining
flour as possible, just enough to keep dough from being sticky
mess. Knead 5 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn dough onto a floured work surface and knead by hand a
few seconds to form a smooth, round ball. Transfer to a bowl and
cover with plastic wrap; let rise until doubled in size, 1 to 2
hours. (You can cut rising time if you are in a hurry, or you can
let dough rise more slowly in refrigerator for 6 to 8 hours.) Dough
can then be used immediately or wrapped tightly in plastic wrap and
frozen for a month. Defrost in covered bowl in refrigerator or at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. Form risen dough into a ball and divide into two or more
pieces; roll each into a ball. Place each on a lightly floured
surface, sprinkle with a little flour, and cover with plastic wrap
or a towel. Let rest until slightly puffed, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Oil one or more baking sheets, then press each dough ball
into a flat round directly on sheet. Pat out dough as thin as you
like, using oiled hands if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   5. Proceed with any recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Enough dough for 1 large, 2 medium, or more smaller
pizzas.
</P>
</TEXT>
