<HEADER>
A2595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAY-LEWIS-HNS &LR;      07-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAY-LEWIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEWIS HAD SUPPORT OF TEAM DURING MURDER TRIAL ORDEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM ORSBORN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTMINSTER, Md. _ Ray Lewis is understandably reluctant to talk
about what it was like living as an accused murderer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, we're in the first day of training camp,'' the Ravens
linebacker said Monday. ``Let's just talk about football.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there is one aspect of his ordeal that he will discuss.
With a smile and a look of peace, he will tell you that teammate
Shannon Sharpe held him together while he was being tried for
murder in connection with two stabbing deaths during a post-Super
Bowl brawl outside an Atlanta nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a blessing,'' Lewis said of having the former
Broncos star on hand during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, who lives in Atlanta during the off-season, came to
Lewis' aid shortly after learning of the charges against his friend
_ and before the Pro Bowl tight end signed with the Baltimore
Ravens on Feb. 22 as an unrestricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shannon is a friend who's been around for a long time,''
Lewis, 24, said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to keep Lewis' mind off the trial, Sharpe convinced
the former Miami Hurricane that he should spend his free time in
Atlanta working out rather than worrying about his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I was leaving the courtroom, I was going to
(Sharpe's) house and working out,'' Lewis said. ``My mind was never
on (the trial). That's what kept me settled. We worked and worked
and worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' nightmare finally ended last month when prosecutors
dropped all murder charges against him in return for a guilty plea
to a misdemeanor charge of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   But the end of the trial did not mean the end of Sharpe's
involvement with Lewis. Sharpe, a 10-year NFL veteran with 662
career receptions, tried his best after the trial to convince Lewis
that he needed to make better choices and stay out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ray is young, but I've also told Ray, at some point, you can't
use age as an excuse,'' Sharpe, 32, said. ``I told him, at some
point, people are going to start to say, `Maybe the decisions that
he makes are a reflection of the person, instead of the age being a
reflection of the decisions he makes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you have to be accountable. (I told him),
`You've got your one strike. Learn from it, and let's move on.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, after running some post-practice wind sprints with
Sharpe, Lewis sounded like a man happy to have received a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful to wake up every morning,'' Lewis said. ``That's
what I feel joy about.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sharpe: ``He realizes he made a mistake, and he's going to
learn from it. I can imagine how happy he is. Spending the rest of
your life in prison is no joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe hasn't been the only Raven to openly support Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition for Ray to come back was very easy because of
the fact that he has so much support from the team,'' said running
back Priest Holmes. ``We welcomed him with open arms, and we were
waiting for him when he came back to practice in June. We rallied
around him and supported him and gave him as much attention as we
could.''
</P>
<P>
   Said cornerback Rod Woodson: ``We're just happy it's over for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his off-season troubles, Lewis is expected to have
another big season. The three-time Pro Bowl choice led the NFL in
tackles the past two seasons and has been Baltimore's leader in
stops the past four campaigns. Led by Lewis' 167 tackles, the
Ravens finished second in the league in total defense, surrendering
263.9 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus this season is to be No. 1 in defense, period,''
said Lewis, in the second year of a four-year, $26 million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ravens coach Brian Billick: ``I think, quite frankly, that
we have the best defense in the league. I can't think of another
unit that I would trade for.''
</P>
<P>
   Billick and his players expect a banner season. The Ravens, who
finished last season in third place in the tough AFC Central with
an 8-8 record, strengthened themselves during the off-season by
acquiring Sharpe and tight end Ben Coates and drafting Tennessee
running back Jamal Lewis and Florida wide receiver Travis Taylor in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations here are high,'' Billick said. ``Anything
less than a playoff appearance will be considered a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
