<HEADER>
A2598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN26-CO     07-25 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Baseball park's demise like losing
a loved one
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Don Gardner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Special to Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGH POINT, N.C. _ Dad and I attended almost all the games at
Finch Field after World War II to see our beloved Hi-Toms play
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   I could hardly wait for him to come home and eat dinner so we
could pile into the truck and go to the game.
</P>
<P>
   I remember how I always ran up the steps of the grandstand ahead
of dad, anxious to see the players and drink in the scene with one
quick, exciting gulp.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the sounds of balls smacking gloves and the sharp
crack of a bat followed by the sudden roar from the fans as a
batter drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the pleasant smell of grass, freshly mowed before the
game, and shelling roasted peanuts and putting them in my bottle of
Pepsi.
</P>
<P>
   There was the one glorious year the scoreboard had a large
mechanical goose, and how everyone laughed and cheered as she
slowly waddled along, squawking dramatically over the p.a. system
as she laid an ``egg'' each inning the opposition failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same year our bat boy was named Egolly. Whenever he
went onto the field to deliver baseballs to the umpire, the fans
shouted, ``By golly, there's Egolly.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that happened a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many years later after a career in the Coast Guard, my wife and
I moved to High Point. After settling in, I revisited Finch Field.
</P>
<P>
   I knew a professional baseball team had not played there for
more than a decade, but I wasn't prepared for what I saw.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous small, dingy industrial shops occupied what once had
been the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Entire sections of rusty outfield fence had fallen, and tall
weeds covered the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   The light poles seemed to stand as patient beacons, waiting
forlornly to be illuminated again for a night game.
</P>
<P>
   Peeling paint exposed countless scabs and scars in the wooden
grandstand, which looked tired and worn, as if ready to give up the
ghost.
</P>
<P>
   I felt vaguely embarrassed to be here as the scene etched itself
forever into my heart.
</P>
<P>
   Finch Field had once been a special place for me, but now I felt
I was standing at the grave of a loved one.
</P>
<P>
   Reliving long-ago memories, to see the changes and disfigurement
that time has wrought, is often bitingly painful.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been a wonderful miracle to be 17 years old once
more, at least for a day, and to see another baseball game at Finch
Field.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether the tears were for Finch Field or for me as
I drove quickly away.
</P>
<P>
   Don Gardner, a former senior chief radioman who retired from the
Coast Guard after 20 years, lives in High Point. N.C.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(AT)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
