<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2610 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-HUECOTANKS-CLIMBING-T     07-25 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUECOTANKS-CLIMBING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS PARK LOSES APPEAL FOR CLIMBERS AS STATE PROTECTS ANCIENT
DRAWINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HANNA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Hueco Tanks State Historical Park was considered a
rock-climbing mecca, once attracting enthusiasts from as far as
Europe, only a few now scale its cliffs and boulders.
</P>
<P>
   And, avid climber Jeffrey Drucker is moving away.
</P>
<P>
   Drucker, a physics professor at nearby University of Texas at El
Paso, says the state's clampdown on access at the far West Texas
park _ to protect ancient cave drawings _ was a factor in his
departure for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as rock climbers are concerned, Hueco Tanks has ceased
to be a rock climbing destination,'' Drucker said. ``We have tried
every avenue known to us and have failed utterly. I suspect it's
all over but the crying. They just don't trust people in that park.
They've made the choice of preservation at any cost over
recreation.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, Texas Parks and Wildlife restricted visitors
at the 860-acre park, 32 miles east of El Paso, to protect the rock
art and sacred American Indian sites on its grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Historical preservationists had wanted tighter restrictions to
preserve pictographs, some of which have been defaced by graffiti.
Arrowheads and spear heads in the park date back 10 millienia,
according to The Handbook of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The artwork's spiritual value was so unique to Native Americans
that the Texas Historical Commission's first archaeologist, Curtis
Tunnell, compared Hueco Tanks to the Sistine Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Parks and Wildlife revised the park's rules this month,
allowing a few more visitors and the return of overnight camping,
which was expected to begin this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But the restrictions against climbers, including being monitored
by guides, have not been lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go there if you follow the rules, but you are still
extremely limited,'' said Mike Lewis, a 40-year-old San Antonio
climber. ``You have to get a reservation, which isn't easy. Then
you have to find a guide who may not be able to go when you can.
And then a majority of the areas you want to climb are restricted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes it frustrating is there is no evidence that the
climbers caused any damage or vandalism to the rock art,'' Lewis
added.
</P>
<P>
   John Moses, Hueco Tanks park manager, said the rules aren't
meant to single out climbers but simply to protect the rock art
that dates back centuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take off on your own and go climbing,'' Moses said.
``I think that's a little too civilized for some people. We have
some of the same problems with Native American groups who don't
want certified guides or rangers going along with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Access Fund, a Boulder, Colo.-based climbing advocacy group,
proposed last month to donate $100,000 to Hueco Tanks as part of a
cooperative agreement. But ``we were flatly rejected,'' said Sally
Moser, the group's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The money would have been used not only to build trails and
protect rock art but also to help re-open some sites on a test
basis to climbers, Moser said. In a June 30 letter, Walter Dabney,
director of the state parks division, said he could not support the
agreement ``that would allow climbing in areas outside of North
Mountain without the presence of a tour guide.''
</P>
<P>
   The park has a staff of seven and a list of 30 guides. The 1998
restrictions allowed up to 210 visitors at any one time. That limit
has been raised to 230.
</P>
<P>
   Moses, the park ranger, said that the rules are applied equally
and that he cannot exempt climbers.
</P>
<P>
   For many rock climbers, Hueco Tanks is not worth the trouble
despite the world-class terrain, Lewis said. Most Central Texas
climbers now prefer mountain sites near Monterrey, Mexico, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you have to put up with the hassles of Mexico and crossing
the border but that's still easier than the restrictions at Hueco
Tanks,'' Lewis added.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Todsen, a Las Cruces, N.M., archaeologist and park volunteer
who studied the Hueco Tanks rock art for years, said the
restrictions are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the climbers' complaints, for the most part, don't
really have a lot of validity,'' said Todsen, 57. ``It is really an
archaeological park. I think a lot of the climbers are very
conscientious but there is a fringe element that would just as soon
eliminate the rock art so they could go climbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Todsen said rock art that had been obscured by charcoal residue
is reappearing in one place in the park.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
