<SLUG> BC-NAPSTER-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING TODAY COULD MEAN NAPSTER SHUTDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in San Francisco is set to hear
arguments Wednesday in the recording industry's request for a
preliminary injunction against Napster, the controversial
music-swapping service. The closely watched case is expected to
have dramatic implications for the future of how consumers buy and
listen to music. The judge could rule that Napster is guilty of
copyright infringement and opt to shut the service down
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing comes as Napster is scrambling to establish itself
as a legitimate music-sampling business that respects artists'
rights and spurs CD sales. At a digital music conference in New
York, Napster CEO Hank Barry said that the company is working to
figure out a way to compensate artists when their works are traded
on Napster. ``The question is, `Where would we send the check?' ''
he said Monday at the Jupiter Communications Plug-In conference.
</P>
<P>
   Barry's remarks came after Time Warner president Richard D.
Parsons lambasted Napster, invoking the language of the Cold War
and likening the service to hijackers, pirates, and the devil.
Paraphrasing the words of President John F. Kennedy, Parsons vowed
that Time Warner and the recording industry would ``pay any price
and bear any burden . . . to protect the copyrights of their
artists.'' At the same time, he admitted that the major record
labels have been ``asleep at the switch'' and needed to act quickly
to offer digital music distribution over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Barry said that he is still trying to settle with the record
labels, but added that the company will comply if the judge pulls
the plug. The case is being heard by US District Court Judge
Marilyn Patel, the same judge who ruled earlier this year that
another Internet company, MP3.com, was guilty of copyright
infringement in a separate case.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources expect that Napster will ultimately lose the
case but that the record labels will likely develop their own
music-sharing services. ``Napster is the sacrificial lamb, and
probably rightly so,'' said Marc Geiger, CEO of Artist Direct, an
Internet music company. ``But file sharing is here to stay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
