<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NIEMAN-GILES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILES NAMED CURATOR OF NIEMAN FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Nieman Foundation curator Robert Giles says he intends to
build on his predecessor Bill Kovach's ``wonderful efforts to
elevate the standards of journalism'' as he takes the reins at the
nation's most prestigious journalism fellowship program.
</P>
<P>
   Giles, 67, a senior vice president at the Freedom Forum, was
named curator Tuesday. The announcement by Harvard University
followed a bruising process that included a lobbying campaign by
unions angered by what they described as Giles's divisive role in
the Detroit newspaper strike when he was editor and publisher of
The Detroit News. Giles supporters, including a number of prominent
newspaper editors, countered with a lobbying campaign on his
behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it, I think, fairly philosophically,'' said Giles of
the controversy over his candidacy. ``One of the values of
journalism that is very important to me is freedom of expression. I
think Harvard gave (my critics') concerns a lot of careful
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Harvard president Neil Rudenstine said that
``with all the forces acting today on the field of journalism, a
program such as the Nieman has more to contribute than ever. I am
confident that Bob Giles is the right person to lead it at this
stage of its work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
