<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MYJOB-TASTER-NYT &LR;      07-25 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MYJOB-TASTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I SAY IT TASTES LIKE SPINACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Gail Vance Civille is a professional taster and president of
Sensory Spectrum, Inc., Chatham, N.J.; this was written with Julia
Lawlor.)  
 By GAIL VANCE CIVILLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the house where I grew up in Brooklyn, food was a
religion. Christmas dinner would last four hours. You'd have the
appetizer, talk about it, have another course, talk some more. You
were aware of not just what went into the meal, but what the
textures were supposed to be like, why one dish was better than
another.
</P>
<P>
   I graduated with a degree in chemistry, then took a job at
General Foods, now Kraft Foods, in the sensory-product evaluation
group. I worked on Jell-O, Minute Rice, Cool Whip. Finally I was
trained to be a coffee taster. Just to be asked to do that is a big
deal. Wine and fine fragrances are the most difficult things to
evaluate; then come coffee and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I ever tasted at General Foods, the group leader
said: ``Here are three samples of Jell-O. We think there might be a
problem with one.'' They all tasted like red Jell-O to me. I looked
up, and everyone was writing furiously. I thought: this must be a
hazing. They finished and started to talk about ethyl maltol. I
thought, ``Ethel who?'' Ethyl maltol is the chemical flavor in
strawberry cotton candy. It's very sweet. Every other person in the
group said the second sample tasted like wet wool, wet sweater, wet
dog, wet fur. The reason was that the second sample was made with
gelatin that wasn't clean; it had an animal-fur note. I was so
depressed. I couldn't detect defective gelatin, and I thought my
career was over. I tell people this story when they're starting out
in the field, just to say: ``Hang in there. You'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   When you evaluate food, you pay attention to what you feel on
the tongue _ bitterness, sourness, sweetness, saltiness. There are
also chemical feelings _ cooling, metallic, astringent, nasal
pungency (like horseradish). Smell is the hardest. When I train
people, I have them smell vials of chemicals or flavors _ orange,
mint, cinnamon, oregano, clove, strawberry. If I'm tasting coffee,
for instance, in the nose I might perceive fruity or winy, the
roasted character, whether it's nutty or woody _ those are the
positive notes. Negative notes would be cereal (caused by the
inferior robusta bean), rubbery, burnt.
</P>
<P>
   I've been doing this for 35 years, and I never get bored. It's a
sensory jolt every day. Tasting or smelling is like anthropology or
archaeology. You're watching to see what unfolds in a product,
discovering new things. But there is a limit to how much tasting
you can do. I could probably taste 10 coffees in an hour, but only
3 salsas and one toothpaste. In a week I probably do about 10 to 15
hours of evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 300 professional tasters in the United States,
and we consider it unprofessional not to evaluate something just
because you don't like it. I hate cinnamon _ as a child, I got sick
on cinnamon candy _ but I can taste it. I don't like sea slugs;
they're chewy and slimy. But every time I go to Japan, I try them.
</P>
<P>
   Because I'm so critical about food, people don't want to invite
me home for dinner. I just tell them to roast a chicken and steam
some vegetables, and I'll be happy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1605EDT &QL; 
