<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIR-DELAYS26-COX     07-25 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-DELAYS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR DELAYS RISE 58 PERCENT IN FIVE YEARS, FEDERAL REPORT SAYS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ROB O'DELL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One in every five airplane flights in the United
States is delayed, according to a federal report issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued by the Department of Transportation's
inspector general,
</P>
<P>
   also said that since 1995 there has been an increase in both the
number of flight delays and cancellations and in the average length
of a delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we don't have a uniform measure to track delays, the
Federal Aviation Administration reported an 58 percent increase in
delays from 1995 to 1999 _ and even more troubling _ flight
cancellations increased 68 percent over the same time,'' said
Inspector General Kenneth M. Mead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most delays are occurring on the ground, and the number of
flights experiencing a taxi-out time of at least one hour increased
a staggering 130 percent,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport was cited for having
the fourth worst increase in flight cancellations between 1995 and
1999, at 138 percent. The total cost to the airlines of flight
delays at Hartsfield in 1999 was estimated at $250.9 million, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of flights at Hartsfield in which planes spent more
than one hour taxiing on the runway rose to 2,445 in 1999, an 111
percent increase from 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's O'Hare airport had more than twice as many flights
that taxied for more than an hour as Hartsfield. The number of
flights that taxied for more than four hours at O'Hare was 57,
compared to two at Hartsfield.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials also noted that flight operations at Atlanta were
less affected by poor weather than the two other airports with the
most flights analyzed in the study, Dallas-Ft. Worth and O'Hare.
</P>
<P>
   The precise number of flight delays nationwide is undetermined
because the two major agencies collecting data _ the FAA and the
Bureau of Transportation Statistics _ use different methods, Mead
told the transportation subcommittee of the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two agencies is more than 1.7 million
delayed flights, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA's statistics do not report flight delays that are
caused by the airlines, it only reports delays that occur after the
plane comes into the FAA's control,'' Mead said. ``In addition,
according to the BTS, a flight is considered on time if it departed
or arrived within 15 minutes of schedule, meaning the plane could
taxi on the runway for four hours and still not be considered
delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kragh(CQ), an air traffic controller from Newark's
airport, said that the airlines ``pad'' their schedules with extra
time for flights so as not to adversely affect their on-time
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, a flight from Washington, D.C., to Atlanta takes
a little over an hour in actual flight time, but the airlines
schedule the flight to last two hours because they know the runways
will be overbooked on departure and/or arrival,'' Kragh testified.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the subcommittee, said
the airlines and the FAA need to cooperate to find an answer as to
what is causing the increased delays and cancellations of flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines blame the FAA and the air traffic controllers for
mismanaging the national airspace system, while the FAA blames bad
weather, aircraft equipment problems, and outdated technology, and
the air traffic controllers point the finger at the airlines for
scheduling so many flights at the same time during peak hours,''
Shelby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there is probably validity to all of these points of
views, passengers know the simple truth that air travel is costly,
unpleasant, and less reliable than they would like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: www.faa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Air Traffic Controllers Association: www.natca.org
</P>
<P>
   Rob O'Dell's e-mail is rodell(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
