<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2616 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     07-25 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN I COULDN'T SAY WHAT I WANTED TO SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month I watched Texas Rangers manager Johnny Oates
give umpire Tony Randazzo a tongue-lashing because of the way he
was calling balls and strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Oates appeared to have lost it. He jerked his head back and
forth as fast as the words coming out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Star-Telegram sportswriter T.R. Sullivan quoted Oates
in the next day's paper as saying that he had gone too far in
berating Randazzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't have done that,'' the manager was quoted as
saying. ``Tony didn't deserve that.''
</P>
<P>
   As I watched Randazzo stand tall and silent before finally
ejecting Oates, I thought to myself:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he knows exactly how a newspaper ombudsman feels
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of readers I dealt with during my years as
ombudsman of this newspaper were courteous. But there was that
small number who really put me to the test.
</P>
<P>
   They were the racists, the homophobes, those who just seemed to
enjoy hating another person or group, and those who simply did not
know what they were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, they were few.
</P>
<P>
   Often I could quickly spot them. Frequently, they would begin a
phone conversation by saying, ``I'm not a racist, but ...'' or ``I
don't hate gays, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Many spewed forth their venom while declining to identify
themselves on the phone or in writing.
</P>
<P>
   But few that they were, they still drove me to the brink of
striking back in their terms. Those who love to hate drove me over
the brink on at least two occasions. Both times I found it
necessary to call the reader back to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   We ombudsmen do not have the right to eject a reader as Randazzo
ejected Oates.
</P>
<P>
   But I did have one ground rule _ one shared by many other
ombudsmen _ concerning the rantings of the haters. When their words
became personally abusive, I would caution them that I was not
expected to take that kind of treatment. If the abuse continued, I
would hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Few were the times I was forced to do this, but there were many
times I had to restrain myself from striking back in kind in spoken
or written words.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders LaMont, the ombudsman of The Sacramento Bee, knows what
I mean.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent column he noted that those in the newspaper business
_ and other fields _ have ``developed techniques to deal politely
with the thousands of phone calls and letters they receive. Good
listening and conflict resolution skills, along with basic
politeness, are taught in every office.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned his attention to those he termed the
``hard-to-deal-with people.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMont presented a number of ``non-original responses'' that
many ombudsmen undoubtedly would love to resort to when confronted
by an abusive or uninformed reader. He said most of these have been
floating around for years, and one probably dates back to famed
journalist H.L. Mencken in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Here are LaMont's wish-we-could-use responses (and I'm sure
there are times that many of you wish you could use them):
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir. You are correct. The reason we made that mistake is
that we knew it would drive you crazy, and we wanted to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir. Thank you for calling it to our attention that the
2,000 employees of this company are all incompetent and motivated
by a desire to do a bad job, waste your time and personally make
your life miserable. We appreciate your business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir. Thank you for having the courage of your conviction
to call and let us know, anonymously, that you have a strong
command of profane language.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Madame. Thank you for the helpful critique of our
product, and the promise that you will never buy from us again no
matter what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir. Thank you for calling it to our attention that
everyone at this place of business is driven by a burning desire to
bring down democracy as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   And this is LaMont's favorite for someone who supplies a name:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Sir. I think you should be aware that some idiot is
writing letters and signing your name. You might want to
investigate to avoid legal action.''
</P>
<P>
   I would on occasion hear from a reader who was so angry _
frequently righteously _ that he or she was almost incoherent.
</P>
<P>
   I had a pretty effective response to screamers. ``Be quiet!'' I
would shoot back. ``You are so mad I'm afraid you are going to have
a heart attack, and we simply are not worth that.''
</P>
<P>
   This frequently would calm the reader down to the point where we
could have a rational discussion of the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, whose anger had turned to laughter, actually replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, you're good.''
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram and is the newspaper's professional in residence at
Texas Christian University's Department of Journalism. He can be
contacted at precord(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
