u a BC-NY-WILDLIFE-PATHOLOGI     07-25 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WILDLIFE-PATHOLOGIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A QUIET WOOD, A PATHOLOGIST UNDER SIEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELMAR, N.Y. _ Here, in the dappled woods of upstate New York on
a kiss-perfect summer day, Ward B. Stone is downstairs in the
laboratory, showing off his freezer collection.
</P>
<P>
   The walk-in model. Then the chest unit, stocked with neatly
labeled jars _ bits of brains, livers, spleens mostly. Next, a
stainless steel beauty with shelves, on wheels. ``This is the
mobile mort,'' explains Stone, 61, whose flannel shirt-sleeves are
rolled up, jeans faded, eyebrows tufted, white hair long, unruly.
``It's for dead people, but we use it for turtles.''
</P>
<P>
   In this, Stone's 32nd year as chief and only wildlife
pathologist for New York State, his freezers are crammed with
animals whose deaths will have to wait to be investigated _ victims
of illegal hunts, poisonings and pesticide ingestions among them.
It's triage time.
</P>
<P>
   This summer Stone, who works a seven-day week in normal years,
has a corpse crisis: everybody's nervous, so everybody's shipping
him their dead crows, sparrows and blue jays, about 300 a day, to
be checked for West Nile virus. He estimates finding about 50 cases
so far.
</P>
<P>
   He looks over the latest delivery. ``What's this chicken doing
here?'' grumbles Stone. ``We're not doing some veterinarian's work
for free! Next thing, everybody will be sending us their pet
parakeets.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``we'' means Stone, two assistants, a secretary and a couple
of summer interns. Now consider that in addition to the West Nile
candidates _ which, depending on a host of factors, his team may
slice, dice, type and pickle, sending tissue to a nearby lab for
testing _ the daily haul for necropsies can include bear, moose,
beaver, swans, hawks, bats and deer, deer, deer.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider that he is always running a study on pesticides;
writing scientific articles (in today's mail, acceptance letters
for two); inveighing against human-made threats to wildlife;
lumbering off to inoculate infested ducks, which cause swimmer's
itch in local lakes; testifying in court; nursing wounded animals;
and swabbing down his crematory. Stone, whose last raise lifted his
salary to $59,908, may be a touch overwhelmed. But now, for a
change, no one is trying to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all getting along,'' remarks Stone, with a dramatic eye
roll. ``At the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a file of dire letters from the many superiors he's
outlasted. (And they have plenty from him.) A darling of
environmentalists, who praise his pioneering work in detecting
pollutants like polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCB's, in wildlife,
and who rally when his job is in jeopardy, Stone turns out to be a
loud, throbbing administrative pain.
</P>
<P>
   He has leaked data to reporters, sampled landfills and
incinerator ash _ far afield from pathology, sniff specialists who
call him untrained, a meddler _ attacked popular fishing practices
like lead sinkers and embarrassed bosses at the New York State
Department of Environmental Conservation by finding traces of DDT
on the grounds of a regional office.
</P>
<P>
   But Stone, whose ancestors landed at Plymouth Colony, has a
sturdy sense of self-importance, a taskmaster's bite, a truculent
shoulder shrug and a lifelong sense of wonder about wild critters.
In wildlife pathology, Stone, who has a master's degree in zoology,
is influential, regarded as innovative but precise. So he
apologizes not.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary. ``There's always so much going on that I have a
nagging feeling I'm not doing enough,'' says Stone, leaning back in
his office chair and using his belly as an arm rest.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with a nagging feeling about those dying crows, Stone
was one of the early investigators to send samples around the
country persistently, until the deadly, mosquito-borne virus was
identified.
</P>
<P>
   About the recent public response, he has mixed emotions. The
spraying may threaten monarch butterflies and some fish, he says.
Yet West Nile threatens not only humans, he notes, but large
mammals and birds like the bald eagle and the peregrine falcon,
which have scant populations.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who grew up in rural Columbia County, tries to live
within the means dictated by his convictions and his bank account.
He has been driving the same gas-efficient car since 1992. His lawn
is green, free of pesticides, lush with weeds. With his partner,
Mary Bayham, an ecologist, he has four children under 7 (and an
adult daughter from a past marriage); he and the kids built their
swing set from road scraps. He teaches them to whittle toys,
garden, fish and stroll through streams.
</P>
<P>
   Nature, as Stone knows too well, can also be savage. Last month
he and Bayham buried their fifth child, a newborn. His grief is raw
and tear-drenched. ``I was the scientist but I had the most faith
that something could be done,'' he whispers.
</P>
<P>
   So he steeps himself in the work _ today's birds from New York
City have just arrived _ walks in the woods and attends to the
life-affirming demands of his brood.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Ward Stone, age 6, bursts into the office, announcing
that he wants to look for frogs along the trails surrounding the
Wildlife Pathology Unit. Ask him what he wants to be when he grows
up, prods his beaming father.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan?
</P>
<P>
   He is already running down the hall toward the perfect summer
day. ``A wildlife pathologist!'' echoes the reply. ``You got a
problem with that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
