<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOANS-EXEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL HAIL THE TAXI BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Andrew Murstein is president of Medallion Financial Corp., a
lender to small businesses; this was written with David
Leonhardt.)  
 By ANDREW MURSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My father and I are probably two of the only people in the
United States not to have made money in real estate in the last 20
years. In 1987, when I was getting my M.B.A., we bought 100 acres
of land in Old Westbury, N.Y. We wanted to develop luxury homes,
but the project ended up being a 12-year ordeal. It took us five
years to subdivide the land, and we didn't sell off the final lot
until last month. We barely broke even. That taught me that I
didn't know as much as I thought I did. It also reminded me of the
motto that my father has passed down to me, ``In niches, there are
riches.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, I concentrate on the businesses that I really
understand: taxis.
</P>
<P>
   My grandfather got to this country from Europe, via Argentina,
in 1923. He had $150 in his pocket, and soon after he got here, New
York City issued 11,787 taxi medallions _ the same number as there
were until just a few years ago. Back then, they cost $10 apiece.
My grandfather bought one, and he started driving a cab. In his
mind, it was one of the few jobs in which success depended only on
how hard you worked.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he had saved up enough to buy his second medallion, and by
the 1960s, he had 150. They were terrific investments _ better than
stocks. We recently figured out that since the 1930s, the Dow Jones
industrial average has gone up 11 percent a year on average, and
taxi medallions 17 percent. Today, they sell for $250,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, my father started selling off some of the
medallions to diversify. But no bank would lend money to the buyers
_ immigrants from the Soviet Union, Haiti and India _ because they
didn't have any bank statements. So he started a loan business.
We've lent over $1 billion and never had to possess a single loan
even though the interest rates are higher than on bank loans.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried to identify other niche businesses where immigrants
are active and banks are not: dry cleaners, laundromats, grocery
stores and corporate car services. We also install the ads on the
tops of cabs. We give the taxi company $50 each month, and we get
$350 from the advertisers _ a much better return than my real
estate deal. There's no question about where our focus is: our
Nasdaq symbol is TAXI.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Sotheby's auctioned off the last Checker cab
to come off the streets of New York. It had a million miles on it.
A taxi owner heard I wanted to bid on it and called me to offer
another Checker for $25,000. I said no because the Sotheby's cab
was supposed to go for about the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   So I went to the auction and opened the bidding at $20,000.
Nobody else was raising their paddle, and I thought I was going to
get it. But then a guy called in and offered $30,000. So I said 40,
and he said 50. It just kept going. It was well past the point
where I wanted to end up; but all these people were watching, so I
kept going. He said 100, I said 110, he said 130, and I stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Then the guy who had wanted to sell me the other Checker came
up, and I said, ``I'll take your cab now!'' He said: ``Oh, no. Now
it will cost you $50,000.'' So I drove with this stranger to Queens
to check it out. When we got there, right near his Checker was
another car under a sheet. It turned to be yet another Checker. It
belonged to his uncle, who lived in Florida. So I asked him to call
his uncle, and his uncle took $2,000 for it. I still ask myself why
he let me buy that one when I was ready to pay $50,000 for his. But
soon it will be on the streets of Manhattan. Anybody can have a
limo as a company car. We'll have a Checker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
