<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY FOR SLAVE LABOR ON U.S. CAPITOL?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seldom have stranger political bedfellows than Rep. John Lewis,
D-Ga., and Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., found common cause on a
controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two men share the common bond of African-American
derivation, they have been for the most part as far apart
ideologically as opposite sides of the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   It, of course, is not surprising that a liberal like Lewis would
support legislation calling for a thoroughgoing inquiry into the
use of slave labor in the construction of the U.S. Capitol. But it
is a hair short of amazing for an avowed black conservative like
Watts to be calling for the creation of a task force to explore the
facts of that glaring historical irony.
</P>
<P>
   What is even more astonishing is that Watts has indicated that
he might go so far as to endorse paying reparations to the
descendants of the slaves who worked on the Capitol, if the
genealogical connections can be proven.
</P>
<P>
   Records in the Architect of the Capitol's office reportedly
indicate that at least 400 slaves were used in the building's
construction from 1792 to 1800. Further exploration of the records,
says a recent story in USA Today, is expected to reveal that many
more worked on the project after 1800.
</P>
<P>
   That news story credits Edward Hotaling _ a Washington TV
producer who has written a book on black jockeys of the late 1800s
and early 1900s _ with the discovery of those records.
</P>
<P>
   However, TransAfrica President Randal Robinson dwelt on that
subject at length in his book ``The Debt,'' which went on sale
several months ago. Perhaps it was a case of inquiring minds
focusing on the same subject independently.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson wrote of speaking by telephone to William Allen,
Architect of the Capitol, and finding out that:
</P>
<P>
   _The U.S. government sent out an initial request for 100 slaves
for the first phase of the project in 1793 to 1802. The
slaveholders were to receive $5 per month for each slave used. The
slaves mined, loaded and transported sandstone blocks; fired and
stacked bricks; mixed the mortar; and sawed the long timbers.
</P>
<P>
   _A slave named Philip Reed cast the Statue of Freedom in bronze
and, along with other slaves, loaded its five 1-ton sections onto
reinforced wagons for the trip to the Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   They spent 39 days assembling the statue. Then they took it
apart again, hoisted it to the dome and reassembled it.
</P>
<P>
   _The Capitol was built in three phases. The second phase began
after the War of 1812. The third was under way during the Civil
War. During that war, many of the slaves who gravitated to the
Union lines were taken to Washington to work on the building. They
were classified as ``contraband slaves'' or ``spoils of war.''
</P>
<P>
   Those revelations might be dismissed as inconsequential
historical curiosities at another time. But because of the news
last week of the agreement reached between the United States and
Germany on compensation for thousands of people used as slave
laborers and forced laborers by the Third Reich, they assume a
heightened significance.
</P>
<P>
   The German government has agreed to establish a $5 billion fund
for the estimated 240,000 surviving Jewish slave laborers and the
nearly 1 million surviving non-Jewish forced laborers. The United
States will contribute $10 million to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of reparations to African-Americans for the
enslavement of their ancestors can seize upon the German
government's agreement as ammunition for their cause. Robinson's
new book is an eloquent call for such reparation. Payment of the
debt, Robinson believes, is an essential condition of racial
reconciliation in America.
</P>
<P>
   Given the enormity of the crime of 350 years of slavery,
segregation and discrimination, the size of America's debt to
African-Americans is too enormous for anyone to give any realistic
thought to paying it outright. What most realistic advocates of
reparations want is a continuation and expansion of policies and
programs aimed at helping African-Americans overcome the
disadvantages that the legacy of slavery has bequeathed to them.
</P>
<P>
   First, however, that debt must be acknowledged. The cause that
has brought John Lewis and J.C. Watts together could be an
important move in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
