   PEACE-TALKS (Washington) _ The Middle East peace summit
collapses over the status of Jerusalem. President Clinton says both
the Palestinians and Israelis had pledged to avoid violence and
unilateral actions. But later each side spoke out against the
other, Israelis vowing never to give up the city and Palestinians
insisting that they will declare their own state in September. By
GREG McDONALD and PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   PEACE-TALKS-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton made a huge
personal investment in the peace talks at Camp David and the United
States put its full diplomatic weight to bear. We look at what the
failure of the negotiations mean to the country's foreign policy
and to the lame-duck president. By GREG McDONALD
</P>
<P>
   BULLET-VESTS (Washington) _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., is
pushing legislation that would punish criminals who use
bullet-proof vests by increasing penalties for those who wear them
while committing a crime. The measure was inspired by the recent
death of a former San Francisco police officer who was shot by a
gunman wearing such a vest. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-TEXAS (Houston) _ A national study of education gives
high marks to Texas and a failing grade to California. The study
credits Texas' restrictions on class size and focus on early
childhood education. By MELANIE MARKLEY.
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (Houston) _ The Russian-made crew module for the
international space station is heading toward the linkup with the
orbiting station tonight. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ What does Dick Cheney, President
George Bush's secretary of defense, bring to the Republican ticket?
He's qualified to be president, if you like conservatives. But he
is hardly the fresh face of change that George W. Bush has been
trying to project. Cheney makes the GOP ticket look more like old
times than new ones. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
