<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2636 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     07-25 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
192-FOOT CROSS A BEACON OF HOPE TO TRAVELERS IN TEXAS PANHANDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``On a hill far away, stood an old rugged cross, the emblem of
suffering and shame.''
</P>
<P>
   _ lyrics from ``The Old Rugged Cross'' by George Bennard
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GROOM, Texas _ Texas Panhandle resident Steve Thomas knows about
suffering. And he has built the state's largest cross _ 192 feet
high _ to remind humans they can overcome suffering and shame too,
just as Christ did centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   The giant white cross, lighted at night on the Texas prairie
just east of Amarillo, is a brilliant beacon for truck drivers and
others seeking solace as they drive down Interstate 40 past the
small town of Groom.
</P>
<P>
   The cross is one of the gargantuan crosses _ including a
100-foot-high cross in Ballinger _ that have been erected across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Those who stop at the gigantic cross at Groom can also pray at
life-size bronze sculptures of the stations of the cross. Also they
can visit a building housing a full-size replica of the Shroud of
Turin, which many believe was the burial cloth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a half-million people stop at our cross last year,''
Thomas, a structural engineer who owns Caprock Engineering in
Pampa, said last week. ``We've seen big, burly truck drivers stop
by and break down crying. I've seen people praying there on hard
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   I stopped by last week at the cross at Groom, which can be seen
for miles driving down I-40, near the legendary Route 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the cross,'' said Jim Moraniec, who wore a broad
smile and a red baseball cap marked by a white cross.
</P>
<P>
   He had just been to early-morning Mass at Immaculate Heart of
Mary Catholic Church in Groom, before taking his turn as a
volunteer host at the cross, completed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had funerals, weddings, prayers for rain, Easter sunrise
services and a Baptist revival here,'' Moraniec said. ``We get a
lot of truck drivers. Some of the most spirited people I've ever
met are truck drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those drivers, Polish-born Marek Wieczorek of Chicago,
came by in his 18-wheeler last week. He wanted to show the cross to
his daughter, Aleksandra, 17, who still lives in Poland but will
soon move to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a blessing to me,'' said Wieczorek. ``I began
stopping by here several years ago when they first started building
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, 50, a devout Catholic who builds oil drilling rigs that
have a structure similar to his cross, has spent at least $1.5
million on the project and plans to spend more. He got the idea for
building the cross while driving down Interstate 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many advertisements for Satan along the
highway,'' he said. ``I wanted to build something that would shock
people into thinking about God.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross also illustrates some of the suffering in Thomas' own
life.
</P>
<P>
   In an audiotape telling about Thomas' inspiration to build the
cross, he relates candid stories about his tormented life as a
child because of his alcoholic parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father were wonderful and caring people as long
as they were sober,'' he said. ``Under the influence of alcohol,
they were different personalities. I remember not sleeping at all
because they would argue until 3 and 4 in the morning. I would get
up and go to school without ever seeing my parents.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, things got worse.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was upstairs sleeping when his emotionally disturbed
father, swinging a claw hammer, severely injured Thomas' mother and
two sisters, and then came upstairs and shot himself with a pistol.
Thomas' father died from the gunshot wound several days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had his own suffering testimony, and there is a
reason for it,'' Thomas said. ``When an individual suffers greatly,
he can either curse God or come much closer to the loving arms of
Jesus. We as God's creation must suffer in order to take up our
cross and produce good fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas also plans to build a Christian pilgrim center near the
cross at Groom, as well as a replica of Jesus' open tomb in the
Holy Land. He praises others who have built large crosses across
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cross at Ballinger gave me the idea to build this cross,''
he said. That cross was built by Jim and Doris Studer.
</P>
<P>
   The largest cross in the world is a 500-foot-high masonry
structure 60 miles north of Madrid, Spain. A cross in St.
Augustine, Fla., is 200 feet high but much smaller in diameter than
the Groom cross.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there is a 110-foot-high cross in southern Illinois and an
80-foot-high cross in northern Michigan, 100 miles north of
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas wants to build a large cross on Interstate 30 between
Fort Worth and Dallas. But for the moment, he is operating The
Cross Ministries in the high plains of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building the cross in Groom has meant more to me than I ever
expected,'' he said. ``I thought I would build it and walk away.
But it has become my life.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
