<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-TASTINGS-NEWZEALAND-S     07-25 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NEWZEALAND-SAUVIGNON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW ZEALAND TAKE ON A FRENCH GRAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: a list of recommended wines appears at end of story.) 
 By   ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the last 15 years, New Zealand has earned a
reputation for producing superb sauvignon blancs, yet if you speak
to New Zealand winemakers, you sense they would rather talk about
something else. ``If you think the sauvignon blancs are good, wait
until you taste our chardonnays and pinot noirs,'' they will say.
</P>
<P>
   Their attitude is not difficult to understand. If winemaking
were the Olympics, ever-popular chardonnay and pinot noir would be
center stage at high noon, like the long jump and 100-meter dash,
while sauvignon blanc would be relegated to the wee hours. Who is
ever remembered for winning the badminton competition?
</P>
<P>
   Having tasted some New Zealand chardonnays and pinot noirs, I
think it's fair to say that most of these wines are not yet ready
to compete in the finals. But the sauvignon blancs are another
story.
</P>
<P>
   The best of them combine the vivid citrus and herbal flavors of
Sancerre with a richness and depth that is New Zealand's own
contribution to sauvignon blanc wines.
</P>
<P>
   The better New Zealand sauvignon blancs are also fine food
companions, versatile enough to stand up to the spice of chili
peppers or the power of salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy Bay is the best-known New Zealand winemaker, and its
sauvignon blancs have excelled year after year, with a predictable
rise in prices. But many other good, less expensive wines are also
available, especially now that the 1999 vintage has come into the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Sauvignon blancs are excellent when young and fresh. As in
France, the best are fermented in steel tanks, with the flavor
coming from the purity of the fruit, so beware the occasional New
Zealand sauvignon blanc that is labeled barrel-fermented. What you
will taste is a mouthful of oak.
</P>
<P>
   It may be true that, like Olympic badminton athletes, sauvignon
blanc doesn't get the respect it deserves. But, eventually,
excellence of all sorts is rewarded; and, one day, New Zealand will
be able to show off its medals.
</P>
<P>
   CLOUDY BAY , MARLBOROUGH 1999 $24 &QL; 
