<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2653 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-OLY-TRACK-FIELD-HNS &LR;      07-25 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRACK-FIELD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EIGHT DAYS OF OLYMPIC TRACK, FIELD QUALIFYING HAD IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that eight tense, taut and terrific days of
the U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials are over, what kind of team
will America be sending to Sydney for the Games?
</P>
<P>
   A relatively inexperienced one, as it turns out. It's deep in
some events and pathetically shallow in others. Of the 122
available spots on the team in 22 men's events and 20 women's
events, more than half _ 65 to be exact _ went to first-time U.S.
Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Included among those rookies are such high-profile athletes as
Maurice Greene, Marion Jones and Stacy Dragila, all of whom have
won world championships since the 1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, it's a typical U.S. team _ strong in the
sprints and hurdles _ but it's also atypically weak in the
horizontal jumps. In fact, this is the weakest contingent of men's
long jumpers and triple jumpers to go to an Olympic Games in many
years; don't expect any medals in these two events.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women, Oakland's Regina Jacobs gives the U.S. team
hope for a medal in an event longer than 400 meters for the first
time since 1992, when Lynn Jennings won bronze at 10,000 meters in
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   In the just-concluded Olympic trials in Sacramento, Calif.,
Jacobs won the 1,500 and 5,000 in an impressive display of fitness
and fortitude. Jacobs will probably run the 1,500 in Sydney but
there's a chance she'll give the 5,000 a go if she and
husband-coach Tom Craig believe there's a better chance for a medal
in the longer event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regina Jacobs has performed brilliantly in the 5,000 and
1,500,'' said women's coach Karen Dennis of Nevada-Las Vegas. ``I
think our distances, which traditionally have been weak, are much
stronger. We have medal hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   While the surreal crash-and-burn of Greene and Michael Johnson
in their 200-meter showdown Sunday is still fresh in the minds of
those who saw it, it's important to remember that both are heavily
favored to win the gold medal in their individual events.
</P>
<P>
   Greene is the world record holder in the 100 at 9.79 seconds.
Johnson has the world record in the 400 at 43.18. Of the two,
Johnson is a stronger favorite because there is less margin for
error in the 100. Both athletes have two months to recover from the
hamstring horrors that befell them in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy where I am in my career,'' Johnson said. ``I still
got the opportunity to go to Sydney and represent my country. I'll
shift my focus to the 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll focus on 42 seconds. That's all I got left.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be the last Olympics for Johnson, Jacobs, hammer
thrower Lance Deal and decathlete Chris Huffins. Others are just
getting started, like discus thrower Seilala Sua of UCLA, Menlo
Park shot putter Adam Nelson, 400 hurdler Angelo Taylor, sprinter
John Capel and 5,000 runner Brad Hauser of Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Great stories abound on this U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   Marla Runyan, who was third in the 1,500 in Sacramento, is
legally blind. At 34, sprinter Floyd Heard returned to competition
after a year off and made his first Olympic team in an individual
event when he finished second to Capel in the 200.
</P>
<P>
   Recent American citizens Mebrahtom Keflezighi (Eritrea) and Abdi
Abdirahman (Somalia) made their new country's Olympic team in the
10,000 meters. At 41 and four years removed from an IAAF doping
suspension, Jud Logan made the team in the hammer but needs to hit
the Olympic ``A'' qualifying standard to go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   And how about the women's 800, an event where the U.S. will send
three members of the same family to the Olympics? Sisters Hazel
Clark and Joetta Clark Diggs finished 1-3 at Sacramento while their
sister-in-law, Jearl Miles-Clark, split the difference by coming in
second.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the focus in Sydney will be on the telegenic Jones as
she attempts to win an unprecedented five gold medals. She's a lock
for three (100, 200, 4x100 relay) and shaky in the long jump. Her
presence anchoring the 4x400 relay can only bolster the chances of
a U.S. victory in an event where it is not the swiftest country in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to Sydney, men's Olympic coach John Chaplin said,
``I want USA 1-2-3. All other controversies make good copy but it
doesn't mean diddly.''
</P>
<P>
   That was plainly evident in the 200, where a week's worth of
sniping by Johnson and Greene evaporated in the Sacramento sun as
they came up injured, one after the other.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the stressful process of selecting the U.S. team is
over, those who survived can now focus on Sydney, the dream
destination for first-time Olympians and veterans alike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
