u f BC-HOME-SALES-STREET &LR;      07-25 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-SALES-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES OF EXISTING HOMES RISE, CONSUMER CONFIDENCE REBOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN VAMES   
 c.2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sales of previously owned homes continued rising in
June, helped by a slight pullback in mortgage rates and the
continuing confidence of gainfully employed Americans. Indeed, July
saw a rebound in consumer confidence, driven by Americans' optimism
that jobs will continue to be plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Existing home sales, which account for the bulk of U.S. housing
market activity, rose 2.8 percent in June to a 5.23 million annual
rate, following a 4.3 percent rise in May, the National Association
of Realtors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer confidence index, a measure of the average
American's comfort with the current economic situation, rose 2.5
points to 141.7 in July after June's 5.5 point decline, the
Conference Board, a private research group, reported Tuesday. The
data are based on a representative sample of 5,000 U.S. households
and measured relative a reading of 100 in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Both pieces of data suggest that some key areas of the U.S.
economy might be on the rebound after slumping in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Housing markets and home building had been on the decline for
several months, and policy makers and economists cautiously
believed that higher mortgage rates were curbing American's
home-buying enthusiasm. But the June rebound might suggest
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, June's sharp decline in consumer confidence had been
seen as a sign that consumers, who account for roughly two-thirds
of the nation's economic output, might have been hunkering down in
the face of higher financing rates. But the rebound in confidence
might point to renewed consumer spending activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer confidence readings continue to indicate a strong
overall economy,'' said Lynn Franco, director of consumer research
at the Conference Board. ``Consumers are not only optimistic about
current conditions, but their expectations for the next six months
signal continued low unemployment and minimal inflationary
pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony on monetary policy last week, Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan said some indications were emerging that
portions of the economy were slowing down. These signs, he said,
include higher household debt, the near-saturation of consumers'
appetite for long-lasting durable goods like automobiles and
appliances, and stagnating stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan also warned that growth might accelerate again,
leading to renewed efforts by the central bank to raise interest
rates to slow economic growth to a sustainable level. Greenspan
also warned that the recent strength in consumer confidence and
home sales activity could be a sign that the economy might be
heating again.
</P>
<P>
   Some economist held a similar view. ``As long as consumer
confidence stays high, which we believe it will provided that the
labor markets stay strong and the stock market does not collapse,
consumption growth is likely to reaccelerate in the coming
months,'' said Joseph LaVorgna, senior economist at Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised short-term interest rates six times in the
past year in an attempt make it more costly for consumers and
businesses to borrow and spend. By slowing spending, the Fed hoped
to put supply and demand back into balance, reducing the risk of
inflation that occurs when too many dollars chase a steady amount
of goods. At its most recent meeting in June, the Fed's
policymaking committee decided to keep interest rates steady,
citing several slowing areas of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     07-25 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TOWN DIGGING IN TO HELP LAY WATERLINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 21-mile ditch being scratched across West Texas from
Throckmorton to Elbert is 99.9 percent finished. Just a few
stubborn rocks remain, and they'll soon be dislodged.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Throckmorton, 125 miles northwest of Fort
Worth, are eagerly looking forward to Friday, when the last length
of pipe will be laid in that ditch and life-giving water can once
again flow freely to the town.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are dirty and lawns are brown in Throckmorton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got almost 9 miles of pipe laid right now,'' said
Kelly Bowlin, the assistant city secretary. ``They should be
through by Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   The town normally draws its water from nearby Lake Throckmorton,
but Elm Creek, which feeds the lake, is bone dry. The watershed is
a small one, and it never captured enough spring rain to battle
heavy summer usage and triple-digit heat.
</P>
<P>
   City officials recently measured the lake and found that they
had only two months' water supply left. The state declared
Throckmorton a disaster area, and the city began searching for more
water.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Graham agreed to sell Throckmorton during emergency
conditions about 125,000 gallons of water a day from its Fort
Belknap Water Supply Corp. in Elbert.
</P>
<P>
   Throckmorton got an $800,000 grant from the state for a new
pipeline, but the estimated cost of the project hovered above $2
million. The town asked for volunteers to help lessen the cost, and
it got them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a man from Pennsylvania out there yesterday,'' Bowlin
said. ``It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, hundreds of volunteers have come and gone
along the pipeline route, and the call for volunteers has been
replaced with a call for money to help feed them.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross chapter from Abilene set up in Throckmorton to
help feed the workers, along with members of the Texas Baptist
Men's Association from Wichita, Archer and Clay counties. The Red
Cross chapter in Wichita Falls also sent support.
</P>
<P>
   The Baptist men are doing the cooking. The Red Cross is handling
the shopping and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pipeline has been progressing nicely _ they're ahead of
schedule _ and we've been feeding folks and making sure they're
getting their liquids,'' said Brian Aird, executive director of the
Abilene Red Cross chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a number of drives for water and Gatorade _ we've
got that covered _ but we need funds so we can buy food in bulk.''
</P>
<P>
   Aird said the meals are costing $3.33 each. The daily total has
been running $700.
</P>
<P>
   The menu has run from chicken to hot dogs and hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial estimate for the pipeline project was about two
weeks,'' Aird said. ``We felt we needed about $15,000.'' So far,
the chapter has raised about $4,300, he said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in recent memory that the Red Cross has
helped in a drought-relief effort, Aird said. But given the
scarcity of water across the state, it may not be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Throckmorton residents are pitching in as well. Along with
locals who have manned the ditch-digging and pipe-laying equipment,
others are making sandwiches and hauling water.
</P>
<P>
   Several women in town are making desserts to go out with the
lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Bowlin, a 17-year-old Throckmorton resident has made the
pipeline project a family affair. Her mother, Kelly, is helping at
City Hall, and her dad, Steve, is the town's public works director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ashley has been driving up and down that pipeline every day,''
her mother said. ``She has kind of adopted some of the volunteers.
Every day she finds a new one. She makes sure they get what they
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in Throckmorton appreciate the help.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
