<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2658 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-BRAUGHER-TEX     07-25 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BRAUGHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT SCRIPT LURES ANDRE BRAUGHER TO `GIDEON'S CROSSING'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKI TURNER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It was two years ago that Andre Braugher laid
out the criterion for his return to series television: He said he
would only consider working on shows shot on the East Coast, where
he lives with his wife, actress Ami Brabson, and two small sons.
The Chicago-born, Juilliard-trained thespian doesn't care much for
Los Angeles. It's far too pretentious for his tastes, he says. And,
as an avid angler, Braugher prefers fishing in the lakes near his
northern New Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher was shooting ``Passing Glory'' at the time. The TNT
film was the first television project he'd done since leaving his
Emmy Award-winning role as Detective Frank Pembleton on NBC's
critically acclaimed, but ratings-challenged drama ``Homicide: Life
on the Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, after reading the script for ABC's new drama ``Gideon's
Crossing,'' and checking with the ``commander'' (his wife),
Braugher, 38, has headed west again. He went alone, however,
because he didn't want to uproot his sons again or have his wife
sacrifice her career goals for his.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my agent called and said he had a script he thought I
should read, my first question was where was it shooting,''
Braugher said between sessions at the Television Critics
Association press tour. When he learned it was Los Angeles, he
said, ``Well, then I don't even know if we need to read it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Braugher read the script anyway and immediately knew he
wanted to do it. ``(My wife) and I understood that this was
material that couldn't be refused,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gideon's Crossing'' is a hospital drama starring Braugher as
an unorthodox chief of experimental medicine at a prestigious
Boston teaching hospital that is often the last hope for critically
ill patients. Ben Gideon's passion for healing has been intensified
by the recent death of his wife to ovarian cancer. The pilot
episode does a masterful job of exploring his motivations
professionally and personally. At work we see him trying to
persuade dying patients to fight; at home we observe him trying to
come to grips with the fact that he couldn't get his wife to do the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Dr. Jerome Groopman's book, ``The Measure of Our
Days,'' the show also stars Russell Hornsby, Rhona Mitra, Eric
Dane, Hamish Linklater, Ravi Kapoor and Sophie Keller; and reunites
Braugher with ``Homicide'' creator Paul Attanasio, ``Gideon's''
executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brilliant writer and his reputation alone was
sufficient to make me come out here,'' Braugher says of Attanasio.
``He has proven to be very talented, tasteful, hard-working and
sane. A man couldn't wish for a better executive producer.''
</P>
<P>
   You're likely to see shades of Pembleton in Ben Gideon. ``I love
(playing) men with flaws,'' Braugher says. Both are intense. But,
as Braugher says, the difference between them is that ``Gideon is
going into the very place that Pembleton is exiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we'll see on a weekly basis is the transformation
of Ben Gideon into himself,'' Braugher says. ``He has been through
the crossing. The Ben Gideon we would have met two or three years
down the line was not as fine a doctor as the man we meet today.''
</P>
<P>
   Braugher quit ``Homicide'' after six seasons in 1998, deciding
he'd had enough of Pembleton's issues. ``I thought it was time to
go on to a new challenge,'' he said. ``The trap of playing an
episodic character for too long is that the character begins to
play you.''
</P>
<P>
   The versatile actor has since appeared in two TV movies _
``Passing Glory'' and Showtime's ``Love Songs,'' _ and the feature
films ``Frequency,'' the upcoming ``Duets'' and ``A Better Way to
Die.'' Despite steady work, however, he says the quality of feature
film scripts sent his way leaves much to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty poor,'' he says. ``In terms of television,
there's been some good scripts and some interesting ones, but
(`Gideon's Crossing') is the highest caliber I've seen in a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Attanasio says he's glad Braugher felt compelled to do this
series. ``What we were really looking at in casting the part of Dr.
Ben Gideon was the essences of that character,'' he says. ``He had
to be somebody who had a real toughness and command, but who also
had warmth and a depth and a humanity.'' Braugher captures those
traits and ``is just a joy to write for.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that will be enough for Braugher to stick around for a
while. ``Past performances are no indication of future results so
I'll burn that bridge when I get to it,'' he says. ``We'll see how
it goes episode by episode and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
