r e BC-VIDEOGAMES-SEQUELS-TE     07-25 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAMES-SEQUELS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME VIDEO GAMES SPAWN SEQUEL AFTER SEQUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some video games _ OK, a lot of video games _ never die.
Instead, they reproduce, spawning sequel after sequel. Three recent
examples of games that refuse to die:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mortal Kombat Special Forces'' (Midway for PlayStation): One
of the oldest fighting games this side of ``Street Fighter,''
Midway's ``Mortal Kombat'' takes on a new face for this, its fifth
``MK'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being a straightforward, head-to-head, fist-to-fist
fighter, ``Special Forces'' is an action/adventure game along the
lines of ``Tomb Raider.'' Players take on the role of Jax, the
steel-armed character from ``MK II'' who's out to settle a score
with longtime rival Kano.
</P>
<P>
   Kano's hidden somewhere in a ``Doom''-influenced complex that's
littered with bad guys. Players must battle the goons using
hand-to-hand combat and guns as they make their way to the grand
showdown against Kano.
</P>
<P>
   Not much here resembles the old ``Mortal Kombat''; it's an
entirely different _ and much more satisfying _ game. The only
leftover from the old ``MKs'': the fighting. As with the
traditional ``MK'' titles, players use special combo moves to
thwart enemies. Unfortunately, there are no humorous finishing
moves. Bummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rampage Through Time'' (Midway for PlayStation): ``Rampage''
is an old, old, old arcade game that was as simple as it was fun.
Players controlled monsters _ based on Hollywood heroes like King
Kong and Godzilla _ who gathered points by smashing city buildings
to bits. You even got to gobble up people. Yeah, it was pretty
cool.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``Rampage'' game pays homage to the original, but
with a futuristic twist. Now the monsters are traveling through
time, destroying cities from different time eras, like ancient
Egypt. That's cool.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 cities await the monsters' stomping and pounding,
all of which are nicely detailed _ that is, until you rip 'em to
shreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street Fighter III Double Impact'' (Capcom for Sega
Dreamcast): This is actually two games in one: ``New Generation''
and ``Second Impact,'' both culled from the ``Street Fighter III''
series. Yes, keeping track of all the ``Street Fighter'' games is
confusing. Pity the poor birthday-present-hunting parent who's
gotta figure out which ``Street Fighter'' game their kid
``doesn't'' have.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the current crop of three-dimensional, high-tech
fighting games will yawn at the crudeness of ``Street Fighter
III,'' but real fighting enthusiasts know that the flat graphics
don't mean flat game play.
</P>
<P>
   These are fast and furious games in which strategy and timing
are essential. Whereas most fighting titles play up easy-to-use
combo moves that can wipe out an opponent instantaneously, these
focus on individual kicks and punches. So what if the graphics look
like they were pulled from a comic book? This is far more realistic
fighting than anything else out there.
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Mayhew is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7713, or e-mail:
mmayhew(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2663 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AOL-MERGER26-COX     07-25 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MERGER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOES SAY AOL-TIME WARNER COULD BECOME AN INTERNET TYRANT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Federal Communications Commission reviews
the proposed combination of America Online Inc. and Time Warner
Inc. on Thursday, it will get an earful of boos from merger
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest companies, including Walt Disney
Co. and General Electric Co.'s NBC, are asking regulators to limit
the power of a merged AOL Time Warner to prevent creation an
Internet bully.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has been especially aggressive on Capitol Hill, darkly
warning lawmakers and regulators that AOL Time Warner could choke
off competition in ``interactive TV'' _ the place where the
Internet and old-fashioned media are coming together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger will allow AOL to leverage its dominant position in
online Internet services with Time Warner's local cable monopolies
to control the emergent interactive television market,'' Disney
said in an FCC filing submitted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks are just ``more misinformation from our
competitors,'' responded AOL spokeswoman Kathy McKiernan. Disney
executives ``seem more interested in spinning fantasy than in
talking facts,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney is not alone in its complaints. In the seven months
since AOL, the No. 1 Internet service provider, and Time Warner,
one of the world's largest entertainment and news companies,
announced their proposed merger, critics have been growing louder.
</P>
<P>
   Ths will hear testimony from Disney, as well as other merger
critics, such as BellSouth Corp. and the Consumer Federation of
America.
</P>
<P>
   While media companies are fretting about interactive television,
online companies are complaining about what they call AOL's
``monopolistic'' practices involving its popular instant messaging
system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of 16 companies released a policy paper
condemning AOL, saying it has put a virtual stranglehold on instant
messaging, a popular way to send quick notes to online ``buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL's messaging system, with about 50 million users, is bigger
than all of its rivals combined. The 16 companies say AOL's system,
which blocks other instant message users from AOL members, hurts
both consumers and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In June, AOL told the FCC it supports the idea of allowing its
messaging system to work with others, but said it had to move
slowly to protect its cu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
