<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HDTV26-COX     07-25 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HDTV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS SEEKS FASTER HDTV ROLLOUT
 &HT;    Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two key members of Congress warned the nation's
broadcasters Tuesday that they could lose their free access to the
airwaves if they fail to make good on promises to roll out full
high-definition television (HDTV) programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be making a very big mistake by keeping these
next-generation TV services from the American consumer,'' said Rep.
Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the telecommunications
subcommittee, at a hearing called to review the current muddled
state of digital broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin's remarks were echoed by Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., who
chairs the parent House Commerce Committee. ``The picture of HDTV
still has some analog snow,'' Bliley said. ``There are
disagreements at the (Federal Communications Commission) and within
the industry over HDTV. Not only do these issues stall the sale of
new television sets, but these internal squabbles prevent digital
television from being a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress originally set 2006 as a deadline for the conversion of
the nation's TV signals to an all-digital standard, scapping the
analog system that has been in place since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   As the hearing ended, Tauzin said the broadcasters ``run the
risk of Congress claiming the (digital) spectrum back'' if they
sought to market the allocated band for subscription services ``and
not show the American public HDTV.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Bliley, ``It would be a mockery of the laws passed by this
Congress to allow the broadcasters to create secondary markets for
the spectrum they should return to the FCC as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin summoned an 11-member panel of witnesses to testify. It
reflected the full range of industry and government views on such
thorny HDTV issues as ``must carry'' cable rules and digital
transmission techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Since digital broadcasting began some 20 month ago, only 34,000
HDTV-capable sets have been sold, joining the nation's stockpile of
250 million analog models, Mark Hyman, an executive at
Baltimore-based Sinclair Broadcasting Group, noted.
</P>
<P>
   Although the price of some new sets has fallen to around $2,000,
most major networks have been slow in offering extensive HDTV
content. Some pullbacks, such as ABC's decision to no longer air
``Monday Night Football'' in HDTV, have also taken place.
</P>
<P>
   With some support from the major networks, Sinclair is
campaigning to add as an option to the current digital transmission
standard the one now being used in Europe, Asia and South America.
While similar, the two systems are mutually incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   In what Tauzin cited as ``an engineering duel that I hoped to
avoid,'' the proponents of the rival HDTV standards _ in league
with several digital commercial and public stations here _ sought
to demonstrate to the legislators their respective claimed virtues
and purported drawbacks in on-the-air tests.
</P>
<P>
   But in a July 24 letter to the National Association of
Broadcasters, FCC Chairman William Kennard argued that current
digital standard is ``superior'' to the one championed by Sinclair.
Any further changes in the technology, Kennard warned, ``could lead
to uncertainty that might jeopardize the ultimate success of the
transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying on behalf of the set makers, Gary Shapiro, head of
the Consumer Electronics Association, said: ``The American ...
standard has sufficient headroom and flexibility to accommodate new
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that the broadcasters have recently modified
their business plans to put more emphasis on data services, we ask
them to use the American standard in a way that will be compatible
with existing equipment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.digitaltelevision.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
