<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2667 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHOREOGRAPHERS-LEGACY     07-25 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOREOGRAPHERS-LEGACY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTIONS OF PROPERTY TIE UP DANCE LEGACIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of dancers recently asked the longtime stage manager
Maxine Glorsky for a list of choreographers whose work she would
like to see performed at ``Party for Max,'' a celebration of her
60th birthday at the Joyce Theater in September. Most readily
agreed to having their work performed on the program. But dance by
two major choreographers she named will not be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been impossible to pursue'' a piece by Martha
Graham, said Richard Daniels, one of the tribute planners, in view
of bitter ongoing battles between the Graham board and dancers and
Ron Protas, head of the Martha Graham Trust, which licenses her
dances.
</P>
<P>
   And the fee to restage a piece by the West Coast choreographer
Lester Horton, which included travel from California for a restager
designated by Lester Horton Dance Theater, was more than the cost
of the tribute itself. Luckily, Glorsky did not ask for a piece by
Erick Hawkins, who died intestate in 1994. The ownership of his
work is still in question.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a dance isn't danced, does it really exist?'' Daniels
asked. His question is rhetorical but valid.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the chief impediment to reviving dances
was that the work was out of fashion. Now, death and the notion of
ownership have seemingly created even more insurmountable problems.
</P>
<P>
   Growing sophistication about preserving the legacy of dance has
to a large extent institutionalized the handing-down of
choreography, which was first passed down from dancer to dancer,
then by written notation and film and video. The idea of owning a
dance as property is relatively new. Changes in copyright law that
went into effect in 1978 are partly responsible for that notion; so
is an increasing general interest in copyright and ownership as new
media widen the possibilities for illegally appropriating the
artistic property of others.
</P>
<P>
   An era died with Graham. The ownership of her dances is
emotionally fraught. In recent months, the Graham board has
effectively closed down the operations of its senior and junior
companies and school and removed Protas, who inherited Graham's
dances and the right to her name on her death in 1991, from the
board. Engagements in the United States and abroad have been
canceled. Protas has denied the company and its dancers the right
to perform the choreography. And the dancers have appealed to
institutions and individuals worldwide to boycott the works. The
trust is expected to take legal action soon.
</P>
<P>
   Horton, an innovative modern-dance choreographer with a
distinctive movement style, died in 1953. Frank Eng, to whom Horton
left his works, created the Horton foundation last year and
appointed Don Martin, a former Horton dancer, to stage the pieces.
``My only interest at this point is to reconstruct and hand down
the most accurate material possible,'' Eng said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is raising money to train a group of Horton
restagers who will be able to assist Martin. But first- and
second-generation Horton performers and teachers scattered across
the United States complain that they know at least as much about
the dances as Martin does and are eager to recreate Horton's
seldom-seen works and teach his technique before they vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographers of Horton's era often did not bother to arrange
for their work to live on after their death. Charles Weidman, who
formed a pioneering modern-dance company with Doris Humphrey in
1928, did not leave a will when he died in 1973. Eventually the New
York State Surrogate Court's public administrator gave his dance
material to a newly formed foundation that is responsible for their
restaging today.
</P>
<P>
   Most living choreographers own their own dances and license them
through their companies or foundations. Though choreographers have
been fond of proclaiming that they do not want their work to live
on after them, some do make provisions. George Balanchine left his
dances to colleagues, who restage them for ballet companies
throughout the world under the aegis of the Balanchine Trust,
formed in 1987 and considered a model in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey left her dances to her son, Charles Woodford, who
arranged for their licensing through the Dance Notation Bureau, a
center in Manhattan for the preservation of choreography and dance
techniques through written notation. The bureau also handles the
smaller ballets of Antony Tudor and works with the Weidman
Foundation. Jose Limon, a leading modern-dance choreographer who
died in 1972, did not mention his works in his will. They were
divided among his heirs and sold back to the Jose Limon Dance
Foundation, which is now responsible for their licensing.
</P>
<P>
   But no will has been found for Hawkins' widow, the composer
Lucia Dlugoszewski, who died suddenly in April. The public
administrator must now provide for the disposal not only of the
dances, sets and costumes but also of Dlugoszewski's scores, many
of which were an integral part of Hawkins' choreography and
aesthetic. The process can be long, depending partly on whether
heirs exist with solid claims to the estate. Katherine Duke, who
now heads the Hawkins company, says that the dancers are ready to
perform. She has also had requests to restage Hawkins' work. ``At
the moment, everything is still in the hands of the state,'' she
said. ``And they're not making any promises.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Even going by the rules can be difficult. Dances go into the
public domain 70 years after the choreographer's death. Work
created before 1909 is automatically considered to be in the public
domain. Later amendments or additions of new material are
copyrighted by the choreographer who creates the additions, and
this has raised legal questions of ownership. Similarly, who owns a
dance made by a staff choreographer for a specific company?
</P>
<P>
   Choreographers have always taken material from one another, and
even the new copyright law cannot prevent that entirely. What the
law did do was to make it easier to copyright a dance, to turn it
into property. Before the changes, dances could be registered for
copyright through often cumbersome and imprecise written
descriptions, the most reliable of which were notated dance
``scores.'' ``It was like trying to get copyright protection by
publishing the libretto,'' said Theodore Striggles, an arts and
intellectual property lawyer and former dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a simple rehearsal film or videotape is enough to ``fix''
or establish the entity of a work. ``In theory, the moment the film
was made there was sufficient fixation,'' Striggles said, ``which
left everything protected that was ever filmed except for
improvisation.'' Those in dance know that they may risk legal
problems if they fold even a few taped moments of Paul Taylor's
version of ``Le Sacre du Printemps'' into a documentary without
getting permission from Taylor and the estate of the composer Igor
Stravinsky, even if the documentary is being made by a deserving
nonprofit arts institution.
</P>
<P>
   It is even possible to trademark a choreographer's name, as has
been done by the Martha Graham Trust and the Alvin Ailey American
Dance Theater Foundation. The Ailey board bought the rights to
Ailey's dances from his mother, to whom the choreographer had left
them, and the rights to his name from his step-brother. ``The board
felt the dances had to be owned by a nonprofit institution and not
a single person, who could sell `Revelations' to the Rockettes,''
said Sharon Luckman, executive director of the Ailey company. But
``Revelations'' and another early classic, ``Blues Suite,'' are
never licensed to other companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Who should own a dance? It could be argued that any art might be
described as the intellectual property of a nation after its
creator's death, particularly if it has been made with public
funds. It could also be argued that the old-time dancers who have
gathered regularly over the decades to reconstruct lost works by
long-dead choreographers, relying on their own muscle memory,
should be entitled to some portion of ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Thorny aesthetic questions must often also be addressed. Duke,
the Hawkins dancer, wonders whether companies willing to undertake
the cost of performing the works to live music should get a
reduction in the licensing fee. ``Erick and Lucy lived for live
music,'' she said. ``Some in the company feel the dances will never
be seen if we demand that they be done to live music.''
</P>
<P>
   Choreographers tend to tinker with and rework dances long after
their premieres. Which version of a dance should be considered the
authentic property? Sally Bliss, the head of the Tudor Trust in St.
Louis, Mo., was faced with a difficult question when the Jose Limon
Dance Company asked for Tudor's ``Dark Elegies.''
</P>
<P>
   The dance had been created for a ballet troupe, with the women
performing it on point. Would the flat modern-dance slippers of the
Limon company violate the aesthetic of the piece? She decided to
license the piece to Limon because she felt ``Dark Elegies'' also
needed the kind of physical weight that the modern-dance company
would bring to the piece. (Ballet is airborne; modern dance
traditionally is earthbound.)
</P>
<P>
   The Tudor foundation is known as one of the most generous of
licensing institutions. Bliss charges from $6,000 to $10,000,
depending in part on the size and prominence of the company, for a
three- to six-year contract, with a standard $100 per-performance
royalty fee. Videotapes can only be used for restaging if the
restager has danced a role in the ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says I should raise the fees, but people say they
can't afford it and I believe them,'' said Bliss, a former Tudor
dancer and friend. ``I think it's wonderful so many people are
doing Tudor.'' She gives regional companies a longer contract
because they perform less frequently than big-city troupes. ``The
regionals can't do a work again the next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, fees for the licensing of the dance alone, which
does not include music rights, costumes and scenery rentals and
some other expenses, range from $1,000 per minute, the Horton
foundation's charge, to a scale of $10,000 to $50,000 for one to
three-year contracts. A few choreographers go as high as $100,000.
Factors in determining the fee can also include the length and
complexity of the work, the number of performances and the size of
the geographical area in which the dance will be performed.
</P>
<P>
   Most restagers are longtime performers of the dances who have
often been chosen by the choreographers themselves. The Ailey
company often sends Masazumi Chaya, its associate artistic director
and chief restager, to inspect a company before it acquires its
first Ailey dance.
</P>
<P>
   Once a dance is licensed, it must also be maintained. Changes
inevitably creep in, whether through sloppiness or individual
interpretation. Many licensing institutions require that the
company train an in-house regisseur or ballet master who will
continue to monitor the performing level and correctness of the
work. The Manhattan-based Nikolais-Louis Foundation for Dance
requires that any revival of a work by Alwin Nikolais or Murray
Louis two years after its staging must be restaged by the
designated reconstructor.
</P>
<P>
   Dance companies tend to change their full complement of
performers and staff every two years, Louis said. And unlike
companies that perform only the work of their founding
choreographers, repertory companies dance a variety of styles.
``The internal coloration of a dance can be lost,'' Louis said.
``Dancers remember what but not how.''
</P>
<P>
   Money is less an issue, many say believably, than trying to keep
the dances alive in as authentic a version as possible. ``The point
is to disseminate, not to be billionaires,'' said Jane Hermann, the
director of dance at International Creative Management. ``It's a
judgment call as to how best to disseminate the work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
