<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, July 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers will develop near a wavering front from the
Middle Atlantic coast to southern New England on Wednesday. Strong
high pressure in the central Atlantic Ocean will direct a steady
supply of rich tropical moisture north along the Atlantic seaboard
through Thursday. As a result, downpours with local flooding will
occur especially near the southern New England coast. Farther
inland, abundant clouds and a few showers will occur near the east
slopes of the Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Gradual warming will continue from the interior Southeast to the
Ohio Valley and eastern Great Lakes. Ample sun will raise
temperatures to within a few degrees of seasonal values.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of thunderstorms will accompany a front from the
western Great Lakes to the central Plains. Meanwhile, most of the
interior West will be sunny and hot. Scattered afternoon thunder
will erupt in the Rockies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DEATH VALLEY HEAT
</P>
<P>
   While unusual summer chill has lingered in parts of the East,
the temperature has surged past the 120 degree mark in Death
Valley, Calif., every day since last Friday. Strong high pressure
centered 20,000 feet above the Southwest is producing the intense
heat. High pressure areas are masses of sinking air that warm
through compression during descent. Death Valley holds the national
high temperature record, 134 degrees, and is the American hot spot
because air is further heated in descending to the valley's
location 194 feet below sea level. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
