<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BULLET-VESTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BILL WOULD HIT CRIMINALS WEARING BODY ARMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to
approve legislation that would make it a crime for convicted felons
to possess body armor. The bill also would impose stiffer penalties
on convicts who commit crimes while wearing armor.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would make it easier for the federal government
to donate thousands of pieces of surplus body armor, such as
bullet-proof vests, to state and local governments that can't
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill sponsored by Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., is the
James Guelff Body Armor Act, named after a San Francisco police
officer shot to death in 1994 by a gunman wearing a kevlar vest and
bulletproof helmet.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to approve the bill
Thursday and send it to the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, criminals with violent intentions are more
dangerous when they wear body armor,'' Feinstein said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation directs the U.S. Sentencing Commission, an
advisory body established by Congress, to increase sentencing
guidelines by as much as five years for convicted defendants who
were wearing body armor while committing a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said Tuesday he
supports Feinstein's measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds alright to me,'' Lott said. ``I can't think of many
things I would rather do than make it harder on criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, also pledged
Tuesday to push for the legislation. ``If I can help her, I will,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But time is running out in Congress. Both chambers recess at the
end of this week for the month of August and the political
conventions. When they return in September, Lott has said Congress
will focus first on must-pass spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   A measure similar to Feinstein's Body Armor Act passed the
Senate a year ago as part of the Juvenile Justice bill, but that
measure has been stalled in conference amid squabbling about gun
control provisions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1726EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
