NYT-07-25-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2680 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-ARTISAN-BREADS-0726-C     07-25 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTISAN-BREADS-0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paper bag clad artisan breads a new and alluring choice
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Artisan breads _ made by hand, cherished for
their taste, texture and crust _ have gone mainstream in the Miami
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago everyone bought commercial bread at the
supermarket, mindlessly picking up plastic bags of soft bread. Now
the daily bread may come in paper bags designed to preserve the
cherished crust.
</P>
<P>
   The number of artisan bakeries is growing, and in supermarkets
such as Dorothy Lane Market, which bakes bread in a $54,000 French
oven, hand-crafted breads outsell commercial varieties and account
for 54 perent of total bread sales. More French baguettes are sold
in the two DLM stores than the most popular commercial bread.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who seek out these new bakeries willingly pay from
$2.45 to $4.99 a loaf, considerably more than the cost of national
commercial breads, priced anywhere from $1.19 to $2.69, with house
brands even lower.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent opening of Panera Bread, a St. Louis-based
chain, at Town &AMP; Country Shopping Center in Kettering, the
competition has heated up. To assess the quality of the offerings,
we assembled a panel of tasters and purchased four popular kinds of
artisan breads: sourdough, asiago cheese (a new contender),
multigrain and raisin bread. Dorothy Lane Market, Panera, Big Sky
and Village Bread (formerly Great Harvest) were included.
</P>
<P>
   When the battle of the 13 breads was over, panelists were asked
which single loaf bread they would want to take home. The unanimous
winner was the asiago cheese bread from Dorothy Lane Market. It
trounced the asiago contender from Panera, which is credited with
originating this specialty.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lane Market also came out on top in the four-way
competition of sourdough breads.
</P>
<P>
   Judging of both the multigrain and raisin bread categories was
made difficult by the disparate offerings. The multigrain loaves
ranged from very soft to a dense, in-your-face bread that announced
its healthful intentions. The raisin breads also were varied. Not
all include nuts, and the textures range from fluffy to dense.
</P>
<P>
   We bought all the breads and sampled them the same day; because
some breads are available on rotating schedules, we were unable to
buy comparable samples in each category from every store.
</P>
<P>
   The tasters included a chef, caterer, home baker and two Dayton
Daily News editors, as well as the food editor. The bread was
evaluated on appearance, aroma, taste and texture. Ratings were
done on a 10-point scale, with 10 the highest. Anything under 3 was
rated ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sourdough breads vary in style and shape from store to store.
</P>
<P>
   All six tasters gave their top marks to the Dorothy Lane Market
sourdough, saying the ``well-blistered'' appearance ``holds the
promise of a hearty, chewy, crusty bread.'' Most found it delivered
the distinctive sourdough flavor and aroma. The bread also had a
desirable open-textured crumb.
</P>
<P>
   Panera won most of its points on its good looks. Despite a
``chewy'' crust, the fine-crumbed inside was termed ``too soft.''
Judges also faulted the bread for bland taste and lack of the
distinctive sourdough aroma. The tasters found the Village Bread
sourdough generally acceptable, with a distinctive sourdough taste
but complained that the texture was too doughy. The Big Sky Wyoming
sourdough failed on all points.SOURDOUGH BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Store price Rating
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lane Market $3.89 8
</P>
<P>
   Panera $2.45 6.1
</P>
<P>
   Village $3.00 5.6
</P>
<P>
   Big Sky $3.25 3  &QR;  While Panera may be as known for its asiago
cheese bread as its sourdough, Dorothy Lane Market introduced its
version before the Kettering Panera store opened. Village Bread
also added an asiago cheese bread.
</P>
<P>
   The Dorothy Lane Market version _ the best of this show _ won a
near-perfect score from one taster who noted the cheese is studded
throughout, providing an intense aroma and ``wonderfully cheesy''
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Again Panera won all its points on looks, with all the cheese
baked into a split top. But there was little cheese aroma or taste
beyond the topping. ``A great top crust just isn't enough,'' wrote
one taster.
</P>
<P>
   The Village asiago bread turned out to be flavored with pesto
and tasters found that overwhelmed the cheese. The texture was
judged substantial, with a chewy crust
</P>
<P>
   ASIAGO CHEESE BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Store Price Rating
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lane Market $4.79 8
</P>
<P>
   Village $4.25 5.6
</P>
<P>
   Panera $3.75 5  &QR;  Raisin breads vary considerably at specialty
bread stores. Some, such as Panera, use just raisins and cinnamon.
Because this company doesn't use nuts, the most expensive
ingredient, the loaf is markedly cheaper. Village uses both raisins
and walnuts. Dorothy Lane Market's dense loaf uses an abundance of
dark and golden raisins plus nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Panera's raisin bread, which nudged out the deceptively plain
loaf from Village Bread, would be a good candidate for toast or
French toast, tasters thought. They liked the sweet, simple
cinnamon aroma but generally found the bread too soft. Tasters
detected a molasses smell in the Village raisin bread. Some
complained of a bitter aftertaste, but others said the
plain-looking loaf tasted ``much better than expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dorothy Lane loaf was visibly badly burned, with scorched
raisins, which earned it an unacceptable rating. However several
thought the dense loaf, with its high ratio of raisins and nuts
``could have been good if not burnt.''
</P>
<P>
   RAISIN BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Store Price Rating
</P>
<P>
   Panera $3.10 6
</P>
<P>
   Village $4.50 5.6
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lane Market $4.99 2.6  &QR;  The only bread to earn a perfect
10 from one taster was the multigrain bread from Big Sky, but
another taster found the soft loaf unacceptable. That was typical
of the scoring in this category, indicating wildly different
expectations for multigrain breads. One taster found the Dorothy
Lane Market crust ``hard and dry;'' others thought it overbaked,
but another thought it had a ``great chewy crust.'' The Panera
loaf, scattered with oats for eye appeal, was found unacceptable by
two tasters who complained about the texture and aroma. Considering
that a rating of 5 is considered just acceptable, none of the
candidates scored high marks.
</P>
<P>
   MULTI GRAIN
</P>
<P>
   Big Sky $4 5.8
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Lane Market $3.59 5.3
</P>
<P>
   Panera $2.45 4.6
</P>
</TEXT>
