<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0726-COX     07-25 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0726-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY HITCHED TO TICKET
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush introduced his running mate, Dick Cheney, to a
cheering crowd of supporters in Austin, Texas, Tuesday, calling the
former defense secretary a ``valuable partner'' who will help lead
Republicans to the White House. A week before GOP delegates
formally nominate the Bush-Cheney ticket, Bush turned to the man
who headed his three-month search process - bypassing several
prominent Republicans who had vied for the job. ``I was impressed
by his thoughtfulness and the way he approached his mission and,
gradually, I realized the person who was best qualified to be my
vice president was working by my side,'' said Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER LUCK NEXT TIME
</P>
<P>
   Once Dick Cheney accepted the second spot, George W. Bush made
calls to the also-rans, thanking them for their participation.
Among those contacted: Sens. Bill Frist and Fred Thompson of
Tennessee, John McCain of Arizona and Chuck Hagel of Nebraska;
Govs. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, Frank Keating of Oklahoma, George
Pataki of New York, Christie Whitman of New Jersey; former Govs.
John Danforth of Missouri and Lamar Alexander of Tennessee; and
Rep. John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   GORE ON DECK NOW
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said he's narrowed his running-mate search to a short
list of possible choices and is determined to keep the final
considerations ``very private and dignified.'' Gore met today in
Washington with former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, who
has been conducting the Democratic running mate search _ Dick
Cheney's counterpart. ``We're getting close to what you would call
a short list, but we have some work to do,'' said Gore, posing for
photos with Christopher. ``Only one person is going to be picked
and the others are not going to be. I waEN THERE'S THE ABORTION
ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights activists in the Republican Party reacted with
dismay to the choice of abortion foe Dick Cheney as George W.
Bush's running mate.``I think it sends a clear message ... that
there is not going to be the real option of getting the attention
of Governor Bush in terms of reproductive rights for women,''said
Roselyn O'Connell, head of the National Women's Political Caucus
and a Republican. Said Ann Stone, chair of Republicans for Choice,
claiming most party members favor some sort of abortion rights: ``I
think Bush has successfully united half the party, maybe only 30
percent of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS CHIEF DRIVING OFF WITH GOP
</P>
<P>
   Teamsters President James P. Hoffa will attend the Republican
convention as the guest of honor at a reception hosted by GOP
Chairman Jim Nicholson, Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge and 10
Republican members of Congress. ``This should not be construed as a
message to any presidential candidate,'' said Teamsters spokesman
Brett Caldweg, next Monday. Her subject? ``I'm going to talk about
George, of course,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ROLE FOR TELEGENIC HISPANIC NEPHEW
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's telegenic nephew George P. will have a featured
role at the Republican convention, and brother Jeb, the governor of
Florida, will be doing the rounds of TV interview shows. But Dad
and Mom, the former president and first lady, will be more in the
background. ``We want to be careful it doesn't turn into a Bush
family reunion,'' said convention co-chairman Andrew Card. George
P. Bush, 24, the son of Jeb and his Mexican-born wife, Columba, has
been on a nationwide tour promoting his uncle's candidacy and is
seen as a valuable campaigner in pursuit of Hispanic and youth
votes.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERLYING PROS AND CONS
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News-Washington Post poll out just before George W. Bush
selected Dick Cheney as his running mate, suggested that Bush
retains advantages on several key personal qualities like
leadership and trust. But there's good news for Al Gore as well. A
majority of voters saw Bush as unlikely to keep the budget balanced
while cutting income taxes, and more thought Gore had a better
knowledge of world affairs and a better handle on the key issue of
health care.
</P>
<P>
   THE CRADLE OF LIBERTY
</P>
<P>
   Americans who watch the Republican convention next week will see
a slew of patriotic symbols, from the Liberty Bell to Independence
Hall _ where both the Declaration of Independence and the U.S.
Constitution were created. Such rich imagery gives the Grand Old
Party an opportunity to project its patriotic underpinnings to a
nation of voters that experts say are looking for moral authority.
``Philadelphia says `America' to people,'' said Meryl Levitz, who
promotes tourism for the greater Philadelphia area and has worked
closely with convention planners. ``In many ways, it's the most
American city.''
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-CRASHING SPIN MACHINE
</P>
<P>
   It may be a Republican party, but Democrats are promising to
crash. Al Gore will be vacationing when George W. Bush and his
fellow Republicans gather next week, but a band of Democrats will
infiltrate the GOP show, trying to inject their message and steal a
piece of the limelight. They'll begin by putting a dozen or so
Texans on a bus to wax about Bush's failings as governor as they
travel through battleground states on route to Philadelphia. The
disaffected Texans will fly home, but Democratic operatives will
stay on, offering daily spin to many of the 15,000 journalists at
work.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S PLAY PEPPER SPRAY BALL
</P>
<P>
   Police dealing with protesters at the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles may be armed with paintball guns that
shoot balls filled with pepper spray. Police said the balls, as big
around as a nickel, would be used only against protesters who are
violent or destroying property. Instead of paint, the police would
use the pepper spray. Balls fired from a standard paintgun travel
about 240 feet a second, leaving a welt when they strike someone's
skin.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMING UP AGAINST THE HEAVYWEIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Bob Franks of New Jersey and Rick Lazio of New York, two
little-known four-term suburban Republican congressmen, are the
Davids facing the Goliaths as they seek open Senate seats in
neighboring states. One is running against the biggest Senate
campaign spender in history (Jon Corzine). The other is challenging
the most famous woman in American politics (Hillary Clinton).
Franks and Lazio are taking the unusual step today of holding a
joint fund-raiser in the wealthy Monmouth County, N.J., community
of Rumson, hoping to collect $50,000 each from some well-heeled
Republicans to buy expensive TV advertising this fall.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING RID OF TV AUDIENCE REPELLENT
</P>
<P>
   Reinventing or in some cases abandoning the rituals of party
gatherings past, the Republican convention will more than ever
amount to a lavish multimedia spectacle that pushes controversy to
the sidelines in favor of an unabashed celebration of the goals and
vision of George W. Bush. Missing will be angry debates over issues
and the usual parade of elected officials introducing other elected
officials. But it will still be the oratorical roles of the likes
of Republican stars like Colin Powell and John McCain that are
likely to dominate the window of network news coverage that on most
nights will open at about 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'D ALL THOSE NAMES COME FROM?
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan, the front-runner for the Reform Party presidential
nomination, is suddenly under fire for alleged voter fraud from his
little-known rival in a dispute that escalates the tensions with
the forces loyal to party founderRoss Perot. At a press
conference, John Hagelin, who is competing for the nomination in
the party's national mail-in primary, accused the Buchanan campaign
of election fraud by padding lists of ballot recipients with at
least 250,000 names of Republicans. ``This time Pat's gone too
far,'' said Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   KEYES STILL PUSHING HIS VALUES
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate Alan Keyes was to speak at a
rally in Boston today held by the Parent's Rights Coalition of
Massachus
</P>
</TEXT>
