<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2682 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-VEEP26-COX     07-25 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VEEP26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHENEY CHOICE OPENS CENTER FOR GORE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Vice President Al Gore narrows his list of
potential running mates, experts said the choice would likely to be
tailored to help him stake out the political center.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the day Gov. George W. Bush of Texas solidified a
conservative Republican ticket by announcing his choice of Dick
Cheney, a former defense secretary and Wyoming congressman, Gore
met with Warren Christopher, who heads his search for a running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting close to what you would call a short list, but
we have some work to do,'' Gore told reporters before the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   While political experts suggested that Bush's selection was a
solid choice for the GOP, it also gives Gore a chance to sharpen
his appeal to the moderate swing voters that occupy the center of
the ideological spectrum, often in pivotal states.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats assailed Cheney's voting record. ``He is far from the
mainstream,'' Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said at a Capitol Hill
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're likely to see the Gore camp say that the selection of
Cheney shows who Bush really is _ a conservative rather than a
compassionate conservative,'' said Joel Goldstein, a Saint(cq)
Louis University political science professor and author of the
book, ``The Modern American Vice Presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Cheney is presidential, and Gore has to choose someone who
is at least as presidential as Bush's choice,'' added Goldstein.
``Otherwise, there will be a political payoff for Bush if Americans
perceive that Gore chose badly.''
</P>
<P>
   According to experts, Gore has five main options in making his
selection:
</P>
<P>
   _ If he wants to shore up his political base, he would need a
party stalwart like Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts or House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri. But Kerry is from a
state Gore is likely to carry anyway, and his voting record in the
Senate is left of center. Gephardt insists he is focused on
restoring a Democratic majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   _ If Gore wants to carry one of the key states in the election,
he would need someone like Sen. Bob Graham of Florida, with 25
electoral votes, or Sen. Richard Durbin of Illinois, with 22
electoral votes. Graham has experience as a governor and senator,
but Florida is always a tough state for Democrats. And Durbin is
relatively unknown outside his home state.
</P>
<P>
   _ If he wants to match Bush's choice of Cheney, an experienced
Washington player, he could turn to former Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell of Maine. Maine has only four electoral votes, but
Mitchell earned a national reputation in the Senate and has become
an international figure by negotiating peace in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   _ If he wants a flashy new face in politics, he would find one
in Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana or Sen. John Edwards of North
Carolina. But both are from solidly Republican states, and both are
baby-faced, a likely handicap in a televised debate with the
statesmanlike Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   _ If he wants drama, he can choose former Sen. William Cohen of
Maine, a moderate Republican who crossed party lines to serve as
defense secretary in the Clinton administration. The selection of
Cohen would send a message that Gore wants to restore
bipartisanship in Washington. But a Republican on the Democratic
ticket could be discouraging to partisan Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Elections are not decided by the choice of running mates. In
1988, for example, Bush's father, Vice President George Bush, chose
the unpresidential Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana and still won by a
landslide over Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts and his
presidential running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But in close elections, as this fall's contest between Gore and
Bush is expected to be, the choice of a running mate can be
important, not only in terms of winning key states but also in the
message the candidates hope to send to the voters who are only now
beginning to focus on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Tuesday that he would keep his selection process
``private and dignified ... out of respect for the men and women
who are under consideration.'' He said he would likely make his
choice known several days before the Democratic National Convention
begins in Los Angeles on Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
