<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-IT'S-CHENEY-INDEPENDE     07-25 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IT'S-CHENEY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CHOOSES DAD'S FRIEND, DICK CHENEY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 700-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After three days of fevered speculation, the
Republican Party's presidential ticket was finalized Tuesday when
the nominee, George W. Bush, confirmed that he had chosen Richard
Cheney, former congressman, former White House chief of staff and
former defense secretary, to be his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush broke the news to Cheney in a dawn telephone call to his
home in Dallas; he later announced his choice to reporters in
Austin and planned a joint rally at the University of Texas in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, his columnist wife, Lynne, and their daughter,
Elizabeth, flew to Austin for lunch with the Bushes at the Texas
Governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   At the weekend, Cheney, 59, is expected to accompany Bush on a
five-day progress through Middle America that will culminate in
their arrival, together, in Philadelphia for the final day of the
Republican Convention in Philadelphia next week.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Republicans, including disappointed contenders for the
vice presidential slot, at once rallied around Cheney, describing
him as an excellent choice and an ideal complement to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, who was defeated by Bush in a bitter
primary campaign but still enjoys wide support in the country at
large and in sections of the Republican Party, said that Cheney
would be ``an outstanding vice president...and one that will garner
significant support throughout the party and the country.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's name was briefly back in the frame last week after a
signature-gathering campaign among Republican congressmen last week
lobbying for his inclusion on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush-McCain ticket was seen by many, not only Republicans, as
offering Bush an almost failsafe route to the White House. But
McCain had said he would not accept the number two slot, even if it
were offered.
</P>
<P>
   Some eyebrows were none the less raised at the fact that Bush
had selected the very person he had entrusted with the task of
finding him a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a trusted friend of the Bush family, was chairman of the
search committee and in charge of soliciting information _
including extensive dossiers with personal financial and other
information _ from the short-listed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   He will now know a great deal about individuals who might find
themselves nominated for cabinet posts in the event of a Bush
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that Bush was on the verge of settling for Cheney were
given substance late last Friday when it emerged that he had made a
brief trip to Wyoming, where he keeps a farm, to register as a
voter there.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution discourages a presidential ticket where
both candidates come from the same state. If Cheney had not changed
his registration, Bush could be deprived of all the electoral
college votes from Texas _ votes that could be crucial if the
election is as close as is currently predicted.
</P>
<P>
   It further emerged that Cheney, who has suffered three heart
attacks in the past and underwent a quadruple bypass operation 12
years ago, had spent a day at a Washington hospital late last week
for medical checks to confirm his physical fitness.
</P>
<P>
   In the camp of Bush's Democratic rival for the White House, Vice
President Al Gore, the mood was quietly upbeat. Bush's decision to
plump for a politically ``safe'' Washington insider, and a white
male to boot, was described as ``timid.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also seen as leaving Gore's options wide open. Had Bush
selected a woman or ethnic minority candidate, or someone much
younger than himself, the pressure might have been on Gore to match
that choice.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the selection of Cheney preempt that pressure, it
offers the Gore campaign several new lines of attack. By Tuesday,
Cheney's health record was already the butt of talk-show jokes.
</P>
<P>
   His last-minute change of voter registration exposes him to
accusations of dubious sleight of hand, as Cheney's primary
residence now is clearly Texas, even though he represented Wyoming
for 11 years in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Cheney's position as defense secretary in the
administration of George Bush, Sr. enables the Gore team to present
George W. Bush as a creature of his father or, as Democratic
campaigners were dubbing him Tuesday, a ``retro-candidate.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 700-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
