A2692 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CANADIAN-CHICKENS-1ST     07-25 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIAN-CHICKENS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHILL IN THE AIR FOR FREE-RANGE CHICKENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (subs throughout to change `Gionnone' to `Giannone') 
 By ROZANNE GOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imported free-range chickens processed by a new method are
winning converts among New York chefs and could be in supermarkets
by September.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone Poultry, in St. Cuthbert, northeast of Montreal, has
devised a technique for chilling its freshly slaughtered chickens
with frigid air instead of water, said Tony Giannone, the sales
director. As a result, he said, the birds are less likely to breed
bacteria and also absorb no liquid; the taste and texture both
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone chickens are ``the closest in flavor and juiciness to
the famous poulet de Bresse of France,'' said David Cunningham, the
chef at the Lenox Room, on the Upper East Side. Cunningham, who has
cooked in France, was among the first to showcase the Canadian
chickens on his menu.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are big and meaty, with great chicken taste. They are
raised on corn, soy and wheat and receive no antibiotics or growth
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials studied chicken processing in Europe before
developing the new method, which uses air to evenly chill
eviscerated chickens as they travel through a cooling room for
exactly 64 minutes, reaching a temperature of 34 degrees. The
technique was designed to meet the strict sanitary rules of the
Canadian and United States agriculture departments. It eliminates
the usual final step of spraying the birds with water to keep them
from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens are immediately packaged using a new process that
gives them a 10-to-14-day shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone chickens are served at Bouterin, the Brasserie, Monkey
Bar, Clementine, Tabla, Della Femina and the Water Club as well as
the Ryland Inn in Whitehouse, N.J. At retail, whole Giannone
chickens are $1.95 a pound from D'Artagnan, (800) 327-8246.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
