<SLUG> BC-AOL-MERGER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOES SAY AOL-TIME WARNER COULD BECOME AN INTERNET TYRANT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Federal Communications Commission reviews
the proposed combination of America Online Inc. and Time Warner
Inc. on Thursday, it will get an earful of boos from merger
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest companies, including Walt Disney
Co. and General Electric Co.'s NBC, are asking regulators to limit
the power of a merged AOL Time Warner to prevent creation an
Internet bully.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has been especially aggressive on Capitol Hill, darkly
warning lawmakers and regulators that AOL Time Warner could choke
off competition in ``interactive TV'' _ the place where the
Internet and old-fashioned media are coming together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger will allow AOL to leverage its dominant position in
online Internet services with Time Warner's local cable monopolies
to control the emergent interactive television market,'' Disney
said in an FCC filing submitted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks are just ``more misinformation from our
competitors,'' responded AOL spokeswoman Kathy McKiernan. Disney
executives ``seem more interested in spinning fantasy than in
talking facts,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney is not alone in its complaints. In the seven months
since AOL, the No. 1 Internet service provider, and Time Warner,
one of the world's largest entertainment and news companies,
announced their proposed merger, critics have been growing louder.
</P>
<P>
   Though shareholders of both companies have overwhelmingly
approved the merger, worth roughly $117 billion, the companies
still need the approval of the FCC, as well as the Federal Trade
Commission and the European Union. Each is expected to rule this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   AOL and Time Warner executives say they are confident of
approval because their companies operate in different markets, and
therefore don't compete. AOL has 23 million online subscribers.
Time Warner owns cable TV operations and media companies that churn
out news and entertainment, such as CNN and Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   But merger opponents say that very combination of content, cable
and online access will lead to a new kind of monopoly. For example,
critics suggest AOL Time Warner might provide quick online
connections to its own content, but slower access to competitors'
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of the potential for bullying, Disney points to its
own problems with Time Warner last spring, when the two companies
got into a contract dispute. Time Warner responded to the
disagreement by blacking out Disney's ABC network on the cable
systems it owned.
</P>
<P>
   Then this summer, Disney was rebuffed by Time Warner when it
proposed that the companies try working together to distribute
content.
</P>
<P>
   Now Disney lobbyists are showing a 10-minute video to lawmakers,
spelling out the case against AOL Time Warner in stark, scary
terms. The company is asking the FCC to effectively break up AOL
Time Warner by separating its cable distribution system from the
content-providing operations.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also has filed with the FCC, saying AOL Time Warner should
be forced to provide its online and video competitors with
non-discriminatory access to Time Warner cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing, FCC members will hear testimony from
Disney, as well as other merger critics, such as BellSouth Corp.
and the Consumer Federation of America.
</P>
<P>
   While media companies are fretting about interactive television,
online companies are complaining about what they call AOL's
``monopolistic'' practices involving its popular instant messaging
system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of 16 companies released a policy paper
condemning AOL, saying it has put a virtual stranglehold on instant
communicate freely on the Internet,'' said Margaret Heffernan, CEO
of iCast Corp., one of the 16 instant messaging rivals. ``AOL is
robbing IM users of this right.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, regulators primarily are concerned about the online
delivery of entertainment. That's because AOL has a four-year
agreement with Bertelsmann AG, Germany's largest media company,
guaranteeing that company will have access to AOL as a marketplace
for its music, television and publishing content.
</P>
<P>
   By combining with Time Warner, AOL also will gain ''preferential
access to the leading source of music publishing rights and music
repertoire'' in much of Europe, the European ine companies are
complaining about what they call AOL's ``monopolistic'' practices
involving its popular instant messaging system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a group of 16 companies released a policy paper
condemning AOL, saying it has put a virtual stranglehold on instant
messaging, a popular way to send quick notes to online ``buddies.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL's messaging system, with about 50 million users, is bigger
than all of its rivals combined. The 16 companies say AOL's system,
which blocks other instant message users from AOL members, hurts
both consumers and competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In June, AOL told the FCC it supports the idea of allowing its
messaging system to work with others, but said it had to move
slowly to protect its customers' privacy. The competitors, which
include Microsoft Corp.'s MSN, accuse AOL of stalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers deserve the right to communicate freely on the
Internet,'' said Margaret Heffernan, CEO of iCast Corp., one of the
16 instant messaging rivals. ``AOL is robbing IM users of this
right.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, regulators primarily are concerned about the online
delivery of entertainment. That's because AOL has a four-year
agreement with Bertelsmann AG, Germany's largest media company,
guaranteeing that company will have access to AOL as a marketplace
for its music, television and publishing content.
</P>
<P>
   By combining with Time Warner, AOL also will gain ''preferential
access to the leading source of music publishing rights and music
repertoire'' in much of Europe, the European Commission said. Given
that advantage, AOL could become the ''gatekeeper in the emerging
online music distribution channel.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as competitors and consumer advocates continue to
criticize the merger, AOL and Time Warner executives are insisting
they will play fair. In a recent letter to the FCC, the companies
promised to use as many distribution methods as possible. Rather
than trying to force-feed its content through Time Warner cable
lines, the merged company would offer service via digital
subscriber lines and satellite, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
