<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WYOMING REACTS WARMLY TO CHENEY'S SELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
 (With BUSH-CHENEY) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Wyo. _ While Dick Cheney's ascension from vice
presidential screener to vice presidential running mate might have
surprised Republicans in other parts of the country, the reaction
of those who know him in his home state of Wyoming was, ``What took
them so long?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People here still think he should have run for president the
last time,'' said Wyoming's former senator, Alan Simpson,
reflecting a reverence that many state residents hold for Cheney, a
former White House chief of staff, congressman and secretary of
defense and well-known fly fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   ``So to us,'' Simpson added, ``this is no real surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   By selecting Cheney to join the ticket with him, Gov. George W.
Bush has drawn Wyoming, an overwhelmingly Republican state, into a
rare spotlight of national politics at the highest level. The state
has produced a slew of memorable congressmen over the years,
including Simpson, Clifford P. Hansen and Gale McGee and even a
Supreme Court justice, Willis Van Devanter, who served from 1911 to
1937.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney, 59, who moved to Wyoming from Nebraska as a
teen-ager, would be the first Wyomingite ever elected to either of
the nation's highest offices, a possibility not lost on many of his
friends and acquaintances here in Jackson, where he has a $2.8
million home just off the Teton Pines golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any bigger than this,'' said Jan Larimer, a
Jackson resident who is co-chairman of the Republican National
Convention, which starts next week in Philadelphia. ``We're a state
with just three electoral votes so this was never on anyone's radar
screen. So for a person of this stature, from out-of-the-way
Wyoming to get the vice presidential nomination, that's pretty
terrific. We're all just bursting our buttons.''
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Scarlett, who has known Cheney and his wife, Lynne, for
more than 30 years, said: ``To people in the state, it's an
acknowledgment of Wyoming values and the kind of people who live
here. I'm sure the entire state is genuinely happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends like Larimer and Scarlett say Cheney personifies the
state, as a rugged, straight-forward, no-nonsense, self-effacing
man who exudes a communal spirit that is not only prevalent but
necessary in the state with the fewest people.
</P>
<P>
   Those qualities especially stand out in Jackson, a haven for the
rich and famous who have helped give Teton County, in the northwest
part of the state, the highest per-capita income of any county in
the nation. Among a group that includes movie stars like Harrison
Ford, business tycoons like Tom Kelleher of Southwest Airlines and
Edwin L. Artzt, former chairman of Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., Cheney has
distinguished himself for his selflessness, his friends say.
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney moved here after 10 years in Washington as Wyoming's
congressman, he drove his own furniture in a U-Haul trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that our Dick Cheney, or what?'' said Clarene Law, a state
lawmaker and close friend of the Cheneys.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the nicest, most unassuming and intelligent people
I have ever met,'' said Stephen Vletas, the owner of Westbank
Anglers, who has taken many of Jackson's high-profile residents
onto the Snake River for a day of fly fishing. He recalled some as
loud, selfish, disrespectful and boastful, but not Cheney, he said,
who has fished with him about six times or so in the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dick comes in the shop, he's so polite; he always stands
off to the side and waits his turn, never interrupting anyone
else,'' Vletas added. ``He's so different from every other
politician I've guided. I always had a true sense that he cared
about what he was doing and what was best for the American people.
I wish he'd have run for president last time instead of Bob Dole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
