<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2713 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CONCORDE-FRANCE-BOS &LR;      07-25 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FRANCE, TARNISH DIMS A SUPERSONIC STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In a nation that cherishes its symbols of excellence,
the French dream of aviation superiority crashed a little bit along
with the Concorde Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the French, the famed supersonic jet shared a glamorous
stage with champagne, the Cannes film festival, and truffles. It
was expensive, patronized by movie stars and royalty.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest commercial plane on the planet, the Concorde gave
the French some room to boast in a world where accolades for
technological advancements often went to the United States or the
Far East.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, that dream deflated, as stunned Parisians came to grips
with the fact that the plane they held up as the best in the world
was, also, fallible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Concorde is an important symbol for us, a ymbol for
France'' said Daniel Tresfield, 40, as he lounged against a
streetlamp in the festive Les Halles neighborhood of Paris. ``I
would like to fly on the Concorde, because it is very expensive,
and I am very poor. It is for the stars, for the very rich.''
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde ``is the best,'' Jean-Claude Soboul, 38, mused as
he hawked T-shirts to tourists near the Pompidou Center, a common
meetingplace for local youth. ``Remember the Titanic? It was the
best one, no? It was supposed to be the one that wouldn't sink.''
</P>
<P>
   Many French are proud of their plane, so fast, such an icon for
a country that has an international reputation for insisting on the
very best. It fit an image that demanded purity in language, food
and fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Parisians fear, the country may have lost a little bit of
the luster that came from producing the vehicle of such high-class
travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be culpability for France. The French people will
feel culpability,'' said Valerie Lambert, 37, as she made her way
across the San Michel bridge over the Seine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Concorde, it is the most beautiful plane in the world.
It's the French symbol of technology,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But many Parisians said they thought it unfair that a plane that
had suffered just one crash in decades would be singled out for
public criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old, old plane. I mean, that plane was (developed)
when Charles de Gaulle was president of the republic,'' said Nadim
Benarne, 45, as he perused a menu at a riverside cafe. ``So many
planes crash. For the Concorde, it's the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard of a Concorde crashing, ever,'' said Houman
Zahedi, 30. ``It's very terrible, very tragic. But like it goes,
nothing is 100 percent foolproof.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Paris residents noted the strange foreboding of trouble
only the day before, when the European press was focusing on a
technological problem on one of the planes, and the fact that the
line has not been making money recently.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of profitability, several people said, was bound to
reduce the Concorde's flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbol of France, but a symbol of the past, of the
'70's,'' said a German resident of Paris, who would identify
himself only by his first name, Wolf. ``It's a symbol for France,
not of France.''
</P>
</TEXT>
