<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH-CHENEY ENVIRONMENTAL RECORDS COME UNDER ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As George W. Bush was announcing Tuesday that
former Cabinet official Dick Cheney will be his running mate, the
environmental records of both candidates came under attack from
conservation advocates and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George W. Bush represents the biggest threat to the
environment in the 2000 presidential election, then Dick Cheney is
clearly the second biggest,'' said Deb Callahan, president of the
Washington-based League of Conservation Voters, at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
   She said that Cheney, a Wyoming congressman from 1979 to 1989,
voted to reduce funding for the Interior Department and to postpone
economic sanctions against cities and counties that failed to meet
requirements of the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan also said Cheney voted against a permanent ban on oil
and gas drilling in wilderness areas and against requiring
polluters to report any significant emissions of hazardous
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney's likely nomination as vice president might be good
news for the oil industry, but not for the majority of voters who
want stronger, not weaker, environmental protections,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, has been chief executive officer of Halliburton Co.,
a Dallas-based oil-field services and construction company, for the
last five years. He also served as White House chief of staff under
President Gerald Ford and as secretary of defense under Bush's
father, President George H. W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between his voting record in Congress and his time as CEO of
Halliburton, Cheney has shown that his priorities do not include
protecting the nation's air, water and natural resources,''
Callahan charged.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican strategist Charles Black, who has been a
consultant to the Texas governor, said Callahan was attempting to
``smear Cheney's record on environmental issues. This is a man who
has always fought to protect the environment while not impeding
economic progress,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats went after Bush's environmental record in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., released a report by the
Environmental Working Group, a Washington-based advocacy
organization, that said Texas ranked first in the nation in failure
to conduct inspections of major Clean Water Act violators during
fiscal 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Gov. Bush, Texas has basically let the major polluters
police themselves,'' McDermott said. ``If the governor is elected,
it will be a major threat to America's rivers and oceans.''
</P>
<P>
   The report analyzed inspection data collected by the
Environmental Protection Agency, which oversees the nation's major
pollution control laws but gives the states enforcement authority.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Saitas, executive director of the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission, which enforces EPA rules, called
the findings ``wholly unfair'' and ``false.''
</P>
<P>
   Saitas said the national study's references to Texas were
``based on flawed data.'' He said a number of state inspections
that EPA said were not done were actually completed after the
deadline EPA had set and that certain businesses cited as polluters
had been closed down.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore, often points to
Texas as the nation's most polluted state. Gore cites EPA reports
showing that Houston last year surpassed Los Angeles as nation's
smoggiest city, and that Texas ranked No. 1 in the country in the
number of days with unhealthy ozone levels.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
