<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCY-FLIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL TEAM FLIES TO BERMUDA TO RESCUE AILING INFANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was sunrise over Bermuda one day last month when a
Coast Guard jet took off and raced toward Boston, bearing a rapidly
failing baby and a Children's Hospital medical team that had flown
in to work through the night in an attempt to save him.
</P>
<P>
   The baby, who had a heart defect that no physician on the island
could treat, was named Valiant by a mother who was inspired by the
comic-strip knight of old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wanted a child who was brave and fearless and could
conquer any situation,'' said his mother, Shirlene Ming-Santucci,
in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But after only two weeks of life, Valiant's time was already
running out. A narrowed heart valve forced blood to build up in his
heart and lungs, starving the rest of his 7-pound body. Getting him
to Boston, his local pediatrician decided the evening of June 27,
was his only hope.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's team _ Dr. Kate Ackerman, a pediatrician, and
Christine Katucki, a transport nurse _ tended the boy on the
770-mile flight back to Boston, but saw that he was weakening even
more as an ambulance sped from the airport toward Children's.
</P>
<P>
   ``His blood pressure was dropping dangerously,'' said Ackerman
Tuesday. The blood pressure device measured 40 over 30, and then
``just stopped reading,'' she said.''
</P>
<P>
   Urgent missions are routine for Children's transport team, which
carried out 900 of them between last October and June. Most were by
ground transport, but 65 involved aircraft. Yet the case of the
Bermuda baby illustrates just how far a hospital, even in this age
of managed care, is prepared to go to save one life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most life-or-death transport I've been on,'' said
Ackerman, who is a fellow in critical care pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   A team of cardiologists, anesthesiologists and other specialists
had been assembled at the hospital. They would use a balloon-tipped
catheter threaded through Valiant's tiny arteries to his heart's
aortic valve, which a birth defect had narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Only 20 minutes after the baby arrived, the team headed by Dr.
James Lock, chief of cardiology, and Dr. Stanton Perry, head of the
cardiac catheterization lab, began inserting the catheter into a
groin artery. They worked the balloon tip into the heart valve in
less than 8 minutes, said Dr. Mary Mullin, a cardiologist who
headed the rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really impressive,'' said Mullin. ``It normally takes
longer than that.'' After the balloon inflated several times to
widen the valve, Valiant immediately looked better, she said.
Tuesday, the baby was doing well and was expected to be discharged
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The drama began in the afternoon, when the pediatrician in
Bermuda called Children's to say his little patient was weakening
after having done well for almost two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin, who advised the doctors and nurses at the small Bermuda
hospital on the phone, said it was immediately clear that Valiant
``absolutely needed to be in a setting where the valve could be
opened up,'' and Bermuda had no pediatric cardiologists with such
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Normally the hospital hires a private air transport service _
which is usually covered by the patient's insurance _ but on this
day a line of thunderstorms along the East coast meant that the
North Carolina-based service couldn't fly.
</P>
<P>
   Katucki, the transport nurse, then turned to the U.S. Coast
Guard, whose planes can fly through rougher weather. The Coast
Guard agreed to send an HU25 Falcon _ similar to a civilian Lear
Jet _ and crew, including the pilots, Lt. Robert Barthelmes and Lt.
Cdr. Paul Hansen, based at Otis Air Force Base on Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard provides such flight on the merits of each
situation, and doesn't charge for them. Ming-Santucci said her
insurance company would cover the cost of the surgery but not the
salaries and expenses of the transport team, which will be paid for
by Children's.
</P>
<P>
   The plane flew to Logan International Airport to pick up the
Children's team. Ackerman _ who had to run home to get her passport
_ and Katucki arrived at Logan in an ambulance carrying a high-tech
but heavy isolette to put the baby in, along with several oxygen
tanks and six bags of medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Bermuda, the Children's team found Valiant breathing
via a throat tube and sedated. Ackerman ordered lab tests; they
showed that the baby's condition was worsening. The doctor ordered
drugs to boost the heart and replaced the breathing tube with a
larger one.
</P>
<P>
   For Ackerman, this was the toughest part. ``We needed to get him
back quickly, but every time we started to leave he became more
unstable,'' she said. To make matters worse, the Coast Guard pilots
had now been awake nearly 24 hours and were at their prescribed
limits: soon they would be forced to leave and send a fresh crew
back. If that had happened, the baby wouldn't have survived, said
Ackerman. ``It was a judgment call,'' she said. ``We decided to
pack him up and hope he'd make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic was heavy at Logan when the plane arrived about 7
a.m., so Barthelmes and Hansen requested a special clearance to
land on a runway close to where the Children's ambulance was
parked.
</P>
<P>
   After the emergency procedure opened Valiant's heart valve and
the immediate crisis was past, he began to improve rapidly. About a
week later doctors operated to patch a hole in his heart that made
blood flow the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, cardiologist Mullin said that the infant ``looks
terrific'' and didn't suffer any lasting effects from being in
heart failure for so many hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a wonderful feeling to see the mother holding a baby who
was so critically ill and have her about to return home with a
normal baby,'' Mullin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
