<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-DEGRAAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEGRAAN PRESIDENT OF GILLETTE; ON TRACK TO BECOME CEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a move that had been expected, Gillette Co. said
Tuesday that its board of directors has elevated executive vice
president Edward F. DeGraan, 57, to the vacant posts of president
and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming a new role at a time when the razor giant has been
delivering subpar performances, DeGraan becomes the likely
frontrunner to succeed Gillette chairman and chief executive
Michael C. Hawley, 62.
</P>
<P>
   In recent memory every Gillette president, including Hawley, has
been ultimately promoted to chief executive. Since Hawley's
ascension to the top job last year, the position of president had
been left open.
</P>
<P>
   As president, it will be up to DeGraan to cut costs, boost sales
and profits and help Hawley get Gillette back into investors' good
graces.
</P>
<P>
   All Gillette product lines will report to DeGraan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single, focused point of control over operations will
further align our global product-line strategies and commercial
sales execution, resulting in greater innovation, efficiency, and
cost-savings,'' Gillette spokesman Eric Kraus said of DeGraan's
promotion. ``This appointment will also create a balanced span of
responsibilities between the chief executive and president.''
</P>
<P>
   For most the of 1990s, Gillette was a robust performer. But in
the last two years, its momentum has slowed.
</P>
<P>
   As a company that gets about two thirds of its revenues from
overseas, it has been hurt by a strong dollar and troubled
economies in some of its major foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gillette said both second-quarter revenues and
earnings from continuing operations rose 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While its razor business continues to boom, few of the
Gillette's other divisions turned in impressive results.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, three of the 12 analysts who follow Gillette
have downgraded their ratings on the company, according to First
Call Corp., a Thomson Financial company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel this company has a lot of long-term potential,''
said Patrick Schumann, an analyst with Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumann said he remains concerned about the near-term
performance of Gillette's Duracell battery division and expressed
disappointment that Gillette decided not to sell some of its Braun
small-appliance product lines.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gillette said it entered exclusive negotiations to
sell its stationery division to Newell Rubbermaid Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With DeGraan's promotion, Gillette has hinted at its succession
plans. But is Wall Street willing to wait until Hawley reaches
retirement age?
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, investors and corporate boards have expressed
impatience with newly appointed chief executives who didn't deliver
improved results almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Such consumer giants as Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., Coca-Cola Co., and
Campbell Soup Co. have seen the abrupt departures of chief
executives with little more time in the top job than Hawley.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a South Boston longshoreman, DeGraan is a graduate of
Suffolk University. He will now also serve on Gillette's board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Gillette shares rose 43.75 cents
to close at $30.1875.
</P>
</TEXT>
