<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ITALY-COMMUNE-ART-NYT     07-25 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-COMMUNE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-346-9867.)
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN THE FOOTHILLS OF THE ALPS, THE NEW `NATION' of DAMANHUR  
(Foreign Journal) 
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALDISSERO CANAVESE, Italy _ The cottage cellar door seems to
lead to a basement toolshed. Actually it is the disguised entrance
to the ``Temple of Man,'' a five-story underground warren of vast,
ornately decorated chambers, with towering pillars, 40-foot-high
gold-leaf ceilings, giant frescoes and bronze statues, all linked
by narrow passages and concealed stone doors that spring open and
shut by electrical command.
</P>
<P>
   The temple looks like a cross between Xanadu and the
subterranean headquarters of a Bond villain plotting world
domination. Begun more than 20 years ago in total secrecy, it is
the spiritual core of Damanhur, a 23-year-old New Age commune
nestled, somewhat improbably, amid tiny rural villages in the
Piedmont valley of Valchiusella, in the foothills of the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Members reject the term cult, describing their commune as a
nation, one that aims at total self-sufficiency and boasts its own
currency, schools, federal and local government, newspapers, Web
site and tax code. It also claims to have its own unique
transportation system: time travel.
</P>
<P>
   But the oddest thing about Damanhur is not its belief system,
but the way it has melded California-style New Age spirituality
with the customs and mores of Northern Italy. When its 500
full-time residents are not experimenting with time travel and
``selfic'' healing, they are industriously churning out luxury
items for export.
</P>
<P>
   One Damanhur workshop makes Tiffany-style glass products.
Another business, Atelier Damjl, spins silk and cashmere fabrics on
18th-century wooden looms for Loro Piana and other top Italian
fashion houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never hippies,'' Damanhur's founder, Oberto Airaudi, a
former insurance salesman from Turin who goes by the name Falco
(Falcon), explained as he drove his silver Volvo station wagon up
steep mountain roads to the temple's helicopter pad. ``We believed
in hard work, personal responsibility and bank loans. It was our
own version of the American dream, all built with our own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   A Damanhurian candidate won last year's mayoral election in
nearby Vidracco, and the commune has town councilors in half a
dozen other small villages, worrying some locals who fear that the
commune, which keeps buying land, will soon rule the area. But
Damanhur's political goals are hardly unorthodox: the commune wants
a tax exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Damanhur, which took its name from an ancient Egyptian city,
also shares the Italian aversion to ironclad rules and has only
one: no smoking. Everything else is pretty much permitted,
including long lunches that include wine, pasta and meat, which may
help explain why the community has remained intact for more than
two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no place I can think of in the States with such
successful continuity,'' said David Fuess, 53, a visiting
acupuncturist from Carmel, Calif. Fuess, who uses Damanhur's gold
``selfic'' needles in his healing practice back home, said he was
troubled by only one aspect. ``I'd like to see them be totally
vegetarian,'' he said wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke after attending a packed lecture on the hidden risks of
time travel given by Airaudi. Those include being inadvertently
transported to an ``inhospitable'' primeval forest and being chased
by wolves.
</P>
<P>
   When Airaudi started it, Damanhur was a semiclandestine society
that drew Italian students and young professionals searching for
spirituality, paranormal research and a Marxist rejection of
private property.
</P>
<P>
   Members shed their civil names and adopt animal first names and
vegetable surnames. A current ``king-guide'' for example, is named
Gorilla Eucalipto.
</P>
<P>
   Damanhurians began digging their temple in secret, carrying
buckets by hand to carry out discarded earth and stone. After
rumors of a mysterious sect spread across the valley, Damanhurians
erected a false temple, in ancient Egyptian style, above the real
one as a decoy.
</P>
<P>
   But the real temple came to light in 1992 when one founding
member decided to quit the commune and threatened to expose its
doings unless all his worldly goods were restored. Turning over
one's assets to the commune is one of the prerequisites to full
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute went to court, and baffled Italian judges eventually
ruled in favor of the commune, but it was forced to pay back taxes
on the temple. Airaudi says work is still continuing to dig newer
underground chambers, 10 times as big.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Damanhur dispensed with its early
collectivist spirit and secrecy, and it has since embraced
capitalism and Internet-driven public relations (www.Damanhur.it).
Tourists can tour the temple for a $40 fee, and its bustling
workshops, healing centers and guest houses offer paid spiritual
retreats and seminars.
</P>
<P>
   But Damanhur's ardent work ethic and spiritual zeal wear thin on
some of the group's teen-agers. ``I don't exclude returning
someday, but right now I am sick of it,'' said 18-year-old
Cinciallegra (Titmouse), aka Melissa Baracco.
</P>
<P>
   She has lived in Damanhur since the age of 6. Her hair is dyed a
defiant, nonorganic pink, and she smokes _ off the premises. She
said she yearned to travel and be a normal teen-age slacker.
``Sometimes I just want to do nothing,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the commune draws middle-aged people interested in
mysticism and the paranormal. ``It is a deep, holistic, growthful
environment,'' Peta Lynne, 50, a visitor from the Hawaiian island
of Kauai, who described her day job there as a ``channeler.''
</P>
<P>
   When she began explaining how she rediscovered past lives, she
was cut off by Esperide Ananas, (Butterfly Pineapple), or Silvia
Buffagni, Damanhur's director of international public relations.
Buffagni rolled her eyes and impatiently explained that Damanhur
took a less ``fluffy'' approach to channeling, a somewhat rigid
distinction coming from one who claimed to have witnessed a fellow
Damanhurian travel through time to Atlantis.
</P>
<P>
   Residents along the valley, who live in villages deserted by
young people fleeing rural life and the absence of jobs, express
guarded admiration _ and concern about their neighbor's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay taxes, and I am not saying they haven't done some
good things: repainting Vidracco, adding a children's park and
other aesthetic touches,'' said Domenico Troia Cionin, the mayor of
Baldissero Canavese, referring to improvements made by the
Damanhurian mayor of Vidracco two miles away. ``But we feel a
little like Indians in the American West when the cowboys came.
They tried to resist, and utterly failed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
