   The following stories were skedded earlier in the day; please
note dateline/byline changes and updated summaries:
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Gonesse, France) _ A chartered Air France
Concorde carrying mainly German tourists bound for New York crashed
in flames shortly after take-off from Charles de Gaulle Airport
outside Paris Tuesday, killing all 109 passengers and crew on board
and at least four people on the ground. It was the first ever crash
of a Concorde since the world's first supersonic passenger plane
went into commercial operation in 1976. By Alan Riding. (With photo
NYT1)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH-SCENE (Roissy, France) _ Witnesses described the
brief, fiery flight of AF 4590 as a vision of hell or a kind of
bomb, in flames from the time it rolled down the runway until it
smashed three minutes later into a tiny, wooden hotel. In the
little town of Gonesse, barely four miles southwest of the airport,
there were reactions of shock and distress. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   AIFRANCE-CRASH-CONCORDE (Undated) _ Controversy has swirled
around the Concorde, the world's only supersonic passenger jet,
from the day it began development in 1962. But until Tuesday there
was one area where its record, by modern aviation standards, was
pristine: safety. The fatal crash of Air France Flight 4590, a
charter from Paris to New York, was the first of a Concorde after
more than 30 years of flying, an unusually long stretch for any
type of commercial aircraft. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   This story was not previosly skedded:
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH-GERMANY (Berlin) _ The shaken owner of a German
luxury tour operator appeared on national television Tuesday to
confirm that his company had chartered the Air France Concorde that
crashed near Paris. The passengers had paid between $4,200 and
$11,000 for a journey that was to begin in New York, the
destination of the doomed flight, and continue on a luxury
oceanliner called the ``Deutschland.'' The trip would have taken
the holidaymakers on a cruise through the Caribbean with a final
destination of Manta in Ecuador. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   The N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
