peace process, and without it they could fall out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Violence could be averted depending on how leaders explain the
failure and whether they will, as promised, continue to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   If future talks fail, Arafat could go ahead with promises to
declare Palestinian statehood Sept. 13, when the negotiating period
is set to expire. Such an act could prompt Israeli reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the role of the United States will come under scrutiny.
Palestinians, who feel they have been compromising for years, may
be angered at U.S. President Bill Clinton's statements that
Israelis were more flexible in the talks. Israelis will cite his
comments for legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   In a hopeful view, most agree both sides thawed positions that
had appeared frozen for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Israel showed more willingness than ever to share Jerusalem and
to turn over large expanses of the West Bank to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians appeared ready to accept limits on the number of
refugees that can return to Israel. They also appeared ready to
allow several Jewish settlements to stay in West Bank lands claimed
by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   As many on both sides said, ``taboos'' were broken.
</P>
<P>
   But, the progress could still be overshadowed by the failure to
reach an agreement. It depends on how the leaders explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on the nature of the failure,'' said
Palestinian political analyst Khalil Shikaki. ``If the two parties
reach the definite conclusion that there are things negotiations
will not resolve, then both will try to force the other to think
differently through pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to wait and hear what they say here,'' he added. ``Not
in Washington. Forget Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat made no statement before boarding his plane Tuesday. But,
Shikaki said Arafat can expect a ``hero's'' welcome for not caving
in to what Palestinians saw as pressure to sign a bad agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he will face increased pressure to make progress or
declare a state. Clinton's statements, that Barak appeared willing
to make more concessions than Arafat, could pin the blame on the
Palestinians and undercut international support for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, meanwhile, returns to a governing coalition that controls
only 42 seats in the 120-seat parliament. Any day, opponents who
were against his even going to the peace talks might be able to
force new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Already Tuesday, political opponents said that, even though he
had not made an agreement, he had offered compromises that would
come back to haunt Israel.
</P>
<P>
   A small group of Israelis against the talks held a ``victory
celebration'' on a Jerusalem street.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a former general, tried to offer the failure of the talks
and the violence that might follow as reasons for Israelis to unify
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In preparation for the upcoming days and their risks, we have
to set aside all the differences and unite, as we have known to do
so many times in the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He sought reassurance in Clinton's statement that he had been
ready to make compromises for peace. Palestinians, however, saw the
comment as undercutting America's role as a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very clear that the U.S. supports the Israeli positions.
It weakens the credibility of the U.S., absolutely,'' said Marwan
Barghouti, a member of the Palestinian parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Barghouti is a leader of Arafat's Fatah Party in the West Bank
and holds strong influence over the groups of armed youth that
Israelis fear may react violently to a peace talks failure. But, he
said there needs to be time for assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's necessary to go ahead to violence,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   More ominously, Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, spiritual leader of the
radical Hamas movement that has bombed Israeli cities in the past,
said the failure was proof that armed struggle was the only route
against the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow can be contacted at larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinian views of the peace process see:
</P>
<P>
   www.jmcc.org (Jerusalem Media and Communications Center)
</P>
<P>
   For daily news from Israel see:
</P>
<P>
   www.haaretzdaily.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
