<P>
   EDITORS: Following is a list of stories related to MIDEAST-TALKS
that will move tonight in the New York Times News Service report.
Stories will move in ``i'' news file. For more information, call
toll-free at 888-346-9867. The supervisor is Pat Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   The following stories were skedded earlier in the day; please
note dateline/byline changes and updated summaries:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ After 15 days of emotional
negotiations failed to end in an agreement at Camp David, President
Clinton closed the peace conference Tuesday by praising Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak for being ready to make hard compromises
but declaring that the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, would not
reciprocate. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Thurmont, Md.) _ News Analysis: And on the 15th
day, the Israelis and the Palestinians packed their bags and left
their pastoral retreat at Camp David empty-handed, exhausted and
still conflicted. In immediate retrospect, the idea that they could
have resolved a 52-year-old, bitter, blood-soaked dispute in a
fortnight seems like the summit of idealism. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-REACT (Jerusalem) _ As news of the failure in Washington
spread across this ancient city, from television sets in cafes and
bars, from radios in the bazaars of the old city, and across the
network of mobile phones that have Israelis and Palestinians
engaging in seemingly non-stop talk even on days when there is no
major news, the more common reaction seemed to be one of
disappointment, confusion and even of fear. There was not, however,
much surprise. The likelihood of the Camp David negotiations
breaking down had been bannered across headlines here for days. By
John F. Burns.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ISRAELIS (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
flew home from the breakup of the Camp David summit meeting Tuesday
night to a murky political future, his patchwork coalition in
tatters, his country sharply divided over the startling new
discussion of ceding parts of Jerusalem to some form of Palestinian
control. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Palestinian officials said
after the collapse of the Camp David summit meeting Tuesday that
they would press ahead with plans to declare an independent state
on September 13. Placing the blame for the impasse squarely on
Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel, the officials asserted that
Yasser Arafat had made all the concessions possible before going
into the talks, and that his firm stance at Camp David would boost
his standing among his own people. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Washington) _ Twice in the past seven months
President Bill Clinton has invested enormous amounts of time and
prestige in an attempt to reach historic accords between Israel and
its neighbors, first the Syrians, then the Palestinians. In both
cases his aides bet that changing times and the force of Clinton's
own personality as a mediator with a finely honed sense for the
middle ground might be enough to win agreement, and with it a
legacy for a second term that historians are already discussing as
a series of lost opportunities. Twice so far, Clinton and his aides
have bet wrong.By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   This story was not previously skedded:
</P>
