<SLUG> BC-CENSUS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CENSUS DENIES COUNTS WERE SHAKY AT 15 LOCAL OFFICES
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau should review its population
counts in areas covered by 15 of the agency's 510 local offices
nationwide _ including parts of western and northwestern
metropolitan Atlanta _ to assure an accurate tally, according to
the House Republican who heads the subcommittee on the census.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., told reporters Tuesday he was concerned
that the Census Bureau was in ``a rush to finish at the expense of
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   But Census Bureau officials said there was no cause for concern,
and suggested that the Republican-controlled subcommittee was
misrepresenting the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Miller cited Census Bureau offices that encountered initial
resistance from the public in filling out their census forms and
then surged in later weeks of the count.
</P>
<P>
   The data from these offices suggests ``fraud or irregular
procedures,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman said the Census Bureau has ample quality-control
reviews in place and that there was no concern that the head count
in the Atlanta district or in the other 14 offices cited by Miller
had gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at those numbers every day,'' said Census Bureau
spokesman Steve Jost.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a report produced July 18 by the subcommittee's staff,
based on information supplied by the Census Bureau, Miller
questioned why the Atlanta-West office had a remarkable surge in
its count of the 55,280 housing units in its area of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta office _ which covers portions of downtown, College
Park, Hopeville and East Point _ jumped from 5 percent of all
households completed in the first week of the count to 23 percent
in the second week.
</P>
<P>
   Jost said the steep increase was due to an agency decision to
add additional census-takers to the Atlanta-West office, a common
practice in hard-to-count inner cities throughout the enumeration
period in April and May.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have told the subcommittee not to misrepresent the data
because they are not easily interpretable to the public,'' Census
Director Kenneth Prewitt said in a conference call with reporters.
``But obviously they have not done so.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said his concerns were prompted by Census Bureau recounts
in portions of Chicago and Hialeah, Fla., because of suspicions
that census workers cut corners to complete the count.
</P>
<P>
   The other offices cited Tuesday by Miller include: three in the
Los Angeles area; two in New York City; two in Chicago; and one
office each in Philadelphia; Newark, N.J.; Marion County, Ind.;
Florence, Ala.; Las Vegas, Nev.; Rapid City, S.D.; and Newcastle,
Del.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
