<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-NOPEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOST CHANCE FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is the nature of statecraft and of the Mideast that today's
missed opportunity may presage tomorrow's calamity. There is a
danger that something worse than frustration will result from the
failure of Israel and the Palestinians to strike a historic
compromise at Camp David after two weeks of negotiations shepherded
by President Clinton. Both sides will now be tempted to regress
toward familiar poses of pure intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Clinton acknowledged the stalemate at Camp David
than Israeli and Palestinian officials took to blaming the other
side for causing an impasse. Yasser Arafat's entourage complained
that the Israelis never budged from their refusal to concede
complete Palestinian sovereignty over East Jerusalem. Members of
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's Israeli delegation blamed Arafat for
never once departing from his starting position on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton made a point of bestowing particular praise on
Barak for showing ``courage'' and ``vision,'' there was no
immediate benefit from the compromises offered by either side on
any of the core issues. The ground rules for the Camp David talks
precluded any partial progress, demanding as they did a
comprehensive and final agreement or no agreement at all.
</P>
<P>
   One ominous possibility is that, despite the areas of achievable
compromise revealed in the negotiations, Arafat's inability to
accept anything less than complete sovereignty over East Jerusalem
reveals a chasm that cannot be bridged anytime soon. The fault for
this difference on Jerusalem need not be blamed on Arafat or Barak
alone. Its origins are rooted in history, religion, and political
mythology.
</P>
<P>
   It is crucial that both leaders now keep their commitments to
refrain from taking unilateral actions. If Arafat carries out his
pledge to declare a Palestinian state unilaterally in the event
there is no negotiated agreement by Sept. 13, the gesture will
likely cause most harm to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   After a short interlude for reflection, Clinton should summon
the two sides back to the bargaining table to bridge their
differences. The alternative, as he said Tuesday, is unthinkable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
