<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-PLATE-PAINTING-NYT &LR;      07-25 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATE-PAINTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAINTED PLATES? HOW 15 MINUTES AGO! 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some things you don't notice until they're gone. The
painted plate is one of them. It was not too many years ago that no
plate left a New York kitchen until, like a subway car parked
overnight in a rail yard, it had been decorated in drips, dots,
dabs and hash marks.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic squeeze bottles in hand, Manhattan's chefs rebelled at
the sight of white. Every square inch of blank, shiny china
beckoned like a freshly stretched canvas, begging for a Jackson
Pollock makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Now, white is making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze bottles are still around, but now, more often than
not, they serve a purely utilitarian function. They're great for
storing sauces, vinaigrettes, oils and vinegars. They come in handy
when a chef needs to direct a precise squirt of flavoring. And
pastry chefs are never going to release their grip. The squeeze
bottle is simply too efficient a writing instrument when it's time
to put a sweet signature on dessert. But the great fiesta of finger
painting, like the era of tall food, seems to be over.
</P>
<P>
   Its history is obscure, but it's always safe to blame anything
on nouvelle cuisine. When chefs began developing brightly colored
sauces based on previously unimaginable ingredients, it became
tempting to lay down a perfect puddle of vermilion, or kelly green,
on the discus-size plates that nouvelle favored. With a new,
broader palette, the door was open for a technological breakthrough
in applying the new colors.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for certain who first hit on the idea of the
squeeze bottle, but Jean-Jacques Rachou, the owner of La Cote
Basque, is happy to put himself forward as a candidate. ``I
invented it in 1975 or 1976, when we were starting to use the
lighter sauces,'' he said. Inspiration came after he made a beurre
blanc with saffron. The writing was on the wall. And then, almost
instantly, on the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Moonen, the executive chef at Oceana, said: ``I was
commissioned to buy the bottles. I'd go to the hair-dye section of
the drugstore and buy dozens of the tint and tone bottles.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the painted plate appeared everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the early- to mid-'90s, people were just going crazy with
it,'' said Bobby Flay, a chef who painted with the best of them not
so many years ago, smitten after seeing his first squeeze bottle in
use at Cafe Annie in Houston about 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a piece of technology, it could not be beat. Previously, Flay
and his assistants stored their liquids in wine bottles and,
positioning a thumb over the mouth of the bottle, directed a more
or less steady stream of liquid over the plate. The squeeze bottle
brought instant precision to an imprecise art.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first discovered it, I was definitely taken by it,''
Flay said. ``It was like a new toy.'' Gradually, he worked through
his obsession. He uses the bottles, but not to decorate. ``When I
see sauces on a plate, it drives me nuts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze bottle lent itself to the vibrant colors of Nuevo
Latino and Southwestern cuisine, and to the precious ``small food,
big plate'' format favored by the newer restaurants. Colors and
designs that had been limited to the dessert menu suddenly invaded
the world of appetizers and main courses.
</P>
<P>
   Then, inevitably, the backlash came. Douglas Rodriguez, of
Chicama, well remembers his personal epiphany. ``I overheard a chef
referring to `squirt-bottle cuisine,''' he said. ``I've kept away
from it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chefs have stuck with the squeeze bottle but adopted a
more chaste approach. Andrew DiCataldo, the executive chef at
Patria, likes to circle the plate with dots of diminishing size.
``We use them for herb oils when we really want to control the
amount of oil or sauce on the plate,'' he said. ``It gives you the
essence of the flavor and not a big, greasy slick.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonen still likes to brighten the plate with a dot or a blob,
but not with the sauces that he used back in the days of La Cote
Basque. He sticks to oils, or thickened pepper juices.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, color thrown out the door can come in through the
window. Rodriguez likes to add a touch of brightness with
microgreens, and a lot of chefs seem to be discovering the
eye-pleasing pleasures of brightly colored vegetables, which can be
sliced as finely as thread, deep fried and then piled in a
glorious, tousled toupee atop a main course.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative to liquid color is dry pigment, like a dusting
of cayenne pepper sprinkled with bits of chive or bell pepper.
Another is liquid whipped into a decorative froth.
</P>
<P>
   The squeeze bottle, meanwhile, seems to be wandering the
devolutionary road followed by all trends, which make their way to
the outer boroughs and farther afield, eventually arriving at
destinations like Toledo and Indianapolis. By that time, New York
may be ripe for a revisionist school.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's always foam. We just need someone to
figure out how to get it into a spray gun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
