u f BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-25 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T REPORTS MIXED RESULTS AMID CONCERNS ABOUT GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T reported quarterly earnings Tuesday that modestly exceeded
analysts' expectations. But the company's revenue growth continued
to slow down amid deepening erosion in the core consumer
long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the complexity of AT&AMP;T, the nation's No. 1
long-distance carrier and No. 1 cable television provider, its
overall financial picture is relatively simple. While some of the
company's newer operations, including wireless, are performing
well, the shrinking of the consumer long-distance business makes it
tough for the company to show satisfactory growth.
</P>
<P>
   And in some ways that task is expected to become even tougher
through the end of 2001 because AT&AMP;T will lose the ability to use
its fast-growing wireless unit to buoy its overall financial
results. As AT&AMP;T distributes its remaining 84 percent stake in
separately traded AT&AMP;T Wireless Group to its own shareholders, the
parent company will stop consolidating the wireless unit's results
into its own.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, AT&AMP;T has been able to modestly exceed Wall
Street earnings projections, at least in part because of aggressive
cost-cutting. But that path will not be sustainable indefinitely.
At some point, earnings growth must emerge not from lower costs but
from the introduction of higher-profit services and, preferably,
from robust revenue growth. If the strategy that C. Michael
Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman, has mapped out for the company's future
is to succeed, the revenue growth will soon have to emerge in force
from AT&AMP;T's cable unit.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the company's depressed stock price appears to
be drawing it ever closer to creating additional spinoffs along the
lines of the new shares AT&AMP;T issued earlier this year to track the
wireless unit. In a conference call with analysts Tuesday,
Armstrong responded to a question about a possible spin-out of the
company's consumer long-distance business by mentioning some of the
positive effects such a move would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enterprise share price doesn't represent the asset values
that we have,'' he said, ``nor the growth that we're scaling.''
Without the consumer unit, he said, AT&AMP;T could be seen as a $42
billion company growing at 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not that many enterprises of this size hanging around
that have that kind of growth and scaling as we go into 2001,''
Armstrong added.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T gained 68.75 cents Tuesday, to close at $34, in New York
Stock Exchange trading of nearly 35 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed somewhat encouraged that, excluding special
charges, the company earned $1.88 billion, or 57 cents a share, in
the second quarter. That was more than 16 percent higher than
earnings of 49 cents a share in the corresponding period a year
earlier and 4 cents higher than the consensus estimate by analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Charles H. Noski, AT&AMP;T's chief financial officer, predicted that
earnings in the current quarter, excluding special charges, would
be 40 to 43 cents, higher than the 37 cent estimate of First Call
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the numbers, the second-quarter did not reflect any
gangbusters operational performance. In an interview, Noski said
that about 2 cents of the second-quarter earnings were a result of
higher interest income on AT&AMP;T's cash investments. Some analysts
also gave some credit to the company's success in trying to
eliminate $2 billion in costs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the second quarter, AT&AMP;T showed its worst quarterly
revenue growth in almost two years. Adjusting for the impact of the
acquisitions of the MediaOne Group and IBM's Global Network
operation, the company had pro forma revenue growth of 4.5 percent,
to $16.9 billion. In the second quarter of 1999, pro forma revenue
growth was 6.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit last quarter was, as usual, the consumer
long-distance unit, whose sales shrank more than 7 percent, to $5
billion from $5.4 billion in the 1999 period. In quarters past,
AT&AMP;T's unit serving business customers could be counted on to pick
up the slack, but that unit stumbled earlier this year as it tried
to transfer some big corporate customers to Concert, AT&AMP;T's joint
venture with British Telecommunications. In the second quarter, the
business-services unit posted growth of only 4 percent, to $6.9
billion, and the company said yesterday that the unit would grow
only 6 percent this year rather than the roughly 8 percent it had
sought.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's cable unit grew a strong 10.5 percent, to $2.4 billion in
revenue during the quarter. To meet its targets, AT&AMP;T must deploy
local phone service over cable lines to at least 300,000 additional
homes in areas previously served by Tele-Communications Inc. by the
end of the year. Including areas previously served by MediaOne,
however, the company is already delivering such service to a
quarter-million homes across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Including all special charges, AT&AMP;T reported earnings of $1.75
billion, or 53 cents a share, for the quarter, up from $1.59
billion, or 49 cents, during the second quarter of 1999. AT&AMP;T
formally reported revenue of $16.22 billion, up from $15.75 billion
during the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Wireless reported impressive results Tuesday. Revenue
increased almost 32 percent from the second quarter of 1999, to
$2.5 billion from $1.9 billion. Earnings more than doubled to $200
million from $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The AT&AMP;T Wireless Group rose $2.3125 Tuesday, to $29.375, in
trading of 12.6 million shares. The stock was offered to the public
in April at $29.50 a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
