<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHENEY: DADDY'S BOY LOOKS BACKWARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's selection of a veteran
of his father's Cabinet as his running mate indicates that the son
wants to run another cautious, status-quo administration just like
dear old dad's.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate question is: What does 59-year-old former
Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney, out of the public eye for a
decade, bring to the Republican presidential ticket?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: a calming influence on those skeptics who simply don't
believe the junior Bush is intellectually up to the challenges of
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But is Cheney's experience, friendship with daddy and political
stature enough to get the ticket to the White House? Not by itself.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a better move than picking a coltish, doltish young man
in hopes of creating a glamour quotient, as papa Bush did when he
foolishly made Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana his 1988 choice for veep.
</P>
<P>
   This time the Republicans are fielding daddy's boy, propped up
by daddy's man. It's up to the candidate himself to provide the
glamour and the running mate to provide the substance.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has a formidable reputation within the Republican
establishment for integrity, wisdom and fairness. If you like
conservatives, this is, as Bush said, ``a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   But his mere selection is a public admission that Bush needs all
the help he can get and that he will look to the past, not the
future, for it. His father's influence, mostly hidden until now,
suddenly looms over the scene like that giant spider sculpture in
the doorway of the new Tate Gallery in London.
</P>
<P>
   Are we being asked to vote on a candidate who is his own man or
one who needs a babysitter, or many babysitters?
</P>
<P>
   Does the country really pant for a repeat of his father's
administration, which voters rejected in 1992 for that rascal Bill
Clinton? Think recession. Think goofy remarks. Think boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Texas governor has been trying to project the
fresh face of change, reflecting new directions and a revitalized
moral tone for the nation. He describes himself as an ``outsider,''
someone who would reject ``old-style Washington politics,'' in
contrast to that ultimate insider, Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This line was always political hokum, coming from the son of a
former president, but Cheney's presence unmistakably strips away
the final shreds of that pretense. In addition to his
identification with the GOP old guard, Cheney had a voting record
as a Wyoming congressman that rigidly followed party doctrine _
anti-gun control, anti-abortion and anti-environment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether out of self-confidence or lack of it, Bush is not
embarrassed to defer to senior Republicans when he is on unfamiliar
policy terrain.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he disclosed his strategic nuclear reduction plan
_ a subject on which he has about as much expertise as I do _ while
surrounding himself with big-name Republican props. On the stage
with him were his father's national security adviser, Brent
Scowcroft; his father's chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
Colin Powell; President Ronald Reagan's secretary of state, George
Shultz, and President Richard Nixon's secretary of state Henry
Kissinger.
</P>
<P>
   It was an old boys' club with a younger guy looking out of place
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   We are getting here the image of a candidate who sees being
president as akin to being chairman of the board, relying on a
loyal team to do the real homework and the real thinking. The idea
is to go about a hard-line conservative agenda without being
harshly offensive and partisan about it.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is a team player who fits that mold. He does not offer
inflammatory, damaging sound bites. He is not a Patrick Buchanan,
constantly insulting those who dare disagree with him.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, so the new pair would work well together in the White
House. But first the Bush-Cheney ticket has to win an election. And
Cheney is not a great campaigner or a great speaker. His low-key
style reminds me of Washington Sen. Henry (Scoop) Jackson, a
much-admired heavy lifter who was the frontrunner for the 1972
Democratic nomination until voters discovered he had a mouth full
of mush.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney briefly flirted with a presidential campaign in 1996 and
found he neither liked the work nor persuaded voters to like him.
</P>
<P>
   He is, in fact, much like Jack Kemp, a popular Republican
insider who proved to be a dud as Bob Dole's 1996 running mate
because he had no instinct for the jugular and no passion for his
role. He might not have been a bad president, though.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had wanted an exciting ticket, he would have picked his
primary rival, Sen. John McCain. It would have been stronger than
Bush-Cheney. But Bush did not want to take a risk on a man he did
not trust.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Bush is to be credited with picking a running mate
qualified to assume the presidency himself if required. If Gore
does the same, as I think he will, we may finally have settled into
a political pattern in which we take the vice presidency seriously.
Hooray.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2780 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-LOYALTY-HNS &LR;      07-25 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-LOYALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH PUTS PREMIUM ON LOYALTY IN PICKING CHENEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     A News Analysis   
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his selection of Dick Cheney as his running
mate Tuesday, Republican George W. Bush underscored the premium
that the Bush family places on personal loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor set aside the traditional political calculus
of electoral punch, campaign pizzazz and diversity to select a man
whose reputation for loyalty and discretion was unblemished during
the 14 months he served as White House chief of staff to President
Gerald Ford in the 1970s and as secretary of defense in the Bush
administration through the Persian Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush said he decided to choose Cheney after working closely
with him the former Wyoming congressman since April on the
politically sensitive task of identifying prospective vice
presidential running mates and thoroughly checking their
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gradually I realized that the person who was best qualified to
be my vice presidential nominee was working by my side,'' Bush told
a boisterous rally in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush cited Cheney's ``outstanding judgment,'' his ``keen
insight'' and ``the thoughtful and thorough way he approached his
mission'' of screening prospective running mates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's personnel selections during two terms as governor of
Texas have been long on the loyalty trait and many of his closest
aides _ disparagingly called ``the Austin Mafia'' _ have been with
him since he took office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   A Yale college classmate, Clay Johnson, serves as Bush's chief
of staff. A long time chum from his days as a West Texas oil
entrepreneur, Don Evans, serves as Bush's national campaign
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Black, a Washington, D.C. political consultant who has
advised the presidential campaigns of both the Bushes, said Cheney
has proven to both father and son that he can keep confidences,
offer candid advice and serve as a loyal subordinate, no matter
what the outcome of a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney demonstrated as defense secretary that ``if the president
sets the policy, he'll carry it out,'' Black said. ``Whatever Gov.
Bush wants to do in the way of policy, Vice President Cheney will
do an excellent job of following the president's lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a presidential scholar at the Brookings
Institution who served four presidents in the White House, said the
Bush family has long emphasized loyalty as an iron-clad constant in
the tumultuous upheavals of state and national politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of family and the sense of loyalty go very deep
here,'' Hess said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush learned the value of personal loyalty while watching
his father fight his way to national prominence through the
hard-bitten politics of Texas in the 1960s when Republicans were so
scarce that mutual loyalty was essential for political survival in
the largely Democratic state.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush, who fought former California Gov. Ronald Reagan
for the GOP nomination in 1980 and lost, joined the Reagan-led
ticket that won the White House twice in the 1980s. Bush, as vice
president, won and cherished his reputation for loyalty to Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   When Vice President Bush fought off rivals for the GOP
nomination in 1988 and it came time to choose his own running mate,
he waved aside more prominent or politically experienced
prospective running mates to choose a running mate who could be
counted upon to be loyal.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush passed on nationally known politicians such as
Sens. Bob Dole, R-Kan., Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., and Pete Domenici,
R-N.M. to choose Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., then a 41-year-old ``Baby
Boomer'' politician who had not been tested in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson, a prospective running mate at the time, said that
Bush's choice had come in large part from his eight years as vice
president under Reagan ``when his L-word has been 'loyalty' [to
Reagan].''
</P>
<P>
   The president's son _ now the governor of Texas _ served as
loyalty enforcer for his father during the 1988 transition, making
sure that Bush loyalists won key positions in the holdover
Reagan-Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush also intervened toward the end of the Bush
presidency to help sack chief of staff John Sununu when political
backbiting had flared between the White House and the Bush
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   As president, Bush remained true to friends, even at a political
price. He named a longtime Texas ally, then-Sen. John Tower,
R-Texas, as his nominee for defense secretary after taking office
in 1989. But the nomination backfired in the face of senators'
antipathy to Tower's high-handed leadership of the Senate Armed
Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Senate rejection of Tower's nomination cleared the way for
President Bush to choose Cheney, then the popular minority House
whip, who quickly won Senate confirmation as defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush's renowned emphasis on loyalty made him known as
a politician who often seemed ``long on friends and short on
ideology,'' Hess recalled. ``That was both a strength and a
weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
