<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-CABLE-TV-ART-2     07-25 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-CABLE-TV-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SHEDDING CABLE TV ASSETS, IS DEUTSCHE TELECOM TRYING TO CURB
COMPETITION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Richard J. Callahan started his career
stringing telephone lines in South Dakota in the 1960s. Now he is
stringing together cable television systems in Europe, and he may
soon be one of its biggest operators.
</P>
<P>
   To the astonishment if not anger of many rivals, Callahan
recently outmaneuvered a number of European companies in acquiring
one big cable television system from Deutsche Telekom, Germany's
biggest telecommunications company. He is well on his way to
acquiring a second system from Telekom, the former government
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan's venture is a local sideshow to Deutsche Telekom's far
more prominent effort to buy VoiceStream, a cellular telephone
company in the United States. But it offers an important glimpse
into what some see as Deutsche Telekom's efforts to insulate itself
from competition at home, even as it seeks to expand abroad.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to plan, Callahan and his partners will
serve about one-third of Germany's 17 million cable customers by
the end of this year. And like a number of other cable operators,
Callahan has big plans for upgrading his systems to offer telephone
service, high-speed access to the Internet and interactive
television.
</P>
<P>
   But looming over all these plans is the giant shadow of Deutsche
Telekom itself. The upgraded systems would compete directly with
Deutsche Telekom, which has insisted on keeping a 45 percent stake
in each cable system. Indeed, other aspiring bidders complain the
German company went out of its way to make sure the cable systems
would be too fragmented to pose a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   Some go further, arguing that Deutsche Telekom intentionally
picked buyers who would be the least likely to cause it competitive
heartburn. When Deutsche Telekom announced plans to sell its cable
systems two years ago, more than 35 companies expressed interest.
Today, all but a handful of those companies have either dropped out
or have been deemed unqualified by Deutsche Telekom executives.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only people who have actually bought a system so far
are Callahan and a secretive American financier named Gary A.
Klesch. Even more striking, executives on all sides say that
Deutsche Telekom selected Callahan's bid even though it was lower
than one from the investment arm of Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear that Deutsche Telekom wanted to keep as much
control of these systems as it could,'' said Paul Thomassen, chief
financial officer of Primacom, Germany's fourth-largest cable
operator, whose bids were also rejected.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Callahan declined to be interviewed, saying that the company had
just completed a bond offering and was prohibited by U.S.
securities laws from making public statements.
</P>
<P>
   But Callahan has been quite public about his plans. As head of
international ventures from 1984 to 1996 for U S West, the regional
Bell telephone company, he helped launch Telewest, the British
cable company that was one of the world's first to offer telephone
and cable television over the same system.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   backed by investors like the Blackstone Group and GE Capital,
Callahan Associates International is already building advanced
cable systems in Spain and France and has raised nearly $8 billion
to pay for its German venture.
</P>
<P>
   Under orders from antitrust regulators at the European
Commission, who wanted to see cable systems competing with
telephone carriers, Deutsche Telekom agreed to spin off its cable
properties two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, Callahan's group paid about $3.5 billion
for a controlling stake in Deutsche Telekom's cable network in
North-Rhine Westphalia. Now he is in exclusive negotiations to buy
a second German system for nearly $2 billion, which would give him
control of about one-third of the German cable television market.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, however, Deutsche Telekom executives have
made it clear they are worried about somebody transforming the
cable systems into a nationwide rival of the phone company.
</P>
<P>
   To block potential buyers from establishing a nationwide
network, the German telephone giant divided its national network
into nine regions. It also insisted on retaining a 45 percent stake
in each of the systems, which is enough under German law to veto
mergers and perhaps capital increases as well.
</P>
<P>
   The most startling aspect of the process is the way buyers have
been selected. Executives on all sides of the auction say that
Callahan's bid for the North Rhine system was significantly lower
than an offer from Deutsche Bank's investment arm, DB Investor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Deutsche Telekom executives flatly rejected DB Investor's
bid. ``They basically told us they didn't want us to have those
systems, because it would make us too big,'' said one person close
to DB Investor, which had outlined plans to stitch together a
nationwide network.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich Lissek, a spokesman for Deutsche Telekom, insisted that
his company had no intention of blocking competition or influencing
the cable systems. But he acknowledged that the company had not
necessarily picked buyers who offered the highest price.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it is not interesting just to get the best price,''
Lissek said. ``The best price says nothing about the future of the
company, nothing about the targets of the owner and nothing about
the future of the employees.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Those arguments are believable when applied to Callahan. But
they strain credibility when applied to the other big winner in the
cable auctions, Klesch.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Callahan, Klesch has no experience in running cable
television systems or any other kind of communications business. As
founder of Klesch &AMP; Co. in London, he spent much of the last decade
investing in the securities of financially troubled European
ventures like the Channel Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Klesch's lack of experience, Telekom executives selected
him to buy a system that serves more than 1 million subscribers in
Hesse, the prosperous state that includes Frankfurt. As soon as
that deal closed, the company picked Klesch to enter exclusive
negotiations for two other systems in Lower Saxony and in eastern
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Klesch remains a mystery to most people in the industry and
refused to return numerous calls requesting an interview. He
appears to operate out of a small office in London with a handful
of employees. He has been secretive about his sources of financing,
but a prospectus for a new junk-bond offering earlier this month
disclosed that he recently sold a 35 percent stake in his German
venture to NTL Communications, which owns cable systems in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, by contrast, has been comparatively open. His company
has raised nearly $5 billion for its German efforts, including $1
billion from the Blackstone Group and other investors; more than $3
billion in senior debt and about $750 million in high-yield junk
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Klesch, Callahan has also recruited a high-powered team
of executives. Last month, he persuaded Andrew Sukawaty, the chief
executive of Sprint Corp.'s nationwide wireless telephone network,
to become president of Callahan Associates. William Barker, who had
previously headed a unit of GE Capital devoted to investments in
telecommunications, is one of Callahan's lead scouts for deals.
Many other executives are veterans from U S West International and
were involved in introducing Telewest and the One-2-One mobile
telephone network in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   None of that erases the question of whether Deutsche Telekom
will allow Callahan to operate freely in Germany. One of Telekom's
hottest businesses is providing Internet access, and it is
aggressively marketing high-speed lines known as digital subscriber
loops.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan, along with many other cable operators, plans to
compete head-to-head in those fields by upgrading the traditional
systems with fiber optics and two-way communications.
</P>
<P>
   Telekom executives made it clear more than a year ago that they
were worried about overly aggressive competitors. People close to
Telekom say one reason they were hostile to Deutsche Bank was that
they suspected it was acting as a front for Mannesmann, its
archrival in both wireless and hard-wired telephone services.
Mannesmann had wanted to bid on several cable properties, but was
turned down flat.
</P>
<P>
   Telekom executives had originally proposed selling only minority
stakes in its cable systems, but that idea was rejected by
antitrust regulators. But in retaining 45 percent of each system,
the telephone company can block mergers and other major corporate
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers are almost certain to be of critical importance, because
Callahan needs more scale in Germany and it also needs to acquire a
number of companies that actually own the wires into customers'
homes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Callahan executives say they negotiated legal agreements under
which Telekom agreed not to invoke its veto rights on questions
about capital increases. According to its bond prospectus, Telekom
also agreed not to veto most acquisitions within the cable system's
own region.
</P>
<P>
   But Deutsche Telekom did not agree to accept mergers with
neighboring cable operators automatically. That is potentially
important, because Callahan officials are already looking for other
networks to buy and link with their existing properties.
</P>
<P>
   Lissek, Telekom's spokesman, said his company simply wanted to
protect itself. ``If we go under 25 percent, the majority
shareholders can make a capital increase or a merger without our
agreement, and suddenly we are completely minority shareholders,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As if those restrictions were not enough, many industry
executives note that Deutsche Telekom will retain control over 10
channels _ expandable to 80 channels, if signals are transmitted
with digital technology _ that will be used to fulfill long-term
contracts between Deutsche Telekom and the Munich-based Kirch
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Telekom and Kirch have formed their own joint venture, called
MSG, which will transmit programming and has developed its own
system of encryption and billing. Though obscure, the demands to
accommodate Kirch and MSG worry outside programmers as well as
cable operators like Thomassen of Primacom.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan executives say they are not worried, but admit that
they will have to build additional capacity into the systems before
they can embark on their plans for offering full broadband services
to customers. That means heavy upfront expense with little initial
increase in revenue. Nobody is predicting profits for the next
several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' said one Callahan executive, ``is a long-term
position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
