<P>
   HDTV _ WASHINGTON _ Broadcasters tell a congressional committee
Tuesday the government should switch the national standard for
digital TV to one used in Europe. Cable interests fear the change
would let the broadcasters ``multiplex'' the digital signal into
several channels, allowing a consortium of local stations to
compete with cable. (Glass, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   RAND-SCHOOLS _ WASHINGTON _ Three popular education reforms seem
to have worked in some states between 1990 and 1996, according to a
massive RAND Corp. report to be released here Tuesday. Comparing
NAEP achievement scores by students from similar families from 44
states, the researchers found that fast-improving states like North
Carolina and Texas had smaller classes in the early grades, more
kids in public pre-kindergarten programs and a higher number of
teachers who said they had adequate resources than was true in
states like Georgia, where scores stagnated, or California, where
scores plunged in those years. Some other plausible explanations _
such as higher scores by students whose teachers had masters
degrees or higher salaries _ didn't pan out. But, years after the
fact, it now appears that the post-1996 decisions by policy-makers
to stress pre-k classes in Georgia and to lower class size in
grades 1 to 3 in California were smart moves. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 16.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: A national version has moved on the NYT wire. Versions with
inserts for each Cox state are available via the budget tool.
</P>
<P>
   CARA-FLA _ WASHINGTON - Florida could receive about $139 million
a year for the next 15 years under bill approved Tuesday by a
Senate committee.(Lipman, Cox News Service). 12.
</P>
<P>
   UGA-ADMISSIONS _ U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield had
warned about the ``road ahead.'' In prior rulings, the Savannah
jurist stated clearly that he believed the use of racial
preferences in college admissions was unconstitutional. In Monday's
order, he forcefully backed that up, retracing prior U.S. Supreme
Court rulings, disparaging pre-trial testimony by former UGA
president Charles Knapp and making UGA have to decide whether to
appeal on this very issue. Lee Parks, the lawyer for the women
plaintiffs, predicts he will now prevail in more recent lawsuits
challenging the 2000 freshmen class and law school admissions.
Comments from academics also and trying to reach victorious female
plaintiffs. (Rankin/McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau should review its
population counts in areas covered by 15 of the agency's local
offices nationwide _ including parts of metropolitan Atlanta _ to
secure an accurate count, according to the House Republican who
heads the subcommittee on the census. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TURNER-UNFOUNDATION _ Ted Turner's UN Foundation announced it
will provide more than $42 million to support UN social and
environmental projects worldwide. The foundation, which has awarded
more than $300 million in grants since 1997, will invest more than
$21 million to improve the social situation of adolescent girls in
countries ranging from Malawi to El Salvador and Mongolia to
Mauritania. In addition, the foundation will provide almost $13
million to clean arsenic-contaminated well water in Bangladesh and
protect coral reefs around the world. Other grants will be used for
providing health information on the Internet, studying the economic
agendas of factions in civil wars and evaluating an anti-personnel
landmine convention. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CONCORDE-CRASH _ PARIS _ An Air France Concorde jet, Flight
4590, crashed near a hotel outside of Paris Tuesday killing all 109
people _ passengers and crew _ on board. There are reportedly four
people dead on the ground, as well. It was a charter flight that
took off from Charles de Gaulle Airport with German tourists on
board en route to Ecuador via New York City. The crash comes just
days after British Airways grounded a Concorde jet for showing
cracks in its wings. But there is no evidence as to whether this
was at all involved in the crash. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News
Service). WITH GRAPHICS.
</P>
