   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   EDITORIAL-MARRIAGETAX _ You'd think the GOP had rewritten
Mendelssohn's wedding march the way it's touting its ``end to the
marriage penalty'' proposal. Party leaders pushed the tax relief
measure through both Houses in time for the opening of the
Republican Convention next week. The president should veto the
measure. (The Atlanta Constitution). 9.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ ``The definition of insanity is doing the same
thing over and over and expecting different results.'' This wisdom
_ variously ascribed to Einstein, Unknown, Anonymous and other
great thinkers of our time _ would seem to fit the persistent Star
Wars delusion. The scaled-down version that the Pentagon and a slew
of contractors and their political hangers-on are pushing recently
failed its third test, the one ballyhooed as the most telling.
(Teepen, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ As if the Middle East negotiations weren't
tangled enough, the Vatican has decided to insert itself into this
most difficult of situations. Last weekend, Pope John Paul II has
suggested that Jerusalem, the heretofore unfixable sticking point
of any negotiations, be internationally controlled. It has a
familiar ring to it, a quite familiar ring. This is what was first
decided by the United Nations in November 1947 when Palestine was
partitioned into separate Jewish and Arab states with Jerusalem as
an international enclave. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ PELEE ISLAND, Ont. _ Boy meets girl. Boy gets
girls. Boy and girl get married and open a bed and breakfast in the
far north boonies. Then one fine autumn morning, boy comes to
breakfast grumpy. Girl hasn't got a clue. He glowers. She chirps.
That's where the play begins. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ The issue may not be how exactly Texas' finances
shake down but how it continues to pace the nation in dereliction
with all that cash available, and how one could construe any of it
as compassionate conservatism. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   AOL-MERGER _ WASHINGTON _ When the Federal Communications
Commission meets Thursday to review the proposed combination of
America Online Inc. and Time Warner Inc., it will get an earful of
boos from merger opponents. In the seven months since the two
companies announced plans to combine forces, opposition has been
growing from companies that fear the creation of an ``arrogant''
monopoly. From media giant The Walt Disney Co. to Internet startup
Red Gorilla, competitors are complaining about what they consider
abusive business practices by either AOL or Time Warner. (Geewax,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   AID-DELAY _ A Senate subcommittee holds a hearing on aviation
consumer service and delays. The senators will review a new
Transportation Department study that says reported delays would
have been greater except that airlines have increased the scheduled
duration of many flights. (O'Dell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
15.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: Financial
investing for younger people. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TOO-MUCH _ Call it the revolt of the Soccer Mom. With the
proliferation of kid activities, and the sprawl that means they are
further apart, many families find they spend more time on the road
or with Little League coaches than with each other. With all the
shuttling, the average American mother now makes 5.5 car trips per
day, up from 3.5 in 1983, and compared with 4.5 trips for the
national average. One town in Minnesota is rebelling. We check with
Atlanta families, and with experts, some of whom are critical of
the current obsession with extracurriculars. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TOO-MUCH-STATS _ Statistics, According to a study by the
University of Michigan Institute for Social Research. Such as:
Families spend 137 percent more time driving to accomplish family
and personal errands than in 1969 and go 88 percent farther.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTSBEST-MOVIES _ What are the real movie hits so
far this year? Maybe ``Mission: Impossible 2'' did top $200 million
at the box office, but it also cost an estimated $125 million to
make. That makes its dollar-for-dollar return not so golden. The
really big financial hits this summer are the smaller budget movies
raking in unexpected millions _ namely ``Scary Movie,'' the
filmed-in-Georgia ``Road Trip'' and ``Big Momma's House.'' 9ongino,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-RAILROAD _ Movie review: ``Thomas &AMP; the Magic Railroad.''
Teeny kids' movie with Peter Fonda and Alec Baldwin. Grade: C+.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).TRAVELGETAWAY-BEACHES _
Pensacola, Fla. _ When we saw that Perdido Key was included in the
ranking of top 20 American beaches compiled by the expert who bills
himself as ``Dr. Beach,'' we had to check it out. But when we found
it to be, in our humble estimation, less than award-winning, we
decided to see how it ranked among this Panhandle city's other fine
beaches. In this report, we're not claiming to be real Dr. Beaches,
we're just playing one. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
30.
</P>
