<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      07-25 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATCHUP MADE IN GOP HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By selecting former Defense Secretary Richard B. Cheney as his
running mate, Governor George W. Bush Tuesday filled out the
Republican ticket _ and rounded out the GOP's own profile as it
heads toward the midsummer convention.
</P>
<P>
   In every respect _ in temperament, in background, in age, and
and outlook _ the running mate complements the candidate. It is a
classic matching of attributes. But in making the seemingly
risk-free decision to select a respected and seasoned party elder,
Bush may have taken the biggest risk of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Where Bush is an outsider, Cheney is an insider. Where Bush is
inexperienced, Cheney is tested. Where Bush is a blank page, Cheney
is reams of agate type on pages of the Congressional Record. Where
Bush came of age politically in the 1990s, Cheney came of age in
the 1970s. Where Bush leans to the middle, Cheney leans to the
right.
</P>
<P>
   They are, moreover, so compatible a team precisely because they
are so different.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is easy-going, Cheney is deliberative. Bush was unmarked by
the tensions of his time, Cheney is branded by them. Bush is
intuitive, Cheney is introspective.
</P>
<P>
   The governor calculated that the addition of a battle-tested
veteran of wars political, idological and military would complement
the profile of a candidate whose experience in elected office is
less than six years long. He sought, and found, a running mate who
offered comfort to the candidate and presumably will do the same to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, the selection of a onetime White House chief of
staff, House Republican leader and civilian commander of the
military was hailed by Republicans as the perfect match for the
party and, they hope, for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is, above all, steady. There will be no anxious moments
in debates, no stumbles on the campaign trail, no gaffes in
televised interviews. There will be no asides about ``Democrat
wars,'' as Senator Robert J. Dole made as the GOP's 1976
vice-presidential nominee, no moments of terror to compare with the
frightened look in Senator Dan Quayle's eyes during the 1988 debate
with Senator Lloyd M. Bentsen of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But in the uncertainties of American politics in the new
century, there is no assurance that a risk-free choice makes for a
risk-free strategy.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to avoid the error his father made in selecting an
unseasoned runningmate, Bush may be suggesting that he is fighting
the last campaign or, more specifically, the 1988 and 1992
campaigns. In seeking to install a mature figure at his side _ the
phrase that bounced around political circles in the wake of
Cheney's selection was that the man from Wyoming was an ``adult'' _
Bush may be risking the conclusion that the man who wants to lead
the country himself is in need of a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the selection of a running mate who is so
experienced, so safe and so familiar runs the risk of undercutting
the campaign's effort to position itself as an agent of excitement,
experimentation and change.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, however, Bush has hired a man who knows
Washington, knows the government, knows the White House, knows the
business world and knows his own mind. The danger _ and this the
Bush campaign understands_ is that Cheney's own mastery of all
those areas may exceed the governors.
</P>
<P>
   That said, leadership is an intangible quality, resistant to
definition. Bush will formally receive the Republican nomination
next week because of a bundle of intangibles: his personality, his
ability to set others at ease, his insight that the party would
embrace a conservatism-in-a-velvet-glove, his impulse to reach out,
not only to Democrats but also to the minorities and the striving
who through much of the last century found the Republican Party
inhospitible.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is a master of the levers of government. Bush is a master
of the reflexes of the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of Cheney is the modern affirmation of one of the
principles of Richard M. Nixon, who twice ran for vice president
and four times selected a vice president. Nixon's maxim was simple:
Be assured that your number two does no harm.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney will do no harm. And it may not matter if he does no
good.
</P>
<P>
   This month the CBS News poll surveyed American adults and asked
them whether they had ever changed their minds or voted for a
different presidential candidate because of the identity of the
vice-presidential contender. Only one in 11 said they had. And
eight out of nine said they had not.
</P>
<P>
   But the very process of selecting a vice president _ of making a
high-level, high-profile, high-stakes appointment in the middle of
a presidential campaign _ shapes more than a ticket. It shapes how
a presidential candidate is viewed. Bush has made a choice, not
about a runningmate but about himself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POPULAR-COLLEGES-NYT &LR;      07-25 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPULAR-COLLEGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS COLUMN: FINDING THE `HOT SCHOOL' FOR YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATE ZERNIKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, convinced that it could attract more students if it
could just show them what happens in the classroom, Mount Holyoke
College tried out a new marketing strategy: it sent professors to
three cities to teach hourlong lectures, much like what they would
teach back on campus, to prospective applicants.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when colleges wrangle over who ranks highest on the
``most wired'' list, it seemed like such a quaint idea, almost
naive: lure 'em with good teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But it hooked me. I walked away from the biology lecture
wondering not only why, when I looked at colleges in the 1980's, I
hadn't considered a women's college, but also why I had not thought
more seriously _ that is to say, at all _ about studying science.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Because I did like so many other people did, and do:
with the wisdom typical of age 16, I chose the ``hot'' school _ so
hot that it was pictured on the cover of The New York Times
Magazine with the headline ``The Hot School,'' so hot that it
didn't accept me, leaving me to scramble for an alternative that
worked out, but far from ideally.
</P>
<P>
   Just punishment, then, that I should be assigned to cover
education, a job that means I find myself at least once a week
asking why I didn't consider this college or that, depending on
whatever program I've just visited, whatever professor or college
president I've just interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The point is not so much that I should have studied medicine or
gone to Mount Holyoke (though I did discover that one dowager left
a chunk of her fortune to ensuring the nightly tradition of milk
and cookies in the dorms, which I found pretty appealing). The
point is that like so many prospective college students, I never
thought outside the ``hot'' box.
</P>
<P>
   Hot has only gotten hotter since I set my sights on Duke, in
vain. There are more than 3,000 colleges in the United States. Yet
the ``Harvard or bust'' mentality has grown so frenzied that
excellent colleges complain that they have to give more financial
aid based on merit and less based on need because the only way they
can attract good students away from the big names is to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   I can't help but wonder whether if everyone did for a living
what I now do _ or at least the parents and students out touring
colleges this summer _ people might be less obsessed with the hot
school and more interested in what schools work best for them.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing they'd realize is how many interesting things
are happening at so many different colleges. How about a place
where the college president still teaches class, engagingly so? A
place where alumni barons of the new economy come back to lecture
in small seminars about what they've learned? A place with strong
mentoring? A place that demands that students learn to write and
speak well, whether they major in engineering or English? A state
college that affords you the opportunity to take courses as well at
the most exclusive liberal arts college in the nation, while paying
less than $10,000 a year? These are all things happening at good
colleges whose names aren't among the five or so hot schools that
every student in the country seems to want to attend.
</P>
<P>
   They might also see that hot is a pretty empty concept, based
mostly on rankings that in themselves are fairly arbitrary. The
most popular guides devise rankings based on the number of alumni
donations, the number of students per faculty member, the number of
applications rejected. Some schools have explicitly said they shape
their budgets to make themselves look better in rankings. Others
assemble teams of staff specifically to figure out how to list
information in a way that will lift the ranking; they can dance on
the head of a pin to find the most flattering definition of
``faculty'' or ``alumni.'' Which is better, a school that's figured
out how to ace the rankings, or one that serves students well?
</P>
<P>
   If I were going to do it all over again, knowing what I have
learned from colleges across the country, I would consider the
larger state schools, and smaller strong liberal arts colleges in
the Midwest. I would sit in on classes, and not just English
classes, but physics classes, too. As that lecture last fall taught
me, a professor's ability to intrigue the uninitiate is a pretty
good indication of how dedicated a college is to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   I would remember that college is about exploring your options,
and look for a place strongly encouraging that. I would remember,
too, that college is what you make of it, no matter where you are.
</P>
<P>
   It's become easy to say that professors at research universities
don't do enough teaching. That, too, isn't always true; I've met
plenty of professors and deans at Harvard who care about individual
students. But these aren't the schools for everyone. The trick, as
guidance counselors try to convince their students every year,
isn't to get into the best college. It's to find the best college
for you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
