<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2809 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-LUCENT-SPRING-BOS &LR;      07-25 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-SPRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT PAYING $1.3 BILLION FOR BAY STATE STARTUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Global telecommunications giants appear to have lost none of
their billion-dollar appetite for Massachusetts start-ups selling
innovative products and services they feel they need to compete _
the latest example being Lucent Technologies grabbing a Maynard
company for $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to bolster its strength to compete with Cisco Systems,
Nortel Networks, and others in offering Internet protocol
telecommunications services, Lucent said Tuesday it would issue
26.8 million of its shares to acquire Spring Tide Networks Inc., in
which Lucent already held a 4 percent stake. Two-year-old Spring
Tide has 130 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly speaking, Spring Tide sells devices and software to
allow phone companies and communications providers to deliver
profitable services over any kind of high-capacity network,
landline or wireless, such as private internal networks with
``firewalls'' for businesses and ``follow-me'' one-phone-number
services for business people and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Davidson, president of Lucent Technologies InterNetworking
Systems business, said the deal reflected Lucent's conviction that
``no one company has all the good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see companies that have good ideas that I haven't
thought of, I quickly form a relationship with them,'' Davidson
said.
</P>
<P>
   If those ``good ideas'' are compelling enough, analysts said,
using Lucent's battered but still richly appreciated stock to buy
them becomes a powerful way to fuel the company's efforts to keep
up with the Internet revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, Corning Inc., and Nortel have been no less shy about
using their bull market-fattened share prices to grab promising Bay
State start-ups, in a process many analysts compare to the giants
effectively ``outsourcing'' research and development work to little
companies they later buy for hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Lucent has looked to Massachusetts start-ups
to fill perceived product-line holes in everything from billing
systems, optical networking gear, and super-fast Internet routers
to software-based telecommunications switches that make adding new
calling features as easy as rewriting computer programs, instead of
having to install expensive new boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and industry officials generally were enthusiastic
about the deal, but cautioned that one deal alone will not leapfrog
Lucent ahead of networking market giant Cisco Systems or emerging
challenger Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good acquisition for Lucent, and Spring Tide's
a great company,'' said Hassan Ahmed, president and chief executive
of Sonus Networks Inc. in Westford, who founded Sonus in 1997 soon
after his last company, Cascade Communications successor Ascend
Communications, was purchased by Lucent for nearly $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed said Spring Tide is a leader among companies that are
focusing on helping telecommunications providers offer profitable
services over newer, higher-capacity networks, independent of
whether those are landline, wireless, or cable broadband links.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucent is using the acquisition as a method of getting
themselves into the new technology arena, where arguably they need
more strength in the data world,'' Ahmed said. ``The real challenge
for them once they've acquired these companies is to put the pieces
together and make them all work.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said Lucent will continue to use the Spring Tide brand
name and plans to incorporate it into the Murray Hill, N.J.-based
company as its own operating unit.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide chief technology officer Steve Akers will become CTO
for the entire Lucent unit, which also includes the former Nexabit
Networks in Marlborough, which makes super-high speed Net routers,
and Xedia in Acton, which Lucent bought last year for a combined
total of over $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide CEO Allan Wallack and founder Stephen Collins said
they will stay with Lucent. Top Spring Tide executives come from
Stratus Computer Co., where they developed ``fault tolerant''
computers designed to work all but minutes or seconds a year.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition did not come as a complete bolt from the blue.
Lucent last December formed a comarketing arrangement with Spring
Tide that has led to deals including a $250 million pact announced
last week with AT&AMP;T Broadband to build out its fixed-wireless
network across the US. It also took a 4 percent stake in Spring
Tide in January as part of a venture capital round.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.3 billion purchase price is a home run for venture firms
that have put in a total of $62.9 million, among them North Bridge
Venture Partners, Matrix Partners, Oak Investment Partners, and
Meritech Capital Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has bought 35 companies in the last four years, including
nine this year, most of them focused on fiber optics. Spring Tide
is the second Net-oriented company, and is aimed at a market that
is expected to grow from $660 million annually to $1.6 billion next
year, according to market researchers Ryan Hankin Kent Inc. of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it will take a charge against earnings in whatever
quarter the Spring Tide deal is completed. It said it hopes to
close the deal by Sept. 30. Lucent said the deal will cut earnings
per share by about 1 cent in the fiscal year that begins in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide sells platforms for delivering IP-based services,
which convert voice into Net-style data packets and reconnect it to
create continuous sound, over virtually any kind of network,
including landline, wireless, cable broadband, and digital
subscriber lines. By converting voice to data packets it becomes
possible to add countless new services such as ``unified
mailboxes'' collecting voice mail, e-mail, and faxes in one place.
</P>
<P>
   Davidson said in her view Spring Tide has no direct competitor
in New England because its devices have a unique combination of
reliability, service features, and ``scaleability,'' or the ability
to quickly plug in more users as demands for access grow.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Tide's IP Service Switch 5000 works hand-in-glove with
several Lucent products, including devices for providing DSL lines
and several types of routers and switches. ``Spring Tide's people,
technology and equipment will play a crucial role in our broadband
Internet infrastructure strategy,'' Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent shares dropped 37.5 cents Tuesday to $49.875 in New York
Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1914EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
