<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-VILLALONGA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VILLALONGA EXPECTED TO STEP DOWN AT TELEFONICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chairman of the Spanish telecommunications company that is
acquiring Lycos Inc. is expected to resign, but it was unclear how
the move would affect the planned purchase of Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Villalonga, the controversial chairman of Telefonica SA,
could step down or be asked to leave at a regular company board
meeting scheduled for Wednesday, said an executive familiar with
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A Telefonica spokesman declined to discuss whether Villalonga's
departure would interrupt the company's $12.5 billion deal to
purchase Lycos, of Waltha, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos chief executive Bob Davis said Tuesday the deal would
remain on track no matter what Villalonga's fate. ``This deal was
put together with four strong companies, and it will remain that
way,'' Davis said, echoing previous remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strength of this transaction would not in any way be
lessened by the departure of any one individual,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga has been the driving force behind the expansion of
Madrid-based Telefonica, which in May announced plans to buy Lycos
and merge it with its Terra Networks Internet unit to create a
global content and services company known as Terra Lycos. German
publisher Bertelsmann also pledged to buy up to $1 billion worth of
advertising and services in the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   But Villalonga's aggressive strategy alienated many in Spain's
business establishment, and he also faces an insider-trading
investigation by Spanish government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   While he denies wrongdoing, a Villalonga departure wouldn't be a
surprise to many investors and analysts. The question, they say,
would be whether a successor would follow through with the
agreement to acquire Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Telefonica, representatives of Terra Networks and
Bertelsmann declined to discuss the issue. Many investors hope
Telefonica's board agrees to continue with the Lycos purchase,
since the merger has driven Lycos stock up from around $35 a share
before the merger. Lycos shares closed at $59.69, a gain of $2.81
on the day.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal is completed, Lycos shareholders would receive a
projected $97.55 worth of Terra shares for each of their existing
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Terra Lycos would have its headquarters in Barcelona, though
plans call for Davis to continue to run it as chief executive from
Waltham, where Lycos has about 600 employees. Villalonga was slated
to become chairman of the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   Villalonga's expected departure was first reported by Madrid's
El Mundo newspaper, which supports Spain's center-right government.
The newspaper reported a decision might be delayed several days,
however, because of a death in Villalonga's family.
</P>
<P>
   With Villalonga's position in question, speculation on a
successor centered on Cesar Alierta Izuel, head of Spain's monopoly
tobacco company. ``Alierta is the only candidate that can be named
quickly'' under complicated succession rules, Luis Padron, a
telecommunications analyst at Banesto Bolsa SA, told Bloomberg
News. Izuel's views on the Lycos deal aren't known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
