u f BC-MA-TAXES-BOS &LR;      07-25 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TAX REVENUES SURGE 10 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With Massachusetts enjoying the bounty of a robust and
long-running economic expansion, the state's tax revenues surged 10
percent in fiscal year 2000, which ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Revenue confirmed Tuesday that
the $15.7 billion collected in the last fiscal year was a record.
And while collections of revenues have risen every year since 1990
_ that year, revenues declined in the midst of a deep recession _
last fiscal year's increase was unusually large.
</P>
<P>
   The annual report on the state's fiscal condition comes as
lawmakers on Beacon Hill last week approved a $21.55 billion budget
for the coming fiscal year, which includes a $164 million tax cut
for charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Paul Cellucci is also currently being watched for possible
vetoes of items in the Democratic Legislature's budget. The
Republican governor, for example, is expected to veto a raise for
low-paid workers at state-sponsored nursing homes, though the
administration is likely to approve funds for financially
distressed hospitals. Lawmakers are also in the throes of
negotiating a financing package for a new baseball park for the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Revenue Department said the 10 percent revenue gain in
fiscal 2000 surpassed last year. In fiscal year 1999, by
comparison, the state collected $14.29 billion _ about a 2 percent
gain over the prior year. In 1999, a doubling in the personal
exemption allowed for individuals cut into tax receipts, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's primary sources of revenue are individual income
taxes, sales taxes, and corporate excise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   James St. George, executive director of the Tax Equity Alliance
for Massachusetts, a liberal tax advocacy group, said that he
believes last year's revenue may have also benefited from capital
gains earned on stock portfolios and from stock options granted
Massachusetts workers, particularly in the booming high-technology
industry. The alliance, he said, is researching the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is a bubble, the state could be in a lot of trouble,''
said St. George, who criticized a tax cut at a time state schools
are in dire need of funds.
</P>
<P>
   But Frederick Laskey, Massachusetts' revenue commissioner, said
stock gains were only ``a modest part'' of the state's bonanza.
Income tax and sales tax receipts are up, Laskey said, because so
many people are working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got record low unemployment, record high employment and
very strong wage growth,'' the commissioner said. ``That translates
into very robust revenue collections for us.'' He said
Massachusetts is ``doing very well'' compared with other states.
</P>
<P>
   In fiscal 2000, individuals paid $9.041 billion in income taxes,
more than $1 billion above what they paid during the prior year,
according to Revenue Department data, which was initially released
on July 14.
</P>
<P>
   Sales and use taxes collections were $3.565 billion, up from
$3.270 billion in 1999. Corporate excise taxes totaled $3.093
billion, up from $2.984 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, corporate excise taxes were 10.3. percent of total
state collections, compared with 10.9 percent in fiscal 1991, the
revenue department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
