<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2812 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TOYSMART-AGREEMENT-BO     07-25 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSMART-AGREEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
38 STATE LEGAL CHIEFS PROTEST TOYSMART SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Attorneys general from 38 states joined a chorus of opposition
Tuesday to a Federal Trade Commission settlement that would allow
failed Internet retailer Toysmart.com to sell customer data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toysmart had an explicit promise to consumers that their
privacy would be protected and their information would not be
shared with a third party,'' Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas
F. Reilly said. ``I see the sale not only as a threat to consumers
but also to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The FTC sued the Waltham, Mass. toy seller earlier this month in
US District Court in Boston, saying the company had promised
shoppers it would never sell their personal information. Last week,
the federal agency reached an agreement allowing Toysmart.com to
sell customer files with certain restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, Toysmart.com could sell its database only
to a family-oriented company that buys the entire Web site and
adheres to the online retailer's privacy policy. The company also
must delete 2,000 records that the FTC said were collected in
violation of the Children's Online Privacy Protection Act, said
Harry Murphy, an attorney for Toysmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   The new law bars sites from gathering data from children younger
than 13 without permission from their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC's restrictions have not appeased consumers and privacy
advocates, who fear other beleaguered Internet retailers will
attempt to auction off customer data.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said Toysmart.com should not be allowed to sell the
database of more than 250,000 customer records without permission
from the retailer's shoppers. Without such protections, he fears
wary customers will begin abandoning the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is a balanced position,'' Reilly said. ``It
protects consumers. And it protects the Internet from itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is the leader among 38 states that filed an
objection to the sale in US Bankruptcy Court in Boston, where
Toysmart.com filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection last month.
Attorneys general from Texas and New York have filed separate
objections to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two potential buyers for the database have emerged.
Last week, Direct Research Inc. of Kennebunk, Maine, said it would
enter the bidding. A subsidiary of Walt Disney Co., Toysmart.com's
majority owner, has bid $50,000 for the customer files.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney subsidiary would not stand in the way if the court
awards the database to a buyer who abides by the online retailer's
privacy policy and uses the list in ``continuation of Toysmart's
business,'' said Andrew Schwartz, an attorney for the Disney unit.
</P>
<P>
   If no such buyer emerged, the Disney subsidiary would buy the
database and have it destroyed, Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement between the FTC and Toysmart.com requires the
approval of US Bankruptcy Judge Carol Kenner, who has scheduled a
hearing Wednesday in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the court ultimately is going to be faced with the
question of whether the settlement negotiated with the FTC
represents a fair balance between the interests of customers and
the needs of creditors,'' Toysmart attorney Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenner has a reputation as a no-nonsense judge who has stood up
to protect consumers in the past. She is perhaps best known for
exposing the unlawful collection practices of Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
_ after learning about the company's actions in a letter from an
unemployed and bankrupt security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Sears agreed to plead guilty to a criminal charge of
bankruptcy fraud and pay a record $60 million fine for illegally
collecting more than $100 million from bankrupt credit-card
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
