<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-GEORGIA0726-COX     07-25 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GEORGIA0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. - The heat has been turned up and the
expectations for this year's Georgia football team are boiling
over.
</P>
<P>
   From the preseason publications to the Bulldog Club meeting in
Macon to the massive media contingent here, inquiring minds want to
know: Is this the year the Bulldogs finally catch Florida and
Tennessee?
</P>
<P>
   Most preseason prognosticators think so. Georgia, which returns
19 starters from last year's 8-4 squad, has been ranked as high as
third nationally in preseason polls. The Bulldogs haven't won an
SEC title since 1982, and haven't finished in the top five in the
national rankings in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least one Georgia player believes this year's team
will be up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations are realistic,'' Bulldogs quarterback Quincy
Carter said. ``To me, winning the national championship is
realistic. But at the same time, we've got to understand that we
haven't accomplished any of those goals throughout the 1990s. To
start 2000 off with an SEC championship is our goal. I know the
stakes are high this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are especially high because Carter's junior season
will probably be his last one at Georgia. Bulldogs fans also are
impatient because Florida and Tennessee could be as vulnerable as
they've been in more than a decade. Both programs suffered heavy
personnel losses since last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of expectations and a lot of people are asking
me about our team,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``I do think
one of the reasons for the higher expectations is that we have a
lot of people coming back and Florida and Tennessee lost a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that is the main reason the Bulldogs seem to be a
popular pick to win the SEC East - over Florida and Tennessee,
which combined to win 17 of 18 games vs. Georgia in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bulldogs athletics director Vince Dooley, long known for
his conservative demeanor, sounds optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I'm more excited and more optimistic than
I've been in a long, long time,'' Dooley said at last week's Middle
Georgia Bulldog Club meeting in Macon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got the hour, and we've got the man, and when the two
meet, I think we're going to see something we're all going to be
very happy with.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan, who guided the Bulldogs to 27 wins the past three
seasons, seems to be the only one trying to temper expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to our team about the people saying that if
Georgia doesn't do it this year they'll never do it,'' Donnan said.
``I really think we're going to do it eventually. I feel that we've
laid a good foundation and are doing a lot of good things as a
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't say, `It's now or never.' The reality is that
we've got to be one of the best three or four teams in the country
to (win the SEC). We haven't proven that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Before last season, Donnan boasted that his program had closed
the talent gap on the Gators and Volunteers. The Bulldogs lost to
both of those schools by a combined score of 67-34, and the Georgia
defense finished last in the SEC, allowing 382.6 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan fired defensive coordinator Kevin Ramsey after only one
season, and replaced him with former Oklahoma head coach Gary
Gibbs, who had been retired since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Gibbs has a lot of experience,'' Georgia defensive
tackle Richard Seymour said. ``When you combine experience with
talent, it equals championships. I wouldn't trade our roster with
anyone right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs inherits a Georgia defense that includes three potential
first-round draft picks: Seymour and defensive tackle Marcus Stroud
and middle linebacker Kendrell Bell. But the Bulldogs must replace
two starters in the secondary and their punter and kicker.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgia must prove that it has finally reached its two
longtime rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked Georgia to win the SEC East,'' said John Adams,
sports editor of the Knoxville News-Sentinel, ``but there's little
conviction behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, they've got more talent than any team in the SEC.
But Georgia has to prove it can win the games that matter most.
Georgia has become what Tennessee once was - a team with a lot of
talent that has yet to win a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
