A2814 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS0726-CO     07-25 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Revised rules prominent as Olympic gymnastic selections begin
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - One fall no longer can doom aspiring Olympic gymnasts.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 John Hancock U.S. Championships begin today in St.
Louis. The top 14 men and 12 women advance to the Olympic trials,
Aug. 17-20 in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, each routine no longer is do or die. New
Olympic rules and a revamped selection process have led to the
possibility that a specialist or two on each team might go to
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually less pressure, I think,'' said Vanessa Atler,
18, one of the rising stars among U.S. women. ``If you've shown
that you've worked hard throughout the year, that's the big thing.
At Olympic trials, everybody's always afraid, `What if I mess up on
this one meet? This one meet determines, like, my whole life.' So I
think (the new procedure) is actually good.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team at the Olympics can bring six gymnasts. Five compete
on each apparatus, but only four scores will count, so a specialist
can shore up the weaker events.
</P>
<P>
   For the men, the four gymnasts with the best combined scores
from the nationals (40 percent) and the Olympic trials (60 percent)
will be on the team. The other two will be selected by coaches. For
the women, all six gymnasts will be selected by a four-member
committee, which includes national team coordinator Bela Karolyi.
The gymnasts' performances at the two major meets, as well as in
monthly training camps at Karolyi's ranch, will be factors.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the gold-medal-winning ``Magnificent Seven''
from Atlanta are back for another tumble at Olympic glory. Two-time
Olympians Shannon Miller and Dominique Dawes, as well as Jaycie
Phelps, came out of retirement, while Dominique Moceanu and Amy
Chow had remained competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who injured her leg in practice recently, might compete
only in balance beam and uneven bars in St. Louis and then petition
into the trials.
</P>
<P>
   Atler said she does not think the gold medalists should step
aside for the younger athletes, including her, Kristen Maloney and
Elise Ray and Morgan White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whoever wants to do it, and whoever wants to put in
the hard work, it's fine with me,'' she said. ``The better the
team, the better for the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi promises that the ``most spectaculous'' athletes will go
to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Men's team coordinator Peter Kormann, a 1976 Olympian, calls his
crop ``the deepest team that we've had in the last 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-time national champ Blaine Wilson is the top contender,
along with two-time Olympian John Roethlisberger, Jason Gatson and
Augusta's Jay Thornton. Thornton's brother, Todd, and former
Atlanta gymnast Michael Ashe also will compete.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
