<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SUSPENSE-HUNGRY PRESS LOOKING TO GORE
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   As George W. Bush named Dick Cheney the man he wants as his
vice-presidential running mate Tuesday, one big question loomed in
the minds of political pundits and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Already sure the Texas governor will be named the Republican
presidential candidate at the GOP national convention next week and
that Cheney is a cinch to win the delegates' approval as Bush's
running mate, the press was wrestling with one more
vice-presidential question.
</P>
<P>
   Who, they pondered, will Al Gore select to run on the Democratic
ticket with him?
</P>
<P>
   And that, friends and neighbors, sums up about as well as
anything the state of party politics and major party nominating
conventions in America.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the press, much less the public, had a clue Cheney
would be Bush's ultimate choice, the press already was so restless
with the Republican process, many members of the corps were picking
up on hints Gore might name his veep choice about the time the
final gavel came down at the GOP confab in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The idea would be to flatten the bounce the Texas governor
rightly could expect to lift his political standing as he and his
running mate come out of what rightly can be expected to be four
days of political sweetness and light among the GOPers.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, political media, thy true calling is as scenario spinners.
</P>
<P>
   Even to the very last, there were those who would not give up on
the prospect Colin Powell had changed his and his wife's minds and
he would run for vice president with Bush after all. They spun
wonderful yarns about how all the moves Cheney was making to clear
the way for him to become Bush's running mate actually were part of
a grand subterfuge designed to obscure the fact Powell would be on
the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   This example, as will be the increasing speculation about Gore's
final choice, is not simply a press device to create interest in
its product _ be it printed or broadcast. It, far more, is a way to
try to inject some suspense into a convention structure designed to
be suspenseful but reduced to being more informative pep rallies
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, while Bush's selection of Cheney may not play to
excite, it does a super job of strengthening what Bush considers
one of his strongest points as a candidate and a quality most
Americans would relish in a president.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney was chief of staff for former President Ford, he
served six terms as Wyoming's rep in the U.S. House, where he was
considered a leader who had no way to go but up, when he was tapped
by GWB's father to be secretary of defense in the elder Bush's
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   A strong, but calm, conservative, he is widely well-liked and
widely well-regarded by many Democrats _ including, at least at one
time, Al Gore _ and by many members of the Washington press corps.
</P>
<P>
   Who better, on reflection, to back up a presidential candidate
who is campaigning as someone who can, and will, tamp down the
partisan fires that have burned so hotly in Washington of late.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's ability to work well with Democrats has been one of his
greatest assets as governor of Texas. Even today, as Republican
Bush is campaigning to move way up the political ladder, current
Democratic Speaker of the Texas House Pete Laney still openly
speaks quite well of him.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, it has been reported that Jan Bullock, the
widow of Democrat Bob Bullock _ one long alternately revered and
feared as a political force in Texas _ will be one of several
Texans to introduce Bush the final night of the GOP convention when
he is to accept the presidential nomination in a speech that will
be madly critiqued for political eons yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   So yet to be interpreted ad infinitum _ maybe ad nauseam _ is
Bush's selection of Cheney as his running mate. There is no
question Cheney well meets the principal criteria Bush consistently
has said he was seeking in his choice for vice president: that he
be someone well-qualified to assume the presidency if need be and
that he be someone Bush likes and respects and who will be loyal to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but the wires hummed as the pompoms still were waving at the
GOP ticket's first appearance together. Cheney is not a bold
choice. He's safe, we were told. He's blah, we were not told but
led to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The suspense was gone from the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Now it centers on Gore, who, it already was being said Tuesday,
could really make political waves if he could figure out how to get
Colin Powell on his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a question. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
