<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-25 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CHENEY: HE'S CONSERVATIVE AND CIVILIZED
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's not to like about Dick Cheney, if you fancy a very
conservative-but-pragmatic internationalist Republican who's
familiar with the horrors that lurk in the loopy wing of his party.
Given George W. Bush's decision not to stand up to the
anti-abortion zealots, the Texas governor could have done a lot
worse in selecting a vice-presidential running mate.
</P>
<P>
   In a Republican context, Cheney is politically safe without
being boring. He's establishment without being Ivy League unto
death. There's a youthful charm in his flunking out of Yale. Almost
40 years on, Cheney oozes seriousness and probity, which he can
carry off while wearing cowboy boots. He has credibility on the old
twin avenues of the Republican universe _ Wall Street and Main
Street. He is a quick study whose low-key authority should wipe the
smirk off Democrats' faces when they say the word ``debates.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is unlikely to make the kind of mistake that takes
vice-presidential candidates from their traditional obscurity to
unwanted notoriety. And Cheney fills Bush's two principal
requirements: He could serve, without hesitation, as president, and
his loyalty seems unshakable.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and his campaign chiefs, depending on who's running the
show this week, may overreach and seek to portray Cheney as the
anti-Christ. They may want to pick over his student and parental
deferments during the Vietnam War (he never served in the military,
but later was its civilian chief) and his health record (three
heart attacks, beginning at age 37, and subsequent quadruple bypass
surgery). At the least, the Democratic campaign will attempt to
paint Cheney as a retro leftover from an administration (that of
Bush's father) which voters rejected in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's own record, in the House of Representatives and at the
Pentagon, is not without its serious flaws. He opposed sanctions on
the apartheid government in South Africa and was an enthusiastic
supporter of three of the biggest excesses toward the end of the
Cold War: Ronald Reagan's Star Wars fantasy and aid to rebels in
Nicaragua and Angola. As defense secretary he hung tenaciously to
the old canard that service by homosexuals is incompatible with
necessary military standards.
</P>
<P>
   So, he's a Republican. And being from Wyoming (now and again),
he's not too keen on gun control either and even voted against the
ban on armor-piercing ``cop killer'' bullets.
</P>
<P>
   But in a game and a town in which personality and style can be
as important as policy positions, Cheney quickly won and maintained
high marks in Washington for civility. Close associates can
remember seeing him distressed and disappointed but never in the
purple rage that too often is a politician's response to challenges
or adversity. Since his name surfaced over the weekend as Bush's
likely selection, Democratic associates from Cheney's days in
Congress have had to try to check their enthusiasm for him
personally _ and several have failed at the task.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Bush-Cheney administration, and the new president
carries through on his determination to seek a bipartisan working
relationship with a cosmically riven Congress, in Cheney he will
have an experienced partner for the challenging endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bruce Cheney can be fiercely, but not blindly or
stupidly, partisan. He is firmly grounded in the civilized wing of
his party that stretches back through Gerald R. Ford, the GOP House
leader who became the un-elected president and tapped Cheney as his
chief of staff, and Robert H. Michel, the House GOP chief to whom
Cheney became No. 2. Those were the days before the House devolved
into a full-time, scorched-earth food fight.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney arrived originally in Washington as a Congressional
Fellow. He worked for Rep. William A. Steiger, one of the class
acts in Congress until his untimely death at 40 in 1978. Cheney was
handed along the Republican talent network to the Office of
Economic Opportunity under Donald Rumsfeld, another of the GOP's
``bright young things'' from the House in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, however, soon learned to fend for himself in the
byzantine byways of Washington, moving on to the White House
(youngest chief of staff ever at 34), the House and then the
Pentagon. It's a solid career that has earned him a place on Bush's
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
