<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2818 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CHENEY-VOTE-NYT     07-25 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY WAS ONE OF THE MOST CONSERVATIVE VOICES IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (With BUSH-CHENEY) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his 10 years as a Republican congressman from
Wyoming, Dick Cheney had one of the most consistently conservative
voting records in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly voted for the tightest restrictions on abortions,
including proposals to ban Medicaid coverage of abortions for poor
women whose lives could be endangered by continued pregnancy. And
he voted against all gun-control legislation, including measures
that were supported by all but a handful of lawmakers from both
parties, like one bill to regulate what are known as cop-killer
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   On issues where business and labor were on opposite sides, he
invariably supported the business position. When developers and
environmentalists were at odds, he was on the side of the
developers.
</P>
<P>
   He opposed a constitutional amendment to guarantee equal rights
to women and voted against economic sanctions on South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   During Cheney's time in Congress, from 1979 to 1989, Democrats
were in control of the House. As is normally the case with
lawmakers in the minority party, he was not directly responsible
for any major legislation.
</P>
<P>
   While he was rigidly conservative on issues, he was never known
for strident rhetoric and was well liked by Democratic colleagues.
Cheney was not a visible leader in the fight to outlaw abortion,
but the National Right to Life Committee said Tuesday that he voted
against abortion rights on all the roll calls for which he was
present.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he voted in 1984 for a measure to define
``person'' under discrimination laws to include fetuses. The
sponsor of the measure, which Al Gore, then a congressman, also
supported, said its purpose was to deny federal funds to all
institutions performing abortions. Cheney also expressed support
for a constitutional amendment outlawing abortion, though the
matter never came to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations that lobby for and against abortion rights
were unable Tuesday to find a single instance during Cheney's time
in Congress when he spoke out on abortion, and none appeared in
computer data bases of news articles. In an interview in 1995 on
CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Cheney said, ``I'm personally pro-life.
I've always supported that position.''
</P>
<P>
   He was an unwavering advocate of the Reagan administration's
economic policy of deep tax cuts, more spending for the military
and less money for social programs, and he was instrumental in
rallying support for these programs.
</P>
<P>
   Annual vote analyses by Congressional Quarterly showed that in
most of the years he was in the House, Cheney supported President
Reagan more consistently than almost any other member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In only his second term, he moved into the Republican
leadership, and by the time he left, to become secretary of defense
under President Bush, he was the Republican whip, the No. 2
position. Had he stayed in the House, he might well have become
speaker when Republicans gained control in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his leadership responsibilities, Cheney was most deeply
involved in foreign policy and intelligence matters. He strongly
supported covert funding of guerrilla forces trying to oust the
communist governments in Nicaragua and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Cheney served as the top Republican on the House
committee that investigated the Iran-contra affair. The committee
determined that the Reagan administration had secretly sold arms to
Iran and had used the proceeds to fund the rebels, known as
contras, in Nicaragua. Cheney voted against the final report, which
accused Reagan of failing to live up to his constitutional mandate
to ``take care that the laws be faithfully executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some issues that were politically important when Cheney was in
Congress are no longer in the news. For example, he repeatedly
voted to produce the MX missile, a hugely expensive weapon designed
to carry 10 nuclear warheads that was the political symbol of what
opponents believed to be the excesses of the Reagan nuclear weapons
policy.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, he often voted against proposals to apply
economic sanctions on South Africa to protest that country's
apartheid policy. He even voted in 1986 against a nonbinding
congressional resolution calling for the release of Nelson Mandela
from prison.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year in Congress, Cheney voted for a constitutional
amendment to ban busing for school desegregation. In 1980, he voted
against strengthening the laws banning discrimination in housing.
</P>
<P>
   The only time he turned against the Reagan administration on an
important issue was in 1985, when he helped lead a Republican
revolt against a bill negotiated by the president and Democratic
leaders to overhaul the federal income tax system. He accused the
administration of selling out to the Democrats. Even after the bill
was further modified by the Republican-controlled Senate and came
back to the House in 1986, he voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan signed the tax bill and considered it one of his foremost
legislative accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Many other issues of Cheney's time in Congress will be top items
in this year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, he was one of just 21 House members to vote
against a measure regulating the manufacture, import and sale of
armor-piercing ammunition known as cop-killer bullets. He was one
of four who voted in 1988 against a proposal to ban firearms that
did not contain enough metal to be picked up by a metal detector.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Cheney often voted against Head Start, the federal
preschool program for poor children. He also voted in 1985 against
federal aid to college students, and he opposed the creation of the
Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   On the environment, he voted in 1987 against extending the Clean
Water Act and in favor of postponing sanctions against cities that
did not comply with it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he managed to keep friends on the Democratic side of the
aisle and when he joined the Bush administration as defense
secretary, among those predicting he would do a good job were two
Democratic congressional colleagues, Al Gore and Tony Coelho, the
former chairman of Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
