<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-ARCTIC-TRAIL-A     07-25 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ARCTIC-TRAIL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW CANADIAN TRAIL, FROM COAST TO COAST TO COAST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUKTOYAKTUK, Northwest Territories _ Here on North America's
northern edge, a treeless peninsula offers a timeless scene: slabs
of whale meat drying in the 24-hour summer sun, a chained husky
barking at visitors and a chill wind blowing off polar ice, only 10
miles offshore.
</P>
<P>
   But wedged between a Royal Canadian Mounted Police barracks and
the wind-whipped waves of the Beaufort Sea, tourists now inspect a
new sight: a tricolor sculpture marking this native village as the
Arctic trail head for a new 10,000-mile trail network stretching
from sea to sea to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Atlantic, Pacific and Arctic, the Trans Canada Trail
is to be inaugurated in September when relay runners converge near
Ottawa with flasks of water from Canada's three oceans. Billed as
the world's longest recreational trail, it will be open to hiking,
bicycling, horseback riding, cross-country skiing and, in some
areas, skating and snowmobiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecotourism is becoming a huge industry,'' said Rob McPhee, a
Yellowknife resident who was part of a five-member team that
undertook an 86-day trans-Arctic snowmobile trip from here to
Iqaluit, capital of the new Nunavut Territory, which was carved out
of the eastern half of the Northwest Territories in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The team left here in February after ceremonies that included
drilling through six feet of ice to draw sealskin bags filled with
water from the Arctic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing Canada's 10 provinces and three territories, the trail
is doing more this summer than promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 19th century, Canadians rallied around the epic
effort to push a railroad across their new nation. As the
automobile age flourished after World War II, Canadians rallied
around the construction of the Trans-Canada highway. Today, the
construction of a cross-country recreational trail has become a
21st-century exercise in nation building. In a country where each
province trades more with the United States than with the rest of
Canada, the trail redirects the Canadians' gaze from south to east,
to west, and even to north.
</P>
<P>
   ``It encourages people from the south to go up and see what our
country really is,'' said Carol Jones, an occupational health
specialist who divides her time between Ontario and Inuvik, a town
85 miles southwest of here that is Canada's northernmost spot
reachable by car. ``During the summers, you used to see more people
here from Europe than from Canada. All of a sudden you are seeing
Ontario vehicles. I give a lot of credit to the publicity the media
has done of the trail.''
</P>
<P>
   One visitor, Betty Veitch, a retired schoolteacher who drove
from Ontario to Inuvik with two friends, said after flying here:
``We had our picture taken with the monument. It was quite
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   As the three relay teams snake their way this summer across
Canada, the world's second largest country, after Russia,
excitement is building. So far, 5,000 volunteer water carriers have
signed up for the relay, 250,000 Canadians have donated money for
trail construction, and, in June, trail brochures were mailed to
every household in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting Canada's diversity, the water canisters have moved by
dog sleds here in the Arctic, by Indian war canoes in the Pacific,
and, to the sound of bagpipes, by a team of joggers from a
lighthouse in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in one town of 60 people, and they had 300 people
there,'' said Sherman Olson, chairman of the Trans Canada Trail
Foundation, the nonprofit group that is creating the trail. The
inauguration ceremonies in Hull, Quebec, across the river from
Ottawa, are set for Sept. 9 so schoolchildren across Canada can
watch live television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Intended to celebrate the millennium, the project, integrating
existing trail networks and adding new ones, is expected to be only
75 percent complete this fall. The trail's biggest benefactor so
far has been Canadian Pacific Railroad, which donated 1,000 miles
of discontinued rail lines. Canadian National Railroad is expected
to make a similar donation in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing will probably take another five years to
complete,'' Olson said from his home near Vancouver. ``Then you
will be able to walk from Victoria, British Columbia, to St.
John's, Newfoundland, on a trail, not on a road.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian magazines regularly publish free supplements about the
progress of the trail and DaimlerChrysler Canada has donated fleets
of Jeeps to the Trail Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronfman Foundation has given $1 million for signs and
pavilions. The pavilions will hold trail information as well as the
name of each person who donated $25 for the construction of a yard
of trail.
</P>
<P>
   The trail logo is a stylized maple leaf composed of three
arrows, which represent the three coastal trail heads and
``directions west, north and east emanating from Canada's
heartland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have politicians saying `coast to coast,' not `coast to
coast to coast,''' said Katherine McPhee, northern coordinator of
the relay race and wife of Rob. ``When you hear people talk of
Canada's three waters, it is a tremendous boost for the north.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
