   STOCKTRADES-MARKETPLACE (Washington) _ Many investors know to
the penny how much they pay in commissions when they trade a stock,
but have no idea how good an execution they get for their money.
The Securities and Exchange Commission on Tuesday proposed a rule
that will force the people who actually execute the trades, ranging
from Nasdaq market makers to specialists on the New York Stock
Exchange floor, to compile and disclose statistics on how they
trade each stock in which they make a market. The SEC is asking for
comment for 45 days, after which it will decide whether to act on
the measure. By Floyd Norris.
