<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2823 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-TEST-SCORES-BOS &LR;      07-25 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-SCORES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SHOWS LONG-TERM BENEFITS OF EDUCATION REFORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years of scores on a respected national test suggest that
education reforms by states eventually may bear fruit, according to
the authors of a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The RAND Corp., a nonprofit, nonpartisan think tank, analyzed
scores on the National Assessment of Educational Progress and
determined that Texas, which implemented standardized testing and
extensive school accountability systems before much of the rest of
the nation, performed the best.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1990 and 1996, the Lone Star State had the
second-greatest improvement in math scores and ranked the highest
when RAND compared students from similar socioeconomic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay State's 1993 education reform law includes reforms
similar to those in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't explain the gains in Texas strictly by the amount of
resource changes,'' said David Grissmer, one of the authors of the
study. ``We think the changes in scores have to reflect the
systemic reform efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The RAND study is based on test scores from 1990, 1992, 1994 and
1996. The US Department of Education administered the test to
representative samples of 2,500 students from each of 44 states
which volunteered to participate. The National Assessment of
Educational Progress is generally viewed as a more accurate
barometer of student achievement than state tests because teachers
don't know which students will be taking it and therefore cannot
teach to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts ranked 10th out of the 44 states in terms of its
``raw'' scores. But the authors of the study say that comparing
students from similar backgrounds is more meaningful, and when the
scores were adjusted for that, Massachusetts fell to 17th. The Bay
State ranked 28th in math score improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors that seem to boost performance, according to
Grissmer, are small class sizes, ``well-resourced'' teachers, and
extensive pre-K programs.
</P>
<P>
   The American Federation of Teachers compared Texas to its
demographic cousin, California, in arguing that the report shows
the importance of spending enough money on public education.
California ranked last when students of similar backgrounds were
compared.
</P>
<P>
   ``California, which fared poorly in the report, is an example of
what happens when you take away investment from public schools,''
federation president Sandra Feldman said in a written statement.
``California's public schools were once a source of great pride _
before they were starved of resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-     07-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB LEADERS BEHIND ARAFAT'S UNWILLINGNESS TO COMPROMISE ON
JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS; see also MIDEAST-ADVISORY-NYT for complete
list of stories) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The refusal of Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, to negotiate away his claims to Jerusalem may have dashed
U.S. hopes of a Camp David peace agreement Tuesday, but it allowed
him to return home with his credibility among other Arab leaders
intact, Middle East analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is now expected to solidify that backing with a round of
consultations in the region, beginning with a visit to President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt on Wednesday morning in the Egyptian port
city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials here said that Arafat would probably meet
soon with many of the Arab leaders who had urged him, in public
statements and private telephone conversations, to hold firm on his
demands for an end to Israel's 33 years of exclusive control over
East Jerusalem and the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Jerusalem, which contains sites holy to Muslims
and Christians as well as to Jews, was said to have been the main
sticking point in the intense negotiations at Camp David in pursuit
of a settlement to the long Palestinian-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official reaction from Arab capitals to the
announcement that the Camp David talks had ended. A spokesman for
the Arab League in Cairo said officials would wait until Arafat
briefs them on his negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Arab television channels, which are state owned, reported the
breakdown without commentary.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the Al-Jezeera satellite TV station, owned by a
member of the ruling family of the Gulf state of Qatar, and one of
the few outlets for debate in the Arab world, the analysis was
overwhelmingly supportive of Arafat. ``Clinton said Israel
compromised more than the Palestinians, but this is not accurate,''
Helmi Barakat, a political analyst based in Washington, said in a
Jezeera interview. ``According to international law, Jerusalem is
occupied land, and I do not believe the Arabs should be expected to
compromise or give up their sovereignty over Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few days, a number of Arab leaders, from Crown
Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia to Mubarak, have joined with
Arafat's domestic opponents in various Islamic militant movements
to weigh in on the issue. They all but threatened Arafat with
political excommunication if he accepted Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's proposals for only administrative control over parts of the
city and access to _ but not sovereignty over _ the major Muslim
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of many analysts, however, Arafat did not need any
reminders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat knew beforehand that any compromise on Jerusalem would
be the end of Arafat,'' said Tahsin Basheer, a former aide to Anwar
Sadat, the late Egyptian president who was the first Arab leader to
make peace with Israel, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials also said Arafat was acutely aware,
throughout the peace talks, that Jerusalem was an especially
sensitive issue for the Arab leaders whose support he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that here in Egypt, just like in Saudi Arabia, in
Jordan and elsewhere in the region, the leaders have to worry about
their own home constituencies when it comes to Jerusalem,'' said
Mohammed Subieh, the general-secretary of the Palestine National
Council and the Palestinian representative in the Arab League in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Arab control of the Old City has been a rallying cry not only
for Palestinian nationalists through the years. It has also been a
slogan for the Islamic fundamentalist movements that have mounted
violent opposition to any Arab regime that attempts to normalize
relations between Arabs and Israelis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mubarak, who has been actively involved in the Arab-Israeli
peace effort for years, conferred several times with Arafat during
the talks. But he did not follow the U.S. line and push Arafat to
compromise, as he has in the past on issues other than Jerusalem,
Egyptian officials and diplomats in Cairo said.
</P>
<P>
   As Mubarak's information director, Maged Abdel Fattah, said
earlier this week, the Egyptian president saw his role as helping
U.S. diplomats, and not Arafat, understand that Christian and
Muslim Arabs around the world can accept only certain
``parameters'' when it comes to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Clinton said in his post-mortem on the negotiations,
these were the first substantive talks between an Arab leader and
an Israeli leader on the subject of Jerusalem. But outside the
confines of the presidential retreat, analysts said, they also
revived old shibboleths and emotions that could be difficult to
contain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
