<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0726-C     07-25 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MIDEAST PEACE TALKS END WITHOUT AGREEMENT, NO JERUSALEM
COMPROMISE
 &HT;    With SUMMIT-REACT-0726.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S.-sponsored Mideast peace talks broke up in
failure Tuesday, as Israeli and Palestinian leaders were unable to
resolve the most intractable issue at the heart of their 52-year
dispute, the fate of the holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   A deeply disappointed President Clinton, who spent most of the
past two weeks pressing the negotiations at nearby Camp David, said
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat made ``real headway'' on many of the territorial and
security issues dividing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we were, in the end, unable to bridge the gaps,'' Clinton
said. ``They couldn't get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The acrimonious collapse of the summit _ each side blamed the
other for its failure _ left in its wake a feeling of uncertainty
and a potential for violence in the fractious Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the summit fallen apart than some Palestinians in
Gaza threatened to try to win through bloodshed what they couldn't
secure at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed to pick up the pieces of the dangling peace
process in the weeks ahead, in hopes of reconstituting the talks in
late summer or early fall between Arafat and Barak. He said both
left Camp David still committed to their self-imposed Sept. 13
deadline for completing a comprehensive peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the sake of their children, they must re-dedicate
themselves to the path of peace and find a way to resume their
negotiations in the next few weeks,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venue's not important, the mechanisms aren't important,
but we know what the state of play is now,'' Clinton said. ``If
we'll keep at it, I still think we can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   After 14 days of intensive talks produced no accord at Camp
David, however, Clinton conceded that there was no clear way
forward in the Mideast peace process and no assurance that the
region won't veer off the path of diplomacy and descend into
violence in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a script that's never been written before,'' Clinton
told reporters at the White House, immediately after the half-hour
helicopter flight from the presidential retreat in western
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stopped just short of blaming Arafat for the failed
talks. He did say, though, that Barak showed greater flexibility
than the aging Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister moved forward more from his initial
position than (PLO) Chairman Arafat, particularly surrounding the
questions of Jerusalem,'' Clinton said. ``He (Barak) came in
knowing that he was going to have to take bold steps, and he did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the contrast between Clinton's effusive praise for Barak's
approach to the talks and his comparatively dim assessment of
Arafat's performance left little doubt that Clinton saw a need for
further movement by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Barak showed particular courage, vision, and an
understanding of the historical importance of this moment,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Clinton said Arafat ``made it clear that he too
remains committed to the path of peace,'' at several points in his
White House press conference, he returned to praising Barak without
offering comparable support for Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he (Barak) took a big risk,'' Clinton said. ``This is
not a weak man. I mean, he didn't come over here to play safe with
his political future, he came over here to do what he thought was
right for the people of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak called a press conference to lay the blame for the failed
summit directly on Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had offered Palestinians limited sovereignty over
parts of East Jerusalem. Arafat rejected the compromise, however,
insisting instead on full Arab control of the enclave, which he
wants as the capital of a new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to end the conflict,'' Barak told reporters at a
hotel in Frederick, Md., about 20 miles from the Catoctin Mountain
retreat at Camp David. ``But, unfortunately, Arafat somehow
hesitated to take the historic decisions that were needed in order
to put an end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak was careful, though, to leave the door open for future
negotiations with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision of peace suffered a major blow,'' he said. ``But I
believe that with good faith, goodwill on all sides, it can
recuperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat left the summit without making any public comments.
</P>
<P>
   However, Palestinian officials have consistently blamed Barak
throughout the talks for not yielding on the question of East
Jerusalem, territory Israel seized during the 1967 Arab-Israeli
war.
</P>
<P>
   By publicly ruling out any division of Jerusalem from the
beginning of the summit, the Palestinians have said, Barak poisoned
the atmosphere and doomed the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli position was the cause of failure,'' Tayeb Abdel
Rahim, a top Arafat aide, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The talks fell apart despite aggressive bargaining by Clinton,
who said he gave Israelis assurances of U.S. security assistance
and promised American aid dollars to help resettle Palestinian
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave no further details on those commitments, but he
left no doubt that Jerusalem was the sticking point that sunk the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most difficult problem,'' Clinton said. ``We tried
a lot of different approaches to it and we have not yet found a
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   In Palestinian-controlled Gaza, the militant group Hamas called
for a resumption of armed struggle against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution now is that Mr. Arafat and the negotiators
declare the failure and futility of the entire peace process and
return to the path of resistance and jihad (holy struggle),''
senior Hamas official Abdel-Aziz al-Rantissi told the Reuters news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has threatened to unilaterally declare a Palestinian
state if he and Barak can't agree to a peace treaty by the
mid-September deadline.
</P>
<P>
   While Arafat did not withdraw the threat _ at least not publicly
_ he did agree, in a statement that he, Clinton and Barak all
signed, to ``understand the importance of avoiding unilateral
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters there was
no question that the statement applied to the declaration of
Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were working at was to have a Palestinian state as
part of a comprehensive aspect, not unilateral,'' she said. ``We've
made very clear that we think that unilateral actions are not
useful. That includes the declaration of a Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating criticism that he had called the summit before
laying the groundwork for success, Clinton said the atmosphere
between Israelis and Palestinians had been deteriorating in recent
months and that the summit was the best way he knew of to try to
arrest the slide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had no choice,'' he said. ``We can't afford to
leave a single stone unturned in the search for a just, lasting and
comprehensive peace.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
