<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2827 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PUBLIC-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      07-25 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY CREDITS SMALL CLASSES AND PRESCHOOL FOR STUDENT ACHIEVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smaller class size in early grades and access to preschool
appear to increase student achievement, particularly in
impoverished communities, more than the salaries, education or
experience of teachers, a national study released Tuesday says.
</P>
<P>
   The state-by-state analysis of standardized test results
suggests that policy initiatives to boost student achievement have
been effective, with math scores climbing steadily across the
country at an average rate of about one percentile point each year
from 1990 to 1996. Texas and a handful of other states that were
among the leaders in adopting new standards and accountability
systems have shown particular gains, including significantly higher
scores by poor students and those from minority groups than by
their counterparts in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public education is reformable,'' declared David Grissmer, the
principal author of the book-length study published by Rand Corp.,
a policy and research group based in Santa Monica, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, we were unsure whether reform in the states
was working and if spending more money would make any difference in
educational outcomes,'' Grissmer said. ``We see gains in some
states from reform efforts, and we see that resources, if they're
properly targeted, can be very effective at raising achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   The study presents a mixed picture for politicians arguing over
how to spend education dollars, and, in calling for increased
federal spending to reduce disparities among states, is sure to
provide fodder for debate in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice President Al Gore
immediately highlighted the report on their campaign Web sites,
with Bush celebrating the declaration of his state as a national
leader and Gore noting that class-size reduction and universal
preschool _ programs praised in the report _ form the centerpiece
of his $115 billion education agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of the results we have achieved in education in
Texas,'' Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee, said in a
statement. ``As president, I will achieve the same results,
ensuring that no child is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   But William A. Galston, a senior adviser to Gore, the
all-but-named Democratic nominee, pointed out that Bush did not
even become governor until 1995, near the end of the period
studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm told, though I'm not a farm boy, that roosters crow when
the sun comes up,'' said Galston, director of the Institute for
Philosophy and Public Policy at the University of Maryland. ``I am
told by some farmers that some roosters are under the impression
that they have caused the sun to rise, but they did not.''
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the partisan pot shots, though, educators and state
policymakers found crucial lessons in the report, which links
scores on a national standardized test to census data and variables
such as per pupil spending and class size for the first time. The
study looked at seven math and reading tests administered in 44
states through the National Assessment of Educational Progress, a
federal program that tests samples of 4th-, 8th- and 12th-graders
and is often referred to as the nation's report card.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings:
</P>
<P>
   There is wide disparity in performance across the states for
students from socio-economically similar families. Texas topped the
list, with students scoring an average of 11 percentile points
higher than their counterparts in last-ranked California. The
states succeeding in this measure tended to spend more money per
student, have lower student-teacher ratios and less teacher
turnover, provide more public pre-kindergarten classes and have
teachers report satisfaction with their classroom resources.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at raw scores, states clustered near the top were mostly
northern and rural, including Minnesota, Montana and Maine, while
the 10 lowest performers were eight Southern states, California and
New Mexico. The study's authors attribute this largely to
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   While math scores increased across the country, there was
considerable range in gains among the states. North Carolina
students improved nearly 2.5 percentile points each year, and those
in Texas and Michigan 2 percentile points, more than twice the
national average; Wyoming, Georgia, Delaware, Utah and North Dakota
showed minuscule gains or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher salaries, their years in the classroom and the
percentage of the teaching force with masters' degrees appear to
have little impact on student performance, though Grissmer said
more study of these factors is necessary. The report said education
dollars would be better spent on classroom-based resources to
improve teacher working conditions _ such as computers and voice
mail and curriculum materials _ or on reducing class size than on
wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to see such a sophisticated study confirming a
truth too many people want to ignore: poor children achieve at
lower rates because we give them an inferior education,'' said Kati
Haycock, director of the Education Trust, a Washington group
focused on disadvantaged students. ``With targeted investments and
high expectations, we can close the achievement gap once and for
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But while most people praised the report's rigor, some
questioned the usefulness of analyzing test scores that predate
many state reform initiatives and other aspects of its methodology.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Loveless, a fellow at the Brookings Institution who is also
studying NAEP data, pointed out that the math scores Grissmer used
come from a new test that tracks curriculums introduced widely in
the last decade, and that scores on an older form of the exam,
which emphasizes basic skills such as arithmetic, have been flat in
the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Feldman, president of the American Federation of
Teachers, questioned whether the analysis of teacher pay and
experience remains relevant now that the country is facing a
teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   And Susan K. Burr, California's interim secretary of education,
noted that in the past two years, her state has cut class size in
kindergarten to fourth grade from 28 students to 20; increased per
pupil spending by nearly $1,000, and instituted an accountability
system similar to the one in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The report, she said, is ``ancient history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
