<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, July 26. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ After 15 days of emotional
negotiations failed to achieve agreement at Camp David, President
Clinton ends the peace conference praising Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak for being ready to make hard compromises but declaring
that the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, would not reciprocate.
By Jane Perlez. (We plan to move the story by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``i''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   This story runs under a 6-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT2, NYT3, NYT10, NYT18, NYT19 and a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: See MIDEAST-ADVISORY-NYT and AIRFRANCE-CRASH-ADVISORY-NYT
for complete list of stories related to today's events.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Thurmont, Md.) _ News Analysis: The Israelis and
the Palestinians packed their bags and left Camp David empty-handed
and exhausted. Putting the best possible face on the failure,
President Clinton asserts that the Israelis and Palestinians did
break seven years of silence to conduct a discussion on emotional
issues like Jerusalem. He said that the parties made significant
progress on the core issues. By Deborah Sontag. (Scheduled to move
by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   AIRFRANCE-CRASH (Gonesse, France) _ A supersonic Air France
Concorde carrying mainly German tourists bound for a cruise ship in
New York crashed in flames shortly after take-off from Charles de
Gaulle Airport outside Paris, killing all 109 passengers and crew
on board as well as at least four people on the ground. It was the
first ever crash of a Concorde since the world's first supersonic
passenger plane went into commercial operation in 1976. By Alan
Riding. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT1; a small locator map; and graphics depicting the
jet, what happened during the take off and how the Concorde
compares to other planes.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY (Austin, Texas) _ The presumed Republican
presidential candidate, Gov. George W. Bush, announced that former
U.S. defense secretary Dick Cheney would be his vice-presidential
running mate. By Frank Bruni and Alison Mitchell. (Scheduled to
move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photos NYT14, NYT15, NYT16.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CHENEY-ASSESS (Undated) _ News Analysis: In the most
momentous decision of his political career thus far, Gov. George W.
Bush took the least adventurous course possible and one that
several scholars called the safest choice of a political partner in
a generation. But the selection of Dick Cheney was deeply revealing
about Bush's approach to politics and to governing. By Richard L.
Berke. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
