<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-REACT-NYT &LR;      07-25 1247
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOY, DISAPPOINTMENT AND CONFUSION IN ISRAEL _ BUT LITTLE SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: For complete list of related stories, see
MIDEAST-ADVISORY-NYT)  
 By JOHN F. BURNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ When the news from Washington crackled through on
their transistor radios, a group of Jewish men keeping vigil atop
the Mount of Olives broke into songs of praise that East Jerusalem,
spread out before them in the last rays of a setting sun, would
not, at least for now, be reverting to any form of Arab control.
</P>
<P>
   From dawn, the cluster of ultraconservative ``rejectionists'' _
rabbis, professors and right-wing sectarian leaders who have
opposed peace talks with Israel's Arab neighbors since the original
Camp David talks in 1978 _ had been encamped above the Jewish
cemeteries that cascade down the hillside.
</P>
<P>
   Through the heat of the day, they prayed, fasted and alternated
readings from the Torah and the Talmud, imploring God to condemn
the latest Camp David talks to failure.
</P>
<P>
   About 6 p.m., when the Voice of Israel announced that the talks
had collapsed over the disagreement of the future status of
Jerusalem, with Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, reportedly rejecting proposals that would have
given limited control over parts of East Jerusalem to the
Palestinians, the mood became triumphal.
</P>
<P>
   In moments, the biblical songs began ringing out across the
valley toward the Temple Mount on the other side where Arabs, at
the Dome of the Rock, and Jews, at the Western Wall, were gathering
at dusk to pay their separate obeisances to God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been praying all day that God would intervene and
prevent this disaster from befalling the people of Israel,'' said
Baruch Ben-Yosef, a 41-year-old rabbi who came to Israel from New
York as a teen-ager. ``Now, our prayers have been answered. Barak
has been stopped from selling out the land of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   But just in case, he said, he and his fellows would maintain
their vigil through the night. ``We want to be sure he gets on the
plane, that he doesn't loop back to Camp David and change his mind,
that the whole thing is done and dead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But on an evening that many Jews and Palestinians described as
marking a watershed in their shared history, the certainties of the
men atop the Mount of Olives were rare.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the failure in Washington spread across this ancient
city, from television sets in cafes and bars, from radios in the
bazaars of the old city, and across the network of mobile phones
that have Israelis and Palestinians engaging in seemingly nonstop
talk even on days when there is no major news, the more common
reaction seemed to be one of disappointment, confusion and even of
fear.
</P>
<P>
   There was not, however, much surprise. The likelihood that the
Camp David negotiations would break down had been bannered across
headlines here for days. But more than that, what emerged from a
random sounding of reaction across the city as the evening wore on
was a mood suggesting that many here, on both sides, had been
forced by events in Washington into accepting harsh realities they
always knew were likely to overwhelm the hopes and dreams nurtured
by more than two decades of on-and-off peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   In a dozen conversations, the common thread was a sense that
Barak and Arafat, in dashing the hopes of a final peace agreement,
had bowed to a gap, irreducible now and possibly for a long time to
come, between the competing political visions of their
constituents. On the issue of Jerusalem, it seemed from these
conversations, it is not only hard-liners like the men atop the
Mount of Olives, but also many others on both sides who consider
themselves secularists and moderates who are not yet ready for the
historic concessions that would have been necessary under President
Clinton's compromise plan.
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian shopkeeper from Bethlehem, Ismail Kanan, caught
the mood of many other Palestinians when he said he was bitterly
disappointed that the Camp David talks had ended without agreement,
because the peace effort had come a long way since 1978, and the
two sides, in Barak and Arafat, had leaders who were as flexible as
they were likely to get. During 20 years, he said, Jews and Arabs
had learned that ``we are all humans, we all want to live, and we
have to recognize each others' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kanan, a 36-year-old shopkeeper, waiting at a bus
terminal in the heart of the Old City for his brother to arrive
with his family for a get-together in East Jerusalem, had a crucial
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in traditional Arab dress, with a flowing white robe and
a banded white headdress, he said ordinary Palestinians like
himself could never accustom themselves to getting back parts of
East Jerusalem piecemeal, as Clinton's plan would have required.
``Barak cannot make a deal without conceding control of East
Jerusalem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Palestinian, a 30-year-old resident of the Old City who
was not born when Israel captured it in the 1967 war, overheard
Kanan's remarks and felt that he had not gone far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all rubbish, a waste of time,'' said Ismail Jaber, a bus
driver. ``We must have the Old City back, and if they won't give it
to us now, we won't go away, we'll still be here, they'll still
have to deal with us.'' As if to make his point clearer, he added
that ``it's back to Hamas,'' the radical Islamic group that
detonated bombs in Jerusalem in the Palestinian uprising a decade
ago that was known as the Intifada, and which remains Arafat's most
powerful rival in the areas of Gaza and the West Bank already ceded
to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, before the Damascus Gate in the Old City wall that
leads on to the Dome of the Rock, two other Palestinian men paused
on their way from a pizza supper to evening prayers at the Muslim
shrine. Daoud Abdelhadi, a 44-year-old hairdresser, and Mohanad
Awad, a 43-year-old insurance salesman, both from the
Palestinian-controlled city of Ramallah on the West Bank, were
among the few strollers who appeared not to have heard about the
collapse of the talks, perhaps because they had spent much of the
afternoon on an overcrowded bus journey to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Told that there was to be no peace pact, at least not this time,
they were visibly dismayed. ``It's a bad thing, a very bad thing,''
Abdelhadi said, shaking his head. He described Palestinians as
``tired, so very tired'' by the long years of struggle dating to
the founding of Israel in 1948, and desperate for relief from the
kind of inconveniences he said the two men had faced in making
their journey to Jerusalem. They were forced by Israeli rules, he
said, to come by bus rather than by car, held up for repeated
scrutiny of identity papers at Israeli checkpoints, and denied, in
Abdelhadi's case, the right to bring his 17-year-old son, who
lacked the right papers, to Jerusalem with them.
</P>
<P>
   But after a few minutes of discussion, the two men turned their
frustration not against Barak, nor Arafat, whom they described as
having made the right choice in holding out for broader concessions
on Jerusalem, but against Clinton. ``I'll tell you this,''
Abdelhadi said. ``If the United States wants to do something to
correct the wrongs done to the Palestinian people, it can do it, no
problem, it has the power over Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Awad agreed. ``I want to ask you,'' he said, ``why is America
always on the side of Israel?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
