<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2833 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-     07-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS SAY THEY WILL DECLARE INDEPENDENCE ON SEPT. 13 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS; see also MIDEAST-ADVISORY-NYT for complete
list of stories.) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian officials said after the Camp David
summit meeting ended Tuesday without an agreement that they would
press ahead with plans to declare an independent state on Sept. 13,
whatever the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The officials asserted that Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, had made all the concessions possible from the Palestinian
side before going into the meeting, and that the firm stance that
he apparently took at Camp David would boost his standing among his
own people. They contended that Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel
is responsible for the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will produce full support for Arafat and strengthen his
credibility from the point of view of the Palestinians,'' said
Marwan Barghouti, West Bank leader of Arafat's al-Fatah movement,
the mainstream group in the Palestine Liberation Organization. ``We
have to start to prepare for the declaration of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians had set Sept. 13 as a deadline for
a final peace agreement, and Arafat has asserted that he would
declare statehood this year, with or without an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Fatah called for a general strike and demonstrations in support
of Arafat in the West Bank and Gaza Strip on Wednesday. That raised
concerns among Israeli army officers that demonstrators might clash
with Israeli soldiers, although Barghouti said that his group would
keep the peace.
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Arafat has been accused by domestic
critics of failing to stand up to the Israelis, his apparent
insistence at Camp David on Palestinian sovereignty in East
Jerusalem and on formal recognition of the right of return for
Palestinian refugees was expected to earn him a hero's welcome from
supporters when he returns home.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat ``proved to be one of the last of the historic leaders,
because he said no at the moment when no one says no to America,''
said Freih Abu Meddein, the justice minister in Arafat's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sheik Ahmad Yassin, the spiritual leader of the militant
Islamic movement Hamas, had words of praise for his political foe.
``I welcome his steadfastness,'' he said in Gaza. ``There is no
choice but the choice of resistance. What was taken by force must
be returned by force.''
</P>
<P>
   Tayeb Abdel Rahim, a top aide to Arafat, accused Barak of
scuttling the talks by insisting on his self-declared ``red
lines.'' These would bar Palestinian sovereignty in East Jerusalem,
formal recognition of the right of return of the refugees and a
full withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped for success, but unfortunately we kept bumping
into these noes, which were the main reason for the crippling of
the peace process,'' Abdel Rahim said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the end of the summit meeting ``doesn't mean that the
peace process will collapse'' Abdel Rahim asserted. ``We are ready
to continue efforts to push the peace process forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Arafat is under mounting pressure from his supporters to
declare a state on Sept. 13, regardless of whether it might provoke
violent confrontation with the Israelis, who have said they would
respond by annexing areas of the West Bank still under Israeli
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will persist in declaring the sovereignty of the
Palestinian state _ our date is September 13,'' said Hani
al-Hassan, a member of Fatah's central committee and a longtime
comrade-in-arms of Arafat. ``We are ready to bear the
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials insisted that Arafat had reached the limit of his
concessions even before the Camp David meeting because he had
already recognized Israeli sovereignty over 80 percent of what used
to be British-ruled Palestine and over the western half of
Jerusalem. He could not compromise on what was left: the West Bank,
the Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem, they said.
</P>
<P>
   By hinting that it was Barak who went the extra mile at Camp
David, President Clinton was taking the Israeli side, Abu Meddein
said. He drew a parallel, contending that Clinton had also placed
the blame on the late Syrian leader, Hafez Assad, after an
unsuccessful meeting several months ago in Geneva to restart
Syrian-Israeli negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Faisal Husseini, the top Palestinian leader in Jerusalem, said
that despite the failure to reach an agreement at Camp David, the
meeting had begun the process of resolving the dispute over the
Holy City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taboo on opening the file of Jerusalem has vanished,'' he
said. ``This file has been opened, and we hope it will generate
more discussion in the Israeli community and that we can reach a
solution before September 13. I don't believe that this is the
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
