<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2835 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TOO-MUCH-STATS26-COX     07-25 0218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-MUCH-STATS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More time, more distance
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a study by the University of Michigan Institute for
Social Research:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Families spend 137 percent more time driving to accomplish
family and personal errands than in 1969 and go 88 percent farther.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kids spend 50 percent more time playing organized sports than
in 1980, boys more than twice as much as girls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children today have 75 percent of their weekdays programmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Free time is down from 40 percent of the average kid's day to
less than 25 percent. Or six hours instead of 9.5 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family meals during the week have become a rarity. And the
average kid spends only 10 or 12 minutes a day reading.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the Washington-based Surface
Transportation Policy Project:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Two-thirds of all shuttle trips are made by women.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  61 percent of women (46 percent of men) make at least one stop
after work, and 30 percent make two or more.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On a typical day, the average mother travels 29 miles and
takes more than five trips, mostly errands and chauffeuring.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
