<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2836 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TOO-MUCH26-COX     07-25 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-MUCH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burnout: Time at premium for kids, and their parents
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it a baseball night? Game or practice? And what time? And
where? Or is this the night for Carolyn Grove to take her daughter
Ryann, 14, to Callanwolde to sing? Or the Alliance Theater for
acting class? Or to cotillion dancing lessons?
</P>
<P>
   But wait. Maybe it's swimming at the YMCA for the boys, 11 and
7. Or Boy Scouts?
</P>
<P>
   Even though Grove uses a computer for other tasks, she resorts
to shuffling through an old-fashioned calendar to keep her life in
some semblance of order. She reckons she spends five hours a day in
her car.
</P>
<P>
   And her dizzily hectic schedule is far from atypical. Millions
of American families are busier than ever, raising concerns that
we're all just another drive-through burger away from burnout.
</P>
<P>
   For millions of parents, life today is like ``Ozzie &AMP; Harriet''
in triple fast forward. It's a blur of hectic travel, meeting
deadlines and keeping up with the Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   But not for everyone. Uprisings by harried parents have begun.
In Wayzata, Minn., a suburb of Minneapolis, parents have formed a
group called Family Life 1st (FamilyLife1st.org). Its mission is to
spark a national backlash that will make parents think twice about
keeping their children so busy. They've urged others involved in
youth activities, such as band directors and ballet teachers, to
work toward the same goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good idea,'' Grove said. ``If there's a logical
medium between the kids having activities and giving the parents
and kids more time ... I'd like to see a group like that in Atlanta
and sit in and see what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury's still out on whether frenetically programming
children's lives is good or bad for them. Or for the parents who
are doing the schlepping.
</P>
<P>
   That will be the subject of future studies. Recent ones suggest
angst-ridden parents don't know whether to feel pride or remorse
about keeping their kids, and themselves, so busy.
</P>
<P>
   That's bad, says Sandra Hofferth, author of a study on
overscheduled children. But there's plenty of evidence, she adds,
that keeping kids jumping has benefits, such as teaching them how
to hustle to get homework done and developing social skills they'll
need later in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that activities like sports affect how well they do on
test scores,'' she says. ``I don't mean to imply that
overscheduling is good, but having some organized activities is
good. Sports provides self-esteem. But I'm concerned that kids
don't have enough downtime, to read or imagine, which is critical
for developing cognitive skills.''
</P>
<P>
   But because 64 percent of families have two wage earners,
parents often feel they have no choice.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first generation of youngsters in history whose
parents have had the time and money to do so much for their kids.
</P>
<P>
   And often, it takes lots of money.
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Karen Hughes of Marietta have been traveling all over
the country for years to take son Matt, 17, and daughter Ashley,
14, to tennis and cheerleading competitions, respectively. Karen
even home-schooled Matt for a year because that was the only way
she could juggle the kids' schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``You about need a private secretary,'' Karen says. ``Plus, you
can't forget the deadlines for turning in entries to tournaments
and competitions. It's expensive. But it builds character. And
we're so close because we spend so much time together, and it's
good time, even in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Another positive: TV time for youths 18 and under is decreasing,
having dropped from 15 to 13 hours a week in the past decade or so,
says Hofferth.
</P>
<P>
   William J. Doherty, a University of Minnesota social scientist
and co-founder of the Wayzata group, has written a book,
``Intentional Families,'' which contends that if families don't
make time for each other, they can say goodbye to emotional ties.
</P>
<P>
   Rearing children, he says, has become more like ``product
development,'' and Family Life 1st is ``blowing the whistle on this
problem of scheduled hyperactivity and calling for reclaiming
family time and family activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has received 20 inquiries from across the nation from
parents interested in starting chapters. But Doherty stresses they
are calling for a scaling back, not elimination, of activities.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine by Dr. Richard Winer, a Roswell psychiatrist, who
urges parents to exercise common sense, not try to ``go back to the
way things were in the 1950s when kids didn't do very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Popkin, a noted Atlanta child psychologist, warns
that generalizing is dangerous; having hectic schedules may do more
good than harm for kids, if not their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some kids thrive on lots of activity, while others become
stressed out and depressed,'' he says. ``Too little stress can be
as debilitating as too much. Ever been bored to death?''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Reiner, 13, says he'd be depressed if he weren't so
busy. His dad and coach, Michael Reiner, a 47-year-old Atlanta
financial planner, would be, too, though he concedes some people,
like wife Shelly, think he's ``crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   He was head coach of two teams in the spring, and now he's
running two all-star squads, both of which practice a couple of
times a week, plus playing one or more games, many far from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are games and practices and tournaments, so basically
four or five nights a week are baseball,'' says Reiner. ``Often
I'll leave the office at 4:30 p.m. and not get home till 11:30. I'm
taking a team soon to Boca Raton (Fla.). But after the second week
of August, I'm done _ until fall ball starts in September. That's
usually over by Halloween, then we start again in February.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, he adds, is ``just my baseball schedule. There's also
lacrosse, and golf lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he worry the kids on his teams might be too busy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that,'' he says. ``It keeps them out of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the consequences, there's no doubt family time
increasingly is being spent in the car. Due to urban sprawl, the
metro area leads the nation in miles driven per person per day,
according to the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Washington-based Surface Transportation
Policy Project found that the average mom spends 17 days a year
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But breadwinner fathers also have less time than most people
think, says a Canadian study. They're working longer, then rushing
to help their wives meet commuting deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   Arranging her schedule this week by cellphone, Grove conceded
she's often not sure what she's supposed to do on any given day.
But daughter Ryann is grateful for her mom's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been doing it so many years, it's a way of life now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
