<HEADER>
A2837 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY-BEACHES26-COX     07-25 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-BEACHES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four Pensacola spots rate with different strokes for sandy folks
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PENSACOLA, Fla. _ When Perdido Key's shoreline made the annual
top 20 list of American beaches compiled by the expert who bills
himself as ``Dr. Beach,'' we just had to check it out.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time we got here, we were certainly ready for an
award-winning splash, having fought through Panama City and
Destin's tangled traffic, in stupefying heat and humidity, from our
vacation spot on the Panhandle's lower-key eastern end. The
temperature according to one bank sign near the beach: 103 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem was, when we finally got to the Perdido Key State
Recreation Area, the main public beach access, things hardly seemed
golden. Black flies were on the attack. The park's amenities were
spartan, not much more than litter-blemished boardwalks leading
from the parking lot to the beach, grim restrooms and some picnic
pavilions. Even the usually gorgeous Gulf of Mexico was a thick and
chunky soup of seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Beach, we figured, had done some of his computations at the
nearby Flora-Bama Lounge, the legendary dive on the Florida-Alabama
line where the big fun includes an annual mullet toss competition.
</P>
<P>
   We were unwowed by Perdido Key, but undaunted. We decided to
spend the next day doing a totally unscientific survey of how it
ranks among Pensacola's other beaches. We may not have a doctorate
in beachology, but we know a nice stretch of sand when we see it.
</P>
<P>
   GULF ISLANDS NATIONAL SEASHORE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Printed slogan or boast: ``A place of myriad riches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accuracy of that claim: Truth in advertising! Heading west
from Pensacola Beach along Santa Rosa Island, we quickly witnessed
a sign of nature's unsullied magic: a halo of sand blowing over the
road on the horizon. We were entering a pristine, 7.7-mile stretch
of federally protected shoreline that leads to Fort Pickens, an
imposing brick edifice completed in 1834. (This is but a small
section of the national seashore, a series of barrier islands
stretching 150 miles along the gulf, from Fort Walton Beach, Fla.,
to Ocean Springs, Miss.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High tide (highlights): Most of the hooks were coming up empty
on the pier by the fort, but we saw a sea gull nab a fish out of
the water and, in midair, go chomp! ... Retreating to the quiet
Langdon Beach area, we followed a winding boardwalk from the
parking area through scrub and over sea-oat dotted dunes to _voila!
_the most perfect stretch of shoreline we could imagine. ... Blue
and jade bands of gulf waters that up close were so clear you could
watch the minnows darting about. ... A wide beach with sand as
white as Dixie Crystals. ... A glorious, unobstructed gulf view.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low tide (lowlights): Not many places to grab refreshments,
but if you wanted to snorkel beside a 7-Eleven you probably
wouldn't be happy here anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Our unscientific ranking: First. Reminds you how beautiful the
gulf can be when the developers leave it alone.
</P>
<P>
   PERDIDO KEY STATE RECREATION AREA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Printed slogan or boast: ``Welcome to paradise found''
(actually the Perdido Chamber of Commerce's pitch).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accuracy of that claim: That's not what the tossed mullet
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High tide: Beer and other ice-cold beverages and eats are in
close proximity. ... Covered picnic pavilions offer handsome gulf
views and a place to escape the fireball sun. ... If you feel an
uncontrollable urge to be in Alabama, you're almost there. ...
Temporary tattoos are now available at the Flora-Bama Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low tide: The Perdido chamber tourism office could hardly
provide a warm greeting, since it closed 15 minutes before the time
on the door said it was supposed to. ... Development, especially
the muy gigantico, Cancun-style condos on the 'Bama side, blots the
gulf panorama. That, and the fact that the state recreation area
parking lots are just off the main drag and awfully close to the
shore, doesn't exactly encourage a communing-with-nature feeling.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Our unscientific ranking: Fourth. Maybe you have to have a pad
in one of those 'Bama towers to really appreciate it.
</P>
<P>
   BIG LAGOON STATE RECREATION AREA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Printed slogan or boast: ``The real Florida'' (actually the
slogan of the entire state park system).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accuracy of that claim: Nothing Mickey Mouse about this place
_ thankfully. You certainly get a lot with your beach _ a 698-acre,
family-friendly park that includes slash pine woodlands, salt
marshes bordering Big Lagoon, nature trails, countless birds and
other fauna to train binoculars on, an observation tower
overlooking the lagoon, five picnic pavilions, boat ramps and
camping facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High tide: The East Beach is barely wide enough to throw down
a beach towel, but the shallow lagoon waters are filled with sea
life, including tons of hermit crabs squatting in seashells of all
sorts. It's a meditative place where it's easy to pass an hour or
more with your head down trying to spot marine life in the swaying
marsh grass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low tide: The meditative mood can be broken by noisy boats and
jet skis detouring over from the Intracoastal. ... The park ranger
at the entrance offered no insight or even a brochure, only the
encouragement to ``Have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Our unscientific ranking: Second. We did have fun _ and would
gladly return.
</P>
<P>
   PENSACOLA BEACH
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Printed slogan or boast: ``World's whitest beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accuracy of that claim: Hard to tell, with all those
washboard-stomached, cigarette-dragging, teenage hunks and hotties
in the way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High tide: Parents, do you know where your teens are? Here!
This entire scene is ready for an MTV close-up, or maybe Discovery
channel could do an expose: ``Secrets of the Hormonally
Hyperdriven.'' ... Those nice, young, tattooed men sure are helpful
_ holding down the shower fixture levers so that the bikinied
ladies have both hands free to wash the sand off their suntanned
bods. How sweet! ... Those Florida Seminole insignia coolers seem
to hold an unending supply of Bud Lights. ... Lots of food and
drink places in the nearby Quietwater Beach and Boardwalk complex,
including a Hooters. Have we spotted a trend?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Low tide: Any visitor on the far side of 20 will instantly
feel older than the Queen Mother. ... Have to be careful not to get
flattened by the jacked-up cars and pickups in the parking lot. ...
This overpopulated beach has been virtually denuded of plant life
by wildlife of the two-legged variety.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Our unscientific ranking: Third, unless you're in the MTV
demographic (if you are, there is no other beach).
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 south to Montgomery, then follow I-65
south to U.S. 31 south to U.S. 29 to I-10. Go east on I-10 to
I-110, then south into Pensacola. It's about a five-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: The Pensacola Convention and Visitors Bureau can help
you select from the many lodging choices along or near Pensacola
Beach and Perdido Key. A recommended inn within a walk of downtown
attractions and restaurants is the Pensacola Victorian Bed and
Breakfast, 203 W. Gregory St.; 1-800-370-8354.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: Downtown harbors many fine restaurants, including Mr.
Manatees, with a deck overlooking the marina (850-434-0001); Dharma
Blue, with outdoor seating overlooking Seville Square
(850-433-1275); and Screaming Coyote, a cantina with monster
burritos and an inventive salsa bar (850-435-9002). The Pensacola
Bay view impressed more than the food at Landry's Seafood House,
but this chain link does a big family business (850-434-3600).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Upcoming event: The 23rd Annual Pensacola Seafood Festival,
with 185 arts and crafts booths and 21 food vendors, cooking
demonstrations and children's activities, is Sept. 22-24.
850-433-6512; www
</P>
<P>
   .fiestaoffiveflags.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other attractions: The National Museum of Naval Aviation
displays 130 restored aircraft and exhibits on historic battles,
and has an Imax (850-452-3604). The nine-square-block Pensacola
Village boasts city history museums and tours of restored homes,
costumed interpreters and craft demonstrators (850-444-8905).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Pensacola Convention and Visitors Bureau,
1-800-874-1234; www.visitpensacola.com.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
