<SLUG> BC-BEST-MOVIES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Scary Movie' shapes up as surprise financial hit
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who's the top dog at the movies this summer?
</P>
<P>
   You may think it's ``Mission: Impossible 2'' with its hefty
$209.9 million take so far at U.S. box offices. But consider this:
``M:I2'' cost an estimated $125 million to film, which places its
return on the dollar at about $1.68.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the ratio of money spent to money earned, Keenen Ivory
Wayans' ``Scary Movie'' looks as if it could be the summer's
biggest financial success. Its meager $19 million budget has
translated into $116.4 million in domestic ticket sales. That's a
return on each dollar of $6.13.
</P>
<P>
   At left is a chart of some of this summer's biggest movie
winners and losers (metro Atlanta moviegoers favored the winners,
especially ``Scary Movie'' and ``Big Momma's House'').
</P>
<P>
   But before ``Scary Movie'' fans start boasting, remember this:
Summer 2000 has nothing on last year's movies. You recall a scary
little movie called ``The Blair Witch Project''? It cost $350,000
and ultimately earned $140.5 million in domestic sales. That's a
return on the dollar of, ahem, $401.43.
</P>
<P>
   Now you know why the most oft-heard words in Hollywood financial
circles are ``Blair'' and ``witch.''
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Jorunal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
