<HEADER>
A2840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-LYNNE0726-COX     07-25 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNNE0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney's spouse carries conservative credentials of her own
 &HT;    By Gary Susswein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - As Dick Cheney oversaw American troops during
the Persian Gulf War in the early 1990s, his wife Lynne was busy
fighting her own battles over the lessons and values taught in
American schools.
</P>
<P>
   More than just a ``politician's wife,'' Lynne Cheney has been an
author, television pundit and, from 1986 to 1993, chairwoman of the
National Endowment for the Humanities, where she began her
controversial efforts to bring conservative values to college
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting the former defense secretary as his running mate
yesterday, Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush also
brought aboard a spouse whose resume evokes Hillary Clinton or
Elizabeth Dole far more than Barbara or Laura Bush _ and whose
background could become a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not one who followed (her husband) on the campaign
trail gazing unblinkingly and adoringly during his every
utterance,'' said Oliver Walter, a dean at the University of
Wyoming. ``One thinks of them as Lynne and Dick rather than as the
Cheneys.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials on Tuesday stopped short of trying to sell
Lynne and Dick as a buy-one, get-one-free package - as the Clintons
described themselves in 1992. But they made it clear Lynne Cheney
will play a role in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a woman of many accomplishments,'' Bush said. ``Lynne is
an incredibly important member of this team, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues describe the Casper, Wyo., native as
bright, personable and quick-witted. They say she's as well-versed
in many public policy issues as her husband.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps more controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who has a doctorate in British literature, drew fire
from some academics during her tenure at the National Endowment,
which distributes grant money for research projects. Critics
accused her of injecting politics into the agency and supporting
programs that reflected her conservative views.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney vetoed funding for a movie that said Christopher Columbus
had committed genocide in the Western Hemisphere. She appointed a
panel to develop standards for American history students _ then
blasted the standards because they placed as much emphasis on
African and Native American contributions to American society as on
European contributions.
</P>
<P>
   She has criticized schools for de-emphasizing Shakespeare and
other Western classics. And last year, she supported the Texas
Board of Education's decision to introduce phonics-based reading
over the objections of some educators and parents who felt it
suppressed critical thinking skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Lynne Cheney's activities mean she's extremely
well-connected and well-regarded in the religious right
community,'' said Sam Smoot of the Texas Freedom Network, a
religious right watchdog group. ``As the vice president's wife, she
would have a national platform and would use it to promote her
political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   But supporters see Cheney's ``agenda'' as a necessary
counteroffensive to the so-called politically-correct values they
say have become popular on campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is deeply interested in the academic health and
intellectual life of the country,'' said Anne Neal, former general
counsel of the National Endowment for the Humanities who works with
Cheney at the conservative American Council of Trustees and Alumni.
</P>
<P>
   That interest could make her more popular among some voters this
November than either her husband or Bush, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynne, because the reputation she gained at Humanities, is
seen more as a conservative ideologue - thus appealing to the right
wing of the party,'' said Walter.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Gary Susswein at gsusswein(at)statesman.com or
445-3654.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
