<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-SCENE     07-25 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-SCENE-690&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAMES, THEN SHOCK AND DISBELIEF FOR WITNESSES TO AIR FRANCE
CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (See AIRFRANCE-CRASH-ADVISORY-NYT for complete list of related
stories.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROISSY, France _ Witnesses described the brief, fiery flight of
AF 4590 as a vision of hell or a kind of bomb, in flames from the
time it rolled down the runway at Charles de Gaulle airport until
it smashed three minutes later into a tiny, wooden hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like some bomb taking off,'' said John Palmerston, an
Australian who saw the plane take off from the airport here. ``The
whole back end of the plane was on fire. I thought it was going to
crash right here at the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   In the little town of Gonesse, barely four miles southwest of
the airport, there were reactions of shock and distress. ``It was
truly a hell, there were flames everywhere,'' a witness told French
television channel LCI. ``There were pieces of the fuselage over
more than 200 meters, pieces of plastic, of cloth, bits of metal,
pieces of the wing, rivets. As for the hotel, there is nothing
left; it was blown to pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, 109 people died on the airplane, and
four more on the ground, apparently in the Hotelissimo hotel. A
huge cloud of gray and black smoke surged into the sky, visible for
at least 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   For Fabien Tillon, trying to manage the crisis from the offices
of the local authorities in Cergy-Pontoise, the first crash of a
Concorde was also a terrible blow to French pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big national shock,'' he said, as he tried to handle
two telephones and a cigarette. ``Many people died, but the symbol
of the Concorde, too. The Concorde is a huge national idea for
France, a symbol of engineering pride, and the fact that the
Concorde crashed, and so many people died, and on the soil of
France, it's a terrible shock.''
</P>
<P>
   The elegant, needle-nosed Concorde, the world's first supersonic
passenger plane, was developed by the French and the British in the
1960s as a kind of response to the U.S. and Soviet technological
competition, another version of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   It also served to heal some wounds left by France's veto in
December 1967 of British membership in the Common Market, now the
European Union _ hence the name of the plane. In more than 20 years
of commercial flying, however uneconomical and however noisy, the
Concorde had never crashed.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Firemen placed traffic cones across a blackened field,
apparently marking the places where charred bodies were found.
``Once you got used to looking through the smoke, the horror hits
you,'' an emergency worker who had been at the scene told Agence
France-Presse. ``By the dozens, bodies, or pieces of bodies,
horribly mutilated. Here and there, shoes, books, parts of
suitcases that are wasted away.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hotel, another witness told French television that
onlookers had smashed a window and tried to get into the building,
but the victims inside were already dead. ``There was nothing we
could do.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one guest jumped out the window to safety, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   Extraordinarily, it seemed, another hotel nearby, Les Relais
Bleus, was untouched. ``I thought the plane was going to land on my
desk,'' the owner told Europe 1 radio. ``I saw it heading for me in
flames. I just let go of the telephone and ran.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tillon said his staff was unbelieving at first. ``Frankly, when
we heard the news, we thought it was some kind of joke or an
emergency exercise,'' he said. ``And then we had confirmation that
the Concorde had crashed and presumably everyone was dead. It
really came like a blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Frechet, who worked in the normal flight path of the
Concorde and told Agence France-Presse that he flew on the
supersonic plane last December, said there had been growing fear of
a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew something like this would happen one day,'' Frechet
said. ``There is just too much traffic at Charles de Gaulle. There
is no zone for any plane to get rid of its fuel if had the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Tourbon, a Frenchwoman flying Tuesday from Charles de
Gaulle, echoed the normal sense of pride felt when a Concorde is
spotted in the air. ``It always excites me to see one,'' she said.
``It makes me proud. It's awful what's happened.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tillon described the ``red plan'' for national emergencies that
went smoothly into operation in his department, Val d'Oise, which
governs Gonesse. More than 200 firefighters were soon on the scene,
along with 110 policemen and 80 gendarmes, 13 ambulances, three
helicopters, the prefect and the prime minister, Lionel Jospin.
</P>
<P>
   But even as more emergency workers arrived, their vehicles
blocking the roads, there wasn't much to save, Tillon said. The
passengers all appeared to have died, and after the fire was put
under control, there came the grisly task of bagging the dead and
taking them to the line of waiting hearses.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, there was a large explosion, then, barely a second
later, another large explosion,'' an office worker said. ``We went
to the window, and the flames were higher than the trees. When we
went outside, pieces were falling down on us.'' One piece of metal
fell on the roof of a colleague's car, the worker said.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness told French television: ``I heard the noise,
because each time the Concorde flies over, I always have a look. I
saw it coming with an engine on fire, it tried to turn on its left,
then it fell and fell onto the hotel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
