A2842 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CONGRESS26-COX     07-25 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney's voting record has no left turns
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You won't find any dead armadillos or yellow
stripes on Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Bush's running mate has a congressional voting
record full of right turns and no drift across the middle of the
road _ where Texas liberal commentator Jim Hightower says only dead
critters and highway stripes are found.
</P>
<P>
   After Bush introduced Cheney as his running mate Tuesday, the
two did not dampen the pep rally atmosphere at the Frank Erwin
Special Events Center by fielding questions on how relevant
Cheney's voting record will be in the Bush's campaign of
compassionate conservatism. The Democrats are sure to try to paint
the Bush-Cheney ticket as too right wing to win, but Bush's
campaign aides swatted aside those suggestions after Tuesday's
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Albert Gore wants to suggest that this campaign be
conducted over somebody's voting record in the 1970s and 1980s,
we're happy to engage him,'' said Karl Rove, Bush's campaign
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Few political observers expect the issue to stick. After all, as
University of Texas political science professor Bruce Buchanan
said, ``It's the top guy, not the second guy, who sets the tone of
the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cheney, who represented Wyoming from 1979 until 1989,
likely will have to explain some of his votes.
</P>
<P>
   He supported income tax cuts, incentives for businesses and
increases in military spending that would fit nicely in a Bush
agenda. He also was one of eight lawmakers to oppose the Clean
Water Act of 1987 and fought more funding for the Endangered
Species Act and ``Superfund'' cleanups.
</P>
<P>
   He championed opening wilderness areas to more petroleum
exploration until drillers targeted lands near Wyoming's
Yellowstone National Park. He favored money for President Reagan's
Star Wars missile defense while wanting less money for Head Start.
He opposed gun control, supported school prayer and voted against
abortion rights, including measures that prohibited abortions even
in cases of rape, incest or when a woman's life was endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights, in particular, is a litmus issue for a core of
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The selection of Richard Cheney as Governor Bush's running
mate is a slap in the face of every American woman and the men who
care about them,'' said Gloria Feldt, president of Planned
Parenthood Action Fund. On the other side, Carol Long Tobias,
director of the National Right to Life Political Action Committee,
praised the Cheney selection: ``Mr. Cheney had a one hundred
percent pro-life voting record during his time in office and will
be a great asset to the Republican ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry J. Sabato, director of the University of Virginia Center
for Governmental Studies, said Cheney could use a couple of tactics
to slip criticism of his congressional record.
</P>
<P>
   First, he can blame Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can say, 'I was representing my constituents in Wyoming.
Since my years in Congress, I've modified my views,''' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   Or Sabato said Cheney can take the traditional route for a vice
presidential candidate and just disappear into the background of
the campaign. For years, Cheney's low-key personality has moderated
his public image. He has never been confused for the controversial
Newt Gingrich in style, although he could match him in votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was a human being created to fade in the background,
it's Dick Cheney,'' Sabato said.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, the Bush campaign will emphasize Cheney's last turn
on the political stage as Secretary of Defense during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the America people have seen Dick Chaney on a world
stage in a decision-making role,'' said Linda Divall, a GOP
political consultant. ``I don't think Dick Cheney's voting record
in the 1980s will be relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Madonna, director of the Center for Politics and Public
Affairs at Millersville University in Pennsylvania, said the
Democrats will find plenty in Cheney's record with which to attack.
</P>
<P>
   As the latest New York Times/CBS poll finds the race tightening,
it also finds voters shaping their opinions about Bush and his
Democratic opponent, Al Gore. A majority find Bush more likely to
reduce taxes and consider him a strong leader, while a majority
believe Gore is more likely to protect abortion rights, improve the
environment and make health care affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the Gore campaign will likely try to use
Cheney to paint the GOP ticket as too conservative on certain
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna said the Bush campaign probably can explain some of
Cheney's votes by putting them in context. Some of the votes are 20
years old and the issues have changed. For example, in an era of
budget surpluses does Cheney's support of a balanced budget
amendment mean anything to voters? Madonna doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   He said some social issues _ Cheney's opposition to the Equal
Rights Amendment for women _ might strike a chord with women
voters. That, Madonna said, probably would be the exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not going to live and die on the vice president's
record,'' he said. ``In the end, it's going to be about Gore and
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
