<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: O.J. SIMPSON; `EARLY SHOW'; NICK AT NITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson: More Debates
</P>
<P>
   O.J. Simpson, who is in the midst of a publicity push for his
new Web site, is quickly becoming the hot potato of the television
news industry.
</P>
<P>
   Last week ``The View,'' after booking Simpson for an interview
that was to take place Wednesday, canceled it amid complaints from
viewers and staff members who did not think Simpson should appear
on the syndicated program.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Monday, after originally agreeing to interview Simpson
for Tuesday's edition of NBC's ``Today,'' Matt Lauer, the program's
co-host, alerted producers that he did not want to take part in the
segment. Executives said he came to that decision after considering
over the weekend whether to do the interview. It was instead done
by his co-host, Katie Couric.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't feel comfortable doing it,'' said Jeff Zucker, the
executive producer of ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said that he allowed Lauer to excuse himself from the
Simpson interview duty because ``my position, since Day 1, since
I've been here, has been that I'd never put somebody in a position
of doing an interview they don't feel comfortable doing.'' Couric,
he added, had no objection to doing the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' executives did not offer many particulars on Lauer's
reasons, other than to indicate that he had expressed a personal
aversion to the Simpson subject and raised questions about the
newsworthiness of the interview, in which Simpson was certain to
plug his new Web site (as he did).
</P>
<P>
   For $9.95, the Web site, AskOJ.com, allows users to pose
questions to Simpson, who was acquitted in the murders of his
ex-wife, Nicole, and her friend Ron Goldman but was later found
liable in a wrongful-death civil suit. The site also sells
memorabilia relating to Simpson's football career.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer had plenty of company in refusing to do the interview. The
producers of ABC's ``Good Morning America'' and CBS's ``Early
Show'' _ both competitors of ``Today'' _ said they also declined to
have Simpson on their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Friedman, senior executive producer of the ``Early Show,''
which has Bryant Gumbel as co-host, said he declined because his
interview with Simpson would have come after the one scheduled for
``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I declined because we couldn't have him first,'' Friedman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Ross, the executive producer of ``Good Morning
America,'' said she declined to have Simpson on her program because
she does not believe he will offer any new information on his case.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is just never going to advance the story,'' said
Ross, who was in charge of all prime time news magazine coverage of
Simpson's criminal trial for ABC News. ``To have him come in and
promote a Web page, that's something that is underneath the limbo
pole of taste for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zucker said he believed that Couric's interview with Simpson
did break some new ground. For instance, she presented Simpson with
a statement from Camp Goodtimes, one of the charities to which
Simpson has said he will donate the profits from his Web site, that
said: ``We have not given approval to Mr. Simpson or his
representatives to use our name.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Zucker said, he believed the interview made for
``good journalism and good television.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few days ago, Lauer disclosed to television journalists
gathered in Pasadena, Calif., that he had fought, loudly, with
Zucker earlier this year, when he was asked to do more than one
interview with Darva Conger, the bride from Fox's ill-fated ``Who
Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire.'' However, Lauer said, he did
not refuse the assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Is Lauer developing an attitude? Not at all, Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that people feel comfortable enough to speak up,'' he
said. ``That's the hallmark of an open and professional
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Simpson's television publicity tour is scheduled to continue
today. He is to appear on Court TV's ``Crier Today'' and on the Fox
News Channel, which was forced to cancel separate appearances with
the anchors Paula Zahn and Linda Vester on Tuesday. Those are
scheduled to run Wednesday, instead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger E. Ailes, the Fox News Channel chairman and chief
executive, said that because of Tuesday's crash of a Concorde jet
outside Paris, he believed it would have been inappropriate to go
ahead with them Tuesday, though he said he expects that they will
be newsworthy in their own right. Simpson is also scheduled to
appear on CNN's ``Burden of Proof'' Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   `Early' Is Surviving
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, the producers of CBS's ``Early Show,'' which
made its debut in the fall, say they believe they are finally
making gains in the morning television ratings race.
</P>
<P>
   The morning program, which is shown from 7 to 9, is still a
distant third in the ratings behind its competitors, NBC's
``Today'' and ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' But it is getting a
nice bump, apparently because of the popularity of CBS's new
prime-time reality shows, ``Survivor,'' which has proven to be a
smash hit, and ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the program _ with Bryant Gumbel and Jane Clayson as
co-hosts _ was watched in 2.1 million households, more than in any
other week since March. That is considered a feat because the
summer is traditionally the slowest time of the year in the
television business.
</P>
<P>
   The program also seems to be making real gains among women ages
18 to 49. About 30 percent more women tuned into CBS between 7 a.m.
and 9 a.m. last week than did during that time period last year,
when CBS was running ``This Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly `Big Brother' and `Survivor' have given us a
boost,'' said Friedman, the senior executive producer. ``They've
opened the door, and we've kept them in the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The ratings represent the best news Friedman has had in a while.
The program has been slow to take off with viewers and had been
struggling to draw a higher audience than the show it had replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Nick at 15
</P>
<P>
   Nick at Nite, which takes over for the Nickelodeon cable network
at night, turned 15 this month. Since July 1985, from 9 p.m. to
5:30 a.m., it has been showing reruns of old sitcoms like ``Happy
Days,'' ``The Brady Bunch'' and ``All in the Family.'' Watched in
1.4 million households each night, it has become the
fourth-highest-rated channel in prime time on cable, after the USA,
TBS and TNT networks, which are helped in the ratings by sports or
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Nick at Nite will celebrate its birthday on Sunday with an
anniversary special in which television producers from the days of
old like Sherwood Schwartz (``The Brady Bunch,'' ``Gilligan's
Island'') introduce their favorite episodes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
