u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      07-25 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMOND IN THE ROUGH NEEDED TO MAKE PATRIOTS SPARKLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ The Patriots are not the Redskins, Ravens,
Titans, and Jaguars, teams that have some of the best pure talent
in the NFL. They are a team with a few stars, a few players who
have been All-Pro, but a team that must find a diamond in the rough
before the start of the season if they are to pull it together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Belichick will do this,'' said an AFC executive. ``He'll
bring young free agents in and turn one or two of them into
players. You watch, there'll be someone who makes that team and
plays a prominent role that has come out of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In this day of highly specialized scouting, few players slip
through the cracks and become great NFL players. Belichick brought
up the name Laroi Glover Tuesday as an example of a player nobody
knew much about but who learned to play for Jack Bicknell in
Barcelona a few years ago and is now an All-Pro for the New Orleans
Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then there is a late bloomer, such as Chad Eaton,
or a player who improves by leaps and bounds every year, such as
cornerback Kato Serwanga, a perfect example of what Belichick is
trying to find.
</P>
<P>
   Serwanga, who was signed as a free agent in 1998 during the
Bobby Grier regime, figures heavily in Belichick's thinking. In
camp, he is taking most of the reps on the first team, alongside Ty
Law. If Belichick doesn't give the nod to Antonio Langham, a former
Cleveland Browns draft pick of his, Serwanga appears to be in line
to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kato had a slow start in the spring and missed a number of
practices,'' said Belichick, ``but he's come back and had a solid
camp. He has to earn his spot. He'll have to beat out Tebucky
(Jones), Antonio Langham, and fifth-round pick Antwan Harris, but
he's in the running to be a good player for us. He's got a good
work ethic and he understands team defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Another such player could be Marc Megna, a former nose tackle
from the University of Richmond who went to New York Jets camp last
year and switched to middle linebacker before being cut. He was
picked up by the Patriots and switched to outside linebacker. A
high-motor player who never stops working to improve, Megna could
wind up being a top special teams player or even a superb pass
rusher like Chris Slade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's way ahead of the game,'' said Belichick. ``I don't see
him beating out Chris Slade, but he's come so far since I first saw
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the place where the Patriots need the biggest diamond
is the offensive line. Center Damien Woody is basically the
grizzled veteran of this group after one year on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are starting Adam Davis, a free agent rookie from
Oklahoma State, at right guard in place of injured Todd Rucci.
Davis, 6 feet 4 inches and 300 pounds, started 37 games at Oklahoma
State and helped his team average 311 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Grimes, a rookie free agent from Alabama, has performed
well at defensive end subbing for the injured Brandon Mitchell. He
appears to be quite athletic, a 6-4, 290-pounder who played against
tough competition for the Crimson Tide.
</P>
<P>
   Another player drawing some attention is receiver Shockmain
Davis, a 6-foot, 205-pound rookie free agent. Davis was a teammate
of Michael Bishop at Blinn (Texas) Junior College before
transferring to Angelo State, where he caught 67 passes for 1,120
yards (16.7-yard average). He seems to have the same attributes as
Tony Simmons, strength and speed.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard tight end Chris Eitzmann shows interesting ability, as
does offensive lineman Ryan Tujague.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Belichick brought 26 rookie free agents into camp. He
has weeded some out but remains very interested in some of the
players mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had such severe salary cap issues that they weren't
able to add depth by signing veterans. Their draft picks have added
little thus far. Second-rounder Adrian Klemm, an offensive tackle
from Hawaii, will miss all of camp following major knee surgery;
running back J.R. Redmond, their third-rounder, is coming off groin
surgery and a holdout; and fifth-rounder Dave Stachelski, a tight
end from Boise State, has had one injury after another.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the injury situation hadn't opened the door for
unheralded players to step up, Belichick's method is to give the
Megnas, Grimeses, and Davises of the world a chance.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't find his diamond in the rough, the Patriots may be
in for a long season. The attitude might be better and the schemes
more creative, but no coach can win without good players. Now
Belichick must get a little lucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
