<HEADER>
A2848 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUM     07-25 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERYDAY-ETHICS-COLUMN-ADV30-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV30 
 EVERYDAY ETHICS 
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 30, AND THEREAFTER.
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's EVERYDAY ETHICS column. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the EVERYDAY ETHICS column _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By RANDY COHEN 
 c.2000 Randy Cohen 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIVE UP YOUR SEATS
</P>
<P>
   Q: We are cleaning out our basement, selling a few yard-sale
items and giving others to charity, including two child-safety car
seats built five years ago. At that time, they met all safety
standards, but they fall short of today's stricter standards. Is it
ethical to sell them? To give them away? What if a warning is
provided? _
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cushman, Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   A: Your intentions are honorable, but at least two of your
yard-sale choices are ill-advised. There is something unseemly
about selling subpar baby seats to the poor (or the overly frugal):
surely we don't want a society with one set of safety standards for
those with money and a set of inferior standards for those without.
</P>
<P>
   Giving away your car seat might remove the taint of financial
gain, and providing a warning allows the recipient to make an
informed decision. He's made the wrong decision, however, if he
decides to use the car seats, according to Liz Neblett of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. Besides today's
stricter standards, ''the Juvenile Product Manufacturers
Association recommends that seats not be used after six years, and
some manufacturers have adopted a five-year standard because of the
possible degradation of material,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be swayed by the argument that an inferior car seat is
preferable to none, either. ''There are organizations in almost
every state that make seats available free or at reduced prices to
those who truly can't afford them,'' Neblett says.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, as standards are upgraded for products, we needn't
discard all of our old stuff. For example, you might ethically sell
a used car that lacks air bags. But in this case the federal
highway agency's position is wise, car seats being relatively
inexpensive and children being relatively fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of the references I used in a job application is my
former boss, whom I am now dating. We were not romantically
involved while we worked together, and she says our current
involvement has no bearing on the recommendation she would give me.
Am I obliged to reveal our relationship to my potential employer? _
Anonymous, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A: Even with a sincere determination to be punctilious, your
former boss faces a conflict of interest in writing a reference for
someone she has seen naked. If no one else at the old firm is in a
position to write you a recommendation, then she may write it, but
she should acknowledge your personal connection and leave it to
your potential employer to gauge its effect on her comments. Her
disclosure can be brief (''As someone I have known both personally
and professionally. . . .'') and need not extol your kissable lips
or that funny way you crinkle your eyes at a moment of passion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I got home with a new drill, I discovered that the
salesperson had given me a box that held three smaller boxes, each
containing a drill. When I returned it, that salesperson begged me
not to report him, saying: ''I have been selling them like this all
day. If the boss finds out, I will be fired.'' I left with three
drills. He started restacking the display with single drill boxes.
Did I do the right thing? _ Ronald R. Graham, Elmhurst, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not exactly. While you do not have to report the clerk to his
boss - his mistake was an honest one, and it can't be undone now -
that does not mean you get three drills for the price of one.
Surely a way can be found to return two of them without costing the
clerk his job. Can't he slip them back into the display? One
caution: if rectifying the situation involves hiding a power drill
in your pants, be insanely careful with the on-off switch.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Do you have ethical questions that you need answered? Send them
to ethicist &LR; nytimes.com, or Everyday Ethics, New York Times
Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., 14th floor, New York, N.Y. 10168.
</P>
