<HEADLINE>
STOCKS ADVANCE, LED BY SEMICONDUCTOR COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The main stock market gauges rose for the first time
in three sessions Tuesday, led by solid gains in big semiconductor
companies like Intel and Applied Materials.
</P>
<P>
   But the rise in prices was far from uniform. On the New York
Stock Exchange, the ratio of stocks that rose to those that lost
value was about even.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty lackluster session, but at least we finished
in the green,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst at
Prudential Securities. ``The one positive was a rebound in
semiconductor stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 14.85 points, or 0.1
percent, to 10,699.97, led by Intel, Wal-Mart and Procter &AMP; Gamble
.
</P>
<P>
   Gains in Cisco Systems and Nortel Networks helped to lift the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index by 10.18 points, or 0.7 percent,
to 1,474.47.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nasdaq composite index gained 48.00 points, or 1.21
percent, to 4,029.57.
</P>
<P>
   Over the previous two sessions, the Nasdaq had fallen 4.9
percent on concern that profit growth would slow in the third and
fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Chip-related stocks rallied after the Semiconductor Equipment
Association of Japan said sales soared 126 percent in May. That
report followed stronger-than-expected earnings from Texas
Instruments, which posted its results after the market closed on
Monday and painted a bright outlook for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Among chip stocks, Intel gained 2~, to 140~. Micron Technology
rose 1}, to 86}. And Applied Materials rose 4, to 84\.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the news on semiconductor sales, there was not much
to impress traders or investors.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Federal Reserve chairman, Alan Greenspan,
offered few insights during semiannual testimony before the House
Banking Committee on whether policy makers will raise short-term
interest rates at its Aug. 22 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of guidance places even greater importance on data that
will be released over the next few weeks, including reports on
second-quarter gross domestic product and the employment cost
index, a key inflation measure. The employment cost index is
scheduled to be released Thursday. And the first estimate of
second-quarter economic growth is expected on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Greenspan is saying they don't know what they are
going to do on Aug. 22,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst
at Cantor Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   Piskorowski added, ``Greenspan made it plain they are waiting to
see what the data are showing before they will make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug shares were generally weak Tuesday after a report from
Pfizer showed slower-than-expected revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer fell 4[, to 43 11/16. Bristol-Myers Squibb lost 1 5/16,
to 48|. Schering-Plough dropped 1 61/64, to 43 5/16. And Eli Lilly
slipped 9/64, to 101.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com was another loser. Shares of the Internet retailer
fell 1[, to 37|, after the company said Joseph Galli, its president
and chief operating officer, was leaving to become chief executive
of VerticalNet Inc. Galli had held those positions for only a year.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters Group , the financial information provider, rose 3}, to
119\, after it reported that first-half earnings soared 75 percent,
in large part because of higher revenue from Instinet, its online
trading network.
</P>
<P>
   But MedQuist tumbled 12], or 40 percent, to 18 13/16, after the
medical records transcriber reported operating profits that were
weaker than expected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
