<SLUG> BC-RACING-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-YEAR-OLDS TO BE FEATURED AT RENEWED SARATOGA 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ They called it Horse Haven when racing
was inaugurated at Saratoga Springs in 1863 for a meet that lasted
three days. But the next year, the ``new'' Saratoga Race Course
opened on Union Avenue. And on Wednesday, for the 132nd year, it
will open for racing again, starting a prestigious six-week
schedule that will feature 35 stakes races carrying purses of $8.7
million along with historic reminders that the stately old track
has also grown to become ``the Graveyard of Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same oval where Man o' War lost his only race in the
Sanford Stakes 80 years ago, seven 2-year-old fillies will take the
spotlight on opening day in the Schuylerville, followed one day
later by juvenile colts in the Sanford. They will be the first
brace of races for 2-year-olds at Saratoga, where horses begin
careers and strengthen their claims to championships.
</P>
<P>
   The opening-day crowd will be greeted by $3.5 million in
renovations that were performed without altering the country style
of the old track. They include new jockeys quarters inside a quaint
colonial building dating to 1890, new entrances to the clubhouse
and grandstand, irrigation systems for the Oklahoma turf training
course, dormitory upgrades on the backside and the replacement of
1,275 seats in a remodeled grandstand.
</P>
<P>
   But one change will be made on the track. D. Wayne Lukas, who
has won 5 Schuylervilles, 5 Sanfords and 27 stakes for juveniles
overall at Saratoga, will not have a filly in the opening-day
feature. But he will be represented through his extended family, so
to speak. Mark Hennig, one of several former assistants to Lukas,
will enter an all-star pair, Gold Mover, with Craig Perret riding,
and With Ability, with Jerry Bailey riding, and they will go to the
gate as solid favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Hennig also trains a third star juvenile filly, Raging Fever,
who will wait for her chance on stage later in the meet. All three
fillies are owned by Edward P. Evans, the owner of the 2,500-acre
Spring Hill Farm in Virginia, who also bred them. So, Hennig and
Evans can take a clear shot at all three major races for young
fillies at Saratoga: the Schuylerville at six furlongs, the
Adirondack at six and a half furlongs on Aug. 14 and the Spinaway
at seven furlongs on Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a chance to win the first stakes of the
meet, and it's nice to be in a position for the sweep,'' Hennig
said. ``But Saratoga is a funny place. Strange things can happen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to stretch his memory very far back for proof.
Two years ago, the long shot Call Me Up went to the gate at 17-1,
led wire to wire and cruised home the winner in the Schuylerville.
</P>
<P>
   The five other fillies facing Hennig's pair in the Schuylerville
also have great expectations starting with Caught Out, who has
raced twice and won twice at Woodbine in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a filly that wants to run on,'' said Roger Attfield, who
trains Caught Out for Richard Bonnycastle. ``She's got enough class
to win sprinting, but she's not a sprinter. She's definitely
training well enough, and she's ready for this race.''
</P>
<P>
   When the juvenile colts appear on Thursday to complete Round 1
of the 2-year-old series, Lukas will be back on track with Michael
Tabor's Yonaguska. The colt, a son of Cherokee Run, the 1994 sprint
champion, was bought in February for $1.9 million. He won his debut
at Churchill Downs by nine lengths and won his next start at
Belmont in the Flash Stakes, dashing five and a half furlongs in 57
4/5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know he's fast,'' Lukas allowed. ``Now the trick is getting
him to relax. We've had 14 different 2-year-old winners this year,
and it's been our most successful summer with them yet. We're very
deep on these colts, and it's too early to tell who's the best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
