<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ EARNINGS MEET EXPECTATIONS, DESPITE SLUGGISH PC SHIPMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compaq Computer Corp. reported second quarter earnings Tuesday
that met analysts' estimates, and the company's executives forecast
strong revenue growth in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended June 30, Compaq reported earnings of $387
million, or 22 cents per diluted share, compared with a loss of
$184 million in the comparable period a year ago. Revenues grew by
7 percent to $10.13 billion from $9.42 billion in the second
quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding investment gains of $25 million after tax, Compaq
earned 21 cents per diluted share, equal to the consensus estimate,
according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq reported its results after the close of the market.
Compaq shares closed at $28.1875, up $1.5625, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's results come after quarterly reports from IDC Corp. and
Dataquest Inc. that showed that PC shipments rose less than
forecast in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   IDC said PC unit shipments in the second quarter rose 14.5
percent from the year-earlier period, below its estimate of 15
percent. Dataquest said global shipments rose 18 percent, below its
forecast for 18.5 percent growth. IDC said U.S. shipments rose 7.2
percent, while Dataquest reported 11.5 percent. Analysts blamed the
slower-than-expected growth on slowing consumer sales and on
shortages of microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole PC sector took a hit from the IDC and Dataquest
numbers coming out, but those were essentially retrospective,''
said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan. Compaq ``was
spot on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After stumbling badly two years ago, Compaq has continued to
lose market share, primarily to Dell Computer Corp. and
Hewlett-Packard Co. Although Compaq remains the leader worldwide,
it now has has 13.2 percent of the global market, down from 14.3
percent in the year-ago quarter, according to IDC.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said enterprise computing revenue was $3.4 billion, an
increase of 9 percent year-over-year. Compaq's commercial PC group
reported revenue of $3.3 billion, an increase of just 3 percent
year-over-year, but, more significantly, returned to profitability
in the second quarter. Compaq's consumer group posted revenue of
$1.6 billion, an increase of 32 percent over the prior year period.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter marked the end of Michael Capellas' first year as
Compaq's president and chief executive. Capellas has worked to turn
Compaq around by streamlining manufacturing processes and
rationalizing its product lines. But the company's revenue growth
still pales in comparison to market leaders like Dell in PC's or
Sun Microsystems Inc. in servers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to deliver strong, double-digit revenue growth in
the second half of the year,'' Capellas said in a statement. ``I
feel the renewed energy and enthusiasm in our people and their
determination to succeed. I am very confident in our ability to
meet our third quarter and full year objectives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles R. Wolf, an analyst with Warburg Dillon Read, said
he thought Compaq would be challenged to meet these goals. ``While
the quarter was on target, they've got to deliver substantial
revenue and earnings gains to meet guidance because Capellas is out
there with these very aggressive promises,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
