<HEADER>
A2858 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-TURNER-UNFOUNDATION07     07-25 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-UNFOUNDATION0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Environment, welfare of adolescents recipients of Turner
largesse
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Ted Turner's latest round of international
philanthropy, announced this week in Brazil, focuses largely on two
areas dear to the Atlanta businessman's heart: improving the lives
of adolescent girls and protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Foundation, the organization set up to to
distribute Turner's $1 billion, 10-year gift to U.N.-related
causes, held its board meeting in Rio de Janeiro _ board member
Ruth Cardoso is Brazil's first lady _ and awarded $42 million in
grants. That brought the total distributed so far to more than $300
million.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $42 million, about $21 million will be devoted to
improving ``the social and economic situation of adolescent girls
worldwide,'' the foundation said in a statement. Another $6 million
went to environmental projects, including some designed to protect
U.N.-designated ``World Heritage sites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with the U.N., we have developed an exciting program
to help protect some of the world's most important natural
resources,'' Turner, the foundation's chairman, said in the
statement. ``By investing in these incredible World Heritage sites,
we hope to protect these sites for future generations and work with
local communities to demonstrate the economic benefits of
conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   The full list of grants awarded this week is as follows:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $2.9 million over three years to the U.N. Children's Fund
(UNICEF) and the U.N. Population Fund (UNFPA) for phase two of a
project to enhance the health and development of adolescents. This
phase will focus on empowering adolescent girls in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $3 million over three years to UNICEF to improve the ``low
status of adolescent girls in Malawi society'' through education,
youth centers and vocational schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $2.2 million over three years to the U.N. Gender Task Force
and the U.N. country team in El Salvador to ``ensure human
development opportunities'' for poor girls in El Salvador through
education, training and ``awareness raising.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  $836,000 over three years to the U.N. Development Program
(UNDP) and UNFPA country team in Sao Tome to ``create sustainable
livelihoods for adolescent girls and promote gender empowerment in
their communities.'' The project will also provide reproductive
health services through ``peer educators.''
</P>
<P>
   -$1.5 million over three years to the Mongolia country team of
UNICEF, UNFPA, World Health Organization (WHO) and the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) to
improve the lives of adolescents in Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   -$1.1 million over three years to the UNICEF/UNFPA country team
in Senegal to improve the lives of adolescent girls by helping with
reproductive health, education and employment.
</P>
<P>
   -$1.3 million over three years to UNFPA and UNICEF to improve
health and social services for adolescent girls in Benin.
</P>
<P>
   -$679,000 over three years to UNFPA to improve the lives of
adolescent girls in Burkina Faso by addressing limited employment
opportunities and ``gender inequality.''
</P>
<P>
   -$2.1 million over three years to the UNFPA/UNICEF country team
to improve the lives of adolescents in Palestinian society by
addressing the ``critical need for quality reproductive health
information and education.''
</P>
<P>
   -$1.6 million to the UNICEF/UNFPA/UNDP country team in Mali to
improve the lives of adolescent girls by increasing their access to
family planning services, promoting their involvement in politics,
and by paying special attention to girls who live on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   -$3.15 million to UNFPA to develop ways to improve sexual and
reproductive health care provided by donor agencies around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   -$1.6 million over three years to the UNICEF country team in
Mauritania to educate adolescent girls in that country.
</P>
<P>
   -$400,000 to the U.N. Institute for Training and Research
(UNITAR) to help developing countries reach the technical expertise
necessary to effectively negotiate the emissions reduction
mechanisms related to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol on global warming.
</P>
<P>
   -$77,000 to UNESCO to encourage development of a major World
Heritage biodiversity program for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   -$2 million over four years to UNESCO, to be matched by $500,000
raised by tour operators, to use World Heritage sites to develop
ways to link tourism and conservation.
</P>
<P>
   -$4.2 million over four years to the U.N. Environmental Program
(UNEP) to support the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment, an
assessment of the ginvestment in Nigeria's economic infrastructure,
democracy, health services for children, and to explore ways of
reducing Nigeria's $31 billion external debt.
</P>
<P>
   -$132,000 to the U.N. Development Group to create a
communication tool with information on development issues that
would be available to U.N. development agencies and country teams
on the internet.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: U.N. Foundation: www.unfoundation.org/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
