<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MARRIAGETAX     07-25 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MARRIAGETAX26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDITORIAL: Married couples entitled to relief
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now here's a doozy of a justification, even for the
president of the United States, who's had plenty of practice of
late.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton has vowed to veto legislation that would do away
with the ``marriage penalty'' tax. It would immediately raise the
standard deduction for married couples to to that of two single
people, and gradually expand the 15 percent tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton considers the legislation too costly. He described
it as ``one part of a fiscally irresponsible, poorly targeted and
regressive tax plan.'' (Another part, apparently, is the phaseout
of estate taxes, which Clinton has also promised to veto.)
</P>
<P>
   ``By itself, I will veto the plan,'' Clinton said. Unless, of
course, the GOP ``compromises'' by agreeing to Clinton's latest
Medicare entitlement. If Republican lawmakers let Clinton have his
own fiscally irresponsible $250 billion Medicare prescription
benefit plan, so appealing to the powerful senior voting bloc,
well, Clinton just could find this $90 billion marriage penalty
relief thing a whole lot more palatable.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight percent of married couples pay the marriage penalty,
according to the Treasury Department. The average annual tax
``penalty'' for not being single is $1,400, Republicans say. The
measure that lawmakers approved last week would reduce taxes for
married couples by $90 billion over the next five years. And the
evidence shows there's nothing irresponsible about ending the
marriage penalty but a whole lot that's questionable about
Clinton's Medicare prescription coverage plan.
</P>
<P>
   Fact No. 1: Just last week, the Congressional Budget Office
projected a massive $2.17 trillion in federal surpluses over the
next decade. Last month, the White House had projected a $1.87
trillion surplus, more than double its January forecast of $887
billion. Any customer overcharged in a store would return, receipt
in hand, and demand the difference. The customer would get it, and
an apology, too. Why is it so difficult for the government to
refund the money it's overcharged taxpayers?
</P>
<P>
   Fact No. 2: Democrats complain that the GOP's plans to eliminate
the marriage penalty, along with estate taxes, would result in 43
percent of the cuts benefiting the wealthiest 1 percent of
Americans. They call it a giveaway to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   The Tax Foundation reports that the wealthiest 1 percent paid
one-third of the federal individual income tax in 1997, the most
recent data available. The top 5 percent of income earners made
31.8 percent of all income, but paid 51.9 percent of federal
individual income taxes. The top 10 percent made 42.8 percent of
all income and paid 63.2 percent of the taxes.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the bottom 50 percent of the nation's taxpayers
earned 13.8 percent of all income in 1997, and paid 4.3 percent of
taxes. That those who pay most of the taxes receive most of the tax
cuts is neither unfair nor a giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   Fact No. 3: Only 2 percent of Americans are currently affected
by the estate tax that allows the federal government to tax up to
55 percent of estates worth more than $675,000. But this punitive
``death tax'' forces one in three families affected to sell all or
part of their business to pay the estate tax, according to the
Small Business Administration. Similar to the recently repealed
federal phone tax, it used to be a tax on the rich. But in these
economic good times, the homeowner with a 401(k) plan and some life
insurance that would place his estate in the death tax bracket
isn't rich, just a careful planner.
</P>
<P>
   Fact No. 4: The Medicare plan Clinton is touting would offer
prescription drug coverage for all Medicare beneficiaries. The GOP
has offered its own version. But, according to the Heritage
Foundation, although nine out of 10 Medicare beneficiaries use
prescription drugs, only one in 10 has annual out-of-pocket
expenditures for prescription drugs of $1,000 to $2,000, and only 4
percent report spending more than $2,000. And according to the
Kaiser Foundation's latest data, nearly 70 percent of Medicare
recipients have some form of prescription drug coverage _ through
employer-sponsored health plans, Medigap, Medicare HMOs or
Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Government is obliged, of course, to provide for the truly needy
among Medicare recipients. It is not fiscally responsible to
provide another, costly government-run entitlement to all 40
million recipients when, clearly, only a few need it. It is,
however, politically expedient in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Taking all this into account, Clinton should be hard pressed to
come up with an explanation as to why relieving the tax burden on
families in a booming economy is anathema, but why Americans should
consider it noble that the government is taking their money to
spend on an unnecessary entitlement. We urge the president to sign
the estate tax and marriage penalty legislation and allow families
to keep more of their hard-earned money.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial appeared in The Atlanta Journal
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
