<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HUNTRESS-TV-REVIEW-NY     07-25 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNTRESS-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE HUNTRESS': SINGLE MOM, DESPERATELY SEEKING BAIL JUMPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look, it's another vulnerable single woman with a heart of gold,
just trying to find her way along life's rocky road, which is
strewn with all the wrong men. But Dottie Thorson stands out from
the pack. She drinks, smokes, cusses and uses her 19-year-old
daughter and large firearms as accessories in her work. Dottie is a
bounty hunter, making ends meet by hauling in miscreants who have
jumped bail.
</P>
<P>
   That's the premise of ``The Huntress,'' a series USA is
unveiling Wednesday night. Played straight, it would surely be
tiresome. But presented as an off-kilter spoof, and draped around a
winningly drawn central character, the premise has promise.
</P>
<P>
   As portrayed with slightly nutsy, dewy-eyed enthusiasm by
Annette O'Toole, Dottie is someone you know you'll never meet. But
that doesn't stop you from wishing that you could.
</P>
<P>
   Just to make things complicated, there really is a bounty hunter
named Dottie Thorson, who was the inspiration for a television
movie, shown on USA in March, that also starred O'Toole. Thorson,
you're told, took up bounty hunting, the occupation of her husband,
Ralph, after he was killed by a car bomb. And despite such
occupational hazards, she brought her daughter, Brandi, into the
family business. Thus the voice-over line that opens the series:
``Only the unbelievable parts are true.'' True? Well, who cares?
</P>
<P>
   When first glimpsed, Brandi (Jordana Spiro) is standing on a
street corner in the flimsiest of tiny frocks, winking at passing
cars. An S.U.V. stops, she climbs in and throws a pair of handcuffs
on the driver, announcing that she knows he's a fugitive. Mom shows
up in an instant, holding a rifle to the guy's head, and Brandi
socks him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get blood on that dress, I'm gonna kill you,'' wails
Dottie. Brandi whines back, ``Chill out, Mom, OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Luis Antonio Ramos plays Ricky Guzman, the bail bondsman who
reluctantly hires the Thorsons. Ricky's business is a mess. His
office is overflowing with the appliances and other large objects
his long-gone clients left as collateral. ``I make half my money
these days on eBay,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Tiny Bellows (James Remar). Dottie brought him in,
but he captured her heart. When her daughter describes Tiny as
``the baddest killer psycho biker in the state,'' Dottie coos:
``He's not a psycho, Brandi. Yes, he's made some bad lifestyle
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to Dottie, Tiny's in prison, where she visits him
for heart-to-heart chats. When he assures her that she is a natural
bounty hunter, she's so thrilled she giggles. ``It's like finding
out you're naturally talented in karaoke or something,'' she says,
beaming.
</P>
<P>
   On another visit she confesses her lack of confidence about
finding her prey. ``I feel like I'm chasing a ghost,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   He replies dreamily, ``You are.''
</P>
<P>
   That ghost is Ralph, whose wife and daughter are still pretty
angry over his neglect. As they try to deal with their feelings,
the show threatens to turn maudlin. Big mistake. Even a little more
of that would turn this loopy soap bubble into mere soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately &UR; , &LR;  there's little time for feelings in Wednesday
night's episode, written by the series' executive producer, Pamela
Norris, and directed by Jeffrey Reiner. Mother and daughter race
another bounty hunter to capture yet another bounty hunter who has
gotten himself into more than the usual trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Dottie and Brandi catch up with their quarry (Gary Busey, who
fits right into the antic spirit of the enterprise) at a car wash,
where Brandi chases him through suds and spray.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that smell?'' asks Dottie, once they get back in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi replies: ``That would be me. Got the optional air
freshener applied.''
</P>
<P>
   That kid's smart mouth does get annoying after a while. Good
thing her mom is such a charmer.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE HUNTRESS'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Wednesday on USA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A USA Cable Entertainment production. Pamela Norris, writer and
executive producer; Jeffrey Reiner, director; Scott White,
producer; Bruno Heller, consulting producer.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Annette O'Toole (Dottie Thorson), Jordana Spiro (Brandi
Thorson), James Remar (Tiny Bellows), Luis Antonio Ramos (Ricky
Guzman) and Gary Busey (Tommy Van Slyke). &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Just before ``The Huntress,'' on Wednesdays at 9 p.m., USA is
offering new episodes of another familial adventure, ``Cover Me.''
This is the story of Danny Arno (Peter Dobson), an undercover FBI
agent who shares his work and peril with his wife and three
teen-age children. Despite that obvious similarity, these two shows
are far apart in approach. ``Cover Me'' is far more slick, for good
and ill. Its production has the sheen of the best television
productions, but you may feel that you've been down this road a few
times too many.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's episode puts the family in danger as a onetime
pornographer gets out of prison vowing vengeance upon Danny and the
mysterious femme fatale who helped Danny get the goods on the guy
years before. There is a nifty plot twist, but you may well guess
the secret long before the bad guy does.
</P>
<P>
   Melora Hardin, as Danny's wife, Barbara, and Cameron Richardson,
Antoinette Picatto and Michael Angarano, as the children, make a
sensitive, picture-perfect family. The suspense is supposed to come
from your fears that at least two family members may be killed by
that bad guy. On the first night of a new season? You think so?
</P>
</TEXT>
