<SLUG> BC-TV-TOUR-SPELLING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATIRE CREATOR BACKS OFF WHEN IT COMES TO THE SPELLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Never underestimate the power of a mogul
peeved. Aaron Spelling, father of Tori and countless prime-time
soaps, didn't appreciate some passages in The WB's new soap spoof,
``Grosse Pointe,'' and changes are being made in the pilot, which
critics haven't seen yet.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Star, creator and producer of the half-hour comedy about
behind-the-scenes antics on a fictional show that's eerily similar
to ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' says his relationship with the
Spellings is too important to ruin for a Hollywood satire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my intention to go out and hurt anybody's feelings,''
Star said Monday. ``Aaron Spelling and Tori Spelling were upset and
they are people who I have really great relationships with.''
</P>
<P>
   Star, currently the golden-boy producer of HBO's ``Sex and the
City,'' created and produced ``90210'' and ``Melrose Place,''
making lots of money for Spelling's production company over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that ``Grosse Pointe'' remains satirical, but
that a character whose appearance and mannerisms are much like Tori
Spelling's will be modified. Star said the Tori-like actress
(Lindsay Sloane) will have brown hair instead of red, references to
her career emerging out of nepotism will be eliminated, and a scene
in which an actress purges herself in the back of a limousine will
be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not easily letting it go,'' Star admitted, ``but the
important thing to me is that it wasn't really worth fighting to
the point of perhaps not seeing it on the air. ... I agree if
you're doing a satire, you sometimes have to be merciless and
that's where the humor comes from, but I feel confident that we'll
be able to sort of dance around this without hurting the show.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I've always had a nice relationship with Aaron.
That's why I'm taking a lot of his concerns to heart. If I didn't
have a good relationship with him, this would not be my response.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Saturday has been the graveyard shift of prime time.
Often, producers who were told their new series had been picked up
didn't know whether to celebrate or toss in the towel when they
learned their show would be airing on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   This season, after struggling gamely for several years with
``Profiler,'' ``The Pretender'' and a variety of other dramas, NBC
is surrendering and going with theatrical movies on Saturday. ABC
chose that route last season. With Fox continuing its reality
package of ``Cops'' and ``America's Most Wanted'' on Saturdays,
only CBS will be presenting original, scripted material on Saturday
nights this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Even the energetic WB network, which had always planned to be a
seven-night-a-week operation, has changed its mind for now. Jamie
Kellner, the network's CEO, said: ``I think Saturday night is the
least exciting place to try to invest money in programming. And
since a number of our stations continue to have sports commitments
(on Saturday nights), I think it may be a place that we stay away
from for quite a while.''
</P>
<P>
   James Cameron sank the ``Titanic.'' Now it's Seattle's turn.
</P>
<P>
   The mega-producer of blockbuster films tries his hand at
television this fall with Fox's ``Dark Angel,'' a sci-fi drama
about a genetically altered superwoman (Jessica Alba) who
reluctantly fights for truth, justice and a place to park her
motorcycle while eluding the bad people who did experiments on her
when she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   The year is 2020. The scene is Seattle, shortly after terrorists
have set off an electromagnetic pulse in the atmosphere that knocks
out all satellites, toppling the economy and plunging the world
into a 1930s-style depression in which politicians are for hire,
cops are crooked and the future looks drearier than Seattle in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Why Seattle?
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's co-producer, Charles Eglee (``Murder One''), said:
``What we really wanted to get a sense of was an urban landscape
kind of pressing in around people, to see it teeming and
overflowing, and Seattle has that sort of downtown. You've got that
sense of enclosure. And all of it is happening against this
beautiful backdrop with mountains and water and everything. The
visual tension between this distressed world and this natural
beauty was kind of interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the series is being shot in Vancouver, B.C., where
natural beauty costs 30 percent less. But there will be shots of a
charred Space Needle in ``Dark Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just this symbol of 1960s buoyant American optimism about
the future and technology,'' Eglee said. ``We thought it would be
interesting to take that location in a post-dot-com world, where
the old money is the faded dot-com fortunes, where people are
trying to keep up appearances and keep things together because the
world is broken. It just seemed like a logical setting for this
piece.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
