<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKTRADES-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MARKET PLACE: SEC PROPOSES DISCLOSURE of DATA ON STOCK TRADES  
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many investors know to the penny how much they pay
in commissions when they trade a stock, but have no idea how good
an execution they get for their money.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission Tuesday proposed a rule
that will force the people who actually execute the trades, ranging
from Nasdaq market makers to specialists on the New York Stock
Exchange floor, to compile and disclose statistics on how they
trade each stock in which they make a market. The SEC is asking for
comment for 45 days, after which it will decide whether to act on
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   If the rule is adopted and works as is hoped, it will provide
answers to many questions that have bedeviled the market as
competition has grown. For the first time, investors will be able
to see what they are getting for their commissions in terms of
quality of execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can it be that most investors today simply do not know
what happens to their orders after they click `submit'?'' asked
Arthur Levitt, the SEC chairman. ``It doesn't make sense when you
recognize that missing the best price by the minimum increment
available _ 1/16 _ on a 1,000-share order is worth $62.50, an
amount that dwarfs the commission of most online firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those online firms, as well as others that take orders
by phone, have been able to offer low commission rates because they
effectively get a portion of the profit generated from trading
orders. Some do that by sending orders to markets or market makers
that pay for order flow _ or giving a penny or two a share to the
firms. Some others send their orders to sister companies, a
practice known as internalization.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics the SEC is requesting will make it possible to
assess the quality of execution offered by each market maker in
each stock, and to measure its performance on different kinds of
orders. The figures are likely to provide information on whether
market makers who pay for order flow are able to do so because they
often force investors to pay higher prices than their competitors
would have done.
</P>
<P>
   They will show how often market makers were able to improve
prices _ that is, to allow the investor to buy or sell a stock at a
price better than the posted bid or asked price for a stock _ and
how often investors ended up doing worse than that price. The
figures will also show how fast orders were executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will provide information on the cost of trading, which I
don't think most investors understand,'' said Laura Unger, a member
of the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Colby, deputy director of the SEC's division of market
regulation, said he hoped the disclosures would force some market
makers to improve the quality of their markets or risk losing
business.
</P>
<P>
   Some market makers voiced support of the SEC while noting that
they had not yet seen details. ``This will hold everyone's feet to
the fire,'' said Bernard L. Madoff, the chairman of Bernard L.
Madoff Investment Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Michael T. Dorsey, general counsel of Knight Trading, said that
``disclosure is the right way to go'' and that he was pleased that
the SEC had not moved to impose rules mandating market structure.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC said it would study trading on Nasdaq and the New York
Stock Exchange to see if further steps were needed on
internalization and payment for orders.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, analyzing the numbers produced by the firms will
be a daunting task, but the SEC hopes that the financial press and
others will make sense of them. Each market maker will be releasing
about 300 numbers on each stock that it trades, and it will be
doing so on a monthly basis. The figures are to be posted on each
firm's web site.
</P>
<P>
   The volume is so large because there are many different kinds of
orders. It is clearly easier to execute small orders than large
ones, and market orders, to buy or sell a stock at the best price
available, differ from limit orders, which call for buying or
selling a stock only at a certain price. Moreover, limit orders
that are close to the current market price are different from
orders that are farther away. So numbers are needed for many
different permutations.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage firms will have to tell their customers once a quarter
how they decide where to send orders, and what relationships the
firms have with those places. They will also have to state the
rationale for choosing that market maker. The statistics would then
make it possible to ascertain whether that market maker really was
making a good market.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are one way the SEC is trying to deal with issues
raised by the recent proliferation of competitors, who have
fragmented the markets. Such competition can bring efficiencies,
but it also risks stranding orders. One investor enters a limit
order to buy a stock at $20, and another may be trying to sell it
for the same amount. But if the orders are sent to different market
makers, neither could end up being executed.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious way to deal with fragmentation would be to create a
central limit-order book, or a ``clob,'' in Wall Street jargon. But
that would effectively make all markets into one, and the SEC has
backed away from that proposal under heavy pressure from both
markets and some members of congress.
</P>
<P>
   A similar restraint by the SEC was shown Tuesday when it dealt
with the options markets, where intermarket competition has grown
sharply since last fall. Those markets have no way to send orders
from one market to another that might have better prices, and the
SEC has been asking them to develop linkages.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC approved a proposal from three of the five options
exchanges _ the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the American Stock
Exchange and the International Securities Exchange _ for a linkage
that will allow unlimited transfer of customer orders but only
limited ability by a market maker at one exchange to trade on
another exchange. It stopped short of requiring other exchanges to
join that linkage or creating a central limit order book.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the other exchanges _ the Philadelphia Stock Exchange
and the Pacific Stock Exchange _ will be free to come up with their
own linkage plan if they want, or to join the other one. If they do
neither, however, they will have to disclose to customers when an
order was executed at a price that was not as good as was available
in another market. Fear of having to make such disclosures is
expected to propel all markets into some sort of linkage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
