<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEAM GUY' EVERETT WORKS OUT AS SUSPENSION CLOCK TICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Most of his Red Sox teammates had already dressed and
left the clubhouse to take batting practice Tuesday when Carl
Everett set about his pregame routine and began changing out of his
street clothes. On any other game day, Everett would have little
time to entertain questions from reporters, but this game day was
not like most others.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second of Everett's 10-game suspension. So he had
plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was replaced in center field by Darren Lewis
Tuesday night against the Minnesota Twins, began serving his
sentence Monday when he dropped his appeal of the suspension, which
was levied after his bumping incident with umpire Ron Kulpa in a
July 15 game against the New York Mets at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   After his vehement on-field protest, Everett seemed ready to
pursue an appeal off the field to any length. So why the sudden
change of heart?
</P>
<P>
   Everett wasn't offering much in the way of an explanation _
though he did offer an apology to fans, his teammates, and the
front office.
</P>
<P>
   Everett issued a statement that said, ``I apologize most
importantly for not being on the field during this 10-game period.
For playing late through October is the goal that each of us have
set our sights on, and for where I am, and in light of my daily
rule with attaining this goal, I apologize once more. I want to
thank the fans for all the support that they have given me,
especially here in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But as for dropping the appeal, Everett said, ``There's not much
to say. Everybody's already been speculating, so there's no sense
in saying anything. I'll just let them continue to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that Everett dropped the appeal
because his hand is injured _ he punched the bat rack during his
tirade _ and it would need time to heal anyway. Everett said his
hand was fine, even though it apparently kept him out of the lineup
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Everett also said he simply doesn't want to create a distraction
in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for the teammates,'' Everett said. ``Everybody wants to
go to them on how they feel about this and how they feel about
that. It's not fair to them and it's best to get it over with right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Everett will sit and wait, ineligible to play until Aug. 4,
when the Sox are scheduled to face the Kansas City Royals. He will
be allowed to travel and work out with the team, but he must leave
the premises once the game starts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was disappointed that he wasn't going to have a
chance to give his side of the story in an appeal hearing, Everett
said, ``No, because that's what I elected to do. It was ignorant on
everyone's part to say what is and what is not without (knowing).
Everybody wanted to expound on their own, so I shall let them
continue to expound and that's the choice that everyone made and
that's what you have to live with.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few good people get ruined by a bunch of bad apples.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Everett was taking the media to task; he has blamed
them for portraying him as ``a monster.'' Tuesday, though, he was
in a jocular mood in the clubhouse and even threw a playful bear
hug on Tomo Ohka, which caught the rookie pitcher by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But it stings to have to sit out 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to sit out, period,'' said Everett. ``But I'm a
team guy, and so I'm going to root for my team and try to stay in
shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
