<SLUG> BC-FILM-THOMAS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAGIC RAILROAD' IS CHARMING BUT STRANGE LITTLE TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C+  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Thomas, you're a really useful tank engine.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the highest compliment you can receive in this odd little
moppet adventure, based on the 1940s series of children's books by
the Rev. Wilber Awdry and the long-running TV series they inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be responsible, reliable and really useful'' is the mantra of
Mr. Conductor, played by a spirited Alec Baldwin. He's at once
playful, bemused and convincingly sincere as the diminutive
gatekeeper between the life-size real world of Shining Time, a
rather funky small-town station where new-age and old-world peoples
mix in accepting harmony, and the Island of Sobor, a toy-size world
of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a train hobbyist's version of Mister Rogers'
Neighborhood of Make-Believe. Friendly steam engines bicker like
playground kids, and a mean diesel engine with a clawed shovel
attachment plays the bully.
</P>
<P>
   When the gold dust that allows the conductors to magically
travel through the lands runs out, Mr. Conductor embarks on a quest
to recover a legendary lost engine that holds the secret to the
magic railway, the tunnel between the two worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett Stone (Peter Fonda), a lonely old man haunted by a
failure in his past, holds the key in a hidden cave in Shining
Time. Fonda's performance is so low-key it's almost mummified: His
stone face never cracks a smile and his droning delivery is simply
flat.
</P>
<P>
   The movie preserves the cute low-tech effects of the TV show:
Toy trains chug along lovingly sculpted landscapes that would do a
hobbyist proud. A dash of digital gold dust and little flourishes
of fairy fireworks add a little modern sheen to the toy-box
make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   The lone 3-year-old at the screening I attended offered his
expert opinion: ``Good.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is inoffensive, and Baldwin is fun and engaging, but
the subplot about hard work and being ``useful'' just becomes more
insistent. Even when things are at their darkest, the engines keep
working because ``that's what Mr. Conductor would have wanted,''
and Mr. Conductor's happy-go-lucky nephew learns his lesson by
adventure's end: He's ready to stop playing and go to work.
</P>
<P>
   It's the strangest collision of lessons I've ever seen in a
kid's film: Believe in magic but respect the work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   THOMAS AND THE MAGIC RAILROAD
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Britt Allcroft
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Alec Baldwin, Peter Fonda, Mara Wilson, Didi Conn, Russell
Means
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 89 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: G
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
