<HEADER>
A2872 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-HEYNS-NYT &LR;      07-25 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-HEYNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEYNS SEEKING TO RECAPTURE THE RECORDS AND THE GLORY OF OLYMPICS
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Day after day, for more than two months in early 1998, the South
African Olympic champion swimmer Penny Heyns arrived at the pool to
begin her training. Yet, day after day, the only thing that kept
rising to the surface was her discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire any more,'' recalled Heyns, 25, who trained at
the University of Nebraska, where she was pursuing undergraduate
studies. ``I was miserable. I had no peace. I would sit there and
just leave. Now and then, I'd get in the water, but it would be for
maybe 2,000 meters,'' only a third of her previous training
standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't lifting weights,'' she said. ``People were telling me
to quit, that I had already accomplished enough.''
</P>
<P>
   They had a strong case. During the 1996 Summer Games in Atlanta,
Heyns had won the first two gold medals for South Africa, which had
been banned from Olympic competition from 1964 until 1992 because
of the country's racial policies of apartheid, since 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the last day of the 1996 Games, Josia Thugwane, a black
South African, won the men's marathon. Although Thugwane's triumph,
dedicated to ``my country and to President Mandela,'' put an
emotional exclamation point on South Africa's Olympics in Atlanta,
Heyns' two victories were more impressive. She established Olympic
records _ in the 100-meter (1:07:73) and 200-meter (2:25:41)
breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing left for Heyns to accomplish. Nonetheless, the
notion of retiring from the sport that she had long adored made her
feel as unsettled as the prospect of all-out preparation. So, she
left Nebraska in April 1998 and moved to Calgary, reuniting with
her longtime coach, Jan Bidrman, who had moved on to the University
of Calgary. In the process, Heyns somehow found a way to summon the
energy and motivation to take on the challenge one more time. She
has no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to enjoy it again,'' said Heyns, who will compete in
the same two events in Sydney, as well as the 4 x 100 medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   Part of what inspires Heyns to try to duplicate what she
achieved in Atlanta is the belief that, if she is fortunate enough
to stand on the podium again, she will appreciate it more than she
did the last time. After her victory in the 100 in Atlanta, instead
of excitement, she felt empathy for her fellow competitor, Samantha
Riley of Australia, who took the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had been a bit of a hero,'' Heyns said. ``I knew how
disappointed she must have been. The swim was way below her
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after Heyns followed two days later with a triumph in the
200, becoming the first woman to capture both events in the same
Olympics, she was not able to fully absorb the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen people crying and waving and being overjoyed,''
said Heyns of some other athletes' response to winning medals,
``but I felt if I were to do that, it would be acting. I didn't
know what to do. Being South African, I didn't grow up with the
Olympic dream like most people. Only when I went back to South
Africa did I realize what a big deal it was.''
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly a bigger deal this time, especially since Heyns
gives every indication that her days of competition will likely end
in Australia. Spirited and spiritual _ she credits God frequently
for guiding her to make the proper decisions _ Heyns does not seem
to be an athlete who will linger on the stage too long, tarnishing
images of her past glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very grateful and humbled by my achievements,'' said
Heyns, who also competed in the 1992 Olympics at Barcelona, Spain.
``I think it's a gift. But, at the same time, there are more
important things in life. There are more than external things.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next two months, however, her focus will remain on
Sydney. Even so, it will not be easy to repeat. After a remarkable
1999 _ in a two-month stretch, she set 10 world records in the
breaststroke _ Heyns has staggered a bit this season. At last
week's Janet Evans Invitational in Los Angeles, a meet she
dominated in 1999, Heyns finished second in the 200-meter finals
with an unimpressive 2:29:89, more than six seconds slower than the
world mark she established last year. She and Bidrman chose to
emphasize the positive, that Heyns had actually improved a few
seconds from an even poorer performance a week earlier in
Vancouver. Nonetheless, still feeling the effects of some rigorous
training and a recent excursion to South Africa, Heyns is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any answers right now,'' said Heyns, who skipped
the 100-meter final in Los Angeles to do more training. ``I have
tired legs. It takes more out of me than it did in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The year held so much more promise in the winter when Heyns
posted her best training times. New world records in spring
competitions seemed attainable. That changed in March, however,
when a member of the University of Calgary's swim team was
seriously injured in a car accident. While the rest of the team was
at a meet, Heyns stayed behind to help comfort the swimmer's
family. She was at the hospital every day, and was in the room when
her friend died.
</P>
<P>
   Heyns refuses to use the tragedy as an excuse, and said, ``I had
never dealt with death before.'' Mike Blondal, the team's head
coach, added, ``It took a lot of emotional and physical energy for
her to be around the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it would be premature to dismiss Heyns' prospects in
Sydney. She still holds the world records in the 100 and 200, and
according to Bidrman ``always performs when it matters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she'll swim fast,'' Bidrman said. ``Whether it will be
fast enough to win, I don't know. Maybe it is the best thing,'' he
said, referring to Heyns' current fatigue. ``Nobody will expect
anything from her.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Blondal: ``She has an incredible faith in herself. She'll
be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, except for a meet in Winnipeg, Manitoba, next month,
she will spend most of her time training. She will not have any
trouble finding the motivation to do laps and lift weights. Sydney,
after all, is less than two months away, and any signs of
discontent are long gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
