<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERTICALNET-AMAZON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF AMAZON QUITS TO JOIN VERTICALNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Galli, it seems, isn't one to mull major career moves for
a long time. Just over a year ago, Galli a 19-year veteran of Black
&AMP; Decker, accepted the job as chief executive of Pepsico's
Frito-Lay division, then hours later changed his mind to become the
president and chief operating officer of Amazon.com instead.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Galli said he would quit Amazon to become president
and chief executive of VerticalNet, an Internet company that runs
56 Web sites devoted to specific industries, such as Pollution
Online. He took the job only a week after meeting Mark Walsh,
VerticalNet's current chief executive, over dinner at an industry
conference. Walsh will become chairman of VerticalNet, which is
based in Horsham, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Galli said he had been considering leaving Amazon, which is
based in Seattle, for some time because his children live with his
former wife in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back most weekends,'' Galli said, ``and I made a
decision this wasn't right.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that the decision of Galli was a gain for
VerticalNet and a loss for Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazon handpicked Joe from a large pool and there has to be a
sting with him leaving,'' said Derek Brown, an analyst with WR
Hambrecht &AMP; Co. Amazon's shares fell $1.125, to $37.625 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which lost $720 million last year, has been under a
great deal of scrutiny by investors in recent months as some
analysts questioned whether it could afford to pay for its rapid
expansion from simply selling books to offering everything from
paring knives to lawn chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Galli said his departure had nothing to do with any
disillusionment with Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Amazon.com, and I think that the company has enormous
potential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, the chairman and chief executive of Amazon, said
Galli's departure was amicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was his reference yesterday with VerticalNet,'' Bezos said.
``I would have loved to keep Joe around, he has helped us
tremendously, but this is the right thing for him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At Amazon, his most visible accomplishment was spearheading the
company's entry into the tool and home improvement business, a
business line that has yet to prove successful. Bezos credited
Galli with recruiting talented mid-level managers.
</P>
<P>
   Internet executives who know both Bezos and Galli wondered,
however, how well the two driven and forceful men worked together.
Galli was hired to bring order to Amazon's sprawling operations,
yet Bezos himself has a history of being a hands-on manager.
</P>
<P>
   Galli said he worked well with Bezos.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said that it was not looking for a replacement for Galli,
and that Bezos would assume the additional title of president, and
the eight executives who had reported to Galli would report to him.
</P>
<P>
   Galli may well find the job at VerticalNet to be more
financially rewarding, given the drop in Amazon.com's stock. When
he joined, Galli was granted options to purchase nearly four
million Amazon shares over 20 years, at a price of $57.95, some 80
percent above where the shares trade today.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Internet executives, Galli received substantial cash
compensation in addition to his stock options.
</P>
<P>
   He received an initial signing bonus of $100,000, a $200,000 a
year salary, and an additional bonus of $3 million for the first
year, $3 million for the second year, and $2 million the third
year, all payable at the beginning of the year. Galli just received
the second $3 million installment on June 24. According to Amazon
documents, Galli's contract says that if he leaves Amazon before
the end of the year, he must return the share of that year's bonus
that reflects the number of days he did not work.
</P>
<P>
   Galli and Walsh declined to specify Galli's compensation at
VerticalNet. Walsh did say, however, that it resembles most
Internet companies in that it is mainly composed of stock rather
than cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If VerticalNet hits on all cylinders, then Joe Galli will be
one happy cat,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Galli was drawn to VerticalNet through a series of contacts.
Several months ago he met Kenneth Fox, the managing director of the
Internet Capital Group, one of VerticalNet's main backers, through
a dinner arranged by Fox's father, a construction executive who had
done business with Galli at Black &AMP; Decker.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was interested in recruiting Galli and arranged the dinner
with Walsh last week. There the two executives discovered that
Walsh's father was an advertising executive who worked on the Black
&AMP; Decker account.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh added that he and Galli hit it off right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a down to earth guy who wanted to come back to the East
Coast,'' Walsh said. ``We weren't looking for a CEO. But I said
let's make room on the bench.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
