<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS REVIVE INQUIRY INTO WHETHER RUSSIAN BANK LAUNDERED IMF MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Swiss officials are investigating whether $4.8 billion
paid to Russia by the International Monetary Fund in 1998 was
laundered through Swiss banks in transactions involving the Bank of
New York, according to investigative documents that revive
questions thought to have been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Kaspar-Ansermet, a Geneva investigating magistrate,
asked banks in the southern canton of Ticino earlier this month for
help in locating accounts through which the money might have
passed.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-page letter to the banks, Kaspar-Ansermet wrote of
``certain elements of information'' indicating that the $4.8
billion was deposited in a Ticino bank account opened in the name
of the Ost-West Handelsbank AG, a German affiliate of the Russian
central bank, and an Austrian bank, Creditanstalt AG, before it was
funneled to banks in other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is remarkable since the IMF commissioned an
audit by PriceWaterhouseCoopers last year that cleared the Russian
central bank of wrongdoing in handling the money.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Ost-West Handelsbank were not available for
comment. A Creditanstalt spokesman in Vienna, Peter Thier, denied
that the bank, now part of Bank Austria, had accounts in Ticino or
any contact with Ost-West Handelsbank.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, a copy of which was obtained by The New
York Times, Kaspar-Ansermet began an investigation last October of
money laundering charges against Peter Berlin and Lucy Edwards,
former employees of Bank of New York, who pleaded guilty to similar
offenses in a trial in New York earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Kaspar-Ansermet said by phone that he was prevented by judicial
secrecy from commenting. But he indicated that the letter was only
one element in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, the $4.8 billion of IMF money was
supposedly deposited in the Ticino account on Aug. 14, 1998. On
that day, or shortly thereafter, transfers totaling almost $7
billion were made from the account to banks in Britain, Australia,
Switzerland, and the United States, including a payment of $1.4
billion to the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dawson, the IMF's director of external relations, said the
IMF was aware of the Swiss inquiry but that ``we have received no
information that contradicts what is in the PriceWaterhouseCoopers
report.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF ordered the Russian Central Bank's handling of the $4.8
billion examined last year after allegations arose that it was
improperly funneled into private bank accounts outside Russia. But
auditors found the money was distributed to roughly 18 Russian
commercial banks in order to support the value of the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The report strongly criticized the central bank's use of a
finance company on the British Channel Islands, Fimaco, in the
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the transactions outlined in Kaspar-Ansermet's
letter appear to be virtually identical to those provided last year
in Moscow by Viktor Ilyukhin, a communist member of the Russian
parliament, that were examined by IMF auditors and found to be
inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, for instance, Kaspar-Ansermet says the $4.8
billion was transferred from the New York Federal Reserve in one
sum on Aug. 14, 1998, when in fact it was doled out piecemeal over
several days. Moreover, he cites a transfer of $2.35 billion from
the Ticino account to the Bank of Sydney, Australia, though the IMF
found no such bank exists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISABILITIES-NYT &LR;      07-25 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING LAWS FOR DISABILITIES OF THE ATTITUDE
</HEADLINE>
  By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago Wednesday, when the Americans With Disabilities
Act became law, the unemployment rate among disabled people was 70
percent. It still is, almost everyone agrees. And the stories of
Sarah Triano and Richard Clark help explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, 36, was a five-year veteran of the Chicago police force
when a car crash left him almost completely paralyzed. The police
department put him on leave, and he has lived on Social Security
since. Clark, who uses a wheelchair and can walk with a cane,
argued, however, that he could do desk work, and he sought help
from Equip for Equality, an advocacy group in Chicago, which sued
for Clark's reinstatement in 1997. The United States District Court
dismissed his claim once, but it is now scheduled for trial in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many throughout the department,'' Clark said of the
number of desk jobs. ``I've done a few of them before when I was in
uniform, administrative stuff, like keeping logs and records.
There's no question in my mind that there is a place for me where I
can continue to make a valuable contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Chicago police force said Clark was
offered a desk job but ``he wanted to remain a sworn police
officer,'' a title reserved to people who can respond to
emergencies and fire their guns from a standing position. ``This is
mostly where the dispute comes from,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Triano, she says she always wanted to be a lawyer, and
after graduating Phi Beta Kappa from the University of California
at Santa Barbara in 1996, she set out to take the law school
admittance exam. But a hereditary immune-system disorder makes her
highly susceptible to colds and infections and prone to diarrhea
and vomiting when under stress. Because of that, she had always
been given access to a bathroom while taking tests in high school
and college.
</P>
<P>
   The Law School Admission Council, which administers the Law
School Admission Test, refused to grant her special privileges, she
says, even after she submitted medical records from her
immunologists and letters from Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   In frustration, Triano, 25, started an Internet support group
for people who had had similar problems in taking the law exams,
and 50 people joined, she says. She also complained to the Justice
Department, saying that her rights for reasonable accommodation of
her condition had been violated. As a result of similar complaints,
she says, the department sued the Law School Admission Council last
year in the Eastern District Court of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia
to try to force it to change its policy on accommodating students
with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the council is ``in extreme disagreement on
whether or not we've violated'' the disabilities act, said Joan E.
Van Tol, its corporate counsel. ``We've complied with all the
requirements'' in accommodating the complainants and ``in
responding to the thousands of other test takers who have requested
accommodations.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, though, the experience so upset Triano that she
abandoned law and enrolled in the Ph.D. program in disability
studies at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people with disabilities try and get into traditional
employment fields like law and are getting turned down,'' Triano
said. ``So they're going into a field where they can get the
accommodation they need, which is in the disabled community. I've
seen this happen time and again.''
</P>
<P>
   The frustrations that Clark and Triano have encountered mirror a
larger and troubling reality: despite federal law to protect them
against discrimination in hiring and promotion, and despite efforts
by companies to recruit and train them and make job sites more
accessible to them, the disabled continue to face a huge struggle
for full workplace equality.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason seems to be that although the law has changed,
attitudes have not. ``Clearly, many employers don't know how to
level the playing field and engage people with disabilities in
jobs,'' said Dr. Susanne Bruyere, director of the program on
employment and disability at Cornell. ``We need to infuse all
participants _ from upper management to supervisors to workers _
with new attitudes toward the one in six Americans with
disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   William G. Stothers, deputy director of the Center for an
Accessible Society, a resource group in San Diego, says many
employers are simply nervous about hiring disabled people. They
wonder, he says, how much training and special attention such
workers will need, whether they will be productive and how their
presence will affect their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a stretch for some employers to expect a person with
disability to be a valuable employee,'' Stothers said. ``That's the
risk that needs taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Odzer, the chief executive of Global Supply Net, a
company in New York for the janitorial industry, says his managers
sometimes question him for hiring so many mentally disabled
workers. They say, ``Let's get a regular person,'' he said. ``I
say, `That is a regular person, it's just a person with a
disability.' People are people, but not everyone sees that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor is the difficulty in enforcing the disabilities
act. Indeed, just determining what constitutes a disability can be
a problem. Obviously, paralysis and blindness qualify, but other
conditions, like attention deficit disorders and alcoholism, are
debated. As a result, the figures for the number of disabled
Americans vary widely, though a generally accepted estimate is 54
million.
</P>
<P>
   Activists say adverse rulings and contradictory federal policies
add to the confusion. Almost 90 percent of complaints to the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission are rejected, and 98 percent of
disability discrimination lawsuits are decided for the defendants,
which are usually businesses, the American Bar Association says.
</P>
<P>
   For all the obstacles they see, though, activists mostly hail
the act as a landmark in the struggle for full acceptance. Marca
Bristo, 46, chairwoman of the National Council on Disability, is
paralyzed from the neck down as a result of a diving accident but
can use her hands. She says that discrimination against the
disabled is rampant in the workplace and that she experiences it
daily. Yet, she says, the disabilities act has had a transforming
effect on her and millions of others because it gives them hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived in three Americas,'' Bristo said. ``The first was
as a nondisabled person in a world where I didn't know there was
discrimination against disabled people. The second was for the 13
years after I broke my neck but before there was an A.D.A. The
third has been the America I've lived in since the A.D.A. The
experiences have been like three different countries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
