<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-UGA-ADMISSIONS0726-CO     07-25 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-ADMISSIONS0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Federal judge had warned University of Georgia about race policy
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    and Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - U.S. District Judge B. Avant Edenfield had warned the
University of Georgia about ``the road ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   In prior rulings, the Savannah jurist told UGA that if it
continued using racial preferences to ensure a diverse student
body, the policy would not withstand scrutiny. On Monday, Edenfield
followed through on that admonition and said UGA's use of race
violates the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield, who was appointed by President Carter, minced few
words on how he felt about the policy. And his ruling becomes the
second in the nation to question the significance of a landmark
1978 U.S. Supreme Court decision on the use of racial preferences
in university admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield's ruling resolved only one of several lawsuits pending
before him attacking UGA's admissions program. Plaintiffs' lawyers
predict they will prevail in the other cases as well, while
advocates of the progam say they hope Edenfield's ruling will be
overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem, of course, is that in UGA's world some are `more
equal' than others,'' Edenfield wrote. ``UGA's claim that it can
simultaneously ensure equality of both opportunity and result,
particularly by means of an admissions process that awards bonus
points to some races but not others, simply defies logic.''
</P>
<P>
   UGA officials say they are not sure how the ruling will
influence the admissions criteria for those students applying for
slots in the class of 2001. So far, race remains part of the Total
Student Index, a set of factors used in evaluating about 1,200
applicants each year.
</P>
<P>
   Gender was removed from the index last year. Remaining criteria
include economic and academic disadvantage, Georgia residency,
academic factors, leadership and whether parents attended college.
The UGA admissions policy, and its inclusion of race as one of many
factors, was devised after the 1978 Supreme Court ruling in Regents
of the University of California vs. Bakke.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield ruled in favor of three white women _ Jennifer
Johnson, Aimee Bogrow and Molly Ann Beckenhauer _ who filed suit
after being denied admission to UGA in 1999. Edenfield ordered UGA
to pay damages to the women and offer them admission. Fall semester
begins Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson filed suit, UGA granted her admission. But the
Jonesboro High School graduate had already committed to attend
Mercer University. Saying Johnson is entitled to recover expenses
she paid Mercer in excess of what she would have paid UGA for the
1999 Fall semester, Edenfield ordered UGA to pay her $2,060.
</P>
<P>
   Beckenhauer, who graduated from Lakeside High School in Martinez
and attends Clemson University, is entitled to $7,184 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Bogrow, who graduated from North Springs High School in North
Fulton, attends the less-costly Georgia Perimeter College.
Edenfield awarded her a nominal amount of $1.
</P>
<P>
   Bogrow's father, Bernie, said Tuesday that his daughter was on
vacation and unavailable for comment. As to whether she will now
attend UGA, he said, ``I am not sure. That's her call, her
decision. I do know this is a late date ... If (the ruling) came a
month ago, it would be a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials say they are considering whether to appeal
Edenfield's decision to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case that Judge Edenfield was ruling on didn't exclusively
focus on gender, it focused on race and gender, but we'd already
dropped gender as a consideration for the class of 2000,'' UGA
spokesman Tom Jackson said. ``The law has been very murky in this,
and an appeal might move us closer to the definitive ruling we all
seek. An appeal is being considered as a way of trying to get
clarity on this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kronley, senior consultant to the Atlanta-based Southern
Education Foundation, urged UGA to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   He also gave Edenfield credit for addressing the issue head-on.
``It's what a conscientious federal judge does,'' Kronley said.
``He ruled with the understanding that the issues raised here are
of profound importance and that higher courts ought to review it
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the federal appeals court in New Orleans ordered the
University of Texas Law School to stop discriminating against white
applicants, saying the factor of race may no longer be used to
achieve a diverse student body. The court also said the Bakke
ruling was no longer good law.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bakke case, the high court invalidated the University of
California at Davis's medical school admissions policy, which
included racial quotas. But the late Justice Lewis Powell also
wrote that diversity in higher education was a compelling state
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield acknowledged that lower courts have since issued
rulings assuming that Powell's writing on diversity was the law of
the land. But Edenfield said he would not engage in that type of
```assumption` dodge'' because he does not believe Powell was
writing for the court's majority.
</P>
<P>
   The high court handed down six separate opinions in its Bakke
decision and, Edenfield noted, Powell's opinion was not joined by
any other justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Shaw of the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund said
Edenfield's reasoning ``is flat-out different to our interpretation
of Bakke. ... Bakke is still the law of the land, despite what this
federal judge says.''
</P>
<P>
   Edenfield also disparaged pre-trial testimony given by former
UGA President Charles Knapp, who said that diverse student bodies
help students learn how to work cooperatively inside and outside
the classroom. ``This sort of circular, `It is so because I say so'
logic is precisely what the Supreme Court resoundingly rejected''
in other affirmative actions cases, Edenfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Lee Parks, who represents the three women
plaintiffs, has filed other lawsuits against UGA; one attacks the
2000 admissions program and another attacks UGA's School of Law
admissions program.
</P>
<P>
   UGA will not prevail on these lawsuits either, Harlan Miller, a
partner of Parks', said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the people at the University of Georgia are
well-intentioned in what they are trying to do, but it's not
consistent with the Constitution,'' Miller said. ``That's just the
way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
