<SLUG> BC-BOEING-FARNBOROUGH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRBUS GETS MORE ORDERS AT AIR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Airbus Industrie won more than $7 billion in new
airplane orders Tuesday at the Farnborough air show and picked up a
key endorsement for its A3XX super jumbo from the world's second
largest leasing company.
</P>
<P>
   International Lease Finance Corp. said it will buy five of the
555-passenger A3XX jets as part of an order for 87 Airbus planes.
The announcement nudged Airbus ahead of Boeing in the race for
orders at this year's show. But Boeing is expected to fatten its
totals Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The latest orders for the A3XX also put Airbus nearly halfway to
having the 50 or so it needs to formally launch the program by
year's end.
</P>
<P>
   With so much debate surrounding the A3XX and the size of the
market for such a huge plane, Airbus executives were all smiles as
they listened to an assessment of the market from Steve Hazy, chief
executive of International Lease.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters at a packed news conference that that his
leasing company had studied high density markets served today by
Boeing's 747-400 and concluded that a bigger plane is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have carefully analyzed the markets served currently by the
Boeing 747 and we believe that by 2005 between 30 and 40 city pairs
will reach a saturation point,'' Hazy said. ``The only way to
progress will be through larger aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before the Airbus news conference, Hazy had been with
Boeing executives as they toasted the five major launch customers
for the new long-range 777X jets.
</P>
<P>
   Those customers _ EVA Airways, All Nippon Airways, Japan
Airlines, International Lease and GE Capital Aviation Services _
have ordered 39 of the new planes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those planes were part of $12 billion in orders
announced Monday by Boeing on the opening day of show.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing did not announce any new orders Tuesday, though Dubai's
Emirates airline has reportedly signed a letter of intent to buy
six of Boeing's 737-300 jets. At list prices, the order would be
worth about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus order from International Lease was for 62 of the
single-aisle A320 family of jets, and 20 of the widebody A330 jets.
</P>
<P>
   It was a follow on order to one announced earlier this year by
the leasing giant for 50 Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, the Airbus brand is accepted in the skies of
the world,'' Hazy said.
</P>
<P>
   The order includes five A3XX superjumbos, set to enter service
in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has now announced 22 orders for its A3XX at the air show,
though none will become firm until after the plane is officially
launched.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Airbus disagree about the size of the market for the
A3XX. Boeing agrees some airlines will buy the new jet, but not in
enough numbers to justify its development costs of about $12
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The A3XX, if launched, would bust Boeing's 30-year monopoly in
the market for planes with more than 400 seats that it has enjoyed
with the 747. Boeing is planning a stretch version of the 747 to
counter the Airbus threat.
</P>
<P>
   Hazy said International Lease will evaluate the 747 stretch.
</P>
<P>
   He said the analysis by International Lease shows that markets
served by the current 747-400 are growing from 5 to 12 percent a
year. Once those markets reach saturation in terms of frequency in
2005, bigger planes will be needed to handle the capacity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the order is important for Airbus, the five planes
represent only a small percentage of the leasing company's
portfolio of planes.
</P>
<P>
   Hazy said International Lease will have 250 widebody planes in
its portfolio by 2005, so the five A3XX jets will represent only
about 2 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
   He called the order a ``modest'' and ``measured'' commitment to
the super jumbo.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it was sweet news for Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company like ILFC selects the A3XX, we feel very
comfortable the plane is what the market wants,'' said John Leahy,
vice president of Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus also announced several small orders yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   British Midland said it will buy two A320s and Finnair said it
has ordered six of the A320 family of jets.
</P>
<P>
   And Kuwait Finance House, an Islamic financial institution and
the parent company of Aviation Lease and Finance Co., an aircraft
lessor based in Kuwait, announced intentions to purchase four
A320s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
