<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CHENEY-PROFILE-2TAKES     07-25 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICK CHENEY: A WASHINGTON INSIDER WITH A KNACK FOR WORKING WITH
RIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
 (With BUSH-CHENEY, BUSH-CHENEY-ASSESS) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The night allied warplanes began bombing Iraq in
1991, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney quietly flipped on CNN in his
third-floor Pentagon office, ordered Chinese take-out and sat back
alone to watch the Persian Gulf war unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was concerned about possible losses, but he was
tremendously calm,'' said one former top Cheney aide who was
briefly in the room. ``I asked him why he wasn't more nervous, and
he basically said that he was confident that everything was done
that needed to be done. Once the airplanes were in the air, we just
had to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing Dick Cheney as his running mate, Gov. George W. Bush
has turned to an unflappable Washington insider whose easygoing
exterior masks a steely confidence, a man who, once he makes a
tough decision, never looks back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sort of chews on issues, and chews on them until he makes
his mind up, then he goes on and he doesn't second-guess himself,''
said former Secretary of State George P. Shultz. ``He has very good
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, 59, who served 10 years in the House of Representatives
and four more as President George Bush's defense secretary, brings
stature, decisiveness and decades of government experience to a
campaign sometimes short on all three.
</P>
<P>
   But the real secret of Cheney's success may be his ability to
wrap his staunchly conservative ideology in a mantle of moderation
and civility to get people to trust him and get things done.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has a knack for working with political rivals, colleagues
say, which is why Democrats feel at ease with him, even though,
while in the House, he opposed abortion and gun control and
supported aid to Nicaraguan contras and President Ronald Reagan's
``Star Wars'' anti-missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, a former Democratic congressman and White House
chief of staff, recalled that Cheney was one Republican whom he
could confide in during sensitive budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any question he had conservative views, but he
was always someone you could deal with and talk to, and never one
to demagogue the issues,'' Panetta said. ``I trusted that what I
said would not be used against me in negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wyoming Republican has been a rising star in party circles
since he was President Gerald Ford's chief of staff, at the age of
34. But that political fire appeared to die out in 1995, when
Cheney ended a brief flirtation with his own presidential campaign
and became chief executive of Halliburton, an oil services and
construction company based in Dallas whose revenues have doubled,
to $14.7 billion, under his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   What remains in question is Cheney's ability to wage a punishing
presidential campaign. He is not an electrifying speaker. He is a
balding, overweight, middle-aged man who is not especially
telegenic, though he comes across solidly on television. Cheney
never faced a tough race in conservative Wyoming. And he abhors the
scorched-earth politics that came to characterize House Republicans
under Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick does not bring political sex appeal to the ticket,'' said
Bill Frenzel, a long-time friend and a former Republican
congressman from Minnesota. ``What he brings is the competence and
confidence that if anything happens to the president, the country
will have a competent vice president to step in.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's selection is the latest in a series of unexpected turns
that have shaped his personal life and political career.
</P>
<P>
   He is an Ivy League drop-out who later became a doctoral student
in political science. He was the No. 2 House Republican on the path
to possibly becoming speaker when President Bush plucked him from
Congress to run the Pentagon after the Senate rejected his first
choice, Sen. John Tower, R-Texas. He was a military neophyte,
avoiding the Vietnam War with student and parent deferments, who
steeped himself in military tactics and doctrine and became the
most pivotal defense secretary since Robert McNamara.
</P>
<P>
   As defense secretary, Cheney joined a national security team
that included Secretary of State James Baker, national security
adviser Brent Scowcroft and Gen. Colin L. Powell, chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Under Cheney, 24,000 American troops invaded Panama in 1989 to
overthrown Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</P>
<P>
   When Iraq invaded Kuwait in August 1990, it was Cheney who flew
to Saudi Arabia to present King Fahd with President Bush's offer to
send up to 200,000 American troops to the kingdom. He clashed with
Powell, who recommended keeping economic sanctions in place longer,
and prodded the military to draft a larger, more ambitious
counterattack against Iraqi forces.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, his stint as secretary was auspicious. A week
after taking over at the Pentagon in 1989, Cheney publicly
reprimanded the Air Force chief of staff, Larry D. Welch, for
privately discussing options for updating land-based nuclear
missiles with influential members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Cheney abruptly dismissed Welch's successor, Gen.
Michael J. Dugan, for publicly discussing contingency plans for
waging war against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Even Powell, a close ally of Cheney's, was not above reproach.
Powell recalled in his memoirs that after one meeting with
President Bush during the gulf crisis, Cheney pulled him aside.
```Colin,' he said, `You're chairman of the Joint Chiefs. You're
not secretary of state. You're not the national security adviser
anymore. And you're not secretary of defense. So stick to military
matters.' He made it clear that I had taken liberty for license.''
</P>
<P>
   While Representative Cheney supported most of President Reagan's
military buildup, Secretary Cheney presided over a 25 percent cut
in the armed services and oversaw a bipartisan process to close
hundreds of military bases. He stunned military analysts by
canceling plans to build a $57 billion Navy attack plane, the A-12.
</P>
<P>
   He vigorously opposed allowing gay men and lesbians to serve
openly in the armed forces. But when a magazine revealed that his
longtime spokesman, Pete Williams, was gay, Cheney defended him:
``As long as they perform their professional responsibilities in a
responsible manner, their private lives are their business.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, discretion is a Cheney byword. When President Bush met
with his top foreign policy advisers during the gulf crisis, Baker
and Powell typically briefed their senior aides afterward. Not
Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney was absolutely mum,'' said Paul D. Wolfowitz, the
third-ranking official at the Pentagon, who was forced to beg
colleagues from the State Department and Joint Chiefs of Staff for
a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues say the perception of Cheney as boring
belies his wry sense of humor. After Jimmy Carter was elected
president and considered replacing the chief of staff's job with a
decentralized ``spoke-in-wheel'' system, Cheney left a broken
bicycle wheel in his office as a warning to the Carter team.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had three mild heart attacks before age 48 and underwent
a quadruple coronary bypass operation more than a decade ago. Since
leaving the Pentagon, he has battled a weight problem, gaining as
much as 50 pounds. He is still an avid hunter, fisherman and hiker
in the Grand Tetons near his home in Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Bruce Cheney was born in Lincoln, Neb., on Jan. 30,
1941. But his father, an Agriculture Department soil conservation
agent, moved the family to Casper, Wyo., where young Dick became a
captain of his high school football team and president of his
senior class.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney received a scholarship to Yale University but dropped out
in his second year because of poor grades. He traveled around the
West, at one point laying power lines for an electric company,
before settling down at the University of Wyoming, earning
bachelor's and master's degrees in political science.
</P>
<P>
   He married his high school sweetheart, Lynne, a political
scholar and former head of the National Endowment for the
Humanities. The couple has two grown daughters, Mary and Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney entered graduate school at the University of Wisconsin
and, at 27, was selected for a one-year fellowship in the office of
the late Rep. William Steiger, Wis.-R.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney thrived in the political cauldron of Capitol Hill. When
President Nixon picked Rep. Donald Rumsfeld of Illinois to head the
Office of Economic Opportunity, Cheney sent him a 12-page
memorandum on how to run the agency. Impressed by Cheney's ideas
and audacity, Rumsfeld hired him to run the agency's congressional
affairs office.
</P>
<P>
   As happens so often with aspiring aides in Washington, Cheney
hitched himself to his powerful mentor's rising star for much of
the next decade. When Ford tapped Rumsfeld to become White House
Chief of Staff, Cheney went along as deputy.
</P>
<P>
   When Rumsfeld was named secretary of defense, Cheney, only 34,
replaced him at the White House, the youngest person ever to be
White House chief of staff. Dispensing with the perks of office,
Cheney commuted daily to Washington in his 10-year-old Volkswagen,
rather than a chauffeured government sedan.
</P>
<P>
   After Carter won the presidency in 1976, Cheney returned to
Wyoming a Washington insider seeking his own political identity. In
1978, he successfully ran for the first of six terms in the House
of Representatives. Cheney quickly rose within the Republican
leadership ranks and often acted as a trusted bridge between Young
Turks like Gingrich and the old Republican guard. Cheney's popular
touch extended beyond Washington's power corridors. William F.
Connelly Jr., a politics professor at Washington and Lee University
who was a congressional fellow in Cheney's office in 1985, recalled
a visit to Wyoming with him.
</P>
<P>
   A group of ranchers had demanded a meeting, angry over the
military's plan to use more grazing land to base MX nuclear
missiles. ``These big burly ranchers in sheepskin coats, including
one guy chewing a nail, were fit to be tied,'' Connelly said. ``But
Cheney just talked them down. He said, `Look, this is too important
to America's defense.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2036EDT &QL; 
