u p BC-MRS-CHENEY-NYT &LR;      07-25 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS-CHENEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYNNE CHENEY, AT HER HUSBAND'S SIDE AND TO HIS RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wyo., N.Y.)  (With BUSH-CHENEY) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Smiling alongside Dick Cheney in Texas on Tuesday
as he became Gov. George W. Bush's running mate was Cheney's high
school sweetheart and wife of 36 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Lynne Cheney, 58, is no ordinary political wife. She is an
unusually high-profile figure with a national reputation as a
passionate opponent of ``political correctness'' and a public
record that is even more conservative than her husband's.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the National Endowment for the Humanities during
the Reagan and Bush administrations and later as a television,
newspaper and magazine commentator, Cheney was a cultural warrior
and darling of the right, accusing what she called cultural
relativists of taking over American art, literature and education.
She has become even more muscularly conservative during the Clinton
years, calling, for instance, for the endowment's elimination.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney is one of her party's most provocative figures, and some
Republicans thought she deserved a cabinet post in a new
administration and even belonged on the list of possible
vice-presidential picks for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is fantastic,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
``In fact, she was my wife's first choice. She has a very strong
conservative philosophy. She's just very attractive as a candidate
in her own right, which she's never been. But she certainly will be
a great helpmate to Dick Cheney.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Bush will be getting two for the price of one,
Lott replied, ``This is more like three for the price of one
because she is double good.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Cheney said she has made no secret of her own
political ambitions. Indeed, in announcing Dick Cheney as his
running mate, Bush singled her out, describing her as ``a leader in
education reform in all America, developing high standards and a
sound curriculum for our public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Cheney holds a doctorate in 19th-century British
literature. (She wrote her dissertation on the effect of Immanuel
Kant's ideas on the poetry of Matthew Arnold). She and her husband
wrote a history of eight speakers of the House and she later wrote
``Telling the Truth,'' a book in which she claimed that truth had
become less important than constructing politically motivated
stories.
</P>
<P>
   She has also written novels, one a historical novel about women
pioneers in the American West, another a political thriller about
Washington whose characters include a vice president who dies of
what she delicately calls ``carnal arrest'' while having sex with a
television newswoman.
</P>
<P>
   With a mother who was a deputy sheriff and a father who was an
engineer, Cheney attributes her sense of moral rectitude to her
upbringing in Casper, Wyo. ``You cannot be a good person in public
and a bad person in private,'' she once told an interviewer. ``They
would know in a small town.''
</P>
<P>
   At Natrona Country High School in Casper, she twirled a baton as
chief of the baton squad and reigned as homecoming queen; Dick
Cheney was the captain of the football team, senior class
president, and had, she once said, a terrific crew cut.
</P>
<P>
   As an English teacher at the University of Wyoming in 1978, she
filled in for her husband when he was running for the state's lone
House seat and suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   While her husband served in the House and then as secretary of
defense, Lynne Cheney used her position as head of the NEH as a
platform for her increasingly conservative ideology.
</P>
<P>
   She was accused by many scholars of politicizing the endowment's
grant-making by favoring traditional over multicultural projects
and loading the endowment's peer review committees with
conservatives. She cut assistance to the financially strapped New
York Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   After the Bush administration, Cheney used a perch as a senior
fellow at the American Enterprise Institute, a conservative
Washington think tank, to promote her vision for a more wholesome,
morally correct, educationally rigorous America. She also sometimes
sat in the conservative chair on the CNN television program
``Crossfire,'' where she denounced declining cultural standards,
especially in schools.
</P>
<P>
   She hates concept-based math education and school-to-work
programs, loves standardized achievement tests similar to those
adopted in other industrialized countries and has staked a middle
ground in the debate over English as the official language of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Her tart tongue extends beyond the realm of cultural and
educational issues. At a daylong panel at the AEI on Hillary Rodham
Clinton last spring, she criticized the first lady for maintaining
a false marital facade, citing the Clintons' habit of holding hands
in public. ``It is just so distressing to me,'' Cheney said.
Although she acknowledged that it was no one's business if Hillary
Clinton wanted to stay married to her husband, she added, ``What
drives me crazy is when Hillary acts as the happy wife.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
