<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-FIVES-LADN-(SLANG     07-25 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-FIVES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIVE MIGHT BE MORE SCARY THAN FORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ask just about any course manager or head
professional and they will tell you that most golfers would sooner
give up a prime tee time than play fast and loose with the sport's
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   One significant change, however, seems to have been accepted
with relatively few objections. Many courses are promoting the
concept of fivesomes, in which five players are grouped together on
the course rather than the traditional four.
</P>
<P>
   The change is coming slowly but surely, with the intention of
increasing revenue for the courses by getting an extra greens fee
per every group. And the acceptance is not unanimous, as many
players bemoan the slower play.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, we don't get any real negative feedback,'' said
Adam Hill, assistant general manager at Vista Valencia Golf Course.
``Obviously people want to come out and have a good time, and it
doesn't seem to matter very much how many people are in the group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get some complaints from people who think it slows down the
play, but not too many.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, courses do not force fivesomes on their players,
as they are largely a matter of circumstance. Groups of two and
three players are often paired together, but rarely is a single
player attached to an existing foursome.
</P>
<P>
   A small survey found that 30 percent of the groups sent out by
local golf courses are fivesomes. The number is significantly
higher for public courses, which need revenue more than private
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In public golf, there's pretty much no choice,'' said
Christopher Riddle, assistant general manager at Knollwood Country
Club in Granada Hills, a public course, who estimated that at least
half of his weekend groups end up as fivesomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of golf is going private and the public courses need
to keep up. Fivesomes get more people on the courses and they
increase the revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Fivesomes, which have become popular just in the past five years
or so, are forbidden on many private courses, which tend to be much
more tradition-conscious, even though many golfers are now choosing
to play in groups of five, rather than four.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is that fivesomes slow down the pace of play, a point
which nobody can argue. Five players will take longer to play a
hole than four.
</P>
<P>
   Courses adjust their tee times to allow for more spacing between
groups, which some argue defeats the purpose of fivesomes because
they prevent fewer groups from playing the course.
</P>
<P>
   Still, course administrators feel that fivesomes are the way to
go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Longer rounds are the biggest complaint, but it's not a major
issue,'' Knollwood's Riddle said. ``Even when we send out fivesome
after fivesome after fivesome, it's still pretty evenly spaced out
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most courses have seven minutes between groups, and we have
eight, so I think that helps keep play spaced, but I don't think it
would be a problem anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three pretty long holes on the front nine, so by the
time they get to the fifth hole, there is generally a lot of
spacing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vista Valencia's Hill agrees, adding that players can be
``educated'' _ perhaps subtly encouraged to play a faster round,
and that although individual holes might be slower, the overall
time of a round does not significantly increase with a fivesome.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger challenge is convincing longtime golfers that five is
not a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people object to a fivesome, we will try to accommodate
them,'' Hill said. ``But when you have an 8 a.m. foursome that ends
up being three, and another foursome that ends up being two, it
only makes sense to put them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get people to change, especially in a sport like
golf, which is so entrenched in history. There are always going to
be sticklers who don't like new ideas and who have old-school
thoughts about how the game should be played, but I think you're
seeing a lot more people start to come around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
