u i BC-U.S.-MISSILE-DEFENSE-     07-25 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-MISSILE-DEFENSE-385&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN SAYS U.S. MISSILE PLAN CAN'T SUCCEED WITHOUT NATO SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The proposed national missile defense system cannot
succeed unless the United States persuades its NATO allies to drop
their opposition, Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In order for the anti-missile shield to protect all 50 states,
at a potential cost of $60 billion, it must rely on radar stations
abroad, Cohen said, mostly likely in Britain and in Greenland,
which is territory of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks before he is to make a recommendation to President
Clinton on whether to proceed with the system, Cohen said that a
top priority must be to persuade NATO allies to embrace the
project. But many of them have voiced serious concern that the plan
could upset the nuclear balance or set off a new global arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have a technologically effective system, we need
to have the support of our allies,'' Cohen said. Without X-band
radars overseas, he added, ``you can't see the missiles coming.
Therefore, your interceptors really are not worth very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's remarks to the Senate Armed Services Committee were his
first since the critical failure on July 8 of a high-speed missile
interceptor to properly deploy. Of three tests of the intercept
system carried out so far, this was the second failure for the
complex weapons system that relies on a high-tech web of targeting
radar, homing sensors and communications links.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen hinted that the two test failures might slow down the
entire deployment process. The setbacks ``called into question the
realism'' of having a system in place by the current target date of
2005, but he said the date should remain a goal for a limited
shield of 20 interceptors and the X-band radar.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all the principal U.S. allies in Europe and Asia
oppose the missile defense system. They argue that its efficacy is
unproven and that it could undermine the Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty with Russia, which has been a mainstay of global arms
control since 1972. These allies also worry that the plan could
encourage China and some other nations to beef up their limited
long-range arsenals.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen told senators that administration officials are gradually
breaking through that opposition, though no nation has asked to
join the system, and only Australia has expressed support for it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The allies share the threat the U.S. system is designed to
address, Cohen said: long-range missile attacks from such nations
as North Korea, Iran and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   If NATO allies embrace the project, he predicted, Russia would
feel compelled to drop its opposition to amending the ABM treaty.
``Thus far,'' he said, ``I believe the Russians have devoted
themselves to trying to divide the allies from supporting the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen acknowledged that Clinton has failed to persuade Moscow
that the missile shield would not neutralize Russia's arsenal. The
defense secretary said that President Vladimir Putin's proposal to
work with NATO on a defense that intercepts missiles in the initial
boost phase of flight ``cannot be a substitute'' for the
anti-missile shield and would rely on even less proven technology.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that China would probably increase its
intercontinental missile capability regardless of whether the
United States proceeds on missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to decide this year whether to break ground
on the project. Troubled by Defense Department predictions that
North Korea could develop missiles capable of reaching the United
States by 2005, Congress last year approved a law requiring
deployment of a missile defense system as soon as it was
technologically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia and other nations must understand that the United
States policy now calls for an eventual deployment of a system to
protect ourselves,'' said Sen. John Warner, R-Va., the chairman of
the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than decide on full-scale deployment, Clinton will limit
his decision to whether to begin construction next spring of a
radar station on Shemya island in Alaska, Cohen said. That would
leave it to the next president to determine the scope of the
project, he said. Vice President Al Gore, the probable Democratic
presidential nominee, generally supports the Clinton approach,
while Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican nominee, favors a
more robust system.
</P>
<P>
   By restricting his decision in that way, Clinton might leave to
his successor the contentious issue of withdrawing from the ABM
treaty, a move that requires six months notice from either side.
Administration lawyers argue that the United States will not be in
violation of the treaty until crews lay the rails for the radar
system, which is not expected until March 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., who wants to defer the decision to
permit more study, anticipated that debate. ``A unilateral decision
to withdraw from the ABM Treaty could unleash an offensive arms
race and create major new proliferation problems,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said the administration is determined to deprive hostile
nations of the ability to blackmail the United States with the
threat of a missile attack. He downplayed overtures by the North
Korean government to negotiate terms to end its long-range missile
program and the historic June meeting between the leaders of North
and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Kim Jong Il of North Korea, Cohen observed: ``One
summit doesn't change the tiger into a domestic cat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
