<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2892 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CLINTON-STEEL-NYT &LR;      07-25 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STEEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW U.S. GUARDS PROMISED AGAINST STEEL IMPORT SURGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration plans to take aggressive
new steps to protect domestic steel producers from import surges,
speeding up its use of antidumping measures and providing faster
relief for companies and workers, according to a report the
administration will release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 240-page report seems timed to help Vice President Al Gore
shore up political support from steel workers and unions. Some
union leaders sharply criticized Gore's support for the China trade
bill earlier this year, and many have expressed disappointment that
the Clinton administration has not done more to guard against
sudden increases in low-price steel imports in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The report, prepared by the Commerce Department, said the
administration would start imposing duties on imported steel faster
than it has in the past _ and in some case even before reaching a
final judgment on whether a foreign country is selling steel in
this market below cost _ in order to minimize the damage inflicted
on domestic companies and workers when dumping does occur.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they had also requested funding to
set up an interagency ``rapid response team'' that would distribute
aid to hard-hit communities as soon as it becomes clear that a
sudden rise in import volumes threatens profits and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the United States' leading trading partners, including
Japan, South Korea, Russia and Brazil, have complained bitterly
about American antidumping laws, especially as used to shield the
politically sensitive steel industry. The administration's pledge
to use those laws more proactively seems sure to inflame already
tense trade ties with those nations, and especially with Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, foreign steel producers released their own
study that contended the American restrictions on imported steel
had cost consumers here as much as $150 billion over the last three
decades. Trade barriers and government subsidies effectively raise
the cost of everything with steel components, from aircraft to
kitchen utensils, according to that study, which was prepared by
lawyers for foreign steel makers.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department's study makes essentially the opposite
claim: If anything, it suggests, the United States has erred on the
side of free trade in the past, and needs to speed up and stiffen
its response when the industry faces unfair competition from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The United States imposed antidumping duties on hot rolled steel
from Russia, Japan and Brazil in 1998. The administration decided
at the time that the United States was flooded with below-cost
steel after the Asian financial crisis that began in 1997 led to
devalued currencies and bankrupt companies abroad. Some steel
industry and union officials have complained that it took the
Clinton administration too long to respond to that crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is designed to make sure that what happened to the
industry two years ago doesn't happen again,'' a senior Commerce
official said. ``We want to move as fast and as aggressively as we
can, because we know that it takes time for the remedies to work.''
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the report says, the administration will act
faster to break out and distribute trade data on steel. That will
help people spot evidence of potential import surges. When surges
occur, the administration will act faster to head them off, the
report says.
</P>
<P>
   Among the actions the report recommends: initiating bilateral
negotiations with trading partners as soon as it becomes clear that
an import surge is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that the administration will work to
address long-term ``structural factors'' that cause foreign
countries to sell steel at what the United States has determined is
below the cost of production.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, the report says, has allowed steel exporters to escape
paying bills at home, allowing them to sell goods abroad below
cost. Japan allows steel makers to coordinate with one another and
keep prices artificially high at home to help promote low-priced
exports. South Korea has unsound banking practices that have
effectively subsidized a glut of steel production capacity in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   The administration will use its influence at the World Bank and
other international lending agencies to end loans that expand steel
production capacity, the study says. It will also propose that
international economic bodies study how best to knock down informal
barriers that protect and subsidize steel companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
