<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BUSINESS CLIMATE LUCRATIVE FOR CHENEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BUSH-CHENEY)  
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The business climate of Texas _ entrepreneurial, energy-based
and big _ has been lucrative for both George W. Bush and his
running mate, Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the sale of an ownership stake in the Texas Rangers
baseball team netted a profit of $14.9 million two years ago _ from
an investment of $606,000 nine years before. And with a legendary
Texas financier, Richard E. Rainwater, as his investment adviser,
Bush has had investment income of more than $1 million a year in
the last two years, in addition to his $115,345 salary as Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   For Cheney, the numbers are even bigger. In 1995, when he went
to Texas to become chief executive of the Halliburton Co., a Dallas
oil services company, he received an annual salary and bonus of
$1.3 million to $3 million, along with stock options, Halliburton
shares and other forms of compensation.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Cheney owns 1,089,000 shares of Halliburton, including
shares he owns outright and 860,000 options to purchase Halliburton
shares at a reduced price. With Halliburton trading at about $40 a
share, his stake has a market value of about $40 million, although
he would net somewhat less than that depending on the financial
terms of the options he holds.
</P>
<P>
   Just this year, when Halliburton's stock was trading at a
52-week high, Cheney dipped into his Halliburton holdings and sold
100,000 shares at $50.97 a share. That transaction, on May 31,
netted Cheney $5,097,000. It also took place just before
Halliburton's stock began to fall to its current range.
</P>
</TEXT>
