<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAELIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK HEADS HOME TO AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS; see also MIDEAST-ADVISORY for complete list of
stories.) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak flew home from the breakup
of the Camp David summit on Tuesday to a murky political future,
his patchwork coalition in tatters, his country sharply divided
over the startling new discussion of ceding parts of Jerusalem to
some form of Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   As news spread that the Camp David summit had ended without
agreement, the airwaves were filled with the speculation of
analysts and politicians. Would there be a national unity
government, bringing in Barak's right-wing Likud critics? New
elections? Violence from the Palestinians?
</P>
<P>
   The entire country seemed to tune in to Barak's Washington press
conference. Peppered with questions from Israeli journalists, the
prime minister himself made light of the uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least let me get on the plane and we'll think on the way,''
he joked. ``We will even consult with our journalist friends on the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, more seriously, he added: ``There is no doubt that all of
the options are open. We will have to consider the issues seriously
and assess the situation. We are at the end of a very important
chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither the discussions at the summit nor the public debate in
Israel were marginal issues. We will deliberate on arriving in
Israel what is the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who has been in office only a year, lost his
parliamentary majority in the 120-seat Israeli parliament on the
eve of the Camp David meeting, when two orthodox religious parties
_ Shas, which represents Sephardic Jews, and the National Religious
Party _ along with former Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky's
right-leaning party of recent Russian immigrants, quit the
governing coalition to protest the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The grim picture is further complicated by a vote scheduled for
Aug. 2 _ the last day before the parliament leaves on a three-month
vacation _ on dissolving the legislature and calling new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Barak actually may be returning in a good position,
according to Sever Plotzker, a political commentator for the
newspaper Yediot Ahronoth, which has been doing extensive polling
in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Altogether, he is coming home in a very special situation,''
Plotzker said in a telephone interview. ``He has no government, a
weak coalition. But in my personal opinion he is stronger in the
past few weeks and after Camp David, all our polls show this. He is
coming back stronger. The economy is good and people are seeing
progress toward peace. He is sticking to his agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister's spokesman, Gadi Baltiansky, told Israeli
reporters that ``as soon as he returns, Barak will be busying
himself with the composition of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, Barak's One Israel parliamentary faction began backroom
maneuvering on Tuesday afternoon to kill the bill calling for new
elections, which is sponsored by two members of the right-wing
Likud Party. If the effort to kill the bill succeeds, Barak's
supporters could bain themselves three months while parliament is
on vacation. Barak's problems are largely due to the electoral
changes put in place in 1996, by which Israelis vote separately for
the prime minister and the members of parliament. That has resulted
in a profusion of smaller parties representing special interests,
particularly the Orthodox. While Barak got a strong mandate in the
popular vote, he had to turn to these smaller parties _ sometimes
with contradictory goals _ to form a governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system has created increasing fragmentation which makes
any coalition unwieldy and unmanageable,'' said Joseph Alpher, a
political analyst. ``This has been a constant in Barak's case.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, said Alpher, who has been a special adviser to Barak
during the peace talks, had the prime minister reached an agreement
of major proportions, he would not have been able to get it through
the parliament and would have faced new elections anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Barak now has several options, Alpher said. He could try to
continue to pursue the peace process, possibly with a renewed
summit in late August, to maintain momentum. He could move to a
national unity movement with the Likud party, which would signal at
least a time-out in negotiations. Or he could try to reconstitute
the basic elements of his coalition, probably without the National
Religious Party and Sharansky's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these options are extremely difficult,'' Alpher said.
</P>
<P>
   On the right, Yisrael Harel, a Jewish settler from Ofra and
onetime chairman of the settler's council, took a dim view of
Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I see it, he has a problem with both sides, both the left
and the right,'' Harel said in a telephone interview. ``The left
thinks he should have conceded more including in Jerusalem. For the
right, after he has conceded the Jordan valley, the settlements,
neighborhoods of Jerusalem, it's no longer possible.''
</P>
<P>
   On the left, Prof. Yaron Ezrachi of Hebrew University said
Barak's future was a difficult question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at this moment there is a great, deep sense of
disappointment in his natural constituency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem to me there is no alternative to the peace
efforts even if there is a spurt of violence, so the peace effort
will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharansky, who had been the minister of interior, then set up a
protest tent outside the prime minister's office two weeks ago,
issued a statement calling for a national unity government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under today's conditions, the agreement that would have been
reached at Camp David would have torn Israeli society apart from
the inside and would have been disastrous for Israel's national
interests,'' the statement said in apparent relief at the summit's
failure, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, more than ever, when Israel faces fateful decisions to
its future, Mr. Barak must extend a hand to the heads of the
opposition in Israel to set up a National Unity government. Only a
government representing a broad national consensus, with clearly
defined red lines, can make critical decisions for the future of
the state of Israel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
