<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIGN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-25 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
` AN INVISIBLE SIGN OF MY OWN ':  A DARK MATH OF THE MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a novel that begins with the word ``so.'' So. It is at
once a word, a sentence and a paragraph, followed by a mysterious
parable about a kingdom in which nobody dies, so ... the king
demands that someone from every family volunteer to die.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Aimee Bender establishes from the outset a tone
of casual, offhand intimacy, but the fairy tale-like parable, whose
themes are mortality, self-sacrifice and dismemberment, is not so
simple. And neither is Bender's intriguing ``An Invisible Sign of
my Own,'' which pursues a course through the charmingly deformed
personality of its narrator, evoking as it goes the dark themes of
the parable in the first few pages of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, whose previous book, ``The Girl in the Flammable
Skirt,'' was a collection of slightly screwy young women and their
slightly screwy predicaments, offers us a 20-year-old narrator
named Mona in this, her first full-length novel. Mona is a math
teacher at the grammar school in the small town where she lives,
the previous holder of the job having decamped for Paraguay to
become a revolutionary. She is somewhat beyond screwy. In fact,
Mona is positively psychotic.
</P>
<P>
   Mona is good at a lot of things, but has quit all but one of
them. When she feels sexual or romantic attraction, she eats soap,
which, as can be imagined, successfully distracts her. Once, when
her running coach _ track stardom is one of the things she has quit
_ asks her why she has stopped competing, she answers, ``I quit
because winning is lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bender's purpose is broader than some clinical depiction of
a mental disorder. It is to allow the darkness of the human soul to
seep through the airiness of appearances, to show a small cast of
characters afflicted by terrors unseen to others. In this sense,
``An Invisible Sign of My Own'' is witty and engaging; it is tinged
with a kind of gothic horror and it is certainly stylistically
nimble. And yet it does not entirely succeed in realizing its
purpose, for two reasons: it is too often defeated by the willful
childishness of its characters and, more important, it slides to a
happy, Hollywood, love-conquers-all sort of ending that is
inconsistent with the spiritual darkness of its overall vision.
</P>
<P>
   The story weaves together several strands in Mona's life. She
has been asked by the elementary school's principal to become the
math teacher, even though she is very young and has no experience.
But math, as Mona puts it, was ``the one thing I loved but never
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mix up some numbers and signs,'' she adds, ``and you get an
equation for the way the wind shifts or an axiom for the movement
of water, or the height of someone, or for how skin feels.'' Math,
in other words, has the controllable orderliness that Mona craves,
and being a math teacher would seem to be her perfect job.
</P>
<P>
   But then the 14 members of Mona's second-grade math class enter
the picture; they are an obstreperous and troubled lot, children
whose tormented souls mirror Mona's own. Mona asks each pupil to
take something to class that represents a number _ she herself
takes an ax that she bought at the hardware store on her birthday,
and it becomes the number 7. One boy takes a 1 in the form of the
severed arm of his father, which has been encased in glass. Another
girl makes a zero out of an intravenous feeding tube, since her
mother is in the hospital, dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Just as what Mona calls `Numbers and Materials' &UR;  &LR; illustrates the
deformities in the lives and minds of her pupils, Mona herself is
shown to have problems outside of school. Since she was 10 years
old, her father has been afflicted with an unidentifiable disease,
a condition that both angers and worries her. She notices weird
behavior around her, especially behavior involving numbers, like
that of the school's former math teacher, who now runs a hardware
store and wears a number around his neck to indicate his mood. She
falls in love with the science teacher at school (who asks his
students to act as if they have dread diseases), but when the
moment comes for her to demonstrate her love, her primal fear of
success takes over and she disappears into the bathroom to eat soap
instead.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Bender treats us to many illustrations of her
cleverness with words. ``In the street, two orange cones had tipped
over, vivid and isosceles,'' Mona notes at one point. Later,
sitting in a movie theater with the science teacher: ``My hands
were silent in my lap and I began to cloak the air around myself,
heavying it, thickening it with aggression and glamour, red velvet
breathing, and I made the air seethe off me, onto him, to make him
look over again; I wanted to force him to look over just by the
power of my will.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are also passages of ultra-cuteness that show Bender
losing her grip on her character's own burdened mental world. Mona
tells us of some neighbors who moved to Florida after their newborn
baby died, and that she used to make detours to the cemetery to
visit its grave. ``Hi baby, I said to it, this is your big sister
here. I figured it wouldn't know the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything in Mona's world, all the disparate people and events
that she has been keeping track of in her obsessive way, comes
together in a shocking incident in school, the exact nature of
which it would be unfair to disclose. Let's just say that in it the
children act out Mona's own fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   But strangely, everything just as quickly turns out right, for
no particular reason, though with some maneuvering by a sadder and
wiser Mona. Bender's ending has a kind of tacked-on quality, as if
she herself is not quite sure where the various afflictions of her
characters _ children who don't act like children, and grown-ups
who do _ should take them, or as if she herself is terrified by
their tragic potential.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``An Invisible Sign of My Own'' is an intelligent and
engaging work by a recent arrival on the literary scene, with a
fanciful and original take on the quietly helter-skelter world that
lies within. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ` &LR; AN INVISIBLE SIGN OF MY OWN &UR; ' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Aimee Bender
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 243 pages. Doubleday. $22.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
