<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concorde crash echoes 1962 Paris air disaster
 &HT;    By Andrea Jones
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - The Tuesday crash of an Air France Concorde en route
to New York echoed another Paris air disaster that decimated the
Atlanta arts community nearly 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, 1962, an Air France Boeing 707 crashed and burned
during an aborted takeoff at Orly airfield in Paris. Of the 129
killed, 114 were Georgians, many of whom were prominent Atlantans
concluding a month-long tour of major European art centers.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Mayor Ivan Allen, who flew to Paris the night of
the crash to help identify the dead, said Tuesday that the Concorde
disaster stirred memories from that terrible time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about the crash every time a plane falls from the
sky,'' Allen, 89, said. ``This one seemed particularly similar and
tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 111 Atlantans aboard the 1962 flight were the
cultural and civic leaders of the city. The group was organized by
the women's committee of the Atlanta Art Association in part to
attract new members.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he lost some of his closet friends in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terribly sad time for Atlanta, and really for the
world,'' he said. ``It was a distinguished and influential group of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The crash galvanized city leaders to form the Atlanta Arts
Alliance and build the Atlanta Memorial Arts Center, dedicated in
1968 in memory of crash victims. The center was later renamed for
philanthropist Robert Woodruff in honor of a $4 million donation.
</P>
<P>
   The French government also honored victims with a donation of a
copy of Rodin's statue ``The Shade.'' The sculpture is on display
at the High Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
