<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-PATENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH GIANT FILES SUIT IN BATTLE FOR PATENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mass.)  By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A second biotechnology giant, Genzyme Corp., has filed a patent
infringement suit against Transkaryotic Therapies Inc., the upstart
company locked in a closely watched patent battle with Amgen Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme said Tuesday that it had filed suit in U.S. District
Court in Wilmington, Del., accusing Transkaryotic, which is usually
called TKT, of infringing on a patent covering the production of an
enzyme to treat Fabry disease, a rare inherited disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Transkaryotic and Genzyme, both based in Cambridge, Mass., are
in a race to be first to market with the enzyme, known as
alpha-galactosidase. TKT applied for marketing approval from the
Food and Drug Administration on June 16 and Genzyme followed a week
later. If not blocked by the patent lawsuit, TKT's drug, which it
calls Replagal, is expected to be the company's first product.
</P>
<P>
   TKT has developed a technique for making biotechnology drugs
that it says avoids the patents held by industry giants. Instead of
splicing the human gene for a protein into bacteria or hamster
cells, which is the conventional approach, TKT turns on the
inactive gene in human cells. In a trial already under way in
Boston, Amgen is trying to stop TKT from using this technique to
produce a version of Amgen's huge-selling anemia drug,
erythropoietin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is not clear that TKT is using the controversial
technique to produce its drug for Fabry disease. The company has
never said how it is making Replagal and might be using more
conventional recombinant DNA. But Genzyme said its patent covers
both methods.
</P>
<P>
   TKT said it did not infringe and thought the Genzyme patent was
invalid. ``It is a shame that Genzyme has chosen to compete based
on a frivolous lawsuit rather than on the merits of their
products,'' Dr. Richard F. Selden, TKT's chief executive, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   People with Fabry disease have a deficiency of the
alpha-galactosidase enzyme and therefore cannot break down certain
fats, which then accumulate in the lining of the blood vessels in
the kidney, heart and other organs. The condition can cause pain,
numbness, kidney failure and heart disease. Death typically occurs
about age 40.
</P>
<P>
   Genzyme estimates that only 2,000 to 4,000 people suffer from
the disease worldwide. But even such a small number of patients can
mean high revenue if there is no competition and the drug price is
high. Genzyme's leading product, a drug called Cerezyme, which
treats another rare inherited disorder called Gaucher disease, has
annual sales of about $500 million. Even though only 3,000 patients
are taking the drug, each one is paying about $170,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of the lawsuit was announced after the markets
closed. Shares of TKT fell $1.75, to $30.375. Shares of Genzyme
General, the division of Genzyme that is developing the Fabry drug,
fell 85.9375 cents, to $68.3125. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2899 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GM-AD-COLUMN-1STLD-WR     07-25 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-AD-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GM UNITES MEDIA PLANNING AT NEW SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Revises and expands with additional information and quotes; story
grows by   about 700 words)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest assignment in the history of Madison Avenue was made
Tuesday when General Motors consolidated responsibilities for media
planning _ deciding where to run ads with an annual budget of $2.9
billion _ at a new shop to be formed by a unit of the giant agency
company known as the B Com3 Group.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation of media planning under the unit, the Starcom
MediaVest Group, came after a monthlong review of three contenders
and will affect all GM brands sold in the United States except Saab
and Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you can imagine, this is a huge undertaking for us,''
Michael A. Browner, executive director for media and marketing
operations at General Motors Corp. in Detroit, said in a conference
call to reporters to announce the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Media planning is taking on additional strategic importance as
marketers seek to increase the long odds that a potential customer
_ busy with life and bored by most ads _ will pay attention to a
sales pitch, particularly when many products are aimed at narrow
demographic groups rather than mass audiences.
</P>
<P>
   One way media planning works is to use tools like consumer
research to try tailoring media schedules to the tastes of would-be
buyers so they are more likely to encounter the ads, whether
watching television, listening to the radio, surfing the Internet,
passing by billboards or reading a newspaper or magazine. Another
way media planning tries to improve the chances that consumers will
see ads is to have them appear in unexpected places, from store
floors and plastic bags wrapped around dry cleaning to elevators
and airport baggage carousels.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do our job well, the effectiveness of our advertising
will be improved by putting ads in better places at better times,''
Browner said, ``making sure we can reach more of the target
audience more effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to select Starcom MediaVest was made by a committee
of seven high-ranking GM marketing and advertising executives.
There were two other agencies under consideration in the review:
Interpublic Group of Cos. and Carat North America, part of Aegis
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by GM to consolidate media planning at a standalone
shop came seven years after the company, the nation's largest
advertiser and largest automaker, consolidated media buying _ the
negotiations to determine how much ads will cost _ at GM Mediaworks
in Warren, Mich., formed by Interpublic at GM's request.
</P>
<P>
   The creative duties for GM brands remain at the various agencies
now handling those tasks, including Starcom MediaVest siblings like
Leo Burnett in Chicago and D'Arcy Masius Benton &AMP; Bowles in Troy,
Mich., as well as Interpublic agencies like Campbell-Ewald in
Warren and McCann-Erickson in Troy. The creative agencies had also
been handling media planning for their particular brands; so, for
instance, Burnett took care of creative and planning tasks for
Oldsmobile and D'Arcy did the same for Cadillac and Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of consolidation is to wring additional economies from
the elaborate planning and buying processes that lead to the
delivery of ads to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Efficiencies come from improved effectiveness in the
marketplace,'' said John G. Middlebrook, vice president and general
manager for vehicle brand marketing at GM, during the conference
call.
</P>
<P>
   That will best be accomplished, he added, by ``the formation of
a dedicated media-planning operation, tentatively titled GM
Planworks,'' to consolidate the national and regional
brand-planning duties that had been divided among 17 agencies. The
responsibilities had been about evenly divided between agencies
owned by B Com3 and Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   Starcom MediaVest will form GM Planworks _ in Detroit or a
nearby suburb _ to handle the media planning for brands that
include Chevrolet, Pontiac, Oldsmobile, Buick, Cadillac and GMC.
Currently, more than 200 people handle those planning tasks,
developing and producing media schedules for each brand based on
the intended audience for each car, minivan or truck. GM Planworks,
which is to be fully operating by the first quarter of 2001, is to
have 150 to 200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about trying to raise the bar higher,'' said Jack
Klues, chief executive at Starcom MediaVest, which was formed by B
Com3 in May by merging Starcom Worldwide, affiliated with Burnett,
with MediaVest Worldwide, affiliated with D'Arcy. Other Starcom
MediaVest clients include Coca-Cola, Philip Morris and Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always admired and respected'' the performance of GM
Mediaworks, he added. ``Now our goal and purpose is to deliver that
same quality of work from a strategic planning perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Carat North America, unlike Starcom MediaVest and Interpublic,
has not handled media planning for GM. But the chief executive
there, David Verklin, is well known to the automaker for his work
at the San Francisco agency now known as Publicis &AMP; Hal Riney,
which handles creative and media planning assignments for Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two `inside' competitors and the one `outside' competitor
all came in with an equal opportunity to win the assignment,''
Browner said, adding that the criteria by which Starcom MediaVest
was chosen included ``the successes the agency has had for GM as
well as with other companies'' and ``its strategic media
research.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had no dissatisfaction with the quality of the media
plans done for our brands by the individual agencies,'' Browner
said. ``But we should benefit from the integration across the
brands, the shared learning when you've got best-in-class
research.''
</P>
<P>
   Riney continues to handle media planning for Saturn and the
Martin Agency in Richmond, Va., owned by Interpublic, continues to
handle media planning for Saab.  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
