<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH26-COX     07-25 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush officially taps Cheney for VP.
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It was in March, over dinner at the Governor's
Mansion, that Gov. George W. Bush first asked the man who had
served as his father's defense secretary if he would consider
taking another job in government: vice-president.
</P>
<P>
   Richard B. Cheney said no.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next four months, Bush said he grew to realize that
the man he had chosen to help Bush look for a running mate himself
possessed the characteristics that Bush sought for his ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the Bush-Cheney courtship emerged during
Tuesday's national debut of Bush's much-anticipated and, to some,
surprising decision to choose a stalwart from his father's
administration, a former White House chief of staff to Gerald Ford
and a six-term congressman who has been out of public service for
nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deeply involved in running a business, enjoying private
life and I certainly wasn't looking to return to public service,''
Cheney told a crowd of state employees, Bush campaign workers and
their friends Tuesday at his debut as Bush's running mate. ``But I
had an experience that changed my mind this spring. As I worked
alongside Gov. Bush I heard him talk about his unique vision for
our party and for our nation. I saw his sincerity. I watched him
make decisions, always firm and always fair, and, in the end, I
learned how persuasive he can be.''
</P>
<P>
   If the veteran Washington insider _ the man Bush eventually
charged with finding him a running mate _ was slow to be converted,
he moved quickly once it came upon him. Over July 4 weekend, after
talking with Bush at his Crawford ranch, Cheney changed his mind
about his willingness to consider the vice-presidential slot.
</P>
<P>
   By July 12, Cheney was in Washington getting a full physical
exam and called Bush that night from a dinner in Minneapolis to
report the results _ a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, he met with Bush and his top level campaign
advisors to discuss the implications of taking the job he was
vetting candidates for. Four days after that, he told the board of
directors at Halliburton, the Dallas energy company where he is
chief executive officer, that he was being considered for the
ticket's number two spot.
</P>
<P>
   On July 21, Cheney flew to his home state of Wyoming to change
his voter registration in order to comply with a constitutional
provision which penalizes a ticket where the president and vice
president are from the same state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not notify the campaign,'' campaign spokeswoman Karen
Hughes told reporters Tuesday. ``Gov. Bush was not aware he was
doing that. None of us at the campaign were aware in advance that
he was doing that. He felt that that was part of the process he
should go through to prepare himself to be considered to establish
his residency in his home state of Wyoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes recounted the tale of Cheney's emergence as Bush's
running mate just after the two men appeared with their wives for
the formal unveiling of the Bush-Cheney ticket at Austin's Erwin
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign was quick to try to clear ho had a conservative
voting record in Congress and has the hearty approval of the
Republican party's right flank _ will help Bush fulfill his promise
to be a different kind of Republican who can reach out to Democrats
and independents, Rove cited Cheney's support for school reform
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And he discounted questions about whether Cheney's association
with President Bush's administration will make the Bush-Cheney
ticket look more like a thing of the past to voters than the wave
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, virtually everybody that we've talked about has some
association with the last three Republican administrations in one
way, shape or form,'' Rove said. `` Whether it's friendship with or
service in..., that's just the nature of garnering the credentials
necessary to show the American people you're up to the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said only Bush, Cheney and the team Cheney established to
find a running mate for Bush know for sure who was on the list of
candidates. Tuesday, some of those whose names were mentioned in
news reports as possible contenders, took it upon themselves to
wish the two good luck in November, including former Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole and Illinois Congressman John Kasich, who
congratulated Bush on making, ``a solid choice. ``
</P>
<P>
   Ridge sent out a press release informing reporters that he
withdrew from consideration on July 6 to spend more time with his
wife and teenage children. He said that he and Bush agreed not to
make his decision to withdraw public until Bush announced his final
decision for a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said he did not believe that Ridge's support for abortion
rights was a factor. Indeed, the nitty-gritty of winning
battleground states, appeasing Republican party constituencies and
other such political calculations had little to do with Bush's
ultimate decision _ at least as Hughes and Rove recounted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became really vital to name somebody who could be seen as
president of the United States,'' Rove said. ``That was the only
political consideration if you will.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
