<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2906 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BOX-EVANDER0726-COX     07-25 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield resumes his eclectic search for the heavyweight belts
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - This just in: Evander Holyfield is about to become the
trainer of an ex-con boxer trying to repair his life. And a
consultant to the trainer of a fighter who falls for a wealthy
woman.
</P>
<P>
   No, you didn't miss his latest retirement news. It is the
fantasy side of Holyfield's eclectic life. He has landed roles in a
pair of movies, portraying _ himself. On celluloid, as in real
life, he is who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to reality. In 17 days, Holyfield will resume his
scavenger hunt for the heavyweight division's three principal belts
when he confronts unheralded John Ruiz in Las Vegas. This one, for
the WBA crown, is the relatively easy part.
</P>
<P>
   Then, how would he wrest away the WBC and IBF titles, held by
the ever-improving Lennox Lewis? Let us count the ways.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lewis is targeted for a mandatory defense against David Tua,
the human tree stump, by November. Tua is heavyweight boxing's
flavor of the month, with his lethal punch, strong chin and
Samoan/New Zealander background. Should the champion prevail, next
spring could bring Lewis-Holyfield III.
</P>
<P>
   The squat Tua, capitalizing on a seven-inch height disparity,
could get Lewis flummoxed and slip in a knockout blow. That result
ultimately could set up Holyfield against his onetime sparring
partner.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  After disposing of Tua, Lewis could submit to public sentiment
_ and the prospects of a paycheck with endless zeroes on it _ and
meet Mike Tyson. Should Tyson triumph without committing any
felonies in the ring, the clamor for Holyfield-Tyson III would be
high-decibel. The WCW and WWF could not dream up such a dramatic
matchup.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the last scenario is the least likely. Lewis is
affiliated with HBO, Tyson with Showtime. President Clinton has
been too busy with Barak and Arafat to bring the enemy cable
networks into agreement on a bout between their bell cows. In
boxing, money talks, but it could take awhile to be heard in this
case.
</P>
<P>
   Further, because of his quick kayoes, Tyson remains caked in
ring rust. Even going on and off anti-depressants, Tyson is
cognizant enough to know he must log plenty more rounds to sharpen
himself for Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also is a soldier for Showtime. But because the
networks have reached accord for two Lewis-Holyfield bouts already,
precedent has been set.
</P>
<P>
   The path to the belts would be clearest if Tua topples Lewis.
And to hear Jim Thomas, Holyfield's manager, it would be the most
welcome sequence. ``Evander sees some pretty significant flaws in
Tua that he believes he could easily exploit,'' Thomas said. Left
unsaid is that Lewis controlled Holyfield both times, although
judges denied him one win.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters for Holyfield is the dreaded word
``mandatory.'' Boxing bodies often give fighters little or no
choice about their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Next in the WBA line is Wladimir Klitschko, an imposing 6-foot-6
Ukrainian who dazzled recently on the Lewis-Frans Botha undercard
and could bother Holyfield. Then, the Lewis-Tua winner might be
ordered to duke it out with someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield tries not to concern himself with all of the maybes.
While eating breakfast recently at his second home, near his
training gym in Houston, the Atlantan said his attention is
occupied by restoring lost fitness after a pulled muscle pushed
back the Ruiz fight nine weeks from its original date.
</P>
<P>
   After 1 1/2 weeks of weight and aerobics work, Holyfield
returned to the sparring ring last weekend without negative
consequences. Aside from minor discomfort, he pronounced himself
healthy. ``The soreness doesn't go away as fast as before,'' says
the 37-year-old. ``That's part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The postponement raised, Pavlov-like, suspicions in the boxing
community that promoter Don King had concocted the injury to cover
up for supposedly modest ticket sales. ``They always try to blame
Don,'' Holyfield said. So he accepted King's invitation to fly to
Las Vegas and speak for himself. If Holyfield cannot be trusted,
nobody in this sport can.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like somebody was cutting me,'' he said about the
pain, which sprang from the back right side of his body from
lifting weights and wound up on the left under his rib cage. Burned
by previous instances of fighting below optimum condition, he
decided, ``You really don't need to go in there this time. It ain't
worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise decision. One more loss probably would end his quest for
the distinction of being the only four-time undisputed heavyweight
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz does not seem to pose steep problems. ``He's an aggressive
fighter, throws a lot of punches,'' Holyfield said. ``He's very
ordinary. He's not a very crafty fighter. He doesn't move his head.
He never thinks about (whether) he's going to get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz, he deduced, is a one-trick pony, always aiming for the
knockout. ``I've been around long enough'' to decipher those types,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield found solace in the unplanned layoff by sharing the
first days of summer with eight of his nine children living in
Atlanta. He attended track meets involving his four oldest and
baseball games for his 10-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Other items of his calendar needed readjusting, notably the
taping of his part in a Canadian boxing film, which, according to
Thomas, might feature Kate Winslet of ``Titanic'' fame.
</P>
<P>
   For the other big-screen gig, Thomas said the lead role was
turned down because the character is a drug user with a prison
record. ``It's not a role kids should see him in,'' the manager
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the comparatively bit part that Holyfield accepted,
Thomas asked that profanity be minimized, which might be a tall
order if Spike Lee agrees to direct.
</P>
<P>
   After Ruiz, Holyfield hopes to toast the end of summer by taking
some of his children on an island vacation, followed by a trip to
Saskatoon to shoot his film part.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the hard part: waiting for the heavyweight situation
to sort itself out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
