<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-BOS &LR;      07-25 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-CRASH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
30-YEAR RECORD BROKEN AS CONCORDE JET CRASHES NEAR PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A New York-bound supersonic Concorde jet carrying 109
people crashed into a small hotel shortly after takeoff here
Tuesday afternoon, killing all those on board and at least four
people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first fatal accident involving the jet that travels
at twice the speed of sound, makes the trans-Atlantic journey in
just 3 1/2 hours and is the airliner of choice for those who can
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   After the crash, British Airways and Air France, which created
the supersonic jet in 1969, indefinitely grounded the other
Concordes in operation. One other Concorde had been grounded in
London last week because of cracks in its wing.
</P>
<P>
   The Air France charter that crashed Tuesday was carrying a group
of German tourists bound for New York City, where they were to
embark on a two-week cruise of the Caribbean and South America. One
American, a retired Air France employee who was not identified, was
among those aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The airliner's full fuel tanks ensured a fireball on impact _
and no survivors. The fiery fuselage enveloped a small hotel in the
village of Gonesse near Charles de Gaulle airport, killing at least
four people there and injuring about a dozen others on the ground.
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, visibly shaken while touring the
scene, said the death toll is not expected to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found the cockpit voice recorder and flight data
recorder and hoped to use them for more clues to the crash. ``It
remains to be seen what condition they are in,'' a French Transport
Ministry official told Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   The crash came a day after British Airways acknowledged it had
grounded one of its seven Concorde jets at Heathrow Airport in
London because cracks were detected in its wings. Air France also
found cracks in the wings of its six-plane Concorde fleet, but on
Monday assured passengers the cracks were the result of normal wear
and tear and did not make the jet any less safe.
</P>
<P>
   Many aviation experts dismissed suggestions that such cracks
could contribute to Tuesday's crash, with some saying that engine
failure was the most likely cause, after witnesses said the jet
appeared to stall just moments after its takeoff, having climbed no
more than 200 feet. Fire streaked from one of the jet's two left
engines as it screamed toward the ground.
</P>
<P>
   One witness, Sid Hare, an American pilot for Federal Express who
watched the crash from his airport hotel room, told reporters the
jet appeared to be ``struggling to climb'' when suddenly its nose
went straight up, an indicator of engine failure. Hare, who saw
smoke and flames coming from one of the engines, said the plane
rolled to its left, then crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, Leonel Francsque, 25, a truck driver, was about
a half-mile away from the eventual crash site when he saw the plane
descend: ``First I heard some kind of explosion, then I saw huge
flames leaping into the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other witnesses who stood for hours on a grassy mound on
Gonesse, silently watching the rescue effort on a blackened wheat
field, Francsque described seeing the pilot apparently struggle to
keep the plane aloft.
</P>
<P>
   At one point he banked to the left, the side which was on fire,
``as if to avoid Gonesse,'' said Willy Corenthin, 29, an
electrician at the airport, who was driving from work to his
parents' apartment nearby when he witnessed the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The passengers included 97 adults and three people under age 18,
among a group that was scheduled to board the MS Deutscheland in
New York City for a 16-day luxury cruise of Latin America.
Round-trip seats on the Paris-New York Concorde cost $9,000, about
25 percent more than normal first-class fares. Similar New
York-London service is nearly $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tour operator Peter Deilmann said the cruise, which had a total
of 510 passengers booked, would not be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Moody, a former pilot who writes regularly for British
aviation magazines, said he doubted the wing cracks had anything to
do with the crash. He described the Concordes, with an average age
is 23 years, as among the safest airliners ever made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real workhouse,'' Moody said.
</P>
<P>
   He said it has had only one mishap, in 1979, when a tire blew
out on landing. No one was seriously injured and the accident led
to a design modification that prevented any repeat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde flies at some 55,000 feet, nearly twice ordinary
passenger jets, and travels at nearly 1,350 miles per hour, twice
the speed of sound.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's crash, besides being a tragedy for the families of the
victims, was a crushing blow to Gallic pride. The crash comes as
the French were riding high, taking over the six-month rotating
presidency of the European Union and winning the European soccer
championship, two years after claiming the World Cup. Paris was
still basking in the glow of Sunday's conclusion along the
Champs-Elysees of the Tour de France, the world's most celebrated
bicycle race.
</P>
<P>
   The last few weeks have been what Pierre Wilmotte, a French
businessman, described as ``heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he added, ``is hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilmotte, returning from business in Britain, said he winced and
almost cried as he watched the scene of devastation from the lounge
at Waterloo Station in London, as he waited for the train to bring
him home to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a punch in the stomach,'' he said. ``After this,
how can you even talk about football?''
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board chairman James Hall Tuesday
said the NTSB, at the invitation of its French counterpart, the
Bureau Enquetes (Accident Bureau), will send a safety investigator
to serve as an NTSB observer. The NTSB was invited becuase the
Concorde provides regular scheduled service to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB conducted two preliminary investigations in recent
years involving the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Last Aug. 24, two British Airways Concordes came within 800 feet
vertically and 0.7 miles horizontally near New York's John F.
Kennedy International Airport. One flight had departed to Heathrow
and one flight was inbound on final approach when they came too
close.
</P>
<P>
   And on Oct. 8, 1998, British Airways Flight 001 to New York was
cruising at 54,700 feet at Mach 2.0 off the coast of Newfoundland
when the flight crew noticed a ``thump felt throughout the
airframe, followed by a buzz,'' according to the NTSB preliminary
report.
</P>
<P>
   The flight continued on to New York without incident, but on
landing, airline personnel found that 40 percent of the lower
rudder was missing from the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Matthew Brelis of the Globe Staff contributed to this report from
Boston, as did correspondent Vivienne Walt from Gonesse, France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
