<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2908 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ASSESS-NY     07-25 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CHENEY'S LACK OF NEGATIVES MAY HAVE BEEN HIS BIGGEST
POSITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BUSH-CHENEY) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the most momentous decision of his campaign thus far, Gov.
George W. Bush took the least adventurous and least sensational
course possible.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Dick Cheney was deeply revealing about Bush's
approach to politics and to governing. It underscored that Bush is
generally not a bold risk taker in his public life. He is so
confident that he will win the election (too confident, some
Republicans say) that he was looking more for a partner who could
help him in the White House than on the stump. He wanted someone
beside him who is utterly loyal, and with whom he is comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   And his decision suggests that Bush would be a president who,
despite his own lack of seasoning on the national stage, is not
afraid to surround himself with more experienced hands.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney brings so few overt political advantages to the ticket
that it is clear that Bush determined that whatever may win him the
White House, it would not be who he picked as his No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his decision had dribbled out over the past few
days, Bush's choice was so unexpected that as recently a week ago,
virtually every prominent Republican insider was tossing out names
like Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma, Sen. John McCain of Arizona,
former Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, and, everyone's favorite,
former Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Yet aside from his failure to win over Powell, Bush's
calculation was that a choice with more sizzle (and with more
potential liabilities) was not worth the gamble to his election _
or to his happiness in the Oval Office. Although Democrats were
gleefully digging out Cheney's conservative voting record in
Congress, Bush advisers said they were confident he would never
embarrass the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also passed up an opportunity to try to break the abortion
barrier in the Republican Party by daring to go with a supporter of
abortion rights, like Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania or Gov. George
Pataki of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's less ambitious objective was settling on a No. 2 who
passes what Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., calls the John Rocker test.
``It's like the Atlanta Braves and John Rocker,'' Kerrey said.
``You can't afford to make a selection that becomes bigger than
you. You can't afford that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's play-it-safe approach may well have stemmed from a
determination not to repeat mistakes of the past, namely his
father's selection of Dan Quayle. Again and again, his advisers
said over recent months that Bush was less insistent on bringing
added value to the ticket and more on not doing anything to hurt
it.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the first joint appearance by Bush and
Cheney, in Austin on Tuesday _ the most subdued, low energy vice
presidential roll-out in years _ and the introduction of Quayle 12
years ago could not have been sharper.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney stood placidly next to Bush, his hands clasped in front
of him. The newly burnished ticket did not even partake in the
customary overhead victory clasp. The presidential candidate, who
is derided by critics as being so unpresidential, picked a partner
whose presence practically shouts: grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from 1988 when Quayle, looking much like George
Bush's son, bounced around the stage in Huntington, Ind., appearing
so grateful to be picked that he could not contain himself.
</P>
<P>
   But while nothing went awry Tuesday, it was hardly a rousing
debut. It did not approach the energetic tableau eight years ago in
Little Rock, Ark., when Bill Clinton, Al Gore and their families
joined for one of that campaign's most memorable moments. There is
no chance that Bush and Cheney will be dubbed the ``hunks of the
heartland,'' as were Clinton and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There certainly were candidates out there who were more
eye-popping,'' said Paul Light, an authority on the vice presidency
at the Brookings Institution in Washington. ``This would go down in
my book as arguably the safest vice presidential choice of the last
50 years. I can't think of any one that is this solid, this
noncontroversial.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans were jubilant Tuesday that Bush had found a
running mate who would not lead delegates at next week's Republican
convention to utter the dreaded ``a word'': abortion. Cheney is,
safely, an abortion foe. He is also, safely, conservative, but one
who gets on well with moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lack of interest in a political quick fix also shows that
he is mindful of history. The last vice presidential candidate who
actually made a difference in the outcome was forty years ago, when
John F. Kennedy picked Lyndon Johnson, who assured him that he
would carry Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheney pick is not devoid of political upsides _ or risks.
Cheney's vast experience in Congress, in the White House and in
national security issues will help counter critiques from the
Democrats that Bush is not ready for the White House. While Powell
was not available, it could be that Bush saw the next best thing in
Cheney, who was also a mainstay of the Persian Gulf war, his
father's Bush's greatest triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Bush sought to score political points for picking a
partner for reasons that did not appear baldly political. ``I have
to admit something,'' he said. ``I didn't pick Dick Cheney because
of Wyoming's three electoral votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Safe it may seem, but not foolproof. One of Bush's prime
advantages over Vice President Al Gore is that he does not have a
long trail of congressional votes to be mined by the opposition.
But Cheney does _ and many of his votes are decidedly conservative.
For all the stature he brings, Cheney, who is close to former
President Bush, could suggest to voters that Governor Bush is a
daddy's boy.
</P>
<P>
   Also, even with his doctor's stamp of approval, Cheney's history
of three heart attacks is hardly reassuring to some people.
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans seemed pleased, if not exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as good as he could have done,'' said Charles Black, a
veteran Republican strategist. ``It's a risk-free choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But in politics even playing it safe has risks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
