<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      07-25 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YEARS OF EFFORT, FINAL MIDEAST ACCORD ELUDES CLINTON'S
GRASP 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By MARC LACEY with DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was shortly after midnight, sitting across from
Yasser Arafat in the small presidential cabin at Camp David, that
President Clinton realized that the foreign policy achievement he
desired more than any other during the waning months of his tenure
had slipped from his grasp.
</P>
<P>
   On the table in the rustic cabin was an American proposal on the
future of Jerusalem, a proposal that Prime Minister Ehud Barak of
Israel was edging toward accepting.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat had repeatedly refused to give ground, and early on
Tuesday Clinton, mustering all his legendary powers of persuasion,
launched into a final pitch: If you take the deal, he told the
aging Palestinian leader, you will have achieved legitimacy and
international recognition, as well as aid and investment from the
West. If you walk away, he added, according to a senior
administration official deeply involved in the talks, ``you will
lose a Palestinian state of substantial size,'' and risk a slow
slide into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who Americans describe as ``a deeply conflicted man,''
decided to walk. He stood up, left the cabin, and at 3 a.m.,
through an aide, rejected Clinton's deal. He also refused to go
along with Clinton's Plan B: Announcing a settlement on all issues
except the status of Jerusalem, which would be kicked down the
road, with both sides agreeing to resolve it eventually, and
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, at a White House press conference, a deeply
frustrated Clinton compared the days of painstaking talks that
ended in failure to ``going to the dentist without having your gums
deadened.''
</P>
<P>
   This was hardly Clinton's first trip to the dentist's chair.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the past seven months he has invested enormous amounts
of time and prestige in an attempt to reach historic accords
between Israel and its neighbors, first the Syrians, then the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Clinton's foreign policy team was betting that
changing times plus the force of Clinton's own finely honed sense
for the middle ground might be enough to win agreement, and with it
a legacy to cap his second term.
</P>
<P>
   Yet twice so far, Clinton and his aides have been proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hardly to be blamed for the failure of the talks that
collapsed early Tuesday morning. He entered the process with little
to lose, save for his dwindling hoard of time.
</P>
<P>
   And while his second term may be viewed as a series of lost
opportunities _ two years squandered on scandal, two years locked
in stalemate with Congress _ few presidents have devoted his kind
of time to peacemaking, from Northern Ireland to the Korean
Peninsula to the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get credit for his huge effort,'' said James MacGregor
Burns, a presidential historian at the University of Maryland. ``He
has not only talked peace but has devoted hundreds and hundreds of
hours to it. Even the collapse of this negotiation will not hurt
his standing on this score.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, not surprisingly, argued on Tuesday that the Camp David
meeting was worth the shot _ and may yet prove productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, on balance, it was very much the right thing to do,
and it increases the chance of a successful agreement, and it
increases the chances of avoiding a disaster,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks, one American official said, even a Palestinian
negotiator noted that during the two weeks of the summit, ``all the
taboos have been broken,'' as both sides discussed compromises on
Jerusalem and other areas that had never been broached outside of
policy institutes that study such issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he held out the hope that new talks could resume in
late summer or autumn, Clinton clearly sees his season drawing to a
close.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago he entered the talks privately exuding cautious
optimism. One of his closest aides said at the time that while no
deal was certain, the stars were uniquely aligned. Barak, the White
House had concluded, needed an agreement if he had any hope of
remaining in office after the recent collapse of his ruling
coalition. Arafat, they continued, knew that his own days as the
leader of the Palestinians were dwindling, and that an agreement
was his only hope for a different life for young Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   And America's prosperity and budget surpluses, Clinton's aides
concluded, meant that the president was likely to succeed in
convincing Congress to pay the huge bill necessary to support a
Middle East peace, opening the floodgates for aid from other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be all gone,'' one of Clinton's aides said on
Tuesday. The president's last, best hope, the aide continued, is
that Barak survives the breakup of his coalition to negotiate
another day, and that Arafat concludes that declaring a Palestinian
state on Sept. 13 was ``the path to conflict when a compromise is
within reach.''
</P>
<P>
   But that is betting on the last pitch of the last inning, and it
may be little solace to Clinton. In some ways he had been preparing
for Monday night's meeting for seven years, since the Oslo accords
and then the agreement reached at Wye Plantation, all dress
rehearsals for the big show that never came off at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks he had worked late into the night, coming up
with ``bridging proposals,'' which were the basis for the final
proposal Arafat rejected. ``Give me a test on some piece of land
anywhere in Jerusalem or Israel, I know the answer,'' Clinton had
said the eve of the talks, discussing his late-night preparations.
``Ask me to draw a map of the West Bank in my sleep, I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   His frustration seemed particularly high on Tuesday because in
the hours after he returned from Japan on Sunday afternoon, it
seemed as if real progress was being made.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of his return, he called a meeting on security
issues, and ``there was real progress,'' one senior American
official said. Then there were sessions on borders and refugees,
and ``for the first time, we could see the outline of an
agreement,'' the official said. ``But neither side wanted to make
final decisions until they tackled Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton turned to that subject, he put together what one
official called ``a mosaic of ideas, our ideas and others' ideas,
that we felt could be the basis of a final settlement.'' That was
the proposal put to Arafat, with Clinton making the case that a
generation of Palestinians ``are on the verge of living a different
life than you lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, though, could not break free of several generations of
Palestinian ideology about the sanctity of sovereignty over
Jerusalem. Nor would he allow the issue of Jerusalem to be
deferred. His refusal to do so ``surprised'' Clinton in the words
of one aide, and ``frustrated him'' in the words of another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted it badly for the right reasons,'' an administration
official said of Clinton. ``He's invested seven years in this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
