<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-FUTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TALKS FAILED, SOME SEE MIDEAST CONFLICT AS INEVITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The walls of the Old City glimmered in the distance
Tuesday night, warmly embracing Islam's golden Dome of the Rock,
Christianity's towering church spires and Judaism's Western Wall
with its massive Herodian stones.
</P>
<P>
   This is the view from the Promenade, where just about every
night Palestinian and Israeli families from east and west Jerusalem
gather in separate clusters for the view and the cool breeze that
breaks the day's heat.
</P>
<P>
   Here, both sides showed little surprise that the talks in Camp
David had failed, and both expressed a sense of fatalism that
conflict was inevitable over the emotional and spiritual attachment
both have to the shimmering city below _ Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence will break out. It is only a question of how and to
what extent,'' said lawyer Jeff Ostrov, 27, a religious Jew who
emigrated with his family from Newton, Mass. 17 years ago. ``There
is very little room to negotiate when it comes to Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 50 yards away on the walkway _ past stroller-pushing
mothers in Muslim veils or in Orthodox Jewish clothing _ an
extended Palestinian family sat along a stone wall.
</P>
<P>
   Cabbie Amed Ziad, also 27, said Yasser Arafat correctly refused
to compromise on Palestinian control of Jerusalem: ``The trust in
him rises now. We will not give up on our Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the violent Palestinian uprising that began in
1987, Ziad added, ``The Palestinian people learned a lot from the
intifadah. People know what to do here to get their rights. They
know this is the language that Israel listens to.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than two weeks of talks in Camp David, Jerusalem had
waited as if it were expecting a baby. But during that time, a new
sense arose of what is possible, a discussion of ideas on how to
share control of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But with the summit's collapse, lower-level Palestinian and
Israeli negotiators are expected to try to pick up the pieces and
prepare for a US delegation visit within weeks. Both sides said
they would continue to resolve the final issues of the peace
process before Sept. 13, when Arafat has vowed to declare
Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Camp David, both sides were bracing themselves for
the possibility of failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli army moved tanks into the West Bank. In Gaza, Jewish
settlers stacked sandbags and built other fortifications. Tuesday
night, in outlying Palestinian villages such as Abu Dis and
Bethany, a reinforced Israeli military had set up checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian police, which looks more like an army with its
fatigues and its machine guns, also beefed up its presence in its
parts of the West Bank. There were reports that Palestinians
stockpiled food and water, anticipating conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who campaigned last year on a
promise not to divide Jerusalem, returns to a government that
virtually collapsed just before he left. To survive, Barak may have
to ask the opposition Likud Party to join his coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Rabinowitz, 31, who is traditioinally a more
conservative Likud voter but supported Barak last year, said, ``I
think he won the election by promising not to divide Jerusalem.
Then he marched off to Camp David and started offering to divide
it. He acts like he's still in the army and he's chief of staff.
He's lost his credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat faces different constraints. He must contain violence
from breaking out on streets that has grown restive after seven
years of the incremental peace process. And he will have to shore
up political support in the Arab world that will allow him to
continue with negotations with a more unified front.
</P>
<P>
   Ghassan Khatib, director of the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center, said, ``The Palestinian street will wait
until the 13th of September because that is the date they care
about. They want a state, and they know that Arafat was dragged to
this summit. They'll wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the extremists on both sides have already begun their
drumbeat on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual leader of the Islamic
militant group Hamas, said in an interview at his home in Gaza,
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure of Camp David was expected. No concessions can be
made on Jerusalem and the Israelis do not want peace. I am calling
upon the Palestinian people to go back to use the language of
power, weapons, resistance and Jihad to regain their occupied land
as Hezbollah did in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Also applauding failure was Yehuda Etzion, a Jewish religious
extremist who espouses a reubilding of the Jewish Temple and was
convicted in 1984 of trying to blow up the Muslim Dome of the Rock,
built 1300 years ago atop the Second Temple's remains.
</P>
<P>
   Etzion was holding a small rally among several groups who
believe rebuilding the Temple is the only way to achieve redemption
for the Jewish people. They gathered on the Mount of Olives
overlooking what Jews call the Temple Mount and what Muslims refer
to as Haram al-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   It is a 35-acre compound that sits atop the Western Wall and the
rest of what archelogists believe is the site of the remains of the
First and Second Jewish Temple. And it is the holy ground of the
Dome of the Rock, where Muslims believe the Prophet Mohammed
ascended to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Just after the news of the failure at Camp David, Etzion said,
``I thank God, and now we have to prepare for a war here. I don't
often compliment our prime minister. But in this case God saved us
from a very bad and black day had we given the Temple Mount to the
Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meron Benvenisti, a former deputy mayor of Jerusalem, was less
bleak in his assessment of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in neither redemption nor apocalypse,'' he said. ``I
just believe the two sides are not ready for a final settlement.
This may mean we have some violence, but it also means the two
sides just have to work harder. And I hope that is what they do,
and not just become further entrenched in their own positions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
