<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-U.S.-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND AFRICA WILL TEAM TO FIGHT GLOBAL CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By   HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ American law enforcement officials
have agreed to set up a regional academy in Botswana to help train
police officers and prosecutors from crime-ridden South Africa and
many neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which will be 160 miles north of here, just outside
the Botswana capital, Gaborone, will be the third such academy set
up by the State Department in its effort to bolster the fight
against burgeoning global crime syndicates.
</P>
<P>
   Under the direction of the Bureau of International Narcotics and
Law Enforcement Affairs, the academy, like ones in Hungary and
Thailand, will bring experts from the FBI and other federal and
international agencies to countries where the criminal justice
system lags far behind the cunning and creativity of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Since South Africa opened its borders several years ago as the
apartheid era was coming to a close, it has become a hub of
criminal activity, from counterfeiting and money laundering to drug
trafficking and alien smuggling. Lured by the high life here in the
country's richest city, criminals have come from across the
continent, overwhelming a poorly trained police force that has been
hard pressed to control its own thieves and murderers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Botswana is one of the safest countries in Africa.
Unlike Budapest or Bangkok, where the other two academies are, its
capital is not a hub of crime in its region and it has seen only
hints of the complicated criminal enterprises that are thriving in
Johannesburg. It is a country of about 1.5 million people, with a
police force of about 6,500 officers. South Africa has 44 million
people and more than 100,000 police officers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, South Africa was the original choice for the academy,
but leaders there suggested that the United States consider
neighboring countries, according to a State Department report. As
the most advanced country in the region, South Africa is often the
location of choice for offices of international organizations. It
is a privilege that its neighbors have come to envy, even resent,
and in bowing out of this opportunity, South Africa was ceding it
to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that comes to the region comes to South Africa, and
in that sense it's prudent not to follow that pattern,'' an
American official involved in the selection process said. ``We had
a very willing partner in Botswana, and they committed the funds.''
Commissioner Norman Moleboge, the head of the Botswana police
force, said that while South Africa's crime problems were enormous
compared with Botswana's, they had to be treated as a regional
concern that, if left unchecked, would eventually undermine even
the most stable of southern Africa's countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neighbor's problems are as good as mine,'' Moleboge said in
a telephone interview from Gaborone. ``If major crimes find their
way into neighboring countries, they will find their way into
Botswana, so we need to fight crime from a national, regional and
international point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   American and Botswana officials signed an agreement on Monday in
Gaborone to establish the academy, and training programs are
expected to begin in the next few months. Courses will cover
subjects from forensics and narcotics to organized crime and public
corruption. Eventually, the academy is to be housed in Botswana's
national police college, which is expected to be completed in about
a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
