<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cheney pick may prompt Gore to choose Graham
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Supporters of U.S. Sen. Bob Graham say
his chances of becoming Vice President Al Gore's running mate
improved Tuesday when Texas Gov. George Bush chose Dick Cheney to
join the Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's Democratic supporters are looking for any hopeful sign
because they are convinced that Florida's senior senator can push
Gore over the top in the Sunshine State. A victory here, they
believe, could be devastating for the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to Cheney, the former defense secretary in President
George Bush's administration, fell predictably along party lines.
Florida Republicans applauded the pick while Democrats called the
choice uninspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great choice, a really solid choice,'' said Jillian
Inmon, Bush's Florida campaign director.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1.6 million veterans living in Florida, Cheney,
who helped lead the Persian Gulf War, could be used to target those
votes, said Randy Enwright, a Republican political consultant based
in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's an excellent choice who brings a lot to the
ticket,'' Enwright said. ``There's a comfort level with Cheney that
you just don't get with a lot of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling Bush's decision ``overly cautious,'' Democratic
consultant Karl Koch said, ``Cheney doesn't deliver a single vote
in Florida. The fact is, Cheney is not a proven vote-getter
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch says the logic of picking Graham improves with Cheney on
Bush's ticket. ``This allows Gore to come into Florida and pick
someone who can help him carry an important state.''
</P>
<P>
   One theory evolving is that the Cheney pick allows Gore to
concentrate his efforts on the vital Midwest states and to use
Graham to force Bush to compete in Florida, a state Republicans
once thought they had wrapped up.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls suggest that if Graham is on the ballot, Florida
would be a toss-up. Without Graham, Republicans have a stronger
edge here. With 270 electoral votes needed to capture the White
House, Florida's 25 votes are critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush's choice helps Graham,'' said Koch
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
