u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      07-25 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MIDEAST PEACE GAMBLE ENDS IN FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY AND ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The Middle East peace summit at Camp David broke
up Tuesday without an agreement, shutting down a high-stakes gamble
that for 15 days sought to end 52 years of bloody conflict between
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton stressed that both sides had made
substantial progress in the talks on a secluded mountaintop, he
acknowledged, ``They couldn't get there _ that's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was the first time, in an organized disciplined way,
they had to work through, both for themselves and then with each
other, how they were going to come to grips with issues that go to
the core of their identity,'' Clinton said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he hoped the talks would lead to further
negotiations before Sept. 13, the day Yasser Arafat has said he
would unilaterally declare a Palestinian state. Clinton also
expressed the hope that the summit ``increases the chances of
avoiding a disaster of violence'' in Israel and in Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
   But that was far from certain, as both Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak were to arrive home Wednesday to protests from
both Jewish and Islamist factions.
</P>
<P>
   Barak left Washington bluntly blaming Arafat for the Camp David
breakdown, saying the Palestinian leader was not ready to be a
peacemaker. But Arafat left Washington without comment, and senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat gave an optimistic assessment of
the talks, saying, ``Prospects for agreement on all permanent
status issues are stronger than at any time in almost nine years.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit-breaker was Jerusalem. The holy city was the subject
that took up almost all the time at the summit, according to US
officials, an astonishing switch from every previous
Israeli-Palestinian negotiation. All the previous talks dealt with
peripheral issues, not the core problems of Jerusalem, Palestinian
statehood, refugees and Jewish settlers.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. Tuesday, Arafat wrote a letter to Clinton saying that
Israel's offer on Jerusalem was not acceptable. Fifteen minutes
later, Clinton ended the talks for the night, deciding ``this knot
couldn't be untied,'' said White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't over quite yet. The three leaders agreed to sleep
on it.
</P>
<P>
   About 10:30 a.m., Clinton, Arafat and Barak gathered around a
dining room table in Aspen, the president's cabin at Camp David. It
was the 12th time that they had met, the third three-way meeting
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, they agreed there was no place to go but home.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders signed a five-part trilateral statement, written
with the help of their aides, that said the aim of their talks was
to ``put an end to decades of conflict and achieve a just and
lasting peace'' and both sides ``understand the importance of
avoiding unilateral actions that prejudge the outcome of
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, said Lockhart, was that Clinton became convinced
that he had exhausted all the possible solutions. ``It wasn't going
to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea at Camp David was that if they could solve Jerusalem,
they could solve everything.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't. Barak offered the Palestinians partial
sovereignty over East Jerusalem, which Israel captured from Jordan
in 1967 and annexed, in exchange for broadening the geographical
boundaries of the city to include several Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not enough for Arafat, who decided he could not
negotiate away the Arab sections of the city. He would be condemned
by Islamists throughout the Arab world because the Old City, with
its Muslim and Christian quarters, is home to the sacred Muslim
sites of the Dome of the Rock and the al-Aqsa mosques, the third
holiest site in Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Barak offered continued control over the mosque complex plus
limited sovereignty over Arab villages and neighborhoods in East
Jerusalem. In exchange, he wanted the borders of Jerusalem to be
redrawn to encompass huge Jewish settlements in the West Bank,
including Ma'ale Adumin, Givat Harel, and Pisgat Ze'ev and the
Etzion Bloc.
</P>
<P>
   But under the rules of the summit, nothing was agreed unless
everything was agreed. As Barak put it at a news conference in a
hotel ballroom basement in Frederick, Md., ``Even those ideas are
now null and void.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton said it was ``essential that they
not lose hope, that they keep working for peace.'' In a highly
unusual comment, Clinton went out of his way to praise Barak for
showing ``particular courage, vision, and an understanding of the
historic importance of this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, perhaps for domestic political reasons, blasted Arafat
only minutes after the president's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painful to realize that the other side is not ripe for
peace, but it's always better to know the realities than to delude
ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hebrew, he added, ``Arafat was afraid to take the necessary,
historical responsibility at this moment to bring about an end of
the conflict. The positions of Arafat on Jerusalem were those that
prevented the achievement of an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other issues as well, he said, including the fate of
Palestinian refugees. On those issues, he said, ``there are still
wide gaps of a kind of conceptual nature, not just technical
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   But Erekat, the Palestinian negotiator, said, ``I believe that
the continuation of our efforts will produce an agreement no later
than Sept. 13.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear, however, whether Clinton would find the time and
commitment in his last five months to help both leaders reach a
deal. In addition to planned trips to Nigeria and Vietnam, his time
will be taken by the Democratic convention in August; the
presidential campaign of Vice President Gore, the New York Senate
race of Hillary Rodham Clinton; and an ambitious legislative plate,
including a number of health initiatives such as reforms on HMOs,
prescription drugs and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House Tuesday, Clinton seemed relaxed, if tired. He
framed the conflict in religious terms, saying that the ``children
of Abraham, the descendants of Isaac and Ishmael, can only be
reconciled through courageous compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   He also described the talks as ``like going to the dentist
without having your gums deadened,'' and he compared the
negotiators at Camp David to those who forged peace deals involving
Bosnia, Kosovo and Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when we first started the Irish peace talks, we were
dealing with people who would hardly speak to each other. . . . We
were dealing with people who thought they were from another planet
from one another, whose wounds were open,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as his daughter, Chelsea, sat on the sidelines of the White
House press room listening raptly, Clinton said the Israelis and
Palestinians had an extraordinary relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know each other,'' he said. ``They know the names of each
other's children. They know how many grandchildren the grandparents
have.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know their life stories,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   That, he said, gave him hope despite failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've got to do, they've got to go home and check,'' he
said. ``They've got to feel around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
