<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-GERMA     07-25 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF CRASH A `BOMBSHELL' TO LUXURY TOUR OPERATOR IN GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
 (With AIRFRANCE-CRASH) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The shocked and shaken owner of a German luxury tour
operator appeared on national television Tuesday to confirm that
his company had chartered the Concorde that crashed near Paris,
killing 109 people on board and at least four more on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who died had paid thousands of dollars to be
whisked to New York and a waiting cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Deilmann, of Peter Deilmann Reederei GmbH, also expressed
the dismay of a nation about to embark on its own sacrosanct August
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The news was relayed by telephone to me by Air France and it
came as a bombshell,'' Deilmann said. ``We are in a state of deep
shock. I can tell you that 99 passengers booked their passage on
the aircraft through my company.''
</P>
<P>
   Deilmann, whose company is based in the Baltic port of Neustadt,
about 50 miles northeast of Hamburg, said the passengers came from
many regions of Germany. The Foreign Ministry said the single
largest group of passengers _ 39 _ was from Germany's biggest
state, North Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry declined to identify the 96 German victims before
families were notified. Most of the passengers traveled from
Frankfurt to Paris before boarding the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Air France said there were 100 passengers on board _ a figure
that apparently included the 99 passengers mentioned by Deilmann
and the lone American on board. Christopher Korenke, an Air France
vice president, told reporters at Kennedy International Airport in
New York that the American was a retired Air France employee.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the passengers were children, the ministry said. The
cruise was to have gone through the Caribbean to a final
destination of Manta in Ecuador, with an option to sail on as far
as Sydney, Australia, and the Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Germans are enthusiastic travelers, swarming across the globe in
search of warmer climes. The passengers on the Concorde had paid
between $4,200 and $11,000 for a cruise that was to begin in New
York on a luxury liner, the Deutschland.
</P>
<P>
   The ship was built two years ago in a mock Roaring '20s style,
with crystal chandeliers, a ballroom, a palm-filled winter garden
and a salt-water swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany expressed his
condolences to the victims' families and canceled plans to see a
performance of Goethe's ``Faust'' at the Expo 2000 world fair in
Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   The German cabinet, headed by Schroeder, said it would attend an
ecumenical service for victims of the crash Wednesday at a chapel
on the Expo grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Germany immediately indicated it intended to play a central role
in the investigation of the crash, dispatching its transport
minister, Reinhard Klimmt, to Paris and announcing that the federal
agency would begin an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The news punctured a generally upbeat mood in Germany, as a
strong economy and the passage through parliament of the largest
tax cuts for many years have bolstered the national mood and
increased Schroeder's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Deilmann said this was the fourth time that his company had
offered a Concorde-cruise package _ and it would be the last. But
the cruise, which had 510 passengers booked, would not be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense letting the ship lie there,'' he said. ``Life
goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York, some passengers felt differently.
</P>
<P>
   Gitta Schoeneberg, 47, and her 48-year-old husband, Willi, were
among the hundreds of passengers who had boarded the Deutschland in
Germany and sailed into New York on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a sad voyage for us,'' Mrs. Schoeneberg said.
``Whenever we look over at an empty seat, we will think of this
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband said, ``It's better to end the cruise here.''
</P>
<P>
   He said this was the most luxurious of the 25 cruises that he
and his wife _ both teachers _ had taken since 1990. ``I would ask
the captain not to go on. We're not in the mood for a party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
