 PERSONALS: Xxxxxxxxxxx Xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; EARNING AND SPENDING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Harper's provides a list of job titles from the U.S. Department
of Labor's Dictionary of Occupational Titles. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Bed rubber, bologna lacer, bosom presser, chicken fancier, crown
pounder, devil tender, egg smeller, Frickertron checker,
marshmallow runner, nibbler operator, pantyhose-crotch-closing
machine operator, pickle pumper, retort forker, seed-potato
arranger, smearer, stereotyper, wad impregnator, wax-ball knockout
worker, worm bed attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, working-class Hollywood stiffs have ponied up a range
of donations to political candidates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nancy Sinatra &LR;  and  &UR; Aaron Spelling &LR;  each gave  &UR; Al Gore &LR;  $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-range Gore givers (one or two thousand bucks) include
 &UR; Jane Alexander &LR; , &UR; Candice Bergen &LR; ,  &UR; Nicolas Cage &LR; ,  &UR; Tommy Lee &LR; 
 &UR; Jones &LR; ,  &UR; Dennis Miller &LR; ,  &UR; Lou Diamond Phillips &LR; ,  &UR; Jerry Seinfeld &LR; 
and  &UR; Gwyneth Paltrow &LR; .  &UR; Jimmy Smits &LR;  gave $750.
</P>
<P>
   The folks who dug deep for spare change ($250, and isn't it more
fun to keep track of the tightfisted than the big spenders?) were
 &UR; Jack Nicholson &LR; ,  &UR; Ossie Davis &LR; ,  &UR; Lily Tomlin  &LR; and  &UR; Larry &LR; 
 &UR; Hagman &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Jim Adams &LR;  had breakfast at the Ritz-Carlton in San
Francisco last week, and  &UR; Margaret &LR;   &UR; Thatcher &LR;  was sitting at the
very next table. Despite the recent auction of her Ferragamo
handbag, she wasn't carrying her things in a paper bag. Adams
reports that Maggie's bag was large, very black and alligator.
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; Lynne Cheney &LR; , wife of the Republican veep choice, published
a novel 12 years ago in which a vice president dies of a heart
attack and staff members keep it a secret. MSNBC quotes a
Washington Post review: ``Vice presidents, according to the cliche,
are superfluous. In fact, the premise here isn't all that
outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   --  &UR; O.J. Simpson &LR; , who said on yesterday's ``Today'' show that
everything is hunky-dory, tried to book the top floor of Lotus, a
fashionable New York club, for his birthday party, the New York
Post reports. Owner  &UR; David Rabin &LR;  turned him down. ``Not a shot,''
he said, ``under no circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Wash that pager out with soap:  &UR; David Daniels  &LR; of the Web
site development firm CloudSource followed up a meeting with East
Coast venture capitalists by e-mailing them about some details. The
response he received (via e-mail): ``F_ you.'' Subsequent
communication revealed that the East Coast businessman, who gets
e-mail from his pager, had left it on the subway, where a
mischievous finder had jumped right into the chain of
communication.
</P>
<P>
   -- Although San Francisco lawyer  &UR; Stacey Stillman &LR;  is a
``Survivor'' castoff, she is ``adorable,'' says  &UR; Lynn Claxon &LR; ,
president of Stars, the Agency, which has signed her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DECORATING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Architectural Digest says that U.S. Ambassador to Vietnam
 &UR; Douglas Peterson  &LR; ordered a statue of  &UR; George Washington &LR;  and one
of  &UR; Abraham Lincoln  &LR; for niches in the facade of his mansion from a
workshop in Hanoi that usually creates statuary of Ho Chi Minh.
</P>
<P>
   The statues delivered were of Honest Abe and  &UR; Benjamin &LR; 
 &UR; Franklin &LR; . Off with his head, said the ambassador, who had Franklin
decapitated and recapitated with the head of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; A ROYAL SNIT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Prince  &UR; Norodom Sihanouk &LR;  of Cambodia has announced plans to sue
the South China Morning Post for defamation after an article
appeared saying that the queen's son,  &UR; Norodom Sihamoni &LR; , is not
the son of Sihanouk.  &UR; Peter Stein  &LR; forwards a story from the Kyodo
News Service, which says that Sihamoni, a ballet dancer who lives
in Paris, was mentioned in a story about possible successors to
Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
   The king made an official statement last week that ``I am,
Norodom Sihanouk, his real father.'' He said he hopes a court in
Hong Kong, where the newspaper is published, will hear the matter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   ``Q: Does living in San Francisco give you that distance you
need from Hollywood? A: It's actually a much better place to be
unemployed. You can be creative, you can read, and you don't have
to be beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   -- &LR;   &LR; Director and actress  &UR; Joan Chen &LR; , whose new movie is
``Autumn in New York,'' in Interview magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
