<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2     07-25 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 30,
2000. If you have questions about stories, call 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   THE FOLLOWING STORIES WILL MOVE IN THE `E' CATEGORY FOR RELEASE
SUNDAY, JULY 30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAGE ONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-CLIBURN (Fort Worth, Texas) _ It's 2 a.m. and Michael
Kimmelman is interviewing Van Cliburn at home, where Cliburn is
playing Chopin on an out-of-tune Steinway. Cliburn sings while he
plays and Kimmelman describes the room, the house, the sound,
Cliburn's hands, the picture of his mother, the view of the city.
``Want to hear the F major?'' Cliburn asks. Kimmelman lets readers
attend this very private concert and interview. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-ART (Undated) _ When Deborah Solomon signed on to
www.eBay.com, there were listings for 37,814 fine-art objects _
everything from a signed Christo photograph to a work identified as
``Artist Has Same Astrology Chart as Picasso $50.'' Ten days later,
she had a taste of auctionitis and received the victorious message:
``You won the Vasarely litho.'' The price was $225 for a signed,
framed and numbered print purchased from a dentist in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-SHAKESPEARE-UTAH (Cedar City, Utah) _ As many as 155,000
theatergoers surge into Cedar City, Utah, each summer for the Utah
Shakespeare Festival. The festival began in 1962 with $1,000. Now
it has a $5 million budget and this year won a Tony award for
regional theater. The afternoon that theater executives returned
from New York after the Tony ceremony, the 350 members of the
festival's company and 400 volunteers passed the award from one
person to another. It was a moving moment, especially for those who
years ago had tried to make it in New York and didn't. By Bernard
Weinraub. &QL; 
 &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-LINCOLN-CENTER (New York) _ When Leonard de Paur became
Lincoln Center's director of community relations in 1970, two
things concerned him: the lack of community participation in the
center's activities and the vast, empty plazas. He created a
program that solved both problems _ Lincoln Center Out of Doors.
Now two years after his death, the festival, which starts Aug. 5
and runs through Aug. 29, draws an audience of 200,000. By Valerie
Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WENDERS (Undated) _ Wim Wenders' lack of consistency has
resulted in his last few movies' getting spotty releases at best.
His most recent film, ``Million Dollar Hotel'' may be the only film
to feature Mel Gibson in the last 20 years that has gone unreleased
in the actor's biggest market, America. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-AMERICAN-HIGH (Los Angeles) _ Eschewing paid actors,
writer-producers and most of the crew used on such teen dramas as
``Beverly Hills 90210,'' R.J. Cutler set out to illuminate high
school life at about one-third the cost of those series. In 13
half-hour episodes, ``American High'' tells the stories of 14
students at Highland Park, a public high school near Chicago. The
material of ``American High'' came from 2,800 hours of digital
footage, about 70 percent of it shot by two crews and the balance
provided by ``video diaries'' kept by the subjects. In Los Angeles,
six ``loggers'' entered the characters' conflicts and dialogue into
a database. An eight-person story department selected footage to
become episodes. Now the question is, Will American teen-agers want
to watch real teens with less than perfect complexions? Fox will
find out Aug. 2 when the ``non-fiction drama'' premieres. By Andy
Meisler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART/ARCHITECTURE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ART-LONDON (London) _ All over London, the words ``make it new''
have been applied to museums. Through Sept. 17, the National
Gallery is presenting an exhibition in which 24 artists were
invited to choose a painting from the collection and take off from
it however they like. John Russell also recommends seeing the newly
renovated Wallace Collection in Manchester Square; ``The
Holocaust,'' at the Imperial War Museum; and amid the 20th century
masterpieces at the Tate Modern, an awesome video by Bill Viola. On
the left of a screen, a baby is being born second by second; on the
right, an elderly woman in dying breath by breath.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGN-AIRSTREAM (Undated) _ Philip Nobel reviews the Airstream
recreational vehicle and decides that its aversion to styling is
what made the Airstream so good and such a kitschy status symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ART-NELLIGAN (Brunswick, Maine) _ Emily Nelligan's charcoal
drawings are almost all 10 inches wide by 7 inches high and they
all depict the same landscape: Great Cranberry Island in Maine.
Twenty-six of them ring a galley at the Bowdoin College Museum of
Art here. It's one of the few times Nelligan, who has been making
drawings for more than 50 years, has permitted them to be shown
publicly. Nelligan's work has long been a well-kept secret, but no
more. By Deborah Weisgall.
</P>
<P>
   These stories moved in the ``t'' category on Monday, July 24 for
release on Sunday, July 30.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of this week's section is Getting Away, the Dutch Way.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GOLF-NETHERLANDS (Undated) _ The Netherlands has not been
known for golf since the 17th century, when an early form of the
game called kolfspel was played with a wood club on the frozen
canals. The terrain in most places is famously flat, but it has a
handful of world-class courses that offer challenges and beauty. By
Robert Sidorsky.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NETHERLANDS-LEIDEN (Undated) _ With the exception of
Amsterdam, which has a population nearly seven times that of
Leiden, no other city in the Netherlands has such a broad range of
museums and historic sites. Rembrandt was born there. In the 17th
century America's Pilgrim Fathers took refuge in Leiden before
leaving for the New World. The first tulips in Holland (originally
from Turkey) were planted in the university's botanical garden and
imports from the New World _ tomato, potato, tobacco and corn _
were introduced into Northern Europe through Leiden. By Christopher
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COAST-NETHERLANDS (Undated) _ Geraldine Fabrikant got
away from the crowds of Amsterdam to quaint fishing villages on the
coast and other towns in the Netherlands. Marken had a naive charm,
Edam, its prosperous homes and its cheeses. In Volendam there are
boats to watch and koffie verkeerd to drink while watching the
clouds glide by.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-INDIA-SPA (Undated) _ If ever there was an escape from
the heat, dust and noise of India's cities, Ananda is it. Ananda
offers luxury for the sybarite, hiking, squash and rafting for the
athlete and yoga, meditation and Ayurvedic massage therapies for
the stressed out. In a $50 million renovation, Ananda's designers
have grafted an air-conditioned, spa and 75-room hotel, onto a
mahajara's palace. Celia W. Dugger treats readers to the details of
being anointed with warm sesame oil for 45-minutes; the tangy taste
of banana lassis sipped on a deck overlooking the Himalayas and
expert reminders to avoid the monsoon season in August. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK (Undated) _ Bookings are at a nine-year high on Amtrak,
which in recent years has reversed the ``Perils of Pauline'' saga
in which the onrushing train, not the damsel on the tracks, is in
danger. Amtrak has has begun to refer to passengers as ``guests''
and a few weeks ago announced a service guarantee backed up with
free tickets. In the first 15 days, 3 free tickets were given out
for every 1,000 passengers. The free tickets were worth $228,000,
but they paid off. Ticket sales in the same period were $57.6
million, up $8.3 million, or 17 percent, above the same period last
year. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ESSAY (Undated) _ A vacation is a state of mind,
concludes Marialisa Calta, who lives in Vermont with her family.
That explains why as countless vacationers come to Vermont, she
packs up her family and drives 16-hours north to Prince Edward
Island. She goes to get away from laundry, shopping, cooking and
email. They read books and play hearts and come home to stacks of
mail just like everyone who else who goes on vacation. If that's
not enough to convince her that a vacation is a state of mind, a
recent e-mail she received from friends in Prince Edward Island
does. The friends are thinking of taking a vacation _ in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REGULAR FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Of the 10 major United States
airlines, eight either have defibrillators on all their planes
already or expect to by the end of the year. Only Trans World
Airlines and America West have not begun the process, which in
September will be mandatory on all flights carrying 30 passengers
and one flight attendant. In the meantime, two overseas airlines,
British Airways and Virgin Atlantic, which both have defibrillators
on their fleets, announced plans to add an additional medical
device, one that can transmit an electrocardiogram by satellite
from a conscious but ill passenger to a medical enter on the
ground. By Betsy Wade.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated ) _ Suzanne MacNeille answers questions on
birding in Trinidad and Tobago; the 600th anniversary of Chaucer's
death; and travel in Central Brazil. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
