<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-CONCO     07-25 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-CONCORDE-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEFORE TUESDAY, BAD LUCK BUT NO CRASHES FOR CONCORDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Va.)  (With AIRFRANCE-CRASH) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN and MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad luck has plagued the Concorde, the world's only supersonic
passenger jet, from the day it began development as British-French
joint venture in 1962. But until Tuesday there was one area where
its record, by modern aviation standards, was pristine: safety.
</P>
<P>
   The fatal crash of Air France Flight 4590, a charter from Paris
to New York, was the first of a Concorde after more than 30 years
of flying, an unusually long stretch for any type of commercial
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Since Air France and British Airways began scheduled service
between Paris and London and New York in the late 1970s, the
distinct needle-nosed Concorde with its swept-back delta wing has
carried more than 4 million passengers. Its manifest regularly
contains celebrity names from the worlds of business,
entertainment, sports and fashion, who pay as much as $11,000 for a
round-trip ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But the Concorde, hailed as the plane of the future in the
1960s, has become a high-tech orphan. Only 20 were built because
airlines refused to buy them. By today's standards, the Concorde is
too noisy and its engine exhaust is too dirty, which is why it is
barred from flying regularly to all but a handful of airports.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of squeezing into a Concorde seat, which offers
less room than business class on slower jets like the Boeing 777,
in addition to rubbing elbows with the elite, is the ability to
cruise at 1,350 mph 11 miles above the earth, twice as fast and
twice as high as typical subsonic jetliners.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers never feel the weariness of time-zone changes known
as jet lag, boasts Air France, because the trans-Atlantic trip
takes only 3{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years the Concordes in commercial service _ all
built in the 1970s or early 1980s _ had begun to show their age. On
Monday, the two airlines reported that microscopic cracks had been
discovered on the wings of several planes. British Airways took one
out of service but Air France said the cracks posed no threat to
safety.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Tuesday's crash, British Airways suspended
Concorde flights for the day. Air France canceled flights until
further notice.
</P>
<P>
   It is still far too early to conclude why Flight 4590 went down.
There are numerous possibilities, and many may be completely
unrelated to the Concorde's age or its unique design. Indeed, by
the standard of many commercial airplanes, the Concorde is
considered young because each flies less than 1,000 hours annually.
By contrast, there are more than 1,200 Boeing 747s, and they
typically fly thousands of hours a year.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft that crashed Tuesday had only flown 11,989 hours
since it entered service in 1980, according to Air France. The
airline said the jet went through it most recent heavy maintenance
overhaul on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   One difference between the Concorde and other aging planes,
though, is that in models produced by the hundreds over a period of
years, the oldest planes are like sentinels, giving early warning
of problems with the younger ones. But with so few planes built the
Concorde has had no such guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were all built around same period of time, and whatever
happens to one is probably going to happen to all of them, about
the same time,'' said James G. Ladesic, a professor of aerospace
engineering at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Daytona
Beach, Fla. ``It's a little scary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supersonic flight at high altitude also places different
stresses on the Concorde than those experienced by subsonic
aircraft. For example, the rush of passing air on supersonic planes
heats the skin above the boiling point, which can weaken the
airplane's construction.
</P>
<P>
   That may be what happened to a section of the lower rudder on a
British Airways Concorde bound for New York from London that fell
off during a transatlantic flight on Oct. 9, 1998. That plane
landed safely in New York. It is one of several occasions on which
tail pieces have fallen off. In May 1998, a British Airways
Concorde lost a section of an elevon, a device on the tail used to
make the nose point up or down.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Concorde, like other supersonic planes, has a
history of wheel and tire problems, and these can lead to fires.
The Concorde's V-shape optimizes it for flying fast enough to break
the sound barrier but it also requires the planes to fly about 50
percent faster on landing and takeoff than is typical for subsonic
passenger jets.
</P>
<P>
   That heats up the tires. After takeoff, when they are retracted
into the wheel well, which is crammed with hydraulic lines, the
fluid could be in danger of igniting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wheel wells on supersonic airplanes are a pretty tight
fit,'' said Charles N. Eastlake, a professor of aerospace
engineering at Embry-Riddle, who worked for the Air Force for 13
years on the design of the B-1, the F-14 and the F-15 supersonic
jets. ``If you've got a blown tire, and you retract the landing
gear, the shredded parts of blown tire are more certain to hit
something inside the wheel well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That did not appear to be the case in the Air France crash,
since photos of the foundering plane showed the landing gear was
still down.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, after Concordes blew out their tires on four occasions
over 20 months at Dulles and Kennedy International Airports, the
American safety agency, the National Transportation Safety Board,
warned Air France that pilots should not retract landing gear with
blown tires, a practice it said could have ``potentially
catastrophic'' results. The French later advised the safety board
that they had changed procedures, and the recommendation is
recorded by the board as ``closed, no longer applicable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   American aviation experts said Tuesday that the pictures of the
plume of fire behind Flight 4590 might have indicated the
Concorde's use of an afterburner, a feature common on
high-performance fighter jets but unique to a passenger jet. These
devices squirt fuel into the engine exhaust to create quick extra
thrust. If an engine had a mechanical failure, according to one
expert, and the operator continued to operate it, it would provide
far more fuel to burn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's some massive failure in the engine and everything
has turned to mechanical confusion, then the total amount of fuel
there is dramatically bigger,'' said Eastlake, of Embry-Riddle.
</P>
<P>
   But Ladesic pointed out that even if an engine was on fire, it
was not necessarily the cause of the crash. ``There may be other
systems that were affected, such as control systems, or flaps,'' he
said. ``If one is sitting around speculating, any of those could
have caused them to lose their ability to climb.''
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde was conceived at a time when people believed there
would be Pan Am shuttles to the moon by the year 2001. The British
and French reluctantly joined forces to build the supersonic
transport because they feared that the Americans and Russian would
build them, leaving Europe behind.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Americans gave up when Congress cut the
financing in 1971. The Soviet Tupolev 144, which was based on the
design of the Concorde after Soviet agents stole the plans, crashed
famously at the Paris Air Show in 1973, ending that program.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1970s, the Concorde stood alone. The British and
the French needed to sell 300 to recoup their $3 billion
investment. Sixteen airlines had placed orders for 74 of the jets,
which was a promising start. Then oil prices shot up in 1973. The
orders dried up.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde was eventually given to British Airways and Air
France, both then state-owned, but they had trouble finding
destinations because of protests about noise. Scheduled service to
New York finally began in 1977 after the U.S. Supreme Court struck
down a decision by the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey to
ban the jets from landing at Kennedy Airport. British Airways now
also offers regular flights between London and Barbados in the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Controversy about the Concorde has faded in recent years and it
has became a profitable niche for both airlines and the flagship of
their fleets. Though maintenance costs for the jets are four times
as high as what it costs to maintain a subsonic jet, each airline
still makes a profit on the Concorde. Most of the money is made on
the scheduled trans-Atlantic service with about 10 percent of sales
coming from charters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both British Airways and Air France wouldn't fly this plane
for two seconds if it was losing money,'' said Donald L. Pevsner,
an aviation attorney and part-time tour operator who has chartered
the Concorde several times.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to charter it again in June to fly over the Ascension
Islands to view a total eclipse of the sun. ``I've flown it several
hundred times,'' he said. ``I love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
