<HEADER>
A2927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT &LR;      07-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMPAIGN NOT WORRIED BY BUSH'S SELECTION OF CHENEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The intense speculation that had surrounded Gov.
George W. Bush as he selected a running mate swung Tuesday to Vice
President Al Gore amid signs that the Gore camp was relieved and
even joyful at Bush's choice of Dick Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Advisers for the vice president said the selection of Cheney, a
59-year-old oil executive and former defense secretary, gave Gore a
freer hand in picking a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats could hardly believe their luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our side, there was maybe 70 percent relief and 30 percent
glee,'' said James Carville, a Democratic strategist and longtime
adviser to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign quickly mobilized to paint Cheney as far
outside the mainstream, citing his votes against abortion and
against the South African government's release of Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   And speculation here was that the Cheney selection elevated
certain possibilities for Gore, like Sens. John F. Kerry of
Massachusetts and John Edwards of North Carolina
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more people viable now,'' said a Democratic
strategist. ``It probably improves the chances of a `generational'
candidate _ youth, style, the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore met with Warren Christopher, the chairman of his search
committee, at Gore's residence in Washington on Monday night and
Tuesday morning. The vice president's every move is being examined
for its implications in the selection of a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Gore described the meeting as part of his
effort to maintain a dignified process.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters that he was down to a short list but did not
want to divulge any names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only fair to the men and women involved to keep
it private and dignified,'' he said, ``because only one person is
going to be picked and the others will not be, and I want the ones
who are not picked to feel respected and well-treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gore has managed to bump into several of his prospects
along the campaign trail. He attended a fund-raising reception
Tuesday night at the Virginia home of Kerry. On Sunday, he met with
Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut at the Manhattan apartment
of singer Paul Simon. He begins a vacation on Thursday in North
Carolina on an island that is home to Edwards. Sen. Evan Bayh of
Indiana will be vacationing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore had to cancel his appearance at a dinner in Nashville
last week, he asked Sen. Bob Graham of Florida to fill in. After
Christopher met with Gore on Tuesday morning, Christopher met with
Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Harkin would not say whether the 40-minute visit focused on his
selection or someone else's. The senator, who has met with
Christopher before, could help Gore with organized labor, farmers
and the liberal wing of his party, but at 61, he could be perceived
as part of the past and not the future.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the names, and with Bush's selection of Cheney, talk of
former Sen. George Mitchell of Maine has died down. If Bush had
picked a relative newcomer, like Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma,
Gore might have felt the need to pick an older voice of experience,
like Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters believe that Gore already has the experience that
Bush had to seek in a running mate, and some say that frees him to
pick someone with a young and vigorous image.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fabiani, a spokesman for Gore, called Cheney a ``retro''
choice, indicating that Gore wanted someone who speaks to the
future. Chris Lehane, also a Gore spokesman, said the selection
underscored that ``this really is your father's Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush had picked a woman, or someone who could have helped the
Republicans win a critical state, Gore might have felt pressured to
pick someone with the same appeal. Some in the Gore camp were
worried that Bush would pick either Sen. John McCain of Arizona or
Gen. Colin L. Powell, who might have electrified voters in a way
that would have been difficult for Gore to counter.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, those close to the Gore campaign said, the choice of
an older white man who brings little charisma to the ticket and
whose home state of Wyoming was already in the Republican column,
means that Gore does not have to match a particular quality or
region or find a political superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Allan J. Lichtman, an specialist on presidential politics at
American University, said: ``This gives Gore an absolute free shot,
politically. It puts no pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a Democratic consultant, said that the Cheney
choice could even provide some momentum to Gore's candidacy. He
said that Cheney's past heart problems prompted a flurry of stories
about his health, thus squandering a chance for a boost.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is retreating from its earlier consideration
of trying to cut into Bush's ``bounce'' from the Republican
convention by announcing the Democratic running mate shortly after
the Republicans leave Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, one possibility was to set a date the following week in
which Gore would announce his choice, a process that advisers said
would bring more dignity to the selection.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts, the Democratic
nominee in 1988, said in an interview that the choice of Cheney
``should not make one particle of difference'' for Gore. Whatever
Bush's choice, Dukakis said, Gore is still under obligation to pick
someone who could step into the job of president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really have a free hand,'' Dukakis said. ``You
still fundamentally have to pick someone who really shines as a
potential president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
