<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2930 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-GEORGIA-SENATE0726-CO     07-25 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-SENATE0726-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   By Kathey Pruitt
</P>
<P>
   and Mark Sherman
</P>
<P>
   C. 2000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Georgia's eight congressional Republicans met among
themselves and with national party leaders Tuesday. But after
daylong talks they couldn't settle on a candidate to take on U.S.
Senate appointee Zell Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Three members of the House GOP delegation are considered among
the best hopes for their party to regain the seat held by the late
U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell, who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   But Reps. Bob Barr of Smyrna, Saxby Chambliss of Macon and Jack
Kingston of Savannah were not ready to declare themselves
candidates the day after Democrats called Miller out of retirement
to fill the vacancy temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of a special nonpartisan election Nov. 7 will fill
out the remaining four years of Coverdell's term. The three-day
candidate qualifying period begins next Wednesday. Miller has said
he will run.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Johnny Isakson of Marietta, one of the most discussed
potential Republican challengers, said Tuesday he will not run for
the seat.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson admitted the race was a temptation. But he said he had
to honor commitments he made when he won his 6th District seat in a
special election last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a man allows his ego to override his good judgment
and commitments to others, he is no longer a public servant,''
Isakson said. ``He is just a politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's appointment reduces the Senate's Republican majority to
54-46. The popular former governor is headed to Washington as early
as this afternoon, where he will be sworn in Thursday. He is
expected to begin assembling a staff immediately and could cast his
first Senate vote by Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Republican leaders in Georgia say, they hope to
have decided on a single candidate to reclaim Coverdell's seat.
Sen. Mitch McConnell, chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Campaign Committee, met with the Georgia delegation
Tuesday. He acknowledged a quick resolution is needed ``because of
the absence of time'' before the special election.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans criticized state officials' decision to set
candidate qualifying for next week, Aug. 2-4, during the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Cathy Cox said the qualifying period needs to
begin as soon as possible since the election is only three months
away. And candidates don't have to be present to register.
</P>
<P>
   But state Republican Chairman Chuck Clay called it ``bully
politics at its worst.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They absolutely want to make it as difficult as possible for
us,'' Clay said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republicans initially have deferred to the congressional
delegation for possible candidates. Reps. Charlie Norwood of Evans
and Mac Collins of Hampton also have said they won't run.
</P>
<P>
   For those evaluating a bid, there are other uncertainties.
Chambliss, for example, met privately with the Senate leadership as
well as House Speaker Dennis Hastert, who would be concerned about
the Republicans' ability to hold onto Chambliss' House seat if he
leaves to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the congressional delegation, Georgia Republicans
have a limited pool of candidates that could immediately mount a
statewide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the possibilities are former Georgia Attorney General
Mike Bowers, former U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich and Atlanta
businessman Guy Millner, none of whom has publicly expressed
interest in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Mack Mattingly, the last Georgia Republican to serve in the U.S.
Senate before Coverdell, is among the few remaining potential
candidates with statewide experience.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
