<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: NUCLEAR PLANT CANCELED
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit canceled plans for Turkey's first
nuclear plant, saying that the $5 billion facility would have
imposed a heavy economic burden on the country at a time when the
government is fighting a deficit. Environmental groups had warned
that the proposed location of the plant, on the southern
Mediterranean coast near Mersin, was near an earthquake fault.
</P>
<P>
   THE VATICAN: AN APPEAL TO VIRGINA John Paul II has asked the
governor of Virginia to stop the execution of Rocco Barnabei, 33,
who is on death row for the 1994 murder of his fiancee, the Vatican
said. Barnabei's mother, Jane Barnabei, met with Vatican officials
last week.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: REBELS CLAIM ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   A guerrilla group claimed responsibility for an attack on a
roadside office of the federal police outside Mexico City that left
one officer with minor wounds and two children with cuts from
flying glass. The Revolutionary Armed Forces of the People said in
a statement that the attack was meant to show that insurrection
remained a valid strategy despite the governing party's defeat in
presidential voting.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: PLAN FOR WATER SYSTEM
</P>
<P>
   Two months after a deadly strain of E. coli bacteria killed at
least 7 people and sickened 2,000 in Walkerton, Ontario, provincial
environmental officials have abandoned attempts to clean the town's
water system and will replace 5.5 miles of water pipes. The old
cast-iron piping ``cannot effectively be swabbed as part of the
continuing decontamination program,'' the Environment Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   IVORY COAST: NEW CONSTITUTION
</P>
<P>
   A new Constitution was approved by 86.53 percent of voters,
according to final results released by the military government. The
turnout was 56 percent. The draft constitution had been endorsed by
all major parties, including the Rally of Republicans led by
Alassane Ouattara. Many believe its strict nationality rules were
intended to exclude Ouattara from running for president, but
Ouattara, a former prime minister, has said he meets all the
requirements to run.
</P>
</TEXT>
