<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2939 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-$ADV30-     07-25 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-$ADV30-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYING WHEN HE WANTS, AND REMEMBERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 30)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's 2 a.m., the middle of the day for Van
Cliburn, who gets up when most people go to bed, and he's at the
piano in his living room, playing Chopin ballades. He starts the
Ballade in F minor, skips to the middle, then to the coda, nodding
to show how he keeps the same tempo. He does the same with the
Ballade in G minor. ``Want to hear the F major?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, if he must.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn will perform Tchaikovsky's Piano Concerto in B flat
minor with Seiji Ozawa and the Boston Symphony at the Tanglewood
Festival in Lenox, Mass., on Friday. He gives a dozen or so
concerts a year instead of the hundred he used to give, year in,
year out, for 20 years, a schedule that finally wore him down.
</P>
<P>
   Except for gray hair and a few lines, he still looks pretty much
as he did on the cover of his famous recording of the Tchaikovsky
with Kirill Kondrashin and the RCA Symphony Orchestra, which was
the first classical LP to sell a million copies. Americans who
owned no other classical recording bought that album. That was in
1958, the year he won the Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow and got
a ticker-tape parade in New York. A ticker-tape parade for a
classical musician. Think about that for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, last month America's musical golden boy turned 66.
Think about that, too.
</P>
<P>
   I might mention that he sings while he plays the ballades.
Loudly. Nicely. He has sung at church since childhood. Another
reason he says he quit giving concerts for about 10 years was to
give himself more time to go to the opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every composer the most admired instrument is the human
voice,'' he says. ``My mother would make me sight-sing before I
would play any piece to cement in me the realization that striking
the keys is not a digital or mechanical thing. The goal is to make
a singing sound, to let the sound penetrate the air like a human
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   His piano, a nine-foot Steinway covered with silver-framed
photographs, is completely out of tune. Out of tune like a
summer-camp piano during off-season. Steinway's chief technician,
Ron Coners, has offered to come and tune Cliburn's piano. But
Cliburn doesn't mind it the way it is. Most pianists obsess about
pianos. He doesn't obsess.
</P>
<P>
   That he hits a few wrong notes while he plays may be taken as a
sign of great generosity. He's not performing. This is a chat at
the keyboard, and there's no vanity on display here. There's no
vanity about Cliburn at all. He is comically modest. It's as
impossible for him to speak flatteringly about himself as it is to
hint at something even remotely critical about anyone else. He is
charming and at the same time withholding, and this combination can
make him seem vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   What's most remarkable about how he plays the ballades is the
sound. It's the old Cliburn sound, huge and sculptured, the bass
and top voices booming out to fill a concert hall, which this
living room virtually is. The room, the house, the sound, Cliburn's
hands, the picture of his mother on a placard from a concert she
gave that is in the next room, the view of the city that stretches
out below the house, the accumulated history: everything here is
Texas-scale.
</P>
<P>
   Fame, on this scale, is always a target. When his energy lagged
and his playing declined in the late 1970s, before his sabbatical,
the daggers came out. He couldn't handle the spotlight after all.
He hadn't learned enough repertory to sustain a long-term career.
He was spinning his wheels. The Tchaikovsky concerto again? An
entertainer for the masses, he was talented, sure, but where would
he have been without the Cold War and the boyish, squeaky-clean
looks and his genius impresario, Sol Hurok? With all the other good
pianists in the world, Cliburn was lucky.
</P>
<P>
   So, for the record: he was from the start a phenomenal, natural
musician, as every other pianist recognized. Prolific enough in the
standard repertory. He played or recorded Beethoven's Third, Fourth
and Fifth Piano Concertos, Rachmaninoff's Second and Third
Concertos and Rhapsody on a Theme of Paganini, both Brahms
concertos, both Liszt concertos, Chopin's First, MacDowell's
Second, the Schumann, the Grieg, Mozart's C major (K. 503),
Prokofiev's Third. Shall we go on?
</P>
<P>
   Standards vary. A pianist like Arturo Benedetti Michelangeli,
playing a mix of less conventional and familiar music, had a
minuscule performing repertory, but that was considered a sign of
his perfectionism. When he canceled concerts, people used words
like ``elusive'' and ``enigma.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn always was the opposite of a shallow showboat. When
other young American pianists of his generation were perfecting a
midcentury style of bloodless technique, he was an instinctive,
honest, ardent player of absolute control, the model of modern
musicianship. Listen to the recordings. Rock-solid beat. Minimum of
rubato. Moderate-to-slow tempos. Architectural solidity, which gets
back to his point about the ballades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much rubato is a big mistake, especially with Romantic
music,'' he says. ``It's the opposite of what people assume.
Rachmaninoff said that if you play a passage very evenly and more
slowly than you think it should be played, then it will sound fast,
and he was right. If I try to play faster than I can hear the
notes, then I'm finished. You can't let the horse ride you. That's
what my mother taught me, and it's what Friedheim taught her.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Friedheim is the key. Although Cliburn became known as a
pupil of Rosina Lhevinne, the famous Russian pianist and Juilliard
teacher, she came along late in his development. His mother, Rildia
Bee O'Bryan, a gifted player, made him what he was at the keyboard
before he arrived at the Juilliard School. She, in turn, had
studied with Friedheim, who studied with Anton Rubinstein and
Liszt, so Cliburn is, among other things, a straight descendant of
the two great figures of 19th-century pianism.
</P>
<P>
   Friedheim's legacy was to promote Liszt's Classicism. Friedheim
played in an Apollonian style: long lines, direct expression,
beautiful tone. ``Friedheim always told my mother that music has to
be nearly metronomic if the lines are to be long and the effect is
to be like a singer singing,'' Cliburn says. ``And so that's what
my mother drilled into me.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it surprising that what first impressed the Russians at the
Tchaikovsky Competition was how Cliburn played not Russian music
but Bach and Mozart? He hardly plays them in public anymore. At
Juilliard, the faculty jury for his graduation recital heard him
perform Brahms' F minor Sonata and Hindemith's Third Sonata, but
those works didn't make it into his concert repertory, either.
Neither did Schubert's B flat Sonata or D major Sonata, which
Lhevinne encouraged him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 18 or 19, I went through a vast amount of the piano
literature,'' Cliburn says. ``But I felt if I were to have a
career, I would not be a musicologist: I had no desire to play all
the works of anyone. I decided what I could do well and stuck to
that. I'm very realistic about myself, where I have flaws, what I
really don't do well.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds: ``I play what I feel most comfortable with, but this
doesn't mean that I am not very anxious when I perform. I am always
anxious. Rarely have I ever been happy with anything I've done on
stage.'' That's a curious thing to say, even considering how
artists typically demur.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Cliburn spoke to a group of amateur pianists taking
part in a competition here run by the Cliburn Foundation. (He has
even less to do with that contest than with the professional one
named after him, but he lends his name and talks to the players,
which turns out to be plenty.) He told the amateurs that the stage
is the loneliest place he knows, and he said pianists spend their
lives preparing music only to walk before an audience and not have
the slightest guarantee of what will happen. This may be true, but
it is not exactly a love sonnet to concert life.
</P>
<P>
   This year's amateurs heard a fable about music besting painting
among the arts because it is intangible and indestructible _ like
memory, Cliburn said. At least memories last.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
