<HEADLINE>
CONCORDE CRASH STUNS AEROSPACE INDUSTRY GATHERED AT AIR SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARNBOROUGH, England _ The Concorde has been a popular visitor
over the years at the Farnborough International air show, and the
first-ever crash of the supersonic jet stunned the world's
aerospace industry gathered here this week.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the crash broke in midafternoon, while fighter jets were
making their daily demonstration flights over the air show.
</P>
<P>
   Some show participants had already returned to London, which is
about 50 minutes from Farnborough by train. But most were still at
the air show, and they gathered around TV sets at the media center
and in the chalets to watch news reports of the crash. Suddenly,
the business of the show did not seem so important.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that organizers might approve a memorial
fly-by Wednesday by some of the planes that fly daily at the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde, flagship of British Airways, has a very special
place in the hearts of people in England, which jointly built the
plane with France. When one of the jets flies over the city in late
afternoon after a flight from Kennedy airport in New York to
Heathrow, people look up to follow the graceful plane.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde can still turn heads, even though it has been in
service for nearly three decades.
</P>
<P>
   But the crash was personal for many at Farnborough.
</P>
<P>
   The European Aeronautical Defense &AMP; Space Agency (EADS) and BAE
Systems are joint manufacturers of the Concorde, and both have a
large presence at Farnborough, as does Rolls-Royce, which makes the
Concorde engines.
</P>
<P>
   The EADS chalet became a crisis headquarters Tuesday night for
dealing with the crash.
</P>
<P>
   BAE Systems and EADS provide technical support for the Concorde
fleet of 13 planes. They issued a joint statement from Farnborough
that said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that a Concorde operated by Air France was involved
in an accident shortly after take-off. The special flight, AF4590,
was operating from Paris to New York for a German operator.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its prestige and technological achievement, Concorde was
a financial white elephant. The production run was halted after
only 20 airplanes. The mistakes of the Concorde program have been
recalled in stories and in discussions at the air show this week
about the next great European aeronautical venture _ the Airbus
A3XX superjumbo.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, whose roots go back to the Concorde, says things will be
different this time.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde project began in 1962 when France and Great Britain
signed a historic agreement to work together for the first time to
manufacture an aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus did not yet exist, but two of the companies involved in
the project, British Aircraft and Sud-Aviation, a leading aircraft
manufacturer in the south of France, later became the initial
partners in the Airbus program before companies in Spain and
Germany joined.
</P>
<P>
   The French company later became Aerospatiale, which is now part
of EADS. British Aircraft became British Aerospace, which is now
BAE Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus was formed in 1969. Earlier that year, the Anglo-French
Concorde prototype made its first flight at the Aerospatiale
airfield in Toulouse, which became the headquarters of Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   The French-built Concorde was manufactured in the same building
at the Toulouse airport where today Airbus builds its A320
single-aisle jets.
</P>
<P>
   Henri Ziegler, who had commanded the Free French Air Force in
World War II, headed the newly created Airbus consortium. It had
been Ziegler who pushed hard for the Concorde project and lobbied
U.S. airlines to buy the jet.
</P>
<P>
   They did, taking more than two dozen options on the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which was developing its own supersonic passenger plane
before the funding was canceled by Congress, was one of the early
opponents of the Concorde. When Pan American, the launch customer
for the 747, canceled its order for the Concorde, other American
carriers followed. Without American markets, Concorde's fate was
sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the battle is over the A3XX. Boeing is trying to persuade
airlines to forgo the Airbus plane for a stretch version of the
747.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
