<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2941 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-$ADV30-     07-25 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLIBURN-$ADV30-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
Fort Worth, Texas: memories last.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You hang on to a moment here or there that's acceptable,'' he
said about recollecting his past performances, ``but I don't know
the experience of being fully satisfied. I remember being asked to
approve a live recording of the Third Rachmaninoff, which I knew
had something good about it, but I couldn't stop feeling upset by
the smudges. Recording makes me nervous. It's enough to deal with
an audience. It was 10 years before I let the tape of the
Rachmaninoff Second Sonata go.'' Which, of course, is now regarded
as one of his best recordings.
</P>
<P>
   He describes hearing William Kapell play Rachmaninoff's Rhapsody
on a Theme of Paganini at Lewisohn Stadium in New York in 1953,
just before Kapell was killed in a plane crash. Cliburn didn't see
the point even of learning the piece after that performance,
declining invitations to play it for years, until Eugene Ormandy,
his friend, who had conducted Rachmaninoff playing it, finally
coaxed him in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   He did it partly to be accommodating. That has been his problem
sometimes. When people have clamored to hear him play what he is
already famous for, he has. Critics who have heard the Tchaikovsky
concerto over and over again may be bored by it, but most people
rarely hear it live and will get to hear Cliburn play it live only
once. And he has known that.
</P>
<P>
   It's nearly 4 a.m. now, and he is on the sofa, reminiscing,
which can be an uncontrollable phenomenon. Ask him why, after
winning in Moscow, he went to study with Bruno Walter and he
recalls playing the Prokofiev Third on Dimitri Mitropoulos' piano,
then describes what he calls an unremarkable conducting stint in
1963. The stories, although familiar, are to say the least
exceptional, but it's not clear by the end exactly what he learned
from Walter.
</P>
<P>
   Or what he learned from Rosina Lhevinne, which is another
question put to him: ``One of the things I distinctly remember was
being a little early for a lesson and she was playing, and I opened
the double doors to the studio and heard her play Chopin's `Aeolian
Harp' Etude _ oh my, as if from heaven!'' Yes, but about the
lessons? ``Well, I remember she wanted tempi faster sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   So Cliburn gives the impression of being utterly content now and
not too inclined to excavate the past afresh. He lets on at one
point, as if revealing a deep family secret, that he's thinking
about performing Bach again, the E minor Partita, maybe, and he
floats a program for a scheduled Chopin recital in Boston that is
so preposterously long that it sounds like a fantasy of a young
pianist in the first flush of success _ as if, no matter how
stressful the stage may have been all those years, it is still the
locus of his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   How much is enough for a career?
</P>
<P>
   Only he has the right to say, of course. His place in history is
reserved. Cliburn, who spent years living out of a suitcase in
hotels, a born performer but a private man, having made several
landmark albums, now plays when he wants, if not always at the
level he did when he was young and playing all the time. He lives
in a real house, cooks for pleasure, socializes, does nothing if he
feels like it, goes to the opera, travels constantly without
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Among the mementos on the piano is a snapshot of Vladimir
Ashkenazy, the pianist, who once said: ``Van is what he is; he is
not pretending to be anything else. And there are not so many
people in the world, especially in the artistic world, who are just
as they are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
