<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS &LR;      07-25 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LOSES BID TO CUT MIDEAST DEAL 
 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ President Clinton gambled and lost in his bid to
cut a peace deal between the Israelis and the Palestinians at the
Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   But, ever the optimist, he refused to give up hope that some
kind of settlement might be possible once both sides take time to
mull over the consequences.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 days holed up at the Camp David presidential retreat,
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat, along with Clinton, gave up their monumental search for a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   The talks ended after Arafat apparently refused to budge from
his position that the old walled city and most other parts of east
Jerusalem be placed under Palestinian sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to characterize the collapse of the summit as a
U.S. foreign policy failure. Instead, he portrayed the talks as a
historical meeting that allowed the leaders to at least make some
progress on other key issues that separate them. Those issues
included the final borders of a Palestinian state, the fate of Arab
refugees in the region and Israeli settlers in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the failure to make an agreement they made
real headway,'' Clinton told reporters at the White House. ``In the
last two weeks significant progress was made on the core issues.``
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton had sought an all-encompassing agreement that
would leave few if any issues unresolved in the 52-year-old
Israeli-Palestinian conflict. What he got in the end was only a
pledge from Barak and Arafat to continue working without any
guarantee of future meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ross, Clinton's special Middle East envoy, is scheduled
to visit the region in two weeks to assess whether it might be
possible to revive the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a little bit of reflection,'' said one
senior U.S. official, ``before we try again.``
</P>
<P>
   While both leaders rejected the use of violence to achieve their
goals in a trilateral statement issued with Clinton at the summit's
conclusion, there was no commitment from Arafat not to unilaterally
declare a Palestinian state, as he has threatened to do on Sept. 13
if no settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is concerned that such a declaration
could ignite another Israeli-Palestinian war.
</P>
<P>
   One U.S. official who briefed reporters said Clinton had
emphasized in his final discussions with Arafat the importance of
not doing anything that could touch off violence and lead to a
total breakdown in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   This official said Clinton cautioned that the result would be
loss of U.S. support for the Palestinian cause, which is ultimately
a peaceful settlement that will lead to the establishment of a
separate Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't support unilateral moves. Our focus will continue to
be on good faith negotiations,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the talks, it seemed naive of Clinton to think that
he could overcome the problems separating the two leaders no matter
how long he kept them captive at his rain-soaked retreat in the
Catoctin Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for example, registered strong objections about
convening a summit in the first place. He said in no uncertain
terms that he was not yet ready to make the hard concessions
necessary to strike a deal unless Israel honored previous
commitments concerning scheduled withdrawals from Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader even warned Clinton that anything less
than full sovereignty over east Jerusalem would be unacceptable, a
position he stuck to despite attempts by the president to get him
to accept Israeli and U.S. proposals.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. official described Arafat's unwavering position as
similar to that of the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat, who in
1978 insisted on holding out for the return of all the Sinai desert
during the negotiations with former Israeli President Menachem
Begin and President Carter that yielded the Camp David Accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Arafat's mind, it really came down to swapping land for
peace,'' said this official. ``He felt he was being offered less
than what (the Palestinians) have a right to.``
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton pressed ahead and insisted again on Tuesday
after the summit that forcing the two sides into talks was ``the
right thing to do'' even if it meant dragging Arafat kicking and
screaming to the mountaintop retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was essential for Israelis and Palestinians finally to
begin to deal with the toughest decisions in the peace process,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said both sides now would at least be able to examine their
options more objectively as they pursue the ultimate goal of peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clock is still working against us,'' he said referring to
the Sept. 13 deadline that both sides have imposed for completing a
deal and that Arafat has set as the date he will declare a
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is we don't have a deal. The good news is they
are fully and completely and comprehensively engaged in an official
way for the first time on these fundamental issues,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Saeb Erekat, one of Arafat's chief aides, agreed, telling
reporters that Clinton's effort had made both sides realize ``more
than ever what it takes to make a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the exhaustive discussions on Jerusalem had also yielded
a view that it might be possible for the city to serve as the
capital for both Israel and a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem will stand as the capital of the state of Palestine
and the state of Israel. Jerusalem will be the place of freedom for
all,'' he said, adding that the prospects for negotiations to
succeed are much better now than before Clinton convened the
summit.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that the two sides are still far from an
agreement and not likely to get one if each continues to accuse the
other of being intractable.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for example, blamed Arafat for the summit's collapse,
accusing him of not being ready to make the kind of sacrifices
necessary to make peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat was afraid to take the necessary, historical
responsibility at this moment to bring about an end of the
conflict. The positions of Arafat on Jerusalem were those that
prevented the achievement of an agreement,'' Barak said at a news
conference following the talks.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, he seemed to harden his own positions, saying that
none of the progress made in the talks on other issues would be
``binding'' or used as a starting point if and when future
negotiations occur.
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed to suggest that he had given all he can by
conceding a number of Arab neighborhoods in east Jerusalem to
Palestinian control and would not be able to move further toward
Arafat's demand that all of the old walled city be placed under
Palestinian sovereignty as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we must go to confrontation, we will be able to look our
children in the eye and say, we did everything, everything to
prevent a confrontation,'' he added, in apparent reference to
Arafat's threat to declare a Palestinian state in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had offered as a final negotiating position parts of Arab
east Jerusalem. But the Palestinians insisted on full sovereignty
over all of east Jerusalem, including the OLD City. The only
exception they made was the city's Jewish quarter and the Western
Wall, which is Judaism's holiest site.
</P>
<P>
   In convening the talks, Clinton faced a difficult task not only
in trying to get the two sides to put aside deep religious and
cultural differences, but in getting them to disregard political
fallout at home in order to make difficult choices.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the summit, both leaders kept a watchful eye on
public opinion back in the region and may have adjusted their
positions during the summit because of it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
