<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2955 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONCORDE-PLANE0726-CO     07-25 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-PLANE0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concorde, Air France have ties to Atlanta aviation community
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    and Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Traffic came to a halt around Hartsfield International
Airport as the Concorde taxied to the runway for its first-ever
takeoff from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of cars pulled over on roadsides and airplanes paused on
ramps so occupants could watch one of the most impressive
spectacles in aviation. It was an overcast day in October 1985, and
members of the Skylarks, an Atlanta travel club, had chartered the
luxury plane for a trip to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilot came on the public address system and announced
that, since there were so many observers, he planned to make a
rather 'sporty' takeoff,'' remembers Hamp Vason, co-founder of the
Skylarks. ``Let me tell you, that was one dramatic way to leave
town. What a thrilling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The symbol of European aerospace prowess leapt into the clouds
with its four afterburning jets roaring, then streaked into the
blue sky thousands of feet above. The plane stopped in New York,
then continued to London.
</P>
<P>
   Another chartered Concorde landed here in 1997 carrying European
vacationers on an around-the-world dash.
</P>
<P>
   Air France also has Atlanta ties.
</P>
<P>
   Air France and Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines headline an
alliance of international airlines, called SkyTeam, whose members
sell seats on some of each others' flights. The agreement does not
allow Delta to book seats on Air France's Concorde flights, though.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman said Tuesday the airline has hoped to expand
the ``code share'' deal to include Concorde flights. He added it is
too soon to say how Tuesday's crash might affect those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Air France jointly sell seats on trans-Atlantic
flights by regular jets, including those operated by the two
carriers between Atlanta and Paris. Delta also books passengers on
certain Air France flights from Paris to other parts of Europe, and
Air France does the same on some Delta domestic flights.
</P>
<P>
   Such alliances have become common over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The supersonic Concorde's visits to Atlanta demonstrate the
public fascination, economic obstacles and environmental
controversies the Concorde has evoked during its 31 years of
flight. Protesters and city officials almost blocked the 1985 trip
over concerns about noise. And the 1997 event was nearly canceled
when organizers couldn't sell enough tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde has been a perennial money loser for Air France and
British Airways even though almost all 100 of each flight's seats
are typically filled by passengers paying nearly $10,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Gourmet meals, unsurpassed customer service and posh terminals
cut into operating margins. Spare parts are increasingly rare and
costly. And the plane's extraordinary speed of 1,350 mph comes at a
price: The Concorde is a gas guzzler.
</P>
<P>
   Each Concorde burns more than its own weight in fuel during
every trans-Atlantic crossing. That's more than a B747-400, which
travels at slightly less than half the Concorde's speed but can
transport four times as many people and far more cargo.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde had never had a fatal accident before Tuesday. But
a former flight dispatcher for Air France said the planes fly at
the edge of their aerodynamic capabilities all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Each plane takes off at its maximum weight in order to carry
enough fuel to cross the Atlantic, and the flight engineer must
constantly shift fuel among 11 tanks to keep the plane balanced.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the aerodynamic characteristics of the Concorde's
triangle-shaped delta wing make it unstable at slow speeds _
especially in a situation like the Paris crash, when one or more
engines apparently failed on takeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Concorde wings don't have slats on the leading edges or
traditional flaps on the trailing edges to aid low-speed handling.
And the plane's downward sloping nose has been known to interrupt
air flow over the tail during takeoff and landing.
</P>
<P>
   When the plane operates normally, however, it is a marvel.
</P>
<P>
   A Concorde typically flies at altitudes up to 60,000 feet _
about twice that of most passenger jets. And it takes just three
hours, 23 minutes to fly from New York to Paris. Flying the
opposite direction takes three hours, 45 minutes against prevailing
winds.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers say the cabin noise level is slightly higher than on
other aircraft, and passengers sit two-abreast on both sides of a
narrow aisle. But there are typically six flight attendants on each
plane, or one for every 17 passengers, and service is unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flying has been a big part of my life, and the Concorde was my
only chance to go supersonic,'' said the Skylarks' Vason, 70, a
former Air Force bomber and transport pilot. ``I imagine (Tuesday's
crash) will be the end of the Concorde program, and I find that
very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
