<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2956 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-W     07-25 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST SUMMIT ENDS WITHOUT AN AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs for rewriting throughout)  
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT2,3,10,18,19,20 _ are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At the end of two weeks of marathon negotiations
with the leaders of Israel and the Palestinians, a visibly fatigued
President Clinton announced on Tuesday that they were unable to
reach an agreement ``at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and other American mediators made clear that it
was Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, who balked in the end,
and by all accounts the issue was Jerusalem, the holy city both
Israelis and Palestinians claim as their sacred capital.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the White House, Clinton singled out the Israeli
prime minister, Ehud Barak, for his readiness to make hard
compromises. ``I would be making a mistake not to praise Barak,
because I think he took a big risk,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He also declared that the discussions at Camp David had been
``really unprecedented'' in raising issues ``that had long been
considered off limits.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Jerusalem in particular had never been discussed
before by Palestinians and Israelis in face-to-face encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the operating rules that nothing is agreed until
everything is agreed, they are of course not bound by any proposal
discussed at the summit,'' Clinton said. ``However, while we did
not get an agreement, significant progress was made on the core
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton convened the summit in an ambitious attempt to reach a
sweeping settlement before Sept. 13 on questions _ such as the
shape of a new Palestinian state, the future Palestinian refugees _
that have kept the two sides in a state of conflict for 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   None of the sides announced any immediate plans to resume talks,
and Arafat's declared intention to unilaterally proclaim a
Palestinian state on Sept. 13 imposed the next serious deadline on
a process that has see-sawed from hope to despair and back since
the Oslo agreements were signed in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In a somber parting statement, Barak laid the full blame for the
setback on Arafat, and declared that Israel was prepared for
``every possibility.'' But he did not exclude another try: ``The
vision of peace suffered a major blow, but I believe that with good
faith, good will on all sides it can recuperate.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat made no comment before departing. But his chief
negotiators, Saeb Erekat and Mahmoud Abbas _ more commonly known as
Abu Mazen _ put an unexpectedly optimistic face on Camp David,
saying that the negotiations had laid groundwork for an agreement
by Sept. 13. ``What happened at Camp David are seeds that will grow
every fast,'' said Abu Mazen.
</P>
<P>
   The two-week sequestered talks at Camp David, which included
round the clock negotiations _ much of the time with Clinton as
mediator and go-between, as well as threatened walkouts and at
least one narrowly averted breakdown, marked one of the most
intensive mediating efforts by an American president in the Middle
East since Jimmy Carter brokered a peace between Israel and Egypt
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, it was hardly surprising, Clinton said, that
the summit, with its qualities of an almost brutal showdown in
close quarters, had not produced what he wanted. ``This is like
going to the dentist without have your gums deadened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, the Israeli and Palestinian leaders left the rainy
hills of Maryland for the Middle East confronting the potential for
increased violence and political uncertainty _ particularly in
Israel, where Barak faces criticism for considering concessions to
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the comprehensive agreement the White House had hoped
for, the summit concluded with a five-point statement of
``negotiating principles'' agreed to by the Israelis, the
Palestinians and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The document said that the two sides understood the ``importance
of avoiding unilateral actions that prejudge the outcome of
negotiations'' and that differences would be resolved ``only by
good faith negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   More particularly, the national security adviser, Sandy Berger,
said it was Arafat who had a lot of thinking to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak was far more willing to think out of the box, far more
willing to consider, though he never accepted, solutions that could
have broken the log jam,'' Berger said. ``Arafat on the other hand,
while he did make some compromises on Jerusalem, was not prepared
at this point to crack open his traditional positions.''
</P>
<P>
   A best hope, Berger said was that the summit would provoke a
reassessment within the Palestinian delegation, a group of about a
dozen of Arafat's top political and security aides.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with the last days of the summit, the Egyptian
president, Hosni Mubarak, met with other Arab leaders in the Middle
East in a spurt of diplomacy, the goals of which were unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior administration official said Mubarak did not help
Arafat reach the bold decisions that the White House wanted. ``I
didn't see any evidence that a positive influence was being brought
to bear,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   According to officials involved in the negotiations, the
prospects for an accord finally fell apart just after midnight
Monday night, the second all-night session that Clinton had led
since returning to Camp David from Japan on Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday nights, Clinton worked with negotiators
from both sides and progress was reported on the borders of a
Palestinian state, on the fate of the three million Palestinian
refugees scattered through the Middle East and on security
arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it came down to whether we could cut the Gordian knot on
Jerusalem,'' a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   For what turned out to be the last effort by the president to
get the Palestinians to agree to a deal on Jerusalem, Clinton met
with Arafat sometime after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Barak had made what the administration regarded as
considerable concessions in relinquishing control to the
Palestinians in the outer and inner suburbs of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The administration declined to go into precise details on
Tuesday, but in the last week of the summit, according to Israeli
reports, proposals were put forward by the Americans on concepts of
shared sovereignty in East Jerusalem. Barak was considering these
ideas which represented a radical departure from established
Israeli policy that Jerusalem was the united, undivided capital of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the ideas raised by the president were
far-reaching and justified a kind of positive response from Arafat.
They didn't,'' Barak told a news conference before is departure.
</P>
<P>
   But when Clinton spoke with the Palestinian leader, Arafat was
unwilling to budge from his position that East Jerusalem must be
the capital of the new Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The question of sovereignty over the holy sites in Jerusalem,
home to major places of worship for Jews, Christians and Moslems,
was at the heart of the problem, the administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of Jerusalem as four concentric circles,'' said the
official. ``Outer suburbs, inner suburbs, the Old City and the
religious sites. As you move into the center, the issues become
more intense, historical, religious.'' There was surprising
convergence on how different parts of the city would be managed,
but severe disagreement on the notion of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   In that last conversation between Clinton and Arafat while the
talks were still alive, Clinton tried to explain, once again, the
advantage for Arafat in making a compromise on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president described one again what was at stake: gaining a
state, international legitimacy, international economic support,''
the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if Arafat let an agreement pass by he could declare
a state, but it would be on 40 percent of the West Bank, and the
Israeli reaction would be strong _ possibly the forcible annexation
of the Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   After Arafat rebuffed Clinton, the president's senior aides _
Berger, the secretary of state, Madeleine K. Albright, and the
senior co-ordinator for the Middle East, Dennis Ross _ met with one
of the Palestinian's negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed, for one last time, the possibility of Arafat
accepting a partial agreement which would deal with the shape of a
Palestinian state, refugees and other matters but put the question
of Jerusalem aside for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   This last effort did not appeal to Arafat either, who, according
to the administration's account, felt he would lose some of his
leverage over Jerusalem if he settled on the other issues first.
</P>
<P>
   AT 3 a.m., Arafat, ensconsed in his cabin, called ``Birch,''
sent one of his negotiators to Clinton with a letter. The letter
politely thanked Clinton for his efforts but said that Arafat could
not accept the proposal on Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
