<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2968 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-AMAZON-GALLI-SPI &LR;      07-25 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-GALLI-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM PRESIDENT RESIGNS UNEXPECTEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK and KATHY MULADY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When Joseph Galli joined Amazon.com as president and
chief operating officer last June, the former Black &AMP; Decker
executive said he was looking forward to ``making history'' at the
Seattle online superstore.
</P>
<P>
   But Galli Tuesday became a short chapter in the Amazon.com
history books.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected move, the 42-year-old executive announced his
resignation from Amazon.com and said he would become chief
executive of Horsham, Pa.-based VerticalNet. He worked at
Amazon.com 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me this is just a great, great career move,'' Galli said.
``It is not about the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Galli's departure came a day before Amazon.com and VerticalNet
are expected to announce second quarter earnings. It also comes one
month after Galli received a $3 million one-year-anniversary cash
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the president of a company resigns it does raise
questions,'' said Todd Weller, an analyst at Legg Mason Wood
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Banc of America Securities analyst Tom Courtney expressed
concern. He cut Amazon's stock rating from ``strong buy'' to
``buy'' and withdrew his $80 per share price target saying that he
has ``lost some confidence'' in the company's growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com fell as much as 14 percent in early trading, hitting
a low of $33.25 before rebounding to close at $37.63, down $1.13
for the day. VerticalNet, which has lost more than half its value
in the past four months, climbed 63 cents to close at $57.38. On
the day Galli joined Amazon.com last summer, the company's stock
closed at $56.81.
</P>
<P>
   Galli earned $200,000 a year in salary at Amazon.com, but also
received a $3 million signing bonus, and a one-year bonus of $3
million on his anniversary at the end of last month. He would have
received another $2 million if he had stayed one more year. Galli's
original incentive package also included options to purchase 1.47
million shares through 2009 and 2.45 million shares from 2009 to
2019 at $57.95 a share. As a result of the resignation, Galli will
forfeit his Amazon.com stock option package. Under the terms of his
employment agreement, Galli will have to pay back about $250,000 of
the $3 million signing bonus he received on his first anniversary.
Galli also will give up his board seat at Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Galli's lucrative bonus package, Weller said: ``I
bet Amazon is not too happy about that.'' Galli, who did not
disclose his compensation package at VerticalNet, said he fully
expects Amazon.com to honor the terms of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   A Pittsburgh native who spent 19 years at Black &AMP; Decker in
Maryland, Galli said he wanted to return to the East Coast where
his family still resides. Galli's children live near Baltimore,
about an hour and half drive from VerticalNet's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sad to leave Amazon and Jeff Bezos was very good to me,''
said Galli, in a conference call. ``I can't think of having a
better mentor in the new economy than Jeff.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, Galli started discussing his family
situation with Bezos and indicated that he might want to leave the
company. When he was offered the CEO position at VerticalNet, which
is located in a Philadelphia suburb, Galli said it was the perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hagan, VerticalNet's co-founder and chief operating,
said the company was not actively looking for a CEO. But when the
executive team met Galli for the first time earlier this year, he
said there was instant chemistry and they decided to ``make room on
the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are a professional football team and you see a great
player on the draft board, you have to grab him,'' Hagan said.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message to employees, Amazon.com chief executive
Jeff Bezos said he wishes Galli all the best in his new pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that you know this is a peaceful parting, I'll tell you
that I served as Joe's top reference with VerticalNet just
yesterday,'' Bezos wrote. ``Joe is a talented executive who really
helped us over the last year. I would ask all of you to join me in
wishing him the very, very best.''
</P>
<P>
   Bezos will continue as CEO and resume the duties of president.
Warren Jenson, who joined the company at about the same time as
Galli, also with a generous signing package, remains as Amazon's
chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time that Galli backed out of a job with
short notice. Before joining Amazon.com, Galli reportedly accepted
the chief executive position at Frito Lay North America. But a day
after accepting the job at the snack food maker, Galli told them he
was not interested and would go to Amazon.com instead. Galli
downplayed questions about job-hopping, saying his 19-year career
at Black &AMP; Decker through multiple management shakeups speaks for
itself.
</P>
<P>
   VerticalNet, in many ways, is the Amazon.com of
business-to-business e-commerce. It operates 57 industry-specific
Web sites, including Aerospace Online, Nurses.com and
SolidWaste.com.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the five-year-old company is much smaller than Amazon and
not as well known among consumers. It employs just over 650
employees and recorded revenues of $20.7 million last year.
Amazon.com, with more than 7,000 employees, reported sales of $1.6
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably a combination of wanting to be closer to his
family, along with his own ambition,'' said Adam Hamilton, a
research analyst at McAdams Wright, Ragen in Seattle. ``He is a
young, energetic and a smart guy. That's why the company brought
him in to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Galli's departure is a loss for Amazon.com. He was credited with
streamlining the company operations during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously this is something that makes people nervous, look
what the stock did today,'' said Hamilton, commenting on
Amazon.com's 2.9 percent stock drop. ``But I think the company can
survive this. I am impressed across the board with the talent they
have. The loss of one person isn't a nail in the coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
