<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-     07-25 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARAB-LEADERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB LEADERS BEHIND ARAFAT'S UNWILLINGNESS TO COMPROMISE ON
JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add `and Muslim' to lede; 2nd graf to clarify; deletes
`exclusive' from 3rd graf; 6th graf to rephrase; after optional
trim, adds new graf on Arab religious leaders; adds 3 grafs to end
of original text.)  
 (With MIDEAST-TALKS; see also MIDEAST-ADVISORY-NYT for complete
list of stories) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The refusal of Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian
leader, to negotiate away his claims to Jerusalem may have dashed
U.S. hopes of a Camp David peace agreement Tuesday, but it allowed
him to return home with his credibility among other Arab and Muslim
leaders intact, Middle East analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is expected to solidify that backing with a round of
consultations in the region, beginning in Egypt on Wednesday
morning with a visit to President Hosni Mubarak in the Egyptian
port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials here said that Arafat would probably meet
soon with many of the Arab leaders who had urged him, in public
statements and private telephone conversations, to hold firm on his
demands for an end to Israel's 33 years of control over East
Jerusalem and the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Jerusalem, which contains sites holy to Muslims
and Christians as well as to Jews, was said to have been the main
sticking point in the intense negotiations at Camp David in pursuit
of a settlement to the long Palestinian-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official reaction from Arab capitals to the
announcement that the Camp David talks had ended. A spokesman for
the Arab League in Cairo said officials would wait until Arafat
briefs them on his negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Arab television channels, which are state owned, reported the
end in the talks without commentary.
</P>
<P>
   However, on the Al-Jezeera satellite TV station, owned by a
member of the ruling family of the Gulf state of Qatar, and one of
the few outlets for debate in the Arab world, the analysis was
overwhelmingly supportive of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton said Israel compromised more than the Palestinians,
but this is not accurate,'' Helmi Barakat, a political analyst
based in Washington, said in a an Al-Jezeera interview. ``According
to international law, Jerusalem is occupied land, and I do not
believe the Arabs should be expected to compromise or give up their
sovereignty over Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few days, a number of Arab leaders, from Crown
Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia to Mubarak, have joined with
Arafat's domestic opponents in various Islamic militant movements
to weigh in on the issue. They all but threatened Arafat with
political excommunication if he accepted Prime Minister Ehud
Barak's proposals for only administrative control over parts of the
city and access to _ but not sovereignty over _ the major Muslim
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the view of many analysts, however, Arafat did not need any
reminders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat knew beforehand that any compromise on Jerusalem would
be the end of Arafat,'' said Tahsin Basheer, a former aide to Anwar
Sadat, the late Egyptian president who was the first Arab leader to
make peace with Israel, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials also said Arafat was acutely aware,
throughout the peace talks, that Jerusalem was an especially
sensitive issue for the Arab leaders whose support he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that here in Egypt, just like in Saudi Arabia, in
Jordan and elsewhere in the region, the leaders have to worry about
their own home constituencies when it comes to Jerusalem,'' said
Mohammed Subieh, the general-secretary of the Palestine National
Council and the Palestinian representative in the Arab League in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   Arab control of the Old City has been a rallying cry not only
for Palestinian nationalists through the years. It has also been a
slogan for the Islamic fundamentalist movements that have mounted
violent opposition to any Arab regime that attempts to normalize
relations between Arabs and Israelis.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An uncompromising view toward the status of East Jerusalem,
which was controlled by Jordan from 1947 until 1967, has also been
the standard position of Arab religious leaders, both Christian and
Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, who has been actively involved in the Arab-Israeli
peace effort for years, conferred several times with Arafat during
the talks. But he did not follow the U.S. line and push Arafat to
compromise, as he has in the past on issues other than Jerusalem,
Egyptian officials and diplomats in Cairo said.
</P>
<P>
   As Mubarak's information director, Maged Abdel Fattah, said
earlier this week, the Egyptian president saw his role as helping
U.S. diplomats, and not Arafat, understand that Christian and
Muslim Arabs around the world can accept only certain
``parameters'' when it comes to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Clinton said in his post-mortem on the negotiations,
these were the first substantive talks between an Arab leader and
an Israeli leader on the subject of Jerusalem. But outside the
confines of the presidential retreat, analysts said, they also
revived old shibboleths and emotions that could be difficult to
contain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going home, on the face of it, empty-handed, creates a problem
of damage control,'' a former diplomat said. ``Fourteen days of
uninterrupted negotiations made the anti-peace forces on both sides
very active. Everyone is trying to remobilize their forces and
their arguments, even arguments from 30 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials, however, expressed some hope that some
agreement could be salvaged before mid-September, when Arafat has
pledged he will declare a Palestinian state. ``Let us wait and
see,'' said Subieh when asked if the pledge would be kept.
``Clinton has promised to send one of his senior people to the
region, and we are hoping that will help.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, another Palestinian official said he hoped to
see broad Arab support rallied behind Arafat so that he could
continue to negotiate. ``There is still a chance until Sept. 13,''
Marwan al-Bargout, a leader of the Palestinian Fatah faction, said
on Al-Jezeera. ``We are calling upon Arab nations and leaders to
support the Palestinians and hold an emergency Arab summit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
