<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-1STLD     07-25 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFRANCE-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
113 DIE IN FIRST CRASH OF A CONCORDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS 4th graf to add info on American victim; adds new 5th graf on
black boxes; In 2nd take, subs grafs 5,6 to CORRECT typo, `Gosenne'
to `GONESSE')  
(See AIRCRASH-CRASH-ADVISORY for complete list of related
stories.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT1, NYT21, NYT22, NYT23 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. A locator map is being sent to graphics clients.
Graphics showing the Concorde, what happens during take off and how
the Concorde compares to other planes are being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GONESSE, France _ A supersonic Air France Concorde carrying
mainly German tourists bound for a cruise ship in New York crashed
in flames shortly after take-off from Charles de Gaulle Airport
outside Paris Tuesday, killing all 109 passengers and crew on board
as well as at least four people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only crash of a Concorde since the world's first
supersonic passenger plane went into commercial operation in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Eyewitnesses said one or both of the plane's left engines were
on fire and smoking heavily even as the aircraft sped down the
runway. They said it had failed to gain height, banked heavily to
the left and then crashed, demolishing a small hotel and restaurant
in Gonesse, a suburb nine miles north-east of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Air France identified the passengers on board the chartered
flight AF4590 as 96 Germans, two Danes, one Austrian and one
American. The American was a retired Air France employee, but the
company did not release a name. The nine crew members, three pilots
and six stewardesses were all French. French government officials
said those killed in the hotel included three staff members _ two
Polish and one French _ and one British tourist. Five others were
reportedly injured, four of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The two black boxes _ the flight recorder and the cockpit voice
recorder _ were located a few hours after the crash and handed to
investigating officials, said the head of the French civil aviation
authority, Pierre Graf.
</P>
<P>
   The crash came just weeks after cracks were discovered in the
wings of several aging Concordes. Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the
president of Air France, said cracks had been found in four of the
airline's six Concordes, but not on the one that crashed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no possible link between the engine and these
cracks,'' he told reporters at scene. He added that the Concorde
that crashed Tuesday entered service in 1980 and had undergone a
mechanical check up as recently as last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft had been chartered by a German tour company, Peter
Deilmann Reederei GmbH &AMP; Co, based in the northern German town of
Neustadt. Deilmann, the company's chief executive, said the
Concorde's passengers were scheduled to join a luxury cruise ship,
``Deutschland,'' Tuesday evening in New York at the start of a
16-day tour of the Caribbean, traveling through the Panama Canal to
Manta in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the crash, which occurred here at 4:44 p.m.,
airport emergency trucks arrived on the scene to find flames and
smoke engulfing both the remains of the plane and the remnants of
the hotel, a wooden building called Hotelissimo. Dozens of police
vehicles and fire trucks soon arrived, and the area was immediately
cordoned off.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, with planes again leaving Charles de Gaulle
airport and flying over the wreckage, firemen were still trying to
put out the fire, which continued to spew thick, white smoke across
a nearby highway and wheat fields.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists who reached the area were kept at a distance of some
100 yards, but they could see darkened pieces of the plane's
fuselage as well as a solitary wheel and what looked like one of
the turbines. Only a tiny section of the 45-room hotel remained
standing, charred and ruined. The wreckage of the plane was
confined to a small area, a little larger than its own size,
seemingly confirming eyewitness reports that it fell on its left
side and tipped over on its back.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The crash and the minutes preceding it were witnessed by a
number of people, both at the airport and around Gonesse. Even now,
more than 30 years after the plane was unveiled as the pride of the
British and French aviation industries, passengers and airport
workers routinely turn their eyes toward the runway to watch the
aircraft's swan-like form take to the air. Tuesday was different
only because smoke and flames were spewed from the plane's engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hadn't left the ground and already it was on fire,'' said
Sylvie Lucas, who had gone to the airport to pick up her children,
who were on another flight. ``The flames were coming from the back
of the plane. We were waiting to hear the explosion because we
thought it was going to fall here.''
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of the ill-fated Concorde in the air, taken by a
young Hungarian plane-spotter, showed flames stretching some 60
feet behind the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Udel, a New York musician who had just finished touring
Europe with the Blue Brothers jazz band, said he looked up and saw
the Concorde on fire. ``It looked just like virtual reality,'' he
said. ``Of course, we all knew what it was. And there was nothing
on earth you could do. It looked like it was trying to ascend, but
its nose was down. First there was smoke, then there was fire, then
it just went nose in and all that was left was a white billowy
cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses who watched the crippled plane as it flew toward
the southeast also anticipated the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw its rear engine in flames,'' said Samir Hossein, 15, a
student in Gonesse who was playing tennis at the time. ``We saw it
lose altitude, it chopped off those trees near the hotel and headed
to the ground. The pilot tried to bank, but the plane rolled over
and hit the hotel nose first and turned over.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, who visited the scene of the crash
some two hours after the disaster, said the plane's pilots
apparently had time to signal an emergency because the runways at
both Charles de Gaulle and the nearby Le Bourget airports were
ordered cleared. ``But the plane could not return, even though it
tried,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Willy Corenthin, 29, an electrician who saw the crash as he
drove on a nearby highway, said he also heard an explosion while
the plane was still in the air. ``I saw smoke and flames coming
from the engines, then I heard an explosion, and the plane heaved
to the left and crashed,'' he said. ``When it fell, it seemed to
fall very slowly, then the smoke and flames erupted. I didn't hear
another explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the plane with a full fuel load demolished the small
building of the Hotelissimo hotel, it narrowly missed an adjacent
and larger hotel, Les Relais Bleus. The owner of Les Relais Bleus
said he saw the burning plane heading towards him and fled. If it
had continued another 300 yards, it would also have crashed into
the town of Gonesse, presumably causing many more deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had fallen on Gonesse, it would have been an
unbelievable disaster,'' said Corenthin, who echoed the views of
several local residents who felt the pilot had steered the plane
away from the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure the pilot was trying to avoid more populated areas,''
said Christine Turpin, who saw the flaming plane flash by just 150
feet above her gasoline station. ``I think he was trying to get
back to the airport or land in a field.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, the French transport minister, Jean-Claude
Gayssot, said he had asked the civil aviation authority to cancel
all Concorde flights Wednesday. In London, a spokesman for British
Airways, the only airline apart from Air France to fly the plane,
said that Tuesday evening's flights to and from New York had also
been canceled. But a spokesman for the British Civil Aviation Board
said it had no intention of grounding the Concorde.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, British Airways grounded one of its seven
Concordes after cracks were found in its wings, but the remaining
six in its supersonic fleet continue to fly.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Britain's BAE Systems and France's Aerospatiale
Matra, the successors to the companies that built the aircraft,
said they were forming a joint investigating team. The U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board said it was also sending an
investigator to Paris to work with the French team.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from Rolls-Royce, the manufacturer of the engines, were
traveling to Paris to investigate the apparent failure of one or
two of the plane's four Olympus 593 engines.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac of France as well as Jospin expressed
condolences to the German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, who in
turn noted that ``Germany and France are united in their horror
over the accident, in mourning for the victims and in sympathy for
the families.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton also spoke of the crash Tuesday. ``Like all of
you,'' he told reporters, ``I have just heard the news of the crash
of the Concorde outside Paris, and I wanted to extend the deepest
condolences of the American people to the families of those who are
lost.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Concorde, which can fly at 1,350 miles per hour at some
60,000 feet above sea-level, has long been regarded by France as
proof of its technological prowess. Even though supersonic travel
never caught on widely, it has been a favorite of prosperous
businessmen and show business personalities who welcome being able
to cross the Atlantic in around half the time _ just three and a
half hours _ of regular commercial flights. For the convenience,
roundtrip tickets can cost up to $11,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although Concorde only makes the return flight to New York three
times a day _ once from Paris and twice from London _ its aura of
romance and luxury has made it popular for charter by travel groups
catering to the well-heeled.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the plane, which was first flown in tests in 1969,
has had a good safety record, albeit with sporadic difficulties. In
January, two British Airways Concordes made emergency landings
within a 24-hour period, one after an engine switched off, the
other after a fire alarm went off in the cockpit. On at least three
occasions, the rubber tires on the Concorde's landing gear have
exploded upon landing. But in those and other incidents, no
passenger has ever been injured.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Air France has predicted that its fleet of
Concordes would continue flying until at least 2007.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
