<SLUG> BC-SPACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE STATION LINKUP SUCCESSFUL 
 

</HEADLINE>
 STATION-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S.-led international space station successfully linked up
with its tardy Russian crew module late Tuesday, adding living
space for future resident astronauts and cosmonauts to the slowly
developing orbital outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The linkup occurred 7:45 p.m. CDT, as the 43-foot-long module
coasted more than 229 miles over central Asia. The milestone sets
the stage for a flurry of long-delayed assembly missions.
</P>
<P>
   The docking of the unpiloted spacecraft drew to a dramatic close
as a combination of two other modules that were launched and joined
in late 1998 to kick off the station's assembly crept within range
of the crew module and docked.
</P>
<P>
   Russian and American experts supervised and monitored the
automated rendezvous operation from mission control facilities in
suburban Moscow and the Johnson Space Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confirmation of contact and capture,'' Kyle Herring, a
NASA spokesman at the Moscow facility ``Everything has gone exactly
by the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Also known as Zvezda, Russian for ``star,'' the 42,000-pound
crew module lifted off late July 11 from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in
Kazakhstan, its departure stalled 27 months by Russian economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The crew module's arrival promises to unleash 15 station
assembly and supply missions by the United States and Russia over
the next 12 months. Those include the launching in late October of
the embryonic station's first resident crew, American commander
Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Sergei Krikalev and Yuri Gidzenko.
They plan a three- to four-month stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really happy we've got this milestone behind us,''
Shepherd said after the docking. ``You have a lot of happy
astronauts and cosmonauts.''
</P>
<P>
   First up, however, will be the lift off, tentatively scheduled
for Aug. 6, of a Russian Progress cargo capsule, the first of
dozens of the unmanned spacecraft that will be needed to keep the
station stocked with supplies and fuel to keep it circling the
Earth at safe altitudes.
</P>
<P>
   The American shuttle Atlantis is scheduled to follow in early
September with seven astronauts and cosmonauts. They will deliver
more supplies and unload the Progress to prepare the station for
the arrival of Shepherd and his crew.
</P>
<P>
   In early October, the shuttle Discovery and another crew of
seven will follow with the first large segment of external
trusswork and streering gyroscopes. Another shuttle crew will
arrive before Thanksgiving with the first U.S. solar power
generator.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-2001, subsequent shuttle missions will deliver the
bus-sized U.S. laboratory module and equipment to outfit it for the
wide range of physics, biology and medical experiments that are
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   As the equipment aboard it are gradually activated, Zvezda will
act as the station's central nervous system as well as its crew
habitat. Its systems will furnish guidance, propulsion and
communications as well as living quarters for three occupants,
cooling, air and water re-generation, a toilet and galley.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in spite of the many new capabilities it affords the orbital
outpost, the crew module also arrived with several previously
disclosed safety lapses the Russians were unable to resolve without
additional delays.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd and his crew will be required to wear ear protection
because of the high internal noise levels. The station's first
occupants will plan to augment the noise dampening insulation and
install quieter air flow fans as a remedy.
</P>
<P>
   The module also lacks adequate external shielding for long term
protection from impacts with micrometeorites and small bits of
man-made space debris. It will likely be another four years before
all of the additional shielding required for better protection can
be launched and installed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NASA is proceeding with plans initiated more than a
year ago to purchase at least $35 million in new hardware for the
station from the Russian Aviation and Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The space agency said there is no link between the purchases and
warnings from top officials of RSC Energia, one of Russia's most
influential aerospace contractors, that their country's future
contributions to the new station are underfunded.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings followed the launching of the crew module.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the Russians say every bit of cash they can get
helps because they need the money to pay their suppliers,'' said
Kirsten Williams, a NASA spokeswoman in Washington. ``But in terms
of these particular procurements there is no where else to get
these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The first purchase is for $14 million in Russian docking
mechanisms. The hardware would allow two different American
propulsion modules to dock with the station. The modules would keep
the station safely aloft in the event the Russians were unable to
launch adequate numbers of Progress capsules with fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents in Congress have criticized the purchase because it
rewards the Russians for failing to keep their commitments to the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the $35 million would pay for a range of
safety, ground test and life support equipment. The hardware
includes a Russian version of a backpack mounted jet pack worn by
spacewalking astronauts. The device enables spacewalkers to propel
themselves back to the station if their safety tethers are severed
during a stroll in space.
</P>
<P>
   The second installment would also cover the cost of a device
that purifies condensate from the station's air conditioning system
into drinkable water. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
