<SLUG> BC-NY-WEST-NILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIGHT AGAINST FEAR AS WELL AS MOSQUITOS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After blanketing Central Park, Staten Island and
parts of Queens with pesticide in a stepped-up campaign to knock
out the West Nile virus, city officials were preparing to spray
Roosevelt Island and a large section of Manhattan Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a day after they announced that the virus had been
detected in mosquitoes in the city for the first time this year,
officials said they were still planning to attack mosquitoes
primarily from the ground, spraying the pesticide Anvil from
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread aerial pesticide spraying was used last year when an
outbreak of West Nile, a mosquito-borne disease, killed 7 people in
the New York area and sickened 55 others. City officials said
Tuesday that they had received permission from the state to use
helicopters to drop a bacterial larvicide that kills mosquito eggs
in the wetlands of Staten Island, but they said they planned to
rely on ground spraying in residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, city health officials announced that they had found
mosquitoes infected with the virus in three sample pools one in
Central Park and two on Staten Island, that were tested as part of
a surveillance program.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials reported on Tuesday that West Nile had
been found in two more samples of mosquitoes, both in Rockland
County, bringing to eight the total number of mosquito pools in New
York that have tested positive for the virus. In New Jersey, no
mosquitoes have tested positive for the virus, and in Connecticut
one pool has tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have placed 120 mosquito traps at more than 70 spots
around the city, and the state provides weekly reports of the test
results.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Staten Island, where last week two dead crows tested
positive for the virus, had already been treated, but after the
virus was found in two mosquito pools there, the rest of the
borough was sprayed Monday night and yesterday morning, officials
said. Neighborhoods in Queens, and a small section of Brooklyn,
were to be sprayed Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And in Manhattan, areas from 23rd Street to 110th Street,
between the East River and the Hudson, and on Roosevelt Island were
scheduled to be sprayed from midnight Wednesday to 5 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of West Nile virus in Central Park, in a pool of
54 mosquitoes trapped near 63rd Street and Fifth Avenue, prompted
the city to close all 843 acres for overnight spraying Monday and
to postpone a New York Philharmonic concert until Tuesday night.
The Central Park spraying began at 10 p.m. Monday and ended at 5
a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two and a half hours after it ended, the park was bustling with
joggers, cyclists and in-line skaters, many of whom said they were
not concerned or did not know about the pesticide spraying. But it
was another story with the dog owners.
</P>
<P>
   The usually crowded dog run near West 72nd Street had only a few
of the regulars Tuesday, and those who took their dogs out for a
walk were trying to avoid the grass, fearing their pets would
ingest the pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's uncanny that there's nobody here,'' said Dana Weiss, 48,
who was walking her golden retriever, Buddy, and said she was
surprised to see so few dogs around. ``This is very odd.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said she normally walked her dog for 45 minutes, but she
had limited it to 10 minutes and kept him on a leash, even though
dogs are allowed off a leash until 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Francis Ginsberg, 45, walked into the park with her two dogs
about 8:30 and discovered that she had little company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is everybody?'' she said, pulling a newspaper out of her
bag and glancing at the headlines. When she saw that the park had
been closed the previous night for pesticide spraying, she looked
down at the dogs, Angelo, a bichon frise, and Valentina, a Maltese,
and said, ``I have to go to Riverside,'' and left the park. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
