<SLUG> BC-GLF-KUYUM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S KUYUMJIAN MAKING NAME FOR HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Being the new kid on the block wasn't all that
difficult for Alex Kuyumjian, but that probably had a lot to do
with the success he enjoyed in his first season with the USC golf
team in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Kuyumjian, a transfer from College of the Canyons in Santa
Clarita who also graduated from Westlake High, began last season at
the bottom of the Trojans' depth chart but wound up the team's best
finisher at the Pac-10 Championships, and he is building on his
spring success with a productive summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kuyumjian's last two tournaments were the biggest of his career.
Two weeks ago, he played in the U.S. Public Links Championships in
Milwaukie, Ore., and survived the stroke-play cut before losing in
the first round of match play to Andy Sanders of the University of
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kuyumjian played in the California State Amateur,
with similar results _ stroke-play survivor, first-round exit _ but
experience is more important than results to a player such as
Kuyumjian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' the 21-year-old said. ``The PubLinks course
(Heron Lakes Golf Club) was probably one of the toughest I have
ever was a USGA setup, so just making it to match play was an
accomplishment in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, Kuyumjian, who will attempt to qualify for the
U.S. Amateur next week, will carry over this success to the Trojans
he will begin practicing for his junior season in just a couple of
weeks. If the Trojans are lucky, he will build on last year's
success.
</P>
<P>
   He came in as something of an unknown, an outsider who was seen
as a threat to golfers who had already spent a year or two on the
team and who weren't particularly enthused about giving up their
spot in the regular tournament rotation. But Kuyumjian couldn't be
ignored for long and he was a postseason Pac-10 all-conference
selection, long after he had already earned the respect of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I didn't really feel quite in place,'' Kuyumjian
said. ``After a while, though, the chemistry of the team started to
things got a little bit easier for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gradual, but I can understand that. These guys really
didn't know a whole lot about me, so there was definitely an
adjustment period.''
</P>
<P>
   The adjustments continue for Kuyumjian, who now must prove he
can succeed in Division I golf on a consistent basis. And he isn't
about to shy away from a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he set out to maintain a scoring average of 72 and
finished at 72.7, which gives him more motivation to perform well
in his second year at USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to set goals for myself every year,'' Kuyumjian said.
``Maybe this year I'd like to get my average down to 71 and keep
setting the standards higher every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always something for me to work on with my game, but
I'm definitely excited about this season. Last year I got a change
to show people what I could do and I want to keep improving as time
goes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
