<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3004 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-1STLD-     07-25 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-1STLD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: DESCENDING THE SUMMIT INTO VALE OF UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS graf bgng `It was perplexing...' to clarify.) 
(With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ And on the 15th day, the Israelis and the
Palestinians packed their bags and left their pastoral retreat at
Camp David empty-handed, exhausted and still in conflict. In
immediate retrospect, the hope that they could have resolved a
52-year-old, blood-soaked dispute in a fortnight seems like the
summit of idealism.
</P>
<P>
   With the potential for violence looming, what happens now to
this prizefight of all ethnic, religious and territorial conflicts?
The Palestinians entered swinging, and the Israelis left swinging,
and while the American referees bounced quickly back to their feet,
it is unclear when and if the two sides will re-enter the ring. In
the end, did the meeting help or hurt the peace effort?
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton described it on his return to the White
House Tuesday, he believed that he was compelled to force the issue
by convening the talks. After seven years of stop-and-start peace
negotiations, with the threat of an impending return to violent
conflict, there was no longer any reason to avoid an official
grappling with the thorniest points. It was time for a moment of
reckoning, for the leaders to stare at themselves in the mirror and
also face ``the abyss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Camp David meeting, Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, repeatedly said that the moment had not
arrived, that the talks were premature, that the groundwork had not
been laid. Perhaps he should have been heeded. As Prime Minister
Ehud Barak repeated Tuesday, it does take two to tango.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and U.S. officials knew that in general, Arafat makes no
decision before its time, and Arafat's personal working deadline is
Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the most recent interim peace agreement expires,
and when the Palestine Liberation Organization leadership has
pledged to unilaterally declare a state if a permanent peace has
not been reached _ an action that could provoke a chain of
unilateral actions and violent events.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the best possible face on the meeting's failure to
produce an agreement, Clinton asserted that the Israelis and
Palestinians had broken seven years of official silence to conduct
``unprecedented'' discussions on emotional issues like Jerusalem.
He said that the parties had made significant progress on every
core dispute, and U.S. officials said that they expect the peace
process to continue after a period of ``reflection.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak made it clear that he believed the present ``chapter''
of peacemaking had reached an end. Addressing reporters at the
Hampton Inn in Frederick, Md., Barak spoke as if he had already
moved on. ``If we have to go to a confrontation,'' he said, ``we
will be able to look straight into the eyes of our children and say
we did everything, everything in order to prevent a
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   Having reportedly offered concessions on every issue, Barak, who
has staked his political career on the single goal of peacemaking,
does not apparently see a clear path ahead. He called the summit
meeting a ``significant milestone and, at this point, the last one,
in intensive and deep negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   All understandings reached at Camp David, he said conclusively,
were moot, vanished into the mist that clouded the talks during two
weeks of intermittent rain and a steady news blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's somber assessment did not square at all with the
uncharacteristically upbeat one offered by a senior Palestinian
negotiator Tuesday afternoon. Speaking in Pentagon City, Saeb
Erekat said emphatically that Camp David had paved the way for a
peace agreement by Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of an agreement is much stronger than ever
before,'' Erekat said. ``What happened at Camp David are seeds that
will grow very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a perplexing optimism, although it may have expressed a
certain amount of anxiety that the Palestinians had squandered some
reserves of American good will toward their cause. But after two
weeks in intensive, round-the-clock negotiations during which the
U.S. president pushed aside nearly all other business, the Israeli
and the Palestinian leaders explored every issue and, particularly
in regard to determining the sovereignty of Jerusalem, hit a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Why would lower-level negotiations be able to progress further,
or, if the leaders reassembled, why would the picture change?
</P>
<P>
   After all, Erekat continued to insist Tuesday that all would be
well and good provided that Barak does what he has said he cannot
do _ acknowledge Jerusalem as the capital of both Israel and the
future Palestine. Is Jerusalem an inexorably intractable issue, or
is there some give on either side that somehow was not discovered
in the seclusion of the Catoctin Mountains but will emerge later?
</P>
<P>
   Arafat will return home to a hero's welcome, not just in the
West Bank and Gaza but in the Arab world, whose capitals he will
tour immediately.
</P>
<P>
   His popularity at home, lower than ever before he departed, will
be boosted by the perception that he faced down Israel and a
superpower without conceding any of what Palestinians consider
their sacred principles, especially the sovereignty of East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that everyone will go out to applaud Arafat and say
to him, `Welcome home, Mr. President,''' said Hani al-Hassan, a
member of the central committee of Arafat's Fatah movement.
</P>
<P>
   It is more complex for Barak. Right before he left, he lost
three right-leaning parties from his broad coalition. Leaving
without a government and returning without an agreement, he faces a
good deal of uncertainty, and any uncertainty about his political
future clouds the prospects for peace, too.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has political options that would involve alliances
incompatible with any immediate progress at the peace tables. What
he cannot do is continue at the head of a minority government,
representing only 42 out of 120 members of Parliament. It is not
sustainable; he would not be able to accomplish anything.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Barak will bring home a one-page, trilateral
statement reaffirming the value of making peace. It is a long way
from an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Camp David represents a significant juncture in the
history of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. But where it will
lead, beside through a thicket of diplomatic and political
complications, is impossible to predict.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-NYT     07-25 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE STATION IS CONNECTED TO MODULE FROM RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A long-awaited Russian component docked with the
International Space Station on Tuesday night, marking what project
planners hoped would be a resurgence in construction of the orbital
outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian service module, named Zvezda or ``star,'' and the
two components making up the budding station closed on each other
and docked at 8:45 p.m. Eastern Time while soaring 230 miles above
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contact is confirmed,'' said Kyle Herring, a NASA commentator
at the Russian control center outside Moscow as applause broke out
in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Latches on the space station closed to secure the new module,
which is to serve as the command and living headquarters for
international crews while the station is being built.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda, a 42,000-pound pressurized section the size of a city
bus, joined two previously orbited units that together weighed
70,000 pounds to form the core around which the rest of the $60
billion research station could be built.
</P>
<P>
   Late arrival of the 43-foot-long Zvezda, delayed more than 19
months because of financial problems in cash-strapped Russia and
trouble with the Proton booster rocket that eventually sent it into
space two weeks ago, has stymied space station construction and
strained the international partnership sponsoring the ambitious
project.
</P>
<P>
   After confirming the attachment of Zvezda to the station and
testing the airtight seal between components over the next three
days, computers in the new module are to assume control over the
entire complex as it awaits a space shuttle crew, due in early
September, to complete the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's activities were the culmination of a two-week orbital
ballet in which Zvezda slowly worked its way up to the two
previously launched space station components. Zvezda had an almost
flawless launch from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan atop a
three-stage Proton rocket on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the usual two-day trip to the existing station,
flight controllers decided to take two weeks to move the units
together so that they could thoroughly test Zvezda's systems before
the docking attempt. Engineers took the time to test the command
module's power and guidance systems, maneuver its giant solar power
panels, and check out the docking systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of rocket firings, the final three of which occurred
last Friday and Saturday, the new module moved to a 224-mile-high
orbit to await the rendezvous with the space station.
</P>
<P>
   After all of its previous activity, Zvezda let the space station
take the lead in the final stages of the rendezvous, approaching
Zvezda and controlling the docking operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian control module is the third of what are to be
two-dozen major components of the International Space Station, a
project involving 16 nations, led by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The partners, including members of the European Space Agency,
Canada, Japan, Brazil and Russia, have so far spent billions of
dollars building more than 300,000 pounds of equipment and supplies
for the station. When completed in five years, the research outpost
is to be a complex of six laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda, which cost about $340 million, is the first station
module fully financed by Russia. Experts said it also is one of the
most essential components of the station, a necessary building
block on which the rest of the outpost is constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Zvezda not only provides living quarters for the initial crews
to staff the station, but it also is to command the station's
position in space and control all electrical, computer,
communications and flight systems for the complex. The module,
which is almost identical to the core component of the Russian Mir
space station, also will be the base for spacewalks needed to
maintain the station and help in its expansion.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year-and-a-half, the station has consisted of
just two components that could not be expanded without the critical
service module. The Russian-made, but American-financed, control
module, called Zarya, became the first part of the station launched
in November 1998. The following month, an American space shuttle
took up an American docking module called Unity. American shuttles
visited the complex twice since then to outfit it, perform
maintenance and boost the station's altitude, which slowly
decreases because of atmospheric drag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
