<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3006 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CONCORDE-RIDE0726-COX     07-25 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONCORDE-RIDE0726-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concorde provides mega-dose of refined traveling
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Crossing the Atlantic Ocean aboard the
supersonic jet, the Concorde, is a journey of elegance and
refinement, even if the legroom is a mite cramped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seats are comfortable, the service is superb and the food
is excellent,'' said former Palm Beach Mayor Yvelyne ``Deedy''
Marix, who has made the transatlantic flight aboard the
needle-nosed aircraft several times.
</P>
<P>
   Marix and her late husband, Nigel, owned Embassy Travel in Palm
Beach for more than 30 years before selling it in the mid-1980s.
She last flew aboard a Concorde more than a decade ago in
connection with her travel consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I infinitely prefer it to a 747,'' she said. ``It's like
comparing oysters to a green dress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde provides an unending stream of gourmet food and
drink, served on crystal, china and linen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jumbos are huge and packed with people,'' Marix said. The
Concorde holds only about 100 passengers. ``Even in first class or
business class, people bump you with their luggage trying to get
through. The Concorde is more like a private airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   The real attraction, of course, is that it crosses the ocean at
60,000 feet at 1,350 mph and can reach London from New York in
three hours, 50 minutes, about half the time of regular jets.
</P>
<P>
   Such speed and luxury come at a price: $10,000 for a round-trip
commercial flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to get where I'm going (fast),'' said Palm Beach
attorney and real estate broker Martin Klein, who formerly did work
for both Air France and British Airways, which operate the
remaining 11 Concordes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a marvelous experience and a wonderful way to minimize
jet lag. If you're traveling from London to New York, you can
arrive before you left,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   The tall and the bulky find it cramped, however, and there are
no telephones, headphones or in-flight movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you're high enough to actually see the curvature of the
Earth and generally you're unaffected by the weather or other air
traffic,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, no Concorde had crashed in the plane's 30-year
history. The closest call came in 1979 when a hard landing blew out
some tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are aging,'' Klein said. ``Perhaps it's time for a
second-generation Concorde.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
