<HEADLINE>
PHOTO:
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of
tonight's New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 07/25/00.
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Editors please note:
</P>
<P>
   We have issued an elimination for NYT7 sent July 13, 2000
with the story slugged: AIRBUS-NEW-JET. The photo was incorrectly
made available to the New York Times News Service and should not have
moved.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, July 23, 2000, we transmitted the photo NYT1
showing a an infant being carried by his mother during a
demonstration by actors with the Screen Actors Guild. The caption in
the photo identified another scene in the demonstration. We have
retransmitted the photo as NYT99 with the correct caption.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we have sent NYT98 which contains the
individuals mentioned in the original caption.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- AIRFRANCE-CRASH-4 -- An
Air France Concorde carrying mainly German tourists bound for a
cruise ship in New York crashed in flames shortly after take-off from
Charles de Gaulle Airport outside Paris Tuesday, killing all 109
passengers and crew on board as well as at least four people on the
ground. The aircraft had been chartered by a German tour company and
the passengers were scheduled to join a luxury cruise ship,
"Deutschland," Tuesday evening in New York at the start of a
Caribbean tour. Hayo Jassen, the captain of the Deutschland, standing
in front of his ship in New York awaiting to talk to the media.
(Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- AIRFRANCE-CRASH-3 --
With flames and smoke streaking from its engines, an Air France
Concorde carrying German tourists to New York for a Caribbean cruise
crashed into a hotel outside Paris shortly after takeoff Tuesday. At
least 113 people died. One of the buses that was to pick up the
tourists is seen parked at John F. Kennedy Airport, Tuesday.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- AIRFRANCE-CRASH-2 -- An
Air France Concorde on the tarmac at John F. Kennedy Airport,
Tuesday.  With flames and smoke streaking from its engines, an Air
France Concorde carrying German tourists to New York for a Caribbean
cruise crashed into a hotel outside Paris shortly after takeoff
Tuesday. At least 113 people died.  All other Concordes in France and
Britain, which also flies the supersonic transport, were grounded.
(Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- July 25, 2000 --
MIDEAST-TALKS-3 --  After 15 days of emotional negotiations failed to
end in an agreement at Camp David, President Clinton closed the peace
conference Tuesday by praising Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak for
being ready to make hard compromises but declaring that the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, would not reciprocate. U.S. Air
Force personnel salute Arafat's plane as it departed Andrews Air
Force Base on Tuesday following the collapse of the talks.  (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- July 25, 2000 --
MIDEAST-TALKS-2 --  Palestinian representative Hassan Abed makes a
statement to the press as Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's plane,
in the background, departed Andrews Airforce Base on Tuesday. The
Middle East peace talks at Camp David collapsed Tuesday over rival
claims to East Jerusalem. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. -- July 25, 2000 --
MIDEAST-TALKS -- Palestinian Leader Yassar Arafat waves as he departs
Andrews Air Force Base, Tuesday. Arafat attended the Mideast Peace
Summit at Camp David which came to an end Tuesday without an
agreement. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- NY-WEST-NILE -- After
blanketing Central Park, Staten Island and parts of Queens with
pesticide in a stepped up campaign to knock out the West Nile Virus,
city officials were preparing to spray a large section of Manhattan
and two more areas of Queens Tuesday night. Francesca Paolozzi, left,
and Richard Banister, right, with their dogs Tuesday morning in
Central Park after it was closed overnight while authorities sprayed
the park with pesticide. (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 25, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-3 --
Reaching into the well of his father's presidency, Gov. George W.
Bush chose Richard Cheney, the former Defense secretary, as his
running mate Tuesday, adding a respectable party elder to the
Republican ticket. From left: Lynne Cheney, her husband Richard, Bush
and Bush's wife Laura following Tuesday's news conference announcing
Cheney as Bush's runningmate.  (Sung Park/Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 25, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-1 --
Reaching into the well of his father's presidency, Gov. George W.
Bush chose Richard Cheney, former Defense Secretary, as his running
mate Tuesday, adding a respectable party elder to the Republican
ticket. Cheney, left, with Bush during their news conference,
Tuesday. (Sung Park/Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) AUSTIN, Texas -- July 25, 2000 -- BUSH-CHENEY-1 --
Reaching into the well of his father's presidency, Gov. George W.
Bush chose Richard Cheney, former Defense Secretary, as his running
mate Tuesday, adding a respectable party elder to the Republican
ticket. Cheney, left, with Bush during their news conference,
Tuesday. (Sung Park/Austin American-Statesman) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 --  PARMIGIANO-2 -- Most
people who buy Parmigiano-Reggiano never give a thought to the
variations in the way it tastes. They always assume the flavor
differences have to do with the aging process or the quality of the
cheese itself. Yet, the seasonal differences in the cow's milk affect
the flavor of the finished cheese. Parmigiano-Reggiano at an Italian
specialty market in Little Italy. (Tony Cenicola /The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- PARMIGIANO-1 -- Most
people who buy Parmigiano-Reggiano never give a thought to the
variations in the way it tastes. They always assumed the flavor
differences had to do with the aging process or the quality of the
cheese itself.  Yet, the seasonal differences in the cow's milk
affect the flavor of the finished cheese. Lou DiPalo, who sells
Parmigiano-Reggiano cheeses from every season, in his Italian
specialty market in Little Italy. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- July 25, 2000 -- LONG-ISLAND-WINE -- The
Long Island wine business is booming; it's almost giddy from its own
success. Handsome new wineries are opening, old ones are changing
hands for astonishing prices, new vineyards are springing up, and
suddenly, there isn't enough wine to go around. Susan Wine and Robert
Ransom sell only New York State wines at their store, Vintage New
York, in SoHo.  (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- July 25, 2000 --
MIDEAST-TALKS-CLINTON-3 --  President Clinton heads to the podium to
