<HEADER>
A3013 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WEST-NILE-BATTLE-N     07-25 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WEST-NILE-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISEASE CONTRAL OVERSHADOWS PESTICIDE EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The aggressive expansion of pesticide spraying in New
York this week, and Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's comments that some
local species, including some fish, could become casualties of war
in fighting the West Nile virus, have raised new concerns among
environmentalists that the region's fragile ecosystem could fall
victim to the anxiety over public health.
</P>
<P>
   But even the harshest critics of the spraying program concede
that there has been little conclusive evidence so far to back up
their fears.
</P>
<P>
   Like pesticide spray itself, which drifts on the wind to kill
airborne insects, then dissipates, the hints and suggestions of
broader environmental impact are impossible to pin down, the
experts say. Especially within New York City, where every species
has to confront an array of environmental assaults, from poor air
quality to polluted water, determining the relative effect of the
latest toxin in town is a difficult science.
</P>
<P>
   And with city and state resources committed first and foremost
to fighting the virus, there has also been little political
initiative to even begin such an analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a grossly inadequate effort to track the collateral
impact on the environment and on humans,'' said William Cooke, a
spokesman for the National Audubon Society in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even the few observations that have become part of the public
record are in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   State wildlife officials concluded last fall, for example, that
the city's pesticide program, then using the pesticide malathion,
was responsible for the deaths of several hundred small sun fish in
Clove Lake on Staten Island. But a raw sewage leak into the lake at
the same time made the post-mortem conclusions unclear, according
to a report by the city's Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents also reported seeing numerous dead butterflies,
bees and beetles last year during the time when the city was
spraying for mosquitoes, according to the National Audubon Society.
But without an entomological study, those deaths remained simply
unexplained observations. Butterfly populations are down again this
year, but the causes are just as unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Some pesticide experts argue that the lack of knowledge about
the long-term impact of spraying in a dense urban environment _ for
both human and nonhuman species _ is as big a story as West Nile
itself. But officials around the country who have been battling
other mosquito-borne diseases, like St. Louis encephalitis, in some
cases for decades, say that knowledge is hard won and comes only
with time.
</P>
<P>
   In Harris County, Texas, for example, which includes the city of
Houston, mosquito-control officials have assembled a 25-year
database about when and where and under what conditions of rainfall
and temperature the St. Louis virus has emerged. That has allowed
the county to concentrate its efforts and sharply reduce both
aerial and ground spraying for mature mosquitoes over time.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of pesticide use say that its effects on humans are not
being adequately explored or discussed with the public by
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Several medical studies have said, for instance, that the class
of chemicals now being used by the city, called synthetic
pyrethroids _ sold under the brand names Anvil and Scourge _ may
interfere with endocrine and immune systems in humans, according to
a report earlier this year by Environmental Advocates, based in
Albany. Chronic exposure to resmethrin, the active ingredient in
Scourge, has also been linked to effects on the human liver and
thyroid, the report said. But the Environmental Protection Agency's
lead pesticide official said those studies were not conclusive and
that the substances being used in the New York region were among
the safest on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the EPA said that the chemical used around New
York last year, malathion, posed no threat to people when used with
properly, although there was ``suggestive evidence'' that high
doses of the chemical could cause cancer in laboratory animals.
Next month, however, the agency will conduct a two-day peer review
session with independent scientists who are expected to hear
evidence from some of the agency's own researchers suggesting that
the chemical is more carcinogenic that the earlier report had
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The initial malathion review was conducted under the 1996 Food
Quality Protection Act, which required the EPA to reassess more
than 20,000 pesticides. Agency officials said that they prioritized
the work based on preliminary indications of which chemicals were
considered most toxic, and that the reassessment of the pyrethroid
group _ which includes Anvil and Scourge _ is not scheduled to
begin until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a pesticide has a registration number with the
EPA doesn't mean it's been fully evaluated,'' said Jay Feldman,
executive director of National Coalition Against the Misuse of
Pesticides, a Washington environmental group. ``People don't know
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
