<SLUG> BC-PEACE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST PEACE TALKS END IN FAILURE 
 

</HEADLINE>
 TALKS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The Middle East peace talks collapsed Tuesday as
Israeli and Palestinian leaders failed to agree on the future of
Jerusalem despite 15 days of intense negotiations at the Camp David
summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't get there,'' President Clinton said as he
returned from the presidential retreat to the White House Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak for showing
``courage and vision'' and said that both Barak and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat remain committed to reaching a peace agreement
by their self-imposed deadline of Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Barak took some very bold decisions, but we
were, in the end, unable to bridge the gaps,'' Clinton said. ``I
think they will be bridged because I think the alternative is
unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat said in a statement with Clinton that they
would continue their efforts to reach an agreement ``as soon as
possible'' and that they understand the importance of avoiding
violence and unilateral actions.
</P>
<P>
   But at a news conference near the presidential retreat, Barak
blamed Arafat for the failed talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ready to end the conflict. We looked for an
equilibrium point that will provide a peace for generations,''
Barak said. ``But unfortunately, Arafat somehow hesitated to take
the historic decisions that were needed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak said he has not lost hope that the two sides can put
an end to their 52-year conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision of peace suffered a major blow, but I believe that
with good faith, good will on all sides, it can recuperate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who has threatened to unilaterally declare an
independent state if no agreement is reached by the September
deadline, left the United States without issuing a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But a top aide in the talks, Saeb Erekat, told reporters that
progress had been made at the summit and that the prospects for an
Israeli-Palestinian peace deal were better now than at any time in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say the negotiations failed; I can't say the
negotiations succeeded,'' he said. But he added, ``the prospects
for a settlement are real.''
</P>
<P>
   Erekat said no one involved in the talks realistically expected
a settlement to emerge at Camp David, given the difficulty of the
issues.
</P>
<P>
   He described Arafat as ``more determined than ever'' to reach a
deal, and outline his plans to meet with Middle East and European
leaders to give them his assessments of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Erekat's comments appeared to be aimed in part at defusing the
possibility of disturbances among Palestinians who believed that
Camp David might yield an agreement that would pave the way to
Palestinian statehood with east Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is also facing a difficult time at home from Arab
militant factions who are pressuring him to declare a Palestinian
state without waiting for a final deal with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Hamas leader Sheik Ahmed Yassin offered evidence of that
pressure after the talks ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only by force are we able to retain our rights. We are ready
to become martyrs, and (the Israelis) will pay a high price if they
think to attack us and reoccupy the land,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, former Primer Minister Benjamin Netanyahu went on
television, saying he wants to prevent a ``ripping apart'' of
Israeli society ``that could happen in the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we hear from most of the reports out of Camp David does
not answer our hopes,'' Netanyahu said. He had demanded that Barak
reject any deal calling for sharing sovereignty over Jerusalem with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced last Wednesday that the talks had
broken down, but Clinton then persuaded the two sides to negotiate
through the weekend while he attended an economic summit in
Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 a.m. Tuesday, Arafat sent a letter to Clinton saying he saw
no point in continuing because Israel's final offer of limited
sovereignty for the Palestinians over east Jerusalem was not good
enough. Barak had already agreed to give up major portions of east
Jerusalem, but he was not willing to meet Arafat's demand that the
old walled city be placed under Palestinian control as well.
</P>
<P>
   By noon, Clinton was back in Washington. At a news conference,
he acknowledged that Jerusalem remains the major sticking point,
with both Israelis and Palestinians claiming the city as their
capital. But he said the two sides made ``significant progress'' on
several other core issues and had discussed some questions that had
previously been considered off limits.
</P>
<P>
   Even on the issue of Jerusalem, he said, the two sides did not
have a great deal of disagreement over how people would live if
they are able to reach a settlement. He cited as an example the
fact that everyone concedes both Israelis and Palestinians should
have access to Jerusalem's holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emphasized that Arafat and the whole Palestinian team
worked hard, but he credited Barak with deeper concessions,
particularly on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians changed their position. They moved forward,''
Clinton said. ``The Israelis moved more from the position they
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak ``came here knowing that he was going to have to take bold
steps, and he did it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be making a mistake not to praise Barak,'' he added,
``because I think he took a big risk, and I think it sparked
already in Israel public opinion toward the conditions that will
make peace.'' The people of Israel, he said, ``should be very proud
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The president likened the summit to ``going to the dentist
without having your gums deadened.'' But said in comparison to
other peace negotiations he has participated in _ particularly
those involving Bosnia, Kosovo and Ireland _ the Palestinians and
Israelis were better able to work through several difficult issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that in previous peace negotiations he was dealing
with people who often wouldn't shake hands, let alone speak to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me give you some good news: Of all the peace groups I've
ever worked with, these people know each other, they know the names
of each other's children, they know how many grandchildren the
grandparents have, they know their life stories, they have a
genuine respect and understanding for each other,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the United States should be prepared to make a
``significant'' financial contribution to the peace process,
especially to help resettle refugees. While in Okinawa, he called
on Group of Eight leaders to contribute as well. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
