<HEADLINE>
YOUNG GUNS OF DUBAI TO TRY DEL MAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR _ The trainer doesn't have a winner to his name. All of
his horses are maidens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Eoin Harty's barn _ barn K, on the backstretch near the
five- eighths-mile pole _ will be one to watch during the Del Mar
thoroughbred racing season that opens this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Harty (whose first name is pronounced ``Owen'') is here with a
string of 2-year-olds owned by Godolphin Racing Inc., the Dubai
sheikhs' powerful worldwide stable. Godolphin has nominated 15
colts for the meet- ending Del Mar Futurity on Sept. 13 and five
fillies for the Del Mar Debutante on Sept. 2. Up to a dozen others
are expected to run under the royal-blue Godolphin silks during the
43-day meet.
</P>
<P>
   Harty, a 37-year-old Irishman, proved his skill with young
horses as an assistant to Bob Baffert, winner of the past three Del
Mar training titles and the past four runnings of the Del Mar
Futurity (the first with Silver Charm on the way to his 1997
Kentucky Derby victory). Harty was hired away last fall to be the
trainer in Godolphin's ``American Project,'' racing the sheikhs'
2-year-olds in the United States before the best of them return to
the United Arab Emirates next winter to prepare for the Triple
Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The first of those horses went winless in six starts at the
recent Hollywood Park meet after training across town at Santa
Anita. Now the Harty barn faces a fuller test at Del Mar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very disappointed if he's not very strong,'' said Jim
Pegram, agent for David Flores, Del Mar's champion jockey of 1999
and Harty's main rider here. ``He's got a bunch of very, very nice
2-year-olds. He's brought them along slower than he did when he was
with Baffert. The ones that did race over at Hollywood Park needed
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch the development as these horses run. He had a couple
that ran good at Hollywood, but he also had a few who ran poorly.
You figure they were at a disadvantage running there after training
at Santa Anita. They should do better at Del Mar.''
</P>
<P>
   Harty entered two colts in the 6-furlong seventh race on the
nine-race opening-day card. Dubai Breeze, a chestnut son of
Woodman, makes his second start under Flores after rallying
strongly to finish fourth in a 5-furlong race at Hollywood. Matta,
by Unaccounted For, debuts under Eddie Delahoussaye.
</P>
<P>
   Among the more anticipated Godolphin 2-year-olds: Dubai Vision,
a half-brother of the top European horse Dubai Millennium; and
Dubai to Dubai, half-brother to 1999 European 2-year-old champion
Fasliyev.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging 2-year-olds are always big news in the summer. But
the stars of the future might get more attention at Del Mar this
time because so few stars of the present are here.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 horses receiving votes in this week's National
Thoroughbred Racing Association poll, only three are pointing for
races at Del Mar: General Challenge, the 1999 Pacific Classic
winner, aims for a repeat in the $1 million race Aug. 26; Early
Pioneer, upsetter of General Challenge in the Hollywood Gold Cup,
girds for a rematch, and Riboletta, California's leading mare, is
shooting for the Clement Hirsch Handicap (formerly the Chula Vista)
Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   First post today is 2 p.m. The featured Oceanside Stakes, a mile
turf race for 3-year-olds, will be run in $75,000 divisions as the
fifth and eighth races.
</P>
</TEXT>
