<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JSF-COMPETITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT FARNBOROUGH, BOEING SAYS IT IS ADOPTING KEY FEATURE FROM
LOCKHEED DESIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAN PILLER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARNBOROUGH, England _ As Lockheed Martin and Boeing compete for
what could be the last major U.S. fighter contract in the next four
decades, Boeing complimented Lockheed while the companies traded
barbs.
</P>
<P>
   In their proposed design for the joint strike fighter, and to
the surprise of aerospace observers at the international
Farnborough Air Show, Boeing has copied a key feature on Lockheed's
JSF entry.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing JSF chief Frank Statkus told reporters at the show
Tuesday that about 20 percent of the downward thrust on the
vertical lift for Boeing's fighter will come from so-called cold
thrust, or nonjet gas.
</P>
<P>
   That represents a change from Boeing's original plan to copy the
British Harrier military aircraft, using downward-pointed hot jet
nozzles for the vertical takeoff and landing that the new jet
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Since Boeing and Lockheed Martin won the semifinal competition
for the 3,000-plane, $200 billion JSF contract almost four years
ago, Lockheed Martin has touted its system that throws cold air,
rather than exhaust, downward as the fighter hovers above the
ground. The cold air is considered less likely to come back up and
burn up the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin's proponents had said Boeing's design would
handicap Boeing in the final contest for the award, which the
Pentagon will make next year.
</P>
<P>
   But Statkus said Boeing didn't copy Lockheed's design. He
acknowledged that the cold thrust nozzle wasn't in Boeing's
original design, but he noted that 80 percent of the downward
thrust from the Boeing JSF design still will come from jet gas.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden appearance of one cold jet nozzle in the Boeing JSF
design surprised aerospace observers. But Frank Cappuccio, Lockheed
Martin's JSF director, declined to gloat, saying he hadn't heard of
Boeing's change.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, they are working on the problem,'' Cappuccio said.
</P>
<P>
   The JSF will be used by the U.S. Air Force, Navy and Marines,
and the British Royal Air Force and the Royal Navy. It will be the
last major fighter contract until 2040 under Pentagon plans.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it is considered a key to corporate success for
Lockheed and Boeing, particularly for the Fort Worth plant that
will build the airplane if Lockheed wins the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are readying the first flights of their JSF
demonstrator models, which are being assembled in California.
Lockheed Martin Vice President Tom Burbage said he believes that
his company's plane will make its first flight before the summer's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Statkus promised a flight within three weeks, but he later
hedged, saying, ``I never like to give a specific date.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, both companies will fly their conventional versions,
without the vertical lift. The vertical lift versions will be flown
later this year or early next.
</P>
<P>
   With no JSFs to put on view at the worldwide air show in
Farnborough, both companies assembled mockups of their designs and
held briefings to tout their progress.
</P>
<P>
   Dain Hancock, president of the Fort Worth-based Lockheed Martin
Aeronautics Co., which runs the local plant, said his plane ``is
very close to the final proposal that we will make, and that's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said too many changes have weakened the Boeing design.
</P>
<P>
   Statkus said the Pentagon's directives to the two companies
``never said that the plane designs had to be consistent. The
design simply has to be affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon guidelines call for a price of $30 million per plane
for the conventional version and $39 million for the vertical lift
version to be used by the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing hasn't built a fighter for the military since before
World War II, focusing instead on bombers and its successful
commercial airliner business. Lockheed Martin, by contrast, has a
history of fighter building going back to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   But Statkus said Lockheed Martin's long fighter history doesn't
give it a leg up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more to this competition than just saying we've built
planes before and we'll do it again,'' Statkus said. ``Boeing has
reinvented the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The aerospace industry has buzzed for almost four years about
Lockheed Martin's unusual vertical lift design, saying that the
cold air thrust was admirable but that the technology had not been
tested and could be expensive. Lockheed Martin acknowledged to a
defense publication that it had to make design changes as recently
as last month because of problems.
</P>
<P>
   But Cappuccio said Lockheed Martin has successfully tested the
crucial change from forward to vertical thrust ``more than 50 times
in the last two weeks without a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
