<HEADLINE>
MAN ARRESTED IN BRICK ATTACK MAY HAVE ALIBI ON VIDEOTAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A homeless man who had been accused of smashing a
woman on the head with a chunk of concrete was ordered released on
Tuesday after prosecutors said that new evidence may exonerate him.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Bently Louis Grant, 35, has spent the last week in a
mental health clinic at the Rikers Island Detention Complex, and
was expected to be released Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sources involved in the investigation said Tuesday that security
videotapes taken from a Virgin Records store in Manhattan may
provide Grant with an alibi, showing that he was at the store when
the attack took place.
</P>
<P>
   The police said last week that they had strong evidence that
Grant attacked Tiffany F. Goldberg on July 9 on a Manhattan street
soon after she left a church. Investigators said their evidence
included three witnesses and a confession that the police said
Grant made during 20 hours of grilling at a precinct house.
</P>
<P>
   After prosecutors presented the new information in court
Tuesday, Justice John P. Walsh of Manhattan State Supreme Court
granted their request that Grant be released.
</P>
<P>
   While Grant remains a suspect, his release would suggest that
whoever attacked Goldberg is still at large. The attack was one of
the most highly publicized crimes in the city this year, and it
recalled a similar n assault in midtown Manhattan last fall in
which on another woman, Nicole Barrett, last fall. had her skull
smashed by a man wielding a paving stone.
</P>
<P>
   After Goldberg was attacked, the police carried out an intense
hunt for the assailant, finally arresting Grant last week.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Tuesday's developments, the Manhattan district
attorney released a statement saying prosecutors ``have discovered
new evidence that raises substantial questions about Grant's
identity as the perpetrator of the crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   A Police Department spokesman, Assistant Chief Thomas P. Fahey,
said Tuesday, ``We're after the truth, wherever it may take us.''
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Lapiner-Giresi, Grant's court-appointed lawyer said that
she was perturbed by Grant's confession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he did not hit Tiffany Goldberg on the head with a
rock, and anything he said about it is because he was questioned
for 20 hours,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has no previous criminal record and kept to himself,
earning a living by recycling cans. Last week, when Police
Commissioner Howard Safir was asked whether Grant had a history of
mental problems, he said, ``Normal people do not hit people over
the head with concrete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
