<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3132 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      07-25 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING LENNY: P-I WRITER LIVED LIFE WITH GRACE, CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Among the human virtues that have fallen out of favor
these days is grace. So much so, I'm not sure I know what it is
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Except when I see it. Lenny Anderson was grace.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was without noise, odd hair or entourage, he was not a
contemporary happening. The man didn't even have his own cable-TV
show or Web site, fergawdsakes.
</P>
<P>
   But for multiple generations of Seattle newspaper readers, as
well as multiple generations of Seattle sportswriters, Lenny was a
figure of delight and respect. Lenny was grace in a felt fedora.
</P>
<P>
   His passing on Sunday at age 79 will not make a splash with
those who did not know him personally, because he didn't sell
himself beyond himself. For those of us privileged to know him over
his 53 years in newspapering, his death is a cold wave of missed
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his example, which was in front of us here at the P-I
from 1964 to his retirement in 1996, none of us ever quite managed
to distill and emulate what it was that created such effortless
charm.
</P>
<P>
   As a writing rule, I avoid the use of the word ``nice'' because
it is so hackneyed and non-descriptive. But neither the computer
thesaurus nor the reading public is ready to accept ``lenny'' as an
alternative adjective. Pity.
</P>
<P>
   Said longtime friend and sports PR man Bill Sears: ``No kinder,
gentler man ever walked the face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   How, in a business where irony and sarcasm are the primary modes
of conversation, could he stay so sincere?
</P>
<P>
   When he asked, ``How are you?'' he wasn't being gratuitous. He
really wanted to know about your life and times. And if things
weren't so good, he would offer to help fix things. If you weren't
careful, he just might.
</P>
<P>
   A few summers ago, I burst into the sports department in a panic
after my car, parked in its familiar expired-time spot, finally was
towed by the cackling constables just before I had to pick up my
wife and in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   My colleagues who weren't laughing were slinking out of the
office. Lenny practically leaped out of his chair to offer me the
use of his car. In my desperation, I said yes, forgetting that
Lenny drove a vintage Lincoln Continental that was operated not
from the driver's seat but a flying bridge.
</P>
<P>
   As I pulled up _ rather, docked _ a look of astonishment swept
over the family's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask,'' I said. ``If it weren't for my stupidity and one
guy's generosity, you'd be walking. Just get in and leave me
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   We spent the evening searching for my car and attempting to
parallel park Lenny's beast. When I finally returned his keys,
exhausted, he gave the quintessential Lenny response:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need it for the weekend, please keep it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, we're good to go, Lenny, thanks anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny's fundamental goodness was endearing to sports figures as
well. Much of the prime of his sportswriting career came when
Seattle was attempting to become a major league sports city. He was
the P-I's baseball beat writer in 1969, the lone year of the
Pilots, when he befriended the club's owner and local civic hero,
Dewey Soriano.
</P>
<P>
   But it was on Lenny's watch that Soriano, beset by debt and
pressure from baseball owners, pulled the most ghastly local sports
deed of the last century _ selling the Pilots after spring training
to a Milwaukee used car dealer named Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very trying time for Lenny,'' said Sears, who worked
for the Pilots. ``He was close to Dewey, as were many in the press.
But even though he felt great empathy, he had to report the bad
news. I gained tremendous respect for him then. He knew what he had
to do, and did it without making Soriano an ogre and fracturing the
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   While others were reporting that the threat to the Pilots was
overblown, Lenny broke a story in early March, 1970, that said
owners were conspiring to pull the plug in Seattle. The headline:
``Seattle Could Still Lose Pilots, P-I Writer Says.''
</P>
<P>
   The editors knew if Lenny put out the story, it was true and the
town had better believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was hard news or a soft feature, Lenny's wordsmithing
was of a rare standard. Humor, poignance, creativity, elegance,
affection for language _ if he were a modern baseball player, he'd
be called a five-tool guy.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, when he took on copy-desk work, Lenny would hear
his deskmates with young families talking about the hassles of
holiday night shifts. As readily as he would lend his car, Lenny
would volunteer to swap shifts. Sometimes, he didn't get paid back.
Never did he say anything.
</P>
<P>
   Said former P-I sports editor Bill Knight: ``As far as I can
remember, Lenny never said a bad word about anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It was easy to spot Lenny in a media crowd, because he dressed
so nattily _ jacket, vest and tie, felt hat in winter, straw hat in
summer. There was no mistaking the words, either _ a wry, dry wit
delivered in a slow rasp.
</P>
<P>
   But the superficial was secondary to the special: A grace that
gave joy to all it touched.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
