<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3143 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-HNS &LR;      07-25 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS STUDENTS SCORE HIGH ON NATIONAL TESTS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELANIE MARKLEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Texas students, building on reforms launched in the
1980s, outperformed peers with similar backgrounds on national
tests measuring education progress, California-based researchers
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller class sizes, well-funded preschool programs and adequate
resources for teachers are key factors that separate top-ranked
Texas from the likes of California, which came in last among 44
states participating in the three-year private study, Rand found.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare the scores of students from similar families,
Texas does very well with respect to other states,'' said David
Grissmer, lead researcher in the Rand study.
</P>
<P>
   Based on an analysis of the National Assessment of Educational
Progress tests given from 1990 to 1996, the study ranks states by
raw scores, scores that compare students with similar backgrounds
and score improvements.
</P>
<P>
   When comparing raw scores, Texas ranks below most other states.
Maine, North Dakota, Iowa, New Hampshire and Montana are at the
top, while Mississippi, Louisiana, California, Alabama and South
Carolina are at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said the states with high raw scores tend to have
fewer minorities, higher family incomes and better-educated
parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas ranked second only to North Carolina in improved
scores _ about twice as great as the national average _ and
outperformed all other states when variations in demographics were
taken into account.
</P>
<P>
   The study was funded by ExxonMobil's education foundation, the
St. Louis-based Danforth Foundation, divisions of the U.S.
Department of Education and Rand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rand report confirms what those of us in Texas have known
for many years _ that Texas is at the forefront in education
reform, leading the nation in achievement gains among minority
students and students from low socioeconomic backgrounds,'' Texas
Education Commissioner Jim Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The study was championed by the major presidential contenders,
George W. Bush and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of the results we have achieved in education in
Texas,'' Bush said from Austin. ``As president, I will achieve the
same results, ensuring that no child is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Douglas Hattaway said the factors
highlighted for improving achievement _ small class size, preschool
and more resources for teachers _ are all central issues in Gore's
education agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report confirms that Al Gore has the right priorities to
help improve our public schools,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the study found that higher teacher salaries,
higher teacher educational levels and increased experience in
teaching do not show significant effects on achievement.
</P>
<P>
   But Grissmer said because of the growing teacher shortage, he
believes salaries will play a larger role in the future.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, it's hard for Bush to take full credit for the
educational reforms that researchers said are making a difference.
Grissmer noted, however, that the governor has continued the
reforms and provided new resources to support them.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller class sizes and the emphasis on preschool were key
elements of a sweeping education reform law approved by the Texas
Legislature in a 1984 special session.
</P>
<P>
   A commission spearheaded by Dallas businessman and former Reform
Party presidential candidate H. Ross Perot recommended the changes,
and former Gov. Mark White, a Democrat, pushed legislation to
support them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Luce, a Republican who was general counsel of Perot's
commission, said the reforms have been sustained through the years
because of strong bipartisan support and the backing of the
business community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think the Perot commission in 1984 gave us a good start,
but all that work really has been continued and propelled along by
Gov. Bush and a whole lot of other people,'' Luce said.
</P>
<P>
   White said that he, former Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby and former
Speaker of the House Gib Lewis fought to raise taxes to pay for the
reforms during difficult economic times.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with a strong economy, White said the state should do
more to raise the educational level even higher and to compete with
the states at the top of the scale in raw scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, averages and that sort of thing that show us
doing quite well when you take out the socioeconomical
differentials really kind of beg the question,'' White said. ``We
are not really doing as well as we should. Now that we've got good
times, why don't we do better?''
</P>
<P>
   The study in particular compares Texas to California. While the
states have similar student demographics, Texas students on average
scored 11 percentage points higher on NAEP math and reading tests
than their California counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Stone, spokesman for the California Department of
Education, said major reforms, including reduced class sizes and an
accountability system, were adopted after the study, which focused
on national test scores through 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``California has a long way to go, but the seeds have been
planted for what we believe will be many years of continued
academic achievement among most of our students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes the study accurately reflects the status
of education in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think NAEP scores give a broad enough view of what is
happening in the schools,'' said Al Kauffman, attorney for the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Kauffman said Texas schools have improved over the past 10 or 12
years, largely because of more equalized funding and smaller class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   But he and others have begun raising questions about the use of
high-stakes standardized tests when measuring educational progress.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, in particular, has been at the forefront of a national
movement to rate schools and promote students on the basis of test
scores.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Haynes, professor of education at Boston College, said a
study he is completing shows that test scores don't tell the whole
story.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes' research shows a high percentage of Texas students,
especially minorities, drop out of high school every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that it's quite implausible to claim that Texas
is doing good work in educating its minorities if you've got 35 and
40 percent dropping out of school before high school graduation,''
said Haynes, who is also a senior research associate in Boston
College's Center for the Study of Testing.
</P>
<P>
   Linda McNeil, co-director of Rice University's Center for
Education, said the Rand study does not address the fact that every
year, 67,000 Texas students drop out of school and 30 percent of
the graduates need remediation before they can start freshmen
classes in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rand numbers could easily distract people from dealing
with the really serious problems that remain in the schools, and by
many other sources of data, are only getting worse,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
