<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CHENEY-BUSH-HNS &LR;      07-25 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PICKS CHENEY AS RUNNING MATE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Washington insider Dick Cheney, who once told George W.
Bush he didn't want the job, agreed Tuesday to be Bush's running
mate, vowing to help ``restore a spirit of civility and respect and
cooperation'' to the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Bush introduced Cheney, a former congressman and secretary of
defense, to a few hundred flag-waving supporters and a horde of
media as a ``distinguished and experienced statesman'' who is
well-respected by Republicans and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked him because he is, without a doubt, fully capable of
being the president of the United States, and I picked him because
he will be a valuable partner in a Bush administration,'' said the
governor, who will claim the Republican presidential nomination
next week at the party's national convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign released physicians' statements supporting the
governor's assurances that Cheney, 59, who has a history of heart
trouble, was now healthy enough to be one heartbeat away from the
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush's spokeswoman, Karen Hughes, noted that Cheney was
working out on a treadmill at his Dallas home when Bush called
early Tuesday morning to offer him the No. 2 spot on the Republican
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Despite spending much of his own career in Washington, Cheney
spoke like an outsider when he predicted that ``big changes are
coming to Washington, and I want to be a part of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for America's leaders to stop pointing the finger of
blame and to begin sharing the credit for success,'' he said,
echoing Bush's frequent call for more bipartisan cooperation in the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's strong anti-abortion record and conservative
credentials, some political analysts believed, made him a safe
choice for Bush among the Republican Party's conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, in an appearance on Larry King Live on CNN,
Cheney said he could agree with Bush's anti-abortion stance, which
would allow exceptions for the procedure to be performed in cases
of rape or incest, or to protect the life of the mother. While in
Congress, Cheney had generally adopted a position that allowed no
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney also has been criticized for voting, while in Congress in
the 1980s, against the Head Start Program, a federal program
boosting educational opportunities for poor children. Cheney said
he has a different view of the program now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not vote against Head Start today,'' he said. He
explained that many of his votes in the 1980s were designed to cut
spending and reduce the federal deficit. He said today's strong
economy better enables government to consider more of the
``compassionate'' programs Bush favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush's choice of Dick Cheney to be his
vice-presidential running mate is great news for Republicans all
across the nation,'' said Susan Weddington, chairman of the Texas
Republican Party, whose leadership is strongly influenced by social
and religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   American Conservative Union Chairman David A. Keene called
Cheney the ``absolute best choice Bush could possibly make.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who was widely reported over the weekend to be Bush's
first choice for vice president, was scheduled to join Bush today
on a quick campaign trip to sparsely populated Wyoming, where
Cheney grew up and which he represented in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and campaign aides publicly revealed for the first time
that Bush had asked Cheney in March whether he would consider being
a vice-presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had been secretary of defense under Bush's father, former
President Bush, and for several months had advised the Texas
governor on his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he declined the first invitation because, ``I was
deeply involved in running a business, enjoying private life, and I
certainly wasn't looking to return to public service.''
</P>
<P>
   After returning to private life, Cheney became chairman of the
board and CEO of the Halliburton Co. in Dallas, a position from
which he will now resign.
</P>
<P>
   On April 25, Bush asked Cheney to head his vice-presidential
selection process but said he kept the thought of Cheney actually
being his running mate ``in the back of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush asked Cheney again about taking the No. 2 spot on the GOP
ticket over the Fourth of July weekend while the two were at Bush's
ranch near Crawford. That time, Cheney said he was willing to talk
with his family about the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he changed his mind after hearing Bush talk ``about
his unique vision for our party and for our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw his sincerity. I watched him make decisions, always firm
and always fair, and in the end, I learned how persuasive he can
be,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Bush nor Cheney took reporters' questions during their
announcement event, which took no more than 15 minutes, in the
Burnt Orange Room of the Frank C. Erwin Center on the University of
Texas at Austin campus.
</P>
<P>
   But Hughes later said that the two men's working relationship
had deepened over the months.
</P>
<P>
   She said 20-30 potential running mates were proposed to Bush but
said she didn't know how many actually were screened. She confirmed
that Bush had met with Govs. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, George
Pataki of New York and John Engler of Michigan and former U.S. Sen.
John Danforth of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Cheney also fulfilled his initial role and gave Bush
a list of alternative running mates, other than himself. But Hughes
said Bush had asked that the other names not be released. Hughes
said Bush occasionally asked his father what he thought of some
potential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cheney, who is five years older than Bush, has had
three heart attacks and one bypass operation, the Bush campaign
released a statement from Cheney's personal physician, Dr. Gary
Malakoff of George Washington Medical Center, that Cheney is in
``excellent health.''
</P>
<P>
   But Malakoff reported that Cheney has a long history of high
cholesterol, which has been successfully treated with medication;
has been treated for skin cancer; has had several minor episodes of
gout of the foot; and takes a ``long list of medications.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has shown no side effects of any of these medications which
would alter intellectual performance or impair his judgment,''
Malakoff wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Another Cheney physician, heart specialist Jonathan S. Reiner of
the George Washington University Medical Center, said Cheney
``travels extensively for work, exercises 30 minutes per day
several days per week on a treadmill and engages in vigorous
recreational activities such as hunting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said that it was satisfied that Cheney's
background has been thoroughly investigated by the FBI over the
years. In addition to serving in Congress and as secretary of
defense _ including during the Persian Gulf War _ Cheney was White
House chief of staff under President Ford and served in the Nixon
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush reviewed Cheney's personal financial
information for potential conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was born in Lincoln, Neb., on Jan. 30, 1941, grew up in
Casper, Wyo., and is a graduate of the University of Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   He is married to his high school sweetheart, the former Lynne
Ann Vincent. They have two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Cheney told her that, after taking Bush's call at
6:22 a.m. Tuesday, he hung up the phone and said to his wife,
``Honey, sell the house. I'm quitting my job; we're going back into
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign even dredged up some old compliments of Cheney
from Vice President Al Gore, the probable Democratic presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good guy. I like him a lot, and he is well liked by
his colleagues,'' Gore was quoted by the Boston Globe in March
1989, when Gore was in the Senate and Cheney was undergoing
confirmation hearings for his defense appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The only slightly awkward moment in the running-mate
announcement occurred when Bush asked the audience to bow their
heads for a few moments in silent memory of Tuesday's Concorde
jetliner crash in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``May God bless their families,'' he said, before abruptly
adding, ``Now, on a happier note, I believe you're looking at the
next vice president of the United States.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
