<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 
Keeping up with Galloway's speed is Aikman' pleasant problem 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Los Angeles Lakers needed to get the
ball into the hands of Shaquille O'Neal to win a world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Joey Galloway, the Cowboys' version of Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the best way to get the ball into Galloway's big hands
and long arms is a significant part of two-a-day practices at
Midwestern State University, where the Cowboys train.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.5 million signing bonus, the $42 million total contract
and the two first-round draft choices sent to Seattle in February
ultimately will be worth it _ or not worth it _ depending on the
frequency that Troy Aikman and Galloway connect this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey has made it clear to me that I can't overthrow him,''
Aikman said. ``So, the first time I do it, write about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is serious about needing to get the ball far enough in
front of Galloway, even though they have had several months of
off-season and training-camp work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just figure I'm going to start throwing it as far as I
can,'' said Aikman, who is entering his 12th season with the
Cowboys. ``I've got about 55 yards left in my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   During workouts], the deep routes involving either Galloway or
speed-mate Rocket Ismail require Aikman to put a lot of air
underneath the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that makes it worse,'' Aikman acknowledged with a wry
smile, ``because then I get only about 48 yards out of my arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposing NFL defensive coordinators are expected to toss and
turn at night trying to devise methods to stop the Cowboys without
burning double teams on two receivers who are faster than most of
the fastest cornerbacks in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know which one is faster,'' Aikman said of the
Galloway-Ismail comparison. ``I would guess that Joey is, but he's
``deceptively'' faster. He doesn't look like he's moving as quick
as Rocket is when they're running. So, for me, it has taken a
little bit of getting used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway said he isn't concerned about Aikman's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be ones that I don't get to and some others
that he underthrows,'' said the three-time 1,000-yard receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Jerry Jones beat Washington Redskins owner Daniel Snyder
to the punch in obtaining Galloway. Jones had heard all the stories
about Galloway being a ``freak of nature,'' but needed to see him
in person to believe such a disproportionate foot size (12 1/2) for
a man who is 5-foot-11, 188 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys wide receiver James McKnight, a teammate of Galloway's
in Seattle, said Galloway received a ``bad rap'' for being timid
about going across the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, however, questions Galloway's elusiveness underneath on
the quick outs or his straight-away speed on the go-routes.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Zampese, the Cowboys' offensive consultant who spent the
past two seasons at New England, said, ``Terry Glenn and Shawn
Jefferson are fast, but they're not Joey Galloway fast. I've had
Terry Glenn tell me, `I'll go up against anybody, but I can't beat
Galloway.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Andre Patterson, the Cowboys' defensive tackles coach who came
from the Minnesota Vikings, said, ``Joey Galloway is the fastest
human being in shoulder pads that I've ever seen, and I saw Randy
Moss.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, Ismail and Aikman can be seen talking frequently in
camp about routes and adjustments on the ball. Communication is
paramount. Aikman and Ismail have had a full season together,
providing a comfort zone for the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the \RGalloway-Ismail\S gap is closing,'' Cowboys
coach Dave Campo said at the conclusion of practice yesterday. ``As
you know, this offense is different than last year's, so Joey and
Rocket are both working \Rto find\S where they need to be and when
they need to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Campo's main concerns in this camp has been dropped balls
_ by all receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our routes are timing-based,'' Campo said, ``so getting out of
those cuts \Raffects\S how the ball is thrown and where it's
thrown. Still, too many drops for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a dropped ball is the only way Galloway or Ismail can
be stopped.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
