r s BC-BBA-REEVES-RODRIGUGEZ     07-25 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-RODRIGUGEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED PUDGE MIGHT FEEL RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We gathered in the little alcove outside the basement elevator
Monday night at The Ballpark in Arlington, maybe two dozen members
of the media from Texas and Southern California, waiting for Pudge
Rodriguez to come and say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   He had just returned from the hospital, where X-rays of his
right thumb confirmed that it had been broken in a first-inning
collision with Mo Vaughn's bat, and the Rangers' efficient PR
machine had graciously summoned us for the last rites.
</P>
<P>
   We already knew the worst by then, of course. Surgery would be
performed on the thumb yesterday afternoon at the Fort Worth
Surgery Center. Pins would hold the fracture together during a
healing period of six to 10 weeks. God willing, he'll again be the
old Pudge we've known and loved in three to five months.
</P>
<P>
   But all that was just medical jargon. It didn't deal with the
tragedy involved, not for the Rangers, who lost their best player,
and certainly not for Rodriguez, who was having yet another career
season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was on his way to phenomenal numbers, particularly for
a catcher. Better numbers than last season, when he was the
league's MVP. Mike Piazza-like numbers. Johnny Bench numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, we expected dejection; bitter disappointment; sadness at
the loss of what might have been; perhaps even a flare of anger at
this unfair turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   What we got, I think, was relief.
</P>
<P>
   The man who stepped out of the trainer's room door, 8-year-old
son Dereck by his side, wasn't dejected. He showed little or no
disappointment or sadness. He wasn't a bit angry or ruffled.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed, well, almost relieved.
</P>
<P>
   Like maybe he wasn't all that unhappy to be leaving this
miserable wreck of a Rangers' season behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team's not going good for a year, a lot of bad things
happen,'' he shrugged matter-of-factly. ``I'll rest it and start
the rehab when they tell me to, and be ready for next spring
training.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pudge, I ventured (sounding very much like a man who had
just lost the heart and soul of his fantasy baseball team), what
about this wonderful career-year you were having? Doesn't it hurt
to see it end so abruptly?
</P>
<P>
   (It was darn sure hurting me.)
</P>
<P>
   Before he was hurt Monday night, Rodriguez was ranked in the top
10 in the American League in batting (.347), home runs (27), RBI
(83), hits (126), total bases (242), slugging percentage (.667) and
doubles (27).
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, he said in so many words.
</P>
<P>
   As owner-GM of the Amon Carter League's Blue Pigs, I wanted to
reach out and slap some sense into him. As a well-seasoned sports
writer, I restrained myself, not wanting to embarrass him in front
of his young son.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always next season,'' he said. ``I have a really,
really strong mind, and this is not going to affect me.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a man with the ultimate confidence that he can pick
up right where he left off next spring. Or by a man who knows all
too well where this season was headed and one who would just as
soon not be directly involved in the pileup.
</P>
<P>
   This is not meant to be unfair to Rodriguez who, after all, is
on the disabled list for only the second time in his 10-year
career. He's a gamer. It's as simple as that. Sure, he has some
thespian in him. He has been known to squeeze extra camera time out
of the various nicks and bruises that a catcher incurs during a
season.
</P>
<P>
   But all you need to know about Rodriguez is that when a
backswing from a bat broke his jaw a couple of years ago, he missed
only one game. He is absolutely no malingerer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what happens when you play hard,'' he said of Monday
night's accident. ``I was throwing the ball hard, like I always do,
throwing the ball hard to second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the half-season I had so far, but there's
always next year. Next year I'm going to come back strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Implied in Rodriguez's statement is the hope that the Rangers,
too, will come back strong after what has been a disappointing and
broken season.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez and Rafael Palmeiro both went on record from Seattle
over the weekend, urging the Rangers to seriously consider
re-signing free-agent-to-be Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, or a hitter like him, might supply an answer to part
of the problem, but certainly not all of it. Gonzalez can't fill
three spots in the rotation. He can't close games if the Rangers
trade John Wetteland. He's not the answer for improved defense or
for a team needing to hit into about half as many double plays as
this one does.
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers must do in the second half of the season is
find solutions to as many of those problems as possible. They've
made a commitment to young pitchers Ryan Glynn, Matt Perisho and
Doug Davis, and that's good. Put them out there and see what they
can do.
</P>
<P>
   They'll take their lumps, as they did in Seattle over the
weekend, but that's the same thing that the White Sox did a couple
of years ago with young starters Mike Sirotka and Jim Parque. Now
those pitchers have helped lead the White Sox to the best record in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Will Darren Oliver do anything to earn the $12 million the
Rangers must pay him over the next two years? Will Gabe Kapler hit
enough to hold onto a starting position? How can they improve their
infield defense? Will Royce Clayton ever smile again?
</P>
<P>
   Tough questions. The Rangers will spend the rest of this lost
season entangled in the painful process of digging for answers.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder a broken thumb and a three-month rest might seem like
a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
