<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY OF DICK CHENEY 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORN: Jan. 30, 1941, Lincoln, Neb. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOMETOWN: Casper, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION: Natrona County High School, Casper, Wyo.; B.A., M.A.,
University of Wyoming; Ph.D. candidate, University of Wisconsin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAREER HIGHLIGHTS: 1968-69, congressional fellow; 1969-70,
special assistant to the director, Office of Economic Opportunity;
1971, White House staff assistant; 1971-73, assistant director,
Cost of Living Council; 1973-74, vice president, Bradley, Woods, &AMP;
Co.; 1974-75, deputy assistant to President Gerald Ford; 1975-76,
White House chief of staff; 1979-1989, U.S. representative at
large, Wyoming; 1980-87, chairman, House Republican Policy
Committee; 1987, chairman, House Republican Conference; 1988, House
Republican whip; ranking Republican member, House Select Committee
to Investigate Covert Arms Deals with Iran; member, House Committee
on Interior and Insular Affairs, House Permanent Select Committee
on Intelligence; 1989-93, secretary of defense under President
George Bush; 1995-2000, chairman and chief executive officer,
Halliburton Co., Dallas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY: Married to the former Lynne Ann Vincent; two daughters,
Elizabeth and Mary. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOBBIES: Hunting, fishing, hiking and skiing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3157 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ART-1STLD     07-25 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SELECTS CHENEY AS HIS VICE PRESIDENTIAL RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Adds 3 grafs bgng, But Cheney appeared ..., with comments
from Cheney on CNN tonight in 2nd take; other minor changes.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos 14-16 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush formally introduced his
running mate, Dick Cheney, to a cheering crowd here Tuesday,
praising the former defense secretary and longtime family friend as
a man of ``great integrity, sound judgment and experience.''
</P>
<P>
   As Cheney stood almost bashfully at the side of the ebullient
Texas governor, Bush tacitly acknowledged the oddity of his
months-long search for a vice-presidential nominee ending with the
selection of the searcher himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney had been tapped by Bush to supervise that process in late
April. But over the ensuing weeks and months, Bush said: ``I
benefited from his keen insight. I was impressed by the thoughtful
and thorough way he approached his mission. And gradually I
realized that the person who was best qualified to be my vice
presidential nominee was working by my side.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cheney took Bush's place at a lectern set up in front of a
row of 30 American flags, his remarks _ only half as long as the
governor's _ suggested that Bush had found a No. 2 with precisely
the kind of loyalty that the governor had always said he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enthusiastically accept the challenge,'' he told Bush, ``for
this reason: I believe you have the vision and the courage to be a
great president. And I want to do absolutely everything I can to
make certain that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it had been clear for days that Cheney would almost
certainly be the governor's choice, their joint appearance in a
large meeting room here Tuesday marked the first formal
acknowledgment by the Bush campaign that Bush-Cheney was the ticket
with which the Republican Party would try to win the White House.
The two men's wives, Laura Bush and Lynne Cheney, shared a modest
stage with them.
</P>
<P>
   In turning to Cheney, Bush chose someone whose extremely
conservative record from 1979 to 1989, when he represented Wyoming
in the House of Representatives and reliably cast votes against
abortion rights and gun control, was sure to provide Democrats and
liberal interest groups with fodder for their assertions that a
Bush presidency would tilt sharply toward the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is probably as far right as anybody in the Republican Party
today,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic
minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The selection also raised questions about how Cheney, who was
entrusted with the task of screening other potential
vice-presidential nominees, was put through the process himself.
Karen P. Hughes, the director of communications for the Bush
campaign, said Tuesday that Bush had taken on at least part of that
chore, subjecting Cheney to the sorts of questions about finances
and other personal information that Cheney had asked other
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appeared to accomplish several goals at once by picking
Cheney. He supplemented his own limited career in government,
confined to the five and a half years that he has presided over the
nation's second largest state, with the accumulated wisdom of a man
who served as chief of staff under President Gerald R. Ford and
then spent a decade in the House before his appointment as defense
secretary in 1989 by President George Bush, the governor's father.
</P>
<P>
   And because the selection of Cheney did not on its face
represent an overtly political calculation, it enabled Bush to
maintain his claim to being someone who is more interested in good
government than political gamesmanship, someone who is more deeply
wedded to principles than to polls. There was no discernible
electoral strategy at work: Cheney maintains homes in Texas and
Wyoming, two states that Bush should easily win in November.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the remarks that Bush and Cheney made Tuesday amounted
to a preview of that pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is seeking not only to win an election, but also
to lead our nation,'' Cheney said in a voice that was softer,
deeper and steadier than Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes earlier, Bush had said: ``I have to admit something. I
didn't pick Dick Cheney because of Wyoming's 3 electoral votes,
although we're going to work hard to earn them. I picked him
because he is without a doubt fully capable of being the president
of the United States. And I picked him because he will be a
valuable partner in a Bush administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The word ``partner'' suggested something else that Bush had been
looking for: someone with whom he felt a strong sense of comfort
and an equally strong sense of trust. Cheney clearly fit that bill,
partly because of his history with Bush's father, partly because he
helped the governor assemble a team of foreign policy advisers last
year and then got to know Bush even better over the last three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously family-tested _ loyal all the way back,'' said
Professor Bruce Buchanan, a historian who teaches courses on the
presidency at the University of Texas and has closely monitored
Bush's career. ``He's comfortable _ they've developed a
relationship as a consequence of this search process.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan suggested that Cheney might also help fill any deficit
of substance that voters perceived in Bush. ``It's in keeping with
the great pains that he has taken all along to build a shadow
government that's made up of people who quiet the fears that he's
shallow and out of his depth,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Many prominent Republicans sold the selection a different way:
as evidence that Bush, 54, was so secure in his own abilities and
confident in his own leadership that he would recruit a teammate
like Cheney, 59, who looks at least 10 years older than the
governor and has a much longer political resume. Alternately,
Republicans said that Cheney's selection was proof that Bush was
earnestly filling in the gaps in his own experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sending a powerful signal that he's continuing his
preparations to become the president,'' said Gov. John Engler of
Michigan in a telephone interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Engler and other Republican leaders expressed enthusiasm about
the choice, saying that Cheney had a reputation on both sides of
the political aisle as a thoughtful, reasonable, intelligent
politician.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi said that when
Cheney worked on Capitol Hill, ``he was not the kind of guy who was
threatening or in your face or, you know, partisan to the extent
that others didn't feel like they could work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick Cheney is just one of those people, if you're around him
any length of time, you just feel very comfortable with him,'' Lott
said. ``You grow to have a healthy respect for him.'' Lott added
that he had told Cheney several months ago that he would be the
best choice for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, whom many House Republicans had
promoted for a place on the ticket with Bush, said Tuesday that
Cheney's ``leadership skills are proven in many areas. He has an
incredibly impressive resume.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least a few other Republicans were puzzled. They
questioned why Bush, who has pledged to expand the party's appeal
and bring a fresh perspective to Washington, would pick a running
mate with such conservative bearings and such strong ties to the
Republican establishment of the past.
</P>
<P>
   And they wondered why Bush, long eager to emerge from his
father's shadow, would summon it anew with the choice of someone
from his father's cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks to a lot of observers _ and there's a lot of buzz
about this _ like this reflects his father's influence,'' said one
Republican strategist. ``And the campaign has spent two years
saying that his father doesn't have a big influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican strategist said, ``For all the running away
he's done from his father, now he's Velcroed himself to the old
man. It's the old Bush. It's just unfortunate. The Democrats are
gloating.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Tuesday that the only active role that former
President Bush had played in the process, other than being a
sounding board for his son, was to call a prominent cardiac surgeon
who is a family friend and ask him for his opinion on Cheney's
health. Cheney suffered three mild heart attacks more than a decade
ago and had bypass surgery in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers moved quickly Tuesday to dispel any doubts about
Cheney's physical fitness for the long road to November _ and
possibly beyond. The Bush campaign released letters from Cheney's
doctors at George Washington University that provided a detailed
synopsis of Cheney's medical history.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference after Bush's introduction of Cheney, Hughes
was even able to answer a question about the specific food allergy
mentioned in one of these reports. The allergy was to pomegranates,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes also made a point of mentioning that when Bush, at home
in the governor's mansion Tuesday morning, placed a telephone call
to Cheney's house in Dallas to offer him a place on the Republican
ticket, Cheney was exercising on his treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cheney did not take questions from reporters, instead
sticking to the statements they had prepared.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney appeared on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' Tuesday night
to give his first interview as Bush's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   He said the role he would play in a new, second Bush
administration would be that of a frank but discreet adviser. ``He
very much values people who level with him, who tell him exactly
what they think,'' Cheney said. ``I'm most effective when I'm able
to speak my piece, but also when I do it privately.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had found a real chemistry with Bush, and
earlier in the day, he, Bush and Hughes had provided some details
about the evolution of the relationship between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   According to these accounts, Bush had asked Cheney in March,
right after the governor effectively secured his party's
presidential nomination, if he would be willing to be considered
for the vice presidential nomination. Cheney said no.
</P>
<P>
   But about three weeks ago, Hughes said, Bush asked Cheney again,
and drew a different response.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' Bush said, ``he said he was willing to talk with
his family and consider it.'' He smiled broadly, and Cheney reached
over to his wife, Lynne, patted her on the shoulder, then held a
pair of crossed fingers in the air. The crowd of about 200
supporters and friends of the Texas governor laughed loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney provided an unusual physical counterpoint to Bush, whose
facial expression and demeanor conveyed an almost boyish
excitement. Cheney, by contrast, seemed to be trying to hide his
grin. He often cast his eyes downward and could not decide what to
do with his hands, which were alternately deep in his pockets and
clasped modestly in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were scheduled to take a campaign trip to Wyoming on
Wednesday, and Bush's aides said that on Friday, when Bush begins a
five-day trek to the Republican national convention in
Philadelphia, Cheney will accompany him for the first day's stops
in Arkansas and Missouri. Aides said that Cheney will then return
to Dallas, where he is chief executive of Halliburton, an energy
company, to put some business affairs in order before turning his
full attention toward the presidential race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
