<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CHENEY-VOTE-1STLD-WRI     07-25 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-VOTE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY WAS ONE OF THE MOST CONSERVATIVE VOICES IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS last graf with 4 grafs to add Cheney's comments on CNN
tonight; minor changes elsewhere.) 
(With BUSH-CHENEY) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his 10 years as a Republican congressman from
Wyoming, Dick Cheney had one of the most consistently conservative
voting records in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He regularly voted for the tightest restrictions on abortions,
including proposals to ban Medicaid coverage of abortions for poor
women whose lives could be endangered by continued pregnancy. And
he voted against all gun-control legislation, including measures
that were supported by all but a handful of lawmakers from both
parties, like one bill to regulate what are known as cop-killer
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   On issues in which business and labor were on opposite sides, he
invariably supported the business position. When developers and
environmentalists were at odds, he was on the side of the
developers.
</P>
<P>
   He opposed a constitutional amendment to guarantee equal rights
to women and voted against economic sanctions on South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   During Cheney's time in Congress, from 1979 to 1989, Democrats
controlled the House. As is normally the case with lawmakers in the
minority party, he was not directly responsible for any major
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   While rigidly conservative on issues, he was not known for
strident rhetoric and was well liked by Democrats. Cheney was not a
visible leader in the fight to outlaw abortion, but the National
Right to Life Committee said Tuesday that he voted against abortion
rights on all the roll calls for which he was present.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he voted in 1984 to define ``person'' under
discrimination laws to include fetuses. The sponsor of the measure,
which Al Gore, then a congressman, also supported, said its purpose
was to deny federal funds to all institutions performing abortions.
Cheney also supported a constitutional amendment banning abortion,
but the issue never came to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   He was an unwavering advocate of the Reagan administration's
economic policy of deep tax cuts, more spending for the military
and less money for social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Annual vote analyses by Congressional Quarterly showed that in
most of the years he was in the House, Cheney supported President
Ronald Reagan more consistently than almost any other member of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In only his second term, he moved into the Republican
leadership, and by the time he left, to become secretary of defense
under President Bush, he was the Republican whip, the No. 2
position. Had he stayed in the House, he might well have become
speaker when Republicans gained control in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his leadership responsibilities, Cheney was most deeply
involved in foreign policy and intelligence matters. He strongly
supported covert spending for guerrilla forces trying to oust the
communist governments in Nicaragua and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Cheney served as the top Republican on the House
committee investigating the Iran-contra affair. The committee
determined that the Reagan administration had secretly sold arms to
Iran and had used the proceeds to finance the rebels, known as
contras, in Nicaragua. Cheney voted against the final report, which
accused Reagan of failing to meet his constitutional mandate to
``take care that the laws be faithfully executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some issues important when Cheney was in Congress are no longer
in the news. For example, he repeatedly voted to produce the MX
missile, a hugely expensive weapon designed to carry 10 nuclear
warheads that was the symbol of what opponents considered the
excesses of the Reagan nuclear weapons policy.
</P>
<P>
   He also often voted against proposals to apply economic
sanctions on South Africa to protest that country's apartheid
policy. He even voted in 1986 against a nonbinding congressional
resolution calling for the release of Nelson Mandela from prison.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year in Congress, Cheney voted for a constitutional
amendment to ban busing for school desegregation. In 1980, he voted
against strengthening the laws banning discrimination in housing.
</P>
<P>
   The only time he turned against the Reagan administration on an
important issue was in 1985, when he helped lead a Republican
revolt against a bill negotiated by the president and Democrats to
overhaul the federal income tax system. He accused the
administration of selling out. Even after the bill was further
modified by the Republican-controlled Senate and came back to the
House in 1986, he voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan signed the tax bill and considered it one of his foremost
legislative accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Many other issues of Cheney's time in Congress will be top items
in this year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On gun control, he was one of just 21 House members to vote
against a bill regulating the manufacture, import and sale of
armor-piercing ammunition known as cop-killer bullets. He was one
of four who voted in 1988 against a proposal to ban firearms that
did not contain enough metal to be picked up by a metal detector.
</P>
<P>
   On education, Cheney often voted against Head Start, the federal
preschool program. He voted in 1985 against federal aid to college
students, and he opposed the creation of the Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   On the environment, he voted in 1987 against extending the Clean
Water Act and in favor of postponing sanctions against cities that
did not comply with it.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Tuesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live,'' Cheney
discussed his conservative record and said ``I'm proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that some of his votes against certain programs in
the 1980s were motivated by his concern for fiscal responsibility
in an era when the nation did not have the projected surpluses it
has today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not vote against Head Start today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also spoke in a tempered voice about abortion. ``I don't
think it should be a defining issue for our party,'' he said,
adding that the party needed to be sensitive to different views
about abortion rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
