<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-SURHOFF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES INSIST THE YANKEES' OFFER JUST DOESN'T CUT IT
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The two-prospect offer the Yankees made on Monday
for the Orioles' B.J. Surhoff was apparently not good enough, given
that on Tuesday the Baltimore general manager compared it to a
particularly aromatic cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Syd Thrift, the Orioles' executive, generally talked around
questions about the Yankees' offer, which included pitcher Dave
Walling, the Yankees' No. 1 draft pick in 1999, along with another
player to be selected from a group of three minor leaguers: the
Class AA pitcher Brian Rogers, the Class AA shortstop Erick Almonte
and the Class AAA pitcher Ryan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   But when Thrift was asked if the Yankees' offer was close to
being satisfactory, he said: ``Far, yes. Close, no. Way, way far.
You can't even smell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close to being like Limburger cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the proposal earlier, Thrift said, ``Just
because you were born at night doesn't mean it was last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrift could be bluffing, in an attempt to extract a better
offer from the Yankees. More likely, he is serious; talks between
the Orioles and the Yankees regarding Surhoff have repeatedly
stalled. Before the Yankees swapped Ricky Ledee and two pitching
prospects to Cleveland for David Justice last month, they offered
essentially the same deal for Surhoff and were rebuffed by Thrift.
</P>
<P>
   Thrift's suggestion that the Yankees' offer stinks, literally,
probably won't help the chances of the dialogue continuing, so the
Yankees officials will continue to explore other options. They know
what it will take to make a deal for Montreal's Rondell White
(Alfonso Soriano), as well as Pittsburgh's Wil Cordero and
Oakland's Matt Stairs (the Athletics recently asked for Ramiro
Mendoza, again).
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the Yankees don't seem particularly intrigued by any
one possibility. The likes of Cleveland's Manny Ramirez, Houston's
Moises Alou and Kansas City's Johnny Damon do not appear to be
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres were prepared to make a deal for Atlanta's
Brian Jordan, in order to then ship him to the Yankees for a
package of players, but the Yankees do not want to absorb Jordan's
five-year, $40 million contract, which he signed before last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff, 35, said he had heard nothing about the Yankees' offer
before reporters approached him Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even going to speculate on anything with the Yankees,
because I play for the Orioles,'' said Surhoff, who repeated that
his first preference is to play for Baltimore now and in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Surhoff has another year remaining on his contract, but an
option for the 2002 season should easily vest, with Surhoff
scheduled to make $3.5 million in 2001 and $4.5 million in his
option. Knoblauch Injured
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch was not in the starting lineup for Tuesday's
game because of irritation in the inside of his right (throwing)
elbow, and he will go to New York on Wednesday for tests, including
an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch apparently felt the twinge in his elbow while making
an awkward throw at the end of a rundown in Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, referred to Knoblauch's problem
as minor, and Knoblauch worked out before tonight's game and was
available to pinch-hit.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the Yankees' impressions on injuries have not
been accurate. Ramiro Mendoza said he felt discomfort in his elbow,
and shortly after Torre insisted to reporters that Mendoza's arm
was fine, the pitcher was placed on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez has said repeatedly that his elbow bothers
him, and despite three diagnoses from three doctors that resulted
in identical findings _ that Hernandez does not have any major
problems _ Hernandez is on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said after Monday's game that Roger Clemens had no injury
when he paused during the sixth inning and Torre and a trainer
tended to him, and several minutes later, Clemens said he
experienced cramps in his right quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza allowed six hits and three runs in three innings tonight
in a Class A Florida State League game tonight, in perhaps his last
rehabilitation appearance before he is activated. It is expected
that Mendoza will be activated at some point during the four-game
series the Yankees will begin in Minnesota on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw off flat ground again Tuesday and assuming he
has no setbacks, he will throw in a bullpen session Wednesday. He
could be a couple of weeks away from being activated, if he
progresses as the Yankees hope he will.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Watson, who is on the disabled list because of weakness in
the back of his throwing shoulder, threw about 45 pitches in a
bullpen workout Tuesday at the Yankees' complex in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's primary concern was to rebuild the velocity in his
fastball _ which had dropped from 90 miles an hour to about 81
before he was placed on the disabled list _ and the initial
indications are that his fastball is better.
</P>
</TEXT>
