<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIJA BATTLE, 37, DESIGNER OF FURS FOR MUSIC WORLD CELEBRITIES
</HEADLINE>
  By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nija Battle, who brought a swaggering sense of sophistication to
the furs she designed for the music world's most flamboyant
figures, died last Thursday while on a business trip in Montreal.
She was 37.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a brain aneurysm, said her sister, Saddiya Battle.
</P>
<P>
   For a designer who did not have a store, who often met her
future clients at clubs or outside restaurants, and who, until the
editor Andre Leon Talley wrote about her in Vogue last year, was
almost unknown in the fashion world, Battle had a large following.
Her custom-made furs were worn by entertainers like Whitney
Houston, Lil' Kim, Kid Rock and Puff Daddy, who had her make
trousers for him in black sheared mink.
</P>
<P>
   And although much of the attention at the Costume Institute's
``Rock Style'' gala at the Metropolitan Museum of Art last December
was focused on fashion nabobs like Tom Ford of Gucci and Donatella
Versace, it was Battle of Brooklyn who designed the wraps worn by
Naomi Campbell, Iman, Lynn Whitfield and Mary J. Blige.
</P>
<P>
   Battle began making furs about 10 years ago, though in a sense,
she started as a child when she and her sister would take skins
given to them by their father, an avid hunter, and turn them into
blankets and doll clothes. The family lived in Brooklyn but had
relatives in North Carolina, and Battle, who was part Tuscarora
Indian, often visited a grandmother there who raised minks.
</P>
<P>
   After getting experience with Orchard Street furriers, Battle
started her own business and gradually gained a following among rap
and hip-hop stars who saw her out wearing her own designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people like Puff Daddy were photographed for magazines,
they'd say to the stylists, `I'm wearing my own coat,''' recalled
her sister. They meant, of course, Battle's furs. She also created
coats for a number of sports stars, and, on occasion, made
identical styles for their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
   Her custom-made designs, often dyed in colors like champagne,
burgundy and green, projected a high urban style _ what Talley
called ``a ghetto fabulousness'' _ that not only appealed to
Battle's celebrated clientele but also evoked 1970s fashion. She
was certainly among the first designers to recognize the appeal of
reviving that era.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her sister, she is survived by her mother,
Gladys, and her brother, Saleem Muhammad, both of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CHENEY-PROCESS-N     07-25 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHENEY-PROCESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY AS THE FINALIST: BUSH DID THE SCREENING 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Story, eliminated earlier, is now restored for publication.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the end, it was Gov. George W. Bush himself
who did the final, most sensitive background check on the man who
was supposed to be the one running the vice presidential screening
process.
</P>
<P>
   So just as Dick Cheney, the former defense secretary, had met
with other finalists to go over questions about their personal
lives and finances, Bush questioned Cheney. As Karen P. Hughes,
Bush's spokeswoman put it, ``In this case, Governor Bush served as
the chair of the search committee.''
</P>
<P>
   That was just one of the oddities of a vice-presidential search
process that turned in on itself.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, in fact, only a couple of weeks ago Cheney flew to
Washington to conduct interviews with some of the other candidates.
But at the same time, he quietly visited his doctors for a
physical. The next day, July 12, his doctors gave him a clean bill
of health, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   And that night he called Bush to tell him there was no reason
why he could not accept the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the same time, he continued the search process, Hughes
said, because he wanted to make sure Bush had other options.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's courtship of Cheney began in March, just after the
Republican primaries had ended. Bush said he asked if Cheney would
be willing to be considered as a running mate. ``At the time,''
Bush said Tuesday, ``he said no.''
</P>
<P>
   So the governor instead on April 25 named Cheney, now chief
executive of a giant oil field service company in Dallas, as the
head of his vice-presidential search process. But even then, he
said Tuesday, ``I kept the thought of him joining me in the back of
my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Bush sent out hundreds of letters to party
leaders asking for their input. A list of vice-presidential
finalists received detailed questionnaires asking about their
health, their finances, their voting records, their military
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me two weeks to pull together everything required on
that vast questionnaire,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel of Nebraska. ``It
meant getting my business partners involved, my accountants
involved, tax people, doctors, my staff, family. The questionnaire,
as you can imagine is rather intense. It's your whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel praised Cheney's selection, despite the work he had had to
do. ``My goodness, here's a guy who has the character, the
competence, the experience, the ability,'' Hagel said. ``I don't
have any problem with that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The questionnaires came back to the campaign. But this month
once again, Bush circled back to Cheney. It was the Fourth of July
weekend, and the two men were reviewing options at Bush's ranch.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, the two men walked out to the back porch and once
again Bush asked Cheney whether he would be willing to be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed,'' Bush said Tuesday, ``by the thoughtful and
thorough way he approached his mission. And gradually I realized
that the person who was best qualified to be my vice-presidential
nominee was working by my side.''
</P>
<P>
   This time Cheney said yes.
</P>
<P>
   So Cheney began reviewing not just a handful of finalists, but
also himself. ``He knew, he said, at that point that he would have
to begin looking at his own business, his own medical records, his
own background,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the search continued. That week Bush discussed the vice
presidency with Gov. George Pataki of New York on a campaign trip
into New Jersey and New York.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, on July 15, Bush summoned his three top aides _
Hughes, Karl Rove and Joe Allbaugh _ to meet with him, his wife,
Laura, and Cheney. ``We talked through the ramifications of the
leader of the search becoming a potential candidate in that
search,'' Hughes said. Rove, Bush's chief strategist, declined
Tuesday to spell out the considerations but said, ``Obviously, they
were not grave.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the vetting of Cheney began. Allbaugh, the
campaign manager, oversaw the examination of Cheney's voting record
and public history. How well he did should soon become apparent.
Already Tuesday night, on his first television appearance, on CNN's
``Larry King Live,'' Cheney was answering questions about his
congressional vote against the Head Start program and his
uncompromising opposition to abortion in all cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said Cheney's past was not unknown territory.
Cheney, who had a long government career, had been screened by the
FBI three times and had undergone Senate confirmation hearings. As
defense secretary under President Bush, he had held the nation's
highest security clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Bush decided he wanted an independent review of
Cheney's health. He called his father and asked him to ask his
friend, the noted Houston heart surgeon, Denton A. Cooley, to speak
to Cheney's doctors.
</P>
<P>
   On July 18, Bush and Cheney met with another of the
vice-presidential contenders, John C. Danforth, a former senator
from Missouri, and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Bush himself at some point talked with Cheney about
his personal and financial background, but she did not provide
further details. After leaving his defense post, Cheney became the
chief executive officer of the Halliburton Company, a worldwide oil
field services company that has paid him millions of dollars in
salary and stock options.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Bush's father was taking an interest in the
search, and a specific interest in Cheney. Hughes described the
former president's role Tuesday as ``that of a loving father,''
ready to lend an ear to his son. Asked if the former president
supported Cheney above all candidates, she said she was ``sure he
spoke highly of several of them.'' She said she did not know
whether he had personally called Cheney to lobby him.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, Bush called Cheney at his home in Dallas and
asked him to be his running mate. Hours later they stood together
here in Austin before a crowd waving red white and blue pompoms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' Cheney said of Bush, ``I learned how persuasive
he can be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
