<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BRAND'S PITCH, FREE AGENTS NOT LURED TO BULLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KHARY K. McGHEE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Elton Brand was supposed to be the beginning,
the cornerstone of the Chicago Bulls' plan to rebuild a team
decimated by the loss of its championship trio of Michael Jordan,
Scottie Pippen and Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   With Brand, the No. 1 pick in the 1999 NBA Draft, and Ron
Artest, the No. 16 pick in the same draft, the Bulls hoped to
construct a solid team by adding quality veterans from this
summer's talent-rich class of free agents. The team cleared nearly
$19 million in salary-cap room, going 17-65 with bargain-basement
players such as Dickey Simpkins, Fred Hoiberg and Corey Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls have not been able to spend any of that money on
the free agents they coveted: Tim Duncan, Grant Hill, Eddie Jones,
Tracy McGrady and Tim Thomas. And Brand, an active recruiter for
the Bulls in the free-agent sweepstakes, is not happy the Bulls
have seemingly failed to lure any big names to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been tough not being able to sign the top free agents,''
Brand said during a basketball camp for youngsters. ``It's not over
until it's over. But it's tough, especially since I know what a
great city Chicago is.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams may negotiate with free agents this month, but free agents
may not sign until Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Brand said he went to dinner last weekend with Thomas, a forward
for the Milwaukee Bucks and the Bulls' latest free-agent target,
trying to convince him to come to Chicago. But Thomas has said he
will re-sign with the Bucks, making him the third player to spurn
the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan will re-sign with the San Antonio Spurs, while Hill and
McGrady have said they will go to Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a guard with the Charlotte Hornets, hasn't decided where
he'll sign, but there have been reports he will land with the Miami
Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been taking all the guys out, telling them what's going
on, letting them know what we're all about,'' Brand said. ``It's
hard to lure a player from the team that they're with.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bulls will rely on Brand, who led them in scoring (20.1)
and rebounding (10) last season. The Bulls added five rookies in
last month's NBA Draft, including Big 12 Player of the Year Marcus
Fizer and Jamal Crawford, a guard who left Michigan after his
freshman year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want \Rto be the only leader\S,'' Brand said. ``I want
some veteran leadership on the team. Hopefully, we can get some
veteran starters to come help this team.'' \Ntagtop:Khary K.
McGhee, (817) 548-5419 \Ntagbottom:kmcghee\Nstar-telegram.com
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
