<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DOUTY-SOFTBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOFTBALL STAR REACHING OUT TO URGE GIRLS TO PURSUE SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAWN REISS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Always a dreamer, Sheila Douty has a chance to share her dreams
in her new children's book, ``You Can be a Woman Softball Player''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that I can encourage and inspire young ladies to pursue
sports, particularly softball,'' Douty, 38, said. ``I want them to
learn that if they work hard at something, they, too, can achieve
their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The book discusses Douty's life and the basic fundamentals of
softball with drills. Douty's work is one in a series of ``You Can
Be a Woman'' books written for girls 8-14. The series offers
insight into careers traditionally dominated by men, such as
engineering, marine biology, architecture and athletics. Douty's
co-author is Judith Love Cohen, who helped design and engineer the
Hubble telescope.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need for lots of books like these, so little girls
have female role models to look up to,'' said Douty, who lives in
Diamond Bar, Calif., east of Los Angeles. ``I feel we all have
obligations as role models, and this is just one way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Quiet Thunder,'' Douty doesn't brag about her
accomplishments, but has come through time and again with
resounding plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is the backbone of softball and has made an impact on the
national level,'' said UCLA head softball coach Sue Enquist, who
coached Douty from 1981-84. ``She's methodical and intellectualizes
the game, and she's clutch. She remains a quiet hero in our
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the first U.S. Olympic softball team in 1996, Douty
proved her worth in gold. Down one with the tying run at first,
Douty cracked a home run to win Team USA's gold-medal game against
China.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 U.S. Olympic Cup, Douty hit a two-run homer in the
bottom of the seventh that gave the United States a 3-2 victory
against Australia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is an unsung hero in my eyes and to many others,'' Olympic
teammate Jennifer McFalls said. ``She really gets it done for us on
and off the field. She isn't the most glamorous, and she doesn't
jump in front of the camera. She just gets it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Douty has continued to deliver game-winning hits during Team
USA's 31-city tour in preparation for the 2000 Summer Olympics on
Sept. 15-Oct. 1 in Sydney, Australia. In her most recent game, Team
USA's 2-0 victory against the Florida Wahoos on Sunday, Douty drove
in the winning run with a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the person that everybody on the team goes to when they
need a strong opinion,'' Douty's husband, Joel, said. ``While they
don't have captains, she's the honorary captain, and the whole team
values what she has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Team USA (36-0) plays tomorrow in Oklahoma City before coming to
Gateway Park in Fort Worth, Texas, for a doubleheader Saturday. The
Olympians play the Fort Worth Stars at 6:30 p.m. and the Katy
Cruisers at 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in a Los Angeles suburb, Douty wanted nothing more
than to be the next first basemen for the Dodgers, following in the
footsteps of her hero, Steve Garvey.
</P>
<P>
   Douty never made it to the Dodgers, but she did play first base
at UCLA. She was a member of the Pacific-10 all-decade softball
team in the 1980s, helping the Bruins win national titles in 1982
and 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Douty continued to play internationally while earning her
masters degree in physical therapy from Southern California. Then,
she played for the Stratford (Conn.) Raybestos Brakettes and the
California Commotion while working as a physical therapist.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to make softball her career in 1994, when softball
was made an Olympic sport. Now, she must train even harder to
compensate for her age and persistent calf and leg injuries. She
relies on visualization techniques to practice hitting and
fielding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm normally someone who just pushes, pushes, pushes,'' Douty
said. ``but now it's less quantity and more quality with mental
training.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Douty's last Olympics, and her expectations are
high. She wants to win gold and predicts Australia will be Team
USA's toughest competitor because they are the only team to beat
the U.S. in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Even after her career is over, Douty still has dreams for future
softball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are on the brink of a huge uprising of female
athletics,'' she said. ``Young ladies have grown up being
encouraged to play sports at young ages, and because of that, we
are seeing better and better athletes.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
