<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TAKAZAUKAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT TAKAZAUCKAS, 56; DIRECTOR OF PLAYS AND OPERAS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albert Takazauckas, who directed the original New York
production of David Mamet's ``Sexual Perversity in Chicago'' and
``Duck Variations'' and went on to a career as a director of plays
and operas, died on Monday in Los Angeles. He was 56 and lived in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   According to his father, Albert Takazauckas, he was having
dinner in a restaurant and apparently suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   The two Mamet one-act plays, which opened at St. Clement's in
1975, represented the playwright's New York debut. In his review in
The New York Times, Mel Gussow wrote that the plays were ``fresh
and pungent comedies about the rivalry within friendship and man's
natural propensity for role playing.'' About ``Sexual Perversity,''
he said, ``As directed by Albert Takazauckas, the play is a
multipaneled comic strip. . . The work on all counts is unforced
and spontaneous.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Takazauckas specialized in opera and directed
for regional companies around the United States, including ``Madame
Butterfly'' and ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' for San Francisco's Western
Opera Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, he directed Hugo Weisgall's opera ``Six
Characters in Search of an Author'' (based on the Pirandello play)
at the Opera Festival of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   In his review in The New York Times, Anthony Tommasini said that
the director's ``handling of the six rootless characters was very
compelling. . . . grim, unnerving figures, ageless and bound
forever to their creator's conception.''
</P>
<P>
   Takazauckas was born in Manhattan. In addition to his father,
who lives in Manhattan, he is survived by a sister, Victoria, of
Bloomfield, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
