<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHENEY-ANALYSIS-KAN &LR;      07-25 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-ANALYSIS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICK CHENEY CERTAINLY CAPABLE; CAN HE HELP WIN THE ELECTION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smart. Loyal. Experienced. Everything you want in a vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Except maybe one thing: Will Dick Cheney help George W. Bush win
the election?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheney may bring a lot to the job, but he doesn't bring a lot
to the campaign,'' said Stuart Rothenberg, an independent political
analyst. ``Bush had an opportunity to take a step toward winning
the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, he basically said: `I'm ahead. I'm going to win this
anyway. Dick Cheney will be a terrific vice president. I'm not
going to worry about the Electoral College side of this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former Wyoming congressman, doesn't add any states to
Bush's totals; Wyoming is a heavily Republican state. He doesn't
boost Bush in the polls, at least according to early soundings. And
he's no world-beater on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bush acknowledged the lack of a political consideration in
his choice.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, Bush said he hadn't picked Cheney
``because of Wyoming's three electoral votes....I picked him
because he is without doubt capable of being president of the
United States and will be a valuable partner in a Bush
administration.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether a vice president should help the nominee
win the election has long been debated.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Richard Nixon once said the first consideration
in picking a vice president is whether he is qualified to be
president. The second: Would he be a good vice president?
</P>
<P>
   And third, Nixon said, how good a candidate will the vice
president be?
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course, the third is always first because unless
you're a good candidate, you're not going to have a chance to
demonstrate either of the other two,'' Nixon said in 1988 on NBC's
``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush had more politically appealing options. He could have
selected Arizona's Sen. John McCain, who late in the process said
he wanted the job. He could have gone with popular Pennsylvania's
Sen. Tom Ridge, who likely would have tipped that crucial state in
Bush's favor.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was retired Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big missed opportunity for the Republicans: George
W. Bush's failure to get Colin Powell to go on his ticket,'' said
Earl Black, a Rice University political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney's lengthy list of accomplishments could prove
invaluable. He is considered a Washington ``wise man,'' a veteran
of Washington's political wars, having served as the youngest chief
of staff in history when at 34 he was asked to run Gerald Ford's
White House. As defense secretary from 1989 to 1993, his greatest
triumph was the nation's resounding victory in the Persian Gulf
War.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, as a six-term congressman from Wyoming, he was known
for his consistent conservative stances on myriad issues, including
gun control, defense spending and taxes. Still, he was known for
his ability to work with Democrats. He became one of President
Ronald Reagan's most reliable supporters.
</P>
<P>
   By picking Cheney, an abortion foe, Bush can keep the GOP base
intact. Bush has said that consideration has been uppermost in his
mind, given the tendency of Republicans to split apart over the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   That Cheney possesses the international and Washington
experience that Bush lacks could be a winning combination, said
Benjamin Ginsberg, a Johns Hopkins University political scientist.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, presidential nominees picked their running mates
based on a need to balance the ticket geographically or to appease
a certain wing of the party.
</P>
<P>
   But the new style has more to do with the presidential nominee
trying to round out his personality, Ginsberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's voting choice for president is such a personal one for
each voter,'' Ginsberg said. ``It's based on so many issues
involving the personality and character of the (presidential and
vice presidential) nominees that more and more candidates are
looking to augment and supplement their personal characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats insist they are undaunted by the Cheney choice. Look
for them to turn Cheney's experience against him. Roy Temple,
executive director of the Missouri Democratic Party, said Bush's
selection is a turn to the past, not something new and dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's old guard,'' he said. ``If they want to go back to the
recession and deficits of the Bush era, they have their chance
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-night talk-show hosts, meantime, were having a field day
with Cheney's health. He has suffered three heart attacks, the
first in 1978. In 1988, he underwent quadruple bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the time it took me to walk out here, Dick Cheney had five
more heart attacks,'' Jay Leno said to open his Monday night
monologue.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts dismissed Cheney's health as an overriding concern.
Cheney, they point out, managed to oversee the Gulf War without
problems. And other prominent politicians, most notably former
President Lyndon Johnson, went on to lengthy public careers
following devastating health problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Johnson suffered a major heart attack just six months
after he became Senate majority leader and spent weeks in recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats may also try to highlight Cheney's ties to the oil
industry. He made millions from his five-year association as
chairman of Dallas-based Halliburton Corp., a leading engineering
and construction firm focused on oil companies. Bush also has long
ties to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   But said Rothenberg, ``I'd be surprised if it turned the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   How all this affects Democrat Al Gore's thinking on a running
mate remains to be seen. Some insiders immediately dismissed former
Sen. George Mitchell of Maine as a logical choice. He may too
closely resemble Cheney as a wise man from the past.
</P>
<P>
   After the Cheney pick, Gore is free to go in almost any
direction he wants, Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can go old, he can go north, he can go political or
non-political,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000725.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-25 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT &LR;      07-25 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAILURE AT CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, July 26:
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the Camp David talks is a wrenching setback for
Israel, the Palestinians and the cause of Mideast peace. Israel's
prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, came remarkably close to agreement on some of the most
difficult issues of the 52-year-old conflict. But they stumbled at
the most sensitive point, sovereignty over East Jerusalem. On that
subject Barak found Arafat unprepared to make the kind of hard
compromises needed to seal an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   There is now only a remote chance that a comprehensive peace
settlement can be reached before the Sept. 13 deadline the two
leaders have set. It will be difficult enough just to keep the
Middle East conflict from flaring into renewed tensions and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat deserve credit for coming to Camp David and,
for the first time, seriously discussing issues like borders,
refugees and Jerusalem. So does President Clinton, who committed
much time and energy to the talks and made extraordinary efforts to
keep the two sides engaged. Arranging the marathon meeting was a
risk, but it was a chance that had to be taken.
</P>
<P>
   On virtually every issue, previously unthinkable compromises
were discussed. But under the ground rules, none of these advances
will be binding absent an overall accord. Realistically, neither
leader has much chance of winning public support for painful
compromises unless they are part of a deal that delivers a final
peace. Nevertheless, the new understandings reached need not
evaporate. They may be revived if discussions on a comprehensive
agreement resume.
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, both sides will have to look more
creatively, and courageously, at Jerusalem. The larger burden lies
with Arafat. When the talks began two weeks ago, Israel was
insisting on retaining full sovereignty over East and West
Jerusalem while the Palestinians demanded a full return of the
East, including the Old City and its religious sites. Barak moved
far from his initial position, agreeing to consider expanded
Palestinian sovereignty over parts of East Jerusalem. Arafat,
encouraged by Egypt and Saudi Arabia to be unyielding, showed
little interest in American compromise proposals. Washington should
make clear its disappointment with Cairo and Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what happens next. Barak spoke on Tuesday of
considering all options, even a termination of the peace effort
that began with the Oslo agreement in 1993. His political situation
at home is tenuous, with his cabinet reduced to a parliamentary
minority. Conservative politicians argue that he has already shown
too much willingness to compromise. But public opinion supports
him, and he must persevere in his efforts to enhance Israeli
security through a fair and defensible peace.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat must also consider his next moves. He should begin by
resisting pressure to declare Palestinian independence, without an
agreement with Israel, on Sept. 13. Such a declaration would invite
new violence. Israel would probably respond by annexing areas of
the West Bank that it has until now envisioned as part of an
eventual Palestinian homeland.
</P>
<P>
   In the statement ending the Camp David talks, Barak and Arafat
recognized the importance of ``avoiding unilateral actions that
prejudge the outcome of negotiations.'' Proclaiming Palestinian
independence would be just such a step. If there is ever to be a
durable peace, Arafat must reconsider his unyielding approach to
Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-25-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
