<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER WOODS' WORK ETHIC SHOULD BE OUR STANDARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most overlooked aspect of the Tiger Woods phenomenon is the
refurbished sheen it's giving the work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   Once Americans begin to look past the natural gifts that have
made Woods the most skilled practitioner of what is arguably the
world's most difficult game, they will begin to understand what
separates him from other equally gifted colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, only in golf will the achievements won by his
willingness to work harder than anyone else be recognized for what
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has become to golf what Michael Jordan was to basketball.
They're equals by dint of transforming already considerable
aptitudes for their games into performances that seem superhuman.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, according to basketball aficionados, was also one of the
hardest-working athletes of his or anyone else's era. This strength
may have been overlooked somewhat by casual observers, though,
because basketball is a team game.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods, however, the recognition of his work ethic's
contribution to his development will be more obvious, because golf
is an individual pursuit. This will be a good thing in a society
that for nearly a generation has encouraged underachievement among
its young people in the name of preventing hurt feelings and
fostering self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   This unfortunate trend manifests itself in developments such as
grade inflation, competition that de-emphasizes winning and
recognition of superior talent, and equal rewards for unequal
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes Tiger Woods to remind us that nothing pays off
like hard work. As good as Tiger is, everyone who closely follows
golf understands that his golfing life is as noteworthy for its
unstinting commitment to improving his already considerable skills.
</P>
<P>
   After Tiger's British Open victory capped a career grand slam of
golf's major tournaments, he was asked whether he could get better.
Certainly, Woods replied, without seeming to brag. It is, he said,
simply a matter of working on the aspects of his game that need
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said one of the most vivid memories he took from the U.S.
Open in June was returning from the practice range on Friday
evening and seeing 60-year-old Jack Nicklaus working on his putting
in the post-sunset gloaming of Pebble Beach's practice green.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus is the standard by which Tiger measures himself, and
the scene, Tiger related, was a potent reminder of the passion for
improvement that made Nicklaus the world's greatest golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved with golf see Tiger as a savior of the game who
will inspire youngsters to get interested and become the golf
industry's customers of tomorrow. If character is built along with
a rise in commercial fortunes, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's greatest contribution to American society, however, will
transcend golf if he becomes a symbol of how nothing worthwhile can
be attained without working for it. In this respect, Tiger is a
godsend for parents who need an example to show their children
what's possible if you are willing to work hard enough to achieve
it.
</P>
<P>
   Although golf is too hard for most to master, Tiger's example is
universal in the lessons it can teach young and old alike about
almost any pursuit, whether it involves sports, business, career or
life in general.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
